<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS FEARS NOT THE WILLIAMS SISTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over the past year, the shots uncoiled by the
sculptured Venus and Serena Williams have come at Martina Hingis
with the force of uppercuts.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of reacting to the sisters' power by putting up a
scaffold around her fit but slight physique, Hingis will remain as
is. She is not reaching for creatine to turn her body into bulk
mail or searching out supplements for a potent answer. To combat
the Williams sisters, Hingis, the No. 1 player in the world, will
continue to improve on what she does best.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, after the first day of the U.S. Open was christened with
a cloudburst at noon, Hingis revealed an appetizer of the skills
she believes are sharper than ever. By leaning on her almost
clairvoyant anticipation, deceptive speed and crafty shot
selection, she dissected Alina Jidkova in 57 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But once she exited Arthur Ashe Stadium, there were the Williams
sisters again. Not in person, but in the form of questions. But
oddly enough, perhaps as a defense mechanism, Hingis' most telling
response to the sisters was delivered when the subject of her
difficult 1999 season was raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody expects me to do as I did in '97, which, in a way, I
feel is unfair,'' said the 19-year-old Hingis, who won three majors
in 1997 but has won just two since then. ``I have five Grand Slams.
Venus and Serena each have one. Lindsay Davenport maybe now has
three because she played better. But she's 24. The Williamses, you
know, they're my age. I think, so far, I've been better than them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been as injured as them. It's just the consistency,
that's what counts to be No. 1, not who wins the most tournaments
or who hits the ball the fastest or who hits the fastest serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost feisty in her demeanor, this was a more defiant Hingis
than the one who slumped away from Wimbledon with shattered spirits
after Venus Williams crushed her confidence in the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   But like most of the other seeded players Monday, Hingis used
the first round of the U.S. Open as a new beginning. Venus
Williams, on the other hand, continued the momentum she began to
gain in July. Pounding the hardcourts with almost vicious ground
strokes Monday night, the third-seeded Williams won her 20th
straight match, leaving Anne-Gaelle Sidot behind, 6-3, 6-4.
Williams was ahead by 5-0 in the second set, but, as is her trend,
she temporarily lost her focus and allowed Sidot to close in, if
only for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   There were some minor tremors in their midst, but no upsets as
15th-seeded Jennifer Ca-H priati, sixth-seeded Monica Seles,
top-seeded Andre Agassi and fifth- seeded Yevgeny Kafelnikov ad-L
vanced to the second round.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-seeded Pete Sampras also came through with a 7-6 (3),
7-5, 6-4 victory over Martin Damm. Tossing in 22 aces like
lightning bolts, Sampras looked under control in a good tuneup for
the rest of the tournament. In one first-round match, he progressed
further in the draw than he did a year ago. Last year, he was
forced to withdraw before the tournament with a back injury, which
gave him a first real brush with his tennis mortality.
</P>
<P>
   It also started discussions about the life span of his career.
Although the 29-year-old Sampras showed he was still dangerous and
dominant on grass when he won his record 13th Grand Slam at
Wimbledon, the ATP is concerned about the future popularity of the
game. In an effort to promote the young players, the tour has begun
a marketing campaign with the catch phrase: ``New Balls Please.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an interesting slogan,'' Sampras said with a smile. ``I
think it's a sign of what the ATP is trying to do, how they're
trying to push the young guys. A lot of people in the public don't
know the young Europeans. We'll see how the marketing strategy
unfolds. I admire the effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre and I aren't going to play five or 10 years. But for the
next couple of years, I think we'll contend for the majors. It's a
sign of the tour marketing for the young guys. It's no insult to me
or like they're pushing me out.''
</P>
<P>
   The tour still needs Sampras. He is still popular, still a
dominant figure in demand. But in some ways, the women's tour is in
far better shape. With rivalries and charismatic personalities, the
women are in the spotlight. Early in the day, the women provided
one of the first round's most intriguing matches. After the rain,
the flower beds were mussed by gusty winds and the puddles turned
into reflecting pools for Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with a 90-minute rain delay, she had time to contemplate
the approach that undid her in the first set, which she dropped,
7-5, to Joannette Kruger, ranked 63rd on the tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think the rain delay helped me to realize a lot
of what I was doing wrong,'' said Sanchez-Vicario, who won, 5-7,
6-4, 7-6 (2), even though Kruger had a chance to serve for the
match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back hitting well again. I was able to win. I probably
let her play too much. But I think at the end, I pulled it out
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis had an easier time. She had never played Jidkova before
but quickly deciphered the best approach to beating her and went
about her quick work.
</P>
<P>
   But she knows what is looming. She knows there is a potential
meeting against Venus Williams in the semifinals. Even though she
has been rattled by Williams' power in the past, she is mentally
steeled if the occasion to play her should arise once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people don't understand why I'm up there,'' Hingis
said, referring to her No. 1 ranking. ``The fans, when they watch
me, I don't hit the ball as hard as Venus. But you know, I've got a
pretty good all-around game. It's just no weaknesses, more or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had to deal with things, like being No. 1, the pressure.
I think now I've survived quite a bit, and I think I can improve my
game again.''
</P>
<P>
   No redesign necessary. No additives required.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life is too nice,'' said Hingis, who bristled when asked if
she would ever think of taking supplements to help her build
strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I start taking something else to bulk myself up to get
bigger, it's not worth it for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my speed and quickness is my game anyway. If I get
bigger, I just get slower, and that's not my game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
