<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SWEET SORRIES SEEM SO HOLLOW  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Barfomercials, I call 'em.
</P>
<P>
   The company CEO on TV stares into your eyes and pours out his
heart. It doesn't quite fill a shot glass.
</P>
<P>
   By God, he's so sorry, he's almost in tears, and he won't sleep
until the problem has been rectified and you, the cherished
customer, have been taken care of _ up to and including your
funeral costs.
</P>
<P>
   United Airlines' CEO, golly does he feel bad about 10 trillion
United fliers currently camped out in airport boarding areas. Some
have been camped so long that they get mail delivered there.
</P>
<P>
   You know this man is United's CEO because he is talking to you
from inside an airplane, and who but a United CEO could actually
board a United airplane?
</P>
<P>
   The Ford guy is my favorite. Heavy Australian accent, so you
know he's a good bloke who likes to drink beer and laugh when he's
not worried sick about your car rolling over and spilling the
groceries.
</P>
<P>
   The company is working around the clock to fix the problem with
the Explorer's faulty tires and lousy suspension, he says, or words
to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   He also says that there are two things that Ford will  &UR; never &LR; 
take for granted: profits, and the ``personal safety of my precious
arse.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually he says the two things are ``owner safety'' and
``trust,'' but what's the diff?
</P>
<P>
   As Marshall McLuhan or Marshall Dillon or somebody said, ``The
message is the massage.''
</P>
<P>
   INCIDENTALLY, I hear reports that Ford will paste a large
warning sticker on the dashboard of each Explorer to discourage
driving maneuvers that might exceed the suspension limitations of
the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The sticker will say: DO NOT EXPLORE!
</P>
<P>
   AT FISHERMAN'S Wharf, something smells not-fishy.
</P>
<P>
   The Port Commission closed down two seafood-processing
operations because the pier they're on is rotting away and near
collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Nit-pick City! Hope the Port Commission doesn't inspect this
column.
</P>
<P>
   Lotta Dotz cries out, ``Put Christ back in Christmas and fish
back in Fisherman's Wharf.''
</P>
<P>
   MOOCH THE ROMANTIC: 49ers' Forty-Niners' coach Steve (Mooch)
Mariucci got a big laugh at the 49ers' kickoff luncheon Friday,
introducing wife Gayle: ``I haven't seen her in six weeks so I
asked her if she wanted to have lunch in the city. ... So here it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Cute. And that evening, Mr. &AMP; Mrs. Mooch dropped into P.J.
Mulhern's in North Beach. They sat at the bar, ate calamari and
lamb sirloin, talked 49er football with the patrons and watched the
Rams-Cowboys game on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Then they went home, turned off the lights ... and broke down
Atlanta Falcons' game films.
</P>
<P>
   I'm just guessing at that part. Could have been Packers' films.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL AGENT Seymour Seitz was in Palo Alto Sunday, meandering
through the Festival of Arts, and reports:
</P>
<P>
   ``While I was munching on a portobello mushroom sandwich and
watching a troupe of belly dancers sway to the rhythm of conga
drums, a dog fight broke out. God, I miss Marin.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE NEWS from strange countries:
</P>
<P>
   If you plan to do construction work for the city of Berkeley,
bring your attorney and your foreign-policy adviser. In addition to
the usual stack of forms required by every city, Berkeley asks for
a few extras, notes Steve SanFilippo.
</P>
<P>
   Besides asserting that you are nuclear-free and not doing
business with morally repugnant regimes in Ado, Kham and U-Tsang,
you must sign:
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Berkeley Hardwood Disclosure Form that states the
contractor is not using hardwoods obtained from tropical rain
forests. These woods include: apitong, banak, bocote, bubinga,
cocobolo, cordia, ebony, goncalo alves, greenheart, iroko,
jeluntang, koa, luauan, mahogany, meranti, padauk, purpleheart,
ramin, rosewood, satinwood, teak, virola, wenge and zebrawood.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, I'd love to hear this list read by the train-station
announcer (Mel Blanc) on the old Jack Benny TV show, who always
finished his list with: ``... and Cuc ... a-monga.''
</P>
<P>
   HOW FAT are your tires?
</P>
<P>
   Now we know auto tires shred and explode if they're
underinflated or overinflated. When was the last time you checked
yours?
</P>
<P>
   And where? At a gas station? Good luck.
</P>
<P>
   If you're old enough to remember when the station attendant
would cheerfully check your tire pressure, it doesn't matter what
kind of shape your tires are in now because you're at death's door
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   If your station does have an air compressor with a PSI (pounds
per square inch) gauge, chances are the gauge is broken or faulty.
Those gauges, I'm guessing, are made by the same people who make
BART escalators.
</P>
<P>
   SUDDENLY I'm feeling guilty about my U-Tsang bubinga credenza.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
