<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIDER WILL BE FINE, IF HE`S ON TIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO _ Isaiah Rider's introductory press conference Monday
began a few minutes late. It wasn't Isaiah's fault. He arrived
promptly. So we're assured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a problem with the electrical system, so there was a
delay,'' explained Michael Uhlenkamp, one of the Lakers publicists,
gesturing toward the microphones and cameras set up on the team's
practice court. ``He was definitely on time. Early!''
</P>
<P>
   This means one of two things: Rider has mended his ways and will
never be late for a team event again. Or we should expect a number
of ``problems with the electrical system'' at the Staples Center
next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Rider, who is in his late 20s, comes to the Lakers with a
bit of a reputation for disruptive behavior. He has livened up the
basketball scenes in Minnesota, Portland and Atlanta by earning
repeated suspensions and fines for assorted incidents of marijuana
possession, locker-room altercations, ballistic spitting, and
tardiness.
</P>
<P>
   But among these misdemeanors, the one that seems to concern the
Lakers front office is the tardiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first it's the same old questions,'' general manager Mitch
Kupchak said, referring to his examination of Rider's record in the
days before he signed the sharp-shooting guard as a free agent last
Friday. ``He's been late. He doesn't come to practice. But once you
get past that, he's one of the most talented players ever to play
in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst thing I could come up with is that he's late. I
don't see the big risk here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither do I.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers are paying the late, great Rider $736,000 on a
one-year contract, the low end of the scale for seven-year pros.
That's $2.3 million less than Travis Knight will receive next
season and a couple hundred thousand less than Tyronn Lue.
</P>
<P>
   As much as everybody would prefer to fill a roster with Eagle
Scouts boasting 30-point averages, the Lakers are practically
forced by economics to take risks like this. Up against the NBA
salary cap, they must hunt for bargains, players whose prices are
held down by factory defects.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes a matter of what sort of some sort of blemish you'd
rather have, the occasional ``Hey, anybody seen Isaiah?'' or a guy
who can't shoot.
</P>
<P>
   Kupchak suggests the problem could be solved if Riders finds a
home near the arena, or if he hires ``somebody to drive him
around.''
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A.'s not the easiest place to move around in, getting to a
game,'' Kupchak said.
</P>
<P>
   Rider said he has searched his soul and figured out what has
gone wrong with his career, the future of which was up in the air
after the Atlanta Hawks released him March 17. He said he summoned
his better angels and assembled a plan to correct things. He didn't
say if he bought a freeway map.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell you (the plan), but I can't tell you,'' he
said, mysteriously. He indicated he'd try to live somewhere between
the downtown Staples Center and the team's El Segundo training
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somewhere that I can get there on the streets. I'm from Cali
(California, specifically Oakland), I know what it's like at 2
o'clock in the afternoon,'' Rider said.
</P>
<P>
   What I like about the Rider signing is that he might be just the
man to keep things interesting while the Lakers waltz to
championship after championship in the years before Shaquille
O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Phil Jackson go their separate ways.
Otherwise it could get monotonous.
</P>
<P>
   The chances are slim that his behavior will actually disrupt a
veteran team blessed with the confidence and steady self-image of a
defending champion and the most secure head coach in all of sports.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part for Rider might be living up to our low
expectations. Compared to some of the troublemakers who have come
through this town Alex Johnson, Steve Howe, Dennis Rodman, the
Raiders _ a nicely groomed and well-spoken young man with a few
tardies on his report card is kind of a piker.
</P>
<P>
   Better to worry about a player because he might not show up than
because he might.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
