<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CIA-CHILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CIA COVER-UP ON CHILE
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Aug. 29:
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton first promised that the administration
would declassify secret documents on political violence in Chile,
the Central Intelligence Agency pledged to cooperate. Now it is
breaking that promise with regard to the most important information
_ documents about covert operations to destabilize the socialist
government of Salvador Allende and support Augusto Pinochet's
repressive security forces after his 1973 coup.
</P>
<P>
   Although the State Department has cooperated, the CIA argued
that the president's directive did not cover most files on its own
operations. After howls from Congress, human rights advocates and
State Department officials, the CIA last year agreed to review and
release those files. Its declassification experts marked hundreds
of documents for release on Sept. 14 and deleted their references
to confidential sources and methods.
</P>
<P>
   The CIA. is still planning to release files on its covert
operations to keep Allende from taking power after winning the 1970
election. But George Tenet, director of central intelligence, has
blocked release of hundreds of other documents on covert actions
both before and after Pinochet came to power on grounds that the
documents illustrate a ``pattern of activity'' that reveals
``intelligence methods that have been employed worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the National Security Archive, a nongovernmental group
that fought for declassification, points out, the methods these
documents describe were publicly revealed a quarter-century ago by
a Senate select committee on intelligence. There is no good reason
to withhold documents that would help Chileans and Americans
understand their past.
</P>
<P>
   After a public outcry earlier this month, the administration set
up an interagency panel to look at the documents and recommend to
Tenet which of them should be declassified. Clinton should simply
instruct him to declassify the documents. Tenet insists he is not
simply trying to cover up actions that were an embarrassment to the
United States. But it sure looks that way, and his defiance of the
presidential order for openness adds a new embarrassment to the
list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 0022EDT &QL; 
