<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOGA- </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND MAYOR INSPIRES A NEW AGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By JANINE DeFAO 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ Does this look like the urging of some New Age
yogi or Hindu sage?
</P>
<P>
   Try instead an open invitation in a newspaper ad from a big-city
mayor to come make a mind-body connection _ at his home.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly not typical, but not altogether surprising _ not
if that mayor is Oakland's Jerry Brown, nicknamed ``Governor
Moonbeam'' two decades ago for his proposal to have California
launch its own satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Although Brown is more often derided these days for his
unabashed courting of developers and dot-coms, the three-time
presidential candidate, who attended Jesuit seminary and studied
Zen meditation in Japan, has not completely lost touch with his
inner guru.
</P>
<P>
   He offers yoga and tai chi for the public weekly at his home.
And now, Brown is ready to try on a new mantle, that of philosopher
king.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Saturday, his quasi-communal live-work warehouse near
Jack London Square will host two dozen academics led by philosopher
and social historian Ivan Illich, who has been Brown's friend and
teacher for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering, called the Oakland Table, will last five weeks
and will take place twice a year for the next three to five years.
Lectures, discussion groups and seminars are scheduled almost
daily, and all are free and open to the public.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Exploring Society
</P>
<P>
   The theme is the ``city as a place,'' and it will explore the
isolation and homogenization of modern society.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as an opportunity to gain insight on what the
modern world is doing to people, doing to our consciousness, our
sense of who we are and what it means to be human,'' said Brown,
who plans to attend many of the sessions. ``And what it means to be
human in the year 2000 is very different than what it meant to be
human 500 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Nightly seminars will range from ``Medieval Philosophical
Latin'' _ of interest to Brown, who majored in classical languages
in college _ to ``Politics from the Ground Up,'' which Brown
himself will host. Required reading for the seminars will be
available at Oakland public libraries.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting scholars, who will live at the mayor's house during
the Oakland Table, include architects, linguists and
mathematicians. Many are part of Illich's scholarly circle.
</P>
<P>
   Illich will give the first of six Saturday lectures at the We
the People auditorium in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aristotle says the unexamined life is not worth living,''
Brown said. ``So we're examining. That's exactly what this is. ...
What we're looking at is a recovery of what it means to be a human
being, creating your life instead of having it created for you.''
</P>
<P>
   These are definitely not the questions being explored at City
Hall, where Brown is more concerned about the nuts and bolts of
crime statistics and school test scores. But he does see a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as very valuable to study history, to study
traditional thinking to gain distance and perspective on what we're
doing now,'' said Brown.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Disappearance of Commons
</P>
<P>
   One of the topics to be examined is the loss of ``civic
relatedness,'' the disappearance of commons where diverse citizens
can come together outside the confines of their private homes _ and
how such spaces can be re-created.
</P>
<P>
   Brown hopes the Oakland Table can provide such a forum as ``a
group of people sitting around a table, reading books, talking
about ideas, in friendship pursuing truth.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has been a goal of his five-year experiment in communal
living at We the People, the name of his nonprofit educational
association, the warehouse he built near the Oakland waterfront
five years ago and the radio show he hosted from there.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment continues, although some of its loftier goals
have fallen by the wayside. Its environmental School of
Sustainability fizzled after a year. The rooftop garden still
exists, but it isn't being farmed as a cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown's housemates have shrunk to a relatively small circle:
his longtime friend and adviser Jacques Barzhagi, Barzhagi's wife
and toddler, press secretary Erica Harrold and Marcus Clark, a
sometimes driver for Brown and Barzhagi who also works in the
construction and cleaning industries.
</P>
<P>
   But tai chi classes have been part of the scene since the
beginning, and a twice-weekly yoga class, open to the public for a
small fee, was resurrected this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who practiced yoga regularly before he moved to Oakland,
doesn't attend the morning classes in the We the People auditorium,
but he can sometimes be heard in the kitchen next door. Or a
passer-by may wander in, insisting he knows the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's holistic,'' Brown, who is featured this month on the
cover of a Buddhism and meditation magazine, Shambhala Sun, said of
yoga. ``We should definitely be putting more into body-mind
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   It is ``definitely on my `to do' list,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoga teacher Catherine Cowsill said she doesn't push Brown too
much to come to class.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yoga isn't just a physical practice. He's working on his
dharma,'' Cowsill said, referring to the Hindu term for a person's
core mission. ``He's doing something to keep him physical and
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   But she is sure that she ``would not be there if Jerry didn't
want a yoga class there. ... It would never happen at President
Clinton's house. It wouldn't happen anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   The class is small, a mostly word-of-mouth gathering of people
who have some connection to Brown or his housemates. There is a
choreographer, a dancer, a baker, a neighbor and a gallery owner
who sits on the city's cultural arts commission. Press secretary
Harrold is a regular.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the location, it is much like any other yoga class.
People breathe and stretch, balance in poses named warrior and
cobra and boat.
</P>
<P>
   But Cowsill, who lives in West Oakland, believes that her class
can provide a greater good not just for the individual, but for the
city itself.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Sense of Sharing
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, the way (Brown) lives and the projection of how he
is seeps into the fabric of what the city is becoming,'' she said.
To her, Oakland is a place of ``creative people, deep vision and a
sense of real sharing.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown hopes to share with the public his intellectual
meanderings through the Illich project, although he realizes the
subject matter probably will not appeal to a mass audience.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been following the work of Illich, 73, since the late
1960s, when he came across the book, ``Deschooling Society,'' which
criticized formal education as ``a standardizing and dependency-
and privilege-creating institution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men met in the mid-1970s, and Brown has been several
times to Cuernavaca, Mexico, where Illich first brought together a
group of intellectuals and activists who questioned the concepts of
progress and development. Illich now splits his time between
Cuernavaca and Bremen, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a historian, he's a theologian, he's a philosopher. He
has tremendous understanding that is outside the normal
conventional channels that you run into, and that's why I find it
bracing, challenging to spend time with him,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The project is expected to cost $120,000 a year, which We the
People is raising through contributions. The academics involved
hope to publish a book and a series of shorter booklets based on
their work in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a side of Oakland that hasn't ever been explored or
brought out,'' said yoga participant Bridget Berrigan, a former
Brown campaign volunteer. ``A spiritual side, a coming to terms
with what it means to be a citizen of the city these days, what it
means to be a community.''
</P>
<P>
   ``(Brown) has been doing this for years,'' she said. ``It's not
new and radical in his life, but it may be for Oaklanders.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
