 UNITED SERVICE IMPROVES AFTER TENTATIVE LABOR PACT  &HT;     By DAVID R. BAKER and ALAN GATHRIGHT 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For business traveler Peter Molloy, Monday's
United Airlines flight into San Francisco International Airport
proved nothing short of remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   It landed on time.
</P>
<P>
   No mysterious delays on the ground in Tucson, Ariz. or Los
Angeles. No last-minute cancellations, followed by a mad scramble
for another flight. Coming just two days after United pilots
reached a tentative agreement in their summer long labor dispute
with the airline, the entire trip went off without a hitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the shuttle to arrive on time in San Francisco is a big
achievement,'' said a relieved Molloy, 46.
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco and across the country, problem-plagued United
returned to something like normalcy Monday. The airline's network
of flights _ tangled all summer by delays blamed on bad weather and
fed-up pilots _ ran largely on time.
</P>
<P>
   More than 71 percent of United's 2,400 worldwide flights arrived
on schedule Monday, compared to 40 percent overall for the entire
month to date. And the airline, which in May canceled 75 San
Francisco flights in one day, canceled just 61 Monday throughout
its global network.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big sense of relief,'' said Mike McCarron, SFO's
assistant deputy airport director. ``Especially as we're getting
ready for the Labor Day weekend crunch, the last thing we need is
some labor dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Both United, the world's biggest airline, and the Air Line
Pilots Association declined to release details of the agreement,
preferring to wait until after the union's governing board receives
the proposal next week. Several pilots at SFO said they didn't know
the specifics. But they were happy to put the dispute behind them,
saying a quick resolution would benefit both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely good news,'' said First Officer Bill Harris,
37, waiting for his flight to Washington, D.C.'s Dulles
International Airport. ``A lot of times, the pilots get blamed for
a lot of it. People don't understand the full story.''
</P>
<P>
   United's 10,500 pilots have worked without a new contract since
their last one expired in April. Although union representatives
insist the association never organized or encouraged any effort to
delay flights this summer, many frustrated pilots refused to work
overtime, leading to scheduling problems throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Ken Bradley, spokesman for the union's United pilots,
said Monday the association did nothing within the last two days to
get pilots back into the planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has told the pilots to do extra shifts, or do anything
differently, just as nobody ever told them to do anything else,''
Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet travelers used to SFO's crowds of angry, delayed fliers
found a surprisingly quiet airport Monday. Departure boards for
United, the airport's main airline, showed just two afternoon
cancellations _ both of them shuttles to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Many United travelers, anxious about their plans, had already
heard about the tentative agreement. For Garry Wood and his family
_ on vacation from Hertford, England _ the settlement arrived none
too soon. Wood, his wife and three children were relieved to find
their flight to Honolulu boarding on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traveling with a family is difficult already,'' said Wood, 44.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, he said, if the contract dispute had dragged on through
his family's 17-hour return trip to England.
</P>
<P>
   ``You add another six hours to that because the pilots are on
strike, and it's a lot worse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Problems at the airline have been so widespread that few
business travelers flying through SFO managed to avoid them. As
chief executive officer of a Madison, Wisc. biotech firm, Molloy
flies United often, usually through its Chicago hub. The delays can
be maddening, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been caught up in it a couple of times, and it's
incredibly frustrating,'' he said, waiting for his bags to tumble
into view. ``As a business traveler, you expect things to work. And
this doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   The pact probably won't be ratified for at least another month.
The pilots association's governing board will vote on it during a
special meeting Sept. 6-8. Assuming it passes, the union will then
hold information sessions for the rank and file.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement will not end the company's potential labor woes.
Talks with the machinists union are ongoing. Machinists
representatives could not be reached for comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, however, said he hopes the weekend's tentative
agreement will help repair the damage done to the airline's
reputation by this summer's delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is the hope of all concerned that this agreement
will lay the groundwork for United management to get back on track
to rebuild this company and restore public confidence,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
