<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAT-SCORES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MATH SCORES ADD UP TO SAT SUCCESS  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Verbal scores on nationwide college entrance exams held steady
this year, but math scores hit a 30-year high, jumping three points
after dipping slightly last year.
</P>
<P>
   While the national average on the SAT rose from 511 to 514,
California students did even better. For the second year, they
outperformed their counterparts nationwide in math with average
scores rising from 514 to 518, according to information released
Tuesday by the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   The board administers the SAT, an exam that measures the
mathematics and verbal skills of high school students bound for
college. The test, which has a possible score of 800 in each
subject and is used by 83 percent of four-year colleges as a factor
in admission, was taken this year by more than one-and-a-quarter
million seniors nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   This year's scores also show minority groups regaining some of
the ground they lost from 1998 to 1999, when education advocates
worried that the gap between racial and ethnic groups was growing.
Although whites continued to be the top scorers, their math scores
increased at a lower rate than did those of African Americans and
some Latinos.
</P>
<P>
   African Americans scored an average of 426 in math, up from 422
last year, and Mexican Americans scored 460 in math, up from 456.
Whites scored 530 in math, up from 528.
</P>
<P>
   However, verbal scores remained the same for the two minority
groups, while whites gained a point.
</P>
<P>
   Women are making progress in closing the gap with men. Since
1990, the average verbal score for women has risen 8 points to 504,
while men have improved by only 2 points to 507. Since the 1980s,
the gap in math scores has dropped 5 points, although it still
remains large, men scoring an average of 533 and women 498.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the national average for math scores has risen 13
points since 1990, for the first time bringing it above the 1970
score of 512. (The 1970 numbers have been adjusted to reflect a
recentering of SAT scores in 1995.) The increase may reflect a
boost in math and science preparation in high school, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Sixty-nine percent of both men and women report taking four or
more years of mathematics, up from 68 percent of men and 62 percent
of women 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Many districts are strengthening graduation requirements to
include more math, and the state has worked during the past decade
to reform its math program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It contradicts those who claim that all American schools are
falling apart,'' said Bob Schaeffer, public education director of
the National Center for Fair and Open Testing, an organization that
opposes test requirements.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the annual fluctuations mean little. This was a
sentiment reiterated by San Francisco State University math
professor Dan Sendel, who does not expect to see significant gains
until every classroom has a credentialed teacher trained in the
subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a huge set of students, and to make a 13 point jump in
that large a population takes work,'' Sendel said. ``It may be
going in the right direction, but we still have a long, long way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Average national SAT verbal scores remained steady at 505 for
the fifth consecutive year. For the 12th year in a row, California
students lagged behind the rest of the nation in verbal skills,
posting a score of 497, unchanged from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does suggest that it is harder to budge reading scores,
especially in states like California with a high percentage of
students who speak English as a second language,'' said Bruce
Fuller, a professor of education and public policy at the
University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   This year's test takers are the most diverse group ever, 34
percent being nonwhite and a third having parents who did not
attend college.
</P>
<P>
   The number of foreign-born and first generation American test
takers has increased by 47 percent, nearly three times the growth
rate of the overall SAT test takers, since the College Board began
tracking the data in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   In California, 19 percent of test takers reported that English
was not their first language, compared with only 9 percent
nationwide. In California, they gained ground on the test, with
scores rising from an average of 444 to 446 on the verbal section
and from 500 to 507 on the math.
</P>
<P>
   In California, 11 percent of test takers had parents who had not
earned a high school diploma, compared with 4 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even as there is a more diverse population taking the test and
going to college, we are still seeing gains. That is a big success
story for California,'' Fuller said.
</P>
<P>
   The rebound in minority scores is surprising considering that on
Friday, National Assessment of Educational Progress report revealed
what appeared to be contrary data. It showed that the average black
17-year-old reads about as well as the average white 13-year-old
and that the gap between white and minority students is again
widening. Fuller said that since the SAT is taken by students
interested in attending college, while the NAEP is taken by a
sampling of 9-, 13- and 17-year-olds, the apparent conflict may
indicate another disparity.
</P>
<P>
   ``The recent school reform may be helping college-bound students
and not other students,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
