<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-SPARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN CORNERBACK SPARKS SIGNS WITH COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Roughly two hours after giving a ``we got an
experienced player'' speech to a pack of cameras and notepads
regarding Monday's signing of veteran cornerback Phillippi Sparks,
Dallas Cowboys coach Dave Campo was discussing music in the hallway
of the team's Valley Ranch headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder he didn't break out in song.
</P>
<P>
   Caught with his guard down, a gleeful Campo said he was
``extremely happy'' about the moves the Cowboys have made the past
two days and said he ``can't wait'' for Sunday's season opener
against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of Sparks, which improves the team's depleted and
inexperienced cornerback corps, follows the trade for tight end
O.J. Santiago on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, an eight-year veteran who retired after last season,
started for the New York Giants the past seven seasons. Santiago
was a starter for the Atlanta Falcons the past three seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Now, not only are the Cowboys better than they were before the
moves, but they are better than they were before training camp when
the team planned to play a hobbling Kevin Smith (now retired) and
second-year man Mike Lucky (injured) at starting cornerback and
third tight end, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel there is no question that Phillippi can come in here
and give us experience and skill that really benefits this team,''
Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said. ``If you add this to the fact that
we got O.J., we've made an impact on our roster.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, 31, will play and might even supplant rookie Kareem
Larrimore as the starter opposite Ryan McNeil against the Eagles,
depending on Sparks' conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys released middle linebacker Chris Bordano to make
room for Sparks after unsuccessfully trying to trade the former SMU
standout.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks signed a five-year, $18 million deal that includes a
$1.55 million signing bonus. He will get $450,000 in base salary
this season and $1 million in 2001 before his salary jumps to $5
million in each of the final three years.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks, who said he has healed from the groin injury that
sidelined him for the final five games last season, came out of
retirement to sign with the Cowboys. For now, he's taking it one
year at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's one more year?'' Sparks said. ``I'm going to take it
for what it is. I've got one year to get it done. Whatever happens,
Dallas has my rights. You never know, there might be some positive
years ahead. I want to make this one special. I'm not here to be
the savior but I want to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Sparks' presence has already done wonders for members of the
Cowboys' brass, who were admittedly concerned about starting a
rookie at cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said they weren't down on Larrimore, a fourth-round pick.
But starting a rookie was something they didn't plan on, despite
their selection of three cornerbacks in the 2000 draft.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Smith's departure, the Cowboys are without
veteran cornerback Charlie Williams, who missed training camp and
will be out for the first three games of the regular season because
of a staph infection.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' plans suffered another hit when rookie cornerbacks
Mario Edwards (sixth round) and Dwayne Goodrich (second round)
missed the final three weeks of training camp with hamstring
strains. Those events left Larrimore, the most promising of the
rookies, in the starting lineup by default.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't line this thing up by design to go with a rookie,''
Jones said. ``When Kevin retired and Charlie was injured, we were
sitting out here going for it with rookies. Then we didn't get the
competition we really wanted with our rookies. We were way behind
schedule. This was the prudent thing to do. We feel fortunate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, who have pursued the 5-foot-11, 195-pound Sparks
for the past three weeks, convinced him to sign after increasing
their original contract offer. Still, defensive coordinator Mike
Zimmer, who compares Sparks to McNeil, said the Cowboys are
fortunate that he was available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was lucky,'' Zimmer said. ``He had a deal done with the
Rams. Other teams were interested. Obviously, we don't have Deion
(Sanders), but we have two Ryan McNeils. This gives us a chance (to
be good). I feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   And Campo feels like singing. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
