<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
SANTIAGO QUICKLY ENROLLS IN COWBOYS OFFENSE 101 (For use by NYTimes
News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Jerry Jones couldn't sleep. Dave Campo couldn't
wipe the smile off his face. The Dallas Cowboys can hardly wait to
see newcomer O.J. Santiago in the season opener against
Philadelphia on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Cowboys faxed several pages of the Jack
Reilly/Ernie Zampese playbook to the newly acquired tight end
(traded by the Atlanta Falcons for a fourth-round pick in 2001 and
a seventh-round pick in 2002), just so he had something to read on
his two-hour flight from Atlanta to Fort Worth/Dallas on Sunday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In the NFL today, it's all about packaging.
</P>
<P>
   In this offense, Santiago has his name on a few packages already
for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys want to see him in the same lineup as Joey Galloway
and Rocket Ismail or paired with either Jackie Harris or David
LaFleur in the double-tight-end set. They consider the 6-foot-7,
264-pound Santiago's addition to the team as more than just a
backup, or a No. 3 tight end, but another weapon to drive opposing
defensive coordinators crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm learning on the run,'' said Santiago, working mostly in
LaFleur's spot Monday as the Cowboys continue their conservative
approach with LaFleur, who played for the first time Thursday night
after being sidelined with a groin strain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't too bad. I had somebody whispering in my ear what to
do each time I ran up to the line of scrimmage,'' said Santiago,
who had tight ends coach Les Miles on his shoulder throughout the
90-minute practice at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago, a fourth-year player who started on the Falcons' Super
Bowl team two years ago, is as eager as the Cowboys, but also
extremely honest. The playbook that he was handed might as well
have been written in Sanskrit.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the plays looked familiar. Some of the motion influences
were the same as Atlanta. But the terminology may as well have
dropped in out of the sky from Pluto.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this, Miles marveled at Santiago's resolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be real honest with you, there's no chance that I
could do what he did today,'' Miles said. ``He showed up here
today, and the only thing he recognized was that he put his helmet
on the same way he has his whole life. Everything else was new to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago plans to ``memorize the game plan'' _ well, certain
packages _ which he finds to be less cumbersome than trying to
learn the entire playbook as he would have done in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be ready for Sunday,'' he said. ``I was ready to play
against the 49ers ... now it's just the Eagles instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago comes to the Cowboys with a one-year contract after
being tendered the restricted free-agent minimum ($472,000) by the
Falcons, who didn't have Santiago in their future after sending
their 2000 first-round draft pick to Baltimore for a chance to take
tight end Reggie Kelly in the second round in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   When 1998 NFC rushing champion Jamal Anderson tore knee
ligaments against the Cowboys in Week 2 of the '99 season at Texas
Stadium, the Falcons scrapped their plans to use two tight ends in
a featured running attack ... and Santiago became the odd-man out.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way game is going these days. You've got to be
ready to leave for anywhere in 15 minutes,'' Santiago said. ``When
I heard that I was going to be traded, I packed my bag and I was
out of there ... happy to be with America's Team.''
</P>
<P>
   Campo's biggest concern over preparation for the Eagles in five
days is with Santiago, not newly signed cornerback Phillippi
Sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing will be with O.J. getting the terminology
down,'' Campo said. ``That's why it was so big that he practiced
today. I'd rather that it be him than Phillippi because, obviously,
there are more things to learn offensively than defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Santiago expects to have a busy week in a brand-new town.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly reading, probably. BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys were able to call back and re-sign quarterback
Clint Stoerner, running back Troy Hambrick and wide receiver Damon
Hodge to play on the practice squad. Each cleared 24-hour waivers.
The Cowboys will go with the practice-squad maximum of five players
and are expected to add defensive end Aaron Fields and tight end
Chris Fontenot.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Cowboys will hold their annual Kickoff Luncheon on Tuesday
at the Intercontinental Hotel, beginning at 11:30 a.m. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
