<SLUG> BC-SUMMIT-FUND-CORRECTIVE-LADN </SLUG>

 &HT;    (Eds, this is correct story for ``SUMMIT-FUND'' 
LAPD OFFICIALS DISCUSS SURGE IN VIOLENT INNER-CITY CRIME &HT;    (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICK ORLOV 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Top LAPD commanders pledged to mobilize officers
and the community to stop a sudden surge in violent crime in the
city, occurring mainly on weekends among young, inner-city
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Police Department officials said they would detail
their plan next week to fight the sharp rise in homicides in the
South and Central bureaus, even as the San Fernando Valley Bureau
has reported the city's only decline in crime.
</P>
<P>
   After a two-hour meeting of 20 top LAPD commanders during a
summit Monday on violent crime, officials said they are committed
to making sure the streets in the inner city are not surrendered to
hoodlums. But while attacking inner-city crime, staffing levels
will remain at least at current levels in Valley and elsewhere,
they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some clear patterns we identified as it relates to
crime, and we are going to develop some strategies to reduce it
between now and the end of the year and to carry on to next year,''
Police Chief Bernard C. Parks said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have something by next week that we can talk about on
strategies to help us reduce violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit was prompted by a 23.5 percent rise in homicides
citywide, as reported in the Los Angeles Daily News on Monday.
Homicides in the Valley dropped by 8.5 percent, from 47 to 43
slayings, while the South and Central bureaus reported that
increases jumped from 264 to 326.
</P>
<P>
   To be effective against crime, police said more than the LAPD
must be involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It requires the entire community to work together to address
these issues. Various parts of the government must also be
involved,'' said the department's top spokesman, Cmdr. Dave Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we all work together -- the Police Department, the
community, elected officials -- we can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the LAPD will examine the Valley, where community
programs with volunteers assisting police have been effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Valley is really known for citizen participation,'' Kalish
said. ``I imagine other areas will be looking at what's worked in
the Valley and, if appropriate, replicating what's worked there.''
</P>
<P>
   Parks said the session was devoted mostly to an examination of
statistics and to begin looking at possible solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we found are a lot of similarities between the victims
and the suspects,'' the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   They are young -- between the ages of 13 and 23.
</P>
<P>
   They are minority -- 50 percent are Latino, 45 percent are
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   They are out at night and on weekends -- most of the slayings
occurred between 6 p.m. and 3 a.m. and between Thursday nights and
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Malcolm Klein, a professor at the USC Social Science Research
Institute, said there are no easy answers, and he pointed out the
increase in homicides is only over the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are looking at is homicide, because crime generally is
going down across the nation. When you look at why homicides are up
in these areas of Los Angeles, the answers are unknown and the
police will tell you they don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may have to do with an increase in gang-related crime. But
why is that going up? There is no answer. Gang crime has been going
down for six years in a row and at some point it has to bottom
out,'' he said. ``Gang violence is cyclical and maybe what we are
seeing is a statistical phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Klein also said the nature of the inner-city neighborhoods is
changing as more Latino youths move into traditionally
African-American areas, resulting in increased tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Schumsky, chief probation officer for the county, said
he also is unclear about why there is an increase in the homicide
rate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could represent an anomaly, and you hear different
theories, such as prison inmates being released and trying to
reestablish themselves. But it's probably too quick to make a
judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Schumsky said he was pleased with the quick LAPD effort to deal
with the problem and said his office also will have some tools
under new state legislation to do some prevention work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can expect to see some more resources sent to the `hot'
areas and then in a few months we can form a conclusion,'' Schumsky
said. ``It's hard to say at this point if this is more than a
one-time thing or a serious new trend.''
</P>
<P>
   After the LAPD summit, Kalish said the department's first step
will be to gather as much information as possible on the slayings
and the second step will be to look at programs needed while
determining whether adequate resources are available.
</P>
<P>
   But Parks said, ``One thing we want to make clear is that we
will not be taking resources from the Valley or any other portion
of the city to address this. We will not be taking from one area to
help another. We think there are adequate resources within the
department.''
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Joel Wachs, a mayoral candidate who has been
increasingly critical of the LAPD, warned that any reduction in
police protection in the Valley is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we can't do is take resources from the Valley,''
said Wachs, a member of the city's Public Safety Committee who
serves a district stretching from Studio City to Sunland-Tujunga.
``Just because the Valley is lower now in murders doesn't mean it
will stay that way. We have to do what the department is doing and
address this problem immediately, before it spreads to other parts
of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has said before, Wachs stated he believes the department
was distracted while planning for the Democratic National
Convention, which occurred in mid-August, and has failed to fully
staff its anti-gang efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we don't have that distraction, we can get back to
the basics and staff the anti-gang program and return to
community-based policing,'' Wachs said.
</P>
<P>
   Wachs has been a leader in calling on the LAPD to restore its
senior lead officer program to work with the community on
quality-of-life issues. Police Chief Parks has resisted that,
saying he needs the officers on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Parks disagreed that the department has been distracted and said
fluctuations in crime rates can be expected. ``We've had a long
period of decline in crime and this is just a spike,'' he said.
``Even though crime is down 40 (percent) or 50 percent, I don't
think we've bottomed out, and (we) can still have an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Mayor Richard Riordan said the mayor has been
talking with Parks about the matter and remains as concerned today
about public safety as he did when elected in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``While crime has dropped drastically since the mayor took
office, he is concerned that we deal with this sudden spike in
murders as quickly as possible,'' Riordan spokesman Peter Hidalgo
said. ``It remains his top priority, not only for the safety of
people but to make sure Los Angeles is the safest big city in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Los Angeles is to continue to be successful, it has to be
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
