<HEADLINE>
BELCHER BETTER, BUT STATUS UNCERTAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ Tim Belcher said Monday he felt fine one day after
pitching five innings in a rehab assignment for Lake Elisnore at
Rancho Cucamonga and anticipates coming off the disabled list
Friday, when clubs expand rosters.
</P>
<P>
   Just when the 38-year-old right-hander will get back on the
mound again is another question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim came out of (the rehab start) great, he got a little
tired, but it was a great performance,'' manager Mike Scioscia said
of Belcher, who threw 86 pitches and gave up five runs on five hits
in his latest comeback attempt from surgery in December to repair a
torn flexor tendon in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's too soon to tell when he'll pitch,'' Scioscia added.
``We're confident in the arms we have going out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``His stuff was great ... for three or four innings. The
challenge is to take what he has over six innings, or more. That's
the only question right now, not only because of the surgery but
where he is in his career.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Belcher, who's made only four starts all season, is
anxious to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a `clubbie' (clubhouse attendant),'' he said.
``I'm here every day, but I don't play.''
</P>
<P>
   SALMON SALUTED AGAIN: Right fielder Tim Salmon was selected the
A.L. Player of the Week for the second time this month after going
11 for 22 with two home runs including his 30th Sunday night that
enabled the Angels to become the first A.L. team with four 30-homer
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   It's also the fifth time in his career Salmon has earned Player
of the Week honors no other Angel has won it five times and the
fifth time this season an Angel has been selected. Mo Vaughn was
selected May 10-16 and Darin Erstad May 22-28 and July 3-9.
</P>
<P>
   COACH TO COACH: Angels third base coach Ron Roenicke defended
what appeared to be a questionable decision by Cleveland third base
coach Jim Riggleman in the seventh inning Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman waved Manny Ramirez home from second on a single to
center even though Ramirez got a terrible jump off second and was
running with a gimpy hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were two outs, you have to send him,'' Roenicke said.
``He did the right thing. No matter what, you still have to make
the play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels did Garret Anderson threw a strike from center field
to catcher Bengie Molina well ahead of Ramirez' slide
</P>
<P>
   and won the game 10-9.
</P>
<P>
   NO REST IN DETROIT: It was Aug.4 when the Angels launched what
figured to be a make-or-break portion of their season, a 27-game
stretch against six clubs at .500 or better.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night was game No.22, and while the Angels haven't
exactly taken command in the A.L. West, they haven't broken either.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, that demanding stretch of games might end up being a
little longer than 27.
</P>
<P>
   The Detroit Tigers, who the Angels play Sept.4 after two more
games this week at home against Toronto and then three this weekend
in Chicago, are just one game under .500 entering a four-game
series at Baltimore starting tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Garret Anderson started the night needing just
two hits to reach the 1,000-hit plateau for his career. Only four
players have collected 1,000 hits in an Angels uniform: Brian
Downing, Jim Fregosi, Bobby Grich and Tim Salmon. ... Darin Erstad
threw before Monday night's game and might be able to return to
left field tonight. He was the Angels' designated hitter Monday
night for the fourth consecutive game because of a strained muscle
in his left rib cage. ... The Blue Jays and Texas Rangers might
open the 2001 season in Puerto Rico. Details are still being worked
out, but the plan is for the two clubs to play an exhibition game
there March 31 to end spring training, then play a regular-season
game April 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
