r f BC-INTERSTATE-BAKERIES-2     08-29 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERSTATE-BAKERIES-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERSTATE BAKERIES LOOKS TO AN IMPROVED FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JENNIFER MANN  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two years ago,
Interstate Bakeries Corp. was riding high. Earnings were on track,
its stock was strong, and its reputation was solid. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After 11 straight quarters of earnings increases, all was
looking rosy for the country's largest wholesale baker. Then, on
Oct. 7, 1998, the company warned Wall Street that it was probably
going to come up a little short of fourth-quarter earnings
expectations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street pummeled the company so badly that by the time the
market closed that day, Interstate's stock had lost more than 30
percent of its value. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And with each subsequent quarter since then, as one analyst who
follows the company says, ``It's always something with
Interstate.'' Now, its stock is trading at about half of what it
was before that day. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those ``somethings'' include labor troubles, the flooding of a
plant in North Carolina, start-up problems at a new plant in the
Northeast, a big employee discrimination verdict and an inability
to find reasonably priced acquisitions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been absolutely disastrous the last six to eight
quarters,'' said Mitchell Pinheiro of Janney Montgomery Scott.
``Whatever could go wrong has gone wrong.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Sullivan, chairman of the Kansas City-based Fortune 500
company, acknowledges the analysts' criticism but looks forward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Wall Street gets pretty disappointed pretty quick,'' Sullivan
said. ``But we're doing what we think is right.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Does he think those days of ``it's always something'' are behind
Interstate? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, but I would hope so,'' Sullivan said. ``But you
know, we've spent a lot of money in the last three years, about
$200 million. Our major projects, and I think our major problems,
are behind us.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is confident that once the company gets a few good
quarters under its belt, Wall Street will once again warm to the
company. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got their necks out there with `buy' recommendations,
and they want to see good things happen,'' Sullivan said. ``I
understand that.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Stops and starts &QL; 
One of Interstate's biggest problems in the last couple of years
has been start-up complications, particularly at the $100 million,
240,000-square-foot bakery it built in Biddeford, Maine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That one plant replaced four older ones. The new plant uses a
lot of computerized equipment, some of which is three and four
stories high. It's the state-of-the-art bakery in the United
States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But it also was a lot to master all at once, and problem after
problem popped up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then, this spring the company was hit with an eight-day work
stoppage over disagreements with the Teamsters union. That stoppage
caused a dearth of Twinkies, Ho-Hos and Wonder bread products in a
wide swath of the Northeast. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence of the start-up problems and labor strife, the
company lost customers and market share. Some have come back, but
not all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, the analysts got tired of hearing, `Oh, the Biddeford
excuse again,' &UR; '' Sullivan said. ``But you know that plant is
different from any other one out there. And even though we had our
best people there, it was a pretty steep learning curve.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the company is finishing up a new plant in the
Pacific Northwest that will replace three older bakeries. Sullivan
said the company has learned a lot from its Biddeford experience
and expects that start-up to be a lot smoother. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company also is in the midst of retooling the old
Wolferman's plant in Kansas City and starting up a new plant in
Knoxville, Tenn. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another of the ``somethings'' that hurt Interstate much more
than Sullivan believes the investment community understands was the
flooding of two plants last year in the wake of Hurricane Hugo in
North Carolina. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The plants _ a new one and an older one joined together _ were
protected by a 500-year flood retaining wall, as required by the
Federal Emergency Management Agency. Water still rose a
foot-and-a-half over the wall, and 62 inches of water filled both
bakeries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company cleaned up the new plant but decided to go ahead and
retool the older one. Six million dollars later, that plant is
ready to roll, too. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We took an immediate hit with loss of product and an ongoing
hit because we didn't have a lot of the product that the old plant
produced,'' Sullivan said. ``But we're on our feet now _ everything
is OK.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Labor woes &QL; 
Another problem at Interstate is its relations with some of the
unionized workers among its 34,000 employees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One thing that has surprised some analysts is the whipping that
Sullivan's reputation has taken from labor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you historically, (Sullivan) has done very well
with the unions,'' said Bear Stearns &AMP; Co. analyst Terry Bivens.
``But this company definitely has more of a labor problem than it
did a year ago.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One place to get a flavor of some of that disenchantment is on
the Yahoo! message board for Interstate. On that board people post
under names such as Muffin_2000, Backthatthingup, Right_Turn_Baby,
Loser_Company and Famman. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only Famman claims to be in management. The rest say they're
union members. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan is familiar with each of those posters and others. Some
he gives credence to, others he dismisses. But he reads them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That paid off in Cincinnati, where there were several complaints
about bread quality at the company's bakery. Management checked out
the complaints and found that they were true. Interstate's
president, Michael Kafoure, has spent time there in recent weeks
getting the problem fixed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the posters say that management is trying to find out
who they are and pressure them into not posting their complaints. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Sullivan says that's not true, at least not at corporate
headquarters. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd just as soon have people bring these problems to our
attention instead of just closing our ears,'' he said. ``If they
have a legitimate issue to put on the table, we'll check it out.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
