<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISCRIMINATION-COLLEGE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE, JURY CONSIDER SEX DISCRIMINATION ALLEGATIONS AT A MISSOURI
BAPTIST COLLEGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Advocates of
equal treatment for women in college sports are following a trial
in which a former coach accuses Southwest Baptist University of sex
discrimination. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anne Julian, who coached at the Bolivar, Mo., school for three
years, alleges that she was paid less than male coaches with the
same or fewer responsibilities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She also claims that her volleyball and softball teams received
less support in publicity, equipment, supplies and recruiting money
than men's teams did. She says she was fired because she complained
of unequal treatment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The university says that Julian got the same pay as other
volleyball and softball coaches before her and that her team
received as much or more money per athlete as other similar
sports. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Baptist contends Julian did not take the initiative to
raise money or gain publicity for her team. She was fired for not
feeding her players when they lost, the school says, and for not
taking criticism well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Janet Justus, a Kansas City sports law lawyer who used to
specialize in gender equity issues at the National Collegiate
Athletic Association, was in the audience Monday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justus said Julian's case was uncommon because U.S. District
Judge Fernando Gaitan allowed Julian to sue under Title IX, a
federal regulation that prohibits educational institutions from
discriminating on the basis of sex. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in the country, judges have not allowed coaches who
allege sexual discrimination to sue under Title IX, she said.
Instead, they have allowed those cases to go forward under Title
VII of the Civil Rights Act. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Title IX has prompted changes on college campuses in the last
two decades, with women's teams increasing in number, offering more
scholarships, and getting better fields and courts to play on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Justus said it was important for coaches, not just athletes, to
be able to use Title IX to focus attention on inequalities between
men's and women's teams. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Discrimination lawsuits ``are bigger than the individual,'' she
said. ``You're looking at the principles identified. They're about
fairness and equality.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In her opening statement Monday, Julian's attorney, Denise
Henning, urged the jury to focus on fair play. She said women's
sports were considered second-class at the 3,539-student
university, which affected how Julian was treated as a coach. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The university competes in NCAA Division II, fielding seven
women's teams and eight men's teams, including football. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Julian graduated from Southwest Baptist in 1990 and went back to
coach volleyball and softball in 1996. She quit coaching softball
in 1998. She brought a discrimination complaint to the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission in 1998 and coached volleyball
until 1999, when the university did not renew her contract. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The university's attorney, Jerry Kirksey, urged the jury to
focus on Julian as an individual, saying the case was about alleged
employment discrimination, not gender equity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Southwest Baptist has done absolutely nothing wrong,'' Kirksey
said before the trial began. ``And they've done the right thing to
fight it. Just because you file a lawsuit doesn't mean it has any
merit. And just because you're going to trial doesn't mean it has
merit. That just means a judge decided to let the jury hear all the
evidence.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Monday, Matt Henenberg, Julian's graduate assistant
in the 1996-97 softball season, and a personal friend of 17 years,
said she was a good, caring coach who turned a losing softball team
into a winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Keck, who coached women's basketball at the university
in the late 1980s, said she was not given adequate money for
recruiting and unlike men's teams, hers and other women's teams did
not have assistant coaches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   She said she left the university after just two years because
the university reallocated two scholarships it had promised her
team to the men's basketball team. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Keck said she was no longer affiliated
with the university and had no knowledge of current athletic
program budgets. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last into next week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
