<SLUG> BC-PARK-DEDICATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK WILL SHOWCASE KANSAS CITY'S PIONEER TRAIL HERITAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERICA WOOD  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Schumacher Park
stands just minutes from signs of modern living, yet its native
grasses and wildflowers are meant to serve as a tribute to a bygone
era. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, National Park Service officials and local
leaders will gather to officially open the park, though it has been
in development since the late 1980s. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony will include speeches from park service
representatives, City Council members and south Kansas City
community leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park is meant to educate people about the Santa Fe, the
Oregon and the California trails, which crossed through Kansas
City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It benefits tourism in Kansas City,'' said Lou Austin, who
owns a south Kansas City law firm. ``If the trails had not been
here, Kansas City wouldn't exist.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Austin's parents, Lou and Topper Schumacher, donated two and a
half acres to the city for the park. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A crushed-rock trail winds through the front of the park,
allowing visitors to touch the native vegetation and see the
historical exhibits. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The seven exhibits use pictures and text to emphasize the roles
of various racial and ethnic groups, to explain the trails' origins
and to give a glimpse into problems that pioneers faced. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Farther along the trail, visitors can watch trains pass below
while reading about the nation's conversion from trails to
railroads. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Austin said he hoped the path would be paved and eventually
stretch to the nearby Bannister Mall. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   John Conoboy, of the park service's long-distance trails group
office in New Mexico, said that turning Schumacher Park into a
historical site was a great idea. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent opportunity for an urban area to interpret
the trail system in a coordinated way,'' Conoboy said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The project was funded through the National Park Service and
Kansas City tourism funds. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 0100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
