u f BC-TIRE-RECALL-1STLD-WRI     08-29 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRIDGESTONE/FIRESTONE ASKING VENEZUELAN DEALERS TO RETURN TIRES
MADE THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (CORRECTS ``Ford Ranger'' to ``F-series'' in 2nd graf)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. announced Monday evening
that it had asked its dealers in Venezuela to return unsold 15- and
16-inch light truck tires made there, but the company rebuffed the
Ford Motor Co.'s call for a recall of identical tires already in
use in Venezuela, Colombia and Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Ford recalled its Ford Explorer and F-series pickup
trucks equipped with the tires in all three countries, and the
company said Monday that it had urged Bridgestone to recall suspect
tires used on other manufacturers' sport utility vehicles. Ford
also scheduled a news conference on Tuesday in Caracas, Venezuela,
to explain why they thought that tire-related crashes of Ford
Explorer sport utility vehicles in Venezuela had solely been the
result of defective tires and not because of any excessive tendency
of Explorers to roll over.
</P>
<P>
   Jon Harmon, a Ford spokesman, said that Ford had cut open
Firestone tires returned during the recall in Venezuela and found
that many lacked a protective layer of nylon, or were unable to
withstand high-speed driving.
</P>
<P>
   None of the tires made in Venezuela were shipped to the United
States, Ford and Bridgestone said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bridgestone said that problems with its tires were limited
to a mislabeling of their sidewalls and insisted that the tires met
Ford specifications, including the use of nylon layers. The tire
maker said that a broader recall was unnecessary and that it was a
coincidence that the mislabeled 15-inch tires in Venezuela were the
same size as the tires being recalled in the United States because
the treads occasionally come off during high-speed driving.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota, which used some of the tires on Toyota Land Cruisers
sold in Venezuela, said that it had not received any reports of
problems and did not think a broader recall was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Dominguez, a senior investigator at the Institute for
Consumer Protection and Education in Venezuela, said that the
agency was convinced that Ford was partly responsible for a problem
that had caused more than 60 deaths in Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have documentary evidence,'' he said. ``The responsibility
is shared.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the agency's evidence, he said, were communications
between the two companies, as well as stickers that Ford put on its
vehicles showing a lower recommended tire pressure than Firestone
favored.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the tire manufacturer said the tire should be inflated to
32 pounds pressure, they put on their stickers that it should be 26
to 28 pounds,'' Dominguez said. ``We even have photos of the
crashed vehicles showing these stickers in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone have only recently differed in public in the
United States over the recommended tire pressure. Ford has long
favored 26 pounds per square inch. Firestone, after 10 years of
acquiescing to this number, abruptly announced at the beginning of
its recall in the United States on Aug. 9 that the pressure should
be 30 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   Tires inflated to low pressure can overheat and come apart at
high speeds. Virtually all of the deaths in the United States have
occurred when sport utility vehicles, mostly Explorers, have rolled
over when their tires came apart.
</P>
<P>
   Tire makers tend to prefer higher air pressures because it
reduces the risk of failure for the tires, which are covered by the
tire makers' warranties. But higher-pressure tires increase the
risk that sport utility vehicles will roll over during some driving
situations without tire failure.
</P>
<P>
   A Ford memorandum distributed by consumers' lawyers in the
United States showed that Ford rejected higher-pressure tires on a
prototype of the Explorer because they tended to cause rollovers.
Ford ended up choosing a different, lower-pressure tire and a
different suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Ford contends that rollovers are the main cause of crash deaths
for occupants of all brands of midsized sport utility vehicles.
Explorer occupants actually have a lower death rate in rollovers _
and in crashes overall _ than occupants of other midsized sport
utility models, according to Ford safety officials.
</P>
<P>
   In television commercials scheduled to begin Monday night,
Jacques Nasser, Ford's chief executive and president, said that
Ford had one of the best safety records, according to government
data for the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   George Pipas, a Ford market analyst, said Monday that Ford's
sales in the United States in August would be roughly equal to last
year's levels and only slightly below the company's early
projections, a shortfall that he said might reflect response to the
tire recall but also a somewhat slower economy and a highly
competitive market.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Harmon said the company had not found protective nylon
layers in 71 percent of the 15-inch tires from Venezuela that it
cut open, nor in 55 percent of the 16-inch tires. Auto companies
commonly specify that tire makers include nylon for vehicles to be
sold in South America because of the poor roads and because drivers
frequently go extremely fast in the absence of enforced speed
limits, Harmon said. The tires also came apart before reaching 112
miles per hour on a dynanometer, a speed they were supposed to be
able to withstand, particularly because the Explorer's engine has a
computer control to keep drivers from going more than 99 miles an
hour, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has been criticized by consumers' lawyers for not having
Firestone include the nylon layers on Explorer tires for the United
States market. Because of the good roads in the United States,
manufacturers rarely use the layers except for very high-speed
models like the Chevrolet Corvette sports car and the Ford F-150
Lightning pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone hinted in a letter Monday to the Venezuelan consumer
agency that Ford might not have asked for nylon layers until
recently. The letter said that Ford had specified in 1999 that the
nylon be included and that nylon had been included since then. The
tires in question have been produced since 1996, and the
Bridgestone letter did not say whether the earlier tires had the
nylon, nor were officials willing to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Harmon said the company had always asked for the nylon.
``Firestone specified a nylon ply to meet Ford's performance
specifications from the beginning of Ford's Explorer sales in
Venezuela,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Firestone tires in Venezuela, as in the United States, bear
no external signs that the tread may come apart from an inner layer
of rubber. Yet Ford engineers who cut apart the tires from
Venezuela found that they were 100 to 1,000 times as likely to show
early signs of tread separation as even the recalled Firestone
tires in the United States, said a person who had seen the results.
</P>
<P>
   Four investigators for the House Commerce Committee visited
Bridgestone's U.S. headquarters in Nashville, Tenn., Monday seeking
evidence on what the company knew about its American tires and
when.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 0102EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
