<HEADER>
A4930 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS_BREWERS-L     08-29 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS_BREWERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EARLY RUNS ENOUGH FOR AILING DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ There are those Dodgers that are ill. Others are
injured. And between the vomiting and physical therapy, they're
managing to find enough guys to field a team.
</P>
<P>
   Though questions about how long the Dodgers will be able to do
that have arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Two outfielders are injured, another sick and their starting
pitcher was so weak from illness that he said he felt wobbly at
times. Even so, the Dodgers were able to make five first-innings
runs stand up Monday and defeated the Milwaukee Brewers 5-3 at
County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, stuck in his Chicago hotel room for two days over
the weekend because of flu-like symptoms, battled through seven
innings as the Dodgers (69-62) won for the seventh time in eight
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured I'd see what I could get out of myself and try to
save the bullpen,'' Brown said. ``I don't know how fresh (reliever)
Terry Adams was. I think (the illness) was different than what some
of these guys had. But for about 24 hours, I was worthless.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown (12-5) allowed three runs on five hits in seven innings.
He struck out seven and walked three, but the only inning he
experienced trouble was the sixth, when Geoff Jenkins led off with
a triple and Richie Sexson doubled. Sexson eventually scored on a
groundout to make it 5-3, but Adams pitched the eighth and Jeff
Shaw the ninth for his 22nd save.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Brown) was out there throwing that ball in the first
inning I didn't know if he was going to make it five innings,''
said Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, who had a run-scoring
single in the first inning. ``He didn't look like Brownie in the
first inning. It didn't look like he was going to make it through
the first inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for Milwaukee starter Jeff D'Amico, but
for a different reason. D'Amico (10-5) allowed a season-high five
earned runs, all of which came in the first inning. Shawn Green and
Karros had RBI singles, Hundley had a sacrifice fly and Adrian
Beltre continued his torrid hitting with a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, named the National League player of the week after
batting .536, increased his season-high hitting streak to 10 games
with his 14th homer. He also added a double and is batting .295.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The ball) is like a grapefruit,'' Beltre said. ``I feel good
at the plate, and I have confidence. We saw the pitches pretty good
in the first few innings, but then he did something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, Chan Ho Park, Mark Grudzielanek, Mike Fetters and Gary
Sheffield were hit the hardest by this flu-like bug that surfaced
the first week of July and hasn't gone away. In fact, Sheffield
missed his eighth straight game and remains in Los Angeles trying
to overcome the his sickness. He won't join the Dodgers on the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Dodgers are also short in the outfield. Devon White
already has a strained left quadricep and outfielder Bruce Aven
strained a left oblique muscle during batting practice and was
scratched from the starting lineup. Aven will be re-evaluated
today, but Johnson said it could be as much as two weeks before
he's ready to return.
</P>
<P>
   Aven's injury leaves the Dodgers with two healthy natural
outfielders in Tom Goodwin and Shawn Green. Jim Leyritz started in
left field, and the Dodgers are considering recalling outfielder
Tony Mota from Triple-A Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are also 7-1 without Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good defensively, stringing hits together and
everyone is contributing,'' Karros said. ``That's how you win
games.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
