<SLUG> BC-RECALL-TIRES-LADN </SLUG>
 
CALIFORNIA MOTORISTS TRY SHORTCUTTING TIRE RECALL  &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Replacing defective Firestone tires can be a
costly, time-consuming and frustrating experience, say tire makers,
dealers and crash victims.
</P>
<P>
   Motorists who don't like being on a waiting list for new
Firestones can spend $400-plus to buy competitors' tires and then
wait to be reimbursed.
</P>
<P>
   But California consumers have found that's not necessarily a
quicker solution -- because Firestone's rival tire manufacturers
also are scrambling to meet the demand.
</P>
<P>
   Goodyear Tire &AMP; Rubber Co., for example, said it plans to
increase production of compatible models by 500 percent, but a
spokesman said that will take until the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's not fast enough,'' said Goodyear spokesman
Chuck Sinclair. ``Even with all tire manufacturers making them,
when you've got 6.5 million to get off as quick as possible, it's
not fast enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's subsidiaries, Kelly-Springfield and Dunlop, also
are stepping up production, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But availability of Firestone tires and their replacements made
by other companies is uneven, with Los Angeles dealers in the San
Fernando Valley reporting a heavy volume of inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of tires that aren't available right now because
there's a such a big run on,'' said Terry Freed of Tires Buy Mark.
Freed estimates his small store gets between five and 10 calls a
day from people looking for replacements.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone is advising owners of tires subject to recall to be
patient while enduring waits for replacements reportedly as much as
eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varies from place to place,'' said Bridgestone/Firestone
spokesman Walt Sharp. ``We hope to shorten the time frame all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nashvillle, Tenn.-based company said Monday it has replaced
more than 1 million of the tires subject to recall since Aug. 9.
Federal investigators are examining 62 deaths and more than 100
injuries purportedly caused by the treads of the tires peeling off.
</P>
<P>
   Reseda, Calif., resident Matoux DeLaCroix said he became one of
the most recent victims of the peeling tread Friday night, as he
and his 9-year-old daughter drove through Bakersfield.
</P>
<P>
   DeLaCroix said he and daughter, Erica, sustained minor injuries
after the tread on his Firestone ATX tire peeled away and his 1996
Ford Explorer spun out and flipped. California Highway Patrol
officers called the peeling tire a factor in the crash, though they
added DeLaCroix swerved incorrectly in response.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, he had tried to get replacement tires from a
Firestone dealership in the San Fernando Valley, in Northridge, and
was told the wait was between three and eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just find the whole thing outrageous,'' said DeLaCroix, who
is contemplating legal action. ``It's unbelievable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the tires can get replacements from any tire company
that makes compatible sizes. They will be reimbursed up to $100 per
tire. Firestone dealers also offer free inspections on request.
</P>
<P>
   The company is recommending affected tire owners keep their tire
pressure at 30 pounds per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything we can to make tires as quickly as
possible,'' said Bridgestone/Firestone spokesman Doug McGraw.
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
