<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4934 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-GUNS-BILL_CORRECTIVE-     08-29 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-BILL_CORRECTIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    NEW HANDGUN-CONTROL BILL PASSESCALIFORNIA SENATE
</HEADLINE>

 &HT;    (Eds, this story was mistakenly slugged ``BILLS-SFVALLEY'' in
the budget)(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The California Senate recently passed tough
handgun control legislation that requires safety classes and
licensing of owners, but the measure faces an uncertain future in
the Assembly and a likely veto by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Jack Scott, D-Pasadena, authored the bill as a means
of reducing gun crimes and accidents. It passed 22-15 with strong
support from Democrats and opposition from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns are simply a dangerous product,'' said Scott, an
outspoken proponent of gun control and chairman of the Assembly Gun
Violence Committee, said Monday. ``The more we can train people on
safety and keep others with criminal pasts from buying guns, the
more we'll reduce the number of gun-related deaths and injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   But gun lobbyists voiced strong opposition to the new rules,
arguing they will not have an effect on criminals, who they say
mostly acquire guns illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're targeting the wrong people with this feel-good
legislation,'' said John Snyder of the national Citizens Committee
for the Right to Keep and Bear Arms. ``All this does is require
law-abiding citizens to abide to more laws, instead of addressing
the real criminal element.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott, who lost his 27-year-old son, Adam, in a gun accident in
1993, argued the primary impact of the bill would be to reduce
accidents by raising safety standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't allow car buyers to simply drive off the lot,'' Scott
said, ``you have to have a license.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill requires all gun buyers except law enforcement
officials to attend a safety course and pass tests on proper gun
handling, target shooting, and a written test on handgun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers also would have to undergo a background check before
being issued a 5-year renewable license -- with a maximum price tag
of $25 -- from the state Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The bill could be vetoed by Gov. Gray Davis, who, when passing a
landmark set of gun control laws last year, said he wants time to
measure their effectiveness before signing any new gun legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor doesn't want to see any more gun legislation
until the new laws passed last year are given a chance to work,''
said Davis spokesman Roger Salazar. ``However, he has not stated
his position on AB 273, and he'll be taking a close look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bills signed by Davis last year made California one of the
toughest states on gun control, enacting trigger-lock requirements,
expanding bans on assault weapons and banning low-priced Saturday
night specials.
</P>
<P>
   Before reaching Davis, the bill must pass a second Assembly vote
with the amendments added by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has until Sept. 30 to make a decision on all legislation
acted on by the Legislature this week in the session's closing
days. The governor usually has 12 days to make a decision on bills,
but end-of-session rules extend the time because of the large
number of laws being acted on as the Legislature wraps up.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, the law would take effect in July 2002 and be
applicable only to new gun purchases. Current gun owners would not
have to apply for licenses for guns bought before then.
</P>
<P>
   Gun-control advocates, including Mary Leigh Blek, president of
the Million Mom March, also are lobbying state lawmakers to
eventually pass legislation requiring all gun owners to register
with the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Licensing alone can be a very powerful preventive measure,''
she said. ``But we hope that the Assembly will reconsider annual
gun registration during its next legislative session.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
