<HEADER>
A4935 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GLF-WOODS_GARCIA-LADN     08-29 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-WOODS_GARCIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERGIO TURNS OUT TIGER`S LIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY MORGAN  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM DESERT _ So that's how you beat Tiger Woods.
</P>
<P>
   You make him win a tournament in almost total darkness the
previous day, have him come back early the next morning to put on a
clinic and force him to fly cross-country for another round of golf
later that afternoon. Throw in the lingering effects of a cold, and
there is a pretty good chance the unquestioned No.1 player in the
world might not be at his best.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what happened Monday at Bighorn Country Club,
where Spanish sensation Sergio Garcia, ranked 15th in the world,
upset an admittedly weary Woods 1 up in a prime-time television
golf event, the much-hyped ``Battle of Bighorn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I was this tired? I don't know, maybe finals
week,'' Woods joked after Garcia clinched the victory with a
10-foot putt for birdie on the par-4, 355-yard 18th hole. ``I've
had three pretty good weeks, and it just builds up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My body broke down two days early. If it had happened
tomorrow, I couldn't have cared less.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said he was tired, too, after flying in from last
weekend's Reno-Tahoe Open. He tied for 17th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt pretty good until 17,'' he said. ``Then I was a little
tired. After the putt on 18, I was a lot tired.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's competition, which included portable lights
illuminating the final four holes, turned out to be an entertaining
match between two of the world's best, young players. Woods, in
particular, has been brilliant lately. His amazing run has
included, for example, a thrilling playoff victory over former La
Habra resident Bob May in the PGA Championship two weeks ago. Then
he breezed to an 11-shot victory in this past weekend's NEC
Championship in Akron, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Woods returned to Firestone Country Club early Monday morning to
put on a clinic, then flew to Southern California for Monday's $1.5
million match. It was the second time he had been involved in such
a showcase he defeated David Duval in last year's ``Showdown at
Sherwood'' at Sherwood Country Club but his luck finally ran out
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who won $1.1 million to Woods' $400,00, started with a
bogey on the first hole to immediately fall one down, and wasted a
chance to even the match by three-putting for bogey on the par-4,
367-yard fourth hole. But he played impressively from that point,
and birdied four of his final holes for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with a six-under-par 66 to Woods' 67.
</P>
<P>
   The shot of the day might have come on the par-4, 351-yard 14th
hole. Woods had hit a sand wedge to within two feet for a conceded
birdie, and Garcia was 25 feet short. But he made the putt to keep
the match even.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very important putt,'' said Garcia, who admitted he
had trouble seeing the cup because of increasing darkness. ``When
it was four feet short of the hole, I was trying to see where the
hole was. Then when it got closer, I said,`Hey, that's looking
good.'''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia saved par from 10 feet after a bad chip to halve the next
hole, and he curled in a 40-footer on the par-3, 180-yard 16th to
take his first lead of the day. Woods missed left and never
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' loss continued a surprising lack of success in match
play. Not counting his three consecutive U.S. Amateur
championships, he is 3-6-1 in the Ryder and Presidents cups. He
also lost last year's match-play championship to Darren Clarke in a
36-hole final at La Costa.
</P>
<P>
   Woods said he wasn't overly upset with Monday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had better days,'' he said, ``and I've had shorter
days.''
</P>
</TEXT>
