</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ABORTION (Mexico City) _ Abortion rights groups across
Mexico celebrate a defensive victory, in the face of resurgent
efforts by political and church leaders to promote socially
conservative policies. By Ginger Thompson. 1,600 words.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GULEN (Istanbul) _ The Turkish government has dropped
sedition charges against Getullah Gulen, a religious leader who
lives in Pennsylvania. Gulen is the head of a prospering Islamic
community with hundreds of schools in Turkey, the Balkans and
Central Asia. For mny years he was an unofficial ambassador for
Turkey who promoted a moderate brand of Islam. He preached
tolerance, meeting with Pope John Paul II and other religious and
political leaders, among them Turkey's prime ministers and
presidents. By Douglas Frantz.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCOUTS-GAYS (Undated) _ In the two months since the Supreme
Court ruled that the Boy Scouts have a constitutional right to
exclude gays, corporate and governmental support for the
organization has slipped markedly. Chicago, San Diego and San Jose,
Calif., have told local Scout troops that they can no longer use
parks, schools and other municipal sites. Companies like Chase
Manhattan Bank and Textron Inc., have withdrawn hundreds of
thousands of dollars in support to local and national scouting
groups nationwide. Dozens of United Ways from Massachusetts to San
Francisco have cut off money amounting to millions of dollars each
year. By Kate Zernike. 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BLOOD-PRESSURE (Undated) _ Calcium channel blockers, the
second-most popular kind of drug used to lower high blood pressure,
is less effective than other drugs in preventing heart attacks and
heart failure, according to a study being reported Tuesday. By
Lawrence K. Altman. 1,400 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VENICE-SINKING (Undated) _ An American archaeologist
studying the origins of Venice has stumbled on clues suggesting
that a multibillion-dollar plan to build floodgates to save the
city from rising waters is doomed. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT8,9, and a graphic are being sent to NYT
photo and graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GRAVITY (Undated) _ Can empty space be stirred like pancake
batter? According to Einstein's theory of relativity, the gravity
of a spinning object should tug slightly on the surrounding space
and slowly drag it around in circles. Any matter would be pulled
along, even though ordinary gravity can only attract matter, not
push it sideways. Observational astronomers have remained skeptical
of that supremely bizarre prediction, since they have never found
clear, direct proof that the phenomenon exists. But with the
discovery of a strange new signal by the Rossi X-ray Timing
Explorer, a NASA satellite designed to measure X-ray sources in
deep space, a few more astronomers may be ready to get on board. By
James Glanz. (2000 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphoc clients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INDIAN-ASTRONOMY (Undated) _ As part of a new emphasis on
the astronomy of other cultures, Chicago's Adler Planetarium and
Astronomy Museum has revived Skidi Pawnee astronomy in a sky show
that is unusual among cultural shows. To create the show, ``Spirits
From the Sky, Thunder on the Land,'' the Adler astronomers took
their research beyond books and records and onto the Pawnee
reservation where they sought out members of the Skidi Pawnee tribe
to work with them in creating the show. Ann E. Ruderman. (575
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-NORTH-POLE (Undated) _ Recent eyewitness reports of open
water from melting ice at the North Pole have prompted
climatologists and other scientists to make a closer study of
satellite imagery and other observations of northern sea ice, past
and present. They have found substantial evidence that on average
Arctic temperatures in the winter have risen 11 degrees over the
past 30 years and in the late 20th century were the warmest in four
centuries. By John Noble Wilford. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-TURKEY-ARCHEO (Undated) _ Reconstructing a damaged ancient
sculpture recently excavated was a small but satisfying triumph for
archaeologists working in Aphrodisias, Turkey, a field of dreams
for the study of art and architecture of antiquity. Spreading over
a broad plain is an extravagance of well preserved stone remains of
a prosperous provincial city: from a huge theater on high ground to
the squares and building walls of the civic center and beyond to
the standing and fallen columns of the Temple of Aphrodite and then
the stadium that once seated 30,000. By John Noble Wilford. (2175
words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT10,11,12 are being sent to NYT photo
clients)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on new
uses for lard as a fuel, crocodile hearts and space dust. By Henry
Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MEN-OSTEOPOROSIS (Undated) _ Osteoporosis, known as the
``silent disease,'' often has no symptoms until the bones are so
comporomised that a minor trauma causes a fracture. As awareness of
osteoporosis in postmenopausal women has grown, it has become more
common for them to get routine bone density tests. Men, though, are
rarely given bone density tests unless they have significant
symptoms. Even when an older man breaks a lesser bone or loses
height due to bone loss, two red flags in postmenopausal women,
many physicians still don't consider that he may have osteoporosis.
By Laurie Tarkan. (1580 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT13,14 are being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-FEEDING (Undated) _ A recent study in India suggests
that breast-feeding alone may not provide enough sustenance to
babies in developing nations when their mothers are severely
malnourished. The report adds to a renewed debate about a
decade-old campaign by the World Health Organization and other
United Nations agencies that advocate an exclusive reliance on
breast milk for the first six months of life. By Barbara Crossette.
(860 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IRRITABLE-BOWEL (Undated) _ Citing ``rare but serious
risks'' from Lotronex, a drug prescribed for women with irritable
bowel syndrome, the Food and Drug Administration has ordered that a
warning pamphlet be attached to each bottle of pills to alert
consumers to early signs of dangerous side effects. By Denise
Grady. (860 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ The Personal Health column: In the
United States, the incidence of melanoma, the most serious form of
skin cancer, is rising at an exponential rate: 4 percent a year for
20 years, accompanied by an increase in melanoma deaths. One person
in 74 can now expect to develop melanoma at some point, up from one
in 1,500 in 1935 and one in 250 two decades ago. By Jane E. Brody.
(1225 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WEIGHTS-RISK (Undated) _ With more people training with
weights, many more are being injured, especially those over 50. By
Linda Villarosa. (825 words)
