<P>
   CAMPAIGN-DEBATES (Washington) _ The candidates' positions on
debates seems to be as divergent as their competing plans for tax
cuts. Al Gore wants to participate in as many as possible; George
W. Bush is willing to join a handful, but he wants to control the
format as much as possible, and in the process he's challenging the
organization the parties set up in 1984 to hold presidential
debates. The commission plans to hold the first one at the John F.
Kennedy School of Government, but the Bush camp considers Boston to
be hostile turf. Bush also wants a more relaxed format ... more
like a Larry King show than Lincoln-Douglas. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RAY (Washington) _ An exclusive interview with Robert
Ray, the independent counsel. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   WORKPLACE-WORRIES (Boise, Idaho) _ Behold the new face of the
American worker. Economists say few people fret over whether they
can find jobs in the 10th year of the nation's longest stretch of
uninterrupted economic growth. But many employees say they are
concerned about whether they can keep up with technological change
and take advantage of opportunities in ``new economy'' companies.
And many either fear what will happen to their current job or have
looked but did not find another job good enough to persuade them to
jump. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: GRAPHIC is being sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   OPTIONS-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ It is one of the prettiest lies
in corporate America. Stock options dispensed to executives and
workers are not accounted for as an employee expense, even though
they clearly are. So companies that reward their employees with
stock options do not include the costs of those programs in their
overall expenses, giving their earnings a boost. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   COURVOISIER-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Courvoisier is definitely not
just the emperor's brandy anymore. By Bernard Stamler.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   COLLINS-COLUMN _ Gail Collins on Wen Ho Lee
</P>
<P>
   Thomas L. Friedman is on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moved in ``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MET-ASIAN-ART (New York) _ Thirty years ago, Asian art led a
marginal life at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. In 1970 the only
Chinese work on view was a room of Buddhist sculpture and a few
cases of ceramics. As late as 1990, Indian art meant an assortment
of objects crammed into dimly lighted vitrines on the Great Hall
balcony. Things have changed. The museum now has more than 50
permanent galleries devoted to the largest and most comprehensive
collection of Asian art under one roof anywhere. These days the Met
is fond of calling itself a ``museum of Asian art within a
museum,'' and it's justified in doing so. By Holland Cotter. (2000
words)
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-DESERT-EXHIBIT (Paris) _ With the arrival of photography
in the mid-19th century, the desert entered the European
imagination. Endless sand dunes in the Sahara became metaphors for
the grandiosity of Nature, camel trains and nomadic tribesmen
evoked romance and mystery. Of course the first desert
photographers were not artists, but explorers and scientists. Yet
their work passed one test of art: it made people dream. It is no
great leap, then, a century and a half later, to commission 10
European and American artists to travel into the desert and record
their reactions to it. The result is ``The Desert,'' a show at the
Cartier Foundation for Contemporary Art in Paris through Nov. 5. By
Alan Riding.
</P>
<P>
   LIGHT-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Rebecca Goldstein's characters are
descendants of Ingmar Bergman's chilly intellectuals and
Hawthorne's cold-hearted curmudgeons. They want to subordinate the
heart to the head, the spirit to the word; they dream of perfectly
controlled worlds, where messy emotions are subjugated to the
ordering dictates of reason. Michiko Kakutani reviews Goldstein's
new novel ``Properties of Light.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NYT News Service &LR;  &QL;
</P>
