<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARINERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEMENS IS AT HIS OVERPOWERING BEST
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ No words were necessary for the Seattle Mariners to
confirm to the baseball world Monday night that Roger Clemens, even
at his advanced age, is a dominant pitcher, one of the best. The
swings they produced said everything about the quality of Clemens'
overpowering stuff.
</P>
<P>
   There were weak swings and half swings and check swings, little
ground balls and pop-ups. There were no good swings, no hard rips
until Alex Rodriguez's single leading off the eighth. Rodriguez and
Al Martin were the only Seattle batters to pull the ball with
authority against Clemens, who pitched seven scoreless innings,
allowing five hits and striking out seven, as the New York Yankees
wiped out Seattle, 9-1, and increased their lead over Boston in the
American League East to five games. The Mariners have lost 13 of
15, and their advantage over Oakland in the West has shrunk to a
game and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens' earned run average of 3.65 is the second best in the
American League, behind Boston's Pedro Martinez, and his 11-6
record could be significantly better; the bullpen has blown five
leads for him.
</P>
<P>
   While Clemens was on the disabled list in June, his right groin
muscle healed, and as a result, he was able to make a necessary
adjustment to his mechanics, through the guidance of the pitching
coach Billy Connors. Clemens, a right-hander, had fallen into the
habit of swinging his left leg in a long arc as he worked from the
windup, perhaps to compensate for the problem in his groin.
</P>
<P>
   Connors suggested that Clemens draw his leg almost straight up,
with little swinging in his foot; this way, he can keep his body
and weight mostly centered over the pitching rubber before driving
forward toward the plate. The principle is the same in many
athletic functions, whether shooting free throws or throwing a
baseball: eliminate the unnecessary movement.
</P>
<P>
   With his legs healthy, Clemens has been able to throw in this
way and his fastball has been explosive and consistent. There may
have been only two or three games in his time with the Yankees that
Clemens has had a fastball as good or better than he did against
the Mariners Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens seemed to want the Seattle hitters to know exactly how
hard he was throwing _ 94 to 95 mph consistently, reaching 96 mph
once _ because he fired his second pitch of the game over the head
of the catcher and umpire and thumped it loudly against the
backstop. Later in the inning, he pushed Edgar Martinez away from
the plate with inside fastballs, prompting Seattle manager Lou
Piniella to push himself away from the Mariners bench and remark on
the brushback pitches to his own players.
</P>
<P>
   Piniella's voice had already been heard in the Yankees' first
at-bat. Derek Jeter dived back into first base after rounding the
bag and was called safe on a tag play _ wrongly, as a replay
showed, and then Piniella argued. Then, with two outs, the Yankees
leading by 1-0 with a runner at first base, Paul Abbott zipped a
fastball near the inside corner against Jose Canseco. Strike three
to end the inning, Abbott thought; ball two, according to the
rookie home plate umpire Scott Packard.
</P>
<P>
   Canseco smashed Abbott's next pitch about 430 feet, his 13th
home run increasing the Yankees' lead to 3-0, and Piniella yelled
and screamed at Packard from the dugout before the Mariners batted.
Clemens did his fair share of staring and glaring at Packard during
the evening, shaking his head and barking words as he came off the
mound after disagreements in the fifth and seventh innings. It was
as if Clemens and Piniella, with about 50 years of major league
experience between them, were engaged in a tug-of-war over
Packard's strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens may have walked away believing Packard stingy, but it is
scary to imagine what Clemens might have accomplished with a wider
strike zone. He struck out three in the first inning, getting ahead
in the count with the fastball and finishing off the Seattle
hitters with his split-fingered fastball. Fastball, splitter, just
those two; he did not throw his slider until the 55th pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners collected five hits, but all the swings were
defensive, their rallies somewhat pathetic. The
right-handed-hitting Mike Cameron reached to poke a 95-mph fastball
with two outs in the second and dumped a single over first base.
Dan Wilson hit a soft liner through the middle, and Clemens walked
Mark McLemore to load the bases, before Rickey Henderson lofted a
fly to short center. Bernie Williams raced in and made a sliding
catch Clemens whiffed two more in the fourth and struck out
McLemore on three pitches leading off the fifth. With two walks and
another soft single, the Mariners loaded the bases again in the
fifth. But both Martinez and John Olerud, accomplished hitters,
popped up harmlessly. They were overmatched. Clemens' strikeout of
Cameron in the sixth was his 150th of the season; at 38 years 24
days old, he became the oldest Yankee to strike out 150 in a
season.
</P>
<P>
   He has 3,458 for his career, only 50 short of reaching Walter
Johnson's 3,508 strikeouts, which are No. 7 on the career list. He
has 258 victories. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
