<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE JAYS DOUBLE UP ON ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ It figured there'd be a flock of home runs when the
American League's heaviest hitters, the Toronto Blue Jays and the
Angels, got together Monday night, and given the added jolt of
swinging away in a ballpark named for a power company.
</P>
<P>
   What didn't figure was the fact the Angels hit into more
rally-killing double plays than they hit home runs, never a good
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto belted three homers for a major league-leading 217 and,
more importantly, a 4-2 victory over the Angels before 17,483 fans
at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels hit just one home run, their 200th, second only to
the Blue Jays in the A.L. But the Angels also grounded into three
double plays, a little surprising in as much as they've grounded
into fewer DPs than all but one A.L. club.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Salmon hit the Angels' lone home run, his 31st, coming just
one day after hitting his 30th, which made the Angels the
first-ever A.L. team with four 30-or-more-homer men.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays will get there soon enough _ they've got two with
more than 30 now, two others close _ and, the way they're going,
could wind up with six 30-plus homer hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Delgado (No.39), Jose Cruz Jr. (28) and vagabond Dave
Martinez (five), who's playing for his eighth club
</P>
<P>
   fourth this year hit the Blue Jays' homers, all with the bases
empty.
</P>
<P>
   And all of them off of Ramon Ortiz, the third time this season
he's given up three home runs in a game.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the presence of the hot-hitting Delgado, who's making
a strong pitch to win the A.L. Triple Crown _ no one's done that in
33 years _ and Darin Erstad on the same field livened the debate
over who's the league's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado won round one. His homer gave him the A.L. lead, he's
hitting .361, second in the loop to Boston's Nomar Garciaparra
(.371), and he's third in runs batted in with 118.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad had one hit, a lead-off single, but also grounded into
one of the Angels' three double plays. He's hitting .360.
</P>
<P>
   The question was put to Angels manager Mike Scioscia before the
game: How do you pitch to a guy like Deldago?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not a fluke. There aren't a lot of holes. It'll be a
challenge for us to make the pitches to get him out. He's a
legitimate MVP candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   So, who would Scioscia vote for _ if he had a vote?
</P>
<P>
   ``I still like Erstad,'' he said. ``Carlos is a dangerous
hitter, and he's got great numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, when it comes to what a guy means to a ballclub ...
taking in everything, his production, his defense ... I like what
Ersty's done for this club.''
</P>
<P>
   At least the double play Erstad hit into produced a run.
</P>
<P>
   But it was far from enough against Toronto's Esteban Loaiza
(8-9), who scattered seven hits over seven innings, enabling the
Blue Jays to win for only the sixth time in their last 18 road
games.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the Angels three games back of Cleveland in the
A.L. wild-card race. Toronto's right there, too, just a game
behind.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado homered in the second inning, his 87th extra-base hit to
tie the Blue Jays' club record set last season by Shawn Green, now
with the Dodgers; Cruz homered in the third and Martinez, who's hit
safely in 18 games in a row, in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have now been hammered 197 home runs, second only to
the 200 that Kansas City pitchers have allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got an unearned run in the third to get to within a
run, 2-1, when Bengie Molina scored from third as Erstad grounded
into a double play.
</P>
<P>
   But Mo Vaughn hit into a double play in the sixth, just before
Salmon hit his home run. And the Angels missed their biggest
opportunity in the eighth, when they had two on and only one out.
But reliever John Frascatore struck out Salmon, the third time he
fanned, and got Garret Anderson, who had two hits to reach 1,000
for his career, to ground into a force out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
