<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN     08-29 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LLOYD-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
MS. SOCIAL CHARMER A SLACKER AT WORK  &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)
 &HT;    (Ken Lloyd _ a specialist in organizational behavior _ is a
columnist for the Los Angeles Daily News. His column moves Mondays
in the ``f'' financial news file. Send your questions to P.O. Box
260057, Encino, Calif. 91426 or by electronic mail to
LloydOnJobaol.com. Names will be withheld upon request.) 
By KEN LLOYD  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   Q: There is a very popular employee in my department. She is
well-liked by her fellow employees and by many of my peers in
management. The problem is her work, it is often sloppy and late,
and she does not seem concerned about it. I have talked to her
about this, but she seems to think she is so well-liked that
nothing can happen to her. I am ready to terminate her but am
concerned about the backlash against me. Any suggestions? T.R. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: As a manager, sometimes you have to take an unpopular stance
when dealing with a popular person. Be sure you have documented her
performance, discussed it with her, and given her the opportunity
and support to improve it.
</P>
<P>
   If you have done so, only to find she continues to believe
popularity is more important than productivity, it is time to make
a managerial decision. And this decision should not be based on her
popularity, or on the impact the decision will have on your
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Before taking this action, however, consider one unique aspect
of this situation: Employees who do not carry their weight
typically are regarded with disdain rather than adoration. This
worker's popularity indicates she must have some rather compelling
people skills -- which raises the question of whether she is simply
in the wrong position.
</P>
<P>
   Many companies today are trying to fit jobs to people, rather
than fitting people into jobs. If there is a more people-oriented
position in your firm, perhaps she would fare better in it. At the
same time, if there is no appropriate internal option for her, then
it is time for the external option. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whenever I talk with my manager, he inevitably brings up my
co-workers and tells me things about them that are not my business.
He likes to talk about who is struggling and whom he just
counseled. This puts me in a bad position, but I don't want to tell
my manager how to manage. What do you suggest? L.A. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: You are in a bad position, and your manager is in the wrong
position. This single act clearly indicates he has a long way to go
before he is ready for prime time. It sounds like your company is
either overly eager to fill managerial slots on the organization
chart or it lacks adequate communication, education and follow-up
with the managerial staff.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, you do not want to tell your manager how to manage, yet
you can still discuss his babbling. One approach that may protect
his ego and protect you is to mention you are concerned about his
openness. By using the word ``openness,'' already you are placing
your comments in a positive context.
</P>
<P>
   The next step is to mention it is not really fair to your fellow
employees for you to have this kind of information about them. And
further, it may not even be fair to your manager himself, since
other employees might be upset if they learn about this.
</P>
<P>
   If he does not get this obvious message from you, there will be
plenty of other messages he is bound to miss as well. When this
occurs, it should only be a matter of time before senior management
send him the clearest message of all. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last week my manager told me that I am too focused on family
matters and I need to pay more attention to work. I have no idea
where this comment came from. I asked for some examples, but he
couldn't think of any specifics. That's how the discussion ended,
but I'm concerned about what's happening. Should I do anything
else? H.M. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: Whether dealing with employees, children or pets, most people
know that the time to provide feedback is as close to the behavior
in question as possible. If your family dog has chewed up a family
heirloom, it's not going to do much good to confront Fido three
weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   When managers stockpile their concerns about an employee and
then unload at a later date, the employee's reaction is a
combination of defensiveness, denial and distress. If an employee
is engaging in a behavior inappropriate for the job, the manager
should discuss the situation with him or her at the time. That's
the best way to have any kind of acceptance, credibility and
impact.
</P>
<P>
   You should revisit this situation with your manager. Tell him
you have thought very carefully about it and you still do not see
any family interference in your work. In addition, suggest that if
he ever sees such interference, you would like to discuss it with
him at that time. It is hoped he will not need any more feedback
about his feedback. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ken LLoyd, Ph.D., is a specialist in organizational behavior.
Questions can be sent by electronic mail to lloydonjobaol.com, or
they can be mailed to PO Box 260057, Encino, CA 91426. Names will
be withheld upon request. Lloyd's newest book is ``Jerks at Work:
How to Deal with People Problems and Problem People.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
