<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS, CLEMENS EXTEND MARINERS' MISERFY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ When manager Lou Piniella walked off the field after
batting practice, the fans behind the dugout greeted him with a
loud chorus of ``Happy Birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he wanted for his birthday, Piniella replied, ``A win
would be nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe next time, that is, if the current losing stretch doesn't
kill him. Monday night, Roger Clemens and the Yankees presented
their former player, manager and general manager with yet another
clubhouse-quieting loss, wrapping up the Mariners 9-1 and sending
another sellout crowd home wondering when _ or if _ their team will
turn itself around.
</P>
<P>
   It was another loss of missed opportunities and stranded
baserunners, and this one left the crowd occasionally jeering late
in the game before derisively cheering when the Mariners finally
scored a run in the ninth inning on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating obviously,'' said starter Paul Abbott, who
allowed eight runs in seven-plus innings. ``But we're going to wake
up tomorrow and be 1(DD) games up in first place and that's
reality. And there's a lot of season left to play, and that's
reality. But there isn't a guy in this clubhouse who isn't
frustrated. This is too long for a slump.''
</P>
<P>
   The 19-inning victory over the Red Sox, the road trip to New
York and Chicago ... it all seems like a long time ago, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Truthfully, I'm concerned about everything,'' Piniella said,
telling reporters there will be lineup changes for tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just might shake the whole lineup up, put some different
people out there and let them play and see what happens. Playing
the same people right now hasn't been the answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have lost 13 of their past 15 games, watching a
once healthy seven-game lead wither to 1(DD) games over Oakland.
Even with their great road trip to New York and Chicago at the
start of the month, the Mariners are playing sub.-500 baseball
since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   Mondayh's game was the ninth in which Seattle has allowed at
least nine runs during the slide, the third time in four games the
Mariners have scored one run or fewer and the second time this
homestand they haven't managed an extra-base hit. They've been
outscored 122-66 in their past 15 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to start winning,'' Piniella said. ``We can talk about
all the positives you want but the most important thing you can do
is win.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, about the last opponent a struggling team wants to
see is Clemens and the Yankees. Clemens has more wins (21) against
the Mariners than any other pitcher and has been beating them since
he set the major league record in 1986 by striking out 20 batters
in one game. Pitching like the Rocket of old, he's 7-0 in 12 starts
since July 2, with an overall record of 11-6.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott, meanwhile, has been Seattle's most effective starter
since the start of June and he pitched fairly well for six innings
Monday. Unfortunately for him, those six innings came between a
three-run first inning and a four-run eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The first inning could have gone very differently, though. After
Abbott walked Luis Polonia to open the game, Derek Jeter followed
with a single to left-center. Polonia went to third on the play and
when Jeter took a wide turn at first, shortstop Alex Rodriguez
threw to first base for a close play. Jeter was ruled safe, though
replays showed he probably was out by a couple inches.
</P>
<P>
   More frustrating to Abbott was a 2-2 pitch he threw to Jose
Canseco with two outs and the score 1-0. Abbott, catcher Dan Wilson
and Piniella all thought it was strike three but home plate umpire
Scott Packard called it a ball. Canseco hit the next pitch, a pitch
that was out of the strike zone, over the fence to make it 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably let that affect me a little bit,'' Abbott said of
the 2-2 pitch. ``But he's still Canseco and extremely strong. And
he was able to hit a pitch out that most people couldn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I created a hole for myself early and when you do that it
makes it hard for good things to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to leave Piniella squawking from the dugout
between innings, presumeably at the umpires.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's amazing how when we don't get a call or make a mistake,
the other team capitalizes on it right away,'' Piniella said.
``That's what happened in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our chances early in the ballgame if we could have
gotten some hits with men on base and just couldn't do it. They
did. They got the hits when they needed it and beat us handily.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-inning runs were more than enough for Clemens, who
threw hard and just wildly enough to keep batters jumpy (he fired
two pitches to the backstop). Clemens held the Mariners to five
singles and walked four in seven-plus innings, struck out seven and
worked out of two bases-loaded jams.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
