<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 03:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-OLY-SAFRICA-SPI &LR;      08-29 2322
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SAFRICA-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL BRINGS SOUTH AFRICA NEW SENSE OF HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM CAPLE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A softball player, cyclist, wrestler and tennis player
filed lawsuits when they were left off their respective U.S.
Olympic team rosters this year. Salt Lake officials face a possible
criminal trial for their role in the Olympics bribery scandal.
Athletes at the U.S. track and field trials last month were
identified in the results not by their hometown but by the shoe
company sponsoring them.
</P>
<P>
   But just when you question whether the Olympics have outlived
their original purpose, just when you wonder whether the Games are
nothing more than a venue for displaying the latest shoes and
hyping the new prime-time schedule, along comes a team that makes
you reconsider everything. Along comes the South African baseball
team.
</P>
<P>
   The manager is Raymond Tew, a white South African. The batting
coach is Jim Murphy, a graduate of Kentridge High School. The
pitching coach is Jose Alleman, a Cuban who doesn't speak English.
Half the players are white and half are mixed race (or what South
Africans refer to as colored; blacks are a separate group), ranging
in age from 19 to 44. They are teachers and electricians and
plumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, the South African government would have
forbidden these players from competing on the same field. But there
they are, taking grounders and batting practice with what equipment
they have, training to play on the world stage.
</P>
<P>
   Whites and non-whites playing together for post-apartheid South
Africa, with American and Cuban coaches. Interesting, isn't it, how
a 90-foot by 90-foot baseball diamond can hold so much?
</P>
<P>
   ``They say sports brings people together, that it brings
societies together,'' Murphy says. ``That's what we're doing with
the South African Olympic team. ... I feel really fortunate to be a
part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans brought baseball to South Africa during that country's
gold rush during the 1890s, and though the sport did not catch on
to a significant extent, some South Africans have played it at the
club level for decades. Cricket, rugby and soccer are by far South
Africa's most popular team sports, but baseball's popularity is
growing, helped in part by Major League Baseball's international
program.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to truly put the world into a sport with a World Series
(as well as increase revenue sources and the talent pool), MLB
International sends equipment and coaches such as Murphy to 37
countries around the world, ranging from South Africa to Slovenia.
Program specialist Mike McClellan says 170,000 kids have
participated in the South African program the past three years. The
sport is particularly growing among black children, though adult
blacks are all but absent from the high amateur level and not on
the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   Some South Africans are just beginning to feed the U.S. minor
leagues. South African pitcher Tim Harrell is pitching for the
Class A Dodgers team in Vero Beach. Fla. Shortstop Paul Bell is
playing for the Brewers farm team in Helena, Mont. Wes Botha
pitched in the Braves system prior to returning to South Africa
with an injury. The Royals recently hired a part-time scout for the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Still, baseball in South Africa is not the same as baseball in
South Carolina. For one thing, there is the issue of equipment. Or
rather, the lack of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the aluminum bats would crack, and people would keep
using them because they couldn't afford to replace them,'' Harrell
says. ``We have five dozen balls for every game here in Vero Beach.
In South Africa, if we hit a foul ball, we had to chase it no
matter where it was. If it went in the woods or the river, you had
to chase it down. We had maybe two dozen balls for the entire
season. All brown as the dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrell is the son of American Baptist missionaries who raised
their family in South Africa while serving there. He attended
Liberty College in Virginia and was drafted by the Dodgers after
his final season there. His brothers, Richard and Brian, are on the
Olympic team as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``My game really developed when I got to college,'' he says. ``I
don't know if I could ever have had this opportunity (with the
Dodgers) if I hadn't come over here to go to college. Who knows how
many guys over there could make a career of it with better
training.''
</P>
<P>
   Tew, who coaches the South Africa team after installing carpet
all day, took up baseball as age 6 because cricket was too slow for
him. The 50-year-old coach grew up following major league baseball
by watching films of old games sent from the U.S., watching
year-old World Series and All-Star games with friends.
</P>
<P>
   He coached the South Africa team into the Olympics last winter,
leading the plumbers and teachers past Guam in the qualifiying
tournament to secure the final berth in the eight-team field for
Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Of these teens and 40-something parents, among the best players
are Harrell and Bell, the Brewers farmhand. Bell is of mixed race
and the son of Michael Bell, who played for years on a colored club
team in Capetown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know when I'm playing, he's playing with me,'' Bell recently
told the New York Times. ``It makes me feel I'm giving him a part
of his life he never had.''
</P>
<P>
   FROM SEATTLE TO SOUTH AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   A 1985 graduate of Kentridge, Murphy played a couple seasons in
the Chicago Cubs organization before a rare vision problem, dynamic
visual acuity, affected his hitting and forced his retirement in
1991. In addition to hitting poorly, he says, ``I kept getting hit
by pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   He worked for Federal Express in Seattle, parking his truck and
sprinting up hills with packages to meet delivery deadlines. His
love of baseball did not decline, however, and soon he was back
playing in the independent Western League, hitting better than .300
again and rooming with Joe Strong, the 37-year-old who earlier this
season became the oldest rookie to make his major league debut in
40 years.
</P>
<P>
   While Strong reached the majors, Murphy did not, eventually
finding himself at the University of British Columbia, where he
started the school's baseball program from such humble beginnings
that, he says, ``We would get kicked off the field by ultimate
frisbee.''
</P>
<P>
   While at UBC, he met up with an old friend who arranged a
part-time scouting job with the Texas Rangers. He also parlayed a
research paper on the strategies of championship teams into a job
as the hitting coach last year with the Savannah Sand Gnats, the
Rangers' Class A affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, an official with MLB International asked Murphy
whether he could help coach the South Africa team while it trained
for the Olympic qualifying tournament. A month later, he was in
South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   With his background in the low minors, the independent Western
League and UBC, Murphy was as prepared as any American coach could
be for South Africa baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Which is to say, it still was a shock.
</P>
<P>
   For the first couple weeks, there were no bases or batting
helmets. There was no pine tar, either, which wasn't that big a
deal because the team was fortunate to even have bats. Major league
baseball gave Murphy 60 wood bats to take back and the team broke
them so quickly he taped them together as best he could and
rationed them.
</P>
<P>
   The field was a converted cricket field with no infield dirt and
no cutouts for the bases. Players slid on the grass, risking knee
and ankle injuries. There was no locker room; the players would
come to practice straight from work and change clothes in what
passed as a dugout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The level of play is like a junior college league in the
states. It's not real high,'' Murphy says. ``Our national team
would easily beat a junior college team, but if we played a
best-of-seven series, it would be tough. Our No. 1 pitcher is Tim
Harrell, but after him it drops off quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim's done a good job,'' Tew says. ``He's improved the hitting
by 30 to 40 percent, and his knowledge on defense and offense has
helped, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the players are from all around the country and have
families and jobs they can't leave, the team practices in small
groups in different cities, getting together occasionally on
weekends. They will play only a few pickup games before the
Olympics because there is so little competition.
</P>
<P>
   The South Africa team doesn't have the facilities to videotape
and study performances _ there is only one lighted field _ but one
of the team sponsors proposed another idea last winter. Instead of
watching videotape, he suggested, just watch the pitcher's shadow
to determine whether his arm mechanics were proper.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds ridiculous, but at least they're trying. And, as
Murphy says, ``They don't have to fit into me. I have to fit into
South African culture.''
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA'S PAST AND FUTURE
</P>
<P>
   The International Olympic Committee banned South Africa from
competition from 1964 until 1992 due to its apartheid policies, but
the country won three gold medals in Atlanta and also bid for the
2004 Games. While it is re-emerging in international sports, it
still has so very far to go in so many areas.
</P>
<P>
   When Sports Illustrated's Rick Reilly toured Soweto in 1996, his
tour guide pointed out a shantytown of corrugated tin shacks,
saying, ``Right there was the field where we used to play softball.
... We came to practice one day, and a family was living on third
base. It was their home. Within a week there were 50 houses on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst conditions were in the squatter camps where there
was no running water, no sewers,'' Harrell says. ``They would make
homes out of rusted, corrugated metal. Just absolute, destitute
poverty. Their whole day was to wake up and walk to find firewood
to cook with. There wasn't much of it, so each day, the walk to
find some got longer. ``You would see kids with open sores on their
faces, babies with no clothes. You would wish you could help them,
but you weren't sure how.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the poverty, doctors estimate 10 percent of the
population is infected with HIV, and the country's crime rate is
legendary _ Guam was supposed to play South Africa there last year
but refused due to safety concerns. Two Olympic baseball players
had their car stolen this summer, and the team's center fielder
brought a handgun to practice for protection.
</P>
<P>
   Two car bombs exploded when Murphy was in Cape Town, and he says
several passengers and drivers have been shot there in a transit
war between buses and taxi companies. Murphy says a player told him
that no one wears a seat belt in South Africa because they take too
much time to unlatch during a car-jacking.
</P>
<P>
   His residence last winter was protected by a 6-foot wall, an
iron gate and enough barbed wire to pen in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen so much barbed wire in my life,'' Murphy says.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy says he wondered how the different races would mix, but
says there are no more problems than there would be for a team in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``That seems sort of odd to me, but good of course,'' he says.
``I guess I thought the blacks or coloreds would be bitter, but on
our team and in society I really haven't seen any blatent racism.''
</P>
<P>
   With a half-mixed roster, the South African team is
significantly more diverse than the U.S. baseball squad in Atlanta
four years ago, when Jacque Jones was the team's only
African-American.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any window dressing,'' Tew says. ``We really are
one of the only South African teams that have pushed the question
of color. That is a big part of why we got to go. Yes, we
qualified; however, the South African ruling body said we would go
only if we were medal contenders. But because we represent the
demographics of the new South Africa so well, they wanted us to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the noteable absence of blacks from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy says he initially assumed four or five of the team's
players were black because of their dark skin, but he was informed
they are considered colored by South African standards. There are
no blacks on the South Africa team because, Tew says, the black
community was effectively shut out from baseball until apartheid's
end and adults don't play it (soccer was played in the black
community during apartheid and most of the Olympic soccer team is
black).
</P>
<P>
   With the way the sport is catching on with young people in the
country's overwhelming black majority, however, Tew estimates that
within 10 years the South African national team will be wholly
black.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Murphy says the batboy for the South African team is a
black child named Gift, who plays for a 12-under national team that
recently toured Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look forward to the day the South African team has a black
majority, hopefully with Gift as a player,'' Murphy wrote in a
diary for the MLB International Web site.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa opens the Olympics with games against Cuba and the
U.S., games it is almost certain to lose. Tew thinks South Africa
can beat Italy and the Netherlands but said it would be a ``huge
shock'' to make the medal round.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in this case, winning in Sydney isn't really the point.
After so many years of apartheid, the victory is just playing
together on an Olympic diamond.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could see the team, and the spirit we have and who
mixes together, there aren't any little groups,'' Tew says. ``They
go out and party together, and when they fight, they fight
together. Sports has really brought the country together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very confident that things will really become good in
South Africa. It's a beautiful country; we just need to get more
money and jobs coming into the country. It's getting better, and in
a small way, baseball is playing a part.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Jim Caple can be reached at 206-448-8006
</P>
<P>
   or jimcaple &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
