r a BC-PACKARD-AZR &LR;      08-29 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PACKARD-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-PACKARD-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    PACKARD GOES ON THE BLOCK VIA INTERNET(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BOB GOLFEN(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - The Packard Motor Car Co., a Phoenix-based effort to
resurrect one of the greatest names in motoring, is being auctioned
on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   The fledgling company, which has produced a widely acclaimed
running prototype of a modern V-12 Packard, is being sold on the
Internet lock, stock and barrel, according to Roy Gullickson, the
Phoenix engineer and businessman who unveiled his prototype about
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Gullickson is selling the Packard name, its classic logo, the
prototype car, a full-size styling model, factory equipment and
other pieces of his company to the highest bidder. The sale is
necessary, he said, because he hasn't attracted enough investors to
start a factory to build his dream car, the ``ultraluxury'' Packard
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see what happens,'' Gullickson said, still hoping he can
make a go at manufacturing. ``Maybe it will shake some investment
people out of the bushes.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneur said 85 orders already have been placed for the
Packard 12, an extravagant automobile that would compete with such
foreign luxury brands as Rolls-Royce and Mercedes-Benz and sell at
prices well over $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Kruse, president of Kruse International, which is handling
the sale for eBay, said the trademarked Packard logo alone is worth
considerable money. That piece of script lettering goes back to
1902 and recalls a powerful automobile of huge proportions and
beautiful styling. Packards built before World War II are highly
prized by collectors, many of whom yearn to see Gullickson revive
the power and prestige of the brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the Packard people want to see a revival of the car,''
said Ken McCartney, vice president the Packards International Club
in Arizona. ``To my mind, he (Gullickson) has done an amazing job.
He's carried it off very, very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Kruse said his 30-year-old auction company, which was bought by
eBay a year ago, has sold some prototypes and abortive
manufacturing endeavors in the past ``but not with a trademark like
Packard, which is one of the greatest names in automobiles.''
</P>
<P>
   Gullickson would not reveal his reserve, which represents the
lowest price he'll accept for the Packard company. And Kruse would
not speculate as to its value, saying only that Gullickson has a
lot of money invested, ``like 7 or 10 million.''
</P>
<P>
   The auction goes up on eBay on Thursday and concludes on Sept.
4. Kruse said that when the Packard Motor Car Co. shows up on eBay,
it will appear like any other auction item, though with a longer
description and more information.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to sell a Beanie Baby or something on eBay, it's
just a couple of lines,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Kruse International, which was founded in Scottsdale in 1970 by
Dean Kruse's father, Russell, conducts an auction every January in
Scottsdale, one week before the local Barrett-Jackson Classic Car
Auction.
</P>
<P>
   The two auctions were founded together, with Russell Kruse
teaming up with Thomas Barrett and Russell Jackson to put on the
first auction events. Nowadays, Kruse International conducts more
than 60 classic-car auctions around the globe, Dean Kruse said.
</P>
<P>
   The Packard sale will coincide with Kruse's biggest classic-car
auction of the year in its home base of Auburn, Ind. Kruse said the
sale the company will be accompanied with equivalent show-biz
hoopla.
</P>
<P>
   On the last day of the huge Auburn event, the Packard Motor Car
Co. will come up on the block, possibly with the lavish prototype
car driven up on stage, Kruse said. At that point, the eBay bidding
and the live bidding will merge, with the crowd in Auburn vying
against the Online offers.
</P>
<P>
   Gullickson said if the company fails to reach its potential at
auction, he'll go on with his manufacturing plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a pretty low reserve, we feel, and if that isn't
reached, we'll carry on with our search for investors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Kruse said he's confident the bidding will surpass the
reserve and the company will sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for investors - we're looking for a buyer,''
he said. ``We've had a lot interest in this.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like anybody's baby. He just hates to give it up.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach the reporter at bob.golfen(a)arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   republic.com or call (602) 444-8106.
</P>
</TEXT>
