<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 08:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-1     08-29 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LEVENDOSKY-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY SLIPS ON OIL CRITICIZING NATIONAL MONUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.)  (In 10thgraf, corrects number and acreage of abolished
monuments.)  
 (EDITOR'S NOTE: Charles Levendosky, editorial page editor of the
Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune, has written about public lands issues
for over a decade and is respected for his insight into these
issues. His e-mail address is levendos(at)trib.com.)  
 By CHARLES LEVENDOSKY   
 c.2000 Casper (Wyo.) Star-Tribune   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Aug. 24, Republican vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney
threw down the gauntlet, challenging the national monuments created
by President Clinton. It was a big mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney knows as much about national monuments as his
presidential running mate, George W. Bush, knows about foreign
policy. Cheney has spent too many years in board rooms in the
company of oil executives in Texas to speak knowledgeably about
this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney made the assertion that if Bush and he were elected, Bush
might make the decision to rescind the national monument status of
the monuments Clinton has created.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Bush were president, he could not rescind a national
monument status. No president can. Only Congress has that
authority.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of the Interior's top legal counsel,
Solicitor John Leshy, ``The attorney general of the United States
issued an opinion in 1938 that said the president could not undo a
national monument, could not undo it in the sense of completely
repealing it. And no president has ever done that. Presidents have
made boundary adjustments, both enlarging and diminishing the size.
That's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, the reasoning was pretty simple; it just said the
Antiquities Act authorizes the president to proclaim monuments but
not to unproclaim them. Only Congress, according to that view, can
`unproclaim' or outright repeal a national monument altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   And Congress doesn't unproclaim national monuments very often.
Practically, it's politically impossible to do so. The American
people want wilderness preserved and protected.
</P>
<P>
   In general, national monument status prohibits any new mineral
exploration, drilling for gas and oil, or mining. Under the new
policy of landscape monuments, the areas are left pristine and
protected from development, as the people want them.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the furor among some members of the Utah congressional
delegation and other Western congressmen when Clinton created the
Escalante-Staircase National Monument in 1996, there has not been a
successful move in Congress to abolish that monument.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the record: Approximately 64 million acres have been set
aside as 110 national monuments since the Antiquities Act was
passed in 1906. Congress has only abolished 10 national monuments _
comprising about 13,000 acres in total. One of the abolished
monuments was later redesignated as a monument under a different
name.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was mistaken in another criticism of the process of
creating national monuments during the Clinton administration. He
asserted that these proclamations are announced ``willy-nilly all
over the West'' without considering the desires of the people who
will be affected.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Cheney bashed the administration's monument
designations, Secretary of the Interior Bruce Babbitt, in an Aug.
23 interview, repeated what he had said many times before, ``We
have a `no-surprise' policy when it comes to recommending national
monuments.''
</P>
<P>
   A no-surprise policy makes good political sense. Babbitt has
traveled from Western state to Western state repeatedly in order to
gauge residents' interest in having a particular locale set aside
as a national monument.
</P>
<P>
   The records show that Babbitt has met with congressional
delegations, with governors and state legislators, with mayors and
local stakeholders and any others who might have some say in the
matter. There have been public hearings in each state where a new
monument was nominated and then created. Discussions about possible
national monument status has been front-page news in the states
affected.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt has even suggested to congressional delegations that
they take the lead in creating greater protection for unique public
landscapes in their states.
</P>
<P>
   Claims that national monument status has been forced down a
state's throat have no factual basis. It would be political suicide
to take such a tactic.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, 80 percent of the population supports the
designation of Aqua Fria National Monument outside of Phoenix. In
other Western states, polls indicate the support for their new
monuments hovers at 75 percent. Nationally, the American people
have shown unwavering support for the new monuments.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, Babbitt sent the president a recommendation that
proposes the creation of the Vermilion Cliffs National Monument in
northern Arizona. The Vermilion Cliffs proposal covers 293,000
acres of federal land and includes the Paria Plateau. It would
continue to be managed by the Bureau of Land Management.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Babbitt recommended that Clinton expand the current
Craters of the Moon National Monument in central Idaho. The
original 54,440-acre monument was created by President Calvin
Coolidge in 1924. Babbitt proposes that it be expanded by 661,000
acres in order to include craters, cones, lava flows, caves and
fissures along a rift that is 65 miles long.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the end of it. Babbitt will make other
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   About other monument proposals, Babbitt said, ``We have a list
of areas that have been publicly discussed, where I have been out
on the ground and engaged all of the stakeholders: Steens Mountain
(Oregon), the Carrizo Plain in California, the Santa Rosa Mountains
in California, the Missouri Breaks (Montana), the Black Ridge area
in Colorado, the San Rafael in Utah. These areas are in the
congressional phase right now. At this point, these are all areas
of possible future recommendations, but they are areas where we
have emphasized our desire to see legislation coming out of the
Congress. With each of these places, we have stuff going in varying
degrees in the Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no ``willy-nilly'' monuments, despite Cheney's
assertions. But, by his statements, Cheney has certainly broadcast
where he stands on environmental issues _ on the side of oil.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
