<SLUG> BC-TECH-KAWASAKI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR GARAGE.COM'S KAWASAKI, NOTHING IS SACRED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLINGAME, Calif. _ Guy Kawasaki is being wicked.
</P>
<P>
   As moderator to a panel of start-up chief executives, he asks a
question he knows will make them squirm.
</P>
<P>
   ``So are venture capitalists good for anything?'' Kawasaki lobs
with deliberate amiability, arching an eyebrow for effect.
</P>
<P>
   A few CEOs nervously chuckle as they ransack their brains for a
diplomatic answer. Kawasaki glows, knowing entrepreneurs privately
loathe venture capitalists _ call them ``vulture capitalists''
behind their backs _ but dare not say so in public for fear of
losing their funding.
</P>
<P>
   Being a troublemaker is all in a day's work for Kawasaki, best
known in Silicon Valley as Apple Computer Corp.'s one-time chief
evangelist (yes, that was the title), the man who turned down the
chance to interview for the CEO position at Yahoo, and now the CEO
of Garage.com, a venture capital firm in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   He is also known here as a ceaseless self-promoter.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Guy does best is promoting Guy,'' said Andy Hertzfeld,
one of the original engineers at Apple and now head of Eazel, a
Linux software company.
</P>
<P>
   This is something Kawasaki happily and bluntly acknowledges in
his one-page biography: ``Guy wasn't the first or the last
Macintosh evangelist, but he took the most credit.''
</P>
<P>
   It's in this realm of in-your-face ``Aikido marketing'' that
Kawasaki has excelled. What makes him bearable in polite company is
his biting humor, which he directs at himself just as often as he
aims it at others.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking to the guy who turned down the opportunity to
interview for the CEO position of Yahoo,'' said Kawasaki in a
recent interview. ``There were 10 search engines at the time,
including one from (Digital Equipment Corp.) called AltaVista. I
couldn't see how Yahoo would make it. So you see how easy it is to
be a bozo.''
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki also turned down the job because he had a second son on
the way, and the commute to work would have been too taxing on his
young family.
</P>
<P>
   Family is something he refers to often. He points out that his
grandfather, an immigrant from Japan, was a taxi driver in Hawaii,
where Kawasaki was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We clearly weren't wealthy industrialists,'' he said. ``And we
didn't make motorcycles, either.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Kawasakis did well. His father, Duke Kawasaki, was a
Democratic state senator for Honolulu. Guy attended college at
Stanford University and majored in psychology. After a week in law
school, he quit because he ``couldn't take it.'' His calling became
clearer while he was attending business school at the University of
California at Los Angeles. He joined a jewelry company as a diamond
counter and left as vice president of sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   His next job was at a software company, which was sold to a
larger company in Atlanta. Not wanting to relocate, Kawasaki cast
about for another job in California. He landed at Apple. It was
1983, and Apple was an irreverent upstart battling a formidable
IBM.
</P>
<P>
   Kawasaki left Apple in 1987, hacked around on various projects,
and eventually returned to Apple in 1995 as chief evangelist. He
left again in 1998 to become CEO of Garage.com, a company that
funds start-ups, matches investors with entrepreneurs, and stages
``boot camps'' throughout the country for would-be entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Kawasaki still has an edge. He rises at 4:45 a.m. three
mornings a week to play basketball. His sarcasm continues to be
unsparing. And he is an unrelenting smart aleck. It's almost as if
he can't help himself.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest book, ``Rules for Revolutionaries: The Capitalist
Manifesto,'' he writes about naysayers, ``The higher you go in a
company, the less oxygen there is, so supporting intelligent life
becomes difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   In another part of the book, he encourages start-ups to slum it.
``A lousy building and lousy furniture are necessary because
suffering is good for revolutionaries,'' he writes. ``It builds
cohesiveness; it creates a sense of urgency; and it focuses the
team on what's most important: shipping'' new products.
</P>
<P>
   Asked for his thoughts on Apple, Kawasaki responds that as a
consumer he would like to see Apple make an ultra-lightweight
laptop to compete with Sony Corp.'s VAIO line of computers. ``I'd
like a laptop I can carry to five meetings a day,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As a strategist, Kawasaki said, ``The bigger challenge for Apple
is that they have to make a computer that kills the Macintosh.
Right now, they're milking the Macintosh. But what they need to do
is jump to the next curve.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kawasaki is a man on today's curve, and he knows it. That's
why he relishes his current position as sifter of ideas for the
next generation of computing.
</P>
<P>
   As CEO of Garage.com, he sees hundreds of business plans float
across his desk each week. Today, the buzz is around companies
built on solid science, as opposed to marketing, he said. Companies
that focus on building the Internet's infrastructure or wireless
technology are hot. Internet retailers are not.
</P>
<P>
   The weirdest proposal he's seen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone actually submitted a business plan for buying a small,
Middle Eastern country and turning it into an amusement park,''
Kawasaki said. ``We turned him down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Alex Pham is a Globe reporter covering Silicon Valley. She can
be reached by e-mail at pham(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
