<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-MINDBRANCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINDBRANCH UPS THE ANTE IN RESEARCH DATA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANTHONY FLINT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Changing the name was the easy part.
</P>
<P>
   Juiced up with an $18 million injection of capital funding, the
sedate-sounding Publications Resource Group in North Adams, Mass.
is now officially known as MindBranch _ aggregator of
technology-oriented market research.
</P>
<P>
   It's a space that's still surprisingly wide open, but the
company is moving quickly to enhance its Web infrastructure to make
gathering corporate intelligence an easy experience. At the top of
the list: fine-tuning the latest technology to establish a feedback
loop for clients, to help narrow and customize future searches.
</P>
<P>
   MindBranch (www.mindbranch.com) claims to have more than 230
partners signed up for its one-stop-shopping site, including
Forrester Research, the Gartner Group, Giga Information Group, and
dozens of small and medium-size outfits.
</P>
<P>
   Companies doing research on competitors, contemplating an
acquisition, or breaking into a new business will enter their
desired subject _ ``optical scanning,'' for example, or ``undersea
cable'' _ and get back the best and latest work from those
publishers: market research reports, newsletters, directories, and
databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the lessons everyone has learned is, you've got to be
vertical. Claiming the high ground is all about focus, and ours is
technology-oriented information,'' said Alton L. Adams, the
43-year-old former president of Standard &AMP; Poors DRI who is
relocating from Boston to the Berkshires to become chief executive
of MindBranch.
</P>
<P>
   Other players in the space, including marketresearch.com,
Dialogue, and Silver Platter, do a fine job of managing information
via the Internet, Adams said, but tend to be more general. The
individual market research companies have their own Web sites, but
they cry out for being gathered together in one place.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to get the best research now, you'd have to go to
30 different places, a significant investment of time and money.
And you're never sure you have the entire universe covered,'' he
said. ``With us, you can get everyone who's done work on a topic,
and compare. In a market that's changing, and with so much
information available, it's important to be able to go to one
place.''
</P>
<P>
   To make the site as cutting-edge as possible, MindBranch is on a
strict schedule to implement technological enhancements, such as
conference Webcasts, real-time market research, online-catalog
searching capability (by concept or intended use of the
information), and, perhaps most ambitiously, a custom-consulting
brokerage.
</P>
<P>
   Industries covered include business and finance, communications,
computers and information technology, consumer products, health
care, industrial markets, the Internet, and manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
   In concept, at least, outsiders agree there's an important
market niche to tap in aggregating research data.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a need for a site like this, which
aggregates all kinds of information,'' said Steve Miyao, senior
vice president at Kasina Strategic E-Business Solutions in New
York. ``People usually have subscriptions with one company, like
Forrester or Gartner, but there's always going to be additional
information they need, or information from a smaller company that's
done a white paper on a given topic. Certainly for publishers, it's
a great way to disseminate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The ability to get the best thinking and insight from all of
the best providers can be a tremendous value, especially in an age
when information is only a commodity to those who get it second or
can't interpret it,'' said Robert Powell, editor of
mutualfunds.com, which plans to offer a similar service but
specifically focused on market research for the mutual fund
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``To do it well, to distinguish themselves, they'll have to
offer customers the most comprehensive, best-in-class, and timely
information available. And the site has got to be easy to use and
well-organized,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   MindBranch got its funding from Internet entrepreneur Bo
Peabody's Village Ventures Inc., which provides capital primarily
for start-ups outside of major metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   MindBranch, which will have 90 employees by the end of the year,
is moving into a long-shuttered department store space on North
Adam's Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Peabody, who is joining the board of MindBranch, said he hopes
the company's success will further establish the Williamstown-North
Adams area as a fledgling ``Silicon Village'' in northern Berkshire
County, just south of the Vermont border.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, who is leaving the cosmopolitan setting of the South End
for a house in Bennington, Vt., said when he first drove to North
Adams it was raining ``and as I checked into the Holiday Inn I
thought, `There's no way I'm moving out here.' But then I met the
young people (at MindBranch) who had so much enthusiasm, and it was
so different from the conservatism of McGraw-Hill (owners of
Standard &AMP; Poors DRI), I completely turned around on it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Flint is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached
by e-mail at flint(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
