<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-ROUNDUP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTALS: A TEST POSTPONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lawsuit against Yahoo Inc. that had been seen as a key test of
online anonymity was withdrawn before any formal arguments could be
made in court.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was brought in May by an Ohio man who said he was fired
after being identified as the author who posted on a Yahoo message
board criticism of his superiors at AnswerThink Consulting Group in
Miami. The man's lawyer argued Yahoo should have done more to
protect his identity, or at least notify him that AnswerThink was
seeking the information. The American Civil Liberties Union had
supported the suit, contending Internet companies give users the
false impression their online musings will be protected.
</P>
<P>
   The arguments will have to wait for another case, however,
following the withdrawal of the suit by the plaintiff, according to
his attorney, Megan Gray of the Baker &AMP; Hostetler law firm in Los
Angeles. Gray declined to discuss the reasons for the action. A
Yahoo attorney said there was no settlement agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the suit, Yahoo's policy had been that it would
disclose information about its users in response to civil
subpoenas. After the suit was filed, Yahoo said it had changed its
rules. Now, it will notify users when their identities are sought
by a third party, and give them 15 days to take legal action.
</P>
<P>
   One of the suit's original supporters, David Sobel, an attorney
with the Electronic Privacy Information Center in Washington,
called Yahoo's new rules an improvement but said he hopes federal
laws will eventually clarify just how much anonymity users should
expect when using pseudonyms online.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothers me the most is that it's entirely
voluntary, and still probably subject to their discretion, and
there's nothing that obligates them to do more'' to protect a
user's identity, Sobel said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Searching unplugged &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AltaVista Co. has introduced what it calls the world's largest
index of Web pages customized for use by mobile phones and palmtop
devices, a listing of 2.7 million pages in all. AltaVista, a
majority-owned unit of CMGI Inc. of Andover, is best known as a
portal site for PC users. But full Web pages usually contain too
much data, up to 1,000 words, to be useful for most wireless
devices that link to the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Hardware makers hope to overcome the limitation with a standard
known as WAP, or Wireless Application Protocol, which creates Web
pages with fewer characters _ perhaps just 80 words _ that are
easier to download and display on wireless devices.
</P>
<P>
   By listing sites that are WAP-enabled, AltaVista hope its index,
found at wap.raging.com, will become a standard of its own.
Currently a majority of the sites it lists are in Europe, where
mobile-phone usage is more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Google Inc., an AltaVista competitor, uses a technology that
translates sites written in traditional Web codes into another
mobile-friendly language. Earlier this month, Google announced a
deal with wireless-services provider Nextel Communications Inc. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hyperlinks unbound &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A New York company's software turns any typed text into a
hyperlink to other information on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The company is Zapper Technologies Inc. and its program, Zapper,
works with most PC applications. The software develops links to
financial, sports, reference, and shopping sites, and pastes to
them any word or phrase a user highlights with a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   If a user receives an e-mail mentioning the book ``In a
Sunburned Country'' by Bill Bryson, for instance, he could
highlight the title and be linked to Amazon.com, where the book is
for sale, or to a review at CNN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Zapper says it is in talks with several Internet portals,
including AltaVista, Excite, and AskJeeves. Zapper says it won't
limit searches to sites with which it has business agreements,
however.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
