<SLUG> BC-TECH-VENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY IPOS WAIT ON THE SIDELINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   August has been a huge month for IPOs. But not all companies got
out as they'd hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Several local deals have been shelved _ most temporarily _ and
they share one thing in common: They all filed to go public before
or shortly after the April Nasdaq dive.
</P>
<P>
   Take Connected Corp. The Natick-based provider of remote
computer repair and database backup filed April 5 to go public, in
hopes of raising $57.5 million. The company has raised $36 million
in venture capital from a Who's Who of the financial world.
</P>
<P>
   Here's who's on the hook, unable to make a quick buck on
Connected for the moment: Fidelity Ventures (an arm of the mutual
fund giant) holds a 10.6 percent stake. Intel Corp. has 9.8
percent. Baker Communications Fund of New York has 19.7 percent.
And, Softbank, the big Japanese venture group, holds 6.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Connected's chief executive, Robert Brennan, says the company
has plenty of cash and simply doesn't need to go public in a market
he views as rewarding only telecom-related companies lately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until the markets get a little less volatile, I'm not
comfortable entering the fray,'' he says. Brennan left Cisco
Systems to run Connected, right around the time of the IPO filing.
But he says he's willing to be patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got cash that will take us well into 2002,'' he says.
``There's really not a need to go public from a financial
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there have been 26 IPOs withdrawn or postponed this
month, according to Thomson Financial Securities Data, a research
firm in Newark. Five of those are Massachusetts-based companies,
including Connected.
</P>
<P>
   The other Bay State companies are:
</P>
<P>
   --Account4.Com Inc., a Newton maker of Internet-based software
for professional services companies.
</P>
<P>
   --Intrinsix Corp., a Westborough semiconductor maker.
</P>
<P>
   --Modus Media Inc. a Westwood-based customer service and order
fulfillment company.
</P>
<P>
   --A fifth company, NEN Life Sciences Inc., pulled its IPO after
it agreed to be acquired by PerkinElmer Inc. Boston-based NEN makes
tools for genomic drug research.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the IPOs that have been yanked, this has been the
biggest money-raising August on record, observes Richard Peterson,
chief market strategist at Securities Data.
</P>
<P>
   Companies have raised more than $8 billion on IPOs this month.
And there have been 58 deals completed, in striking distance of the
record 75 deals done in August of 1983. The last week of August is
often slow, however, because of the Labor Day holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Investment returns on IPOs this month have been more modest than
in July, Peterson says. The average first-day pop on new stocks has
been 28 percent, about half the average jump they got in July.
Average gains beyond the first day were 35 percent through last
week, for companies that went public in August, compared to a 46
percent gain for companies that sold shares in July.
</P>
<P>
   But the big gains haven't been there for many companies in the
Internet and software realms, as Brennan points out.
</P>
<P>
   Modus Media Inc., a Westwood-based company that handles order
fulfillment for companies selling products over the Web, is no
start-up. The company, which has delayed its IPO plan filed in
December, has 4,800 employees in 13 countries and 1999 revenues of
$697 million.
</P>
<P>
   Big investors include Boston's Bain Capital, which owns nearly
39 percent of the company. An affiliate of Chase Capital Partners
is an investor, as well as BankAmerica Investment Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The company has not discussed the state of its IPO plans
publicly. But in June, it announced it would cut 200 jobs in its
Fremont, Calif., plant, as part of a consolidation of its North
American operations.
</P>
<P>
   After a break this last week of August, many analysts believe
IPO activity will come back strongly for the fall. Optimists
abound, in venture circles and among entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   Zefer Corp., the Boston-based consulting firm, is trying to go
out shortly after Labor Day, having canceled its IPO after the
April crash. But it has lowered its expectations somewhat; Zefer's
trying to raise $45 million, down from $69 million in the first
go-round.
</P>
<P>
   Zefer chief executive William Seibel Jr. had said of the IPO
market back in April, ``We'll just wait for it to be back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beth Healy is a member of the Globe's staff. She can be reached
by e-mail at bhealy(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
