<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Collect not, want not
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANDWICH, Mass. _ Cool, drizzly days here on Cape Cod drive
visitors off the beaches and into the tiny villages situated up and
down the coast line of this intriguing arm of land so boldly
flexing its muscle out into the Atlantic. Like locusts, they swarm
into shopping malls, picking them clean of must-have items like
genuine resin replicas of island lighthouses (made in Taiwan), or
sea shells (shipped in from Florida).
</P>
<P>
   My friend Gail, in her native New England-ese, says rainy days
were different when she was a kid. ``If it rained, we went inside
to play board games or put together jigsaw puzzles.'' She remembers
the family actually talked to one another, even if it was only to
argue over what it cost to land on Boardwalk with a hotel, or to
whine because they'd gotten stuck with all the sky pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Gail and I suspect our lack of enthusiasm for getting
into a pile and shopping our backsides off might be a generation
thing. However, we prefer to think of it as a sign that we've
caught on to a basic fact of life _ stores can put it on the
shelves faster than we can carry it away. Also, there's an
algebraic truth at work here _ it's impossible to jam 50 pounds of
stuff into a 25-pound house.
</P>
<P>
   Our refusal to buy into the American dream of spending a
two-week vacation frantically driving from one outlet mall to the
next in search of shoppers' Nirvana, definitely sets us apart from
friends who plan trips to anywhere around a stop in Hershey, Penn.,
not to visit Willie Wonka and his chocolate factory, but to smoke
their credit cards on stuff they wouldn't have given a second
glance had it showed up in their local K-Mart.
</P>
<P>
   The art of acquisition, always a competitive sport for the
wealthy, seems to have trickled its way down to the rest of the
population, but with one big difference _ rich stuff lasts longer.
Forty-room country houses and Picassos don't overload landfills as
does the buy it, break it, and dump it junk that most folks haul
home in such overwhelming quantities.
</P>
<P>
   Gail tells about her father, a collector of anything touted as
limited edition _ paintings, books, plates, whatever _ and how as
the years passed shelves began to sag under the weight of his
accumulation. Methodically, he'd point out each new acquisition to
his daughter and explain how valuable it would be one day. Sadly,
after he was gone, the inherent truth in the old saying ``one man's
treasure...'' struck home as she wrote the check paying someone to
haul most of it away.
</P>
<P>
   My mother was the collector in our house. She loved miniatures.
If it came in one-quarter scale it found a home with us. Shelves,
table and dresser tops, window sills, and even the tile ledge
around the shower, were loaded with Lilliputian tea sets or
families of diminutive polar bears and striped tigers. It drove my
father nuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too much stuff,'' he'd mutter as he threaded his way through
the fragile minefield our home had become. Once, in one of many
futile attempts to stem the incoming tide, I heard him decree: ``I
don't care what you bring in the front door, as long as something
of equal size goes out the back.'' Of course, that didn't work
either. Mother collected. Daddy complained. And the house bulged.
</P>
<P>
   This morning it's another rainy day on the Cape. The jigsaw
puzzle on the dining table is finished, and Monopoly has lost its
enchantment. We opt for a movie _ drizzle drama we call it. That's
how we came to spend a couple of hours with the ``Space Cowboys'' _
a must-see space spoof. Trust me _ nothing perks up a drab
afternoon quicker than a shot of these aging ``cowboys'' _ Clint
Eastwood, Donald Sutherland, James Garner, and Tommy Lee Jones,
standing bare-bottom nekkid, backs to the camera!
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's an age thing, we decide, but these guys were looking
mighty good in their September `morn suits. I got dibs on Tommy Lee
Jones.
</P>
<P>
   And it sure beats shopping.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(at)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
