<HEADER>
A5065 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-YOUNG0830-COX     08-29 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I-35 maniacs driving 85 mph remind us of tune at 45 rpm
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   With apologies to Jan and Dean:
</P>
<P>
   I-35 was packed that late Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   We were speeding and following way too tight.
</P>
<P>
   Maypearl was in our dust, Hillsboro in our sights.
</P>
<P>
   All that SUV could see was my six tail lights.
</P>
<P>
   He tried me at construction; guy had nerve.
</P>
<P>
   So I punched it and there we were at Dead Man's Swerve.
</P>
<P>
   You've been there, no matter where you drive. If you've been on
the interstate you've been there, at Dead Man's Swerve. Concrete
barriers divide a section of interstate in which one side of the
four-lane highway is under construction. You still have two lanes
going both ways, but no shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   It's like the tunnel of the roller coaster when you suddenly
find yourself wrapped in black. All you can do is scream.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, you could do something else. You could decelerate.
Nobody does that, of course, even as a vehicle threads a muffin
slicer at 70 mph.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like you don't get warned. The signs are explicit.
``Slow down.'' ``No shoulder.'' ``Fines double.''
</P>
<P>
   But you haven't heeded a warning sign for 250 miles.
``Stuckeys.'' That would get your attention.
</P>
<P>
   Speed limit says 50. Speedometer says 80.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Dead Man's Swerve is south of Hillsboro on I-35. The
swerve is where the lanes feed back to normal from cramped confines
between barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting the wall
</P>
<P>
   An 18-wheeler hit the retaining wall not long ago. Every day,
rattled motorists ride the rapids with breaths bated. Someone
commented how many blown-out treads appear along the confined
stretch. The problem is that the treads, like the cars, have
nowhere to go when they blow.
</P>
<P>
   Being on one of the planet's most heavily traveled stretches and
not far from a swarming outlet mall, this stretch has been a major
conversation piece locally. The irony is that the construction
there isn't adding lanes as many would assume. It simply is
reconstructing with an eye to expansion one of these days. In
October, the reconstruction will switch to the northbound side and
traffic will be routed onto the other side, flip-flopping the
swerve.
</P>
<P>
   When construction is done, crews will take their retaining walls
elsewhere down the highway and the adventure will begin again.
</P>
<P>
   What speed limits?
</P>
<P>
   As the state makes plans to add lanes on I-35 from Hillsboro to
Williamson County, motorists should be settling in for hazards like
this and respecting warning signs with sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   The Tribune-Herald editorialized to this effect recently and
almost lost a subscriber.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the last time I pay attention to one of your editorial
recommendations,'' said my wife, not really meaning it, I think.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip to the Hillsboro outlet mall with our son she said she
slowed down as advised at the construction site. She found herself
in the middle of ``Ben Hur'' without a breast plate.
</P>
<P>
   Texas is always warring with Washington about its share of
federal highway funds. It seems that if state troopers would fine
every speeder through Dead Man's Swerve, with fines appropriately
doubled, we could tell Washington to kiss our ruby red patooties.
We could build the NAFTA highway ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Unless or until that happens, remember the refrain:
</P>
<P>
   Dead Man's Swerve is no place to play
</P>
<P>
   Dead Man's Swerve, you'd best keep away.
</P>
<P>
   Dead Man's Swerve, I can hear them say:
</P>
<P>
   Won't come back from Dead Man's Swerve.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
