<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEY-TALK0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SEC scores one for the small investor
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Remember those times you noticed a stock leaping in
value and wished you had invested in it?
</P>
<P>
   Then you found out, two days later, that a privileged few
already knew a secret?
</P>
<P>
   This month the Securities and Exchange Commission acted to
curtail such infuriating surprises.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC's new fair-disclosure rule requires that publicly held
companies spread the news to little-guy investors at the same time
they tell market professionals or major stockholders.
</P>
<P>
   The rule says that when a company discloses ``material nonpublic
information'' to market professionals or selected shareholders who
might trade on it, the company must also spread the information to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   A company can comply by filing a form with the SEC or by issuing
a news release. A conference call, presumably open to the public,
is another alternative.
</P>
<P>
   The new rule follows a two-year campaign by SEC Chairman Arthur
Levitt. When he first raised the subject, Levitt said trading on
privileged information ``has utterly no place in any fair-minded,
law-abiding economy. ... The American people see it, bluntly, as a
form of cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   The public agreed. When the federal agency asked for comments,
it got 6,000 of them, most from individuals and many of them angry
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brokers, market makers and the big-money boys have been
ripping off the little guy for so long they think that they are
entitled to do so,'' investor Philip J. Kaus wrote in an e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Regulation FD is an important victory, according to Barbara
Roper, director of investor protection for the Consumer Federation
of America. ``Information is money on the stock market,'' she said.
``The market sets stock prices based on the best available
information.''
</P>
<P>
   Instant information won't be important to all investors, said
Jan Holman, a market strategist for American Express. ``For most of
us, what's important is having a plan, investing on a regular basis
and remaining invested,'' she said. ``It's easy to get mired in all
the details of whether a new product is, in fact, selling, or
whether a company is going to hit its earnings forecast.''
</P>
<P>
   For regular traders, however, quick disclosures can be
moneymakers.
</P>
<P>
   Timeliness is not the only thing. When a company holds its
quarterly conference call with stock market analysts, it often
provides valuable information about the company's prospects. ``A
conference call provides insight into the the true driving forces
behind a company's performance,'' said Mark Coker. His Web site,
www.BestCalls.com, allows individuals to listen in on the calls of
many companies.
</P>
<P>
   To benefit from the new flow of information, you must find out
how companies you care about will provide their news. You can check
the company's Web site for guidance. Often the information will be
in the investor relations area. Some companies use other labels,
such as About Us or News and Info.
</P>
<P>
   A number of companies have already welcomed little-guy
investors. At www.airtran.com, for example, you can listen to tapes
of the airline's most recent conference call with analysts. You can
also sign up for e-mail notifications when the next call is
available.
</P>
<P>
   You can also get e-mails telling you when AirTran files
documents with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   At www.lucent.com, Internet home of one of the most widely held
stocks, you can sign up for e-mail notifications of press releases
and download filings with the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't find the services you want, it never hurts to send
an e-mail requesting them.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to listen to conference calls in real time, a number
of Web sites may help. Among them are Coker's www.BestCalls.com and
www.fool.com.
</P>
<P>
   (At the Motley Fool site, click on Conference Calls. It's on the
left side, about two screen loads down, under Stock Research.)
</P>
<P>
   Not all companies are available, of course. But last Thursday,
as the quarterly rush of earnings reports was slowing down,
BestCalls carried nine companies' conference calls.
</P>
<P>
   The Motley Fool arranges its offerings in a calendar, making it
easier to anticipate future announcements or go back to listen to
past ones. Monday, for example, you can listen in on Certicom
Corp., Piedmont Natural Gas and T/R Systems.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to see up-to-the-minute SEC filings, go to
www.freeedgar. com and sign up for e-mail notifications of filings
by the companies you are following.
</P>
<P>
   Holman uses a more old-fashioned technique: She watches for
changes or trends in a company's stock price. ``Then I look at what
the news is,'' she said. ``If something looks interesting, I'll dig
it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
