<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 11:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5096 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a k BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR &LR;      08-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEASE-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CANDIDATES ARE BLAH? WELL, WHAT'S YER POINT, PAL? 

</HEADLINE>
   By DARYL LEASE   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had just finished cleaning the gutters and was putting the
ladder away when I spotted, off in a corner of the garage, my high
school yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   I hadn't seen the thing in years, and I figured I'd lost it
several moves ago. How it reappeared is a mystery. I can only guess
that one of the critters running my adopted state of Florida _ fire
ant, palmetto bug, termite, tree rat, wind-insurance salesman _ had
found the book amid the clutter and cracked it open in hopes of
learning more about his prey.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hot, muggy Saturday afternoon, and since I was already
elbow-deep unclogging stuff, I decided to flip through the pages of
the yearbook and test my memory.
</P>
<P>
   I remembered most everyone, although a few folks were, at best,
only familiar faces. Sometime during the last 20 years, their names
must have saddled up a brain cell and ridden off into the sunset.
</P>
<P>
   When I finished with the photos, I began reading the parting
words my fellow students had scrawled in the margins. It was
predictable stuff, mostly. Lots of goofiness, sighs of relief, good
lucks and best wishes.
</P>
<P>
   One note stood out, though, and caused my sweaty brow to furrow.
``Really, Daryl,'' a classmate had written, ``you should try to
look more alive in the future. It makes people wonder, y'know.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahem. There it was _ my condition, my native disposition, my
supine predilection _ but now, after all these years, I suppose it
finally has a name: The Al Gore Syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   Wooden. Laconic. Drowsy. Slow to rile. Ready to tuck in.
</P>
<P>
   I was, and am, all of those things. Always have been, with the
possible exception of the Terrible Twos and certain keggers in my
Terrible Twenties.
</P>
<P>
   I've tried looking more peppy, really I have, but it feels
unnatural, phony, forced. Like Al, I'm pretty much doomed to be a
stick figure in a nauseatingly animated world.
</P>
<P>
   I've accepted my fate, but it's not always as effortless as it
might look. With my first name, I have to put up with a lot of
``Daryl and his other brother, Daryl'' jokes. (I like Bob Newhart,
but really now, isn't it time to put that show to pasture?) I also
encounter people who assume that I'm not the, uh, brightest bulb in
the marquee. (Oh, hell, let's face it: There is no marquee. The
lights are off, the parking lot's empty, and everyone went home
hours ago.)
</P>
<P>
   So, as you can imagine, I feel a certain affinity for Al Gore.
Regardless of his politics, he's my kind of guy. When he shuffled
into the national spotlight as Bill Clinton's running mate, I
listened to all the chatter about what a stiff he is, how
uncomfortable he looks, how dull and listless he seems. ``Yeah,'' I
eventually said, in a slow, drawling mumble. ``So what's yer
point?''
</P>
<P>
   With the passage of time, these so-called negatives look more
and more like pluses to me. I don't know about you, but after eight
fun-filled years of Clinton's redneck debonair, I'm ready for
boring.
</P>
<P>
   Go wonkish on us. Bury us in mind-numbing policy discussions.
Read us a long, snoozy speech. That's fine by me. If I want
animation, I'll watch the Cartoon Network.
</P>
<P>
   As incredible as it sounds, we may be in for several months of
candidates trying to out-dull each other. It seems that Al is now
facing, uh, stiff competition from George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   I nearly jumped out of my seat last week when I read in The New
York Times that, post-Democratic convention, Dubya is making a
point of looking a little less energetic, a little less motivated.
He spent a recent Monday at home and boasted to reporters afterward
that he'd taken a nap. ``Went to bed relatively early,'' he added.
He's taking a couple of days off this week, too, and plans a long
Labor Day break.
</P>
<P>
   Near the end of the story, there was this paragraph: ``Mr. Bush
himself makes frequent comments about resting and sleeping and a
sensible pace, concerns that do not exactly portray him as a ball
of fire. His advisers sought to frame this as an advantage, saying
it casts him as a sensible man not utterly consumed by politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Dubya is my kind of guy, too. The choice this fall is
looking less automatic.
</P>
<P>
   If they want my vote, I think they're going to have to make one
of those scripted, phony, uninspiring, media-hyped campaign stops
at my house. They could, I dunno, take a look at the gutter that's
causing me so much trouble. I'll hold the ladder.
</P>
<P>
   (Daryl Lease is a columnist for the Herald-Tribune in Sarasota,
Fla. Contact him at daryl.lease(AT)herald-trib.com.The
Herald-Tribune is a member of the New York Times Regional
Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1130EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
