<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-PHANTOM-DISCOVER-$ADV22-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUTURE TECH: `HOW DO YOU FEEL?' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tue., Aug. 22, 2000, or anytime thereafter.) 
 &HT;    
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by DISCOVER NEWS SERVICE clients.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 &HT;    
 (Color art is available.) 
 By BRAD LEMLEY 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    I'm beating a monkey's face to a pulp. But don't run off to
alert PETA _ it's really not the way it sounds.
 &HT;    The abused ape isn't real. His face is a digital simulacrum,
floating on a high-resolution screen, created to help me test a
weird computer peripheral called the PHANTOM. It resembles a desk
lamp, minus the bulb and shade, and interacts with the
computer-generated image.
 &HT;    Wherever I move the business end of this gadget, the cursor on
the screen moves in sync, denting the virtual simian's cheek,
flattening an eyebrow or crumpling an ear.
 &HT;    In short, the PHANTOM is a computer mouse that has entered into
another dimension.
 &HT;    A conventional mouse moves a cursor across the screen in many
directions _ up, down, diagonal, around _ but on only one plane.
This new tool goes not only to the x and y axis but also opens the
in-and-out, z axis. With it, I can smash in the monkey's nose,
which is pointed right at me, by pushing my hand forward; the
ball-shaped cursor convincingly shrinks as it glides away.
 &HT;    Even more amazing, whenever the ball smacks the monkey's face, I
feel the resistance in my hand as a stiff, claylike friction. In
less than a minute, I've become so proficient that I can repair the
fellow.
 &HT;    The manufacturer contends a 5-year-old can master this
peripheral. I believe it.
 &HT;    The PHANTOM was designed and built by SensAble Technologies, a
seven-year-old company with 50 employees housed in a nondescript
brick building in Woburn, Mass. Coupled with a software program
called FreeForm, it may herald an important change in the way human
beings and computers interact.
 &HT;    ``The last time the computer-human interface had a substantial
improvement was the mouse, which came out of Xerox about 25 years
ago,'' says SensAble marketing director Andrew Hally. ``This is the
next move up.'
 &HT;    Which sounds like the kind of overheated claims marketing
directors get paid to make. Do computer users really long to
``feel'' the objects on their screens?
 &HT;    After spending a few hours with the PHANTOM, I started to get a
feeling of deja vu. In the early days of personal computing, some
users huffily insisted that arrow keys were more than enough, so
who needed that goofy mouse?
 &HT;    The mouse evolved from toy to essential tool because it inspired
designers to dream up applications for it. An interface based on
haptics _ the more technically correct term for interactions
involving both feeling and position _ will likely follow the same
path.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of problems that you can solve better if you
can use your sense of touch in 3-D space,'' Hally says.
 &HT;    The first widespread commercial application of haptic tools
arrived as part of computer-aided design, or CAD, of complex forms.
My monkey face originated as a concept model to show toy designers
how the PHANTOM could help them with their CAD work.
 &HT;    Most of the 600 PHANTOMs sold to date are used by sculptors and
engineers for companies such as Adidas, Disney, Hasbro, LEGO and
Honda, and users are ebullient. A mouse-driven CAD program works
adequately for designing squarish buildings, but try modeling a
titanium hip replacement or a snazzy new sneaker using only lines,
grids and circles.
 &HT;    ``To a sculptor, it really is a revolutionary development,''
says David R. Fish, who crafts clay footwear models for Nike and is
in the process of switching to PHANTOM-based prototyping.
 &HT;    Not only does the system emulate physical sculpting, it allows
techniques that are impossible in real clay, such as pushing out
from the inside. If an artist wants to sculpt a nose, she can click
the cursor ``off,'' push it inside the digital clay, click it
``on,'' and then pull material toward her.
 &HT;    Coupled with 3-D printers, which can manufacture plastic items
from a computer-specified form, objects sculpted in cyberspace can
become real at the touch of a button.
 &HT;    The $15,000 PHANTOM/FreeForm package is among the first haptic
applications on the market, but more ambitious systems are already
under development.
 &HT;    At the Medical College of Georgia and Georgia Technical
Institute, doctors and engineers have created an eye-surgery
simulator for training students. The digital scalpel feeds back
springy resistance as it touches the white of the digital eye; then
resistance lessens as the cyber-blade slices through.
 &HT;    Physical-skill training of all kinds is ``a huge application,''
says leading haptics researcher J. Kenneth Salisbury, who, while a
professor in MIT's mechanical engineering department, helped to
develop the PHANTOM with SensAble CEO Thomas Massie.
 &HT;    The haptics revolution is bolstering telerobotics, in which a
remote user, watching via video cameras, directs robotic arms
engaged in a task too dangerous, precise or inaccessible for naked
flesh. Telerobotics works a lot better with tactile feedback
indicating what the arms are doing.
 &HT;    Applications for such interactive devices include fighting
fires, exploring undersea or on other planets and handling
hazardous materials, but the most promising home may be surgery.
 &HT;    Already used for heart operations in the United States and
Germany, illion-dollar machines allow a surgeon to operate through
half-inch-wide incisions by manipulating thin robotic arms. The
minimally invasive procedure speeds patients' recovery and someday
may extend surgeons' careers by digitally canceling age-related
hand tremors.
 &HT;    ``Eventually such techniques will be applicable in neurosurgery
or fetal surgery,'' says Salisbury, now a professor in both the
departments of computer science and surgery at Stanford University.
 &HT;    In the long run, virtually every action that involves real-world
touch could be simulated or enhanced via haptic interfaces _ and
some human activities that have never been touchy-feely could
become so.
 &HT;    Someday, we may view haptic interfaces as just one more step we
took toward the computer-immersed human. The evolution began with
the first computers, as punch cards and then screens engaged the
sense of sight. Later, computers gained sound, then touch.
 &HT;    Today companies such as Digiscents, TriSenx and Aromajet are
laboring to bring smell and even taste to the digital realm.
 &HT;    The omega point is the day when the virtual world becomes as
real to humans as the outside, three-dimensional world, with one
important distinction. For good or ill, the virtual world's only
limitations will be the ones we choose.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Brad Lemley is a contributing editor to Discover magazine.)
