   &UR; HOLLYWOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LARS VON TRIER: PRINCE OF DARKNESS. From W magazine. One color
slide. By all accounts, the making of Lars Von Trier's latest
picture, the Palme d'Or-winning musical melodrama ``Dancer in the
Dark,'' was an excruciating experience. The story centers on Selma
(played by pop singer Bjork), a Czech immigrant living in the
Pacific Northwest in the late 1950s who is losing her sight due to
a hereditary disease. She works in a factory, saving up for an
operation that will protect her son from the same fate. But after a
friend betrays her and steals the money, the world caves in on her:
Selma winds up charged with murder. However, the real melodrama
took place off-camera between Von Trier and Bjork, who nearly quit
the film. (At one point, she reportedly climbed a fence to escape
the experience.) An interview with the controversial filmmaker.
(slugged: BC-LARS-VON-TRIER-FAIRCHILD-ART-NYTSF)
</P>
