<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   COPS-RAIDS (San Francisco) _ A federal appeals court has put the
brakes on eager cops who crash through front doors to execute
search warrants, giving residents only seconds to respond. A
three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled
that a search violated the so-called ``knock-and-announce'' law in
that officers did not give the suspect, an alleged member of a drug
gang, sufficient opportunity to let them into his home before they
bashed open the door. By JIM HERRON ZAMORA.
</P>
<P>
   BUSY-SIGNALS (San Francisco) _ A consumer groups is accusing
Pacific Bell of violating the law by interrupting busy signals with
a message that the caller can get ``repeat dialing'' for a charge
of 95 cents. By VANESSA HUA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT(``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOPKINS-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Hopkins 24/7'' is ``Trauma
Center'' with some depth, ``Rescue 911'' without the overwrought
schmaltz, ``ER'' without actors. Filmed by ABC, which was provided
extraordinary access inside Baltimore's Johns Hopkins University
medical facility, ``Hopkins 24/7'' (which premieres Wednesday) is a
documentary series unlike many that have come down the TV pike. By
MIKE McDANIEL.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EURO-TOURISTS (Undated) _ Nobody from Brussels has called to ask
my opinion, and perhaps that's good. I just can't make up my mind
how I feel about the euro, the new common currency of the 11
participating European Union countries. Introduced Jan. 1, 1999 for
credit card transactions, it will arrive as bank notes and coins on
Jan. 1, 2002 and, after a six-month phase-in period, will
completely replace francs, marks, lire, etc. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HAWAII-FLUMING (Hawi, Hawaii) _ For four generations the
boys and girls of North Kohala, on the Big Island of Hawaii, have
been climbing over barbed-wire fences and dodging security guards
in search of an illicit thrill. On inner tubes or boogie boards or
anything else that floats, they've drifted down the 22 miles of
man-made channels and flumes built nearly a century ago by the
Kohala Sugar Co. to carry water from the rain-soaked Kohala
Mountains to the thirsty sugar cane fields on the dry lowlands. By
JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING (Off the Kohala Coast, Hawaii) _ Skipper
Casey Cho gives the order to hoist the sail in Hawaiian _ huki kau
la! - and up goes something you'll never see at a mainland yacht
club. It's shaped not like the inverted-triangle mainsail found on
every sloop from Newport to Tiburon, but like a massive lobster
claw reaching toward the sky. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS-QUARTERBACKS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ For his rookie
season as a San Francisco 49er, quarterback Giovanni Carmazzi will
start out on a low simmer. Very low. In fact, his burner won't even
be turned on. Jeff Garcia's coils will be glowing red, Rick Mirer's
will be on low and Tim Rattay's will be on warm. By JOHN
CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS-DEFENSE (Alameda, Calif.) _ Oakland Raiders
defensive coordinator Chuck Bresnahan is cautiously optimistic
about how his unit will perform Sunday afternoon against the San
Diego Chargers and for the rest of the regular season. By FRANK
BLACKMAN.
</P>
<P>
   KNAPP-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Normally, I'm a purist. Junk
sports may grab my eye, but I always know I'm slumming. The
slam-dunk contest at the NBA All-Star Game? Sometimes a diversion,
sometimes a snore. The home-run derby for major-leaguers? Glorified
batting practice. If I watch, I never admit it. Then along came
Monday night's round of match-play golf between Tiger Woods and
Sergio Garcia. It met all the requirements for utter disdain, the
snob's snub. It was great. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A Honolulu entrepreneur has
created an entirely computer-generated film (``Final Fantasy: The
Movie''). We already have millions of actual people who can easily
smile, frown, express rage, surprise, confusion and lust. Some of
them can even do it convincingly in front of a movie camera. Why
must we rely on computers for actors? By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   KURSK-LESSONS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The loss of the Russian submarine
KURSK holds potential lessons. The Russian military has learned
that there is no gain in delaying a request for foreign assistance.
The Russian political leadership has learned that in a democracy
immediate response to a public disaster is mandatory. By MILLARD
HARMON
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
