<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; tab-z
u e BC-METALLICA-INTERVIEW-A     08-29 1933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METALLICA-INTERVIEW-ADV28-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV28  
 METALLICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Aug. 28 and thereafter.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The rock band Metallica has been nominated for
five MTV Video Music Awards. The awards show airs live on September
7 from Radio City Music Hall. This article from The New York Times
Syndicate is available as a ``separate-buy'' _ the cost is not
prohibitive _ by contacting one of the New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives listed at the end of the text. The article
first appeared in the TV Guide.) 
 (ART ADV: Photos of Metallica are available on Newscom or by
calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By ROB TANENBAUM  
 c.2000 Rob Tanenbaum  
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUD. FAST. BIG. More than any other rock band, Metallica
proudly embody these qualities, which describe not only the music
they play, but also their lifestyles. ``Danger around every
curve,'' says singer James Hetfield, his eyes wide with eagerness.
</P>
<P>
   On a late-July day, Metallica is the climactic band at a
festival called Rockfest (even the name is big), held at the
Chicago Motor Speedway. On the infield of the racing oval, where
cars usually speed through dangerous curves at 180 mph, Kid Rock
sings from a BIG 120-foot stage, to a BIG audience of more than
50,000 sun-streaked zealots. Hetfield sits in a backstage trailer _
which is actually vibrating because Kid Rock is playing so LOUD _
and explains his band's ardent opposition to Napster, the Web site
that allows 20 million users to swap entire CDs through their
computers, an act Metallica considers theft.
</P>
<P>
   Why have so many music fans embraced Napster? ``Because they're
lazy bastards and they want everything for free,'' Hetfield
wisecracks.
</P>
<P>
   Metallica have earned their superstardom. Hetfield, guitarist
Kirk Hammett, bassist Jason Newsted, each 37, and drummer Lars
Ulrich, 36, have sold 71 million records, and won five Grammys.
Their high-action video for ``I Disappear,'' from the ``Mission:
Impossible 2'' soundtrack, was nominated for five MTV Music Video
Awards, including Best Rock Video, with the ceremony set for
September 7.
</P>
<P>
   The LOUD and FAST bands that inspired Metallica are pretty
obscure _ unless you're familiar with thrash pioneers like Diamond
Head and Blitzkrieg _ but Metallica spread pure metal to the masses
by adding hints of melodic appeal and experimentation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, for all the success and adoration, Hetfield is an uneasy
member of the rock establishment. A big-shouldered Californian, he
craves adventure: like a metal-head Huck Finn, he hunts, owns guns,
smokes cigars, rides a custom Harley and jet-skis.
</P>
<P>
   He loved filming the ``I Disappear'' video because he got to
drive a fast car ``without cops chasing me,'' while living out a
macho fantasy: ``I'm Steve McQueen in 'Bullitt,' dude.'' A tattoo
on his left shoulder reads ``Carpe diem baby,'' surrounded by
flames, in recognition of the August, 1992 show when a pyrotechnics
explosion ignited the left side of his body, requiring a year of
physical therapy. ``That tattoo reminds me, you are alive, take
advantage of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   To Hetfield, Metallica's assault on Napster _ they sued the Web
site for copyright infringement and racketeering, and Ulrich
testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee on July 11 _ is
consistent with the band's contrarian energy.
</P>
<P>
   They've defied metal etiquette by writing ballads; they've
trimmed their unkempt hair into stylish male-model cuts; and they
recorded last year's ``S&AMP;M'' CD with a symphony orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been afraid to break the rules of the heavy-metal
school,'' he says. Hetfield offers another high-speed analogy:
``There's no rear-view mirror in the Metallica van.'' He's proud to
be an irritant, an outsider. ``That's the story of Metallica,
really, the story of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   SMART. CONTRARY. UNPREDICTABLE. When Metallica began in Los
Angeles, 19 years ago, ``We were very much the outcasts,'' says
Ulrich, backstage at the Chicago Speedway. ``The first year or so,
it was pretty lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   A proud Danish citizen, Ulrich moved to the U.S. to become a
professional tennis player _ his grandfather, uncle, and father
Torben all played Davis Cup tennis for Denmark. But Ulrich's love
of roaring rock prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   He met Hetfield through a newspaper ad in the spring of 1981,
and they began to play in a fast, heavy style much wilder than
L.A.'s reigning band, Van Halen. Adding to their sense of being
misfits, they felt like the only L.A. band without a sleek,
colorful look. ``The only look we had,'' Hetfield says with a manic
laugh, ``was ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   They moved to San Francisco and named themselves Metallica, so
there would be no doubt what kind of music they played. (Other
names they considered, Ulrich says, included Helldriver and Nixon.)
When they put a ballad, ``Fade To Black,'' on their second album
``Ride The Lightning,'' fans accused them of selling out, Hetfield
recalls. Before releasing ``Load'' in 1996, they cut their hair and
were accused of getting trendy, as though using hair gel was a
hard-rock sin.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Ulrich says, ``I realized that I really hated heavy
metal cliches.'' At times, he adds, when Metallica is ``not
thinking rationally,'' the band has even discussed changing its
name and abandoning the metal association.
</P>
<P>
   Still, through the years, Metallica became known as the smart
metal band. ``I hate it,'' Hetfield says of the reputation. ``I
like to NOT think.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just him playing up,'' counters Ulrich. ``He's brighter
than he wants to cop to.'' Where Ulrich is an excitable spirit, so
colorful and animated he's nearly a cartoon, Hetfield swaggers and
broods. ``He's more comfortable the less people know about him, and
the more mysterious and aloof he can be,'' Ulrich says.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans identify intensely with Hetfield's lyrics, which are
mostly about struggle and alienation. Backstage, a fan from Brest,
France, who won a trip to Rockfest by writing an essay about his
brother's death in a car accident 14 years ago, anxiously waits to
meet the band. Metallica's music, he wrote, gives him comfort. He
once drove 35 hours to see them in Berlin. ``It's more than music
now,'' he says in French.
</P>
<P>
   Music was more than entertainment for Hetfield, too. The dark
lyrics, he explains, spring from ongoing anger about his childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Ulrich's warning, Hetfield cracks jokes and breaks into
accents. Though watchful, he's also surprisingly playful for a guy
whose three big themes are death, destruction and nuclear war.
</P>
<P>
   In frank but matter-of-fact terms, he describes his childhood as
one long convulsion: his parents divorced when he was young, his
mother Cynthia died, and because his dad Virgil, a trucker, was
``nowhere to be found,'' Hetfield lived with his half-brother
David, who was 10 years older. Plus, he was raised as a Christian
Scientist, and the faith's opposition to doctors and medicine ``was
very alienating. It was just weird for me to have to leave health
class during school _ all the kids whispering about you and
thinking you're weird.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in elementary school, being a freak ain't cool.
Later on, maybe it is. So I'd run home and play music. Music became
my friend.'' Years later, Hetfield reconciled with his dad, who
died of cancer five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Hetfield and his wife Francesca have two kids, daughter
Cali, 2, and son Castor, born in May. Ulrich, the other parent in
Metallica, has a 2-year-old son Myles with wife Skyler, an
emergency-room doctor (she previously dated actor Matt Damon, who
made her the model for Minnie Driver's character in ``Good Will
Hunting'').
</P>
<P>
   There's a growing sense of domesticity within the band. Ulrich
often takes his family over to Kid Rock's house, ``and he makes
dinner for us.'' Ulrich discloses a shocking secret about Rock, the
self-proclaimed American Bad Ass: ``He cooks a mean spaghetti.''
</P>
<P>
   And if that's not cozy enough, Ulrich and Hetfield brought their
families together last spring, to have ``an Easter Egg hunt in the
Hetfield back garden.'' The drummer grimaces: the image is more
Martha Stewart than Metallica. ``It's like, people would puke.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Newsted wonders whether fatherhood will lead Hetfield to
write from ``a good, positive spot now, rather than his usual dark
spot,'' when Metallica begin recording new songs after Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must say, the dark spot has worked very well for me,''
Hetfield says with a chuckle. ``I'm absolutely happier as a person;
the kids are a whole new energy. But there's a dark spot you can't
wash off, either _ childhood is always fuel for writing. I've
learned how to go to the dark spot and come back now. I can visit
it. I used to just live in it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, Napster partisans continue to post frequent
attacks on Metallica; some are full of reason, others made mostly
of fury and childish curses.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the criticism accuses Metallica of being ``greedy
bastards,'' as Hetfield says, and trying to earn as much money as
possible by maximizing CD sales. ``No, I don't (expletive) need
more money,'' Ulrich replies hotly. ``I'm fine, thank you. Is it
possible it could be about something else?''
</P>
<P>
   Music, he argues, is a form of property, and ``property
shouldn't be free. We have a right to control what happens to it,
since we own it and pay for it.'' Yes, Metallica encourages fans to
trade homemade recordings of live concerts: ``Make it a part of
your life,``Hetfield says. ``It's a keepsake.''
</P>
<P>
   But they don't want their master studio recordings to be
available for free, any more than they'd want you taking their
cars, houses, or any other property without asking first.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you'd stop being a Metallica fan because I won't give you
my music for free,'' Ulrich says, ``then (expletive) you, I don't
want you to be a Metallica fan.''
</P>
<P>
   By taking the lead in trying to shut down Napster, Metallica
have again leapt into the fire; heat is their favorite element.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kinda like arguing with people,'' admits Hetfield, who says
conflict ``keeps you on edge, keeps you alive.'' By now, he's used
to debating fans about Napster, sometimes fervently.
</P>
<P>
   ``This poor girl in Atlanta, I made her cry. And I ended up
hugging her. She felt money was evil,'' he says with a sneer.
``Well, why don't you go live in Canada, or some socialist country,
like Russia? We have a right to control what happens to our music,
since we own it. This is not a hobby for us. This is what we've
dedicated our lives to.''
</P>
<P>
   The reward for their drive and dedication comes a few hours
later. ``Chicago, let me hear you!'' Hetfield implores the crowd as
the set begins under a night sky. Okay, so sometimes Metallica
still use a heavy-metal cliche or two.
</P>
<P>
   But when they launch into ``Creeping Death,'' the fans try to
match the band roar for roar, enjoying the shared experience of
being rock 'n' roll freaks, savoring the thrill: LOUD. FAST. BIG.
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Tanenbaum writes frequently for The New York Times
Magazine. This article was written for TV Guide.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a ``separate-buy'' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
