<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5127 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-29 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     VIRTUAL REALITY HOLLYWOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ It happened while I was reading a short
interview in the Honolulu Star-Bulletin with Hironobu Sakaguchi, a
video game developer and budding feature film director.
</P>
<P>
   The creative force behind a $70 million, entirely
computer-generated film (``Final Fantasy: The Movie'') Sakaguchi
had just joked about how much easier it is to make a movie with
cyber actors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes human actors can be very selfish and not listen to
the director and producer. But our actors are always willing to
work on time and take direction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then Sakaguchi, 38, was asked, ``What has been the most
difficult aspect technically of making this film?''
</P>
<P>
   He replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural human facial expressions. To have the skin and hair
move naturally like it does in reality. Also the way the clothes
wrinkle when people move. That is very, very hard to simulate
realistically. If you produced wrinkles by hand animation, it would
take probably 10 years. So we created our own software to
accomplish this.''
</P>
<P>
   For one incredible, glimpse-eternity nanosecond, I could ``see''
the collective energy, intellect and achievement of all human
existence. That which has come before us and that which is yet to
be.
</P>
<P>
   And what I saw looked really stupid.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say I think Sakaguchi is stupid. Far from it. He
is one of God knows how many talented and imaginative young men and
women who spend their days and nights creating dazzling alternative
realities via computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   Sony deeply believes in Sakaguchi's vision; the media giant will
distribute the feature film adaptation of Sakaguchi's phenomenally
successful ``Final Fantasy'' video game series when it is released
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Alec Baldwin, James Woods and Donald Sutherland are among the
human actors who supply voices for the movie's real-looking but
computer-generated characters. Oscar-nominated screenwriter Al
``Apollo 13'' Reinert is on the script team.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, ``Final Fantasy: The Movie'' is a big damned
deal.
</P>
<P>
   But ... it's about those wrinkles in the clothes.
</P>
<P>
   And the facial expressions.
</P>
<P>
   And the strands of hair.
</P>
<P>
   We already have millions and millions of actual people who can
easily smile, frown, express rage, surprise, confusion and lust.
Some of them can even do it convincingly in front of a movie
camera.
</P>
<P>
   And we have enough clothes in existence to cover _ what? _ maybe
the Western United States. They wrinkle at the slightest breeze.
</P>
<P>
   But in a Honolulu high-rise, in the labs of Square Co. Ltd., we
have hundreds of artists, craftspeople, technicians and cyber
engineers sweating blood. They are inventing new software, spending
$70 million to make the best computer-generated versions of real
people and wrinkled clothes they possibly can.
</P>
<P>
   What is wrong with this digitally enhanced picture?
</P>
<P>
   As someone who does not play video games and still surfs the
Internet on a big, slow, pre-World War II-board, I do not get it.
The only reason I know about ``Final Fantasy,'' Sakaguchi or the
wrinkles is because I read that they and he have seriously
influenced a Hollywood director named Andrew Nichol (``The Truman
Show'').
</P>
<P>
   Impressed by what he's seen from Square Co., and frustrated by a
fruitless search for a young actress to play the title role in his
new film, ``Simone,'' Nichol reportedly decided to cast a
computer-generated woman instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'' will ``play'' opposite Al Pacino and other human actors.
</P>
<P>
   Some 60 years ago, David O. Selznick experienced a similar
frustration. Despite combing the United States for more than a
year, he could not find the perfect actress to play Scarlett O'Hara
in ``Gone With The Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Despairing but locked into a shooting schedule, he began
production without his leading lady. Then, while filming the
``burning of Atlanta,'' Selznick saw his Scarlett _ behind the
cameras and lights, just another celebrity visitor to the set.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the beautiful (and British) Vivien Leigh would don the
bonnet and dress that a little stunt man wore during the chaotic
scene. Because computer technology had not yet been invented, the
wrinkles in the dress played themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
