<HEADER>
A5161 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-NYT-WORLD-BUDGET &LR;      08-29 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYT-WORLD-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors at publications outside the United States may find the
following stories from the New York Times News Service for
 &UR; WEDNESDAY, Aug. 30, &LR;  of particular interest:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-KIDNAP (Dateline to kum) _ Moslem rebels who thrive
on kidnapping seized an American in the Philippines on Tuesday and
threatened to kill him if the United States does not meet
unspecified demands. The Abu Sayyaf rebels, who have been holding a
group of Europeans, South Africans and Asians for four months, said
in a radio broadcast that ``we have been trying very hard to get an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COLOMBIA (Cartagena) _ The president of Colombia, in an
interview on day before President Clinton arrives, says that
nothing Colombia does about drugs will have any effect unless the
U.S. and Europe curb demand. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MIDEAST (Cairo, Egypt) _ President Clinton said Tuesday
that time was running short for a Middle East peace deal as he met
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to confer on ways to nudge the
Israelis and Palestinians toward an accord. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-CORSICA (Dateline to kum) _ The French interior minister,
Jean-Pierre Chevenement, resigns from the Socialist government of
Lionel Jospin to protest Jospin's controversial plan to grant
autonomy to the Mediterrnen island of Corsica.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-JAPAN (Beijing) _ Chinese President Jiang Zemin meets with
Yohei Kono, Japan's foreign minister, amid tension over several
incursions into disputed waters by Chinese naval and research
vessels that began last spring. (Summary from wires) By Erik
Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Various datelines) _ The World Briefing column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNITED STATES &LR;  _ General (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ Developments in the Wen Ho Lee
Case: The judge in the case holds a hearing on Lee's release and
whether he was selected for prosecution because of his race. By
James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-MEDICAID (Dallas) _ A federal judge says that as many as 1
million Texas children are being denied Medicaid coverage because
the state's system is in a shambles. By Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LYCEE-FRANCAIS (New York) _ The Lycee Francais de New York,
the prestigious French school that attracts European nationals and
American Francophiles, is selling all six of its buildings in
Manhattan. The school expects to sell the buildings to wealthy
individuals who want to restore the one-time mansions to
single-family homes. And the school hopes to make a killing on the
sale _ more than $100 million _ enough to create an endowment and
build a new school. Once considered too costly for private use,
town houses and mansions are making a big comeback as private
residences in a new era of opulence that has left investment
bankers, Internet entrepreneurs and investors flush with cash from
the longest running economic boom in the country's history. By
Charles V. Bagli.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-BOURSES (London) _ A battle for the London Stock
Exchange, Europe's largest equity market, erupts after the owner of
the Stockholm stock exchange makes a hostile bid of $1.18 billion.
The London exchange rejects the Swedish bid, and Frankfurt
indicates that it will make a sweetened offer. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Undated) _ Developments in the Firestone tire
recall, with reporting from Detroit and Caracas.
</P>
<P>
   FOSTERS-BERINGER (San Francisco) _ Looking at what the
acquisition of Beringer Wine by Foster's, the Australian beer
giant, spells for the California wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   AIG-HYUNDAI (Seoul) _ A consortium led by American International
Group (AIG) will invest $1 billion to take control of the three
financial units of the Hyundai group, South Korea's largest
conglomerate said Tuesday. (Summary from wires) By Samuel Len.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN-PERELMAN (Undated) _ In the recently published ``Most of
the Most of S.J. Perelman,'' a portmanteau of Perelmania in the
Modern Library Humor and Wit Series, Woody Allen is quoted as
saying: ``What happens to you when you read Perelman and you're a
young writer is fatal because his style seeps into you. He's got
such a pronounced, overwhelming comic style that it's very hard not
to be influenced by him.'' That influence can be seen by comparing
Allen's movie, ``Small Time Crooks,'' and ``The Night Before
Christmas,'' a play by Perelman and his wife, Laura. By Mel Gussow,
in a Critic's Notebook.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-EXILES (Undated) _ During the 1930s and '40s, hundreds of
German writers, Jews and non-Jews alike, fled Hitler and sought
refuge in the United States. But finding asylum, they were harassed
and spied upon by the FBI and other government agencies which
referred to them as ``Communazis.'' The government tapped their
phones, intercepted their mail, dug through their trash, hired
informants to spy on them, sometimes monitored their sex lives, and
conducted intimidating interviews with them, according to
``Communazis,'' a new book to be published in October by Yale
University Press. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
