<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5180 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      08-29 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSHADED UNPROVEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Saturday's Travers Stakes at Saratoga shedding little light
on the 3-year-old situation, never has the old saying ``champions
are made in the fall'' seemed truer.
</P>
<P>
   Unshaded, a moody gelding, was the deserving winner of the
Midsummer Derby, authoring a determined charge to prevail by a
head. However, Unshaded's chances of future success are shaky. He's
a bad actor, and that's going to be a problem for him as he assumes
a bigger role in the division.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not an ordinary horse,'' said his rider, Shane Sellers.
``He's a difficult horse to ride and he has a bad attitude. You
just have to keep nudging him along, and when he says `no,' you
have to go with him. Sometimes, you have to tell yourself to wait
just a couple of strides longer. He's not much of a fighter when he
gets head-and-head. He has a tendency to wait, and I have to live
by the decisions I make on him. I'm very fit, but he took all of
the energy out of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Carl Nafzger, whose ultimate goal is to get Unshaded to
the Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs Nov. 4, knows that his
charge has a long way to go before he can be considered a contender
for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice division of horses,'' said Nafzger. ``Unshaded has
got to step up to win an Eclispe. He has to go on, and keep
winning. If he does that, he'll be 3-year-old champion. But we
won't know until we get to our ultimate destination. The bottom
line is, assuming he runs, we have to beat Fusaichi Pegasus.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus won the Kentucky Derby and ran second in the
Preakness, but has not raced sinced. Syndicated to stud for $70
million, he had his first workout in three months last Thursday,
going 3 furlongs in :39 2/5 at Hollywood Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just cruising,'' said his trainer, Neil Drysdale.
``He's carrying a bit more weight, and is stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, who is aiming Fusaichi Pegasus at the Classic, has
still not said when the colt will start next. However, he is
planning a New York campaign. Assuming that Belmont Park officials
can't write an allowance race for him (for lack of competition),
Fusaichi Pegasus could appear in the $150,000 Jerome Handicap, at 1
mile for 3-year-olds only, on Sept. 23. That would set him up for
the $1 million Jockey Club Gold Cup, at 1 1/4 miles, weight-for-age
against older horses, Oct. 14.
</P>
<P>
   However, if Drysdale wants to throw Fusaichi Pegasus right in
with the bears, he could try the $500,000 Woodward, at 1 1/8 miles,
weight-for-age, Sept. 16. Waiting for him there would be Lemon Drop
Kid, winner of three stright stakes and the leader of the handicap
division. It may be that the last thing the Fusaichi Pegasus camp
wants is to see the $70 million colt get trounced in a comeback
bid, so the Woodward seems questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens with Fusaichi Pegasus, Unshaded has given
himself a chance to go to the head of the class. Sellers, who can
be openly critical of the gelding, is also one of his biggest
backers, and Sellers thinks he has a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unshaded just gets better and better with every race,'' said
Sellers. ``He was at his best for the Travers. This horse has grown
by leaps and bounds since the Belmont (finished third despite the
heat). He used to get nervous and wash himself out. But he's been
much more calm. He's a real good horse. He's run nine times and
only been out of the money once (9-4-1-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make a case for just about everybody regarding the
3-year-old division. Right now, Unshaded is good and the rest are
not. He's really coming into his own. If it weren't for the heat
exhaustion, he might even have won the Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fair outlook
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Racing at Northampton, the only fair in Massachusetts to host a
meeting, begins Friday. There will be 10 days of action, spanning
three weekends: Sept. 1-4, 8-10, and 15-17. Racing secretary Tom
Creel reports that the response from horsemen has been positive,
and the track opened for training Monday . . . Scheduled to run at
Northampton is Zippy Chippy, a 9-year-old gelding who hasn't won a
race in 86 attempts, which is believed to be a record. Zippy Chippy
recently lost a match race against a minor league baseball player
for the Rochester Red Wings. The ballplayer had a 20-yard head
start in the 40-yard race and won by 3-4 lengths . . . Space
Shuttle, a top-quality pacer, lived up to his billing at
Plainridge, winning Saturday's Beckwith Memorial in the
record-shattering time of 1:49 3/5. ``Space Shuttle is an amazing
little horse,'' said driver Walter Case Jr. ``He has two or three
gears when he is asked.'' The former record at Plainridge, which is
a 5/8-mile oval, was 1:52 3/5 set by Color Me Best in last year's
Beckwith. The supporting feature, the $20,000 Pasquantonio Memorial
Trot, was won by Ringside Rocket, driven by Case. Ringside Rocket
went in 1:54 2/5, also setting a record. The trotting mark at
Plainridge was 1:56, set by American Winter earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Short story
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More Than Ready, once considered a bright Kentucky Derby
prospect, was finally allowed to do what he does best, which is
sprint. What resulted was a powerful victory in the $200,000 King's
Bishop at The Spa Saturday. The King's Bishop is the only Grade I
sprint restricted to sophomores, and Valiant Halory, owned by the
Celtic Pride Stable of Rick Pitino, picked up a nice credential by
finishing second. It is really very simple with More Than Ready. He
has run 14 times, and is 7 for 7 under a mile, 0 for 7 at or over
that distance. The King's Bishop, run at 7 furlongs, was perfect
for him, as he stalked the speed, then ran by the leaders under Pat
Day to score with ease in the time of 1:22 2/5. ``We always knew
that this was Plan B,'' said his trainer, Todd Pletcher. ``If he
couldn't stretch out, he could go back to sprinting. We thought it
was so important to get a Grade I on More Than Ready's resume
(which includes a fourth in the Derby, a second in the Blue Grass,
and a fourth in the Haskell). If ever there was a horse deserving
of a Grade I win, it's him. Maybe the Vosburgh (7 furlongs at
Belmont Sept. 23) and the Breeders' Cup Sprint (6 furlongs) will be
next.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Material from The Daily Racing Form and publicity departments at
various tracks was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
