<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-PETA-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN IT COMES TO GETTING ATTENTION, PETA IS TOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Tuesday, Aug. 29, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's ROEPER COLUMN. For more information about
purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the ROEPER COLUMN _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.) 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Perhaps no organization in the United States this side of the
American Nazi Party invites as much media derision as PETA, or
People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals.
</P>
<P>
   Often the mocking is deserved. Come on, if your organization is
dumping four tons of manure in front of the Wilshire Grand Hotel in
Los Angeles, asking the Green Bay Packers to change the team name
because it glorifies meat packing, protesting the consumption of
rats by the human contestants on ``Survivor'' and campaigning to
save a rare blue lobster in a real-life scene straight out of that
infamous skit on ``Saturday Night Live,'' you know you're going to
be razzed by a largely meat-eating media.
</P>
<P>
   Members of PETA are also not above dressing up in funny animal
costumes to punch home their point and provide an easy photo-op;
for example, the PETA pranksters who dumped that manure in L.A.
were dressed as pigs at the time.
</P>
<P>
   So for material-starved columnists and commentators, PETA is a
perennial duck in a barrel, just begging to be shot. (Ooh,
unfortunate imagery!)
</P>
<P>
   PETA is also unafraid to tip over sacred cows _ so to speak _ in
the name of the greater good as they see it, e.g., their billboards
using Biblical references to hammer home a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus Was A Vegetarian,'' reads a huge sign in Corpus Cristi,
Texas. ``Show Respect for God's Creatures _ Follow Him.''
</P>
<P>
   Another PETA billboard proclaims, ``Thou Shall Not Kill.''
</P>
<P>
   (I seem to remember something about an Old Testament story about
a Passover rite involving the slaughter of a one-year-old animal
and a New Testament parable of a father who celebrated the return
of his prodigal son by killing a fatted calf, but my aim today is
not to argue with PETA, not really.)
</P>
<P>
   Also recently, PETA celebrated a victory of sorts when
McDonald's agreed to no longer purchase chicken products from
suppliers that debeak chickens or withhold food and water as a
method of increasing egg production.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these suppliers will still be cutting the heads off
said chickens, but as PETA president Ingrid Newkirk put it on the
day of the announcement, ``Today is a better day than yesterday for
the birds whose eggs are used in Egg McMuffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, some Wisconsinites were outraged by billboards that
went up depicting New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani wearing a milk
mustache, the caption reading, ``Got prostate cancer?'' In this
case PETA was not-so-subtly insinuating that Giuliani's medical
problem could have been caused by the consumption of dairy
products, which may increase the risk for prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Bing! Instant controversy. Giuliani threatened to file a
lawsuit, the company that put up the billboards started to take
them down and people were debating the merits of milk.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's something in the aforementioned stories that would
offend or outrage just about everyone who's not a charter member of
PETA _ but that's my point. Say what you will about PETA's
extremist tactics and sometimes nutty causes, but you have to tip
your hat to this group.
</P>
<P>
   They're good at what they do. They're really good.
</P>
<P>
   Before 1980, there was no PETA. Now they claim 600,000 members
and they have had an indisputable impact on billion-dollar
corporations as well as the personal philosophies of countless
individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Larger organizations wish they could generate the kind of
publicity PETA creates every week. There have been 634 major media
mentions of PETA in the last 60 days, according to a Lexis/Nexis
search.
</P>
<P>
   We in the press go for it every time _ and how can we not, when
Tyra Banks is posing half-nude for one of those ``I'd Rather Go
Naked Than Wear Fur'' ad campaigns or Jackie Chan is urging the
prime minister of India to stop torturing cattle or there's a
campaign in Las Vegas to retire Gilda, a 42-year-old elephant used
in Siegfried and Roy's act? That's golden stuff.
</P>
<P>
   As for invoking the word of God, exploiting Giuliani's cancer,
sending out Ronald McDonald-looking dolls covered in butcher's
blood, etc., of course it's despicable and disgusting _ that's the
idea. If these tactics didn't provoke a reaction from the masses
and the media, PETA would resort to something else.
</P>
<P>
   But why change when you're ringing up the media mentions? PETA
is so well-known that it's even become the subject of a new urban
legend, in the form of a bogus letter that claims the Dixie Chicks
are donating $1 of every concert ticket sold to the organization,
even as the group tours cattle country. (Actually, the Dixie Chicks
donate a buck from each ticket sale to the World Wildlife Fund.)
</P>
<P>
   I still think a good many of PETA's crusades range from the
inane to the obscene, but when it comes to attracting our
attention, nobody does it better.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the co-host of ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper &AMP; the
Movies.'')
</P>
<P>
   -------------------------------------------------
</P>
