<HEADLINE>
BIG-TIME REMATCH FOR THE US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the US men's team met Guatemala in a World Cup qualifier at
RFK Stadium four years ago, it marked a breakthrough in interest in
the national team. Previously, such games were held at small stadia
in Fenton, Mo., or Torrance, Calif., but expectations changed after
a crowd of 30,082 arrived in Washington Nov. 3, 1996, to set a
domestic record for a qualifying match.
</P>
<P>
   US Soccer Federation officials will be taking a more ambitious
approach to Sunday's rematch with the Guatemalans at RFK. More than
50,000 tickets have been sold, marking the first of three
successive sellouts involving US national team games over the next
five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 22,500 lower-level seats went to US fans, in an
attempt to create a concentrated support group. This appears to be
a good idea, since at least half the stadium will be pro-Guatemala,
including several busloads scheduled to depart from Boston, though
low-level seats are the most vulnerable in what could be a rowdy
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the US team must match the sophistication of the '96 team.
</P>
<P>
   Though the US did not give many inspiring performances during
qualifiers for France '98, and had a disastrous showing in the
finals, the players had experience in difficult matches. The US
struggled against Guatemala in '96, but after Eric Wynalda's goal
provided the lead, the team tactically protected it _ unlike last
month, when the current squad squandered the edge in Mazatenango.
</P>
<P>
   A US victory over Guatemala would virtually assure the team of
advancing to the final round.
</P>
<P>
   The other five teams to advance from the region _ likely Costa
Rica, Honduras, Jamaica, Mexico, Trinidad &AMP; Tobago _also could be
determined by Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The US could be vulnerable, since the Chicago Fire's Chris Armas
will miss the match with a knee injury suffered during a 7-0 win
over Barbados at Foxboro Stadium Aug. 16. Richie Williams (D.C.
United) will likely replace Armas. Goalkeeper Kasey Keller (Rayo
Vallecano), forward Jovan Kirovski (Sporting Lisbon), and
midfielder Richard Mulrooney (San Jose Earthquakes) are the other
additions to the team.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Cunningham, the Columbus Crew striker who was born in
Jamaica and moved to Florida as a teenager, had been expected to
join the team soon, but his application for US citizenship is far
from being processed. As of last week, Cunningham was still filling
out papers. Cunningham, 24, would provide the one-on-one threat the
US team is lacking.
</P>
<P>
   The starting strike combination of Brian McBride and Joe-Max
Moore seems sufficient, but Cunningham could provide a dynamic
threat off the bench and give the US the variety it will need as
the qualifying tournament progresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast
</P>
<P>
   The debut of Cameroon-born Jan-Christian Tchuise with the
Russian national team has been delayed. The Russians begin
Japan/Korea 2002 qualifying against Switzerland Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Tchuise, who plays for Spartak Moscow, would be the first black
player in the country's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tchuise has applied for Russian citizenship but has not been
granted it,'' said Alexander Polinsky, the team's general manager.
``Not yet, anyway. We had only applied for him a few weeks ago but
I don't know how long it is going to take. He may never get it now,
because people are beginning to question our choices.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tchuise case is an example of the changes in ethnic
diversity in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Germany coach Rudi Voeller recalled the Brazilian-born forward
Paulo Roberto Rink for the match against Greece.
</P>
<P>
   John Carew, 19, son of an African father and a Norwegian mother,
was expected to become Norway's goal-scoring star, though he has
been dropped for the match against Armenia. Carew, a former
teammate of Tampa Bay's Mamadou Diallo at Valerenga, has become
controversial and coach Nils Johan Semb apparently wants him to
settle in at Valencia in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best-kept secret
</P>
<P>
   The most undervalued player in Europe might be Mario Almeida
Jardel, the Brazilian striker whose goals gave Galatasaray a 2-1
victory over Real Madrid in the Super Cup last Friday in Monaco.
Jardel, 26, was purchased by the Turkish club for about $16 million
from Porto.
</P>
<P>
   In four seasons with Porto, Jardel scored 166 goals in 170 games
and led the league in scoring four times. That total includes 19
goals in 32 Champions League matches. In his first five games with
Galatasaray, Jardel scored 10 times, including the golden goal in
the 102d minute against Real Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Jardel is not a high-level technical player, nor does he expend
much effort chasing the opposing. Rather, Jardel is a classic
scorer, tall and strong in the air and with excellent instincts
near the goal. He has appeared briefly with the Brazilian national
team, but does not appear to fit in because of his skill level.
</P>
<P>
   Nor does Jardel fit in with the European establishment. When
Jardel became available, Galatasaray was the only European club to
seriously pursue him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jardel appears capable of providing the extra spark to lift
the Istanbul club. Galatasaray became the first Turkish team to win
a European competition when it captured the UEFA Cup title last
season. Management kept most of the team together, then hired
Romanian coach Mircea Lucescu to ensure the continuity of star
midfielder Gheorghe Hagi and defender Gheorghe Popescu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
