<SLUG> BC-COLUMN-POP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MAN DID IT HIS WAY: RAP RECALLS A SWAGGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On ``Pullin' Me In,'' a cut from his new CD, ``The Ecleftic: 2
Sides II a Book,'' Wyclef Jean denounces the state of rap music
where, ``All y'all beats are soundin' the same, y'all rhymin' the
same, some of y'all even wearing the same jewelry, and y'all doin'
the same videos.''
</P>
<P>
   He has returned, he says, to bring the music ``right back to the
essence,'' then intones:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(lyrics style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by gangstas
</P>
<P>
   I don't know how they got here
</P>
<P>
   But I feel like the Haitian Frank Sinatra
</P>
<P>
   In his young years
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end lyrics style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Haitian Frank Sinatra? Absolutely.
</P>
<P>
   In comparing himself to Sinatra, Wyclef seeks to distinguish
himself from the raggedy rap rabble. He's a cut above the rest, the
wise man among fools, the real deal among the poseurs playing their
stupid gangsta games. In a single line, Wyclef discovers what many
rappers have come to understand _ Frank Sinatra was a O.G., the
original Original Gangsta. Forget all this big pimpin' nonsense.
Brothers who know better want to be the Chairman of the Board.
</P>
<P>
   Given his beliefs about about rock 'n' roll _ he thought it
indecipherable noise for cretins and called it ``deplorable, a
rancid-smelling aphrodisiac'' _ one can only wonder what Sinatra
might have had to say about Nelly's ``Country Grammar'' or Eminem's
``The Way I Am.'' But whatever his view of rap, Sinatra, more than
two years after his death at age 82, is the new icon of cool in the
hip-hop nation. His name is evoked without explanation because
everyone, even those who wouldn't know ``Mama Will Bark'' from
``One for My Baby,'' understands that Sinatra was The Man. And it
has little to do with Sinatra, the voice of the 20th century. This
is about the Sinatra who lived by his own code, who made his own
rules, and who answered to no one.You can't get more hip-hop than
that.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't hurt either that Sinatra could raise hell at the
drop of the hat, had run-ins with the law, and was mythologized as
Johnny Fontaine in ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all like an inversion of Norman Mailer's ``White Negro,''
which launched the notion of blackness as the model that cool
whites sought to emulate.
</P>
<P>
   Kool Keith notwithstanding, you won't hear too many black men
comparing themselves to Elvis Presley. But being down with Sinatra
is all the rage, because Sinatra did the things most rappers can
only rhyme about.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Sinatra was, to borrow a phrase coined by writer
Cheo Hodari Coker, ``a white mack,'' the ultimate playa who hung
with presidents, starlets and mobsters, and who lived at the heady
core of hipness. He cared about the cut of his suits, the cock of
his hat, and the ``cuff links'' _ that would be a pair of women _
on his arms. He was a street kid from a tough neighborhood who,
with a well of style, swagger and talent, rose out of his humble
surroundings. In his prime, he didn't just have the world on a
string; he created one of his own that everyone else clamored to be
a part of.
</P>
<P>
   And before the Busta Rhyme's Flipmode Squad, or Wyclef's Refugee
Camp, Sinatra was the undisputed leader of pop culture's first
posse _ The Rat Pack. Sinatra lived his life, and showed everyone
else how it was done.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Sean ``Puffy'' Combs loves to call himself ``the
black Sinatra,'' which instantly lends him a certain cachet he
couldn't get any other way. He's gone to great pains to create his
own Sinatra-like universe, aligning himself with such people as
Martha Stewart and Donald Trump, and hosting mega-parties costing
hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   In a GQ cover story last year, Puff even said a special room in
his midtown Manhattan recording studio was designed with the Rat
Pack in mind. With its low-slung furniture and wet bars, ``the
whole concept of it was Black Sinatra,'' he said. ``Like if Frank
Sinatra was black, and he was my age, and he was me, (this is the)
kind of hangout he would have for Dean and Sammy and the guys to
come see him at the studio.''
</P>
<P>
   Puff has probably seen himself as the heir apparent since he met
Sinatra's daughter Nancy at the American Music Awards a few years
ago. Recalled Puff, ``When she was onstage accepting her father's
award, she said, `The only daddy cooler than my daddy is Puff
Daddy.' That was enough for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, Puff. If only.
</P>
<P>
   What Puff doesn't understand is Sinatra didn't have to play at
cool _ he just was. Through his life, Sinatra represented what's
been called ``a high-flying ultimate guyness.'' And in the
uber-masculine world of rap, there is no greater currency than the
realness _ the unabashed maleness _ Sinatra embodied.
</P>
<P>
   In his storied life, Sinatra was called The Voice, the Chairman
of the Board, and Ol'Blue Eyes. Now, in death, Sinatra has become
something even he could never have imagined _ ghetto-fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Renee Graham covers the pop scene for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1334EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
