<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIKE OR NOT, RAYTHEON   TAX BREAK WAS A MISTAKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon's blue-collar workers in Massachusetts are on strike,
and they are mad. They have watched their ranks thin over the years
_ from 10,000 ten years ago, to 4,200 five years ago, to 2,700
today.
</P>
<P>
   They are especially angry because in 1995 they lobbied the
Legislature to give Raytheon a tax break. In return, they thought
they were getting job security. They got some _ Raytheon is still
in Massachusetts _ but clearly not as much as they hoped for.
</P>
<P>
   We don't have a strong opinion on the strike. But we do have one
on the original tax break: It was a well-intentioned mistake. It
was based on the flawed assumption that the state could dictate the
hiring plans of a company. In an uncertain world, where whole
industries rise and fall faster than a Patriot missile, that kind
of micromanagement can't fly.
</P>
<P>
   A little history: Raytheon asked for tax relief five years ago,
to help it cope with the challenges posed by a shrinking defense
industry. With the Cold War over, there was less money around for
new weapon systems. Raytheon said it needed to cut costs so it
could compete for the few big projects the Pentagon still planned
to build. Without the tax break, the company warned, it might move
its manufacturing plants out of state.
</P>
<P>
   With the union's help, the bill became law. Raytheon, and all
other manufacturers, got lower taxes. In return, Raytheon promised
to keep its total Massachusetts payroll at 90 percent of the 1995
level for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Tolman, then a member of the state Senate, now a lawyer
in private practice, says the unions didn't get what they bargained
for. ``Raytheon hasn't abided by the spirit of the legislation,''
says Tolman, who notes that the company has since closed plants in
Waltham and Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Tolman and the union use the word spirit because Raytheon did
live up to the letter of the law. It kept its payroll above the 90
percent mark, in part by hiring more well-paid engineers and
scientists, even as it cut its blue-collar work force.
</P>
<P>
   The developments of the past five years show just how difficult
it is to forecast the economic future. On the plus side, Raytheon
survived the defense shakeout by buying up its rivals. It is now
one of the nation's three big remaining defense contractors.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, survival hasn't ensured prosperity. Raytheon
has had huge problems digesting its various acquisitions. It has
gone over budget on a series of contracts. The bottom line: The
company's earnings have plunged, and so has its stock price. Last
July, the stock sold for $73 a share. Monday, it sold for $27.
</P>
<P>
   In another unpredictable twist, the tax break Raytheon fought so
hard for has turned out to be much smaller than originally
anticipated. Raytheon hoped for $100 million in tax relief over
five years. The company says it got more like $8.2 million. It
blames the shortfall on changes in federal tax law and smaller
profits.
</P>
<P>
   The Raytheon bill, with its ``you give me something, I'll give
you something'' trade-off, became a model for other tax
legislation. The mutual fund industry won a tax break in 1996, in
exchange for a promise to add jobs over five years. The insurance
industry later got tax relief for a promise to boost investment in
the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, the mutual fund bill is a huge success.
Fidelity Investments says it has added more than 4,000
Massachusetts jobs since 1996, an increase of 46 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But did the tax break really lead to the boost in payrolls? Do
you think the long-running bull market might have had something to
do with it? If the stock market had headed south instead of north,
or if investors had lost faith in mutual funds, would the tax bill
be hailed as a great success?
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth is, the future is hard to see. America seems to
have built a system that is very good at creating jobs, but not
necessarily jobs at any one company or any one industry. In
Massachusetts, more than 200,000 manufacturing jobs have
disappeared since 1984, yet the state has 400,000 more total jobs
than it did back then. Giants such as Digital Equipment and Wang
Laboratories have been swallowed up, while new giants such as EMC
Corp. have sprung up to take their place.
</P>
<P>
   None of these developments could have been predicted. Nor could
they have been dictated by the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   So are we saying that the Legislature should never grant tax
relief? No, we are not. Michael Widmer, president of the
Massachusetts Taxpayers Foundation, says all the tax bills were
designed to improve the state's competitive posture. ``In many
cases we were just trying to maintain a level playing field,'' he
explains.
</P>
<P>
   We have no problem with that. But we do have a problem with the
notion that in exchange for tax relief, Massachusetts can get an
ironclad guarantee that the future will work out just the way it
wants.
</P>
<P>
   Making promises you can't keep inevitably leads to hard feelings
and disappointment. Just ask the union workers at Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
