<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5189 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-29 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAUZIAT IS BOUND AND SHE'S DETERMINED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nathalie Tauziat, the French author who also plays
tennis, is putting on a brave face over her game face, but inside
she is hurting. And as angry as the clouds that took a 100-minute
bite out of opening day at the US Open by leaking on Flushing
Meadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no exit,'' said Tauziat, sounding as fatalistic as
another French scribbler, Jean-Paul Sartre. ``For me there is no
way out, except with my racket. Here. This is where I have to show
I belong.''
</P>
<P>
   Belongs where? After all Tauziat, finishing up a 17th
professional year in her distinguished career, is No. 8 on the
planet. She may be the most remarkable member of the game's top 10,
hanging tough on the cusp of her 33d birthday amid a juvenile
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Belongs where? Belongs in the Olympic Games, that's obviously
where, as the second-best Gallic gal, behind the Franco-American
slugger, Mary Pierce. But she won't be in Sydney, even though she
wore the flag for France in the three previous Games _ 1988, 1992,
1996 _ since the restoration of tennis to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe,'' she said with a laugh, trying to be lighthearted
about her shameful persecution by the French Tennis Federation, ``I
should have tried to play for the Central African Republic. I was
born there, in Bangui, because my father was working there at the
time. But it's too late to apply, and I've already played for
France. I wanted very bad to play again, maybe take a medal. That
has always been a goal.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't happen because her federation, shall we say, threw the
book at her. Her own book, ``Les Dessous du Tennis Feminin'' (``The
Underside of Women's Tennis''), which has been a hit in France,
selling almost 40,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wrote the truth,'' Tauziat said Monday after her rebounding
victory over Ludmila Cervanova, 3-6, 6-2, 6-4. ``I felt after all
my years on the tour I had a right to my opinion. But it is all
politics.''
</P>
<P>
   One undisputed truth is that three of her countrywomen _ Amelie
Mauresmo, Julie Halard-Decugis, Sandrine Testud _ did not believe
in literary freedom for Tauziat. Their reaction to the book was to
threaten the federation with their withdrawal from Olympic
consideration if she were chosen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are fed up with her,'' Testud told a French newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat was not chosen. She appealed. The appeal was turned down
by the federation, and then an arbitrator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how your (American) Lisa Raymond feels,'' said Tauziat.
``She deserves to play, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond, ranked No. 1 in the world in doubles, didn't make the
US team. Her appeal, too, was rejected by an arbitrator, but she
won't have any book royalties to comfort her.
</P>
<P>
   US captain Billie Jean King sympathizes with Raymond. But she
had to make a tough choice: Raymond, whose value in doubles has
been enhanced by her Australian partner, Rennae Stubbs? Or Serena
Williams, winner of the French and Wimbledon titles alongside
sister Venus? A woman without a customary American collaborator? Or
a team favored to win gold?
</P>
<P>
   King says that Serena also gives the US protection in singles if
injury befalls one of the starters: Venus, 1996 gold medalist
Lindsay Davenport, or Monica Seles. ``We have Lisa on the alternate
list if injury removes one of them,'' said King.
</P>
<P>
   But Tauziat isn't even accorded alternate status. How nasty was
the book that got her booked for exile from the Olympics? Not very,
say my informants who read French. She wrote that the French
Federation is incompetent. That's pretty clear if for nothing else
but their reaction to the book: not selecting the strongest team
that would include Tauziat, and neglecting its duty to tell her
detractors to grow up. But that's not news. Finding a competent
national governing body in this sport is as simple as tracking down
Jimmy Hoffa.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat also made fun of Halard-Decugis's husband, Arnaud
Decugis, who uses the pronoun ``we'' when discussing the family
breadwinner's game _ much like a boxing manager. Also of Mauresmo's
girlfriend, hardly a tennis expert, scolding Mauresmo about her
shortcomings on court. And also of Testud's claims of injury
whenever she loses.
</P>
<P>
   Tauziat criticized the Women's Tennis Association for peddling
sex, not an original or outlandish thought. It seems to her that
flesh counts more than earnest hard work, citing, of course, No. 14
Anna Kournikova, ranked six lengths below the industrious Tauziat.
This is a revelation?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, history is crammed with authors discriminated against for
their art. Even in France, which generally venerates writers and
names streets for them. Such as Avenue Victor Hugo, and other
Parisian thoroughfares saluting Moliere, Racine, and Villon to cite
three. But don't expect a Rue Tauziat honoring the spunky one-book
wonder.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will soothe the miserable Tauziat to know that the
great Victor Hugo (of ``Les Miserables'' fame) was exiled in 1851
for his views, and that the Marquis de Sade was jailed for writing
stuff nastier than hers.
</P>
<P>
   In the gallant spirit of an all-time French favorite, Edith
Piaf, whose theme song was ``Je Ne Regret Rien,'' Tauziat said, ``I
don't regret writing it. I wrote the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   At least she won't be burned at the stake like Joan of Arc, who
voiced the same sentiments.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been hard to concentrate with all this going on,'' said
Tauziat, a Wimbledon finalist in 1998, the first of her country to
do so well since Suzanne Lenglen won it 73 years before. ``There is
no way out but with my racket.''
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be fun if she used it to have her best Open, and
make those who objected to her words eat their own?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
