<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-BUFFETT-BOS &LR;      08-29 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-BUFFETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUFFETT KEEPS UP WITH THE TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free agent. We know what the term means in sports, but Jimmy
Buffett is a free agent in the music business, the book business,
and in anything else he chooses to hang his ``Parrothead'' hat on.
He's one of the most admired people in the entertainment industry
because he has reached a point where he truly is making his own
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not under contract anywhere. I don't owe anybody anything.
I can sit out here and do it all on my own schedule,'' Buffett says
from his summer home on Long Island. ``You know, not many people
get to that position. And we're still out here breaking rules and
causing people grief and I like that, too. It's always good to have
a little revolutionary will left in your heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 53, Buffett has two sold-out shows at the Tweeter Center in
Boston on Thursday and Saturday. Once again, they were the quickest
shows to sell out at the venue this summer _ a sign that Parrothead
mania is still alive and well, despite trends buzzing around it
from rap to heavy metal to teen pop.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett, it seems, is always in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd still be here at this level,'' he says.
``At 53 still riding this crest, not slipping into the dinosaur
mode like others have, but still being a very current and
contemporary performer. I'm very lucky to be here. When I am ready
to hang it up, I'll hang it up in style.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's forgotten his early days of scuffling, back 30
years ago when he was a good ol' boy/beach bum who hadn't yet had
hits like ``Margaritaville'' and ``Changes in Latitudes, Changes in
Attitudes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's wonderful now, but for the first 10 to 15 years, nobody
knew my name and I couldn't get arrested,'' says the Alabama
native. ``I remember vividly playing (Boston's) Paul's Mall and
them misspelling my name. I mean, I don't forget that stuff. When
you have to fight so hard for any ounce of recognition at the early
stages of your career, then when you finally achieve some success,
it's a case of, `Hey, they'll probably have to drag my (butt) off
that stage.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Buffett can laugh at those early days now, especially on a new
home video, ``Tales From MargaritaVision,'' which collects all of
his first videos (with hilarious commentaries added) when he was
angling to get on MTV, like other would-be hipsters of the time.
</P>
<P>
   It was to no avail, for his fame would come from word-of-mouth
among fans who loved his live act, rather than from the video
airplay that propelled the likes of Duran Duran and Michael
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been on MTV and never won an award, but I kind of
cherish those facts,'' Buffett says today.
</P>
<P>
   In liner notes to the new video compilation, Buffett writes,
``While the rest of the music world charged like Sherman to the sea
toward the world of music videos, I had to be dragged by my heels
into this new arena. I was a live performer. Hell, I had enough
trouble just trying to get played on the radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the videos are wonderfully cheesy _ football star Joe
Namath shows up as a Hawaiian shirt salesman in one _ and the video
for ``One Particular Harbor'' even has Buffett wearing a coat he
borrowed from Mel Gibson's filming of ``Mutiny on the Bounty.''
Buffett also turns up in a flamboyant red-orange suit in ``La Vie
Dansante'' (``That suit went back to wardrobe _ it's probably up on
eBay now'') and he's shown in Key West playing before a haphazard
cast of locals (including a barefooted hippie who does an impromptu
jig) in ``Nautical Wheelers.'' Two other videos were directed by
Monkees singer/guitarist Michael Nesmith, who was introduced to
Buffett by actor Harrison Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of fun to go back and look at them. You know, back
when I had hair and I was skinnier. Some of them are real dumb and
some are not so bad, but I didn't get the big budgets for videos.
Someone else got all that money. It was an uncomfortable position
to be in, because I never perceived myself as a video-promoted
artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, today video is an integral part of our stage
production,'' he says of the footage projected during his concerts
of Parrotheads tailgating before the show. ``I think we have found
our best use for video, but back then, it was kind of by default.
Nobody really knew what they were doing. And the (record company)
would force you to make videos. I tried to tell them that I'd
rather spend the money elsewhere, but that's the ongoing conflict
between the artist and record company.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, Buffett avoids such conflicts because, as a free agent,
he puts out his own records on the Internet through his Web site,
www.margaritaville.com. He also has his own Internet radio station
(radiomargaritaville.com) and he's personally negotiating a own
movie deal for his novel, the picaresque, Caribbean-centered
``Where Is Joe Merchant?'' Kevin Wade is writing the script (he
also penned ``Working Girl''). And Buffett has just booked his
theatrical production of ``Carnival'' (with songs by Buffett and
script by Herman Wouk) into the Atlantis resort in Nassau for an
expected opening in February. He still hasn't given up on taking
the show eventually to Broadway, but he won't sell his soul to do
so.
</P>
<P>
   Buffett is also stepping out to play a benefit for presidential
candidate Al Gore at Radio City Music Hall on September 14 with Don
Henley, Crosby, Stills &AMP; Nash, Sheryl Crow, Bette Midler, Macy
Gray, and others. While he feels his Parrothead audience is ``split
50-50 between Democrats and Republicans,'' he is an avowed Democrat
who likes Gore for his pro-environmental stand.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Buffett continues to sell out everywhere, though from
spending time in Internet chat rooms, he has learned to appreciate
that Parrotheads follow him for many different reasons _ and have
many strong opinions about his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got those people who don't think that I should have
changed at all, and I should still be the same guy I was in 1972,
which nobody can be,'' he says. ``And there are those who don't
think I have done anything worth a darn since 1980. And then there
are people who just come on board for the party songs. So there are
all kinds of factions out there, but at least they all still
come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
