u e BC-BOOK-SWELLING-BOS &LR;      08-29 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-SWELLING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILSON GIVES SWELLING CELEBRITY HEADS A MASSIVE POP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JULES VERDONE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
A MASSIVE SWELLING 
Celebrity Re-examined as a Grotesque Crippling Disease and Other
Cultural Revelations 
By Cintra Wilson 
Viking, 229 pp., $23.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In writing about fame in these United States, Cintra Wilson is
incisive, inflamed, inflammatory, offensive, astute, vulgar, mean,
wildly funny, compassionate, and sweeping. Her dull moments are
few.
</P>
<P>
   That isn't to say that the subject of her book, ``A Massive
Swelling,'' is always gripping. Wilson, a columnist on pop culture
for Salon.com, has a readership that probably cares about famous
people _ and her digestion of them _ more than most. But for
someone who's not exactly fascinated by our nation's super egos and
the machinery of stardom, Wilson's smart, maniacal writing is the
draw.
</P>
<P>
   The author isn't one to mince words. Her opinions spew out in
profane knowing rants, with crass language that comes off not
self-consciously or for effect, but as if these are the exact words
she would say out loud. Alas, that means many of her sassiest
passages can't be reproduced in a family newspaper, but then, some
of her best lines can't be ruined here, either.
</P>
<P>
   Though the wording is a bit forced, Wilson sums up her thesis in
a heavy-handed introduction and the book's subtitle _ ``Celebrity
Re-examined as a Grotesque Crippling Disease and Other Cultural
Revelations.'' But she hammers the idea home elsewhere in more
potent, less affected ways: ``Fame-cum-sexual attention is like a
bad smack problem . . . you have to keep getting a maintenance
level into the bloodstream just to feel a normal level of
happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Better yet: ``L.A. is the place where Satan squats with an
enormous ladle and dips deeply into his black cavity to extract
huge soiled wads of cash, which he then pitches at the heads of the
inhabitants below with such speed and force that they are rendered
first unconscious, then punchy and depressed.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Wilson lingers on Los Angeles unduly, well, the list of
targets isn't limited to one defenseless city. She strikes without
mercy. Matt Dillon is a vampire. Tonya Harding is a martyr
``cackling dark and crazy at the end of the long ice tunnel.''
Robert De Niro's haircut ``made him look like a fat, mean
pineapple.'' Claudia Schiffer ``was built by professional
scientists and has no distracting human emotions.'' Cher ``has
stretched her face so hard that she looks constantly surprised,
like an ironed geisha.'' James Cameron is ``a totally loathable
Costnerian dullard and an ego-bloated dunce.''
</P>
<P>
   And that roundup isn't the printed equivalent of a trailer that
blows every one of a movie's funny scenes. Don't even get her
started on Celine Dion or Barbra Streisand or Michael Jackson or
Courtney Love.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson slags all types: black, brown, and white, men and women,
gay, straight, Presbyterian, Jewish, Mormon, Methodist, Lutheran,
Scientologist. It's none of those qualities under attack, though;
she homes in on bad taste and bad judgment.
</P>
<P>
   An aside: In the fourth chapter Wilson tells us she is white. It
then became clear that the photograph on the back sleeve, of a
woman donning a red velvet curtain, her upswept hair concluding in
a mushroom cloud, is the author. (Duh.) But though the image is
whimsical, her expression as much sorcerer as sexpot, are we to
take it as necessary _ or ironic or irrelevant _ that her cleavage
and bare shoulders are on display? Isn't this the kind of sexual
packaging she rails against within?
</P>
<P>
   But then, consistency isn't the mission here. Wilson is all
about hyperbole. When she is good, she is very, very good, and when
she is mean, she is ruthless. Ike Turner's new wife ``conjured
images of a rusty trailer in a desolate yard filled with dirty
toys, hedge stumps, angry dogs, and chicken wire.'' Wilson's take
on Ike and his attempted comeback is no kinder but it doesn't seem
so unfair: ``This was a circus of dismay, a terrible thawing of a
career that should have remained cryogenically frozen.'' By
contrast, her heart softens toward the opening band on the bill:
``They were local guys, bursting at the seams with Real Soul, in a
hearty, underdog homespun way that nearly made you cry if you were
tuning into the sincerity of it.'' Evidently, Wilson was.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Wilson's jet streams of foul-mouthed skepticism are
what'll make you laugh out loud, track down her words online, and
pass this book along. ``A Massive Swelling'' probably would pack
the best punch with pauses between chapters, ingested in occasional
installments, columnlike. You might even forgive her for using the
word ``hottie.'' Wilson is naturally, vividly, wonderfully
inelegant, and as sharp as a plastic surgeon's blade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
