<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GETTING TO THE BIG ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (With: TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting there: From Honolulu, we flew Aloha Airlines to the Big
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Celestial navigation class: It's held every Monday night from 6
to 8 p.m. at the Hualalai Four Seasons resort, about 14 miles up
the Kona-Kohala Coast from Kailua on the Big Island. It's free and
open to the general public. Reservations recommended: 808-325-8520.
Meet at the resort's Cultural Center.
</P>
<P>
   Hahalua Lele: It sails daily in the mornings and afternoons from
the Orchid at Mauna Lani on the Big Island. Cost is $95 per person,
with a four-person minimum. For reservations, phone the hotel at
808-885-2000 and ask for the concierge desk.
</P>
<P>
   Where to stay: The Big Island Visitor Bureau can supply you with
a list of accommodations at all price ranges. Orchid at Mauna Lani,
One North Kaniku Dr., Kohala Coast, HI 96743; phone: 800-845-9905;
e-mail: info(at)orchid-maunalani.com; Web:
www.orchid-maunalani.com; rooms start at $325; through December
guests can book a second room for family or friends for an
additional $20. Hualalai Four Seasons, 100 Ka'upulehu Dr.,
Ka'upulehu-Kona, HI 96740; phone: 888-340-5662; e-mail:
hualalai.reservations(at)fourseasons.com; Web:
www.fourseasons.com/hualalai. Rooms start at $450. Packages
available throughout the year; consult a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Voyaging canoes: The Hokule'a's home port is the Hawaii Maritime
Center, Pier 7, 191 Ala Moana Blvd., Honolulu, HI 96813; phone:
808-536-6373. Open from 8:30 a.m. to 5 p.m. daily, the museum has
interesting exhibits on Polynesian voyaging and other aspects of
Hawaiian sailing. Admission: $7.50. For more information on the
Hokule'a and other voyaging canoes, contact the Polynesian Voyaging
Society, at the same address as the Maritime Center; phone:
808-536-8405; fax: 808-536-1519; e-mail: pvs(at)lava.net; Internet:
http://leahi.kcc.hawaii.edu/org/pvs/ The Bishop Museum (1525
Bernice St., Honolulu HI 96817; phone: 808-847-3511; open 9 a.m. to
5 p.m. daily; admission $14.95) has good exhibits on voyaging. For
more information: For information about travel to the island of
Hawaii, contact the Big Island Visitors Bureau, 250 Keawe St. Hilo,
HI 96720; phone: 800-648-2441; Web: www.bigisland.org; e-mail:
thinkbig(at)gte.net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
