<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING     08-29 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HAWAIIANS REDISCOVER THE ROAM OF ANCIENT MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: With TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING-INFO)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OFF THE KOHALA COAST, Hawaii _ Skipper Casey Cho gives the order
to hoist the sail in Hawaiian _ huki kau la! _ and up goes
something you'll never see at the local yacht club. It's shaped not
like the inverted-triangle mainsail found on every sloop from
Newport to Tiburon, but like a massive lobster claw reaching toward
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   I'd seen this odd-looking sail design only once before: in
petroglyphs carved by ancient Hawaiians in the dried lava beds a
few miles away on the Big Island.
</P>
<P>
   These were the sails that carried early Polynesian explorers on
epic voyages of discovery across the vast, uncharted expanses of
the Pacific Ocean in an age when European sailors were too timid to
leave sight of land.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're at the center of a nautical renaissance, as modern
Hawaiians seek to reclaim their remarkable seafaring heritage. In
large, double-hulled voyaging canoes similar to the ones that
carried their ancestors to the islands, they've undertaken journeys
of rediscovery throughout Polynesia in recent years, navigating as
their ancestors did: without the help of maps, compasses, sextants
or GPS receivers.
</P>
<P>
   These voyaging canoes _ the Hokule'a, Hawai'iloa and Makali'i _
have become the icons of Hawaii's burgeoning cultural revival in
hula, arts and language, and the men and women who sail and
navigate them are revered as heroes here on the same scale as Tiger
Woods or Michael Jordan are on the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   Cadging a ride on one of these canoes is just about impossible _
believe me, I tried _ but on a recent visit to the Big Island I
found two ways for visitors to get a taste of Hawaiian-style
voyaging: a working replica of an ancient, inter-island canoe and a
free class in the basics of traditional Polynesian navigation.
</P>
<P>
   First, though, a little background. The early European explorers
who stumbled into Polynesia in the 1500s and 1600s were dumbfounded
to discover that islanders from New Zealand to Hawaii to Easter
Island _ people scattered over 10 million square miles of ocean _
spoke essentially the same language and had the same customs.
Obviously they shared a common origin. But how could these
primitive-seeming natives possibly have crossed vast reaches of
empty sea to discover and settle these tiny specks of land?
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing Western view came to be what, for want of a more
scientific term, I'll call the Gilligan Theory: That ancient
Tahitians or Marquesans had gone out for a three-hour cruise and
encountered a gale that blew them thousands of miles off course,
until they washed up on the shores of Hawaii and other islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``The unskillfulness of the pilot, or the unexpected change of
wind, would often carry the adventurous islanders far beyond their
reckoning,'' wrote Australian John Dunmore Lang, an author of two
books on the subject, in 1877. If the sailors were lucky enough to
drift to a deserted island, ``they would gladly settle on the
new-found land, fearful of again trusting themselves to the ocean,
and entirely ignorant of what course they should steer for their
native isle.''
</P>
<P>
   This view _ along with a twist from Thor Heyerdahl, who believed
Polynesia was populated by South Americans drifting in reed boats
similar to the Kon-Tiki _ was taught in Hawaiian schools until
fairly recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Deep down we were hurt by these stories,'' said Danny Akaka, a
Hawaiian historian, cultural advisor to the Mauna Lani Bay Resort
and son of Democratic Sen. Daniel Akaka. ``They played to the
stereotypes that Hawaiians are lazy and unskilled. But we knew
better.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, a group of Hawaiians got together to try to
refute these theories, to prove that their ancestors had the skill
to navigate their way among the widely scattered islands of
Polynesia.
</P>
<P>
   To recreate an ancient, massive, double-hulled voyaging canoe,
they relied on sketches made by the crews of Capt. James Cook and
other early European explorers. The lobster-claw sail design came
in part from the ancient petroglyphs found in dried lava beds on
the Big Island and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   By 1975 they'd built the Hokule'a, named for the star used by
ancient Hawaiians to steer a course home. But how would modern
Hawaiians navigate their craft? On tiny Satawal atoll in
Micronesia, they met a man named Mau Piailug, a Yoda-like master
who was one of the last remaining men in the world skilled in the
ancient navigational techniques.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 Piailug guided the Hokule'a from Hawaii to Tahiti, a
distance of 2,400 miles, without charts or instruments. Four years
later the voyage was repeated _ this time with Nainoa Thompson, a
young Hawaiian protege of Piailug, at the helm. It was the first a
Hawaiian navigator had managed this feat in 500 years.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Hokule'a and its sister canoes have voyaged
throughout Polynesia, from New Zealand to Easter Island, and even
toured the West Coast of the U.S. from Alaska to San Francisco to
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to overstate the effect this has had on Hawaiian
pride. Think of it this way: It's one thing to grow up believing
your ancestors were hapless castaways; it's quite another to know
you are descended from some of the greatest mariners the world has
ever known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly the Hokule'a was the focal point in the reawakening of
Hawaiian culture,'' said Chad Bayaban, who navigated one of the
canoes from Hawaii to the Marquesas in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Bayaban is a good case in point: In high school he was steered
away from science classes because he wasn't considered bright
enough to grasp them. Now he's developing a Hawaiian-language
science curriculum for the University of Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   As in traditional Polynesian culture, the great navigators are
honored in story and song: In a single afternoon in Honolulu I
heard two different songs on the radio and saw a music video
celebrating the voyages of the Hokule'a. A few months ago a poll
commissioned by the Honolulu Advertiser newspaper found that the
most universally admired person in the Hawaiian islands was Nainoa
Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MASTERING THE STARS
</P>
<P>
   To try to understand how Piailug, Thompson and others pulled off
these feats, I attended a program in traditional Polynesian
navigation offered through the superb cultural center at the
Hualalai Four Seasons resort on the Big Island's Kohala Coast. Held
every Monday evening, the course is free and open to the general
public. It's a subject that takes a lifetime to master, and I
didn't expect I'd become adept in one night. But the program offers
a good basic overview of how it's done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our compass is the stars, the moon and the swells,'' explained
Kaleo Kuali'i, the apprentice navigator teaching the class. ``Our
sextant is this,'' he said, holding up his hand, ``and our GPS is
this.'' He pointed to his head. ``It's all in here.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE ... MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
