<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5198 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-LASER-ART-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     08-29 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LASER-ART-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 CONCORD, Mass.: ... other endorsements.)  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One side effect of all those star-powered patients is that
wannabe athletes of all ages want to have the surgery, too. Which
is no different than their wanting to take the supplement
androstenedione when they heard how it had helped home run king
Mark McGwire, or wanting to rush back into play with a nagging
injury the way Pedro Martinez perpetually does.
</P>
<P>
   All the Stanford University football players who wear glasses or
contacts are asking about LASIK, says Dr. George Paris,
ophthamologist for Stanford teams and for the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My answer to them is that their eye has the potential to keep
growing until their early or mid-20s,'' says Paris. ``I say, `You
should wait until you're 23, 24, or 25 to make sure your eye has
stopped growing and your measurements are stable. If you have it
done when you are 20, it can correct everything perfectly, but
there may be additional growing and you may need something else
done in five years.' ''
</P>
<P>
   There are other reasons for waiting. College students spend so
much time reading books and working on computers that, even if they
had perfect eyesight when they enrolled, the new strains may
require them to be fitted for glasses or contacts and their
prescriptions could keep shifting. The field of laser surgery also
is evolving so fast that techniques are almost sure to keep
improving, making it wise to wait as long as possible before being
operated on. And even though LASIK is free of side effects for most
patients, a few percent report problems like blurred vision or
glare _ and almost all have to pay for the procedure without help
from their insurer, which at a cost of about $2,500 an eye can be a
major burden.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the young who need to think twice about what the
operation could do to them, but also anyone over 40. Nearsighted
people in that age group who get LASIK will see their distance
vision improve but may become more dependent on reading glasses.
And ones who are farsighted and want their near vision back would
find their distance vision impaired.
</P>
<P>
   For the average LASIK patient, a surgeon can minimize the
inconvenience by adjusting one eye to see better faraway and
leaving the other eye untreated or partially treated. But for an
athlete like Irwin, distance sight is so critical that both eyes
have to focus on it, which is why after his operation he needs
glasses to do something as simple as read a restaurant menu.
</P>
<P>
   Special concerns like those about younger patients, and older
ones, are why Dr. Dimitri Azar consults so carefully with every
patient who comes in seeking surgery. Azar, who operated on Nixon
and runs the corneal and refractive surgery program at the
Massachusetts Eye &AMP; Ear Infirmary, says, ``More than a third of the
patients who come to see me and are ready to have the surgery
realize that it's not the best procedure for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kornmehl, also a leading laser surgeon in Greater Boston, says
he turns away four of every 10 patients who come through his door.
And TLC, the largest laser surgery network in North America, says
all of its patients must be 18 or older and have an eyeglass
prescription that has not changed for 6 to 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Siesta, a 21-year-old art history major at Princeton,
heard the cautionary notes sounded for students like her but last
year decided to go ahead with the operation. It was partly that
she'd had the same prescription for nearly three years, and that
her eyes got tired from using glasses and contacts during long
hours of studying. She now is convinced she made the right decision
_ in no small measure because it helps her substantially when she
plays catcher, first base, or right field on the Princeton softball
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is crisper and clearer,'' she says. ``Oh yeah, and
I see the ball better. When I told a couple of my teammates about
it I could see their wheels turning. People definitely will think
about the laser surgery now that they know someone who had it
done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Jim McCabe of the Globe staff contributed to this report from
Akron, Ohio.
</P>
</TEXT>
