<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5199 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r t BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING     08-29 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HAWAII-SAILING-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; OFF THE KOHALA COAST, Hawaii: x x x all in here.'' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   We drove a short distance from the cultural center to a heiau, a
traditional stone temple platform and thatched lean-to built in the
dried lava on a point of land next to multi-million dollar homes.
The lean-to houses a beautifully polished outrigger canoe; the
stone platform is etched with a 10-foot circle delineating the 32
points, or ``houses,'' of a traditional Hawaiian star compass.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information is all around us,'' Kuali'i said. ``The job of a
navigator is to be sensitive to it and to understand what it all
means.''
</P>
<P>
   The position of the stars and moon, the color of the sky, the
shape and size of the clouds, the temperature of the water, the
appearance of certain birds _ it's all valuable data for a master
navigator. As Kuali'i spoke, a green sea turtle poked its head out
of the water and craned his neck in our direction, as if listening
for tips.
</P>
<P>
   Swells, for example, may seem random to an untrained eye, but
there are eight distinct patterns of size and frequency rippling
across the Pacific. Navigators use them to stay a course when
clouds block out the stars and sun. With this method, a master can
detect even subtle changes in course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Mau put me in charge and laid down to get some rest.
After 15 minutes he woke up from a sound sleep and said, `Hey, what
you doing?' I'd let us drift a few degrees off course, and even in
his sleep he could tell by the tiny change in the pitch and roll of
the canoe.''
</P>
<P>
   To measure speed, a navigator will drop a piece of orange peel
off the front of the canoe and count the seconds it takes to reach
the back.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   GUIDED BY THE STARS
</P>
<P>
   As it grew dark, stars began to appear above the dark bulk of
the Mauna Kea volcano. The positions where they rise and set are
the most accurate tools for a navigator, Kuali'i explained.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiians use many of the same stars and constellations as
Western navigators _ with some local twists. Looking up into the
night sky, Kuali'i pointed out something I hadn't realized was
possible: Due to Hawaii's unique latitude, one can see both Polaris
_ the North Star _ and the Southern Cross at the same time.
Generally, the Polaris is visible only in the Northern Hemisphere,
the Southern Cross in the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Hawaiians, of course, have their own names and mythology for
these constellations. For example, there are no scorpions in
Hawaii, so the constellation we call Scorpio the Hawaiians call
Kamakau Nui O Maui _ ``The Great Fish Hook of the God Maui.''
Experts like Thompson are able to use the positions and relative
heights of certain pairs of stars to determine latitude with
surprising accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   For Hawaiian navigators, the most beloved star of all is
Arcturus, which they call Hokule'a _ ``the star of joy.'' At its
zenith it is directly over the latitude of the Hawaiian Islands, a
welcoming beacon to homesick sailors returning from a long voyage.
</P>
<P>
   I came away from the program with a profound admiration for
navigators like Piailug and Thompson, but I didn't pick up much I
could actually use: On my way back to my hotel room I got briefly
lost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few days later I finally got a chance to sail on a traditional
Hawaiian canoe. The Hahalua Lele is a replica of the crafts
Hawaiians once used to sail among their home islands. It looks like
a smaller version of the Hokule'a: same basic double-hulled design,
same lobster-claw sail.
</P>
<P>
   Casey Cho, a former resources manager at Volcanoes National Park
on the Big Island, based the design on the Hokule'a and replicas of
old Hawaiian canoes on display in the Bishop Museum in Honolulu.
The hulls are rounded on the bottom, rather than V-shaped like the
Hokule'a, which makes the Hahalua Lele easier to maneuver in the
big coastal surf and easier to run up onto beaches.
</P>
<P>
   It's constructed almost entirely from wood found on the Big
Island: the hulls are koa, the mast hau, the gunnels ohia. There
are just a few concessions to modernity: an inboard motor for when
the wind goes calm, and the addition of a jib, which allows the
canoe to sail well upwind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old days they used to paddle upwind,'' Cho said. ``Now,
even the big voyaging canoes have jibs. If our kapunas can do it,
so can we.''
</P>
<P>
   Hahalua Lele means ``flying manta ray'' in Hawaiian, and Cho
chose the name after the large, bat-like sea creatures that blocked
the canoe's path the first time he launched it.
</P>
<P>
   Cho takes tourists out on the Hahalua Lele several times a day
from the Orchid at Mauna Lani Resort, a few miles up the Kohala
Coast from the Hualalai Four Seasons. When I visited in June the
canoe was just coming out of dry dock and wasn't quite ready for
customers, but Cho took me out on a short shakedown cruise.
</P>
<P>
   On the beach at the Orchid, I held hands with Cho and his crew
as Cho recited a traditional Hawaiian sailing prayer. It went in
part:
</P>
<P>
   Ho mai ka ike
</P>
<P>
   Ho mai ke aloha
</P>
<P>
   Eola e e olae
</P>
<P>
   (``Grant us insight, grant us love, grant us life.'')
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While two crew members used large koa-wood paddles to maneuver
us out of resort's small cove, a third blew a sonorous note on a
large conch shell, a most effective ship's horn.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the crew was hoisting the distinctive lobster-claw sail.
While traditional Hawaiian sails were made out of material woven
from lau hala leaves _ pandanus in English _ the Hahalua Lele,
Hokule'a and other modern Hawaiian canoes use Dacron, which is much
easier to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster-claw design of the traditional Hawaiian sails _
wider at the top, narrower at the bottom _ allowed canoes to catch
the wind while in the troughs of big swells, Cho believes. It also
made it easier for crew members to maneuver on the small deck
between the hulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked really well _ still does _ but Hawaiians dropped
their sail design for the white man's version shortly after he
arrived,'' Cho said. ``I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Winds were light the day we went out, but what little there was
the Hahalua Lele's sail snared efficiently as we glided silently
through the blue waters off the Big Island's northwest coast. Above
us loomed the hulking volcano Mauna Kea; across the channel rose
Haleakala on Maui.
</P>
<P>
   On a normal cruise, tourists are told about traditional Hawaiian
voyaging, weave sun visors from coconut leaves and are fed such
local fare as fresh coconuts and apple bananas. Our abbreviated
voyage was too short for that; I spent the time taking a Hawaiian
language lesson from crewmember Mele McPherson, who became fluent
at the University of Hawaii in Hilo.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, I understood that Cho's command of huli akau meant
``turn right'' and huli heuna meant ``turn left,'' and that the
Hahalua Lele was, technically speaking, a wa'a kaulua _ a
double-hulled canoe.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Hawaiians, McPherson is eagerly immersing herself in a
culture that is making a remarkable comeback after being all but
exterminated by missionaries and plantation owners in the 19th and
20th centuries. The inspiration for that renaissance, she said,
came from her fellow mariners and their voyaging canoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The symbol for us, the catalyst,'' she said, ``was the
Hokule'a.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
