<SLUG> BC-SCI-MARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINING IN THE TUNDRA FOR A TRIP TO MARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've just arrived on Mars as part of the first human mission
to the frigid, nearly airless world. You stare in horror as you
realize that crucial parts of the habitat that was to be home to
you and your crewmates _ your protection against howling winds, icy
temperatures and relentless ultraviolet radiation _ are lying
smashed on the ground after a landing failure. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   You make do and you improvise, that's what. Some 50 million
miles from home, there is no other choice.
</P>
<P>
   The situation on Devon Island in the Canadian Arctic was not
quite as desperate as this scenario. But it was close enough to
provide some interesting lessons about the challenges that lie
ahead for the first Mars explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and volunteers from the nonprofit Mars Society, along
with a phalanx of journalists, were at the remote outpost last
month for the construction and initial testing of a simulated Mars
base, called the Flashline Mars Arctic Research Station, designed
as a place to test methods and equipment that astronauts may
someday use to live on and explore the red planet.
</P>
<P>
   At first, despite the howling winds, everything went according
to plan. Four crates of habitat sections _ curved panels of
fiberglass that were to be assembled into a 27-foot-diameter,
24-feet-high ``landing capsule'' _ were successfully dropped by
parachute from a cargo plane, far from their target, over rough
terrain, but intact.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the crucial fifth crate separated prematurely from its
parachute 1,000 feet up. As the team of would-be Mars explorers
watched, it smashed to smithereens, destroying a crane they needed
to assemble the base, along with the module's floor panels, and a
trailer for hauling the rest of the equipment back from where the
crates fell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real object lesson,'' Society president Robert Zubrin
said in an interview. ``When we go to Mars, things are going to go
wrong. We're going to have to find alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that anybody is planning to send humans to Mars anytime
soon. NASA has been busy devising mission strategies, but it would
require a presidential decision to begin drawing up formal plans.
In the meantime, advocacy groups such as the Mars Society are
pushing for such an initiative, arguing it could be carried out
within a decade for less than the cost of the Apollo moon landings.
</P>
<P>
   This Arctic simulated base, designed to resemble structures that
could serve as living quarters and research labs for a year or
more, is an attempt to speed up the process by helping to develop
the equipment and techniques that will be needed on Mars.
</P>
<P>
   After last month's air-drop failure, the Colorado-based
construction crew flown in to assemble the simulated Mars base on
this barren terrain concluded that, unless replacements for the
smashed equipment could be found, it would not be safe to proceed
with construction. They hopped on a plane and headed home and it
appeared that the ambitious $300,000 project, funded by private
donations, was dead even before it began _ at least for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other members of the team, including the project's leader, NASA
scientist Pascal Lee, continued to explore alternatives, but they
were resigned to the possibility that construction just might not
be possible under the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, said Zubrin, a longtime believer in the importance
of human beings for planetary exploration, where a relentless
resourcefulness and determination to survive and prevail despite
adversity could prove crucial. With the society's annual meeting a
few weeks off, and the success of the Mars base planned as its
centerpiece, he was desperate to find a way to salvage the project
rather than accept a long delay.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by Zubrin, the team rallied and started brainstorming.
</P>
<P>
   Fiberglass panels that were to form the interior decks of the
two-story module were smashed beyond repair. But the team
eventually found ways to improvise replacements from plywood
obtained at Resolute Bay, the nearest town _ two hours away by
chartered Twin Otter. An old baggage cart was fixed up to replace
the trailer. But how could they assemble the dozen outer panels of
the cylindrical module _ weighing nearly 800 pounds each _ without
the ruined crane?
</P>
<P>
   Zubrin, a ravenous reader of history, happened to have with him
a book about ancient construction methods, which gave him hope.
After all, he reasoned, the Egyptians built the pyramids, and the
Druids built Stonehenge, without any cranes. This would be a lot
easier than those projects.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, a plan began to take shape, based on what Zubrin would
later describe as ``Roman construction methods,'' with a few
concessions to modernity.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a NASA researcher who has been leading scientific research
teams at the research site for four years and would bear ultimate
responsibility for the outcome, carefully reviewed every detail
with an eye toward ensuring the safety of all concerned; nobody
wanted to risk injuries on a project that was to be both an
important research program for the space agency and the crown jewel
of the year-old Mars Society's endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, after long and arduous days with teams pulling
on ropes, prying panels with levers, and slowly pulling panels into
place with pulleys and winches (the winch was electric, one of the
few modern technologies that ended up playing a part), the habitat
was completed. Local Inuit youths had been hired to help, and even
the journalists pitched in (``I wouldn't give them interviews
unless they helped,'' Zubrin saidsmugly). Construction was finished
two weeks behind schedule, and in the end everything went together
perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting structure looks something like a municipal water
storage tank with windows _ a two-story-high white cylinder with
portholes on the side and a skylight on top, and a simulated
airlock (a chamber with inner and outer doors) for for its
entrance. It is designed to hold crews of up to six people for test
runs of up to three months, during which they will study the
geology and biology of the surrounding rugged terrain, using
spacesuits, rover vehicles and other tools being developed for a
real Mars mission.
</P>
<P>
   And the way this first season turned out may bode well for such
eventual missions. ``It's absolutely a story of human perseverance
and resourcefulness,'' Lee said. ``It took resilience, it took
luck, it took close calls, deep breaths, pauses and rethinking. . .
. It took humans, and that's the big lesson I will take from this
field season.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, on Mars there won't be plywood to be scavenged or locals
to be hired. Still, ``in a fundamental sense, it's the same
thing,'' Zubrin said. ``We're going into the unexpected; we're
going to have to do things in a lot of different ways than were
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, although the season of field work was cut short by
the delays, the team was able to spend a week working inside the
simulated Mars base, and began to learn the kinds of lessons that
are the heart of the whole project. In planning a real human
mission to Mars, Lee explained, there is no substitute for trying
things out under the most realistic conditions possible to find out
what works _ and what doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Already, after testing a prototype Mars spacesuit developed by
Hamilton Sundstrand (makers of the spacesuits worn by space shuttle
astronauts), the team concluded that they may want to change the
stairs leading into the habitat to make it easier to climb them
while wearing the bulky suit.
</P>
<P>
   It's just a small example, Lee said, but he is confident that,
as they test spacesuits, rover vehicles, and tools and equipment
for geological and biological investigations, ``I anticipate we'll
learn big lessons there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, they were also learning about the real environment of
Devon Island, chosen because it is one of the few places on Earth
that recreates many of the key features that will be encountered on
Mars. In the years he has been studying the barren Arctic
landscape, similar in composition and topography to much of the
Martian landscape, Lee has already learned a few things that could
end up drastically revising scientists' sense of what Mars was like
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he has found channels and valleys in the frigid
terrain that are eerily similar to river channels that have been
seen on Mars. While most geologists have taken these channels as
evidence that Mars once had a climate much like that of Earth _ far
warmer and wetter than Mars is today _ Lee said that similar
features formed on Devon Island even under a climate that was
always as cold as it is today.
</P>
<P>
   While it is too soon to draw firm conclusions, he said, the
findings could end up rewriting the climatic history of the red
planet.
</P>
<P>
   In the years to come, the new research station should continue
to provide both a base for real research on this unusual and
fascinating terrain, and a test bed for technologies, tools and
methods of working that are being developed for eventual use by the
first humans to someday set foot on an alien planet.
</P>
<P>
   In thinking about how humans will get to Mars and begin
exploring this alien world, Lee said, most of the attention has
gone into the mechanics of getting there, providing basic means for
survival, and getting back home. ``There has been relatively little
attention to what you're going to do there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, after all, that's the whole point of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   For example, what is the best strategy for planning an
exploration of unfamiliar terrain and starting to study its
geology. Does it make more sense to do a quick, wide reconnaissance
and then pick areas for more systematic study, or to start slowly
and gradually widen the circle of exploration? Even on Earth, he
said, ``nobody pays attention to how field work is done from an
operational standpoint. How do geologists work?''
</P>
<P>
   Such questions need to be answered in detail, he said, before
setting out for an environment as hostile and unforgiving, and as
far away from any hope of help or rescue, as Mars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
