<HEADLINE>
GAS COOKING, VS. ELECTRIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I've heard that proponents of macrobiotic diets recommend
cooking with a gas flame instead of an electric burner ``so that
the food's energy won't be adversely affected.'' Is there any
scientific basis for this belief? Isn't a BTU a BTU?
</P>
<P>
   K.B., Pembroke, Mass. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Your intuition is indeed correct _ the macrobiotic notion
sounds like gobbledygook. There are some differences in how you
provide heat to food, however, and they're worth keeping in mind.
Microwaving food is based on heating water in the food and it's
difficult to get over the boiling point of water. Cooking with a
gas flame tends to give you better control over the heat than you
get with an electric burner since the temperature of the stove
reacts more quickly to changes in the heat setting, so chefs tend
to prefer it.
</P>
<P>
   Any details of how you cook food can, in principle, change the
energy content of the food but, if you're just cooking in a pot or
a pan, there should be no difference.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, the reference to ``energy'' refers to some
sort of pseudoscientific, touchy-feely, new-age nonsense, and
doesn't correspond to the usual concept of energy measured in BTUs,
or any other units.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail questions to drknowledge(at)globe.com; or send fax to:
617-929-9263, or a letter to Dr. Knowledge, in care of The Boston
Globe, Health/Science Section, P.O. Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107.
Please include your initials and hometown. Selected questions of
general interest will be answered.
</P>
</TEXT>
