<HEADLINE>
HAVING A BALL AT THE BASKETBALL HALL OF FAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking for an unforgettable weekend, or just a great place to
visit anytime? Then head to the Basketball Hall of Fame in
Springfield, Mass. especially during the Oct. 13-16 Enshrinement
Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend includes not only the enthrinement of six people who
have risen to the top of their game, but also the groundbreaking
for the new Basketball Hall of Fame. The weekend includes the music
of Grammy Award-winning artist Bruce Hornsby during ``Overtime,'' a
new event designed to give those who attend this annual event the
opportunity to mingle with some of basketball's greatest
personalities.
</P>
<P>
   The present Hall of Fame was opened in 1985 in Springfield, the
birthplace of basketball. The hall includes a three-level
entertainment center and museum with interactive exhibits that
honor the game's great players, teams, coaches, and officials.
</P>
<P>
   One of the newest exhibits is a collection of basketball cards
of Jack McCue. The collection dates from 1911 to 1993 with the
majority from the '50s.
</P>
<P>
   A special Enshrinement Weekend package is available through
Sports Travel (888-310-HALL or www.basketballroadtrips.com) that
includes all events and ranges in price from $275 to $995 a person.
For information on individual event tickets, which range from $15
to $300 for the gala, call 877-4HOOPLA or visit www.hoophall.com.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 16, the Basketball Hall of Fame NBA Game between the
Boston Celtics and Atlanta Hawks will be played at the Springfield
Civic Center (tickets are $20-$45 and go on sale Sept. 4).
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame is open daily. Admission is $8 adult, $5
seniors and students. For information, call 413-781-6500.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Foliage train &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The one-day Vermont Foliage Flyer departs Boston's South Station
at 7:40 a.m. for a colorful day of foliage viewing and touring in
the Brattleboro region. The train heads west to Palmer, then north
along the banks of the Connecticut River to Brattleboro, where
riders can continue on to Windsor and White River Junction, Vt. In
Brattleboro, traingoers can take a covered bridge tour, tour farms
or orchards, or just browse. Also available is first-class Caritas
service aboard a private rail car with its own observation
platform. The trip is $70 adult, $40 children 12 and under. Adams
Farm tour is $22, covered bridge tour, $18; orchard, $15; Windsor,
$15 or $12 for children; and White River Junction, $15 or $12 for
children. Include a stamped, self-addressed business-size envelope
with the order and mail to the Mass. Bay Railroad Enthusiasts, PO
Box 4245-BV, Andover, MA 01810. For information, call 978-470-2066.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Four Corners region &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Four Corners Region, the only place where the corners of
four states meet, has suffered with the wildfires that closed Mesa
Verde National Park. The park recently reopened and for tourists
looking for other activities in the area, other sites worth
visiting include Hovenweep National Monument with six ancestral
Puebloan sites, the Crow Canyon Archaeological Center where
volunteers help excavate sites, the Anasazi Heritage Center, and
the Cortez Center with works by local artists. For information,
call 800-253-1616 or visit www.swcolo.org. &QL; 
