 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Caribbean Bermuda &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While Bermuda is not geographically in the Caribbean, it is now
the 33d member nation of the Caribbean Tourism Organization.
Bermuda will share in the group's major regional programs,
including marketing, tourism training and education, research
statistics, and information management. ``Bermuda is one of the
last tourism destinations in the hemisphere that qualifies for
membership based on geographical proximity, cultural links, and a
community of tourism interests,'' said Jean Holder, secretary
general for the organization. For information, call 212-635-9530 or
visit www.caribtourism.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Food vacation &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The newly opened Trout Point Lodge in Nova Scotia is offering
Food Learning Vacations that include seafood cookery, cheese
connoisseurship, wild foods, even French New World Cuisine _ using
the culinary techniques and ingredients of the culturally French
areas of North America. ``We approach food and cooking more from
the ingredients side of things than most other chefs or cooking
schools,'' says Vaughn Perret, who along with Charles Leary and
Daniel Abel moved to Nova Scotia from Louisiana two years ago after
selling Chicory Farm, which had made a name in producing
European-style cheeses, growing organic foods, and operating a
Creole restaurant in New Orleans. The 10-room lodge grows all its
own foods, and uses local seafood. For information, call
902-749-7828 or visit www.troutpoint.com. The food vacations are
offered through October, the lodge is open year round.
</P>
