<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5203 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-LASER-ART-2TAKES-     08-29 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-LASER-ART-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 SEEING BOTH SIDES, CLEARLY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, Mass. _ Aging golf great Hale Irwin threw away his
contact lenses after he had the laser eye surgery that is becoming
the hottest of high-tech fixes for high-powered athletes across
America, including five Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin can now line up a 20-foot putt with his naked eye _ but he
can no longer read the date on his wristwatch. He needs his glasses
to make out the press badge of a reporter standing directly in
front of him. And when he plays in a tournament like the
FleetBoston Classic at Nashawtuc Country Club, the 55-year-old
Irwin has to bring along a mirror with high-octane magnifying power
to let him remove an eyelash or other particle that might land in
his eye.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has heard golfing wizard Tiger Woods trumpet the
laser procedure knows that it can eliminate the need for glasses or
contacts, enhancing an athlete's performance. What they may not
know is that anyone over 40 who has it may be trading
nearsightedness for farsightedness, the way Irwin did. Or that
legions of aspiring athletes college-age and younger are begging to
get the operation in hopes of realizing a competitive edge _
without realizing that they may need more surgery as their vision
matures. Or that Woods and other stars are being paid to proclaim
just how wonderful laser surgery can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``We giveth and we taketh away,'' cautions Dr. Alan Kozarsky, an
Atlanta-based eye surgeon who performed the laser procedure on
Braves ace Greg Maddux and White Sox outfielder Jeff Abbott.
``We'll give you great distance vision but you'll lose near vision,
and for a lot of older people who are active in sports that's a
great tradeoff. But if you're a secretary or librarian, where your
whole life exists around reading and you don't do outdoor
activities, you'd be out of your head to have this kind of
corrective surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   As for aspiring athletes who are trying to emulate their sports
heroes, Kozarsky, like most responsible physicians, refuses to do
laser surgery on anyone under 18 and will treat older youths only
if it is clear their eyesight has stabilized and their eyeglass
prescription hasn't changed in at least a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a young athlete who is completely tolerant of
contact lenses and do perfect with them, then leave it alone,'' he
advises. ``You won't do any better with this laser surgery than
with the best set of contacts.''
</P>
<P>
   What gets doctors even more steamed is the way high-profile
sports stars are hyping the laser eye operation the same way they
might endorse sneakers or golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, personally, it's distasteful,'' says Dr. Ernest
Kornmehl, medical director of Brookline's Center for Laser Vision
Correction and a spokesman for the American Academy of
Ophthalmology. ``It's unfortunate that that's the way that medicine
has gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to hear at the end of their testimonials that `this
is a paid announcement.' It would be nice if they let people know
that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Kornmehl and his colleagues question athletes'
claims that they benefit from the newfangled laser surgery. They
know the testimonials are true, especially with someone like Woods,
whose eyesight was so impaired before the operation that he was,
according to one source familiar with his case, ``legally blind.''
</P>
<P>
   The operation that athletes are getting these days is called
LASIK, which stands for laser-assisted in-situ keratomileusis. It
involves carefully cutting a small flap in the center of the cornea
or outer coating of the eye, reshaping it with an intense beam of
laser light until it corrects that patient's particular vision
problem, then replacing the flap. The only drugs needed are drops
to numb the eyes and maybe a Valium to relax nerves. The laser part
generally is over in under a minute and the entire procedure lasts
less than 15 minutes per eye.
</P>
<P>
   The results generally are spectacular. A couple of hours after
surgery, patients who were nearsighted _ which means they had
trouble seeing distant objects _ suddenly can read the Fenway
scoreboard without contacts. Likewise for those who were farsighted
and for the first time can find their way to the bathroom in the
middle of the night without bumping into anything or having to
reach for their glasses. LASIK also can clear up astigmatisms, the
wrinkles or other defects that blur vision. All without the pain,
glare, and scarring that sometimes accompanied earlier techniques,
and with such easy recovery that both eyes can be done at once.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of how well LASIK works is how many people are having
it: 360,000 patients underwent the procedure in 1998, the first
year it was approved for general use by the US Food and Drug
Administration. Last year there 846,000 operations nationwide, and
this year there are expected to be nearly 1.5 million _ almost as
many as the long-popular cataract surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The real breakthrough, however, is even more recent and has as
much to do with what's happening on the playing field as in the
operating room. It is one thing for an aging aunt or a loud-mouthed
neighbor to boast about the wonders of some novel medical
treatment. It is quite another when Trot Nixon attributes his
newfound hitting prowess to his eye-opening laser surgery, or when
Woods emerges from his operation to win an astounding three majors
in a year.
</P>
<P>
   The operation has become so popular among sports figures that
not even the teams can keep up with who has had it. In the case of
the Red Sox, club officials knew about Nixon, Jose Offerman, and
John Valentin, but not about newer arrivals Mike Lansing and
Bernard Gilkey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helped me a lot,'' says sidelined third baseman
Valentin, who had the surgery in December to correct an astigmatism
that gave him ``a fuzz. I couldn't see the scoreboard that well,
the lights were more blurry,'' Valentin said. ``I really saw the
ball better in spring training, but I only played in nine games
during the season so I can't really tell the difference it would
have made.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey was equally ebullient: ``It worked for me. I was
farsighted and had an astigmatism. It corrected my vision. It's
amazing what you can do with technology.'' As for Lansing, who had
the operation two years ago, he now has ``less dust in my eyes''
than when he was relying on contact lenses. The operation, he adds,
was so free of pain and hassle that ``it's just like having your
tonsils out.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods says he had complications at first: ``One day, everything
would be blurry, the next day it would be perfect. I remember in
the third round of the Disney (his first tournament back after his
October 1999 surgery), I shot 66. The problem was, the first nine
holes, I couldn't really see.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a few months, Woods adds, his eyes ``stabilized'' and now
``I'm able to see things the same way each and every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefits are obvious for major leaguers, who struggle every
day to get a bead on baseballs being hurled at upwards of 90 miles
an hour, and for golfers, who have to track even smaller balls on
faraway fairways. But the sight-improving surgery also has helped
hockey goalies like Jeff Reese of the Maple Leafs focus on pucks
slapped their way, hoop stars like Orlando's Harvey Grant steer the
ball to the basket, and scores of football stars, race car drivers,
and even wrestlers do what they have to do in their sports.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the big thing is improved eyesight, but just as often
it is eliminating the inconvenience and occasional discomfort of
wearing glasses or contacts. And for a few select athletes like
Woods, the positive surgical experience has translated into a
positive financial one, with laser surgeons signing them up for
endorsements. (TLC Laser Eye Centers, the network of more than
12,000 doctors that Woods endorses, declined to say what it pays
him, but sources say he is enough of a TLC fan that he signed up
for substantially less than he gets for other endorsements.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
