<HEADLINE>
AN AUDIENCE FULL OF SOUND AND FURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first Globe Theatre, which opened in London in 1599, lasted
only 14 years. It was destroyed by fire in just an hour, and
although no one was injured, a man's breeches did catch on fire.
Fortunately, a quick-thinking person extinguished the flaming pants
with a tankard of ale.
</P>
<P>
   The new Shakespeare's Globe Theatre, we suspect, will have a lot
more luck. With its re-created 16th-century theatre, its
interactive exhibit area, and its restaurant and cafe, the Globe is
a pleasant place to spend a few hours. Whether you're attending a
play or not (the theater season runs mid-May to the end of
September, and you should book early), do visit the all-oak theater
and listen to the guide's tales of how it was in Shakespeare's day.
Among the facts:
</P>
<P>
   --Many audience members couldn't read, so a flag atop the
playhouse would alert them that a play was going to be given.
</P>
<P>
   --Those who bought the low-priced standing room in front of the
stage were nicknamed groundlings, or penny stinkards. They ate
garlic, you see.
</P>
<P>
   --Elizabethans rarely bathed. They thought it was bad for their
health.
</P>
<P>
   --Thieves in the crowd were known as cut-purses, for obvious
reasons. If caught, they faced hanging.
</P>
<P>
   --Apples were sold for eating, or, if you wished, throwing at
the actors.
</P>
<P>
   (Shakespeare's Globe Theatre, which was completed in 1997, is in
Bankside, about 200 yards from the original site. Tickets for plays
range from about $13 to $40. Adult admission to the extensive
Shakespeare's Globe Exhibition is about $11.50. (And it's worth it
just to hear the recording of Marlon Brando delivering the ``lend
me your ears'' oration.) For more information, call 020-7902-1400
or visit www.shakespeares-globe.org. For more information on all of
London, call 800-462-2748 or visit www.LondonTown.com.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: Where in London will you find St. Stephen's Tower?
(Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: London ``is not a pleasant place; it is not agreeable, or
cheerful, or easy, or exempt from reproach. It is only
magnificent'' _ Henry James. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A word about dining: Now that we're on the cusp of a new
millennium, it's time to discard the 20th-century notion that
London dining is uniformly bad. It just isn't so, and hasn't been
for some time. Today, the city has more than 6,000 restaurants
featuring the cuisine of 60 nations. London, in fact, boasts 27
Michelin-starred restaurants, more than any city outside Paris.
Four restaurants that we have fond memories of after our most
recent visit: Bluebird (350 King's Road), light and airy in decor
and serving contemporary cuisine; Pescatori (11 Dover St.), a good
before-the-theater spot for seafood with an Italian touch; the Rib
Room and Oyster Bar at the Hyatt Carlton Tower (Cadogan Place) for
dishes such as Irish rock oysters and the traditional roast beef
and Yorkshire pudding with a modern twist; and McDonald's at
Heathrow Airport (well, we had only 20 minutes before our plane was
to start boarding). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Advice to go: You don't go to London for the weather, so consider
visiting off-season, as we usually do. All the history and culture
and just plain fun are still there, and off-season vacation
packages by British Airways and Virgin Atlantic are among the great
travel bargains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Dome lives on: Come 2001, London's Millennium Dome will be
converted into a Euro-themed amusement park. A Japanese-financed
company will take over, and attractions are expected to include a
yellow submarine, a vehicle made famous by the Beatles. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A fashionable exhibit: Contemporary fashion photography will be on
display at London's beloved Victoria and Albert Museum Sept.
28-March 18. The exhibition, titled ``Imperfect Beauty,'' will
examine the work of acclaimed fashion photographers, stylists, and
art directors. For more information, call 44 020 7942 2000 or visit
www.vam.ac.uk. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? At Parliament. You may know the tower better by
its nickname: Big Ben. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Compiled from wire service reports, news releases, books,
magazines, Web sites, and the deepest recesses of the author's
mind. Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpenter(at)globe.com. Include
your name and community.)
</P>
</TEXT>
