<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5205 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-SCANS-ART-BOS &LR;      08-29 1409
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SCANS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CLINICS MARKET SCANS FOR THE SYMPTOM-FREE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE BARNARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every worrywart has imagined the scenarios: a golfball-sized
kidney tumor that goes undetected until it has spread
uncontrollably; clogged arteries whose first symptom is a fatal
heart attack; a seemingly innocuous cough that turns out to be lung
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Sudden death lurking somewhere in the body, giving no hint of
its presence until it is too late, is many people's worst medical
nightmare. Now, with high-tech tools making it possible to view
people's innards with increasing ease and precision, a growing
number of people want a peek under the hood _ even if they have no
symptoms and it's not covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   And a growing number of doctors are ready to oblige. Through
radio and Internet advertising, tests once used only on patients
diagnosed with disease, or at least suffering from symptoms, are
now marketed to people with nothing more than a family history of
disease, or even just a touch of hypochondria. Want a computed
tomography (CT) scan, magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), or a
positron emission tomography (PET) scan that can detect malignant
tumors? You can get one, for a price.
</P>
<P>
   In a trend that has drawn fire from some physicians, clinics
across the country _ from La Jolla, Calif., to Jacksonville, Fla.,
Cleveland and the Cooper Clinic and Aerobics Center in Dallas _
offer head-to-toe CT scans, for $2,000 to $3,000. The Army ordered
similar scans for 4,000 soldiers this year, for $1 million. And
Boston's Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center this year became the
first in New England to offer a hotly debated ``heart scan,'' an
increasingly popular $400 CT scan that checks for calcium in the
coronary arteries, which can indicate arterial blockage before
symptoms appear.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Melvin E. Clouse, the hospital's vice chairman of radiology,
dismisses head-to-toe CT scans as ``overkill,'' ``a shotgun
approach,'' ``a California thing.'' But he is a true believer in
the heart scan for men over 40, women over 50, and anyone with a
family history of heart disease, arguing that seeing the white
calcium on the computer screen can spur people to make lifestyle
changes and avoid bypass surgery later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I`m on a mission,'' he said. ``I'm worse than a Baptist
minister on Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Clouse is Boston's flash point in a fierce debate within the
medical profession over high-tech screening of people with no
symptoms: Is it a prevention movement that will save lives and
ultimately cut health-care costs? Or is it medical make-work that
wastes resources and leads to unnecessary worry and followup tests
that could end up harming patients?
</P>
<P>
   The appeal is obvious: The tests are noninvasive, except for low
doses of radiation, and, in an extreme case, could save your life.
</P>
<P>
   But Dennis G. Fryback, a professor of preventive medicine at the
University of Wisconsin, cautioned against the emotional appeal of
individual stories like the one about the Los Angeles police
officer who got a full-body CT scan on a whim and found a malignant
tumor on her kidney.
</P>
<P>
   Far more frequent, he said, are the false positives. For
example, a lump shows up on the scan, prompting invasive, sometimes
dangerous tests, which show it was nothing to fear. Or, in a more
subtle case, the scan finds a cancer that might never have
progressed to be a threat, but once found, must be treated, at
greater risk and cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an imperative to treat,'' said Fryback, who served on
a federal advisory council that in 1996 recommended against routine
prostate cancer screening for the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors have an incentive to offer unnecessary scans, not only
for the up-front payment, but for the followup tests, he said.
``We're creating this whole industry, and you can bet it's money
that's driving this.''
</P>
<P>
   Reimbursements paid by Blue Cross Blue Shield of Massachusetts
for CT scans rose 17.3 percent from June 1998 to June 1999,
according to the company. And Imatron, a South San Francisco
company that makes the $1.8 million electron beam tomography
scanner used to look for coronary disease, sold 19 units last year
and expects to sell 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive officer S. Lewis Meyer said it is not Imatron
but insurers who are too concerned with money. He said insurers
have stayed away from covering the test because it leads to more
prescriptions for $700-a-year anticholesterol drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Anne Meneghetti, director of health care policy at Blue
Cross Blue Shield of Massachusetts, the state's largest insurer,
said the company pays for the test if a managed-care doctor
recommends it, though she could provide no data on whether that has
happened. The company's indemnity plan does not cover the test for
asymptomatic patients; not because of money, she said, but because
of doubts about effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The American College of Cardiologists and the American Heart
Association last month declared that the calcium scan does help
indicate coronary disease, but should not be used for widespread
screening until research clearly shows it prevents more deaths than
conventional lifestyle monitoring and cholesterol testing. Such
research eventually led to the acceptance of routine mammograms.
</P>
<P>
   Clouse said he doesn't want to wait, repeating his mantra,
straight from the AHA: ``Every year, 150,000 people die of their
first, last and only symptom of coronary artery disease: a fatal
heart attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Close has had more than 500 patients since he started
advertising last winter on sports talk and other radio shows. On
the screen in front of him one recent afternoon was the heart of
James Major, 51, depicted in 3-millimeter slices. He traced the
arteries _ left coronary, circonflex, right coronary _ and used a
mouse to circle the white spots that showed calcium.
</P>
<P>
   Major, an advocate for special education schools from Holliston,
said he was already working to keep his cholesterol down because
two paternal uncles ``dropped dead of heart attacks in their 50s.''
But the powerful image of his own arteries on the screen, he said,
would be an additional motivator.
</P>
<P>
   Clouse said patients sometimes get upset at the sight; one man
had to be sent to the emergency room for a panic attack. But Major
was calm. ``I feel a lot better when I know about a problem and am
working on a solution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similar debates are going on in different specialities around
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts General Hospital doesn't actively market its
$3,500 full-body PET scan to people without symptoms, but Dr. Alan
J. Fischman, head of nuclear medicine, said about a dozen
approached him for the tests in the last year, including a member
of the Saudi royal family who was so pleased with the negative
result that his cousin flew to Boston to get one for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Fischman said preventive use of the PET scan _ which detects the
rate of glucose metabolism, highlighting fast-growing malignancies
_ might be worthwhile for a few patients with an extremely strong
family history of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But in terms of overall use of health care dollars, it's a
disaster,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Down the hall, staff radiologist Dr. Michael Zalis is slowly
compiling a study of colonography testing, which uses CT technology
to produce a three-dimensional image of the inside of the colon.
Since the process is far less unpleasant than the traditional
colonoscopy _ in which the patient must empty their bowel and have
a tiny camera threaded along the colon _ he hopes it will
eventually prompt more people to get screened.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very interested in pushing the technology as much as
possible, but we want to do it responsibly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tests such as the heart scan need additional research to more
closely pinpoint when coronary disease becomes a threat, said Dr.
Richard Nesto, chairman of cardiovascular medicine at the Lahey
Clinic in Burlington. But it is promising, he said, especially for
areas with few specialists, where it could be offered at a mobile
clinic, as mammograms are today.
</P>
<P>
   ``People out there are hungry for a new test that isn't
painful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, the advertising is working: ``It's the only test
that patients ask for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
