<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MOSQUITOES-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR MOSQUITOES, GOING FOR BLOOD ALL IN A DAY'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RAJA MISHRA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A frenetic swarm hovers above a tall maple tree near Jamaica
Pond in Boston. Hundreds of male mosquitoes fly in small vertical
bursts, a dance of lust, waiting for mates in the evening breeze.
</P>
<P>
   A female spots the gathering and glides upward. It is time for
the central task of her short life _ to give birth. Any father will
do.
</P>
<P>
   She plunges in. Within seconds, a male locks on to her, grabbing
her scale-covered abdomen from below. Their wings stop beating.
They are belly to belly, drifting to the soft grass below. There,
the male, within a minute, completes his task.
</P>
<P>
   Now, comes the dangerous part, but only for the female. Though
the male's work is done, she needs blood to mature her eggs. She
points her antennae upwind. It can sense the carbon dioxide exhaled
by a potential blood meal from a hundred yards away.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps she'll find a person.
</P>
<P>
   In this season of the West Nile virus, the female mosquito has
become something more than a nuisance. Mosquitoes have infected
five people in New York with the occasionally-fatal virus so far
this year, and dozens of infected birds in the Boston area raises
the risk of human sickness in the region. But the chances are slim.
</P>
<P>
   In other parts of the world _ Southeast Asia, Africa, Eastern
Europe _ she is far more feared, even public enemy number one
because of the diseases she carries. Malaria, the world's leading
communicable disease besides tuberculosis, kills more than a
million people annually. Cases of dengue fever, a flu-like disease
that is sometimes lethal, are up 400 percent since the 1970s.
Yellow fever is rarer, but its symptoms are so horrific _ including
bleeding from orifices and kidney failure _ that the name inspires
fear. All are transmitted by female mosquitoes simply following
their mothering instincts.
</P>
<P>
   But the jet plane has unwittingly aided the spread of these
viruses, making it more difficult for Americans to think of
mosquito-borne disease as something that happens only in the
tropics. An infected person from India flies to New York, is bitten
by a local mosquito, which then begins to spread the virus. That is
how the West Nile virus likely arrived on our shores from Africa.
New York, in fact, has seen a small burst of malaria cases
recently, the result of malaria-carrying visitors whose blood
spread the disease among local mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   But our mosquito is unaware of all this. She bears no malice. To
those who study her, she is a beautiful, efficient creature, an
evolutionary marvel. It just so happens she is a lifeline for
perhaps the simplest of all beings, the virus, a creature that can
only survive if it finds a host to sustain it. She takes viruses
from host to host, where they multiply and flourish, bringing
sickness and death in the process.
</P>
<P>
   But the mosquito does not know this.
</P>
<P>
   So this, then, is a biography of the female mosquito. It is a
simple life, dedicated to children. And it is a dangerous life,
with hundreds of predators and a lifespan of usually a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Our pregnant female is on the hunt for a blood meal. The
thousands of tiny hairs on her antennae can sense moisture, lactic
acid, carbon dioxide, body heat and movement. In the distance, she
spots something _ a man, lazily dozing at dusk on a park bench. He
is wearing shorts. His calves are exposed. She goes in.
</P>
<P>
   Her proboscis, a tiny needle-like apparatus, extends. She sinks
it an eighth of an inch into the skin. Then she begins furiously
jabbing, 15, 20 times. Like a blind nurse, she is searching for a
blood vessel.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, she is secreting salivary fluid. When a blood
vessel is punctured, the fluid prevents the blood from clotting. It
will flow freely into her. Later, it will cause the man to develop
a tiny, itchy red bump. It is his immune system's reaction to the
strange fluid.
</P>
<P>
   It is at this point that she can transmit virus. Even if no
blood vessel is found, the virus will seep into the body and
quickly begin replicating.
</P>
<P>
   And it is here where nature seems most diabolical: Viruses
disable mosquitoes' salivary glands. This makes it harder for them
to draw enough blood. As a result, they must bite many more hosts
than usual. More bites means more spread of virus. In essence, the
virus is forcing the mosquito to help it flourish. Scientists call
the ploy ``ingenious.''
</P>
<P>
   Our female has finally struck blood. In minutes, it fills her.
Her weight increases by 250 percent. Her body becomes a bloated red
sack. It is too much. She begins urinating drops of blood on the
man's skin. He swats his legs. She flies off.
</P>
<P>
   But the blood sac is still too heavy for flight. She finds a
vertical surface, a tree, and sits urinating the unneeded blood for
an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Inside her, the blood triggers ovarian activity. For three to
four days, it nurtures her eggs. Then it is time to expel them.
</P>
<P>
   In a catch basin at the side of a Jamaica Plain road is a small
pool of rancid water. It is still. Green scum floats on it. It has
been there for days. Perfect. She gently sits on the surface. The
eggs roll out from her body. Several hundred tiny white eggs. They
bunch together in a raft, all connected and floating. The raft is
about an eighth of an inch long. Within 30 minutes, the egg raft
has a black color. Her work is done. She flies off. She will never
see her children.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks later, the eggs will hatch. Little aquatic larvae
will emerge, swimming with a jerking, slithering motion. Many will
eat their brothers and sisters. Most will feed on the floating scum
in the water. A few of the offspring may get any virus that the
mother carried, but, for the most part, the females will have to
contract diseases on their own.
</P>
<P>
   Two or three days later, they will become full adult mosquitoes.
They will fly off, all looking for sugar, in honey dew or flowers,
for sustenance. Then, the life cycle repeats itself as the males
will begin their mating swarm and the females will seek a mate.
</P>
<P>
   Our female, having just given birth, seeks to do it all again.
But she doesn't need another male. She still carries some of the
first one's seminal fluid. She just needs more blood.
</P>
<P>
   But with each birth cycle, she grows more weary. Scales have
fallen off her slender body. She has lost a leg. Her wings look
ragged. The color of her two eyes, which dominate her head, has
dulled.
</P>
<P>
   That makes her more vulnerable to the swat of human hands or the
predations of predators. In this case, she does not see the
dragonfly behind her as she decends toward the storm drain of a
house, looking for a place to lay her eggs. With a hard crunch, the
massive dragonfly seizes her.
</P>
<P>
   Her short life is at an end.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not the end of her legacy _ or the West Nile virus.
Even the cold of winter, the strongest defense that this region has
against tropical diseases, doesn't wipe out Culex pipiens, the
species of our now-dead mosquito and the species that carries the
West Nile.
</P>
<P>
   As the days grow shorter, the female offspring of Culex pipiens
stop producing new young. Instead their bodies become efficient
food storage machines, allowing them to survive the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most of the hibernating insects will die, some will
survive in a torpid state until the spring warmth revives them.
Then, any disease carrying females begin the cycle of infection
again, spreading the virus with each blood meal.
</P>
<P>
   And that is why public health officials, while urging people to
remain calm about the hazard, now believe that we must simply get
used to the West Nile virus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
