<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Here's a plan for getting quick meals on the table in
a hurry. Now &AMP; Later is a recipe cooked on the weekend in batches _
enough to serve 12 _ and functions as dinner on the night it's
prepared; freeze the rest for two future meals. The 30-Minute Main
Dish takes a half-hour or less of preparation and Fast &AMP; Fresh
gives you dinner in about 20 minutes. 
 
 The Working Cook: Mixes Can Help You Through the Week  By Tara Duggan  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; Products promising delicious instant meals
continue to flood the market. These flashy new items _ like
precooked pasta and marinara sauce in a fancy black plastic bowl
that's not only microwaveable but can be used as a serving dish _
can obscure the better instant products we've come to depend on.
<P>
   Thai curry pastes fall into the tried-and-true category.
Available in super-concentrated form, they only need a few things
added to them _ fish sauce, coconut milk, a handful of basil _ and
the end result can be surprisingly good.
</P>
<P>
   Today's Calamari with Thai Green Curry Sauce takes advantage of
squid, which often are overlooked even though they are inexpensive
and easy to cook. The spicy, aromatic dish is brightened with fresh
summer vegetables like red bell pepper and yellow squash.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it helped me get through college, I'd almost
forgotten about instant falafel mix. The product is widely
available and the crunchy, savory balls just need a few fixings,
like the tomatoes, greens and easy tahini sauce in today's
30-Minute Main Dish. If you feel like it, make extra falafels
because they stay crisp even when reheated the next day.
</P>
<P>
   The third recipe, Chicken Paella, doesn't really utilize any
quick-cooking products, but it shouldn't take more than an hour to
prepare and can be frozen for later meals. A kind of California
twist on classic Spanish paella, it features poultry sausage,
sun-dried tomatoes and a little kick of cayenne.
</P>
<P>
   Paella can be really difficult to cook. The trick is to use a
wide and shallow pan so it will cook evenly and form a bit of a
crust on top. This one might seem to have too much liquid at first,
but much of the liquid evaporates and it's necessary for even
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; FAST &AMP; FRESH: dinner in about 20 minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CALAMARI WITH THAI GREEN CURRY SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Serve this dish with steamed jasmine rice.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 onion
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound yellow summer squash
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound snow peas
</P>
<P>
   Handful of basil leaves + a few sprigs for garnish
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound cleaned calamari
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   11/2 to 2 tablespoons Thai green curry paste (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   1 can (14 ounces) coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Asian fish sauce
</P>
<P>
   4 radishes, sliced, for garnish (optional)
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Dice the onion. Stem, derib and dice the bell pepper. Trim and
slice the squash. String the snow peas. Stack the basil leaves and
finely slice into strips.
</P>
<P>
   Cut the calamari tubes into 1-inch-thick rings. Chop the
tentacles, making sure to remove any bits of cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil in a large skillet over medium heat then add the
onion, bell pepper and squash. Saute for about 5 minutes. Add the
curry paste, coconut milk, broth, brown sugar and fish sauce; bring
to a simmer. Add the calamari, snow peas and basil leaves. Simmer
for 2 minutes, until the squid are just cooked.
</P>
<P>
   Garnish each serving with basil sprigs and the optional
radishes.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Jarred Thai curry pastes are available in many markets.
For a less spicy curry, use a bit less of the green curry, or
purchase yellow curry paste, which is milder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 355 calories, &LR;   &LR; 14 g protein, 21 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 27 g fat (20 g saturated), 132 mg cholesterol, 390
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; 30-MINUTE MAIN DISH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FALAFEL WITH TAHINI YOGURT SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   This recipe is meant to be served family style, which means
diners put together their own falafels. Don't use high heat to fry
the falafels or they will brown on the outside but be raw on the
inside. It's a good idea to cut one in half as a test before you
remove all of them from the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups falafel mix (see Note)
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups water, or follow package directions
</P>
<P>
   1 small garlic clove
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup tahini
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lemon, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 ripe tomato
</P>
<P>
   6 parsley sprigs
</P>
<P>
   4 to 5 ounces baby greens
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil + oil for frying
</P>
<P>
   4 large pita breads, cut in half
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Put the falafel mix in a bowl and stir in the water. Set aside
for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, finely mince the garlic and combine with the yogurt,
tahini, 1 to 2 tablespoons lemon juice, the salt and cayenne
pepper. If necessary, thin with a few teaspoons of water for a
saucelike consistency. Transfer to a serving bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Core and chop the tomato and place in a small serving bowl. Pick
the parsley leaves from the stems (discard stems) and toss with the
greens in another serving bowl. Dress with the oil and a squeeze of
lemon juice; toss again.
</P>
<P>
   Form the falafel mixture into balls about 2 inches in diameter.
Flatten them slightly. You should have about 4 falafels per person.
</P>
<P>
   Set out a platter lined with paper towels. Fill a medium skillet
with enough oil to come halfway up on the falafels. Place over
medium heat. When the oil is hot, add the falafels (but don't crowd
the pan; work in batches) and fry for 6 to 8 minutes, turning once,
until golden brown on both sides. Using a slotted spoon, transfer
to the paper towels to drain. Repeat with the remaining falafels.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, heat the pita breads in a warm oven, then keep them
warm in a napkin-lined basket.
</P>
<P>
   Bring everything to the table and let diners help themselves,
filling their pitas with falafels, greens and tomato, then topping
with the tahini sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note: &LR;  Falafel mixes are available in bulk or packaged in
health food stores, and in many supermarkets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 625 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 97 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 16 g fat (2 g saturated), 2 mg cholesterol, 658 &LR;   &LR; mg
sodium, 21 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; NOW &AMP; LATER: dinner this week &AMP; 2 for the freezer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN PAELLA
</P>
<P>
   The green beans in this recipe are quite crisp, which gives the
dish a fresh flavor. For softer beans, add them at the beginning of
the cooking process.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 chicken thighs (about 11/2 pounds total)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 red bell pepper, stemmed, deribbed and chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cups long-grain rice
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of saffron
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound green beans, trimmed and cut into 1-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   8 sun-dried tomatoes, minced
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups frozen peas, defrosted
</P>
<P>
   10 ounces spicy smoked poultry or pork sausage, cut into thick
slices
</P>
<P>
   Minced parsley
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Remove the skin and excess fat from the chicken. Cut each thigh
into thirds, cutting lengthwise along the bone. Season the pieces
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Add enough oil to a large, wide, heavy skillet to cover the
bottom of the pan. Place over medium-high heat until almost
smoking. Add the chicken and saute until browned, turning as
necessary. Remove the chicken from the skillet with a slotted
spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Add the paprika, cayenne and onion to the pan. Saute for 3 to 4
minutes, or until just softened. Add the bell pepper and garlic and
saute for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the rice to the pan, stirring to coat it with oil. Return
the chicken to the pan. Add the broth, 2 teaspoons salt, and pepper
to taste. Bring to a boil, then add the saffron and stir until it
dissolves. Reduce heat to maintain a steady simmer; simmer for 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add the green beans, tomatoes and peas to the pan and simmer for
5 minutes. Check the rice; it should be tender. If not, simmer for
5 to 10 minutes longer. When the rice is done, cover the pan and
let rest no longer than 5 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Heat a little oil in a skillet; add the sausages and saute over
medium-high heat until browned on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the paella topped with the sausages and minced parsley.
Garnish with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 510 calories, &LR;   &LR; 29 g protein, 69 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 13 g fat (3 g saturated), 57 mg cholesterol, 367 mg
sodium, 4 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
