<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of
professional tasters tries a different product available in
supermarkets.  
 
 Taster's Choice: One Brand Creams Its Peanut Butter Rivals   By Robin Davis  
 c.2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  So you're getting ready to make brown-bag lunches
for your children again, but you want to cut the fat a bit.
Reduced-fat peanut butter may be an option, but not all brands are
alike.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's panel tasted four different reduced-fat peanut butters
and found one overwhelming favorite. All of the brands had 12 grams
of fat per 2-tablespoon serving, versus 16 grams for full-fat
peanut butter.
</P>
<P>
   By a large margin, the panel preferred  &UR; Laura Scudder's &LR;  (16
ounces, $2.99 at Safeway). All the panelists liked the exceptional
peanut flavor _ this brand contains 90 percent peanuts, while the
other brands are 60 percent peanuts. The panel also liked the dark,
rich color. One panelist described this as ``a more grown-up peanut
butter.'' All would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Second place went to  &UR; Safeway &LR;  (18 ounces, $2.39 at Safeway).
All the panelists noted that this was sweeter than Laura Scudder's,
but many thought children would like it. Two noted a gritty
texture. Three would buy it, one might buy it and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jif &LR;  (18 ounces, $2.79 at Andronico's) came in third. One
panelist thought it didn't have enough peanut flavor, but another
thought the nutty taste was good. Two panelists disliked the gritty
texture. One would buy it, one might buy it and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth place went to  &UR; Skippy &LR;  (18 ounces, $2.59 at Safeway).
Panelists thought this brand was the sweetest. Two panelists
detected a chemical plastic-y flavor; others thought it lacked
peanut flavor. None would buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were Meryl Bennan, food writer and consultant; John P.
Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler, consultant and food
writer; Roland Passot, chef-owner of La Folie in San Francisco and
Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk Webber, chef-owner,
Cafe Kati, San Francisco. A perfect score for any prduct would be
100. All products are tasted blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
