<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOODNEWS-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Food, nutrition and health studies bombard us, but
the seemingly endless information is often as confusing as it is
enlightening. With Food in the News, The Chronicle's Food staff
aims to change that. This round-up column will make practical sense
of the latest nutrition-related studies _ as well as offering
offbeat but tantalizing snippets of other food news to put on your
plate. &HT;     
 Food in the News: Boomers Need Spicier Food   By Kim Severson  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; America's restaurant customers are entering a
meatier, spicier, more experimental phase, according to a
collection of industry trends culled by the California Restaurant
Association.
<P>
   And people are spending more money at restaurants, eating more
take-out food and searching for food they can eat on the move, says
John Dunlap, president of the 3,500-member restaurant association.
</P>
<P>
   He outlined the trends at the Western Foodservice and
Hospitality Expo last week in San Francisco, where 1,100 companies
displayed the latest in large-scale kitchen equipment, mass-market
food and popular drinks for 28,000 visitors.
</P>
<P>
   Spice is a big trend, Dunlap says. Last year, Americans used
over 3.1 pounds of spices, a pound more than used a decade ago. And
between 1992 and 1996, some 2,300 new spices, extracts and
seasonings were introduced in the market.
</P>
<P>
   Salsa and sauce makers also reported increases. The Mexican
sauce market is up about 15 percent over last year, and hot pepper
sauces have jumped by 9.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason, he says, is the Baby Boomer generation.
</P>
<P>
   As the boomers age, their taste buds are becoming less sensitive
and they crave hotter, more flavorful food. That's the operating
principle for some of the vendors at the Expo, who targeted boomers
with items like a spicy, smoky chipotle version of the popular
cheese-stuffed jalape &LR; n &LR; o and spicier versions of chicken wings,
salsa and sausages.
</P>
<P>
   On the upscale level, restaurants are increasingly incorporating
Nuevo Latino food. Look for dishes with corn, plantains, chiles and
tropical fruit, reflecting a growth in the United States' Latino
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Among other trends Dunlap cited: &QL; 
_ As people's lives become increasingly busy and technology changes
more aspects of daily living, restaurants will serve as peaceful
respites from daily life. Dunlap says restaurants that position
themselves as offering a ``high peace'' experience will be popular
antidotes to a ``high pace'' lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   _ When it comes to health, people aren't as concerned as they
used to be, Dunlap says. Americans are less obsessed with dieting
and nutrition than they were in much of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Along those lines, beef continues its comeback. Over the
course of the last decade, Americans ate 13 percent more beef, or
7.1 million servings. A survey last year by Restaurants USA
magazine showed that 41 percent of the people asked want to see
more meat on the menu. And the number of steakhouses increased by
almost 11 percent between 1997 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ethnic food will become more popular, with regional cooking
taking the forefront. Italian food will be subdivided into
Ligurian, Venetian or Milanese, for example. People will seek out
Pueblan, Oaxacan or Yucatan food instead of the ubiquitous Mexican
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   _ The interest in experimenting in the kitchen is rising. In the
West, in particular, people want to try new things. Almost 40
percent of people living in the western half of the United States
say they experiment with their cooking regularly and almost 30
percent say they are always in search for new and unusual flavors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1358EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
