<SLUG> BC-KUNITZ-POEMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME OF KUNITZ'S WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Sidebar to PROFILE-KUNITZ; a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
(Poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``End of Summer''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An agitation of the air,
</P>
<P>
   A perturbation of the light
</P>
<P>
   Admonished me the unloved year
</P>
<P>
   Would turn on its hinge that night.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I stood in the disenchanted field
</P>
<P>
   Amid the stubble and the stones,
</P>
<P>
   Amazed, while a small worm lisped to me
</P>
<P>
   The song of my marrow-bones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blue poured into summer blue,
</P>
<P>
   A hawk broke from his cloudless tower,
</P>
<P>
   The roof of the silo blazed, and I knew
</P>
<P>
   That part of my life was over.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Already the iron door of the north
</P>
<P>
   Clangs open: birds, leaves, snows
</P>
<P>
   Order their populations forth,
</P>
<P>
   And a cruel wind blows.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``An Old Cracked Tune''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My name is Solomon Levi,
</P>
<P>
   the desert is my home,
</P>
<P>
   my mother's breast was thorny,
</P>
<P>
   and father I had none.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The sands whispered, (itals)Be separate,(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   the stones taught me, (itals)Be hard.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   I dance, for the joy of surviving,
</P>
<P>
   on the edge of the road.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Three Floors''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mother was a crack of light
</P>
<P>
   and a gray eye peeping;
</P>
<P>
   I made believe by breathing hard
</P>
<P>
   that I was sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sister's doughboy on last leave
</P>
<P>
   had robbed me of her hand;
</P>
<P>
   downstairs at intervals she played
</P>
<P>
   `Warum' on the baby grand.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the roof a wardrobe trunk
</P>
<P>
   whose lock a boy could pick
</P>
<P>
   contained a red Masonic hat
</P>
<P>
   and a walking stick.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bolt upright in my bed that night
</P>
<P>
   I saw my father flying;
</P>
<P>
   the wind was walking on my neck,
</P>
<P>
   the windowpanes were crying.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From ``Collected Poems,'' by Stanley Kunitz, to be published in
October by W. W. Norton
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
