 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, wine editor Gerald Boyd discusses a
variety of wine topics. 
 
 Wine Potpourri: Cabernet Kicks Merlot to the Curb   By Gerald D. Boyd  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Anyone who doesn't believe there's a lot of
disposable income floating around in Northern California should
read the latest wine buying habits survey from the Wine Club.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Compiled by Gomberg, Fredrikson &AMP; Associates, the annual survey
questioned customers of the Wine Club's three California stores in
San Francisco, Santa Clara and Santa Ana. The GF&AMP;A report notes
that 83 percent of the Wine Club's customers consider themselves
wine enthusiasts who know a lot about wine. They spend
approximately $2,000 a year in retail wine purchases and another
$500 in wine purchases in restaurants. That's big money, although
the survey notes that those high numbers aren't very different from
the results of the 1999 survey.
</P>
<P>
   More than half of the committed wine drinkers told GF&AMP;A that
they enjoy wine five days a week, while 28 percent say they drink
wine every day. Now you know why rare cult wines are so hard to
find.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to two years ago, 64 percent claimed they are drinking
the same amount of wine, 28 percent say they are drinking more
wine, and 8 percent say they are drinking less wine.
</P>
<P>
   Women shoppers account for 20 percent of wine purchases at the
Wine Club, up 3 percent from last year. The breakout by age shows
those 40 years and older accounting for 86 percent of the
purchases, with 65 percent reporting incomes of over $100,000 per
year.
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnay is still the most popular white wine, with 47 percent
saying they purchase Chardonnay most often ($25 is the most
shoppers would pay for a bottle), followed by Sauvignon Blanc at 30
percent (and topping out at $18). Pinot Gris, Pinot Grigio,
Riesling and Viognier together constitute less than 10 percent of
white-wine purchases.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest surprise in buying habits is with the red wines,
with the popularity of Merlot falling way short of Cabernet. Some
35 percent of the respondents say they prefer Cabernet Sauvignon,
while 22 percent opt for Zinfandel, 12 percent for Merlot, and 9
percent for Pinot Noir.
</P>
<P>
   Wine buyers would fork over as much as $40 for a Cabernet
Sauvignon, but only $25 for a Zinfandel. Wise shoppers know, of
course, that many a Zinfandel at $25 or less is the quality peer of
a $40 Cabernet. And who hasn't found a Sauvignon Blanc for less
than $18 that is a better match with food than a $25 Chardonnay?
</P>
<P>
   In addition to wine purchases at the Wine Club stores, 69
percent of those surveyed purchase wine from wineries, 39 percent
from supermarkets, 33 percent from club stores and 10 percent from
the Internet _ double from last year's survey. For a more in-depth
look at wine and food sales on the Internet, see the Sept. 13 Food
Section.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wine Export Success &LR;
</P>
<P>
   While wineries watch domestic wine sales inch up, the wine
export picture is not as rosy, according to a survey by San
Francisco State University business professors Rick Castaladi,
Murray Silverman and Sanjit Sengupta. Out of 240 wineries in
California and the Pacific Northwest, 44 percent are involved in
exporting, although 73 percent say their export program is not
profitable, 60 percent do not consider their export program a
success and 61 percent claim that their export program has not met
their expectations.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; More Stupid Wine Tools &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The June 21 Wine Potpourri on ``Stupid Wine Tools'' got readers
thinking and poking around for more of the same. John Blackburn
Hughes e-mailed, ``At a foodie trade show at the Moscone Center, I
saw an eyedropper-size `anti-freeze' tester, complete with pocket
clip, that has a float within the glass tube neatly graduated to
reveal the `proof' of your personal martini.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only does the tester qualify as a ``Stupid Spirit Tool,''
but its intent as an ``anti-freeze tester'' sends the wrong message
that could be construed as overindulgence. Anti-freeze is a
negative term for spirits that should be forgotten by everyone,
including spirits marketers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
