<SLUG> BC-BUSY-SIGNALS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSY SIGNAL SERVICE DRAWS COMPLAINT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VANESSA HUA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A consumer group is accusing Pacific Bell of
violating state rules by interrupting busy signals with a message
that the caller can get ``repeat dialing'' for a charge of 95
cents.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Ratepayer Advocates, the consumer branch of the
California Public Utilities Commission, filed a complaint charging
that Pacific Bell, a unit of SBC Communications Inc. in San
Antonio, failed to give adequate notice and wrongfully markets the
service to customers with unpublished phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Pacific Bell started pitching the service whenever a
consumer reached a busy signal with this message: ``The number is
busy. For 95 cents, let Repeat Dialing call you back when the line
is free. To use it, just press 3. If you subscribe to Repeat
Dialing, there is no additional charge.''
</P>
<P>
   The service used to be initiated by the customer, by dialing 66,
for a cost of 75 cents. Or subscribers paid $3.23 per month for the
service. Now users just press ``3'' to activate the service.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Pacific Bell sent notices with bills explaining the
new feature, touted as an ``improvement to busy signals . . . an
enhancement to Repeat Dialing.''
</P>
<P>
   In May, Pacific Bell informed the PUC that it planned to raise
prices from 75 cents to 95 cents. The PUC approved the rate
increase, but was not told about the change in the manner the
service would be offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of customers choosing to do this, Pacific Bell
interjects into the phone call,'' said Laura Tudisco, a lawyer for
the Office of Ratepayer Advocates. ``Given this was a significant
change, we think it's important that the commission should have
known.''
</P>
<P>
   A telephone company official said the change of service was
appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commission got back to us and told us our advice letter
had cleared, go ahead and do it. What's approval if that isn't
it?'' Pacific Bell spokesman John Britton said.
</P>
<P>
   Britton said that the repeat-dialing message does not constitute
unsolicited marketing. ``Nobody calls anyone who's unlisted. When
the line is busy, it offers a choice to use technology to help them
reach that person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
