<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Every other week, The Chronicle features ``Learning
to Cook'' by Marion Cunningham, a cooking teacher and cookbook
author best known for her revisions of the Fannie Farmer cookbooks.
This column is intended for novices in the kitchen. &HT;     
 Learning to Cook: Gremolata Brings a Drab Dish to Life  By Marion Cunningham 
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; We've all heard that tired old saying, ``It's the
little things in life that matter.'' Tired or not, this is
especially true of home cooking. A very drab dish can become bright
and sparkling with the right condiment.
<P>
   Gremolata is just such a condiment. This classic Italian
garnish, traditionally served with osso buco, is made of finely
minced garlic, lemon zest and parsley, moistened with olive oil and
seasoned with a dash of salt.
</P>
<P>
   Gremolata can provide a lively finish to a multitude of dishes,
especially bland ones like plain pasta, baked potatoes, mild soups
or rice.
</P>
<P>
   Leftover gremolata often is served with chunks of bread as a
side dish. But beware, dunking bits of bread into this heady
mixture can be addictive. Before you know it, you'll be too full
for the rest of the meal.
</P>
<P>
   Making gremolata a day ahead gives the flavors a chance to
strengthen and blend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
EGGS, TOMATOES &AMP; POTATOES WITH GREMOLATA
</P>
<P>
   Make the gremolata one day ahead to allow the flavors to blend.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   Gremolata
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt + salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Vegetables &AMP; Eggs
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds small red new potatoes, about 11/2-inches in
diameter
</P>
<P>
   8 eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 tomatoes, cored, each cut into 6 wedges
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; To make the gremolata: &LR;  Pour the olive oil into a pint jar
that has a tight-fitting lid. Add the lemon zest, parsley and
garlic. Add 1/2 teaspoon salt. Screw the lid on the jar and shake
until well mixed. Remove the lid and taste the mixture. Add salt in
1/2 teaspoon increments until the gremolata tastes well balanced.
Cover and refrigerate. Bring to room temperature and stir well
before using.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cooking the eggs and potatoes: &LR;  Put the potatoes and eggs
(still in their shells) in a large pot of salted water. Bring to a
boil, reduce heat and simmer for 12 to 15 minutes, or until the
potatoes are tender when pierced with a knife.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the potatoes and eggs and put them into a large bowl,
allowing them to cool enough to handle.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Finishing the dish:  &LR; Cut the potatoes into quarters and place
in a serving bowl. Shell and quarter the eggs, then add to the
potatoes. Add the tomato wedges. Using your hands, lightly toss the
eggs and vegetables, adding salt as you work. Add half of the
gremolata to the mixture and stir to combine. Add more gremolata if
needed.
</P>
<P>
   Any leftover gremolata may be passed at the table. It keeps well
in the refrigerator for up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING (using half of the gremolata): &LR;   &LR; 430 calories, &LR; 
 &LR; 18 &LR;   &LR; g protein, 38 g carbohydrate, 24 g fat (5 g saturated), 416
mg &LR;   &LR; cholesterol, 1,354 mg sodium, 2 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; ZESTING A LEMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Using a vegetable peeler, carefully strip off the yellow skin of
the lemon. Be careful to get only the yellow part, or zest. The
white part, or pith, can be bitter.
</P>
<P>
   Stack the pieces of zest on a cutting board. Using a sharp
chef's knife, cut or chop the zest into the size pieces called for
in your recipe.
</P>
<P>
   If desired, this may be done up to 1 hour ahead of time. Place
the chopped zest on a square of wax paper, fold the paper into an
air-tight parcel and set aside either in the refrigerator or at
room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; CHOPPING PARSLEY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Rinse a bunch of parsley under cool tap water. Shake well to rid
of excess water. Or set aside in a colander to drain for up to 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't need a whole bunch of parsley, place only what
you'll need on a cutting board. Cut off and discard the thick
stems. Fold the parsley into a rough ball and, holding the ball
together, chop into the size pieces you desire.
</P>
<P>
   Put the remaining untrimmed parsley into a plastic bag and store
in the crisper compartment of the refrigerator. (This should keep
well for up to 10 days.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
