A5222 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-ORGAN-SHORTAGE-ART-BO     08-29 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGAN-SHORTAGE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 CHILD'S PLIGHT SHOWS LIMITS IN ORGAN DONATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Rachel Sweet is lying still in the intensive care unit
at Children's Hospital, tubes pumping food into her stomach,
medicine into her arm and belly, and oxygen into her nostrils, as
she waits to die.
</P>
<P>
   What could save the 6-month-old with cafe-au-lait hair and
blue-grey eyes are new lungs. But they have to come from an infant
her age, or at least her size. And they must come soon; even a mild
cold would be more than she could tolerate, her doctor says.
</P>
<P>
   The odds are not good. While Americans' willingness to offer
organs for transplantation has increased in recent years, falling
rates of violent and accidental deaths, combined with rising
numbers of people living long, healthy lives are shrinking the
availability of suitable organs. That depleted organ bank is an
unanticipated and underappreciated dark side of the otherwise
upbeat trends of declining crime rates and growing acceptance of
seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very good news that safety precautions taken by people
are decreasing the underlying potential for donors,'' said Sean
Fitzpatrick of the New England Organ Bank. ``But what that means
for the medical system is we have to maximize our opportunities
with those donors who do become available at hospitals.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients needing organ transplants have always faced long odds.
Only 4 in every 1,000 people who die are medically suitable for
organ donation. Some are too old. Others have died of heart disease
that robbed their organs of blood needed to remain viable. Others
died of cancer that could have spread or of AIDS or other
transmittable ailments.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves mainly those who died of severe brain injuries _
such as car crashes, bicycle mishaps, and gunshot wounds _ so that
their heart and lungs worked until the end, keeping the rest of the
body healthy. Of that group, only about 1 in 100 are of an age that
would be suitable for Rachel.
</P>
<P>
   The New England Organ Bank has been doing what it can to improve
those odds by working closely with Rachel's parents and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel's condition is ``extremely rare,'' her doctors said. It
is called alveolar dysplasia, which, together with her pulmonary
vascular disease, means that she has too few air sacs to breath
normally and that the ones she has do not function properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She cannot breathe effectively and expends tremendous energy,
even at rest, which has secondary effects on the rest of her
body,'' said Dr. Melvin Almodovar, the pediatric cardiologist
overseeing Rachel's treatment. ``Her heart works harder to
compensate, and she can't grow and develop properly, physically and
neurodevelopmentally.''
</P>
<P>
   The only solution is to get her a new set of lungs, Almodovrar
added. Since live donations are not done for infants that small,
the donation must come from an infant or very small child who has
just died. And given the short time to do a transplant, once a
donor is found, the likeliest donors would have lived in the
eastern half of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we find a donor, I am optimistic Rachel could live a
reasonably normal childhood,`` her doctor said. ``The expectation
is a 60 percent chance of a transplant recipient like her being
alive in three years.''
</P>
<P>
   As she waits for a donation, Rachel is being given medicines
through a tube in her stomach and another in her arm, along with
sedatives to prevent her from becoming agitated and putting too
much pressure on her tender organs.
</P>
<P>
   She already has been through more medical stress than most
adults experience in a lifetime, with an operation to close a hole
in her heart two weeks after she was born and all sorts of
treatments during the five of her six months she has spent in the
hospital. She has also needed help breathing from the start,
spending part of her young life living under an oxygen tent and now
getting help from a tube in her nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to call her our `little cake'; when they put the lid
on her air tank, she looked like a cake does when a restaurant puts
a lid on it,'' recalled her mother, Stacey Sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Sweet and her husband have been staying close by Rachel since
she was moved back to Children's in June from the family's home in
Barnstead, N.H. Before she was fitted with her new breathing tube,
her mother said, Rachel was talking, saying, ``Thank you,'' ``OK,''
and ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she is just making cooing sounds like other babies, but
she's very alert, intelligent, and good with her hands,'' Sweet
said.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel is at the top of the list of infants nationwide awaiting
a lung transplant, but that does not mean her chances are good.
Each year there are only about 100 infant donors in the nation,
which includes those giving hearts, kidneys, livers, and all other
organs.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of potential donors is shrinking for all age groups,
but the trend is especially pronounced for those under 14, as
improved bike helmets, child safety seats, and smoke detectors have
helped cut injury-related deaths for that age group by 50 percent
in the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, more than 71,000 people are awaiting organ donors,
with a new one added every 14 minutes. Last year more than 6,000
patients awaiting organs died, for a rate of 16 a day.
</P>
<P>
   In New England, the list of those awaiting organ donations
includes 3,500 names, 2,400 from Massachusetts. The region has seen
its consent rate among eligible donors rise steadily since 1995,
when 53 percent of them or their relatives said yes. Last year the
rate reached 62 percent.
</P>
<P>
   However, the number of actual donors in the region was down last
year to 174, from its peak of 198 the year before, a drop that
donor bank officials attribute to an even steeper drop in the
number of people dying of conditions that would allow them to
contribute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
