<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: The Chronicle regularly features ``Best Way'', a
column in which the Food staff tries to establish the most reliable
way to cook many of our favorite foods. 
 
 Best Way: Storing Fresh Herbs  By Amber Thompson 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO _  &LR; I've watched many a fresh herb lose its life right
in front of my eyes. Stems start to droop, leaves lose color and
I'm left wondering how I could have delayed the inevitable.
<P>
   So what is the best way to store fresh herbs? And does the
answer vary depending on the type of herb? To test which method is
best, we stored five herbs _ parsley, thyme, cilantro, mint and
basil _ 17 ways. We checked their appearance, smell and taste every
day for two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For one set of tests, we placed the stems in glasses of water
and put one glass in the refrigerator and one on the countertop.
For another test, we wrapped the stems and the whole plant in damp
paper towels. With each set, we tested the effects of pre-washing
the herbs and covering them with plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   Not forgetting the easy route, we also tested doing nothing _
leaving the herbs in their supermarket plastic bags and placing
them in the crisper box.
</P>
<P>
   We quickly discovered that some storage methods were detrimental
to all the herbs. Any herb exposed to open air, whether it's in the
refrigerator or on the countertop, begins to wilt within a day.
Beyond that, however, results varied from herb to herb.
</P>
<P>
   Thyme and parsley were the long-distance winners and the easiest
to care for, too. Storing them in a plastic bag _ either the one
from the supermarket or a food storage bag _ and putting them in
the crisper yielded the best results.
</P>
<P>
   Mint and cilantro demand more attention. While both were ruined
by the third day in the crisper box, they thrived wrapped in damp
paper towels, placed in a plastic bag and stored on a refrigerator
shelf. Even by day 10, the mint and cilantro had solid stems, firm
leaves and pleasant aromas.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, delicate basil flourished in a few different
storage environments. But it lasted longest when the stems were
placed in a glass of water, the leaves covered with a plastic bag,
and the herb left on the kitchen counter. If you don't have extra
space on your countertops, basil also stores well, either washed or
unwashed, wrapped in damp paper towels, covered in plastic and
stored on a refrigerator shelf. Basil also likes the crisper box.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; THE BEST WAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Thyme and parsley. &LR;  Keep it simple. Store both herbs in their
original plastic bags and place in the crisper box.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Mint and cilantro. &LR;  Protect these herbs by wrapping their
stems and leaves in damp paper towels then storing them in a
plastic bag on a shelf in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Basil. &LR;  This herb thrives at room temperature. Place the
stems in a glass of water, cover the leaves with a plastic bag and
keep on the kitchen counter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0120 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d BC-SECRET-TEA-SFCHRON &LR;      08-29 0791
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-TEA-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe
for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the chef's
secrets for making it a success. Tips and recipe follow in optional
trim. 
 
 Secrets of Success: Spago's Finesse Shows in Tea-Smoked Salmon   By Michael Bauer  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  Tea-smoked foods, used extensively in Chinese
cuisines, have worked their way into the Western kitchen. More and
more, you find meats and poultry flavored with tea showing up on
Bay Area menus.
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the best examples I've seen was devised by Michael
French, the chef at Spago Palo Alto. He's concocted a process of
tea-smoking marinated salmon fillets on top of the stove.
</P>
<P>
   The only items you need are a roasting pan with a tight-fitting
lid and a rack to fit inside the pan. The pan is lined with foil
and covered by a layer of rice, tea and sugar. The ingredients will
begin to smoke; once you add the fish, it will be done in about 10
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Before serving, the fillets are brushed with a plum glaze and
broiled until crisp on top, adding an alluring contrast to the
salmon. These fillets make great dinner-party fare.
</P>
<P>
   At Spago Palo Alto, French serves this dish with mixed Asian
greens dressed with a citrus-black bean vinaigrette. At home the
salmon can be served on mixed greens for an appetizer, or with
steamed asparagus or other vegetables as a main course.
</P>
<P>
   The salmon dish is typical of Spago and its sister restaurant
Postrio in San Francisco. Both have been pioneers in mixing the
flavors of Europe, California and Asia. The tea-smoked salmon is a
clever example of this often subtle marriage of East and West.
</P>
<P>
   With a bright modern interior designed by Adam Tihany, Spago has
become one of the most popular restaurants in the Bay Area. The
large bar in a building next door and the patio seating in between
the buildings makes it a perfect place during the balmy summer and
fall months.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Spago Palo Alto, 265 Lytton Ave. (near Bryant), Palo Alto; &LR; 
 &LR; (650) 833-1000. Dinner nightly; lunch weekdays. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; SECRETS OF SUCCESS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Stove-top smoking &LR; . The salmon takes on an exotic flavor by
being smoked in a pan layered with rice, sugar and smoldering tea
leaves.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; The curing &LR; . Rubbing the salmon fillets with sugar, salt and
spices and letting them marinate for an hour adds an extra dose of
flavor to balance the smoke.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Two cooking methods &LR; . The salmon is first smoked for 10
minutes, then it's brushed with plum glaze and broiled to form a
crisp skin.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TEA-SMOKED SALMON WITH PLUM GLAZE
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   The Salmon
</P>
<P>
   1 star anise
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon Sichuan peppercorns
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   4 salmon fillets with skin (about 6 ounces each)
</P>
<P>
   Glaze
</P>
<P>
   1 cup plum wine
</P>
<P>
   1 cup mirin
</P>
<P>
   1 cup tamari
</P>
<P>
   2 star anise
</P>
<P>
   2 cinnamon sticks
</P>
<P>
   3 cardamom pods
</P>
<P>
   Smoking Ingredients
</P>
<P>
   1 cup rice (preferably jasmine or basmati)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup loose-leaf green tea
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; To cure the salmon:  &LR; Grind the star anise and peppercorns
in a spice grinder or an electric coffee grinder reserved for
spices. Transfer to a bowl. Add the sugar and salt and mix well.
Spread the mixture over the salmon and refrigerate for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the glaze:  &LR; Combine the plum wine, mirin, tamari, star
anise, cinnamon and cardamom in a medium saucepan. Simmer over
medium heat for about 30 minutes, or until the mixture is reduced
to a glaze. Do not boil. Remove from heat, strain into a bowl and
refrigerate until chilled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To smoke the salmon:  &LR; Line the bottom of a roasting pan with
foil. Spread the rice evenly over the foil, cover the rice evenly
with sugar and top with the tea leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Place the roasting pan over low heat until the rice mixture
begins to smoke. Rinse the salmon. Place the fillets skin-side up
on a rack in the roasting pan. Cover and smoke for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Note:  &LR; The tea should be glowing, which depending on your
stove, may require starting at medium to high heat, then reducing
the temperature to continue the smoking process.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the fillets from the pan and brush the skin side with the
glaze. Place the fish on a broiling pan skin-side up and broil for
about 4 minutes, or until crisp.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 525 calories, &LR;   &LR; 38 g protein, 20 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 18 g fat (4 g saturated), 112 mg cholesterol, 4,207
mg sodium, &LR;   &LR; 0 fiber. &QL;  &LR; 
 &LR; The calories and other nutrients absorbed from marinades vary &LR; 
 &LR; and are difficult to estimate. Variables include the type of &LR; 
 &LR; food, marinating time and amount of surface area. Therefore, &LR;   &LR; the
marinade is not included in this analysis. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
