A5228 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-OLY-KANGAROOS-ART-BOS     08-29 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-KANGAROOS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (i and s coding)  
 AUSTRALIANS AREN'T CODDLING THEIR TOURIST ICON  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY _ Consider the three mascots of the upcoming Olympic
Games:
</P>
<P>
   The kookaburra bird, celebrated in song for its insane laugh;
the platypus, seemingly built from leftover parts; and the echidna,
which looks like the love child of an anteater and a porcupine.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing, of course, is the kangaroo, the bounding symbol
of Australia, enshrined on the national coat of arms and on every
Australian dollar coin.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic organizers say their mascot choices reflect a desire to
broaden awareness of the varied wonders of Australia's native
creatures.
</P>
<P>
   But kangaroo protectionists are suspicious. They say the
exclusion of their beloved marsupial reflects the fact that in the
land Down Under, sentiment toward kangaroos is often ambivalent at
best, hostile at worst.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their status as Aussie icons, millions of kangaroos are
slaughtered each year to make dog food and leather goods. Ranchers
kill them as pests that compete with cows and sheep for precious
grazing land. And increasingly, they're being killed for human
consumption as well.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, the slogan here could well be, `` 'Roo _ it's
what's for dinner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no accident that they didn't choose the kangaroo for the
mascot,'' said Maryland Wilson, president of the Australian
Wildlife Protection Council, the leading opponent of kangaroo
killings. ``If you have a kangaroo representing the Olympics, you
can't also put it on the menu.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, kangaroo is very much on the Olympic menu. Games
organizers have chosen Edna's Table, a well-regarded Sydney
restaurant known for its wild game entrees, to provide meals with
indigenous flair at the main press center during the Olympics,
Sept. 15 to Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Jennice Kersh, the restaurant's owner, said last week she plans
to serve the world's journalists a warm salad of kangaroo fillet,
with beetroot and wild yams. She raves about its distinctive taste
_ it has a strong, slightly sweet flavor, reminiscent of liver _
and its low-fat, low-cholesterol content. Still, she knows that not
everyone is quite ready for 'roo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Americans are a bit squeamish about eating kangaroo, I say
you're only funny about it because your eagle isn't nearly as
succulent, so you can't eat that,'' Kersh said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over the commercial use of kangaroos breaks down
along familiar lines between animal protectionists and the
industry's defenders.
</P>
<P>
   Activists say the government-authorized wild kangaroo harvest is
cruel, ecologically shortsighted, morally suspect, and foolhardy in
terms of jeopardizing the lucrative tourist industry. ``People come
here wanting to see the streets filled with kangaroos, and we're
killing them all,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   She maintained that kangaroo shooters target the largest male
animals, particularly 6-foot red kangaroos, removing the strongest
bloodlines from the reproductive cycle. She also accused kangaroo
meat processors of using unsanitary measures, a charge fiercely
denied by industry and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   In its defense, the $200 million-a-year kangaroo business says
the harvest is a humane, environmentally sound, economically viable
use of an abundant and fast-growing natural resource.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human beings have been managing kangaroos in this country for
at least 60,000 years,'' said John Kelly, executive officer of the
Kangaroo Industry Association of Australia, the leading trade
group. ``As quickly as they reproduce, it would be courting
environmental disaster to not manage kangaroos in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said the harvest reduces pressure on grazing lands and
places reasonable limits on an exploding population. With enough
water available, the number of kangaroos in a given area can
quadruple in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly also defended the harvest methods, particularly when
compared with the processing of pigs, cows, and other animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference in the level of stress is enormous,'' Kelly
said. ``A kangaroo is grazing in its enviroment, wild and free, and
then it's blinded by a bright light. One second later it's killed
by a high-velocity bullet to the head. That's humane, mate.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 60 species of kangaroo and their close
relatives, some of them threatened or endangered. Of the six
species used commercially, three of the largest and most abundant
make up 95 percent of the harvest: eastern gray, western gray, and
red. No one is certain how many kangaroos are in Australia, but it
is generally agreed there are 20 million to 50 million of those
three varieties, according to David Croft, professor of biological
science at the University of New South Wales in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, the government sets a limit on the number of
kangaroos that can be killed, or culled, based on population
estimates. This year, the nationwide quota is 6.5 million, Croft
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, the industry official, said only about half of the quota
will be harvested, in part because animal activists have succeeded
in slowing the growth of the kangaroo market. Some 440,000 tons of
meat were exported last year, most of it to Europe, he said. About
2 million skins were exported for leather goods, largely to Asia
and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1970s, the United States banned the import of kangaroo
products out of concern about declining numbers of red, western
gray, and eastern gray kangaroos. But rising populations prompted
US officials to lift the ban in the mid-'80s. Still, the United
States remains a relatively untapped market, importing only 45 tons
of meat and 82,000 skins last year, Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   All sides of the debate agree that the issue becomes emotional
in part because of kangaroos' unusual reproductive techniques.
Whenever a mature female kangaroo is killed, it is almost certain
that one or more juvenile ``joeys'' is orphaned. That is because
female kangaroos are ``perpetually pregnant,'' Croft said, with one
joey developing in utero, one in her pouch, and one outside the
pouch still dependent on her milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half the population thinks they're an expert on kangaroos,''
Croft said, ``and the other half doesn't think about them much at
all'' _ unless they are about to collide with one. ``One of the
problems is when people see kangaroos in the wild, they're often in
the road just 10 meters in front of their headlights. At that
point, the only thing they're thinking about kangaroos is, `I'm
about to lose my no-claim bonus on my car insurance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Australians' ambivalence about kangaroos is evident almost from
the moment a visitor arrives.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, kangaroo images are a cornerstone of the tourist
industry, serving as the logo of both the Australian Tourist
Commission and Qantas Airways. Popular tours to the remote Outback
promise visitors the chance to see packs of kangaroos, called mobs,
in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, kangaroo pelts and toys made from kangaroo skins are
for sale in souvenir shops throughout Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the messages are mixed. At Featherdale Wildlife Park
just west of Sydney, tourists and Australians alike come to feed,
pet, and mingle with kangaroos. The sight of a baby kangaroo, or
joey, poking its head out of its mother's pouch prompts squeals of
excitement. And yet, the gift shop at the wildlife park sells
kangaroo hides and bags of dried kangaroo jerky.
</P>
<P>
   Sidneysiders, as residents here are known, seem to regard
kangaroos the same way Americans view squirrels. Popular support is
reserved for cuddly, cute koalas, which no one eats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kangaroos are just out there, you know?'' said Trevor
Kelly, no relation to the industry official. ``I've eaten 'em, but
only the tail's any good. I prefer steak.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
