r d BC-SOURCE-BEET-SFCHRON &LR;      08-29 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOURCE-BEET-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers,
anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary
wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field to
forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients stocking our
larders. 
 
 At the Source: Chioggia Beets: Mariquita Farm specializes in 
 Italian heirloom   By Karola Saekel  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 WATSONVILLE, Calif. _  Andy Griffin's and Julia Wiley's stand at
the Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market in San Francisco is heaped with
organically grown produce _ lush basil and crisp spring onions;
huge green- and red-patterned peppers; pale- and dark
green-striped, ribbed zucchinis, ruby-red strawberries, and
dusky-red Chioggia beets, all destined for the tables of the
food-savvy.
<TEXT>
<P>
   But they won't wind up on the Griffins' family table _ their two
children won't eat anything ``natural'' beyond crunchy carrots.
</P>
<P>
   Aged 3 and 5, the little Griffins' general reaction to the
bounty from their parents' Mariquita Farm fields outside
Watsonville is, ``Yucky!''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Wiley has found some devious ways to feed her
children some of this healthful produce. They both scarf up
homemade versions of Popsicles, unaware that they are mom's
strategy for feeding them strawberries.
</P>
<P>
   (She whirls equal parts berries and yogurt, milk, soy milk or
fruit juice in a blender with a little sweetener, then freezes the
resulting slush in drugstore molds with a stick in the middle.)
</P>
<P>
   That works fine for the strawberries, but you can hardly
disguise beets that way.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar dark red variety and the heirloom Chioggia beet
occupy special places in Griffin's history as a farmer. They came
precariously close to spelling his financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   In the '80s, when organically grown produce as well as specialty
vegetables started to take off, a shipper of organics encouraged
growers in the Watsonville area _ Griffin and his then-partner
among them _ to increase their production of beets. They planted,
they harvested and they delivered, but the checks _ due 30 days
after sale by the shipper _ failed to drop into their mail boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin finally investigated the shipper's cooler and found
pallets of beets stacked to the ceiling, unsold and soon to be
unsaleable. The farmer took things in his own hands, selling two
pallets to a non-organic shipper.
</P>
<P>
   He then went home and ripped out the remaining beets to make
room for more saleable crops. It took some years for a leap of
faith and a return to beets, which are now favorites at the market
and in the baskets Mariquita delivers in the South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin, the son of a University of California biology
professor, started his agriculture career at University of
California at Davis studying cattle ranch management. But at that
time (circa 1980), courses were mainly about which defoliant to
spray where, he recalls with a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't fit the young Griffin's vision of agriculture and
life in general. So he switched majors, graduating with an honors
degree in philosophy, and became a farmer, learning the
nitty-gritty of organic farming not from books but from the fields.
He spent several years working for Warren Weber at Star Route Farm
in Bolinas, a pioneer organic farm. Then he ventured out on his
own, finally settling, with his wife, Julia, on his current 25
acres.
</P>
<P>
   The Chioggia is one of Wiley's favorites out of the 100
different herbs, vegetables and berries the couple grows. From the
outside, the beet isn't much to look at, with typical straggly
roots and dull, brick-colored skin. But cut it open and it show its
true colors _ spirals of creamy white and brilliant hues that range
from tomato red to magenta.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin says some beet lovers complain that this glamour root
doesn't have the earthiness of a ``regular'' red beet and that
Eastern Europeans are sometimes disappointed because it doesn't
impart the traditional deep color to borscht. But many cooks,
including his wife, love the sweetness of this Italian beet.
</P>
<P>
   To reap the maximum benefits from both its visual and taste
appeal, she often peels it and serves it raw, sliced paper thin on
a mandoline and lightly dressed with vinaigrette and strewn with a
few torn basil leaves.
</P>
<P>
   The children may not eat it, but just about everybody else loves
it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Mariquita Farm is not open to the public, but the produce is &LR; 
 &LR; available in San Francisco at the Tuesday Ferry Plaza Farmers' &LR; 
 &LR; Market (10:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m. in Justin Herman Plaza), at the &LR; 
 &LR; Saturday Ferry Plaza Farmers' Market (8 a.m.-1:30 p.m. on the &LR; 
 &LR; Embarcadero at Green Street) and by subscription in Santa Cruz &LR; 
 &LR; County and Silicon Valley. Contact P.O. Box 2065, Watsonville, &LR; 
 &LR; Calif. 95077; (831) 761-3226. Or, e-mail  &LR; andy &LR; mariquita.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
