<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN IDIOM GIVES THAT SINKING FEELING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To the consternation of science and math adepts _ and sometimes
of usage mavens _ specialized jargon will occasionally migrate into
the general population, and rarely does it keep its original
meaning once it's being bandied about by the rabble.
</P>
<P>
   You'll still find arguments over the casual use of quantum leap,
for instance, since the original quantum leap was a small (though
significant) jump. Still, the everyday use of the term to mean
``major change'' is now generally accepted, even by scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Usage writers are still trying to rein in parameter, however,
and I've had letters protesting the ignorant use of exponential
increase and the bizarre concept of salaries 200 percent lower than
other people's. Now comes Bob Alexander with a new complaint: What,
he wonders, do we think we mean by lowest common denominator?
</P>
<P>
   ``It is generally used to refer to the people in the population
who are the dumbest, or the weakest, or the slowest, or are in
other ways inferior,'' he writes. ``For example, critics of TV
shows might say that the networks are appealing to the lowest
common denominator.'' (They might indeed, and every season, it
seems, they have more occasion to do so.) But why should lowest
common denominator be a pejorative?
</P>
<P>
   I turned for help to the sixth-grade math book I had at hand
(thanks to a family that never willingly deaccessions, as the
libraries say, a book). Heath Mathematics calls it the least common
denominator (though lowest has been an accepted alternative for a
century), but the LCD, by either name, has nothing ``low'' about
it, except that it's the bottom half of a fraction. You remember
how it's done: If you want to add 13 and 12, you have to convert
them to fractions with the same _ that is, a common _ denominator.
The LCD here would be 6, and our problem would be 26 plus 36 equals
56.
</P>
<P>
   Denominator as a mathematical term dates to the mid-1500s,
according to the Oxford English Dictionary; the first figurative
use is recorded in 1831. But in the early examples, common
denominator (often without the least) carries no stigma; we get a
reference to a common denominator language _ that is, a lingua
franca _ in 1898, with no hint of disapprobation. Just a dozen
years later, though, H. G. Wells uses the term with a distinctly
contemptuous air: ``Most clubs have a common link, a lowest common
denominator in the Club Bore, who spares no one.''
</P>
<P>
   While the neutral sense (emphasizing commonality) and the
derogatory sense (emphasizing lowness) coexisted for decades, the
negative connotations seem to have pretty much taken over in our
time: A New York Times summary of a 1973 Supreme Court ruling on
obscenity spoke of ``adjusting all sex-related literary, artistic
and entertainment production to the lowest common denominator of
toleration'' _ i.e., giving veto power to the most narrow-minded
members of a community. In 1983, the Times described a ``slippage''
of educational standards ``toward `minimum competency' or the
lowest common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   And today, when reviewers say TV shows like ``Survivor'' or
``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' aim at the lowest common
denominator, they don't mean to congratulate the productions on
their mass appeal; they mean that they pander to the rabble, the
great unwashed, lowbrows and yokels, Mencken's booboisie. Sure, the
writers sometimes include themselves among the deluded masses, but
self-contempt is still contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike those earlier terms of insult, though, lowest common
denominator has a nice scientific ring to it. Taken literally, it
wouldn't even be an insult: A lowest common denominator isn't
necessarily low, and common in the original term has nothing to do
with vulgarity. But the combined words, perhaps inevitably, now
suggest a contrast with a higher, less ``common,'' taste.
</P>
<P>
   And thus a term that might have connoted simply ``a level at
which we can all communicate'' has come to mean instead ``a level
to which we should be embarrassed to slip.'' Lowest common
denominator has sunk, as it were, to its lowest common denominator.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Jan Freeman at freeman(at)globe.com or write to The Boston
Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
