<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0830-COX     08-29 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SPY-0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMERICAN BUSINESSMAN ACCUSED BY RUSSIA OF SPYING SOON TO FACE
TRIAL
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Wasted and weary after being held for five months in a
Russian jail on charges of espionage, American businessman Edmond
Pope has little hope of going free or receiving a fair trial,
relatives and U.S. officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pope's wife, Cheri, who was allowed a two-hour visit with him in
the notorious Lefortovo prison on Tuesday, reiterated her husband's
innocence. She said his health has deteriorated so much that she is
afraid Pope, 54, who has a rare form of bone cancer, will die if
not released soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very shaky and very weak. When he does come home it is
going to take a very long time to get back the husband and son and
father that left here,'' she said, her voice cracking.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Security Service, Russia's intelligence agency (or
the FSB, its Russian acronym), arrested Pope, an independent
businessman and former naval intelligence officer, on April 3.
Shortly after he arrived in Russia. They accuse him of trying to
steal state secrets, but have not released details of the case to
the press or to the U.S. government. Pope could face 20 years in
prison, if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Russian media, citing anonymous intelligence sources, say Pope
was trying to buy Russia's latest torpedo technology, the same
weapon that the military was testing the day the submarine Kursk
sank, killing all 118 crewmembers aboard.
</P>
<P>
   However, Rep. John Peterson, R-Pa., denied this claim. Peterson,
who represents the Popes' district in Congress, explained that the
technology Pope was negotiating for was a 10-year-old underwater
propulsion system, not a weapon, that had been available on the
world market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The technology was not secret nor was it the latest thing''
the Russians have, Peterson said. ``The Canadian government has
bought the technology from the Russians ... how can they claim it's
top-secret?''
</P>
<P>
   The Pope case unfolded at a sensitive time in U.S.-Russian
relations, just one week after the election of President Vladimir
Putin, a career KGB officer and former head of its successor, the
FSB. For the first few weeks after the arrest, the U.S. State
Department refused to comment on Pope's circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The profile rose after President Bill Clinton met with Cheri
Pope in mid-July and promised to intervene on her husband's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But despite high-level pressure from U.S. officials to settle
the case, the Russian government appears to be pressing ahead to
try Pope. Last week, a municipal court rejected a plea by Pope's
lawyer to release the businessmen on bail so that he could seek
medical attention.
</P>
<P>
   Pope's cancer is in remission but requires constant monitoring,
according to his family. He has also been diagnosed with Graves'
disease, a thyroid condition aggravated by stress. Cheri Pope, who
had dark circles under her eyes and appeared tired, said Tuesday
her husband has lost about 30 pounds while in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Court sources here say a trial date will not come before
mid-October, a situation that Peterson says is untenable, not only
for Pope but also for U.S.-Russia relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case against Edmond Pope would not hold up in court if it
ever made it to an open court of law. This case is about an agency
fighting for their budget and people who need to prove that they
are tough,'' the two-term congressman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a situation that will damage relations between two
countries that should be friends,'' Peterson added.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
