<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 14:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5249 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-COSTARICA-ECOTOURISM-     08-29 1879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSTARICA-ECOTOURISM-$ADV02-CO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COSTA RICA'S ECOLOGY AN ATTRACTION FOR TOURISM
 &HT;    (1200&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With if-you-go box attached at end of story.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., Sept. 2 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERMOSA BEACH, Costa Rica _ From 120 feet up in a tree in the
Costa Rican rainforest, the view of the broad, blue Pacific is
breath taking.
</P>
<P>
   You can hear howler monkeys up here, jabbering as they dance
among the branches. You might even spot a bright-winged quetzal
bird, a cute sloth or a slow-moving iguana creeping along the
forest floor.
</P>
<P>
   That's if you keep still.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Chiclets Canopy Tour, keeping still is the last thing
you do.
</P>
<P>
   You're too busy gasping for breath as you plunge off the tiny
wooden platforms lashed in the high treetops. One step and whoosh,
you're zipping down a steel cable, plummeting through the branches,
securely suspended from a harness and pulley, screaming your head
off at the rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' gushed one gringo tourist, sweating from the tropical
heat and the excitement as she zipped from one high platform to
another. ``They don't have anything like this in Orlando! The
lawyers would never let them.''
</P>
<P>
   Costa Rica was a pioneer in the field of eco-tourism in the
1980s, turning its lush landscape of rumbling volcanoes, high cloud
forests, rushing mountain streams, vibrant rainforests and gorgeous
deserted beaches into a nature-lover's vacation paradise.
</P>
<P>
   In the past decade, the Central American hideaway has put action
into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors can raft through raging whitewater streams, mountain
bike through dense forests, kayak along unspoiled rocky beaches,
windsurf on a stunning lake in the shadow of a smoking volcano,
explore the azure Caribbean in scuba gear, horseback ride through
the rainforest or surf some of the world's best waves.
</P>
<P>
   For more tranquil souls, there are butterfly farms, orchid
farms, teak reserves, bird- and nature-watching tours, and hikes
along the rim of a volcano. There are also canopy tours high in the
rainforest treetops that let you walk on swinging bridges or ride
in suspended tramcars instead of launching into the great void
clipped to a steel cable with a harness.
</P>
<P>
   But don't think you have to be a high-adventure junkie or an
eco-freak to enjoy a trip to Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   There's also plenty of traditional vacation fare, including
deserted beaches perfect for meandering, sparkling new golf
courses, five-star hotels, day-sailing trips to nowhere, and
casinos and discos offering plenty of night-time action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much to do here,'' said Dave Klostermann, 40, a
California transplant who now runs a horseback-riding outfit in the
Pacific coast surf town of Jaco Beach. ``You can ride horses on a
gorgeous beach, kayak, white-water raft, mountain-bike, surf or
take a canopy tour. But it's also a great place to just hang out
and relax.''
</P>
<P>
   The message appears to be getting out. Costa Rica is now Central
America's top tourism destination, luring more than 1 million
visitors in 1999 who spent nearly US$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   They are drawn by the tiny country's natural beauty, the long
list of activities and Costa Rica's reputation as a peaceful,
relatively prosperous oasis in the midst of a region marred by
poverty, civil war and unstable governments.
</P>
<P>
   While its neighbors spent decades embroiled in wars and
dictatorships, Costa Rica abolished its army in 1949, investing the
money in developing the country's infrastructure and social
services.
</P>
<P>
   Visionary leaders also jumped on the conservation bandwagon
early, and have set aside nearly 25 percent of Costa Rica's
territory as nature preserves or national parks. There are more
than 75 such parks in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The country offers a staggering array of flora and fauna: more
than 9,000 species of plants, including 1,200 varieties of orchids
and 800 different types of ferns. As for animals, there are more
than 850 species of birds, while 10 percent of the world's
butterflies call Costa Rica home. There are more than 5,000
different species of grasshoppers.
</P>
<P>
   And it's all so close together. Wedged between Nicaragua and
Panama, with the Caribbean to the east and the Pacific Ocean to the
west, Costa Rica is only 200 miles long. You can drive almost
anywhere in the country within a day _ although be warned: the
roads are notoriously rough and can be dangerous after dark as
livestock and wild animals like to bed down on the warm pavement.
</P>
<P>
   But driving around Costa Rica is fun. Rent a car in the Central
Highlands at the capital, San Jose, and within a half-hour, you can
be hugging curves on a high mountain road, zipping past coffee
bushes planted on unbelievably steep terraces.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later and you can be standing on the rim of the Poas
Volcano, or dodging drops at the La Paz waterfall. Half an hour
more and you can be touring a butterfly farm, then hiking in the
rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   The country is actually made up of several distinct ``climate
zones,'' and the weather can vary from hot and dry to summer
monsoon to surprisingly brisk. The rainy season runs from May to
December, and the high tourist season, which is dry, lasts from
January until May.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most popular destinations are:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Arenal Volcano, about five hours northwest of San Jose. This
5,000-foot peak is one of the country's most active, and regularly
throws off showers of sparks and smoke. Hiking to the rim is not
recommended, although you can hike along the slopes and see plenty
of dramatic action.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  You can also windsurf on Lake Arenal in the volcano's shadow,
enjoying some of the most predictable high-wind conditions in the
world. Rental equipment is available at several resorts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Also in this area is the Monteverde Cloud Forest Biological
Preserve, which has earned a reputation as one of the most
outstanding tropical reserves in the Americas. Take a guided tour
and you may glimpse any of the hundreds of species of animals
living here, from pumas to exotic moths to 30 species of
hummingbirds.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  About three hours southwest of San Jose, beach-lovers flock to
Manuel Antonio National Park, a small but gorgeous park bordering
the blue Pacific. Visitors can sun on magnificent white sand
beaches, or hike through the park's rainforest, where they are
almost guaranteed to see monkeys, sloths, scarlet macaws and other
exotic wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with your beach picnic, as the monkeys are notorious
thieves.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For whitewater rafting, enthusiasts have their choice of
multi-day trips that include camping by the river or one-day
excursions that range from the relatively tranquil Rio Corobici to
wild, high-adrenaline rapids on the Rio Reventazon. More than a
half-dozen companies offer guided trips, with most departing from
San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For those interested in a more relaxing time, several
companies offer daylong sailing cruises on both the Caribbean and
the Pacific. Most stop on nearby islands, and some offer gourmet
picnic lunches so that visitors can delight their palates as well
as soak up sun and sand.
</P>
<P>
   While Costa Rica has been in the news lately for a few
high-profile crimes against tourists, most veteran travelers will
recognize that it is still much safer than other Latin American
countries. Petty theft is a problem, but robberies and more serious
crimes are still rare. Visitors who take reasonable precautions
should have few problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Costa Rica really is a utopia,'' said David Reid, 56, owner of
Calypso Tours, who moved to Costa Rica 30 years ago and helped
pioneer the country's tourism offerings with his daylong cruise and
gourmet lunch adventure. ``It's such a beautiful place. There are
more people now than before, but there's still so much to do and
see.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mike Williams may be contacted at: mikew(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call the Costa Rican Tourism Institute at
800-343-6332, or go to www.tourism.costarica.com or
www.tourism.co.cr/
</P>
<P>
   ---------------------------------------------------------
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO:
</P>
<P>
   WHEN TO GO: The rainy season runs from May until December. The
dry season, which lasts from January to May, is the most popular
time to visit. However, prices are higher during the dry season and
it doesn't rain all the time during the wet season, so you might
consider a summer visit. Climate ranges from cool in the central
highlands year-round to steamy along the coasts during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING THERE: Many major U.S. carriers, including American,
Delta and Continental, have daily flights to San Jose, Costa Rica's
capital, from cities including Houston, Atlanta and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   GETTING AROUND: All international flights arrive in the capital,
and unless you are staying at an all-inclusive resort that offers
transportation, you'll likely need a rental car. Traffic is bad in
San Jose, but outside the capital, it thins out and driving can be
a gorgeous adventure, with curvy mountain roads and stunning views.
Watch for potholes and road repair crews, as well as livestock and
rural residents, who use the highway as a sidewalk. You will need a
4-wheel-drive vehicle during the rainy season if you plan to visit
a volcano or rainforest.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO STAY: In San Jose, you can find everything from US$15
barebones rooms to a luxurious new five-star Marriott built in the
midst of an old coffee plantation, where rooms start at US$150 a
night. Outside the capital, there are lots of hotels with varying
price ranges in the most popular tourist destinations, including
Puerto Viejo and Limon on the Caribbean and Tamarindo, Jaco Beach
and Quepos on the Pacific side.
</P>
<P>
   SECURITY: Crime against tourists has unfortunately been
increasing in Costa Rica but the country is still relatively safe
compared to other Latin destinations. Petty theft is very common so
don't leave items unattended, even in a locked car. Take the same
common-sense precautions as in other strange places: don't walk
alone at night; don't carry and flash lots of cash; be wary of
over-friendly strangers.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE: The native Costa Ricans, called ``Ticos,'' speak
Spanish, but most tourism-related businesses have English-speakers.
Even in the remote countryside, Ticos are accustomed to dealing
with tourists and you'll probably get by fine even if you don't
even know how to order a ``cerveza,'' (beer) in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   ACTIVITIES: The list is nearly endless. There's whitewater
rafting, mountain-biking, hiking, bird-watching,
butterfly-watching, rainforest canopy tours, cloud forest tours,
volcanoes you can hike or drive up, windsurfing, surfing, scuba
diving, beach-combing, golf, tennis, sailing and sport-fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing to do is decide which activities you want to try
and build a vacation around them. You could start in San Jose, do a
day-trip to whitewater raft, then rent a car and drive to the
Pacific coast for some beachtime and a tour of a rainforest. Then
move on to the Arenal Volcano and the Monteverde Cloud Forest
Preserve.
</P>
<P>
   WEBSITES:
</P>
<P>
   www.tourism.costarica.com
</P>
<P>
   www.tourism.co.cr/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
