<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 14:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5262 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-COPS-RAIDS-HNS &LR;      08-29 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COPS-RAIDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RULING RESTRICTS POLICE IN USING FORCED ENTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A federal appeals court has put the brakes on
eager police officers who crash through front doors to execute
search warrants with little warning.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel of the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
here tossed out the case Monday against an accused drug dealer who
shot and wounded two officers after the police kicked in his front
door just five seconds after knocking.
</P>
<P>
   The panel ruled that the officers did not give the suspect, an
alleged member of an Oakland-based drug gang, sufficient
opportunity to let them into his home before they forced opened the
door. Federal law generally requires that a warrant-armed officer
be refused entry before forcibly storming a residence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court has said that you cannot just knock and then bust
open the door without giving the person whose house is being
searched some reasonable notice,'' said Peter Keane, the dean of
Golden Gate University Law School. ``The court is telling the
police, `We want you to take this very seriously. A person needs a
chance _ more than a few seconds _ to respond intelligently.'''
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. on Aug. 31, 1994, investigators converged on a Hayward
apartment intent on arresting Emmitt Granville, a suspected figure
in an organization thought to be selling large quantities of
narcotics throughout the San Francisco Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Granville said when he was arrested that he did not know the
intruders were officers and, fearing it was a robbery, opened fire,
according to the court. He later pleaded guilty to attempted murder
charges.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday's unanimous opinion, Chief Judge Proctor Hug noted
that the search was conducted at a time when many people are still
asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``The five seconds . . . simply did not provide Granville with a
reasonable opportunity to ascertain who was at the door,'' the
judge wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Hug, who was joined in the opinion by Judges Warren J. Ferguson
and Kim McLane Wardlaw, pointed out that ``a reasonable wait'' for
an occupant to answer the door ``protects citizens and law
enforcement officers from violence; it protects individual property
rights and it protects against needless destruction of private
property.''
</P>
<P>
   Hug noted that there are exceptions in which authorities do not
always need to follow the knock-and-announce rule. This includes
cases in which the police have a reasonable suspicion that
announcing their presence would be dangerous, futile or would
thwart their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the government agreed that authorities
had no information that Granville posed a threat.
</P>
<P>
   Because Granville's guilty pleas to the attempted murder counts
were entered conditionally on the presumption that the premise of
his arrest would be appealed, he can withdraw the pleas and go to
trial on those charges, said defense attorney Arthur Pirelli. The
court's ruling also said that federal prosecutors cannot use 1.5
pounds of crack cocaine seized in the raid as evidence against
Granville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1451EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
