Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   SIRLOIN (Undated) _ Sirloin demystified. By John Willoughby and
Chris Schlesinger.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: Corn souffle. By Eberhard
Mueller.
</P>
<P>
   With recipe.
</P>
<P>
   FLATHEAD-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Ted Lee reviews ``Noodling for
Flatheads'' by Burkhard Bilger.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (New York) _ The column: ``Wine and Beer in Ancient
Times,'' at the Jewish Museum. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   TASTINGS (Undated) _ The column: Macons. By Eric Asimov.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NEW-ORLEANS-CULTURE (New Orleans) _ New Orleans's warehouse
district blossoms into a cultural enclave. By Ralph Blumenthal.
</P>
<P>
   ALLEN-PERELMAN (Undated) _ In the recently published ``Most of
the Most of S.J. Perelman,'' a portmanteau of Perelmania in the
Modern Library Humor and Wit Series, Woody Allen is quoted as
saying: ``What happens to you when you read Perelman and you're a
young writer is fatal because his style seeps into you. He's got
such a pronounced, overwhelming comic style that it's very hard not
to be influenced by him.'' That influence can be seen by comparing
Allen's movie, ``Small Time Crooks,'' and ``The Night Before
Christmas,'' a play by Perelman and his wife, Laura. By Mel Gussow,
in a Critic's Notebook.
</P>
<P>
   GERMAN-EXILES (Undated) _ During the 1930s and '40s, hundreds of
German writers, Jews and non-Jews alike, fled Hitler and sought
refuge in the United States. But finding asylum, they were harassed
and spied upon by the FBI and other government agencies which
referred to them as ``Communazis.'' The government tapped their
phones, intercepted their mail, dug through their trash, hired
informants to spy on them, sometimes monitored their sex lives, and
conducted intimidating interviews with them, according to
``Communazis,'' a new book to be published in October by Yale
University Press. By Dinitia Smith.
</P>
<P>
   PROSTITUTES-BOOK-REVIEW (Undtaed) _ ``The Royal Family'' by
William Vollman. Reviewed by Richard Bernstein.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other
entertainment stories from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona
Republic, Kansas City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles
Daily News, San Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS &LR;  (``s'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN (Undated) _ Sports of The times column on the
Mets, who go into tonight's game against the Astros tied for first
place in the NL East. By George Vecsey.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-ASTROS (New York) _ Houston at the Mets, 7:10 p.m. EDT
start.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-MARINERS (Seattle) _ N.Y. Yankees at Seattle, 10:05
p.m. EDT start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-USOPEN (New York) _ Day Two of the U.S. Open. By Selena
Roberts.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-HOOPS (Lahaina, Hawaii) _ An On Basketball column on the
nature of the U.S. Olympic men's team: This time, the dream team
lacks the jaded, distracted roster that characterized the first
two, especially in Atlanta when many of the players _ Shaq, Hill,
Reggie Miller _ were negotiating new contracts during the Games.
This time the team features a lineup of young players more excited
and impressionable, and probably not so offputting. By Mike Wise.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-HOPEFULS (Undated) _ A handful of teams this season _
Philadelphia, Chicago, the Giants, Oakland _ believe they can be
this year's St. Louis Rams, rising from the pack to contest well
into the playoffs. By Mike Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, Hearst
Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Arizona Republic, Kansas
City Star, Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San
Francisco Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
