<P>
   These excellent articles are from the current ECONOMIST magazine
(week beginning 26 August 2000); they have all moved to the ``k''
commentary category code. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (ATTN. EDITORS: The following material from the New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist. Nonsubscribers
can use these articles only by special arrangement. For purchase
information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN'S SEA OF TROUBLES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PUTIN'S-WATERLOO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The loss of 118 sailors on Russia's nuclear submarine, the Kursk
_ and the bungling that followed _ have dented President Vladimir
Putin's reputation for controlled efficiency and may yet make
Russians rethink the sort of government they deserve. After giving
the impression that he had a tightening grip on Russian affairs,
Putin and his administration seemed to be flailing about
hopelessly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (900 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DON'T BLAME DEREGULATION FOR THIS SUMMER'S `BROWNOUTS' &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BROWNOUTS-CURE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This has been a miserable summer in California. Thanks to a
surge in electricity consumption, Californians and other Americans
have endured several power failures. A growing angry chorus is
arguing that electricity deregulation has gone too far and too
fast. The problem is just the opposite. The real culprits behind
this summer's power failures are the muddle and hesitation
surrounding the introduction of competition in much of America. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and CALIFORNIA) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (650 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; USA &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AMERICA'S OBSESSION WITH LOCAL POLITICS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEIGHBORHOOD-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-825&AMP;add &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Politics is always an illogical business. But two of
the hardest things to explain in the current election are the
general ingratitude and indifference of the American public.
Despite the consensus that the country is on the right track, the
voter turnout in November is expected to be abysmally low. There
are many answers to these riddles, but one thing often lurks behind
the indifference and ingratitude: an obsession with local issues.
For many Americans, parking now matters more than prosperity. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and CHICAGO) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (NOTE: Story can stand in 825 words; 1,100 words uncut) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WWW.MATCHMAKER.COM &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ONLINE-CUPIDS-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Ask any unmarried, overworked middle-class person
looking for love, and he or she will tell you it all seems
hopeless. Finding Mr. or Ms. Right is harder than ever. So what is
a single person to do? The answer, it appears, is to think like a
company. You should ``outsource'' your social calendar to one of an
increasing array of sophisticated matchmaking services that provide
``assisted dating.'' ``It's Just Lunch'' is a firm that arranges
``pre-screened lunch dates'' for busy professionals.
``Goodgenes.com'' is open only to graduates of Ivy League
universities and a handful of other superior colleges. and
``JDate.com'' caters to Jewish singles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: CHICAGO) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (800 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-MIX-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary, Political, Humor Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BETTER SALARIES FOR BETTER TEACHERS? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TEACHER-PAY-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The annual Phi Delta Kappa/Gallup poll of attitudes
towards public education released this week found that a majority
of Americans feel it is important to put ``a qualified, competent
teacher in every classroom.'' Bob Chase, president of the National
Education Association (NEA), the main teachers' union, wasted no
time in pointing out that this will require raising teachers'
salaries so that more qualified candidates will enter the
profession and stay there. Al Gore has won cheers from Democrats
for suggesting a pay hike for teachers. Would it really help? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (550 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CANADA ACCUSES U.S. OF CIGARETTE SMUGGLING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TOBACCO-SMUGGLING-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Your product, despite loyal customers, is not
selling, and your protests against heavy taxes go ignored. Sales
are suffering. If only some of the tax burden could be shaken off.
What to do? Why, team up with your foreign partners to smuggle, of
course. And, according to the Canadian government, this is exactly
what several North American tobacco companies did a decade ago. A
lawsuit currently winding its way through the courts in the United
States is a tale of conspiracy and intrigue as compelling as any
John Grisham novel. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Tobacco-Industry States) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (675 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EUROPE &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CHANGING FACE OF EUROPE'S SEX-SLAVE TRADE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SEX-TRAFFIC-EU-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRAGUE _ Highly organized, ruthless gangs of sex traffickers are
luring and smuggling young women, mostly from Eastern and Central
Europe, into prostitution throughout the continent. There are some
20,000 women in 600 or so brothels in the Czech Republic alone,
most of them foreigners smuggled into the country's thriving sex
industry. While the illicit and violent nature of the trade makes
accurate monitoring impossible, a clear pattern has emerged since
the collapse of communism. Simplistically, there is a two-step
movement of women from east to west. First, of Russians,
Ukrainians, Moldovans and Belarussians into Central Europe; second,
of these women and Central Europeans into western cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (950 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DELL ON WHEELS: DETROIT ROLLS OUT BUILD-TO-ORDER (BTO) AUTOS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CARS-CUSTOM-MADE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Want to customize your dream car? Soon you will be
able to, thanks to a revolutionary concept known as either
Order-to-Delivery or Build-to-Order (BTO). GM's Harold Kutner calls
it ``the most dramatic change I've ever seen in the industry.'' BTO
is based on a system pioneered by Dell Computer: go online or call
a freephone number, and your tailored product will be assembled and
shipped within days. Gentlemen, start your engines... &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: DETROIT) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (725 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GREATERGOOD.COM: A WEB SITE FOR DO-GOODERS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARITY-ONLINE-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Though Internet firms have found many a strange
bedfellow, who would have guessed that a dalliance with
philanthropy would prove fertile? Any self-respecting charity sends
newsletters and solicits donations over the Web, yet it is a clever
capitalist who can make money out of online giving. Now a cottage
industry offering services to not-for-profit types is trying. Enter
GreaterGood.com, a two-year-old Seattle firm that, essentially,
acts as matchmaker, bringing together consumers, charities and
retailers. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GRATITUDE AND GRATUITY: DOES TIPPING WORK? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOES-TIPPING-WORK?-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Everybody loathes it, but everybody does it. A recent
poll showed that 40 percent of Americans, the world's most lavish
tippers, hate the practice. In America alone, tipping is now a $16
billion-a-year industry. Tips, which are voluntary, above and
beyond a service's contracted cost, and delivered afterwards,
should not exist. So why do they? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HAUNTING OF JAPAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GHOSTS-TOKYO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's annual ghost season is underway. Ever since the
Edo era (1600-1868), telling ghost stories has been a traditional
way to while away the sweltering summer evenings. The kabuki
theatres run their traditional ghost plays. Programs about
supernatural experiences and photographic phantasms abound on
television. Youngsters organize gut-testing nocturnal trips to
cemeteries to gauge one another's courage. But ghost stories in
Japan are more than mere summer entertainment. The constantly
evolving Japanese ghost story reflects the changes in the country's
social and cultural values. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
