poll showed that 40 percent of Americans, the world's most lavish
tippers, hate the practice. In America alone, tipping is now a $16
billion-a-year industry. Tips, which are voluntary, above and
beyond a service's contracted cost, and delivered afterwards,
should not exist. So why do they? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (525 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOREOVER &LR;  &QC;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE HAUNTING OF JAPAN &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GHOSTS-TOKYO-ECONOMIST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Japan's annual ghost season is underway. Ever since the
Edo era (1600-1868), telling ghost stories has been a traditional
way to while away the sweltering summer evenings. The kabuki
theatres run their traditional ghost plays. Programs about
supernatural experiences and photographic phantasms abound on
television. Youngsters organize gut-testing nocturnal trips to
cemeteries to gauge one another's courage. But ghost stories in
Japan are more than mere summer entertainment. The constantly
evolving Japanese ghost story reflects the changes in the country's
social and cultural values. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (1,000 words) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
