<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5307 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-PROFILE-KUNITZ-BOS &LR;      08-29 1294
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFILE-KUNITZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANLEY KUNITZ: REJECTION TO POET LAUREATE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes sidebars KUNITZ-POEMS and KUNITZ-LAUREATE; a and e
coding.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVINCETOWN, Mass. _ When Stanley Kunitz is working in his
garden, admiring passersby will often ask if it's his. Kunitz tells
them he is only the hired hand. ``They used to believe me,'' he
says with a soft chuckle, ``but nobody does anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   True, it's hard to believe a 95-year-old works as a gardener's
assistant, pruning and weeding every morning. It's even harder to
believe it when the 95-year-old is perhaps America's most
distinguished living poet, an eminence underscored last month when
Kunitz (pronounced CUE-nits) was named US poet laureate, a post he
will assume in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a wonderful selection,'' said Peter Davison, poetry
editor of The Atlantic Monthly and himself a poet. ``Stanley is
going to hold the office as a symbol of dedication to a life in
poetry. He has been a symbol, and a guide, to a couple of
generations of poets already.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz, whose ``Collected Poems'' is to be published in October,
has won the National Book Award and the Bollingen and Pulitzer
prizes. (He also represents a less-lustrous, if more common,
experience for American poets: No fewer than eight publishers
rejected the book for which he won his Pulitzer, ``Selected Poems
1928-1958.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems so appropriate at the beginning of a new century
to have somebody who knew almost everybody in the last century,''
said Prosser Gifford, director of scholarly programs at the Library
of Congress, which oversees the laureateship.
</P>
<P>
   Just out of college, Kunitz sent a sheaf of his poems to
Marianne Moore at The Dial, the most distinguished American
literary magazine of the '20s. She wrote back, ``We shall be
delighted to publish them.'' Robert Lowell and Theodore Roethke
were two of his best friends. His students and proteges include
such well-known poets as Carolyn Kizer, James Wright, Louise Gluck,
and Robert Hass (himself a former poet laureate).
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz personifies more than just a century's worth of poetry.
To be in his presence is to feel connected to a century's worth of
human experience. He had a horse-and-buggy boyhood _ literally. At
9, in Quinnapoxet, a hamlet near Worcester, where he grew up,
Kunitz drove a carriage, working as a lamplighter. The first
automobile he saw was a Stanley Steamer (no relation, he likes to
say). He's seen Halley's Comet twice.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it's the future he focuses on. ``I never think of myself as
having outlived my useful existence,'' he said. ``I don't wake up
as a nonagenarian. I wake up as a poet. I think that's a big
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pinsky, the current poet laureate, marvels at Kunitz's
``vigor'' and ``feisty energy.'' Though hunched and bent over,
Kunitz moves with an easy stride. He still has a martini before
dinner and every night goes to his desk, working until a few hours
before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``The poems are there,'' Kunitz says, ``but they lie under the
debris of the life. One has to dig for them very much harder than
one had to at the beginning when poetry is so largely, in one's
youth, a glandular activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinsky sees ``absolute conviction in the lyricism'' as the most
distinctive feature of Kunitz's poetry. ``There is no doubt or
irony about the central importance of poetry for the human spirit.
He manifests that loftiness of calling in every line and
sentence.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz started out writing a relatively formal and somewhat
opaque verse. Over the years, his writing has become, as he put it,
``simpler, more open, more intimate.'' He has remained true to his
early masters: Keats, Hopkins, late Yeats, the Metaphysical Poets,
and Blake.
</P>
<P>
   A fascination with nature is the great constant in Kunitz's
poetry. (It has also been a constant in his life: Before he began
to tend his garden, Kunitz twice tried his hand at farming.) ``I
have lived in the country most of my life,'' he said. ``I need it
desperately. Urban life is satisfying for the moment, but for
refreshment and restoration of my primitive impulses I need the
country or the seashore: the natural world.''
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, Kunitz played in woods and quarries on the outskirts
of Worcester. It's hard to imagine the environs of New England's
second-largest city as an outpost of the natural world, but it was
in the 1910s. It's just as hard to imagine it as a hotbed of
poetry. But Kunitz's contemporaries Elizabeth Bishop and Charles
Olson were Worcester natives, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz went to Harvard, where he studied under the celebrated
philosopher Alfred North Whitehead and knew the future head of the
Manhattan Project, J. Robert Oppenheimer, who was a year behind
him. Graduating with a summa cum laude degree in English in 1926,
he planned to get a doctorate, but dropped out after getting his
master's, having been informed that ``Anglo-Saxons would resent
being taught English by a Jew.''
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz worked as a reporter and editor on The Worcester
Telegram. His most memorable assignment was covering the Sacco and
Vanzetti trial. It was also the most eventful: Vanzetti's letters
so impressed him he went to New York to try to find a publisher for
them. Kunitz failed in his mission, but ended up staying there.
</P>
<P>
   His first book of poems, ``Intellectual Things,'' was published
in 1930. He supported himself editing literary reference books,
something he would do off and on for the next few decades.
</P>
<P>
   There were his two attempts at farming: first in Connecticut,
then Pennsylvania. His first marriage failed. His second marriage
produced a daughter, Gretchen, but it also ended in divorce. Kunitz
married again, in 1958. His wife, Elise Asher, is a painter and
poet.
</P>
<P>
   Kunitz was a conscientious objector during World War II. Even
so, he was drafted and served in the Army, rising to the rank of
sergeant. He got his revenge on the military 20 years later when he
and Lowell organized the protest against the Vietnam War in 1965
that turned the White House Arts Festival into what he once proudly
termed ``a passionate fiasco.''
</P>
<P>
   After World War II, Roethke got Kunitz hired to teach at
Bennington College. He later taught at the New School, Brandeis,
the University of Washington, and Columbia, among other
institutions. ``I never accepted tenure,'' he said, ``because I
recognized that it would be fatal for me to be a professor who
wrote poetry rather than a poet who had a job in the academy.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1957, Kunitz and Asher have divided their time between
Provincetown and Greenwich Village. Kunitz is a founder of the Fine
Arts Work Center in Provincetown, and Saturday a ceremony was to be
held rededicating the Stanley Kunitz Common Room there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had visited Provincetown in the '30s when it was a sleepy
little fishing village,'' he said. ``I never forgot walking on the
beach . . . and there were all these women in sunbonnets and long
flowing skirts. That's changed quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also changed quite a bit is the 2,000 or so square feet
of front yard he so diligently tends from June to October. It began
as a sandbank, Kunitz proudly notes, ``without a single blade of
grass on it.'' He brought in soil, laid down seaweed and compost,
built terraces, transforming it from barrenness to lush splendor.
</P>
<P>
   ``To conquer a piece of earth,'' he says, ``an area of earth,
and make it as beautiful as one can dream of it being: That is art,
too. A man cannot be separated from the earth. I come out of the
garden every day feeling, oh, inspired in a way that one needs in
order to convert the daily-ness of the life into something greater
than that little life itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
