</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEIGHBORHOOD-POLITICS-ECONOMIST-825&AMP;add-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S OBSESSION WITH LOCAL POLITICS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors...and CHICAGO...275-word trim)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 825-word (trimmed) material from The
New York Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: STORY CAN STAND ALONE IN 825 WORDS; 1,100 UNCUT)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Politics is always an illogical business. But two of
the hardest things to explain in the current election are the
general ingratitude and indifference of the American public.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the consensus that the country is on the right track,
very few people want to give much credit to the Clinton
administration (or at least its chosen heir, Al Gore). Similarly,
although the election is both close and important, with both the
White House and Congress up for grabs, the turnout will be
abysmally low.
</P>
<P>
   There are many answers to these riddles _ from the assumption
that Federal Reserve Board Chairman Alan Greenspan matters more
than President Bill Clinton to the current addiction to
``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   But one thing often lurks behind the indifference and
ingratitude: an obsession with local issues. For many Americans,
parking now matters more than prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   One good place to look at this is Chicago. Its most famous
mayor, Richard J. Daley, ruled the city through a ward system,
which not only allowed local aldermen to solve local problems but
also linked local politics to the national ticket (Daley famously
delivered Illinois to Jack Kennedy in 1960).
</P>
<P>
   One of Daley's sons is now mayor, the other the chairman of the
Gore campaign. But today the focus of the city's ward system seems
to be entirely local; there is no connection to any national
ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, for instance, Lincoln Park, a prosperous area of the
city. To any visitor, including Bill Clinton (who dropped in
earlier this month), the signs of urban renaissance are pretty
clear. Crime and unemployment have plunged; property values have
shot in the opposite direction. The public schools are still dicey,
but most people think it is Mayor Daley's job to fix them.
</P>
<P>
   You don't hear much about Washington in Lincoln Park politics.
What you do hear about is property taxes. The same skyrocketing
urban property values that have made many families rich on paper
have also pushed up taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The tax hikes after the recent three-yearly assessment by the
city were especially brutal. In Lake View, a neighborhood just
north of where Clinton visited, the median tax bill climbed 53
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are fears that the artists, small manufacturing
businesses and working-class residents that have always given
Lincoln Park a diverse, slightly Bohemian feel will be driven out.
</P>
<P>
   People also worry about the folks who are moving in. Wealthy new
neighbors do not just buy houses; because land is scarce, they
often buy houses, knock them down, and then build bigger houses
that tower over other structures on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, large national retailers are eager to go where the
money is. The list of chains looking for space around Lincoln Park
includes Home Depot, Costco and IKEA _ all names that remind local
residents of suburban shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton's host, DePaul University, has been gobbling up
green space, adding 10 big buildings in Lincoln Park in the past
decade.
</P>
<P>
   One result: nobody has enough room to park.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's zoning laws, written in 1957, require that property
developers provide one parking space for each new unit of housing.
In reality, new families arrive with several cars, at least one of
which is likely to be a hulking sport-utility vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents would like to see street parking limited to
permit holders; local businesses claim it would be their death
warrant. ``It's one of the most divisive issues I've ever
encountered, outside of dogs,'' says Judy Casey, president of the
Sheffield Neighborhood Association.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, dogs. Chicago residents are now more likely to have a mutt
than they were a decade ago, pitting an estimated 750,000 dogs and
their owners against non-dog owners in the battle for open space.
(If your labrador frolics off the leash in a local park, prepare
yourself for a visit to the criminal court.)
</P>
<P>
   The Sheffield Neighborhood Association is wrestling with the
weighty policy issue of whether or not a local park should have a
drinking fountain exclusively for dogs, and if so, where it should
be located.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the frustrations have bubbled over. Community activists
in Lincoln Square, a rapidly gentrifying neighborhood on Chicago's
northwest side, recently took to the streets to protest against the
opening of a third Starbucks coffee shop in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a Starbucks comes in,'' explained one protester, ``there
goes the diversity. Property values go up, rents go up, taxes go
up. A Starbucks is the first sign that much worse things are going
to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of these complaints are beginning to bubble up to the
national stage. At the annual meeting of the U.S. Conference of
Mayors, Beverly O'Neill, the mayor of Long Beach, Calif., told her
peers that prosperity-related pressures are the number one problem
facing the country. &QL;
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE AT 825, OR CONTINUE TO 1,100) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   She had a sympathetic audience. In San Francisco, where
high-tech wealth has had an even more pronounced effect, the
entrepreneurs who were once the pride of the city now find
themselves referred to as ``e-holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty thousand San Franciscans signed a petition supporting a
November ballot initiative that would limit the growth of
technology companies in the city. A group calling itself the Yuppie
Eradication Project has been slashing the tires of sport-utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Such local resentments can be found in suburbs, farms and cities
_ but they seem particularly ungrateful in the latter.
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, American cities are far more pleasant places
to live than they were a decade ago. One Chicago neighborhood
leader recalls that 30 years ago his main challenges were cracking
down on slum landlords, massage parlors and street gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this, even mayors with forceful local records, such as
Rudy Giuliani in New York, have had trouble in reminding the locals
of those achievements (his latest crime: spraying for mosquitoes).
</P>
<P>
   And the gap between local and national politics seems far
greater: zoning and property taxes seem no more on the mind of
George W. Bush and Gore than missile defense is on the mind of
Lincoln Park.
</P>
<P>
   The ``friendship'' that people like the older Daley enjoyed with
voters, and the involvement Chicagoans once felt in national
debates, has ebbed away into a series of local squabbles over
things like utility bills.
</P>
<P>
   It has also given a new twist to an old saying. If you want a
friend in American politics, get a dog (and do please keep him on a
leash). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
