<HEADLINE>
QUIPS, QUIRKS AND QUOTES FROM THIS WEEK'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary, Political and Humor Editors)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 425-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   &UR; POLL OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Asked before the conventions whether they would vote Democrat or
Republican in the congressional elections, voters split evenly (47
percent each) between the two parties. After the conventions, the
Democrats ``surged'' ahead _ 48 percent to 46 percent. (USA
Today/CNN/Gallup poll) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE STORY (1): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was completely spontaneous, I was just overcome with the
emotions that I was feeling with all the people cheering.'' (Gore
on that kiss, ``This Morning,'' ABC, Aug. 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOVE STORY (2): &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``Any smooches, we go up points.'' (Gore aide at a campaign
rally in Iowa, Los Angeles Times, Aug. 21) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEUD OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to show that their man is working harder, the
Republicans claimed that, in the week after their convention,
George W. Bush made 23 stops in five states; Al Gore, they said,
will make only eight stops in four states. The Gore campaign claims
20 stops for their candidate, and says that Bush's figure was
inflated by ``slow rolls,'' towns where his campaign train slowed,
but did not stop. (Washington Post, Aug. 20) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENDORSEMENT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll do it my way, so that I don't hurt the ticket.'' (Jerry
Springer, who will campaign for Gore, if asked, U.S. News &AMP; World
Report, Aug. 28) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUY ME: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``(For sale:) the 2000 election vote of one U.S. citizen who is
a registered voter in Maryland. You may specify whom I vote for in
the presidential and all other elections.'' (A voter, identified
only as ``apragmatic,'' who (illegally) tried to sell his vote on
eBay. The site has since removed the sale details, CNN.com, Aug.
16) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SINS OF THE CHILDREN: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``I like what I saw; I hate to say it, but maybe this did sway
me a little bit.'' (Michael Conwell, a North Carolina State
Trooper, who arrested Gore's son, Albert III, for speeding and
reckless driving. Conwell admitted that he was impressed with the
teenager's honesty and cooperation, New York Daily News, Aug. 22) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GRECIANS ARE BACK: &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot let terrorists and rogue nations hold this nation
hostile or hold our allies hostile...I will work to end terrors and
tariffs everywhere.'' (A tired and emotional Bush in Des Moines. In
a somewhat inarticulate performance, he also promised to put an end
to ``four years'' of Clinton-Gore in the White House (it has been
eight), Washingtonpost.com, Aug. 22) &QL;
</P>
