<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARITY-ONLINE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREATERGOOD.COM: A WEB SITE FOR DO-GOODERS  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Seattle)   (ATTN. EDITORS: The following 600-word material from The New York
Times Syndicate is for use by clients of The Economist.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, call 1-888-269-8796, or Debra Weydert at
732-390-4480.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 From The Economist magazine  
 c.2000 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Though Internet firms have found many a strange
bedfellow, who would have guessed that a dalliance with
philanthropy would prove fertile?
</P>
<P>
   Any self-respecting charity sends newsletters and solicits
donations over the Web, yet it is a clever capitalist who can make
money out of online giving. Now a cottage industry offering
services to not-for-profit types is trying.
</P>
<P>
   By most measures, GreaterGood.com, a two-year-old Seattle firm,
is the biggest of the bunch. It is essentially a matchmaker,
bringing together consumers, charities and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Visit the Web site and you find a series of shopping villages,
each run for the benefit of a particular cause _ UNICEF, say, or a
local school _ and with links to the Web sites of retailers such as
Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   At these sites, a small box reminds you that a percentage of
money spent will be donated to charity; an equal portion goes to
GreaterGood.
</P>
<P>
   Although online retailers, who charge the same price to a
GreaterGood-referred customer as to a regular one, see their
margins shaved by paying a commission, they are eager to take part,
happy to encourage others to send them customers.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Amazon, the granddaddy of Web retailers, has been
running such a pay-the-referrer scheme for years.
</P>
<P>
   Much of GreaterGood's business comes from shoppers following a
link from their favorite charity's site, or reading about the
service in a newsletter. Still more customers are drawn in by stage
two of the marketing plan.
</P>
<P>
   In February, GreaterGood bought The Hunger Site, a Web site that
shot to Internet stardom as soon as it launched. The gist is: look
at a few advertisements, help end hunger.
</P>
<P>
   When a user clicks on the site's ``donate free food'' button, he
is shown half a dozen ``banner ads,'' the colorful rectangles
festooned with slogans that have become ubiquitous _ and
increasingly ignored _ on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For reaching a prospective customer, each advertiser pays half a
cent (the equivalent of a quarter of a cup of food aid) to the
site, which passes it on to the U.N. World Food Program. Which is
good for everybody: users feel virtuous, advertisers entice
customers, and the hungry get food, lately about 1,000 tons a
month.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a win for GreaterGood, whose own message accompanies
each batch of ads, exhorting users to help even more by visiting
its site and shopping for hungry children.
</P>
<P>
   GreaterGood has a patent pending for its Hunger Site model, a
worrying development for genuine nonprofit sites, such as
ClearLandmines.com, which also use banner-ad profits to help good
causes.
</P>
<P>
   GreaterGood recently opened its newest variation on the theme,
TheRainForestSite.com, and has registered scores of other domain
names, including TheHelpingWomenSite.org.
</P>
<P>
   It may not like competitors, even nonprofit ones, muscling in on
its turf. Although GreaterGood is yet to break even, it is already
considering a stock market listing.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ironically, the company is part of a breed much threatened
by the Internet: a bit of Web publishing and helpline-manning
aside, it is simply an intermediary, adding little value for its
cut of the action.
</P>
<P>
   That may be fine for now; with revenues still low, charities
seem happy to let it beaver away. But if commissions continue to
grow, charities may soon tire of losing half and try to do without
GreaterGood, dealing with retailers directly.
</P>
<P>
   As many a matchmaker has found, when a couple hits it off, they
end up more loyal to each other than to the soul, however helpful,
who introduced them. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1524EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
