<HEADER>
A5344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-LALOBA-0830-CO     08-29 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-LALOBA-0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    JAILED 'SHE WOLF' WAS ONE OF MEXICO'S CLASSIC RULING PARTY
BOSSES
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    EDs: Chimalhuacan is southeast, and adjacent to Mexico City.
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHIMALHUACAN, Mexico _ Just talking about ``La Loba,'' the She
Wolf, makes Teresa Gonzalez's palms break out in a sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before Mexico's July 2 election, Gonzalez dared to argue
with La Loba over who she was going to vote for. Days later
somebody pumped a barrage of bullets through the front door of
Gonzalez's cinderblock hovel.
</P>
<P>
   There's no doubt in Gonzalez's mind that the assault was ordered
by La Loba, who's real name is Guadalupe Buendia, a woman who used
nepotism, high-level connections _ and fear and favors _ to run
this vast slum of 1.2 million people like a fiefdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the law here. She had the power to make things better
here and she never did it,'' said Gonzalez, a seamstress who lives
on a tiny plot that La Loba sold her in this urban stew of trash,
mud, sewage and snarling street dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Plump and middle-aged, Buendia's looks belie her intimidating
nickname. But she is an infamous figure in Mexico these days, a
symbol of the abusive local party bosses that this country's
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or the PRI, nourished during its
71-year monopoly on most government offices power.
</P>
<P>
   After a week on the lam, La Loba is now in jail, charged with
gathering a mob armed with wooden boards, pistols and homemade
bombs to attack a rival during his inauguration on Aug. 18 as the
city's new mayor. Ten people died in the melee, which pit one
faction of PRI loyalists against another.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened there is part of Mexican politics that continues
to be savage,'' said political analyst Edna Jaime. On July 2, the
PRI lost the presidency for the first time in seven decades, a
phenomenon that represents ``the civilized Mexico,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But as the PRI's power slips, more violence could erupt as local
party bosses fight to keep the wealth and control they amassed,
Jaime said. ``The PRI knew how to handle these predators before.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Buendia was a behind-the-scenes power in this city
and a PRI operative in a vote-rich area. In exchange for virtual
impunity for abuses and looting _ a traditional arrangement _ she
mustered votes for the party from slum dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   She let poor migrants from provinces squat on land and
shepherded them into PRI-affiliated neighborhood groups that
promised they would one day obtain better services for residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my mother died, she bought the casket,'' said Elsa
Arrieta, who sells chickens on a street _ one of the few that's
paved _ where La Loba had one of her many homes.
</P>
<P>
   Buendia served jail time for extortion in connection with a land
swindle, but she was released in early 1999 and was still going
strong up through April, when her empire began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI declined to put La Loba's son up for mayor in the July 2
election. And La Loba had a lot at stake. Her cousin was mayor,
husband the treasurer, son the municipal secretary and sister the
director of family services. La Loba was in charge of water, and if
one person failed to pay a bill or did something to displease her
she would halt service to an entire block.
</P>
<P>
   She was also director of retrieving garbage _ at which she was
an obvious failure _ using donkey-drawn carts whose owners were
also affiliated with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I talked about mechanizing the garbage collection, she
felt threatened,'' said the new mayor, Jesus Tolentino, also of the
PRI.
</P>
<P>
   He said everyone complained about getting charged for
non-existent garbage collection. And they griped about the police,
who they said extorted with La Loba's blessing.
</P>
<P>
   La Loba's questionable land sales began to make her enemies,
too. Gonzalez, for example, doesn't have the title to her property
nine years after paying La Loba. She paid to have a water pipe put
in four years ago and only got her hook-up in June. Like so many
others here, Gonzalez's only toilet is an outhouse. She steals
electricity from power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez said La Loba was furious with the PRI for turning down
her son, so she lobbied to have a nephew named mayoral candidate
for Mexico's leftist Democratic Revolution Party, which had tried
to make inroads in Chimalhuacan.
</P>
<P>
   She tried to force Gonzalez, who is also considered a local
leader, to gather votes for her nephew. When Gonzalez refused, her
house was sprayed with gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   La Loba did manage to stick with the PRI's candidates for
president and Congress. On Mother's Day, she threw a huge fiesta,
featuring male strippers who peeled off boxers that spelled: ``Vote
PRI.''
</P>
<P>
   That event embarrassed the party. But the PRI was mortified when
followers of La Loba launched an attack during Tolentino's
inauguration at Chimalhuacan's city hall.
</P>
<P>
   La Loba claims she is innocent, and accused followers of
Tolentino that belong to another PRI slum dwellers' group, Peasant
Torch, with inciting the violence.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview at the city hall, Tolentino brushed off unsavory
stories about Peasant Torch, which has also been accused of
shock-troop tactics against enemies.
</P>
<P>
   He said his job now is to restore order and help improve the
party's image here. Tolentino and the new treasurer, for example,
said they didn't find one official document on file here and the
strong box was completely empty. Because of unpaid bills, the city
is about $8 million in debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also clear,'' Tolentino said, ``that authorities in the
state of Mexico and within our party _- the PRI _ always knew what
was going on here.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
