<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5347 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-29 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNAPP-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     TIGER ON `SURVIVOR' ISLAND? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By GWEN KNAPP  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Normally, I'm a purist. Junk sports may grab my
eye, but I always know I'm slumming.
</P>
<P>
   Then along came Monday night's round of match-play golf between
Tiger Woods and Sergio Garcia. It met all the requirements for
utter disdain, the snob's snub. It was a made-for-TV event,
promoted with silly shots of Garcia in a matador's outfit and
Woods' face morphing into a roaring tiger's. It was golf played
under artificial light. It employed carts for two able-bodied
players with a combined age of 44.
</P>
<P>
   It was silly, all show, no substance. It was also irresistible.
And not in a cheap way. If you watched, you know. It was like
buying a skin magazine and becoming absorbed in the articles. Even
the sports purist had to give this event its due.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Garcia's little win did a service to golf, reminding
us that Woods is not a machine. Tiger too often makes what he does
look easy, as if all the victories and records are fate, a destiny
set on auto-pilot. This summer, in particular, he has been the
perfect storm. He has laid waste to the game as it existed before.
</P>
<P>
   The whole time, he has worn an expression that says he expected
this all along. To understand the absurdity of his runaway wins at
Pebble Beach and St. Andrews, you couldn't look at his face. You
had to watch his playing partners.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, at the U.S. Open, looked up at the leaderboard during
the final round and just laughed, shaking his head. David Duval, at
the British, hacked away at a bunker as if he were trying to
dismantle it. Duval was so determined to give Woods a run that he
started swinging like Dave Kingman.
</P>
<P>
   The bunker didn't go anywhere, and neither did Woods. He was
untouchable, unflappable, almost inhumanly so. The Opens are
designed to humble a golfer. Woods strode down the fairways like
John Wayne.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the made-for-TV contrivance, held on a course tricked
up to flatter the golfers, that Tiger stumbled.
</P>
<P>
   He looked exhausted Monday night, occasionally coughing into his
palm as he walked. He'd caught the flu in Ohio, where less than 24
hours earlier he had won the NEC Invitational by 11 strokes,
finishing after nightfall. Then he conducted a morning clinic and
flew to California to tee off for the showdown with Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   That schedule suggests Woods didn't take this event too
seriously _ which only proves that he, too, is a purist. The best
thing about Tiger's last year is the way he has homed in on the
majors, pointed his whole game in that direction. By contrast, this
match was a trifle, and he treated it accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't bring his A game, perhaps because he had wrung it dry
in the NEC Invitational. Still, throughout Monday's match, I kept
waiting for that mask of determination to come over his face. It
never did. He didn't go after Garcia the way he pursued Bob May in
the PGA playoff eight days before. Apparently, he can't just turn
his intensity on with a switch, and it's a comfort to know his
mental energy isn't that shallow.
</P>
<P>
   But don't be surprised if next year Tiger can pack his schedule
and still sink his teeth into a match-play opponent after a
cross-country trip. He keeps getting better, looking for flaws the
rest of us can't see. Eventually, the only way to challenge him
might be through junk sports.
</P>
<P>
   Make Tiger run a marathon, then shoot 18 against the No. 2
flavor of the summer? Why not?
</P>
<P>
   Have him dive into a shark tank, take a turn on a flying
trapeze, then do a 10K pogo-stick ride to the first tee? Sounds
like a plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tiger lives on a deserted island for 39 days with 15 strangers,
then paddles a canoe across the Pacific to go one-on-one with Phil
Mickelson? Here, we have a collision of the summer's two ratings
bonanzas. I'm sure the networks are already on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1526EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
