</P>
<P>
   In most of Japan's folk art of the day _ including pulp fiction,
puppet theatre, storytelling, kabuki, scroll painting and woodblock
prints _ vengeful spirits were among the most popular motifs.
</P>
<P>
   Merchants and socialites played a party game called hyaku
monogatari where they told each other 100 ghost stories through a
summer night. One hundred candles were lit for the occasion, with
one blown out after each tale. After the 100th candle, the room was
plunged into darkness and something spooky was supposed to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Such ghost-revellers would have expected to see a scowling,
long-haired woman in a white funeral gown and with no feet _ the
classic image of the wife who, betrayed and murdered by her
husband, returns from the dead to punish her tormentor.
</P>
<P>
   Historians, such as the eminent Yukio Hattori, have argued that
such apparitions reflected the low status of women in feudal Japan,
not to mention the belief that women were thought to be more
spiteful and attached to life than men.
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries on, Japanese spooks have become more modernized
and westernized, just like Japanese society itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Second World War fuelled a whole corpus of supernatural
tales. People saw apparitions of dead soldiers and heard the
wailing voices of bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Dreams,'' Akira Kurosawa has an eerie episode in which an
officer who survived the war is haunted by a platoon of his men who
died in battle.
</P>
<P>
   A different set of troubled souls haunt contemporary Japanese.
The most emblematic ghost of the 1990s _ popularized in the
``Ring'' series of books that sold more than 5 million copies _ is
a cursed videotape that kills viewers within a week. The only way
to avoid the curse is to copy the tape and force unsuspecting
friends to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Such supernatural terrorism, combining modern technology with
traditional ghost motifs, has become increasingly common.
</P>
<P>
   Suicide, long associated with spiritual reincarnation in Japan,
has likewise become an increasing source of ghostly tales. With the
country's worst recession since the war driving bankruptcy,
violence and unemployment to record levels, more than 31,000 people
in Japan committed suicide last year _ a 30 percent increase over
two years before.
</P>
<P>
   The prominence of tales about bullied children and stressed-out
salarymen haunting their schools and offices after taking their own
lives adds a sad postscript to this tragic statistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horror stories increasingly mirror contemporary ills,'' says
Hideki Sato, the editor of Kadokawa Horror Novels which published
the ``Ring'' series. Not satisfied with mere fringe manias, more
and more readers want the macabre of real life stirred into their
horror stories.
</P>
<P>
   One of Kadokawa's newest chillers, ``Aoi Honoo,'' is a
psychothriller about a juvenile murderer. After a spate of recent
murders by knife-and-bat-wielding teenagers, this comes as no
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese media's fascination with the killings of the past
year does seem to have pushed many of the country's more
traditional ghosts into the shadows. Despite that, nostalgia for
the headless warrior or long-haired harridan has not vanished
completely.
</P>
<P>
   At times Japan's ghosts from the past strike back. The mighty
Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan had its head office in Otemachi on
an urban site that overshadowed the Masakado shrine. Rumor has it
that the bank did not show decent respect to its spiritual
neighbor, and was too mean to pay for proper Shinto purification
rituals.
</P>
<P>
   The LTCB failed in 1998 and soon passed into foreign hands _ in
Japanese banking, a fate worse than death. That surely cannot have
been mere coincidence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
