<SLUG> BC-FANCY-FOOD0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barrage of new products inundate the palate
 &HT;    By Christine Vasconez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As if you didn't have enough sauces, salsas,
marinades and compotes in your kitchen, there are some new products
worth looking for in Miami Valley gourmet food and wine stores.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers at the Fancy Food Show in New York this summer
inundated the palate with sweet, sour, savory and salty flavors in
a barrage of new products.
</P>
<P>
   Fruit _ raspberries, mangoes, kiwi, guava, pear and pineapple _
showed up in vinegars, oils, sauces and dips at the show, which is
sponsored by the National Association for Specialty Food Trade. But
there was no overwhelming trend at the show, where approximately
1,700 manufactures displayed their creations to 24,000 people. But
several unique products made in southwestern Ohio were shown.
</P>
<P>
   Several area companies won awards for their specialties, which
include mouth-watering items like Key Lime Curd Sauce, Oregon Black
Raspberry Preserves and Roasted Red Pepper Ravioli with Goat
Cheese.
</P>
<P>
   All of these products and more are available at specialty food
and wine shops throughout the Miami Valley, with each priced under
$8.
</P>
<P>
   Just north of Dayton in Urbana, Robert Rothschild Berry Farm
continually kicks out high-impact flavorful sauces, dips, vinegars
and dessert toppings. The new hit _ and a finalist for Outstanding
New Product at the Fancy Food Show _ was the Key Lime Curd Sauce.
The sweet and tart combination tastes like Key lime pie without the
crust. It's best served over angel food cake, pound cake or
cheesecake. It's even good folded into whipped cream.
</P>
<P>
   Other Rothschild favorites include the popular Raspberry Honey
Mustard Pretzel Dip and one of its new products _ Lemon Mango
Raspberry Sauce. Use it to fill crepes or drizzle it over
cheesecake for a fruity delicacy.
</P>
<P>
   Marketing director Jill Broering said she mixes the sauce with
yogurt or ice cream. She said the curd sauce is also good blended
with cottage cheese or stirred into a fruit salad.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ship it when it's still warm because we can't keep up with
the demand,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Broering said Bob and Sarah Rothschild have come a long way _
from selling food at a roadside fruit market to their current list
of more than 150 products.
</P>
<P>
   The farm, formed in 1984, offers tours and visitors can pick
fresh raspberries. Call (800) 356-8933.
</P>
<P>
   South of Dayton, 40 minutes away in Sharonville, is Clearbrook
Farms, a fourth-generation business. It won one of the most
prestigious awards at this year's show, Outstanding Classic, for
its velvety Oregon Black Raspberry Preserves.
</P>
<P>
   The award, judged by retailers, is given to a product that's
been in distribution for at least 10 years. It competed against
other foods like Terrine of Foie Gras, Bremner Cracked Wheat Wafers
and Classic Reserve VT Cheddar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to be a very established product in the industry,''
Clearbrook Farms Vice President Dan Cohen said. ``We introduced the
raspberry preserves in 1979. To be a finalist is a tremendous
honor, then to win that honor _ it's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   The seedless preserves, made from berries hand-picked in Oregon,
are tart, yet sweet with no added preservatives or colors. Spread
it onto a bagel, pancakes or muffin. It also can be added to yogurt
or ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it was preserves, teas, coffee, crackers, soup or pasta,
there was a bite or sip of something for everyone at the Fancy Food
Show.
</P>
<P>
   When you think of Italian you think of pasta, and when you think
of pasta you think red or white sauce. But some of Pasta Fresca's
ravioli tastes nothing like traditional Italian.
</P>
<P>
   The New Lexington company, just southeast of Columbus, that
started in 1988 combines several spicy ingredients in its Black
Bean and Salsa Ravioli with Corn in a Jalapeno Shell and Jalapeno
Cheddar Ravioli in a Sweet Bell Pepper Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Both should be served as recommended with olive oil, cheddar
cheese and a dollop of sour cream. Pasta Fresca's Roasted Red
Pepper Ravioli with Goat Cheese was a finalist at the Fancy Food
Show for Outstanding Pasta Rice, Bean or Soup. Also be on the
lookout for its Frittatine appetizers, which many food show
attendees waited in line to eat. The egg-based souffles shaped like
seashells come in broccoli cheddar, Parmesan zucchini and
four-cheese potato flavors.
</P>
<P>
   The Fancy Food Show is a national and international glimpse of
what new products are on the shelves. Be assured you'll see these
products and more at gourmet food and wine stores here.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email:christinevasconez(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO FIND THEM
</P>
<P>
   To get a better look at the products and for more information:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Robert Rothschild products: www.RobertRothschild.com or (937)
653-7397.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Clearbrook Farms: (800) 222-9966.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pasta Fresca:
www.civicnet.org/webmarket/ohio/fresca/fres07.html or (800)
343-5266.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
