<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5363 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-WINECOLUMN0830-COX     08-29 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINECOLUMN0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Incredibly, stemware really does affect a wine's flavor
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - It makes no sense.
</P>
<P>
   It defies logic.
</P>
<P>
   Logic tells us that an identical liquid sitting in two different
containers is going to taste and smell _ well, identical. No
brainer.
</P>
<P>
   Then along comes some smarty-
</P>
<P>
   pants to prove us wrong, to turn logic on its head, to flout the
laws of physics. What next? The sun rising in the west?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But it's true. I was there. So were others. It was no mass
hallucination.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the smarty-pants was Barbara Fredell, a
representative of Riedel Crystal, who came to town a few weeks back
to lead a demonstration of her company's glasses at a wine tasting
at Fairfield Wine in Beavercreek. The idea: show how her company's
stemware outperforms lesser ``regular'' wine glasses by
accentuating certain aromas and flavors in wine.
</P>
<P>
   Riedel _ the company rep pronounced it as if it rhymes with
``needle,'' which means I've been mispronouncing it for years _
pioneered the concept that the shape and contour of a wine glass
can have a noticeable effect on how wine tastes and smells. The
Austrian-based company, founded in 1756 and owned by the Riedel
family for 10 generations, produces approximately 5.1 million
lead-crystal wine glasses a year. So let's acknowledge they know a
thing or two about this business.
</P>
<P>
   The company offers an incredible array of glasses in different
sizes and shapes, each designed to be used with a different variety
of wine.
</P>
<P>
   Not just a white-wine glass. Different glasses for sauvignon
blanc, chardonnay, riesling and on down the line, each built to
emphasize each grape varietals strengths (or perhaps hide its
weaknesses). Riedel's top-of-the-line, handmade ``sommeliers''
series features more than 30 shapes and sizes of glasses costing
$60 to $90 apiece.
</P>
<P>
   The Riedel family also offers less expensive, machine-made
alternatives in its Vinum, Vinum Extreme, Wine and Ouverture
series, with prices ranging from about $8.50 to $30 each. To have a
look, point your Web browser to www.riedelcrystal.com.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of Riedel's glasses are so mammoth that an entire
standard-sized bottle (750 ml) can be poured in. To the last drop.
This brings whole new meaning for those who have been told by their
medical professionals, ``You should be limiting yourself to only
one glass of wine a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that would defeat the purpose of being able to swirl
the wine to release the aromas.
</P>
<P>
   And swirling is exactly what Riedel rep Fredell tells the
Fairfield Wine tasting group to do to launch her demonstration,
comparing the aroma and taste of a chardonnay from a generic, but
decent, wine glass against the Riedel Vinum chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   The Riedel glass is redolent of butterscotch and tropical fruit
aromas. The generic glass doesn't yield much in the way of aromas
at all.
</P>
<P>
   Then Fredell tells us to taste the wine. Again, the difference
is clear and noticeable. The Riedel glass has a brief wave of sweet
fruit, followed by some pleasant tartness, then a little of that
butterscotch. The chardonnay from the generic glass tastes tart and
acidic, but with little else. Just kind of ... flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unbelievable,'' one audience member said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if someone took all the tone out of the stereo,'' a
second taster suggests.
</P>
<P>
   The scene repeated itself with other wines: sauvignon blanc,
cabernet sauvignon, pinot noir.
</P>
<P>
   Fredell can offer a plausible, physical explanation for some of
the differences. The inside of the Riedel glass has tiny, invisible
peaks and valleys because of its 24 percent lead crystal content,
and those allow for greater surface area for the wine, and thus
more pronounced aromas compared with the smooth glass of the
generic stemware.
</P>
<P>
   The rim and bowl of the Riedel glass is much thinner than the
generic, which has a particularly thick, rounded rim. That means
when you lift the generic glass to your lips, the wine has to spill
over the top of the rim to strike your tongue at about its
midpoint. The Riedel glass, with its thin rim, delivers the first
splash of wine directly to the tip of your tongue, where some
mighty sensitive taste receptors lie in wait.
</P>
<P>
   That thinness of the glass also makes the Riedel glasses
dangerously fragile _ I wonder whether half of the 5.1 million
glasses a year Riedel produces are replacements.
</P>
<P>
   But when Fredell asks us to taste wines out of the ``wrong''
Riedel glasses _ chardonnay out of the cabernet glass and vice
versa, for example _ the differences are less striking than she
would have us believe. Some of her observations seem plausible,
others sound like power of suggestion. But the superiority of the
Riedel stemware to the generic remains unshaken.
</P>
<P>
   Now, these fancy glasses won't make bad wines taste good. If
anything, they'll make bad wines taste worse, by accentuating the
faults. And who in their right mind has the room to store a few
gazillion different wine glasses?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the demonstration has left everyone in the room
scratching their heads and questioning the various rules and laws
that they counted on to guide their daily existence.
</P>
<P>
   Me, I'm going to be watching that western sky tomorrow morning.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: markfisher(at)coxohio.com or at 225-2258.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE TO FIND IT
</P>
<P>
   Riedel stemware is available through most Miami Valley wine
shops _ some even use it for Saturday afternoon ``drop-in'' wine
tastings _ or you can check out mail-order companies such as
International Wine Accessories, (800) 527-4072; www.iwawine.com, or
The Wine Enthusiast (800) 356-8466; www.wineenthusiast.com. Riedel
has a Web site (riedelcrystal.com) that describes each glass and
can refer you to the nearest retailer.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
