<HEADLINE>
WEST TEXAS TOWN FINDS A WAY AROUND CURBS ON PREGAME PRAYERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ART CHAPMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pregame high school football prayers are as big a problem for
Texas schools this season as are the win-loss record, cross-town
rivalries and good chili-cheese dogs that won't drip.
</P>
<P>
   Since the U.S. Supreme Court ruled this year that public,
student-led prayers before football games are unconstitutional,
school districts nationwide have been wrestling with options to
have prayers without violating the legal restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a confusing situation. On the one hand, the high
court said there can be prayers, but on the other, it said those
prayers cannot be organized, performed, sanctioned or linked to the
school district or its administrators.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to make sure that people are not coerced into
sitting through prayers that might run counter to their beliefs; to
make sure that no student feels peer pressure to participate in a
religious ceremony that violates his or her faith.
</P>
<P>
   Some districts have simply given up the concept of pregame
prayers, believing that the landscape is laid with legal land
mines. Others still hold that pregame prayers _ such as those
pleading for safety and sportsmanship _ are as much a part of
Friday night football as are cheerleaders, crashing shoulder pads
and face painting.
</P>
<P>
   One Mississippi school has decided that before the game, the
folks in the stands will break out into a spontaneous Lord's
Prayer. Critics ask how anyone can break out in ``planned''
spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Texas town of Albany, they think they have a better
idea.
</P>
<P>
   Plans for prayers before Albany home games were announced last
week at the school board meeting, but the school board didn't come
up with the scheme.
</P>
<P>
   David Mallory, pastor at First Christian Church (Disciples of
Christ), told trustees that the Albany Ministerial Alliance decided
it will lead prayers in a grassy area near the home bleachers
before each home game.
</P>
<P>
   Fans from both teams _ visitors and home _ will be invited to
pray before the Pledge of Allegiance and other pregame activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance feels compelled to offer opportunities for people
to manifest their faith,'' Mallory said in a telephone interview.
``Obviously, the Supreme Court has put restrictions on them, and we
understand that. But many people still want to vocalize their faith
and that's what we're going to help them do.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallory said that at each home game, a minister in the grassy
area will lead prayers. The alliance is made up of about a
half-dozen churches in town, he said. Among them are Baptist,
Presbyterian, Methodist, Catholic and an independent.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Jewish congregation in Albany, a community of 1,985,
about 30 miles east of Abilene, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grassy area is not near the stadium seating,'' Mallory
said. ``But it is inside the gate, and it is a public access area.
The ministers will lead the prayers before the actual, official
activities begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be there 5 or 10 minutes, just long enough to have a
prayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mallory said he doesn't know whether the alliance plan will draw
``a small circle of people, a mob or a block.'' The plan will be
promoted through local churches and the local newspaper, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is completely within the confines of the law. And the
school board cannot validate it or encourage it, but because it is
in a public area, they can't stop it either,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mallory said the players can't take part in the prayers, but he
emphasized that they never did. ``They were always in the locker
rooms when the school prayers were given,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There has been no opposition to the plan from any quarter in the
community, the clergyman added.
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
