<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-DEFENSE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAIDERS DEFENSIVE COORDINATOR HAS REASON TO HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By FRANK BLACKMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ Raiders defensive coordinator Chuck Bresnahan
is cautiously optimistic about how his unit will perform Sunday
afternoon against the San Diego Chargers and for the rest of the
regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I think the sky is the limit with this defense,''
Bresnahan said. ``But we are so unproven at so many positions right
now. We could have as many as six new people on the field at one
time. So I don't want to make any brash statements.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it sounded as if Bresnahan really had to fight the urge.
And based on the unit's improvement during the preseason, his
excitement is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rams effortlessly rolled through the defense for 344
yards in the exhibition opener in St. Louis, the improvement was
marked. The next week, the Cowboys managed only 256 yards rushing
and passing. Detroit was almost completely stymied when it had the
ball, accumulating 221 yards. And in the final preseason tuneup,
when the defense shut out Seattle, 20-0, the Seahawks had 279 total
yards, including only 39 on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to question this statistical improvement. The
Cowboys are adjusting to life under a new coach, Dave Campo, and
went 0-5 in the preseason. The Lions began their game with backup
Mike Tomzcak starting at quarterback, then lost him to an injury.
And the Seahawks, a conference opponent Oakland will play Oct. 22,
appeared to phone in their effort.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one lingering memory from the preseason, it is the
way the first-string Super Bowl champion Rams shredded the Raiders
first-string defense, moving down the field effortlessly whether
NFL MVP Kurt Warner or Trent Green was taking the snaps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have got a tremendous arsenal of weapons in their
offense,'' Bresnahan said. ``So to be tested by them early, in
their home stadium, on that turf, with them already having a
game-type preparation against Tennessee, there was no reason to
panic at that point. There really wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the game was over, the coach wasted no time at all making
sure his players got that message.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told our guys, `hey, don't get discouraged. Understand,
that's what it's going to be like. And we have to raise our bar up
to that level. Just keep doing the things you're doing.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's what they've done. There was no loss of confidence.
There was no panic. They just kept working.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons Bresnahan is reluctant to declare his defense
ready to take on the world just yet is that he hasn't seen his
first-stringers for an entire game. And the defensive line has
hardly worked together at all.
</P>
<P>
   End Lance Johnstone missed the final two exhibition games with a
groin injury. Nose tackle Grady Jackson made a brief appearance
against Detroit and sat out the Seattle game with an ankle injury.
Both returned to practice on Monday and are expected to start
against the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a little concern,'' the coach said. ``You definitely
want to see how these guys work together. For the linebackers to
see how the linemen play. But it's different than the offensive
line. Offensive football is so much assignment football. Whereas we
are an attacking, aggressive-style of defense. So it (playing as a
unit in the preseason) is not as critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Regan Upshaw started three of the four games at left end. He may
start again against the Chargers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, I don't know if there's a true starter,'' Bresnahan
said. ``Tony Bryant brings some things that Regan may lack, and
Regan brings some things that Tony Bryant may lack. And you've got
Josh Taves, too. I'm a firm believer you've got to keep people
fresh. You're going to see a rotation there.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was the starting left end when the 1999 season ended. He
says he's not upset about having to share playing time this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with it,'' he said. ``Regan's been around the
league awhile. This is just my second year. And with my ankle
injury (last season), I haven't played a full year yet. So I'm
still learning.''
</P>
<P>
   While his line coach may urge caution about the defense's
potential, Bryant is having none of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up front, we're looking good,'' he said. ``The linebacking and
secondary are good. In the preseason, when the ones and twos were
in there, we did good. I think we've got great depth. We're going
to be great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
