A5385 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-FLATHEAD-BOOK-REVIEW-     08-29 0564
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLATHEAD-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRAVING FOOD THAT CAN KILL, OR AT LEAST BITE 
</HEADLINE>
   By TED LEE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This year's most fascinating food book, ``Noodling for
Flatheads: Moonshine, Monster Catfish and Other Southern
Comforts,'' is not at first glance a book about food. The only
photo is on the cover, an unappetizing shot of writhing catfish,
thorny mouths agape. The lone recipe in 250-odd pages is for
``sugar liquor,'' moonshine distilled from sugar, malt,
Fleischmann's yeast and horse feed.
</P>
<P>
   The book, by Burkhard Bilger (Scribner, $24), is a collection of
powerful essays about the people who keep vanishing Southern
traditions alive, and because foodways are among the South's most
enduring regional distinctions, five of the eight essays are about
food. Bilger, German-born but Oklahoma-reared, has assembled a cast
of food devotees that would shock and enthrall the most jaded urban
epicure.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Steve Rector, is willing to die for his favorite
dish. Like more than a few rural Kentuckians, he hunts squirrels
for their brains, long considered a delicacy. In 1997, two Kentucky
neurologists posited a link between Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, a
variant of mad cow disease, and eating squirrel brains. Health
officials no longer allow Rector to serve the brains at the state's
annual folklife festival, but he still eats them. ``You gotta die
of somethin', '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In the title essay, Bilger spends a day with a former high
school classmate, Lee McFarlin, who catches catfish using his
fingers as both bait and hook. ``Noodling'' is slang for this
method of fishing; ``flatheads'' are a variety of catfish that
don't bite as hard as ``blue cats.'' Yes, catfish have teeth, and
Bilger loses some skin noodling a 25-pound flathead.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Patridge, in the essay ``Low on the Hog,'' endures a less
physical challenge to satisfy his passion for chitlins, aka
chitterlings, or hog intestines. At Scholars, his restaurant and
teaching center at Morris Brown College at Atlanta, he teaches
continental cuisine and soul food. But chitlins were once slave
rations, and their gamy aroma can be a painful reminder. When
Patridge steams up his kitchen with a potful, his student chefs
steer clear.
</P>
<P>
   Like all Bilger's cooks, Patridge has an enviable closeness to
his ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody has any idea ... where their food comes from,'' the
manager of a chicken processing plant tells Bilger in ``Enter the
Chicken,'' an essay on cockfighting, as he takes the author on a
gruesome tour of the plant. Bilger's subjects know exactly where
their food comes from, and their taste for certain foods has become
an almost physical need over a lifetime. Patridge was 14 when he
slaughtered his first hog. McFarlin noodled his first fish when he
was 8. Rector has hunted squirrel since he was 6.
</P>
<P>
   Progress has turned these foods into fringe indulgences. In
Atlanta, hot dogs have replaced chitlins in some soul food joints.
In Kentucky, coal mining and development have all but obliterated
the nut trees that sustained squirrels. Noodlers fear that the Army
Corps of Engineers' dredging of rivers deprives them of catfish.
</P>
<P>
   But Bilger's book is not a catalog of dying traditions. His
lyrical narratives thrum with energy and affection. They celebrate
cravings as being deeply personal, utterly illogical and
irrepressibly alive.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
