u d BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT &LR;      08-29 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSENCE OF FRUIT, CRYSTALIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK BITTMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Granitas are the most primitive frozen desserts,
reportedly originating in imperial Rome, where Alpine ice was mixed
with fruit juice to make a crunchy, cold treat for the emperors.
They have the flavor of sorbet if not the creaminess, and they take
very little work and even less equipment to make.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect smooth texture from granitas; that's not what
they're about. Granitas are most similar to the shaved ice served
on some New York street corners in the summer _ superrefreshing but
hardly elegant. While shaved ice is just that, with overly sweet,
artificially flavored syrup poured over it, a granita is a frozen
flavored liquid. When you make it yourself, you control the quality
of the ingredients, and, of course, the level of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   All you need is a freezer, an ice tray or shallow bowl and a
fork or spoon to make granitas, but they do require a little
attention. You must stir them every half-hour or so while they're
in the freezer, to keep large chunks of ice from forming. The ideal
granita is a slushy blend of juicy crystals in ice-cold liquid. It
attains this texture after about two hours of freezing, and will
retain it for a couple of hours more with occasional stirring.
</P>
<P>
   If you pack a granita in a tightly sealed container and keep it
frozen, it will hold for a week or more. You can get it to return
to something approaching its original texture by letting it thaw
slightly and raking through it with a fork (or pulsing it several
times in a food processor). But I suggest making granitas the day
you plan to eat them.
</P>
<P>
   Flavor combinations for granitas are unlimited. Fruit or citrus
juices, coffee or chocolate, and fruit purees or juices are best.
You can also take granitas further and add a little coffee to your
chocolate (or vice versa), or try making them with a sweetened
brewed tea, like jasmine or Earl Grey. Or you can simply freeze a
sweetened canned juice like pineapple. But don't use pieces of
fruit, which will become unpleasantly hard when frozen.
</P>
<P>
   To speed the process, chill the bowl or tray before adding the
liquid. The broader the tray, the faster the mix will freeze.
</P>
<P>
   COFFEE GRANITA
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 2 to 3 hours' freezing
</P>
<P>
   3 cups freshly brewed strong coffee
</P>
<P>
   { cup sugar, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon cocoa powder, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Stir coffee, sugar and cocoa together; taste and add more
sugar if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pour mixture into shallow metal or glass pan or bowl. Freeze
about 30 minutes, or until ice crystals begin to form at the edges.
Gently stir the crystals back into the liquid, not breaking them up
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   3. Continue to stir and break up clumps of crystals every
half-hour or so. When the entire mixture has the texture of soft
crushed ice, it's ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
