<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GRAPEVINE: News, gossip from the wrestling industry
 &HT;    By John Allen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is considered to be one of the World Wrestling Federation's
centerpiece pay-per-views and by most accounts ``SummerSlam'' lived
up to the hype.
</P>
<P>
   With additional advertising from MTV, last Sunday's pay-per-view
should be one WWF's most-watched shows for the year. Despite
another main event that featured The Rock and Triple H, the show
was highlighted by some high-flying stunts that only the WWF can
supply (are you listening WCW?). The three-tag team match between
Edge and Christian, the Dudley Boyz and the Hardy Boyz featured
some of the toughest stunts in the history of the WWF. The ``TLC''
match _ which featured tables, ladders and chairs _ resembled a
hardcore match and had all the high-flying antics the Hardy Boyz
have helped fuse into WWF action.
</P>
<P>
   While that was a classic match in terms of the physical
performances, it was the emotional drama of the main event that
helped to sell a match that fans have seen in some form at least 12
times in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Angle made the jump from mid-carder to main-event status
and showed fans that he will be around for a long time. His
``friendship'' with Triple H's wife, Stephanie, helped build a rift
between Angle and Triple H. That split allowed the Rock to retain
his title. The WWF wisely found a way to increase the feud between
Angle and Triple H. As a result, expect those two to be the main
event for the next pay-per-view in the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   Other highlights from ``SummerSlam'' were a return to the ring
for Jerry ``The King'' Lawler. His match with Tazz has really put
the former ECW champion back in the forefront of the WWF fans'
minds. This should propel Tazz into solid mid-card status in hopes
of sending him back to the main event status he enjoyed for years
with ECW. Also, Stephen Richards continues his climb up the WWF
ladder with his censorship group. They are creating good television
and the act is getting the WWF's ``no censorship'' message across.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monday night was a big night for the ``Nitro'' show with the
introduction of the New World Order 2000. Vince Russo has merged
Jeff Jarrett, Kevin Nash and Scott Steiner into the new power of
the WCW. They are pitted against ``Stone Cold'' _ oops _ I mean
Goldberg, Booker T and Mike Awesome. Hopefully this storyline will
last longer than just the next pay-per-view. Putting some
consistency in the storylines would really help WCW's rating more
than anything else they have tried. For those of you who watched
the whole ``Nitro,'' you caught Bret Hart's return. Although the
Hitman was there, it doesn't look like he's in any shape to return
to the ring anytime soon. Too bad for WCW and the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
