<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-SAT-SCORES30-COX     08-29 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAT-SCORES30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAT SCORES REMAIN STABLE
 &HT;    360&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Average scores on SAT college aptitude tests
reached a 30-year high in math and stayed steady for the fifth
straight year on the verbal portion, the College Board announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gaston Caperton, president of the College Board, described the
trend as ``encouraging,'' especially since the tests _ once taken
by an elite that included fewer than one-third of high school
graduates _ now are taken by 44 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rise in math scores is cause for cautious optimism, as is
the stability of verbal scores,'' Caperton said at the National
Press Club.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that the SAT test-takers this year included a
higher proportion than ever before of people who usually score
slightly lower _ women, non-whites, students whose parents didn't
go to college, and those for whom English is a second language.
</P>
<P>
   The maximum possible score on an SAT test is 800 in math and 800
in verbal skills. This year, the average SAT scores:
</P>
<P>
   _ Reached 514 in math, up 3 points since last year and 13 points
since 1990. This year's math scores were the highest since 1969,
when the average was 517.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stayed at 505 on the verbal portion, as it has since 1996.
That was up five points from 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Two new patterns emerged from the statistical studies of test
scores by experts at the New York-based College Board, a non-profit
consortium of colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
   First, more college-bound high school students are taking the
tough courses recommended for anyone who wants to go to college.
More than 1.2 million students took the latest exam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the last decade, male and female students from all ethnic
backgrounds have been taking more pre-calculus, calculus and
physics,'' Caperton said. ``The SAT math scores of students who
take these courses are well above the national average.''
</P>
<P>
   Second, the high school grade-point averages of SAT test-takers
are rising faster than their SAT scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, 40 percent of students reported grade averages in
the A range (A-plus, A or A-minus), up from 28 percent 10 years
ago. We believe this reflects some improvement, but it also
indicates some grade inflation,'' Caperton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   Although women tend to get higher grades in college, men still
get higher SAT scores. Critics of standardized testing once again
pounced upon this anomaly, since SAT scores are touted as a way for
college admission officers to tell how well students will do in
college.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schaeffer, public education director of FairTest of
Cambridge, Mass., a nonprofit group that urges colleges to make
aptitude tests optional, said, ``On the rival admissions test, the
ACT, male and female scores are essentially the same. So the SAT
gender gap says more about the test's biases than educational
attainment.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending the SAT tests, Caperton said the SAT gender gap is
getting narrower.
</P>
<P>
   Men had an edge of 41 points on the math portion and 9 points on
the verbal portion a decade ago. Since then, because women's SAT
scores have been rising faster than those of men, the gap has been
reduced to 35 points on the math portion and 3 points on the verbal
portion.
</P>
<P>
   He said the gap may linger because women are more numerous, more
ethnically diverse and more likely than men to come from families
where neither parent attended college.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also know that there's a difference in their course-taking
patterns,'' he said. For example, he said, women in college may
major in areas like the humanities, in which he believes grades
tend to be higher than in male-dominated majors such as engineering
or math.
</P>
<P>
   This year's results also show that whites continue to get the
highest average verbal scores and Asian Americans the highest
average math scores. Over the past 10 years, the only minority
groups whose SAT scores rose faster than those of whites were
Asian-Americans, Puerto Ricans and American Indians.
</P>
<P>
   On the verbal tests since 1990, scores have risen by an average
of 21 points for Puerto Ricans, followed by Asian Americans, 16;
American Indians, also 16; whites, 9; African Americans, 6, and
other Hispanics, 2, while falling 4 points for Mexican Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On the math tests during that decade, scores rose by 19 points
for Asian Americans, followed by whites, 15; Puerto Ricans, 14;
American Indians, 13; African Americans, 7, and other Hispanics, 3,
while remaining unchanged for Mexican Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   College Board: www.collegeboard.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
