<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SNOW-WIDOW-ART-NYT &LR;      08-29 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SNOW-WIDOW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD FRIEND OF CHINA SEES A BLACKENED STAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE WADLER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It is possible that friendship with a country is not
so different from a friendship with a person. You close your eyes
to flaws, sometimes significant ones, preferring not to see them,
even as others point them out.
</P>
<P>
   This is how it was with Lois Wheeler Snow.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Edgar Snow, was an American journalist who came to
know Mao Tse-tung and Zhou Enlai when they were struggling
communist revolutionaries in the '30s, and he remained on cordial
terms with them even when China was closed to most Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Snow is one of the few Americans to have been buried with
honors in communist China. After her husband's death, Snow, a
onetime Broadway actress who gave up her career to follow her
husband abroad, made several trips to China and was treated as an
honored guest.
</P>
<P>
   Those days, of what she calls ``the nice well-behaved Snow,''
are now over.
</P>
<P>
   Snow, who turned 80 last month, has been protesting human rights
violations in China since the violent suppression of the Tiananmen
Square demonstrations in 1989. This April, she traveled to Beijing
from her home in Switzerland to try to meet with Ding Zilin, whose
son was killed during the Tiananmen crackdown, and was prevented
from doing so by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as Li Peng, the chairman of China's National People's
Congress, who was prime minister in 1989, comes to New York as a
delegate to the Conference of Presiding Officers of National
Parliaments at the United Nations, Snow is also here. Working with
the group Human Rights in China, she is demanding an investigation
of the Tiananmen killings and the release of political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   She has also said that she may have to consider removing her
husband's ashes from China.
</P>
<P>
   Is such a thing possible?
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very difficult physically,'' Snow says, at Human
Rights' Manhattan office. ``I know that they are buried in a cement
or stone container deep in the earth. But what is important is that
I maintain that threat, and if it gets to a point it is necessary
to get the ashes out, at least it will be a worldwide scream. It
would be a tremendous blow to the Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   How did a Broadway actress become an activist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I married Edgar Snow. That's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Their story begins in 1945 in New York. Snow, then Wheeler, 25,
who had grown up in a conservative Republican home in Stockton,
Calif., was a leading lady on Broadway. Edgar Snow, 15 years her
senior, was a journalistic star, the author of the 1937 classic
``Red Star Over China.'' The two met at a party for Russian War
Relief and married four years later.
</P>
<P>
   The McCarthy era was difficult for both. Though Lois Snow says
she never joined any political party, she was blacklisted. She was,
however, able to continue working in a television soap opera, ``The
Guiding Light.'' (``Nurse Janet Jackson,'' Snow remembers. ``She
was after all the doctors in the hospital.'')
</P>
<P>
   Her husband fared less well.
</P>
<P>
   ``China was a dirty word and a very dangerous one, and nobody
was willing to publish Edgar Snow,'' Snow said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1959 the Snows, now with a son and daughter, moved to
Switzerland, where Snow was able to work and Mrs. Snow could not.
In 1970, when Snow was reporting on China, the Snows were invited
to stand with Mao on the reviewing stand during a National Day
observance.
</P>
<P>
   It was the time of the Cultural Revolution, with those critical
of Mao sent to prisons and work camps, but that was not apparent to
the Snows. Her husband tried to learn what was happening, Snow
says, but ``the facts were not there, plus he was ill.''
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, as her husband was dying, Prime
Minister Zhou sent three doctors and a nurse to Eysins, the Snows'
small village in Switzerland. They stayed for three weeks, until
his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything Ed needed was immediately supplied. It was one of the
most wonderful things in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   In the next 15 years, Snow traveled yearly to China, for many
years blind to the excesses of the Cultural Revolution. ``I was
surprised the central bookstore in Peking had nothing but
propaganda,'' she says, using the older word for Beijing. ``I knew
that was crazy, but I accepted it as part of _ I don't know. The
schools were closed, the students were out working, they didn't
have time for books.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she made a living after her husband's death, Snow at
first sidesteps the question. Later, she returns to the subject
herself. She did a lecture tour in the United States and Europe,
she says, telling people how ``wonderful'' the Cultural Revolution
was. In the '80s, as books on the abuses of the Cultural Revolution
appeared, she resisted them. Tiananmen changed her.
</P>
<P>
   Does she now feel foolish about that lecture tour?
</P>
<P>
   A sad, small little smile, which would be recognized by anyone
who has been disappointed in a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to describe how I feel. I feel I was used. I know I
was naive. They encouraged my lecture series. When a few years
later it turned out that what I was talking about was nonsense, it
is true I felt used. They needed Ed; without him, they needed me.
And I fell for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard even for me to realize that I went for such a long
time without being aware of the transgressions of human rights,
that it took Tiananmen to wake me up. There it was on television;
in the living room, in front of your face. The kids, my children,
were with me. We were screaming. It was like being there.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
