<HEADLINE>
RECORD DRYNESS IN TEXAS LIKELY TO UNCORK RICHER WINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GORDON DICKSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE, Texas _ The scorched, yellow grass along highways is
a depressing sight for many as Dallas-Fort Worth eclipses its
50-year-old record for consecutive days without rain.
</P>
<P>
   For 59 days, the area has gone without rain, breaking a record
set in 1934 and repeated in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps nobody feels the effects more than farmers and ranchers.
State agricultural officials estimate $595 million in losses this
year because of the parched conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But not all farmers are hurting.
</P>
<P>
   The relentless dryness, which conjures images of the 1930s Dust
Bowl, is helping Texas grape growers produce sweeter fruit.
</P>
<P>
   Wine drinkers can look forward to richer libations from Texas'
38 commercial vineyards, growers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sunshine and heat make them sweet, and once that sugar
content is up, you've got to harvest,'' said Camille McBee,
marketing director at La Buena Vida Vineyards in Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   The Metroplex has had 36 days with temperatures of 100 degrees
or more this year, including five in a row. The high Tuesday was
expected to hit 102 at Dallas/Fort Worth Airport, and forecasters
at the National Weather Service call for much of the same
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions are similar in wine-growing areas of Texas, from the
High Plains to the Hill Country, and a wave of optimism is blowing
across the wine industry like a November breeze.
</P>
<P>
   For the third year in a row, a hot and dry summer has aided
grape production. The results of harvests will be available for
tasting during fall festivals across the state, including the 14th
annual GrapeFest Sept. 8-10 in Grapevine.
</P>
<P>
   La Buena Vida harvested a week early because the fruit ripened
quickly at its vineyards in Grapevine and Springtown, McBee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't realize that grapes are an arid plant,'' she
said. ``They don't like a lot of water when the fruit is hanging.''
</P>
<P>
   Wine production probably will slip below last year's level of
1.2 million gallons, said Tim Dodd, director of the Texas Wine
Research Institute. Still, wine producers are expected to surpass
the million-gallon mark and bottle high quality wine because of the
dry heat, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some farmers' grapevines suffered early this year because of
depleted water supplies at the start of the growing season, which
contributed to the projected decrease in overall production, Dodd
said.
</P>
<P>
   Grapes, which are among the world's hardiest plants, can endure
hot, dry weather, but they need a generous supply of water in the
spring and early summer, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers whose crops made it to a rainy June that was followed by
eight weeks of savage summer dryness _ a nearly perfect combination
for grapes _ are being rewarded with high-quality harvests, Dodd
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a nice dry spell,'' Dodd said. ``It's usually really
good for grapes to have a dry spell when people are harvesting.
Most of the growers have just gone through harvest. Overall, things
have been excellent for grapes this year, especially up on the High
Plains.''
</P>
<P>
   After three consecutive dry summers in Texas, bottles of wine on
store shelves should be among the best-tasting ever offered by
state wineries, wine enthusiasts said. Many of the white wines in
stores now were manufactured in 1999, and many of the red wines
were made in 1999, 1998 or 1997.
</P>
<P>
   John Brancato, owner and managing partner of La Bodega Winery in
Grapevine, buys some grapes from farmers who used to deal solely in
crops such as cotton and grains.
</P>
<P>
   La Bodega, which is in D/FW Airport, buys grapes from
independent producers and bottles about 1,300 cases of wine each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three years in a row, we are getting a lot of the old
cotton growers who are saying, `You know what? Maybe I need to put
in 50 acres of vines to hedge against the bad times.' A person we
buy from has 900 to 1,000 acres, and 100 acres is grapevines. It is
a hedge crop.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Texans have prayed for rain since early July, but many
grape growers silently hoped for the status quo, winemakers said.
</P>
<P>
   Rainy summers may increase the volume of grapes, but the quality
often is not as good, Cap Rock Winery President Dewayne ``De''
Pierce said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give up a little bit of quality when you get a bumper
crop,'' said Pierce, whose winery operates a 1,200-acre vineyard in
the Lubbock area of West Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Now that harvest is over in most Texas vineyards, it is safe for
everyone _ including grape growers _ to pray for rain.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
