<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5413 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LYCEE-FRANCAIS-ART     08-29 1200
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LYCEE-FRANCAIS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL SEEKS SIX HOME BUYERS WHO WOULD LIKE TO LIVE LIKE
VANDERBILTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Lycee Francais de New York, the prestigious
school that attracts Europeans and American Francophiles, is
selling all six of its buildings on the Upper East Side of
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The school expects to sell the town houses to wealthy people who
want to restore them to single-family homes. And the school hopes
to make a big profit, more than $100 million, on the sale, enough
to create an endowment and build a new school.
</P>
<P>
   Once considered too costly for private use, town houses are
making a comeback as private residences in a new era of opulence
that has left investment bankers, Internet entrepreneurs and
investors flush with cash from the longest economic boom in
history. And with names like Vanderbilt, Gould, Pulitzer and McKim,
Mead &AMP; White embedded in the schools buildings, brokers expect a
rash of bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of these properties are going to be bought by private
individuals, Wall Street money,'' said Jed Garfield, a broker at
Leslie J. Garfield &AMP; Co., which specializes in town house sales.
``There's no question that the dollars in private purchasers'
pockets today are deeper than those of the institutions. It's an
end of an era for some of these institutional buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first six months of this year, the average price for a
town house on the West Side climbed 34 percent to $2.9 million.
During the same period, houses on the Upper East Side sold for $4.4
million, or $814 a square foot, up 19 percent from a year ago,
according to the Corcoran Group, a residential broker specializing
in luxury properties. In contrast, the average price of a
condominium on the Upper East Side is $673 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is rare that six houses would come on the market at
once, real estate brokers said that the school's portfolio was not
expected to dampen prices, because there are so few buildings
available.
</P>
<P>
   In June, an investment banker who took early retirement from
Goldman Sachs paid $5 million for the town house at 25 E. 92nd St.,
between Fifth and Madison Avenues. The house had been divided into
five condominiums. The buyer plans to knock down the walls and make
a home for his family.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Benny Shabtai, president of Raymond Weil-Seville
Watch Corp., paid $8.2 million for the town house at 870 Park Ave.,
between 77th and 78th Streets. The house has a three-story atrium,
fireplaces, a library and a spiral staircase leading to five
bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Elsa Berry, who heads the board at Lycee Francais, said it was
hard to part with the school's six illustrious old buildings, which
sit in two clusters on the Upper East Side and serve 1,000
students.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the buoyant real estate market provided the
school with an opportunity to create an endowment and to build a
new and more efficient, if less historic, school building at a
single location. The school is negotiating to buy a site on either
the Upper East Side or the Upper West Side for a
115,000-square-foot school building, nearly double the current
space. According to one broker, the school is close to a deal for a
site in the East 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to improve our operations from a technological
standpoint and add new facilities for sports, student lounges and a
cafeteria,'' said Berry, who attended the Lycee Francais as a girl
and now runs the corporate finance department for BNP Paribas, a
French investment bank. ``The board is working aggressively on a
long-term strategic plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Lycee Francais was founded in 1935 by Count Charles de Ferry de
Fontnouvelle, the French consul general at the time; Forsythe
Wicks, a businessman who was president of the Alliance Francaise;
and Paul Windels Sr., the city's corporation counsel. The school's
alumni include Philippe de Montebello, director of the Metropolitan
Museum of Art; Michel David-Weil, managing partner of Lazard Freres
&AMP; Co., and Danielle Steel, the novelist.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to be similar to a French lycee, the school emphasizes
a classical education, including Latin and Greek. Instruction is
primarily in French, although the school does provide an
understanding of American language and culture. Berry said that 40
percent of the school's students are the children of French
diplomats or business executives and 40 percent are American, with
48 other nationalities accounting for the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable building owned by the lycee is the Henry T.
Sloane residence at 9 E. 72nd St., which is regarded by architects
as one of the finest Beaux-Arts town houses in the city. The
five-story structure, which has an intricately carved limestone
facade, Ionic columns and French windows, was built in 1896 by
Sloane, son of the founder of the W&AMP;J Sloane furniture store. But
he lived there only briefly before a scandalous divorce in 1898.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Pulitzer, the newspaper publisher, lived there before it
was bought in 1901 by James Stillman, president of the National
City Bank, then one of the most important commercial banks in the
world. Stillman worked closely with William Rockefeller, a founder
of Standard Oil, and Jacob Schiff and Edward Harriman in
reorganizing American railroads.
</P>
<P>
   But starting in the late 1920s, most tycoons abandoned such
luxurious town houses for more fashionable estates in the Long
Island and Westchester countryside or for duplexes on Park and
Fifth Avenues. Too costly to maintain, the buildings were
demolished or converted into apartments, stores or museums. Many of
the original details and fixtures were lost, although the Lycee's
buildings remain in relatively good shape.
</P>
<P>
   The Lycee is also selling the Oliver Gould Jennings mansion, a
Beaux-Arts house next door at 7 E. 72nd St., named after the man
who built it in 1899, who was a director of Bethlehem Steel and the
National Fuel Gas Co.
</P>
<P>
   The third property, at 60 East 93rd St., was built in 1931 for
Virginia Graham Fair Vanderbilt, a racehorse breeder and former
wife of William Vanderbilt, the railroad tycoon. Her father was
Senator James Fair of Nevada, who made a fortune from the Comstock
Lode and the Big Bonanza mine. The limestone building resembles a
French hotel during the reign of Louis XV.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth site is a neo-Classical-style limestone building with
a mansard roof at 3 E. 95th St. It was commissioned by Marion B.
Carhart, after the death of her husband, Amory Carhart, a banking
and railroad executive. She died shortly after its completion, in
1917. The school is also selling the adjoining three-story building
at 5 E. 95th St. and a limestone building at 12 E. 73rd St. that
was built in 1920 by Henry Allan Jacobs.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, one former student and some brokers lamented, the
school may well lose some of the cachet of old New York as it moves
to a modern home.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a sense of history going to school in mansions,''
Garfield said. ``But I'm sure the new building will be more
efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
