<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5429 &Cx1f; kan-z
r l BC-TREND-MODERNGEEZERS-K     08-29 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREND-MODERNGEEZERS-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAY MATTERS:OLDER AMERICANS ARE CARVING OUT A SPACE OF THEIR OWN
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 LISA GUTIERREZ  
 c. 2000 The Kansas City Star   HUTCHINSON, Kan. _ Strapped in and
spread-eagle on a giant gyroscope called a three-axis trainer, Ann
Schaefer looked like she'd rather be walking across hot coals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the contraption slowly flipped and twisted her upside-down
like ribs on a barbecue spit, she yelled out: ``Wait! Stop!'' But
the gyroscope kept gyrating.
</P>
<P>
   Launching that mock satellite on that mock moon had been so much
easier, she thought.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 32 other students in the Elderhostel Astronaut Training
Program, all with at least 60 years logged on Earth, Schaefer spent
last week at the Kansas Cosmosphere and Space Center here testing
her reflexes, depth perception and ability to climb into the tight
confines of both a spacesuit and a space capsule.
</P>
<P>
   These aging astronauts-in-training represent what demographers
call the changing face of maturity, a healthier, wealthier and
wiser generation than those that went before. They are also role
models for baby boomers who are themselves inching their way closer
to AARP membership.
</P>
<P>
   Older Americans 60-plus are the ``younger-older'' who sniff at
labels like senior citizen and who marketers suddenly realize
control nearly 90 percent of the financial assets in this country
and whose faces we're seeing more of in everything from L.L. Bean
catalogs to Old Navy commercials hawking cargo pants.
</P>
<P>
   Retirees? Think again. Two years ago AARP officially changed its
name to simply AARP _ it's not an acronym anymore _ to reflect that
at least one-third of the 34 million people older than 50 it
represents are not retired.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her fellow classmates _ homemakers, teachers, pilots,
travel agents _ who have toured Southern mansions and studied
native plants on the plains of South Dakota through other
elderhostel programs, this was Ann Schaefer's first such
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like stepping into an invisible world, a world I never
knew existed,'' said the 61-year-old, an outreach teacher at the
St. Louis Science Center. ``I come here, and there are women 20
years older, and they have so much energy. So I know that old folks
aren't fuddy-duddies.''
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to that image.
</P>
<P>
   While baby boomers fight over the White House, 70-year-old Clint
Eastwood and his Ensure-swilling ``Space Cowboys'' are saving the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so thrilled to see that movie get top box office,'' said
Allison Patterson in Silver Spring, Md., editor of ``Selling to
Seniors'' newsletter, an industry publication for companies that
market to consumers 65 and older. ``It reflects our demographics,
that the age of our population is getting older.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a comedy that didn't laugh at older people, it laughed
with them.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago AARP redesigned its Modern Maturity
magazine to look, for lack of a better description, more sprightly,
said AARP spokesman Tom Otwell in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Newman and Sophia Loren have both graced the cover since
then, but the list of possible candidates lengthens every day. This
is what 60 looks like today: Ted Koppel, Raquel Welch, Smokey
Robinson, Ringo Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Julie Andrews, Phil Donahue and Woody Allen all turn 65 this
year. Gene Hackman, George Steinbrenner, Joanne Woodward and Sandra
Day O'Connor are five years older.
</P>
<P>
   Do any of those people strike you as geezers? Marketers and
demographers struggle to create new labels for a graying population
that is living longer, working longer and playing harder.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers used to call anyone over the age of 50 a senior, but
that doesn't work anymore, Patterson said. Thus you get labels like
``primers'' and descriptions of people entering the ``third age''
of their lives. Or how about a governmental term: ``nearly
elderly''?
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that Madison Avenue advertising companies, still
fueled by a 20- and 30-something mentality, move at glacier-speed
to change the way they portray older Americans, Patterson said.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, for instance, a television commercial for an
Internet search engine portrayed its competitors as slovenly,
feeble-minded old men shuffling around in bedroom slippers. The
National Council on Aging fired off a letter of protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think baby boomers have been afraid of these negative images
of older people, and they want to change that because they see what
it has done to people, to their parents, to our parents,'' said
Burton Halpert, a social gerontologist in the Center for Aging
Studies at the University of Missouri-Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Images of old men in bedroom slippers don't even begin to fit
teachers Bud Johnson and Ron Maxson, friends from Canandaigua,
N.Y., who came to the space-camp elderhostel.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who flew single-engine planes in the Civil Air Patrol,
had applied in 1980 to be NASA's first teacher in space, something
he has mixed emotions about today, considering the eventual
disaster of that mission.
</P>
<P>
   The two friends went through all the training stations together,
including strapping themselves inside a monster of a centrifuge
machine that spun them around like a carnival ride, locking their
bodies into their seats by pressure five times their body weights.
</P>
<P>
   Maxson almost set a record on the stress test in which students
sat inside what one woman called the ``dishwasher'' and punched at
red lights that flashed quickly on a control panel in front of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Looking around at their classmates, Maxson, 61, noted how much
more healthier and wealthier this generation is than just the one
before. ``You're not told when you turn 55, `Don't get up and
walk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With at least one baby boomer turning 50 every seven seconds in
this country, age has suddenly, but maybe not surprisingly, become
relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that this huge bulge of boomers is entering this age
group, like everything else they have touched, (is) going to have
some impact on how we perceive aging in this country,'' said AARP
spokesman Otwell. ``I think they will start to redefine what it
means to grow old or be old in America.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they turn that corner at 50, AARP has a new magazine
waiting for them. The group next spring will launch an offshoot of
Modern Maturity magazine designed specifically for aging boomers.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have a name yet. But you can bet it won't be Modern
Geezers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
