<HEADER>
A5437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PRISONER-(TRIM     08-29 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRISONER-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE OF AMERICAN HELD BY RUSSIANS FOR ESPIONAGE FEARS FOR HIS
HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The wife of a an American who has been in jail here for
five months on espionage charges came here Tuesday with her
congressman to call on the Russian government to allow Western
doctors to examine her 54-year-old husband, who has bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Pope looked shaken and fatigued after visiting Moscow's
Lefortovo Prison on Tuesday, where her husband, Edmond, a former
naval intelligence officer, has been incarcerated since early
April. He was arrested for supposedly trying to buy classified
plans for a high-technology Russian torpedo system.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian press reports have identified the torpedo
propulsion system, known as the Squall, as the same one carried
aboard the nuclear submarine Kursk, which sank in the Barents Sea
on Aug. 12, killing all 118 crewmen aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing my husband and having to leave him there was extremely
difficult,'' Mrs. Pope said at a news conference, dressed in a gray
suit and speaking in subdued and emotional tones. ``And now I have
to go back to my room and call his mother and father and our sons
and tell them that Ed is not doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John E. Petersen, R-Pa., who accompanied her, was more
blunt. ``If his cancer has returned and we do not catch it soon,
Edmond Pope will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say Edmond Pope has been examined 10 times
since April and is not facing any imminent health threat.
``Allegations about the deteriorating mental and physical condition
of the U.S. citizen spread by U.S. representatives are
groundless,'' the Federal Security Service said on Friday. Last
week, a Russian court denied Pope's request to be released to
receive medical treatment while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. embassy officials have been allowed to visit Pope 11 times,
and Tuesday's visit was Mrs. Pope's second. She said her husband is
being kept in a cell with five Russian prisoners, who all share a
sink and toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson castigated Russian authorities for arresting Pope over
the attempted purchase of ``10-year-old'' torpedo technology that
the Russian government openly sells to foreign governments, most
recently to Canada, he asserted. He asked that all details of the
charges against Pope be made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in America knows that Ed Pope is not a spy,''
Peterson said, ``He is an independent businessman who has been
working with the Russians for five to six years'' to develop and
sell high-technology products. He warned that Pope's incarceration
spelled ``a very bad day for the future of American-Russian
business relations.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials in Washington have said that
President Clinton raised the plight of Pope in a telephone call to
President Vladimir Putin during the frantic rescue operation for
the Kursk. Tuesday, Peterson said that Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright have been raising the issue of Pope's
``unfair imprisonment'' and asking that his case be resolved ``each
time they meet with a Russian official.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Russia's intelligence service, reached by
telephone, said the agency would not comment Tuesday on the charges
against Pope. Nor would a spokesman say when a trial might take
place.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russian press accounts, quoting intelligence officials here, say
that Pope was arrested as he was handing over $30,000 to a
professor from Bauman State Technical University, Anatoly Babkin,
in order to purchase the plans for the high-speed Russian torpedo
system known. Babkin is a specialist in torpedo development and
design.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some reports said that Babkin, 70, was subsequently released
because of his advanced age and a heart condition, raising the
question of how seriously Russia's security services are taking his
offense, normally treated as an act of treason.
</P>
<P>
   The Squall torpedo, according to a report from the Russian
institute that designed it, was developed over two decades as a
``versatile'' design that could be fitted with various warheads and
rocket motors depending on its mission. Its versatility included
configurations for underwater attacks, or for firing over the
horizon at surface ships or distant submarine targets.
</P>
<P>
   Its most remarkable feature is its speed, more than 220 miles an
hour in its own gas bubble, making it the fastest torpedo in the
world, according to an article by Valery Kulbitsky, chief designer
of the Russian Research Institute of Marine Technology.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy navy officials have reportedly shown a great deal of
interest in the Squall system, and two U.S. submarines, one of them
the Memphis, were monitoring the military exercises during which
Kursk was slated to fire a variety of weapons. Two senior Russian
officials connected with the investigation into the Kursk sinking
have asserted that Kursk was carrying an experimental torpedo and
that an accident involving the weapon or its engine could have
contributed to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A source at the Russian navy headquarters told the news agency
Interfax on Tuesday that navy officials have not ruled out a
torpedo explosion as a cause of the Kursk's sinking, along with
some collision that triggered the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said Tuesday that
``There were no new torpedoes on the submarine.'' He said Kursk,
during the military exercises, had launched a type of torpedo that
had been used for 20 years, but he added that some new features had
been added to the torpedo, which he identified as ``a new
accumulator unit with a large resource.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1654EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 16:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5439 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-DIRECTORY-ASSISTANCE-     08-29 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIRECTORY-ASSISTANCE-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: same thing.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wireless phone industry, meanwhile, operates under its own
system. A wireless subscriber who dials 411 is generally connected
to a directory assistance operator affiliated with his wireless
carrier. Those operators generally use a national database.
</P>
<P>
   But no one disputes that the quality of directory assistance
service varies from provider to provider.
</P>
<P>
   The listings themselves are generally compiled and controlled by
the roughly 1,300 individual local phone companies around the
country. Big carriers like AT&AMP;T and Verizon contract with outside
companies to pull together phone listings from the multitude of
local phone databases around the nation. To save money, other,
smaller companies may sometimes try to compile listings by scanning
phone books, property records or other sources that are less likely
to be up to date and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, big phone companies say that directory assistance
listings are about 95 percent accurate. But if there are, as is
estimated, 3 billion directory assistance calls in a year (the
actual figure may be higher), that adds up to 150 million wrong
numbers annually.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Louis S. Richman is restive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a really annoying aggravation that when you call
for the headquarters number for a major corporation that you get
some branch office delivery dock,'' said Richman, finance editor of
Consumer Reports magazine, in New York. ``Or you call for a major
hospital in a major city and they never heard of it, or a
restaurant that you knew was there a week ago but they can no
longer find it or you get a fax number.''
</P>
<P>
   It may help if callers understand that there are gazetteering
limitations with today's patchwork directory assistance. And the
limitations begin with four words: United States Postal Service.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone listings are almost always governed by the post office
address of the residence or business listed. Take Brighton, the
town in upstate New York supervised by Frankel. A letter to her
town must be addressed to Rochester; the Postal Service does not
recognize Brighton as an official mailing location. Given this, and
the fact that there is another community in New York known as
Brighton, near Buffalo, it is understandable that a directory
assistance operator in Omaha, Neb., or elsewhere may become a bit
confused.
</P>
<P>
   But the Postal Service rationale carries little weight with
Frankel. ``I would think that the telephone directory services are
something that should be upgraded,'' she said. ``The technology is
there to do it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   It may depend on which company is wielding the technology.
Although the main local phone company for most of New York state is
Verizon, the local phone company for the Brighton that is near
Rochester, and for Rochester itself, is Frontier.
</P>
<P>
   In an unscientific test conducted from phones in Manhattan,
directory assistance operators for AT&AMP;T and Verizon were routinely
able to find numbers in Brighton for the Twelve Corners Apothecary,
the Bagel Bin Cafe and Frankel's two home numbers. In most cases,
though, the operator would note that the listing was in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   And in a second unscientific test, directory assistance calls
placed from Rochester and within Brighton, also succeeded without
exception in finding those same numbers. The volunteer tester,
Jennifer Leonard, president of the Rochester Area Community
Foundation, a charitable group, called various directory assistance
services to obtain the listings for the apothecary and Frankel's
residence.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, who lives in Brighton, called a Frontier operator from
her office in Rochester, a Frontier operator from a pay phone in
Brighton, an operator affiliated with her local phone company, Time
Warner Communications, and a Verizon operator from her wireless
phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the operators were located in Rochester and all of them
had both numbers and had no problem with the location of Brighton,
N.Y.,'' Leonard reported.
</P>
<P>
   Whether directory assistance in Brighton is as truly bad as
Frankel has found it, or as reasonably good as this informal test
might indicate, it is certain that there are many more paths than
there used to be to that tantalizingly helpful operator's greeting,
``What listing?''
</P>
<P>
   With all the variables, it may be that the best hope for a
caller _ besides keeping those keypad fingers crossed _ is to be
very, very precise.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most cases you can find the one you're looking for,'' said
Agerton at BellSouth, which handles more than 500 million directory
assistance calls a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what happens a lot of the time,'' Agerton said, ``is
someone calls and says, `I want Bill Smith in Roanoke, Va.' And so
you pull it up and there's Bill Smith, so you put them through. But
then they call back and in fact they wanted William T. Smith on
Lovers' Lane.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
