<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5440 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-29 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDERSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFRO'S OK _ ESPECIALLY IF YOU CAN STILL GROW ONE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MONICA FRAZIER ANDERSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Afros are back. I realize that styles are cyclical. I've seen
the camouflage pants that the kids are wearing now. I've noticed
the colorful shirts reminiscent of the '70s disco days. Even the
cars are going retro. No, I'm not blind to the cultural continuum.
</P>
<P>
   However, some fashions hibernate for so long that you forget
about them. They're like vogue training wheels. They're cute for a
while but once they're gone, you really don't think that they'll
come back en masse.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, as an African-American I understand the cultural and
historical perspective of Afros. The natural state of my hair is
curly. I'm just a perm away from an Afro myself.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas, a group of women have banded together and formed an
organization called The Nappy Hair Affair. The members all wear
natural hairstyles like Afros, braids, and dreadlocks that don't
require chemicals and curling irons to maintain.
</P>
<P>
   I'm all for that. If my head had a less oblong shape, I'd shave
this mop off and do a Jordan myself.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not referring to those folks when I talk about this new
trend. I'm talking about these teen-age boys like my son, T-Bone.
That's what he calls himself now. He's USDA prime, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, the problem is that this child's Afro is expensive! When
he was young and we kept his hair cropped, most mornings he brushed
his hair and we left home. Many days, he didn't brush his hair
because he didn't care and I didn't notice until we were at our
destination. All we needed to maintain his former dome was shampoo.
A bottle lasted six months.
</P>
<P>
   Honey, those days are over.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he has three kinds of shampoo. He has conditioner. He has
oil sheen, picks, brushes, big combs and a few other bottles of
stuff that I swear were in my bathroom at one time. After football
practice the other day, I thought I'd surprise the boys and stop at
the ice cream parlor. My youngest son and I hopped out of the car
as soon as it rolled to a stop.
</P>
<P>
   T- Bone looked at me in dismay and said, ``What about my hair?''
</P>
<P>
   Who is this child? Six months ago he didn't know he had hair. I
constantly had to remind him to give it a little attention.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he wouldn't go out in public because his natural looked
like the inside of a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   I looked through the window of Braum's and told him, ``Son,
there is no one in there under 30.''
</P>
<P>
   He still looked skeptical but he got out of the car.
</P>
<P>
   My youngest son tried to grow his hair out too but all of that
washing and picking was just too much for him. I came home one day
to find him pouting and sheared like a lamb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dad cut my hair off!'' he said, pointing to the trash can.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the trash can was a mass of dark, dirty locks that looked
liked a bird's nest. My son looked to me for sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is the last time that you washed your hair?'' I asked,
pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   He dropped his head and walked away.
</P>
<P>
   That night at dinner, he was still perturbed. He stared at his
father's shaved head a while and said, ``Dad, you can't grow an
Afro can you?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband smiled and said, ``Not now, but I used to have a huge
'fro. Sometimes my sister would braid it into cornrows.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have a picture of your braids?''
</P>
<P>
   My husband thought a moment and said, ``No, I don't think I
do.''
</P>
<P>
   My son said: ``That's too bad. You should have taken a picture.
You'll never have that chance again.''
</P>
<P>
   The room got real quiet. My meat was gone so I started slicing
my beans so I wouldn't have to look at anyone. Finally, my husband
started laughing and we all laughed until we had tears in our eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Kids, you gotta love 'em.
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a dentist, TV talk-show host and
author in Arlington, Texas. Her lastest book, ``Mom, Are We There
Yet?'' is a collection of her favorite columns. Contact her online
at www.moeanderson.com or call (817) 548-5564. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1701EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
