<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5441 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-VIDEOGAMES-REVIEWS-TE     08-29 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAMES-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOULD-BE LAME VIDEO GAMES ARE ACTUALLY COOL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week, a roundup of video games that ``should'' be lame, but
for whatever reason are kinda cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ecco the Dolphin _ Defender of the Future'' (Sega for
Dreamcast): Funny how the video-game world works. Heroes like
Superman and James Bond have to fly around, shoot people, make it
with the ladies, and have X-ray vision and big weapons to save the
Earth. Ecco the Dolphin can do it with his, um, fins.
</P>
<P>
   For this game, players take on the role of Ecco, a friendly
Flipper that must complete a series of tasks in order to save
dolphins _ and, apparently, mankind _ from extinction. To do this,
players must fend off evil fish (hey, where's Jaws?) and other
deep-sea dangers, which, for some reason, do not include pollution
and drunken teen-agers out for a Saturday boat ride.
</P>
<P>
   Really, it's a fascinating game, with wonderfully designed
graphics and lighting effects. The sunsets are as beautiful as
anything you'd see if you stepped outside tonight around 8:30, and
the underwater scenes look like they were swiped from ``National
Geographic.''
</P>
<P>
   Sega must have spent some time checking out the fish at local
aquariums, because the ones here, as the game box touts, react and
move about like real fish _ a nice touch to an already impressive
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seaman'' (Sega for Dreamcast, ages 13 and up): OK, I'm gonna
try to explain this without confusing you. Or me. This is a title
to be used with Sega's Visual Memory Unit and Dreamcast Internet
Web site. If you don't have _ or want _ either one of those
add-ons, don't even mess with this.
</P>
<P>
   If you do, this could be a bit fun. Players basically raise an
aquarium fish, which, using a special microphone that comes with
the game and Sega's Web site, you can control, command and even
groom. It's like an interactive Chia Pet.
</P>
<P>
   But it does have a mind of its own; the fish often smarts off
and makes mildly suggestive comments, which will undoubtedly irk
parents. After a while, saying ``turn left,'' ``go right,'' and
watching the fish turn left and go right, gets a little old, so
there's not much of a repeat-play factor. If only it would go eat
Ecco, that would be cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Flintstones Bedrock Bowling'' (WB for PlayStation, all
ages): This is like a music CD that goes straight to the cut-out
bin or a movie that goes straight to video, it's so seemingly lame.
Catch it somewhere for $20, though, and it's not a bad time-killer.
</P>
<P>
   The game premise is self-explanatory: Pick your fave 'stoner and
hit the lanes. It's easy, brainless fun and kinda like listening to
Celine Dion _ you're embarrassed to, but you do anyway.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
