<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-WOODSTOCK-ART-NYT &LR;      08-29 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODSTOCK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTS CENTER, AIDED BY ALBANY, IS TO RISE ON WOODSTOCK FESTIVAL
SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WINNIE HU    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki said Monday that the
state would help finance plans for a new performing arts and music
center on the site of the original Woodstock festival in Bethel,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki was to appear Tuesday with the developer, Alan Gerry, at
the festival site to unveil a proposal for the $40 million center,
to which the state would contribute $15 million. It would be the
first permanent structure built on the gently sloping hillside that
once served as Max Yasgur's alfalfa field and, more famously, as
the amphitheater for the Aug. 15-17, 1969 festival, a defining
moment for some Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry, 71, who built his television antenna business into one of
the largest cable television operations in the country, bought 37
acres of the Yasgur farm in 1997, and has since spoken of creating
a tourist attraction and shrine to the Sixties counterculture
there.
</P>
<P>
   He said the arts center would stage a variety of theater, dance
and music performances _ from classical to rock _ in a 4,000-seat
indoor theater that could be partly opened to accommodate another
15,000 spectators sitting on the back lawn. He said that ground
would be broken next spring and that the center would open in the
summer of 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel it's one of the few things that Sullivan County has to
offer that has brand recognition and is known worldwide,'' said
Gerry, a lifelong resident of the county who has created a
multimillion-dollar foundation to promote economic and cultural
development there. ``It's a natural franchise and no one can take
it away from us.''
</P>
<P>
   The new arts center, which has not yet been named, is intended
to attract thousands of tourists and help revive the Catskills, a
struggling area whose fortunes have declined along with its grand
resort hotels. In recent years, county officials and residents have
tried to draw weekend visitors and other tourists by supporting
proposals for at least two Indian-run casinos and building a $4
million corporate office park for high-tech and start-up companies.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Monday, Pataki said he hoped the
Woodstock center would evolve into a cultural institution like the
Saratoga Performing Arts Center or Tanglewood in the Berkshire
Mountains of Massachusetts. The $15 million in state money, which
will come from discretionary funds controlled by Pataki and the
Legislature, will be used for the construction of the theater and
for road and land improvements. The state will not have any
ownership of the new project, but invested the money to spur the
sagging economy of the area, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it will be a great facility for the Catskills,''
Pataki said. ``They have always been one of the tourism centers for
New York and they have lost that over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said that as a 23-year-old law student, he had to stay
home to tend his parents' farm while his friends went to the
original Woodstock festival. Since then, he said, he has wanted to
attend a concert there.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of makes up for that,'' he said. ``I wasn't at
Woodstock but I loved the music and it's going to be great to go up
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerry bought the 37 acres for roughly $1 million in 1997, and
later acquired more than 1,300 surrounding acres for an undisclosed
price. Gerry said the idea of preserving the site came from his
daughter, Robyn, who makes a pilgrimage there every summer.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry staged two festivals at the site in 1998 and 1999 by
building a temporary metal stage and importing lights and sewage
lines. More than 60,000 people went to the first concert, which
included performers like Joni Mitchell and Pete Townsend, and
35,000 more attended the following year to see Britney Spears and
other stars. They paid $19 to $65 for tickets, but Gerry said the
concerts lost money.
</P>
<P>
   Many Sullivan county officials and residents praised the planned
Woodstock center Monday. Harvey Smith, the acting county manager,
said it would bring a needed influx of customers for nearby hotels,
restaurants, and stores, and also contribute to an active arts
community that already stages classical music concerts and operas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Smith said, the county is used to coping with large
crowds because of its past as a resort area. ``As someone said to
me, ``Happiness is a traffic jam,'' Smith said. ``I think there's
enough infrastructure here for what's planned and I'm sure there
will be enhancements. We are absolutely looking forward to this
kind of economic activity. It's clean, and very positive.''
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the hoped-for economic benefits, the Woodstock center
seeks to transform what was once a makeshift concert ground into a
place where people can bring their families, relive their memories,
or simply find out what the fuss was all about. Even today, many
people still walk through the meadows to a monument that
commemorates the 1969 Woodstock festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come from all over the world,'' Gerry said. ``This site
is on so many people's calendars that it's become a historic
site.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
