<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE-EATING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLES, THE EUREKA MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By   MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I suppose you could call it an apple epiphany. I was trying a
recipe that called for apples, apple butter and apple cider because
it's that time of year: the early apples are turning up at roadside
stands and farmers' markets. Having grown bored with apples from
storage by the end of winter, I look at these with the pleasure
associated with the first strawberry of spring or the first peach
of summer.
</P>
<P>
   My epiphany came with the first bite of this apple-three-ways
dish of pork, mustard, onions and red wine. There is no cream, no
butter and only a modest amount of oil, but it tasted surprisingly
satisfying. It never occurred to me that something rich was
missing, because it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   For most cooks, it is easiest to reach for butter and cream, but
for certain dishes, those that become more interesting when subtle
flavoring is added, an apple is by far the better choice.
</P>
<P>
   This discovery made me feel even more kindly toward apples,
which otherwise offer modest nutritional value. They have small
amounts of vitamins A and C, selenium and potassium, and are a
reasonable source of fiber. At least for now. One day scientists
may learn that apples are a storehouse of micronutrients that make
them a worthy competitor of the cantaloupe. Think of what they now
know about ketchup and how its cooked tomatoes are loaded with
lycopene, a phytochemical that appears to reduce the risk of
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But neither ketchup nor cantaloupe provides the ingredients
often missing in dishes low in fat and calories: rich taste.
</P>
<P>
   The pork with three forms of apple had intensity, but also
subtlety because the sweetness was balanced by the wine and
mustard. It is included in Alison Becker Hurt's book, ``Kitchen
Suppers'' (Doubleday, 1999). For the most part, the recipes are not
from her well-known restaurants, Alison on Dominick in New York or
Alison by the Beach in Bridgehampton. They are ones she cooks at
home, and while the book hardly features low-fat or low-calorie
dishes, she never goes overboard on fat.
</P>
<P>
   The way apples add richness was confirmed by another dish I
tried, a squash soup thickened with potatoes and seasoned with
roasted carrots and onions, garlic and thyme. It has wonderful
earth tones, its richness coming from its complexity. The soup,
from ``Out of the Earth'' by Kerry Downey Romaniello (Spinner
Publications, 1999), is as satisfying as anything laced with cream.
</P>
<P>
   Cooking apples with the skin on provides more body in dishes
where richness and heartiness are the object. Apples are not
interchangeable. For the pork, I would choose tart-sweet apples,
like Macintosh, Gravenstein or even Granny Smith, types that hold
their shape and do not dissolve into sauce. Stay away from
Delicious. For the soup, any apple with a nice balance of sweet and
tart works well, like a Paula Red, a variety that has just started
appearing.
</P>
<P>
   Right now you can compare the flavor and texture of fresh
apples. There were 10 varieties where I shopped last week. But
fresh apples do not have a long season. Before you know it, your
apples will be from storage, which makes them mealy, fit only for
sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Both the soup and the pork reflect the change in seasons, with
cooler nights when warm savory food seems just right.
</P>
<P>
   CREAMY SQUASH SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Out of the Earth'' by Kerry Downey Romaniello
(Spinner Publications, 1999)
</P>
<P>
   Time : 1 hour 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds butternut, buttercup, Delicata or Hubbard squash,
halved and seeded
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 carrots, peeled
</P>
<P>
   2 medium onions, halved but not peeled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and fresh black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, peeled
</P>
<P>
   4 apples, cored but not peeled, cut in {-inch chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 pound red or white potatoes, peeled, cut in {-inch-thick
slices
</P>
<P>
   2 large sprigs thyme, plus extra for garnish
</P>
<P>
   2 quarts chicken or vegetable stock.
</P>
</TEXT>
