<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5462 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-PRISONER-1STLD     08-29 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRISONER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIFE OF AMERICAN HELD BY RUSSIANS FOR ESPIONAGE FEARS FOR HIS
HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (SUBS 12th graf, beginning XXX Russian press XXX, to remove
`known') 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The wife of a an American who has been in jail here for
five months on espionage charges came here Tuesday with her
congressman to call on the Russian government to allow Western
doctors to examine her 54-year-old husband, who has bone cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Cheri Pope looked shaken and fatigued after visiting Moscow's
Lefortovo Prison on Tuesday, where her husband, Edmond, a former
naval intelligence officer, has been incarcerated since early
April. He was arrested for supposedly trying to buy classified
plans for a high-technology Russian torpedo system.
</P>
<P>
   Some Russian press reports have identified the torpedo
propulsion system, known as the Squall, as the same one carried
aboard the nuclear submarine Kursk, which sank in the Barents Sea
on Aug. 12, killing all 118 crewmen aboard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seeing my husband and having to leave him there was extremely
difficult,'' Mrs. Pope said at a news conference, dressed in a gray
suit and speaking in subdued and emotional tones. ``And now I have
to go back to my room and call his mother and father and our sons
and tell them that Ed is not doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John E. Petersen, R-Pa., who accompanied her, was more
blunt. ``If his cancer has returned and we do not catch it soon,
Edmond Pope will die.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials say Edmond Pope has been examined 10 times
since April and is not facing any imminent health threat.
``Allegations about the deteriorating mental and physical condition
of the U.S. citizen spread by U.S. representatives are
groundless,'' the Federal Security Service said on Friday. Last
week, a Russian court denied Pope's request to be released to
receive medical treatment while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. embassy officials have been allowed to visit Pope 11 times,
and Tuesday's visit was Mrs. Pope's second. She said her husband is
being kept in a cell with five Russian prisoners, who all share a
sink and toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson castigated Russian authorities for arresting Pope over
the attempted purchase of ``10-year-old'' torpedo technology that
the Russian government openly sells to foreign governments, most
recently to Canada, he asserted. He asked that all details of the
charges against Pope be made public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in America knows that Ed Pope is not a spy,''
Peterson said, ``He is an independent businessman who has been
working with the Russians for five to six years'' to develop and
sell high-technology products. He warned that Pope's incarceration
spelled ``a very bad day for the future of American-Russian
business relations.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department officials in Washington have said that
President Clinton raised the plight of Pope in a telephone call to
President Vladimir Putin during the frantic rescue operation for
the Kursk. Tuesday, Peterson said that Clinton and Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright have been raising the issue of Pope's
``unfair imprisonment'' and asking that his case be resolved ``each
time they meet with a Russian official.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Russia's intelligence service, reached by
telephone, said the agency would not comment Tuesday on the charges
against Pope. Nor would a spokesman say when a trial might take
place.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Russian press accounts, quoting intelligence officials here, say
that Pope was arrested as he was handing over $30,000 to a
professor from Bauman State Technical University, Anatoly Babkin,
in order to purchase the plans for the high-speed Russian torpedo
system. Babkin is a specialist in torpedo development and design.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some reports said that Babkin, 70, was subsequently released
because of his advanced age and a heart condition, raising the
question of how seriously Russia's security services are taking his
offense, normally treated as an act of treason.
</P>
<P>
   The Squall torpedo, according to a report from the Russian
institute that designed it, was developed over two decades as a
``versatile'' design that could be fitted with various warheads and
rocket motors depending on its mission. Its versatility included
configurations for underwater attacks, or for firing over the
horizon at surface ships or distant submarine targets.
</P>
<P>
   Its most remarkable feature is its speed, more than 220 miles an
hour in its own gas bubble, making it the fastest torpedo in the
world, according to an article by Valery Kulbitsky, chief designer
of the Russian Research Institute of Marine Technology.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Navy navy officials have reportedly shown a great deal of
interest in the Squall system, and two U.S. submarines, one of them
the Memphis, were monitoring the military exercises during which
Kursk was slated to fire a variety of weapons. Two senior Russian
officials connected with the investigation into the Kursk sinking
have asserted that Kursk was carrying an experimental torpedo and
that an accident involving the weapon or its engine could have
contributed to the disaster.
</P>
<P>
   A source at the Russian navy headquarters told the news agency
Interfax on Tuesday that navy officials have not ruled out a
torpedo explosion as a cause of the Kursk's sinking, along with
some collision that triggered the explosion.
</P>
<P>
   But Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said Tuesday that
``There were no new torpedoes on the submarine.'' He said Kursk,
during the military exercises, had launched a type of torpedo that
had been used for 20 years, but he added that some new features had
been added to the torpedo, which he identified as ``a new
accumulator unit with a large resource.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
