<SLUG> BC-MOMS-BACK-AT-WORK-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN WELCOMED BACK TO CAREER PATH 
</HEADLINE>
   By MELINDA LIGOS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Gwen Hahn, a stay-at-home mother, decided this summer that
it was time to re-enter the work force, she braced herself for
rejection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worried that employers might not take me seriously,'' said
Hahn, who had quit her job as a catering manager for a Phoenix
hotel six years ago to spend more time with her three children.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hahn received a job offer even before she had a chance
to send out her resume. Her boss-to-be, Nancy Nachman, president of
a firm in Scottsdale, Ariz., that plans meetings for companies, was
a guest at a party she held and was immediately taken with her
people skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw Gwen, I knew that she was a natural for the
job,'' Nachman said. Not long after, she offered Hahn a position as
a planner with the company, the Meetings Concierge, starting in
early September, and Hahn accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, housewives with resume gaps spanning several
years faced tough slogging in the job market. No more. In today's
full-employment economy, employers are actively wooing women who
held jobs once upon a time and finding in them a rich new source of
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that employers are taking a second look at
women who are re-entering the work force.'' said Marcia Brumit
Kropf, vice president for research and information services for
Catalyst, a New York research group that studies women's issues.
``Today's job market is so tight that employers are opening their
mind to nontraditional candidates. If a woman has talent and a good
track record, a gap in her resume is no longer as relevant.''
</P>
<P>
   And it does not seem to matter if the gap is more a chasm.
Katherine Goldman quit her job as creative director for an
advertising agency in Princeton, N.J., after her first child was
born more than 14 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always kept my eyes and ears open,'' said Goldman, who spent
the next 11 years doing freelance work for ad agencies while caring
for her two children, who are now teen-agers. When Goldman decided
last year to go back to work full time, she called a contact at
Jack Morton Worldwide, a branding communications firm.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a returning mother, I thought I might have to explain
myself,'' she said. ``Instead, after I told him that I'd like to
work for him, he said, `Wow, that's great, you're hired.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Kuker, Goldman's boss, says the hot economy has forced
her company's executives to soften their old hiring requirements.
``We're a niche market without a large employee pool, so we're
bringing in applicants who on paper might not look like the ideal
candidate, but who might have just the skills we're looking for,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And, as was the case with Hahn, those skills went beyond
workplace credentials and centered on personality. The company was
attracted by her maturity and confidence as well as her broad
background in writing and advertising, Kuker said. ``She was
bringing something totally different to the table that somebody who
had just gotten out of school, or maybe had one job, wouldn't
have,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So eager are some employers to tap into the stay-at-home-mom
pool that many are courting them with flexible-work arrangements,
day care and other perks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, I'm seeing a few law firms offer four-day
workweeks to working mothers,'' said Jillian Winoker, director of
associate placements for Corrao Miller Rush &AMP; Wiesenthal, a New
York employment firm. ``You would never have seen that in the legal
profession five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not just law firms. In 1998, Ernst &AMP; Young, the big
accounting firm, created a host of flexible work arrangements, from
compressed work schedules and telecommuting to job sharing. ``Women
returning to the work force are typically highly skilled, and we
have to be creative in attracting them,'' said Deborah Holmes,
national director of the firm's office of retention.
</P>
<P>
   One woman who was attracted was Sharon Kurtz, now a manager of
internal audit services for the firm. Kurtz had previously worked
for Ernst &AMP; Young until her second child was born in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to apply for a second job there in March 1999, after
taking a break to spend time with her children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left, the climate for working mothers was totally
different,'' said Kurtz, who now works a three-day week. ``I would
leave after a nine-hour day, and a co-worker would say, `Oh,
half-day today?'''
</P>
<P>
   Now, Kurtz said, so many employees have flexible arrangements
that nobody questions that she works three days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason women are finding it easier to re-enter the work
force is that they are becoming more adept at keeping their foot in
the door while they are gone. Although they are often busy raising
children, some women make a point of updating their skills, taking
classes and networking with peers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Consider Cindy Bateman, a mother of two from Seattle. Soon after
Bateman left her position as a vice president at the Pacific
National Bank in Newport Beach, Calif., in December 1998, to spend
more time with her children, she enrolled in an MBA program at the
University of Washington. She also accepted a position as a public
affairs officer for an association for women who work in the
financial industry. She plans to resume working in another year,
when her younger child starts school and she has earned her
master's degree.
</P>
<P>
   Though by then she will have been out of the work force for
about three years, she is confident she will find work as a senior
bank manager. ``I'm already getting calls from prospective
employers,'' Bateman said. ``I've gotten so much positive feedback
that I hadn't really considered that there was any difference
between me and a job candidate who hadn't taken time off.''
</P>
<P>
   The journey back to the office is not all smooth sailing, of
course. Hahn, for example, worries about whether her computer
skills are up to speed. Even though her husband is coaching her,
she said, ``It's kind of intimidating; in my old job, I had a
support staff to do this kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the inevitable culture shock. Goldman said
reporting to people who are younger than she is could be tough.
</P>
<P>
   But her biggest struggle, she said, has been making her family
accustomed to the fact that she is working again and to share
household chores like making dinner and doing the laundry. ``We're
having to renegotiate roles,'' she said. `My working is something
we're all still getting used to.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
