<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5464 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-29 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HINES-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ROUTINE
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    JOE'S DEEP FAITH: ALLURING UP TO A POINT
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By CRAGG HINES
 &HT;    
 &HT;    c.2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   As an integral part of his personal life and a guiding force in
his political life, Joe Lieberman's deep religious conviction is
one of his most appealing aspects. As a continuing theme in
Lieberman's national campaign, it is quickly losing its charm.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman moved up to the line and probably crossed it in
remarks Sunday in Detroit, as he began his first solo campaign
swing as the Democratic vice-presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   As a people we need to reaffirm our faith and renew the
dedication of our nation and ourselves to God and God's purpose,
Lieberman said at Fellowship Chapel.
</P>
<P>
   As true as that may be, I don't want a candidate for national
office _ or, for that matter, any political post _ to be the one to
tell me about it.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman tried to sugarcoat his message, even resorting to the
favorite dodge of the current breed of Christian theocrats: The
Constitution guarantees freedom of religion, not freedom from
religion.
</P>
<P>
   Then in a phrase sure to send Pat Robertson and Jerry Falwell
into an approving swoon, Lieberman added: There must be and can be
a constitutional place for faith in our public life.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is that neither Lieberman nor any of the other
adherents of this sweet-sounding line have yet illustrated how to
dissect sectarian religion from faith so that it passes
constitutional muster. George W. Bush and Al Gore both made a stab
at it earlier in the campaign, with calls for government assistance
that would be administered through ``faith-based institutions,''
and failed.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is, of course, not the first candidate to play the
religious card so vigorously. Bush, who once implied that Jews
could not go to heaven, has named Jesus as his favorite political
philosopher and said that in making tough decisions he asks
himself, ``What would Jesus do?''
</P>
<P>
   I will admit to some hesitancy in writing about this issue.
</P>
<P>
   When I first read the reports of Lieberman's weekend remarks, I
cringed. It was the same reaction I had to some of Lieberman's
expressions of religiosity at the time of his selection as Gore's
running mate.
</P>
<P>
   If a conservative Southern Baptist had said the same things,
eyebrows and then voices would have been raised in correctly
questioning such an emphasis by a national candidate on religious
themes.
</P>
<P>
   I fretted over the issue and then put it aside as a column
topic, deciding that Lieberman was new enough at the national game
and deserved to be cut some slack. And did a columnist who happens
to be a Christian have the right to tell the first Jewish candidate
on either major national ticket to can the God shtick?
</P>
<P>
   My reservations, however, receded when a statement from leaders
of the Anti-Defamation League expressed exactly what I had felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates should feel comfortable explaining their religious
convictions to voters,'' said Howard P. Berkowitz, ADL national
chairman, and Abraham H. Foxman, ADL national director. ``At the
same time, however, we believe there is a point at which an
emphasis on religion in a political campaign becomes inappropriate
and even unsettling in a religiously diverse society such as
ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Their statement, an open entreaty to Lieberman to cool it, was
prompted by the senator's remarks in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Language such as this risks alienating the American people,''
the ADL leaders said. ``We feel very strongly ... that appealing
along religious lines, on belief in God, is contrary to the
American ideal. The First Amendment requires that government
neither support one religion over another nor the religious over
the non-religious.''
</P>
<P>
   I was comforted, not to say emboldened, by their statement. The
ADL has fought anti-Semitism and promoted tolerance in this country
for almost a century, and I am happy to be in its company.
</P>
<P>
   The ADL and I apparently are not alone in feeling uneasy about
Lieberman's approach. A Gallup poll taken last Thursday-Sunday
suggests Americans are reluctant to mix religion and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Although 57 percent of Americans say religion plays a very
important role in their life, only a third say their religious
beliefs and faith will be important in deciding their vote for
president this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman should show his deep faith through his life and
career, not in his speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Hines is a Houston Chronicle columnist based in Washington, D.C.
(cragg.hineschron.com)
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
