u i BC-PHILIPPINES-KIDNAP-1S     08-29 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-KIDNAP-1STLD-WRITETHRU-505&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINES REBELS SAY THEY HAVE KIDNAPPED AMERICAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (Inserts 2 new grafs set off by double parentheses. Please change
double parentheses to single brackets) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Muslim rebels who thrive on kidnapping
seized an American on a remote Philippine island Tuesday and
threatened to kill him if the United States does not meet
unspecified demands.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf rebels, who have been holding a group of
Europeans, South Africans and Asians for four months, said in a
radio broadcast that ``we have been trying very hard to get an
American.''
</P>
<P>
   They identified him as Jeffrey Craig Schilling, 24, asserted he
was an agent for the CIA and said, ``We will not hesitate to
execute this American guy if the Philippine government and the
United States will not listen to our demands.''
</P>
<P>
   They said they would announce their demands within three days.
</P>
<P>
   ((In Washington, the State Department demanded Schilling's &UR; 3 &LR; 
unconditional release. ``The United States does not make deals with
terrorists and this organization,'' said the department spokesman,
Philip Reeker. &UR; 4 &LR; ``The Abu Sayyaf &UR; 2 &LR;  group is an organization which
is listed in our patterns of global terrorism as one of the radical
Islamic separatist groups operating in the southern Philippines.''
.
</P>
<P>
   He could not say whether Schilling &UR; 3 &LR;  was employed by the U.S.
States government. Reuters quoted an administration official as
denying that Schilling &UR; 3 &LR;  worked for the CIA ``To my knowledge he
is not a U.S. government employee,'' he said.))
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the group executed two Filipino hostages when
one of their demands went unfulfilled. They wanted Washington to
release several Arab terrorists imprisoned in the United States
after the bombing of New York's World Trade Center in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine government confirmed the abduction, saying that
an envoy had seen Schilling being held in an Abu Sayyaf camp. The
U.S. embassy in Manila said it was sending six officials to
Zamboanga, the nearest city, where Schilling had been living for
several months with his fiancee, a Philippine citizen.
</P>
<P>
   The abduction is the latest twist in a kidnapping spree that
started on April 23 when Abu Sayyaf gunmen abducted 21 mostly
Western hostages from a diving resort on a nearby Malaysian island.
Since then, several hostages have been freed and several more have
been seized. Before Schilling's abduction, the gunmen were holding
six Westerners and a dozen Filipinos.
</P>
<P>
   Six other Westerners were freed on Sunday and Monday in exchange
for reported payments of $1 million each. Libya acted as go-between
in these releases, raising the possibility that the United States
might find itself turning to Libya for help in freeing Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   A Libyan official said Tuesday his nation would be happy to help
if asked.
</P>
<P>
   In the radio interview, the Abu Sayyaf spokesman, Abu Sabaya,
suggested that the ransom for an American should be 10 times as
much as for a European.
</P>
<P>
   If they decide to kill Schilling, he said, ``Then next week we
will get another hostage and do the same thing to him. The
Americans may think we are afraid of them, but we are really
determined to get an American.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its negotiations for the Western hostages, the Philippine
government has relied on intermediaries from Libya, which for years
has had close relations with Muslim separatist fighters in the
southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators have suggested that Libya's mediating role _
including a total ransom payment that has been estimated to be as
high as $25 million in ``development aid'' _ is an attempt to
burnish its international image.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and others have blamed the Libyan leader,
Moammar Gadhafi, for a number of terrorist acts around the world.
Two Libyans are now on trial in the bombing in 1988 of a Pan Am
jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland, that killed 277 people.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time Schilling was being kidnapped, the six
recently freed hostages were arriving to a festive welcome in the
Libyan capital, Tripoli, after being flown there on a Libyan
airliner. The freed hostages, from France, Germany, South Africa
and Lebanon, were to be sent home later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't forget the name that delivered you from the humiliation
of captivity; that name is Moammar Gadhafi,'' a Libyan official
said in a televised speech at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   A Libyan foreign ministry official, speaking on Qatar's
satellite television station, said his nation would try to help win
Schilling's release if asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have to carry out a role to save the life of a human
being, whether he is an American or European, we will not hesitate
to help,'' said the official, Hassounah el-Shawish.
</P>
<P>
   In the Philippines on Tuesday, immigration authorities provided
a copy of Schilling's passport to reporters. It said he was born in
Minnesota on Feb. 4, 1976 and had entered the Philippines on March
8, extending his visitor's visa twice.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Sayyaf, which is a small splinter group from a long-running
Muslim separatist insurgency in the southern Philippines, has
focused more on the business of kidnapping than on ideological
warfare. Kidnapping is so common in the area that it has been
somewhat formalized, with the going rate for ransoms at about
$5,000.
</P>
<P>
   With the kidnappings of the Western vacationers in April, the
island of Jolo became flooded with unheard-of amounts of money. Two
of the bandits were arrested last week when they went to a small
local bank and tried to change $240,000 into Philippine pesos.
</P>
<P>
   However, Abu Sayyaf, small as it is, is broken into several
factions. Philippine officials say that the gunmen's squabbles over
tactics and over the division of ransom money have complicated
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Philippine officials have also complicated negotiations on some
occasions with contradictory or threatening public statements. The
belligerence of some of the statements contrasts with the
helplessness of the government in dealing with kidnappers who have
in the past tortured and executed their hostages.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the spokesman for President Joseph Estrada said the
kidnappers had only made matters worse for themselves by seizing an
American.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to galvanize international action against
them,'' said the spokesman, Ricardo Puno. ``The world will unite in
the realization of what a big problem the Abu Sayyaf poses.''
</P>
</TEXT>
