<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m
</P>
<P>
   STATEOFSOUTH _ CHAPEL HILL, N.C. - A new report analyzing the
South recommends a politically dicey approach to spreading
prosperity across the region: Nurturing the already-booming New
Economy cities, such as Atlanta and Raleigh-Durham-Chapel Hill,
because their prosperity ripples to outlying communities. For
decades, the notion of government and business nurturing its strong
cities has been a sore spot among rural area and their politicians.
But noting that ``the challenge before Southerners is at once
sweeping and exhilarating,'' MDC says, ``It is to ensure that the
region's prospering places and people continue to thrive, while
helping the people and places that are falling further behind gain
the capacity to adapt and flourish in a rapidly changing economy.''
(Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   LABOR _ WASHINGTON _ On Labor Day 1900, the typical American
wage earner was a hardened working man, accustomed to toiling 10
hours a day, six days a week on the farm or in the factory. Still,
optimism was rampant as new technologies stirred hopes for better
days. Electric lights, telephones, trolley cars and
</P>
<P>
   even automobiles were appearing, giving rise to the belief that
work soon would be easier. Those 1900 dreams have become our
reality. On Labor Day 2000, U.S. workers are healthier, safer and
have more buying power than at any time in history. (Geewax, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With (For Cox papers) LABOR-GRAPHIC _ A 4-column PageSpeed
graphic by CoxNet available only on the budget tool.
