<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAMMERING ON CHILDREN'S HEALTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, turning his focus to children's health, says it is
``put up or shut up time'' for George W. Bush to begin dealing with
the specifics of campaign issues. ``The time for generalities
without specifics I think is just about over,'' Gore told
reporters. He said he was largely at a loss to evaluate Bush's
proposals since they lack details. ``I don't really know how they
make it all add up,'' he said. The Bush campaign said that kind of
talk is ``not very presidential.'' Gore plugged away again Tuesday,
in Albuquerque, N.M., for his proposed $100 billion expansion of
child health insurance. Political strategists say that issue can be
used to target Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING EDUCATION ATTACK TO SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did after his 18-point defeat by John McCain in New
Hampshire in February, George W. Bush responded to his recent sag
in the polls with a sharp attack on Al Gore, unleashing sharp
criticism on education. Bush accused Gore of offering a plan ``with
an illusion of accountability,'' presiding over a ``national
tragedy'' in reading, and of being ``locked in old ways.'' Bush was
holding an education discussion Tuesday at a middle school in
Portland, Maine. Today he is scheduled to hold another education
discussion at a high school in Hampton, N.H. In between, he was to
attend a $5,000-a-couple fund-raiser for the state Republican Party
in Rye, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER AND RELIGIOUS VALUES
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is promoting popular conservative themes _
character-building and a strong defense _ on a three-day tour
through Missouri, Mississippi, Georgia, North Carolina and Florida.
He told a gathering of Christian athletes in Kansas City, Mo.,
today that teaching children about character is as important as
showing them how to read and write. Cheney shared the podium with
members of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes, a national group
that encourages students and coaches to practice Christian values
and influence others to get involved with churches. One student
participant, Erica Garris, quoted scripture and told the gathering,
``I stand here today professing God as my savior.''
</P>
<P>
   A SCOLDING ON RELIGIOUS OVEREMPHASIS
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about his recent statements on the campaign trail, the
Anti-Defamation League called on Joe Lieberman to refrain from
overt expressions of religious values and beliefs, stating that
``appealing to voters along religious lines is contrary to the
American ideal.'' Said a statement from Howard Berkowitz and
Abraham Foxman of the ADL: ``Candidates should feel comfortable
explaining their religious convictions to voters. At the same time,
however, we believe there is a point at which an emphasis on
religion in a political campaign becomes inappropriate and even
unsettling in a religiously diverse society such as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   APPLYING PRESSURE FOR DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign chairman tried today to increase pressure on
George W. Bush to accept three nationally televised, prime-time
debates in October, saying they would ``give the greatest number of
voters the chance to hear the candidates directly.'' Bush has
agreed to three presidential debates without specifying which ones.
Bush responded, ``I would welcome all three being in prime time,''
but his campaign said that didn't necessarily mean he would accept
any of the debate commission's proposed dates or formats. Bush has
said he prefers relatively informal debates, such as a session
during the primaries when the participants were seated around a
table with CNN's Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   TWO NEW POLLS SHOW A TIE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore are locked in a dead heat in two new
presidential polls, evidence that Gore is holding his
post-convention poll bounce. The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of
likely voters showed Bush at 46 percent, Gore at 45 percent, Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party candidate
Pat Buchanan at 1 percent. A poll by ICR of Media, Pa. showed Gore
at 44 percent and Bush at 41 percent among registered voters. Both
polls had error margins of 4 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   TAX ISSUE JUST NOT CUTTING IT
</P>
<P>
   Even as George W. Bush pursues his call for a broad federal tax
cut, a new ABCNEWS.com poll shows that three-quarters of Americans
express other priorities for the budget surplus. Twenty-five
percent give top priority to cutting income taxes, up 7 points
since July. But many more _ 42 percent _ prefer to use the surplus
to strengthen Social Security, 16 percent favor debt reduction, and
14 percent give priority to ``other domestic programs.'' When those
``other programs'' are specified as education and health care,
according to the poll (3 percentage point margin of error), support
for that spending rises and support for a tax cut shrinks to 16
percent.
</P>
<P>
   NAMING NAMES IN DRUG COMPANY ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore escalated his attacks against the pharmaceutical
industry, criticizing two drug companies by name and calling for
greater competition in the industry. Gore singled out
Schering-Plough, which makes Claritin, and American Home Products,
the parent company of Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories, which makes
Lodine. In the case of Claritin, Gore said the manufacturer spent
more money on advertising than on research. And in the case of
Lodine, an arthritis medicine prescribed for both people and pets,
he said American Home Products charged pharmacies more than
veterinarians.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA NOW ONE OF THOSE BATTLEGROUND STATES
</P>
<P>
   The State Department's tough talk against Cuba _ publicly
accusing the communist regime of denying exit permits to Cubans
holding U.S. visas _ came as Al Gore stepped up his efforts to win
Florida, an electoral powerhouse that is home to thousands of
Cuban-American voters. Florida is considered crucial to George W.
Bush's hopes of winning the White House, but Gore appears to be
running a surprisingly strong campaign in the state where Bush's
brother, Jeb, is governor. ``Florida is in play. We're all
surprised,'' said Jim Kane of Florida Voter, a nonpartisan polling
organization.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY TRAIL FOLLOWED TO 9 STATES
</P>
<P>
   Republican Party officials pumped $6.1 million into nine states
last month, providing an early road map of where they plan to
compete this fall. The list includes Pennsylvania, Illinois,
Michigan, Missouri, Ohio, California, Oregon and Washington.
Topping the list was Florida, where the national GOP sent more than
$1 million to the state party last month. ``None of the states are
any surprise,'' said Republican political consultant Eddie Mahe.
``Those are the same states (both candidates) have been visiting
since Day One.''
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN CHARGED WITH PLAGIARISM
</P>
<P>
   A Southern Methodist University economics professor has sued Pat
Buchanan and his publisher, Little Brown &AMP; Co., for copyright
infringement. A lawsuit filed in federal court by Ravendra Batra
alleges that Buchanan's 1998 book, ``The Great Betrayal,''
plagiarized parts of Batra's books, including charts and graphs.
Buchanan's book argues against globalization of economies, and he
blasts the major political parties for seeking trade treaties that
he believes hurt American workers and undermine the nation's
sovereignty. Batra appeared on the CNN news program ``Crossfire''
in the early 1990s when Buchanan was co-host.
</P>
<P>
   WEIGHING REFORM IN THREE STATES
</P>
<P>
   California, Oregon and Missouri will offer voters the chance in
November to overhaul their campaign finance laws. California's
Proposition 34 would limit political donations from most sources at
$20,000 for gubernatorial candidates, $5,000 for other statewide
candidates and $3,000 for legislative candidates. Initiatives in
Missouri and Oregon would finance campaigns with taxpayer money,
putting those states in the forefront of the campaign-finance
reform movement. California, on the other hand, is considering the
kinds of donation caps that 44 states already have. In California
now, individuals, corporations and other special interests can
donate as much as they want.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA CLUB SPENDING IN 12 RACES
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Club is returning to the airwaves with $8 million in
TV and radio ads praising a few Republicans and many more
Democrats. Positive ads will air about Democratic Reps. Lane Evans
of Illinois; Mark Udall of Colorado; Joseph Hoeffel of
Pennsylvania; Rush Holt of New Jersey; and Brian Baird, Jay Inslee
and Adam Smith of Washington state; Republican Rep. Jim Leach of
Iowa; and Republican Sens. Jim Jeffords of Vermont and William Roth
of Delaware. Critical ads are airing against two Republicans: Sen.
Slade Gorton of Washington state and former Virginia Gov. George
Allen, a Senate hopeful running against Democratic Sen. Charles
Robb.
</P>
<P>
   THE CASE OF THE STOLEN SIGNATURES
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Nader barely met the deadline for filing to get on
Wyoming's general election ballot, but the theft of nearly 650
petition signatures on his behalf is casting doubt on whether his
name will appear at all. Someone walked off with a clipboard full
of signatures at restaurant in Laramie last week, according to
Nader volunteer Roberta Harper-McIntosh. Supporters turned in about
4,000 signatures to state election officials just one minute before
Monday night's filing deadline, but they had hoped to deliver
between 5,000 and 6,000 _ just in case.
</P>
<P>
   UNION MOBILIZATION IN KENTUCKY
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky, although not as heavily organized as some other
states, is fertile ground for labor this year. One of the most
competitive races in the nation has Democrat Scotty Baesler trying
to win back his House seat from Republican Rep. Ernie Fletcher.
Baesler lost the seat in 1998 when he ran unsuccessfully for the
Senate. GOP Reps. Anne Northup and Edward Whitfield, whose
districts have sizable union populations, also face spirited
challenges. Bill Londrigan, head of the Kentucky AFL-CIO, is well
aware that the three races could help decide who controls the House
next year.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERN SENATE STRATEGY
</P>
<P>
   In Florida's Senate contest, state Insurance Commissioner Bill
Nelson, a Democrat, and Rep. Bill McCollum, a Republican, are
locked in a race to succeed retiring Republican Sen. Connie Mack
that is critical to Democrats' uphill fight to win control of the
Senate. But the race is more than that. Coupled with the Democrats'
likely recovery of a Senate seat in Georgia _ although they might
lose one in Virginia _ the Florida race could be an important
marker in the evolution of two-party politics in the South.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNING ON WITH A MORE VIABLE CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   Tim Goeglein, who described his two-year stint as spokesman for
conservative activist and unsuccessful presidential candidate Gary
Bauer as ``two really terrific years,'' is joining George W. Bush's
campaign Friday. Goeglein, in an e-mail to correspondents covering
the Republican campaign, said that he will be working as part of
the Bush-Cheney communications team.
</P>
<P>
   `BASIC POLITICS'
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas, the high-priced screenwriter behind such sexually
charged films as ``Showgirls'' and ``Basic Instinct,'' wants
Hollywood to withhold support from Al Gore because of the
anti-media rhetoric of his running mate, Joe Lieberman. Eszterhas,
whose own work has often been critically panned for its lurid
nature, came out swinging against Gore and Lieberman in a full-page
open letter in the entertainment trade paper Daily Variety. ``No
more Hollywood money for Al Gore,'' Eszterhas admonishes, in the
ad. ``I'm a writer who likes pushing the envelope, and Joe
Lieberman frightens me.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
