<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5485 &Cx1f; tab-z
u t BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-FR     08-29 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICHELIN-ON-TRAVEL-FRENCH-RIVIERA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ART IMITATES LIFE ON THE FRENCH RIVIERA 
</HEADLINE>
  ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material, the fifth destination
column in the MICHELIN ON TRAVEL feature from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by MICHELIN clients. Nonsubscribers can use
this article only by special arrangement with the Syndicate. For
purchase information, see end of text. 
 (ART ADV: A photo and a map of the French Riviera are available on
Newscom or by calling William Gonzalez at 212-499-3355.) 
 By GAIL ZWEIGENTHAL 
 c.2000 Michelin 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hot sun and cobalt blue sea, red cliffs and golden beaches,
peaceful villages and throbbing night clubs _ the French Riviera
beguiles and seduces. It should be no surprise that this stretch of
Mediterranean coast where sea and sky blend with green forests and
silver-gray olive trees has attracted artists for hundreds of
years.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the 19th century, many painters became fascinated
by the clear light of the south of France. Impressionists such as
Berthe Morisot (who settled in Nice), Claude Monet (Antibes) and
Auguste Renoir (Cagnes-sur-Mer) sought to portray the subtle
effects of light on Mediterranean landscapes.
</P>
<P>
   The Pointillist Paul Signac established himself in St.-Tropez,
while Fauvists Raoul Dufy and Henri Matisse settled in Nice. Later,
Marc Chagall found that the light and flowers of Vence stimulated
his multicolored dreams, and Pablo Picasso, while in Antibes,
created joyful works inspired by the marine and mythological life
of the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   Today's traveler can surely see what inspired these artists as
they transmuted the landscape, light, fruits and flowers of this
glorious coast into great works of art.
</P>
<P>
   In retracing the footsteps of these artists, Nice is a good
place to start. Matisse lived here for 37 years and there's a
magical Chagall museum. As a bonus, the culinary specialties of
this seaside resort are some of the tastiest on the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by the cooking of the Ligurian region of Italy as well
by that of nearby Provence, ``la cuisine nicoise'' takes delicious
advantage of the flavorful local olive oil, all manner of fruits
and vegetables and an abundance of Mediterranean fish and
shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow streets of Old Nice overflow with opportunities to
try such delicacies as ``pissaladiere,'' an onion tart topped with
a rich anchovy sauce and garnished with black olives, and the famed
``salade nicoise,'' a lively combination of tomatoes,
beans,radishes, peppers, onions and hard-boiled eggs garnished with
anchovy and basil and moistened with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   For a snack to be eaten in the street, there is the chick-pea
flour cake called ``socca,'' often accompanied by a glass of local
wine. And a good lunchtime choice is the ubiquitous ``pan bagnat''
(literally ``soaked bread''), a sandwich of tomatoes, onions,
anchovies and garlic, the bread moist with olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   The glisteningly fresh raw materials of these dishes and more
can be bought _ or simply admired _ in the Cours Saleya market.
Once the elegant promenade of Old Nice, this picturesque quarter is
now lined with shops and restaurants. It is also the site of a
colorful flower market and, on Mondays, an antiques emporium.
</P>
<P>
   Ready for some art? The Musee Marc-Chagall, in the sophisticated
Cimiez Hill area of town, houses the most important permanent
collection of the painter's works. The building was designed
especially to display his 17 ``Biblical Message'' canvasses;
recessed walls and large windows opening onto the bright
Mediterranean light show these masterpieces to their best
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Such subjects as the Creation of Man, the Garden of Eden and the
Song of Songs are treated with Chagall's signature poetic lyricism:
Dreamlike figures drift among glowing colors above the rooftops of
sleepy villages. These intensely spiritual paintings took the
master 13 uninterrupted years to create.
</P>
<P>
   Before checking out the work of Henri Matisse, especially if
it's summer, you might want to stop in one of the ice cream parlors
in the Cours Saleya and do a bit of shopping. Local olive oil is
available at Chez Alziari; eau de Nice (mimosa-scented toilet
water) and many other perfumes can be had at Au Parfum de Grasse,
and Provencal crafts such as whimsically patterned tablecloths and
napkins are available in numerous shops on the streets around the
Baroque Ste.-Reparate Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   During his Fauve period, a reaction against Impressionism, Henri
Matisse attempted through the use of pure and brilliant colors
juxtaposed in simplified forms and perspectives to express not just
the fleeting sensations evoked by nature but his own thoughts and
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   He is represented in Nice by the Musee Matisse, housed in a
splendid patrician villa and dedicated entirely to his work. A
large composition of cutout gouaches, ``Flowers and Fruit,'' the
master's last work (1953), greets visitors at the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 canvasses show his progression from a dark, realistic
style to one influenced by the bright Mediterranean light,
culminating in an explosion of pure and brilliant color. Among the
235 works are sketches for his extraordinary mural, ``The Dance,''
as well as bronze sculptures and silkscreen prints.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Nice is just the beginning of an artistic tour of the
Riviera. Matisse moved on to Vence, where he designed the
magnificent Chapelle du Rosaire. (``Despite its imperfections I
think it is my masterpiece ... the result of a lifetime devoted to
the search for truth.'') Also in Vence is the Fondation Emile
Hugues, which offers exhibitions by 20th-century masters including
Chagall, Dubuffet and Dufy.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's Picasso....
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
