<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5488 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PROSTITUTES-BOOK-REVI     08-29 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROSTITUTES-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE ROYAL FAMILY': THE LIFE, AND ITS DESPAIRING UNIVERSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The royal family of ``The Royal Family'' is a group of women
from San Francisco who are in what is knowingly called ``the
life'': the life of prostitution, mostly, but the attendant lives
of drugs, bohemian despair and middle-class strivings frustrated by
abuse or poverty.
</P>
<P>
   Royal is thus an ironic term, though not entirely, since in the
prolific William T. Vollmann's new novel, the ``whores,'' as he
generally calls the members of the family, are given both humanity
and stature. More important in Vollmann's new novel, other people
who are not in the life pay a kind of fealty to those who are, or
as Vollmann writes in a brief foreword, ``Let this book, like its
characters, be devoted to Addiction, Addicts, Pushers, Prostitutes
and Pimps.''
</P>
<P>
   An immense literary talent is on display as Vollmann fulfills
the mission he declares in those lines. Not for nothing has this
author of books like ``The Rainbow Stories'' (in which prostitutes
also figure prominently) and ``An Afghanistan Picture Show'' been
declared a leading member of a new wave of hip, darkly sexual
novelists who appeal mainly to a jaded, gilded youth.
</P>
<P>
   But in rambling through the luxuriant undergrowth of this new
novel, you do wonder about the purpose to which his talent is being
put. ``The Royal Family,'' which starts out with a brilliant sort
of causticity, demonstrates Vollmann's verbal power and
inventiveness. Yet it is a frustrating, tiresome and conceptually
precious book as well, overwhelmed by logorrhea, a numbing
repetitiveness and an underlying moral vision that, despite the
electrical shock treatment that Vollmann gives it, has been old hat
since the days of William Burroughs.
</P>
<P>
   Vollmann has such a penchant for glittery meta-elaboration, for
relentless, spoofy gamesmanship that he leaves the saturated reader
begging for surcease.
</P>
<P>
   The story of ``The Royal Family'' is relatively simple.
Vollmann's sympathetic main character is Henry Tyler, a San
Francisco private investigator who is in love with Irene, the
Korean wife of his brother, John, a smart, ambitious, unlikable
lawyer. Henry has been hired by an unscrupulous businessman named
Brady to find a certain Queen of the Whores, who is reputed to hold
court among San Francisco prostitutes. When Irene, who gives up
striving to endure her life with the disapproving, coldhearted
John, kills herself, Tyler finds a bitter sort of solace by
entering into ``the life'' himself, as a special friend of the
Queen and her stable of women.
</P>
<P>
   The purpose of this novel is much less to tell a story than to
depict the unconventional moral universe of the royal family, which
exists parallel to that of us more conventional commoners.
Vollmann, whose research among prostitutes from San Francisco to
the south of Thailand has been well reported in the press, has done
ample reporting of his own on the subject for this novel, too, and
his characters, with names like Domino, Strawberry and Chocolate,
are brought vividly and lengthily to life.
</P>
<P>
   Vollmann, who makes occasional appearances in his book, tells
us, for example, that he made Strawberry up ``out of three sad
women I know.'' He provides a witty disquisition on bail and bail
bondsmen drawn from his own reporting. He thoroughly explores the
psychic underworld of pimps and johns and others, like Henry, who
discover within themselves hidden reservoirs of sado-masochism, of
urges to be humiliated and hurt, to descend, in other words, into
luscious degradation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Desperate and confused to the very bottom of his soul, he
struggled among square tomblike openings far-spaced in the yellow
walls of death, wanting to escape back into pure numb death but the
Queen would not let him,'' Vollmann writes of Henry, who becomes a
sort of abused lover of the Queen of the Whores. ``It hurt so much!
Tear-streams gushed like pale urine from his eyes. He was weeping
for Irene and gagging on his own grief.''
</P>
<P>
   So forth at considerable length, for there is nothing
epigrammatic in Vollmann, who seems unable to leave out anything
that he has learned or thought during his researches. ``The Royal
Family,'' which starts out with plenty of narrative intrigue, as
Henry searches for the Queen and thinks of Irene, turns into an
extended series of literary displays by Vollmann.
</P>
<P>
   He gives us portraits drawn from ``the life,'' like that of Dan
Smooth, who fantasizes having sex with children and talks about it
with a kind of jaundiced eloquence. He introduces a lengthy
digression on ``a character without a name'' whose fetish is
retarded women. (``They could be called perpetual children. That
was the usual way to think of them, two-day piglets, puny and
short-furred like monkeys.'' )
</P>
<P>
   He writes a series of chapters, parodies of criminal underworld
fiction, on the ``Feminine Circus,'' a virtual erotic emporium
created by Brady in Las Vegas. (``I'm just amazed no one ever
thought of it before,'' Vollmann has a Las Vegas taxi driver tell
Tyler. ``It sums up the national mood, you could almost say. It's
brilliant. It's as real as you want it to be.'')
</P>
<P>
   All along, Vollmann bears us aloft on the swelling currents of
his prose, which is psychedelic, hallucinatory, slyly
self-referential and confiding. It creates a bond of mutual
knowingness and sophistication between writer and reader, who
become brothers and sisters in this extended appreciation of the
perverse side of human nature, refusing ever to be so hokey as to
actually be shocked.
</P>
<P>
   Is Vollmann daring, as the dust jacket contends? Given how
fashionable it is to be jadedly amoral in fiction today, to be
transgressive (a word often used to describe Vollmann), ``The Royal
Family'' is probably less daring than it is chic, with the author
not so much creating a new sensibility as catering to an
established, vicarious, middle-class bohemianism spiced by
recreational drugs.
</P>
<P>
   His novel is in many ways extraordinary, and I will always be
interested in knowing what is stewing in Vollmann's furious
imagination. But this book, despite his talent, is less a fully
realized work of literature than the protracted reverie of an
especially precocious adolescent, full of energy and brilliance.
But it is the kind of brilliance that flares and then fades,
leaving vague, transient afterimages in the mind, but nothing
permanent to alter your vision.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE ROYAL FAMILY'
</P>
<P>
   By William T. Vollmann
</P>
<P>
   780 pages. Viking. $40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
