<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5497 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWT-TV30-COX     08-29 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT-TV30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBS documents Gingrich's plunge from king to exile
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Was it only yesterday that Newt Gingrich was king of the world?
</P>
<P>
   Seems like it. PBS' ``The Fall of Newt Gingrich'' opens on a
Labor Day weekend just two years ago, with the former House Speaker
and Republican Revolution war lord vacationing out West, sporting a
funny hat and indulging his passion for dinosaur remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today,'' the narrator pronounces of that time in 1998, ``Newt
Gingrich may be the most powerful man in America.''
</P>
<P>
   But if that moment seems like yesterday, it also now seems like
ages ago that Gingrich resigned his rule, so thoroughly has he been
``disappeared'' by Republicans trying to recapture the presidency.
His fall, in the midst of Bill Clinton's impeachment, was
blink-and-miss-it stuff: Only months after digging in that western
dirt, Gingrich was out, a pariah to the same upstarts he'd led into
Washington four years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think the House representatives made a mistake,'' says
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott in this more-frank-than-revealing
90 minutes. ``This is a guy that was more than the Moses of the
Republican Party _ he was the Joshua. He not only led us to the
promised land but into the promised land. I consider them
ingrates.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich isn't so Old Testament. Saying House Republicans needed
someone more ``nurturing'' and ``placating'' after losing seats in
'98, Gingrich allows, ``That wasn't a job I was capable of doing. I
have real limitations as a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Produced, directed and written by documentarian Michael Pack
(``Inside the Republican Revolution,'' ``Campus Culture Wars: Five
Stories About Political Correctness''), ``Fall'' does a dandy job
of giving the illusion that it's operating deep behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras follow Gingrich into meetings with lobbyists; into a
limo that takes him from the airport to a fund-raiser for a
Nebraska Republican hopeful; into the Marietta, Ga., ``war room''
on election night 1998, during the unexpected Republican collapse
for which Gingrich would be blamed.
</P>
<P>
   The constant movement and hallway strategizing gives ``Fall''
the feel of a real-life, congressional ``West Wing;'' even
Gingrich's press secretary, as in that NBC political drama, becomes
a kind of character in an on-going series, explaining what she'll
have to do moments after Gingrich opens his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of ``Fall,'' one feels less enlightened than
diverted. The scenes we peek at rarely have much consequence, while
the real action takes place somewhere else. (One's head virtually
spins after learning of a longtime affair ending the speaker's
marriage to Marianne, who's featured cheerfully throughout.)
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's fall, in fact, is disturbingly short-changed; this
project clearly began as a chronicle of what would be -- after
expected Republican triumphs and Clinton's expected demise -- a
kind of coronation.
</P>
<P>
   So the end seems just as sudden and inexplicable as it did in
'98. Only now it seems like ages ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Fall of Newt Gingrich''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on GPTV (98092).
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B.
</P>
<P>
   Verdict: A ``West Wing''-like rehash of events leading up to
Gingrich's 1998 demise.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Jubera writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
