<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5498 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      08-29 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PAT NIXON, REMEMBERED 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARIANNE MEANS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Because most of those in a position to know are
dead, no one can ever be certain whether President Richard Nixon
beat his wife Patricia, as a new biography charges.
</P>
<P>
   But there is plenty of evidence on the record to demonstrate
that during the White House years the Nixons had a chilly
relationship. He behaved toward her in public as though they were
strangers who never had a romantic thought and barely knew each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Covering the White House in those days, I sometimes witnessed
the president's shabby treatment of his wife, whom he never
touched, studiously ignored and kept in the distant background.
</P>
<P>
   How different is this antiseptic marriage from that of the
presidential families who followed the Nixons in the White House
after he resigned in 1974. As far as we can tell, these later
partnerships have been strong and reasonably happy.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, first ladies are playing increasingly prominent
roles, and public displays of affection are now not only standard
conduct but practically required. Al Gore's passionate kiss of
Tipper before his acceptance speech will be remembered far longer
than the words he spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Once politicians fixated on ``family values'' it became
obligatory for presidential contenders to set a good public example
of loyal affection for their mates. President Clinton has taken a
severe drubbing in public opinion for cheating on his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Nixon may have the dubious distinction of being the last
president's wife to be considered an irrelevant appendage to her
husband's presidency. There was no sign of intimate communication
between them, let alone any influence she might have exercised over
his thoughts and policies. He refused to let her take most official
trips with him. He took vacations alone, controlled her staff,
rejected her pleas not to seek the presidency in 1968 and
apparently never discussed Watergate with her.
</P>
<P>
   We reporters constantly looked for evidence of physical or
verbal tenderness as befitting a long marriage _ and found none. In
one memorable episode, the first couple met on stage at a rally in
Nashville after several days spent apart in March of 1974, during
the closing saga of Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   After the audience sang ``Happy Birthday'' to the first lady,
she rose with a smile and walked toward her husband, arms extended
to embrace him. He deliberately turned away from her. Reporters who
were present still recall the snub with horror. The Nixons said not
one word of greeting to each other all that night.
</P>
<P>
   The new examination of Nixon's life, titled ``The Arrogance of
Power: The Secret World of Richard Nixon'' by Irish journalist
Anthony Summers, paints a harsh picture. The book describes Nixon
as secretly using drugs to combat depression. And it calls his
marriage to Pat full of ``prolonged marital difficulty, of physical
abuse, of threatened divorce.'' Based on second-hand accounts and
the observations of acquaintances now dead, the book also claims
that he beat her in times of political crisis, starting in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Nixon Cox denies the accusation, insisting that her
father never struck her mother. She is a loyal daughter and has
always publicly defended her disgraced dad, who was forced to
resign to avoid impeachment for the Watergate crimes. But it is
entirely possible that she might not have known what went on when
her parents were alone and Nixon could indulge his legendary temper
out of public view.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Hillings, a longtime Nixon adviser and one of the book's
deceased sources, once told me that although Pat Nixon was a fully
participating political partner in 1960, she was a changed woman by
the time of Nixon's unsuccessful 1962 California gubernatorial
campaign. She opposed the race and no longer cared to contribute to
the plotting and the planning even though she campaigned stoically
in public with him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964 when he unsuccessfully tried a stealth presidential
candidacy, and 1968 when he eventually won the prize, Pat Nixon
dropped out. When his inner circle came to his New York apartment
to plan the campaign, she was never there, Hillings said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillings, who did not suggest that Nixon abused her physically,
said he felt sorry for her. For whatever reason, she was no longer
an integral part of Richard Nixon's career. When he fell from
power, it was his daughter Julie who undertook a campaign to defend
him, not his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon was asked in an interview after he left the White House
why he had never said publicly that he loved Pat. ``We just don't
go in for those public declarations of _ of love,'' he said,
stumbling over the key word. ``We never held hands in public. She
isn't a public kisser; I am not either.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a sad story of mental and emotional anguish, regardless
of the physical consequences. For all the sloppy sentimentality of
the new rush to flaunt family dedication, it does humanize the most
powerful political office in the world and helps us identify with
the occupants.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon lived alone in his skull and liked it that way.
Poor Pat. Poor us. How did we ever happen to elect such a cold
fish?
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached at the e-mail address means(at)
hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
