<HEADER>
A5502 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-BOS &LR;      08-29 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICAN PANEL TO OPENLY ADDRESS RACISM ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROODEPOORT, South Africa _ On a recent Saturday afternoon miners
from Durban Roodepoort Deep, a gold operation outside Johannesburg,
headed to the racetrack, their pockets jangling with spare coins.
</P>
<P>
   While their bosses enjoyed a round of golf, the miners laughed
nervously about playing the ponies.
</P>
<P>
   But there was little mirth. The horses are a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   As South Africans gather Wednesday for the first national
conference on racism since the end of apartheid, the plight of
Durban Deep's miners illustrates the thorny issues at stake and how
they are seen differently through the prism of race.
</P>
<P>
   The mine closed in March. The miners, nearly all of them black,
were given one day's notice and a small payout. This month another
notice came, giving the miners two days to pay hefty rent hikes or
clear out of the company hostels.
</P>
<P>
   The mining concern cited economics, saying gold prices are too
low for it to dig. The miners saw racism. The company, they say,
ignores new laws designed to protect workers from the abuses that
long marked the mining industry, and did nothing to help them find
new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apartheid is alive and well in the mines,'' said Hezekiel
Manana, who has worked at the Deep since 1979. ``We get no job
training. We have no black shift bosses. . . . When we complain,
they call us `kaffirs' and tell us to go and talk to (President
Thabo) Mbeki about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Racism, never a simple issue in South Africa, at least was well
defined under apartheid, the segregrated system from 1948 to 1994.
Whites governed; Indians, Coloureds (people of mixed race), and
blacks were discriminated against in increasing severity according
to skin tone.
</P>
<P>
   Since the advent of democracy in 1994, accusations of racism
have come from every direction. The minister of safety and security
recently lambasted white women for using a national holiday to go
shopping rather than participating in public commemorations. Mbeki
cried racism after the white opposition leader criticized his
policies on AIDS and regional crises.
</P>
<P>
   Some argue that blacks can't be racist, given South Africa's
history. Others say new laws meant to ensure equality amount to
racism against whites. In nearly every dispute, someone plays the
race card.
</P>
<P>
   However, race was rarely debated head-on. The Truth and
Reconciliation Commission explored the damages of apartheid. The
National Union of Mineworkers developed programs to ease racial
tensions in the mines. The Human Rights Commission held an inquiry
into racism in the media. New laws have gone some way toward
redressing inequalities.
</P>
<P>
   But until now, South Africa hasn't talked openly as a nation
about how racism is changing under democracy and what to do about
it. That discussion has finally arrived. Prompted by Mbeki's call
in February, the Human Rights Commission will convene a four-day
meeting Wednesday to explore the sources and forms of ethnic
division in modern South Africa and how to solve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as South Africans have spoken about everything else
relating to race without calling it that. We've called it
reconciliation and nation building. But unless we force this
discussion and call it by its name, we won't achieve nation
building,'' said Pansy Tlakula, a member of the Human Rights
Commission. ``This conference sends a clear message about South
Africa's commitment to dealing with this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   The preamble to the new constitution states that ``South Africa
belongs to all who live in it, united in our diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   That ideal, however, remains unrealized. The commission held
nationwide hearings in July to listen to personal accounts of
racism from ordinary people. The report based on those hearings,
obtained by the Globe before its scheduled release today, shows
that ethnic tensions pervade every segment of South African society
and still manifest themselves in brutal ways.
</P>
<P>
   The report includes accounts of institutional and structural
racism; deep xenophobia against immigrants from other African
countries; and complex overlapping of racism with other forms of
discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Among the findings, the study stated that ``in the private
sector, only 7 percent of companies expressed a preference for
hiring black women, who are more likely to occupy unskilled
positions.'' The South African Graduates Development Association
told the commission that ``for every 100 black graduates, only 10
or 20 secure jobs despite affirmative action policies.''
</P>
<P>
   The report offers recommendations for government and private
initiatives to ease ethnic discrimination, including education
campaigns, independent investigations into workplace conditions,
and legal reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But Anthea Jeffrey, of the South African Institute on Race
Relations in Johannesburg, warns that the state must be careful in
trying to legislate racism's end. She says South Africa must
respond to two definitions of racism: intentional disparate
treatment based on race, such as apartheid's laws depriving blacks
of the vote and land ownership; and racism that uses criteria _ job
experience, credit history _ that are supposedly race-neutral but
in practice favor whites.
</P>
<P>
   The answer to the first, Jeffrey argued, is the colorblind
ideal, ``where all individuals enjoy equal rights under the law.''
South Africa's new constitution already embodies that. The remedy
for the second ``is to classify individuals by race, so that those
identified as black can be exempted from normal criteria and
accorded preferential treatment until `equality of outcomes'
between white and black groups has been reached.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
