<HEADLINE>
GORE, BUSH SPAR OVER HEALTH CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLEN JOHNSON AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ As Al Gore kept up his criticism of George W.
Bush over health care Tuesday, the Texas governor offered a fresh
response, saying many of the vice president's proposals this year
are the same ones he and President Clinton talked about in 1992 yet
failed to enact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only on the issue of prescription drugs, it's on the
issue of middle-class tax cuts, as well,'' Bush said as he flew
from the parched dirt and 100-degree heat of Texas to the brilliant
sunshine, but considerably cooler climes, of the Down East coast.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, returning to the state of his most stinging defeat
during the primaries, Bush plans to appear at Winnacunnet High
School in Hampton, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember in 1992, the campaign was, `Vote for us, we're going
to provide middle-class tax cuts.' And guess what happened? There
was no middle-income tax cuts; there was a tax increase,'' Bush
said. ``The rhetoric in '92 was, `We're going to do something about
prescription drugs,' and nothing has happened. So, my point is,
it's time to give somebody else the opportunity to get something
done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign responded with its own recollection of
politcal rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you ask the average American the question that
Republicans asked, `Are you better off now than you were eight
years ago,' the average American is going to answer, `Yes,' '' said
Gore spokesman Kym Spell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is, the Clinton-Gore administration has
made tremendous progress in reducing crime, reforming welfare,
reducing class sizes and bringing down the deficit and working on
shoring up Social Security and Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   In his New England swing, Bush continued his two-week focus on
education.
</P>
<P>
   With US Senators Olympia Snowe and Susan Collins of Maine
looking on, Bush participated in an education roundtable discussion
at the Moore Middle School. Former Governor John McKernan was
moderator, and three of the participants were educators Bush
brought with him from Texas, while the other three were current or
former Maine education officials.
</P>
<P>
   Bush made his pitch for giving local schools control of federal
education money in exchange for accountability standards, citing
one of the parents accompanying him, Norma Garza, from Brownsville,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One size does not fit all,'' the Texas governor said. ``I
assure you the school in the district where Norma is from is really
different from the schools in Caribou, Maine.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush also responded to Gore's criticism late Monday that he
``put up or shut up'' when it comes to detailing a
prescription-drug plan for senior citizens. Next week, the governor
plans to expand upon his idea of forcing insurers participating in
Medicare to offer drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like his comments underlined the point I make that if
we want to get something done in Washington, we have to change the
tone of the discourse. It's not very presidential to me,'' Bush
told reporters aboard his campaign plane.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane replied: ``This is from a
campaign that has put up an ad touting a prescription drug benefit
they do not have. . . . The bottom line is, they cannot defend the
indefensible...nor can they explain the inexplicable: Why don't
they have an agenda to help America's families?''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Gore continued his week-long health care push,
promoting a plan to bring health insurance to all children by 2005
during a visit to Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are 11 million uninsured children nationwide;
Gore said his plan would ensure parents are ``never left powerless
and broke in the face of rising health care costs.'' His plan would
also cover 7 million parents who qualify for the existing
Children's Health Insurance Program, also known as CHIP.
</P>
<P>
   CHIP, which was enacted in 1997, is aimed at middle-income
children _ ones whose parents are too affluent for Medicaid but too
poor to buy their own health care. Gore's proposal would, through a
series of incentives to states, expand CHIP to include families
earning up to 250 percent of the poverty level _ a family of four
earning about $41,000 a year, Gore aides said.
</P>
<P>
   The plan would also encourage states to let families earning
more than that to buy into the CHIP or Medicaid program. And it
would provide incentives to make sure all children who qualify for
CHIP are, in fact, enrolled. One element of the Gore plan is to
allow states to link their children's health insurance program to
the school lunch program, since most children in the lunch program
also need health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used the occasion to draw a contrast between his plan
and the campaign of Bush, which is has not moved beyond the general
concept of pushing private insurance to provide prescription drug
plans for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope my opponent will also present to you specifics.
...Presently, he has not presented any plan to adress this
problem'' of children's health care, Gore told a group gathered on
a school lawn. ``But again, it's all about you. You deserve a full
discussion of all the issues that need to be addressed. You deserve
to give a mandate in this election for what you would like to see
in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign also mocked the Bush trip to Maine, saying
children in the state would miss out on needed school repairs under
the Bush education plan, which does not focus on ``bricks and
mortar'' programs such as school renovation.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lehane, the Gore spokesman, 85 percent of the 721
public schools in Maine _ a total of 612 schools _ are crumbling.
Gore has proposed a $115 billion national education plan, which
includes school repairs.
</P>
<P>
   After his stop in Portland, Bush flew to Portsmouth, N.H., and
attended a fund-raiser in Rye, N.H., at the home of Cabletron
co-founder Craig Benson. After another education event Wednesday at
Winnacunnet High, he was flying to Pennsylvania and Ohio, two key
electoral states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore flew to Eugene, Ore., where he and his running mate,
Senator Joseph I. Lieberman of Connecticut, planned to return to
the issue of prescription drug coverage for the 39 million senior
citizens on Medicare. Wednesday the two were headed to Seattle for
more joint apperances highlighting health care.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Johnson, traveling with Bush, reported from Portland; Kornblut,
traveling with Gore, reported from Albuquerque.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
