<HEADER>
A5508 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-ALASKATRAVEL0830-COX     08-29 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALASKATRAVEL0830-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Cruise ships: I like them, I really, really like them
</P>
<P>
   By Whenever the subject of a cruise came up, I had a one-word
answer: never.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise ships, to me, were floating prisons, places from which
travelers had no escape if something went wrong. I prefer knowing I
can pack up and leave if the hotel plumbing backs up, the kitchen
begins serving salmonella as the nightly special or the fireworks
display starts coming from the next room.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the problem. The family had decided that we would
visit Alaska this summer. To really see Alaska, you can't just stay
on land. You can visit Mount McKinley, fish for salmon in the Kenai
River and try to determine whether there actually is darkness in
Anchorage during the summer solstice (there isn't, though my son
reports that there is a period of dusk).
</P>
<P>
   To really see Alaska, however, you have to be on the water. You
have to get into Prince William Sound. You have to get into College
Fjord and Glacier Bay. Which means you have to get on a ... cruise
ship. You can rent much smaller, customized ships for the trip, but
you need six months' revenue from the Prudhoe Bay oil reserves to
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   So you talk to your travel agent. You book passage on Princess
Cruises because your travel agent tells you that the company has
this deal where you stay in Princess lodges, then get on the
Princess ship for your trip from Seward southeast through the
Inland Passage to Vancouver, British Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   And the land part works out fine. You fly into Anchorage
(four-hour time difference) and arrive at 9 p.m. Sunday when the
sun is so high and so bright that you think you're just waking up.
The Princess bus takes you to the hotel. The next day, the Princess
train takes you to the Princess Lodge in Mount McKinley on a clear
day when the summit is visible for miles, and the tour guides are
saying, almost apologetically, that ``only one person'' has died so
far during the summer trying to climb North America's highest peak.
</P>
<P>
   The Princess train and bus take you south to the Kenai peninsula
and the Princess lodge. Then it's on to Seward and the Princess ...
cruise ship.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you realize is that you're not part of the club.
All around you, cruise veterans are comparing their six other
Alaska cruises. They're talking knowledgeably about the Lido Deck
and when to do your laundry. They are ready, like Spaniards waiting
in Pamplona for the running of the bulls.
</P>
<P>
   And what do you know? This boat, the Sea Princess, is barely 4
years old and very nice. Our stateroom, starboard side, has a great
balcony for viewing. Our steward drops by and tells us to call if
we need anything. My wife, our two children and the other family
we're traveling with grab lunch at the 24-hour buffet _ which we
label ``the trough'' _ and a few hours later we slide out of the
harbor precisely at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   And that was the astonishing part. Everything about the
seven-day trip went on time, almost flawlessly.
</P>
<P>
   We left port on time. We arrived on time. We had no mechanical
problems. The luck carried over to the weather. We had virtually no
rain, even in Ketchikan where it rains about 180 inches a year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the food on board, it was good, sometimes very good.
Really liked the Baked Alaska presentation the last night. But the
food paled in comparison to the service.
</P>
<P>
   When you're cruising, I learned, your dinner waiter becomes more
important than your stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   Our ship carried about 2,000 people, which is capacity. With two
dining rooms and two sittings (5:45 and 8), that means 500 diners
each time. Our waiter and assistant waiter were from Romania, and
the hardest thing at the end of the trip was reminding my
16-year-old daughter that, no, she could not expect the same level
of service back home.
</P>
<P>
   A special order? No problem. A little extra helping of the
appetizer or the entree? No problem. Bring out several kinds of
wine until we decided? No problem? A smile for a tired 5-year-old
girl? No problem. Pose for a picture? No problem. Tour of the
kitchen for anyone interested? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoyable as the dining was, the scenery was better.
</P>
<P>
   On the way into Glacier Bay, the ship basically idled for nearly
an hour as we stood on our balcony watching whales roll and eagles
dive for pieces of chopped-up fish. The bright, polar morning was
nearly still, and the whoosh of air coming through blowholes
drifted across the water.
</P>
<P>
   Later, we saw seals sprawled on ice floes near Johns Hopkins
Glacier. I'd be lying, however, if I didn't worry about the
possible environmental consequences of ships going in and out of
the bay each so often. You get the feeling that restrictions will
have to be imposed at some point.
</P>
<P>
   Before the trip, I thought I'd be stir crazy after two days at
sea. Instead, the week went by with astonishing quickness. It
helped that we went on excursions each of the three middle days.
</P>
<P>
   Still, what I had imagined as a floating prison became a
floating small town. When it works right, a cruise ship is a fairly
remarkable place. It hit me one day as I was running on a treadmill
in the workout area. Large windows faced the stern, and I watched
as we pulled out of Glacier Bay. Here I was, watching ESPN via
satellite in a climate-controlled environment while, in the
background, a chunk of ice that is who knows how ancient fell into
the water. One content inmate in his floating prison.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: randyschultz(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   If you go:
</P>
<P>
   Busiest months are May through August. May-June, inside
staterooms start at about $850/person. Outside staterooms w/balcony
start at about $1,750/person. July-August, inside staterooms are
about $1,200, and outside/balcony are about $2,500. Includes port
charges. Booking by Feb. 14 gets you a nice discount. For more
information, please contact your travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
