<SLUG> BC-CRUMBS0830-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Restaurateurs fight back against the food police
</P>
<P>
   ByEAT AND DIE:
</P>
<P>
   Eat and die: The Center for Science in the Public Interest has
been almost that blunt in its denouncement of the American diet,
taking to task such favorites as burgers, fettuccine alfredo, kung
pao chicken, ice cream, movie popcorn and more. And it has
certainly made some diners change their eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   But CSPI has also laid a guilt trip on the pleasures of eating.
And for that, the Guest Choice Network, a group of more than 30,000
restaurant and tavern operators, has decided to fight back on a new
Web site called CSPINOT.com. (That's CSPI NOT, get it?) Admittedly
biased, the site wants to arrest the food police and present the
other side of the plate. Says Ronni Chernoff, past president of the
American Dietetic Association, ``We have a totally different view
on food and nutrition than (Center for Science in the Public
Interest director Michael Jacobson) does. He takes all the pleasure
out of eating by scaring people and using terror tactics.''
</P>
<P>
   Honey, I've shrunk the Oreos: The timing _ right as school
starts _ makes you think Nabisco did this for the kids. But plenty
of adults are excited about the new mini Oreos. The bite-size
cookies weigh 1/10 ounce and are 1/5 the size of their parents, or
small enough to bring no guilt but big enough to cover a quarter.
Nine is considered a serving. Look for the minis in 8-ounce bags
and 1.5-ounce snack packs.
</P>
<P>
   Some like it hot: But most don't, says Taco Bell, which reports
that it goes through 5.2 billion packets of hot sauce a year. About
2.6 billion of those are ``Mild,'' 1.8 billion are medium spicy
``Hot'' and 800 million are five-alarm, according to USA Weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Couldn't prove it by Central Texans, who always thrill to the
burn of back-to-back weekend August fire shows in Austin. Recently,
the Texas Fiery Foods Show, in its fourth year, saw record
attendance and several vendors sold out of their products. And the
Austin Chronicle Hot Sauce Festival, in its 10th year, attracted
approximately 10,000 salsa lovers.
</P>
<P>
   What a whopper: Maida Heatter has always believed in the power
of cookies, and now the restaurant world is catching on, notes the
September issue of Food &AMP; Wine. The magazine salutes Heatter and
her recipe for Chocolate Whoppers, which begat similar bakery
wonders all over the country, including Austin, by such names as
Black Gold (Upper Crust), Triple Chocolate Cookies (Schlotzsky's)
and Whopper (Sweetish Hill). The best chocolate cookie recipe in
the world, it is pure decadence and contains only 1/4 cup flour.
The rest is chocolate and nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Items for this column are drawn from wire reports, mail,
personal observation and comments from readers. To pass on a
suggestion, call food editor Kitty Crider at 445-3656, or write to
Food, Austin American-Statesman, P.O. Box 670, Austin 78767.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
