<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONEFLA0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dispute over reasons behind increase in Florida's minority
students
 &HT;    By Marcia Gelbart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A record number of minorities have enrolled
as freshmen this fall at Florida's 10 public universities.
</P>
<P>
   But while that increase _ 1,234 more students, or 12 percent
more minorities than last year _ is undisputed, there is
disagreement about the factors behind it.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jeb Bush credits his One Florida program, which relies on
factors such as ZIP codes and family income instead of affirmative
action programs to enroll more minority students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have shown that we can promote both opportunity and
diversity in higher education without using unfair and legally
suspect racial preferences,'' Bush, flanked by university
officials, said Tuesday as he celebrated the preliminary enrollment
figures. ``Thanks to the efforts of our outstanding universities,
the One Florida Initiative has succeeded in producing the most
diverse freshman class in the history of Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   The increase in minority students is accompanied by
unanticipated high enrollment at almost every Florida university.
Because of that overall growth, the percentage of minorities
starting college statewide has barely changed. Last year minorities
made up 36.6 percent of the freshman class; this year they account
for 36.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush critics, including some educators, say the credit for the
increase belongs largely to the universities. Under pressure from
the governor, the universities stepped up efforts to attract
minorities, from more high school visits to mass mailings to hiring
special coordinators.
</P>
<P>
   The critics point out that One Florida, in its first year, was
stalled until July by a court challenge and consequently, came too
late to have a direct effect on admissions this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of extra recruitment,'' said Florida Atlantic
University Admissions Director Dick Griffin. ``That certainly
played a part.'' The number of black freshman enrolled at FAU
increased from 223 last year to 358 this fall. Hispanic students
attending the school increased from 184 to 230.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most vocal One Florida opponents, Sen. Kendrick Meek,
D-Miami, said, ``It's really an understatement and misleading for
the governor to say this is a result of his ... program.'' More
reliable results won't come for another two to three years after a
study of retention and then graduation rates, said Meek, who in
January staged a sit-in with Rep. Tony Hill at Lt. Gov. Frank
Brogan's office protesting One Florida.
</P>
<P>
   And even if those results are positive, he worries that under
One Florida, minority growth would be too dependent on the
subjective goals of a governor and education officials, instead of
a matter of objective policy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite thoughts otherwise, Bush said Florida is better off with
One Florida now in place. Elsewhere courts have ruled affirmative
action programs unconstitutional, and ballot initiatives have
forced states to abandon their racial quota and preference
programs. States that continue to do nothing, he said, ``do so at
their own jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: marciagelbart(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
