<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARTHRITIS0830-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Arthritis a crippling disease with more than 100 variations
</P>
<P>
   By Carolyn Susman
</P>
<P>
   c. 20000 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - ``People like you shouldn't have
children.''
</P>
<P>
   Even 25 years later, those hurtful words from a doctor she
trusted bring tears to Leona Malone's eyes.
</P>
<P>
   She was 31 and already eight years into a battle with a vicious,
debilitating disease: rheumatoid arthritis. She had suffered so
much with painful and swollen joints that made it hard to walk,
hard to chew, hard to use her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted a baby,'' Malone recalls, the supercharged
memory momentarily taking her breath away and causing her eyes to
fill.
</P>
<P>
   But she had stumbled into the office of a doctor who didn't
think a woman who might someday be wheelchair-bound should take on
that responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   While friends her age were pursuing their dreams full speed,
Malone found herself fighting just to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to excel,'' she recalls of her plans to get a
doctorate that were cut short by her illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I just wanted to be normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthritis. Typically, it conjures images of old, bent people
suffering with a disease that is an inevitable part of aging.
</P>
<P>
   Few know that there are 100 forms of arthritis, and that one out
of six Americans is affected, nearly 300,000 of them children with
juvenile arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   There is no established cause or cure.
</P>
<P>
   Osteoarthritis is the most common form, but rheumatoid is the
most common form in children and one of the most virulent. It
primarily affects girls and women. Scientists don't know why.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Aida Turturro, who plays Janice Soprano on the popular
HBO series ``The Sopranos,'' was diagnosed at 12 with rheumatoid
arthritis. Actress Kathleen Turner, famed for her roles in ``Body
Heat'' and ``Romancing the Stone,'' was diagnosed at 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a chronic, inflammatory disease that can affect the
heart, nerves, the lungs, any organ system,'' says Dr. Michael
Schweitz, a West Palm Beach rheumatologist who treats Leona Malone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible disease, a nasty disease. Rheumatoid carries
with it a certain mortality from the body being ill.''
</P>
<P>
   Projections are that all forms of arthritis will increase as
baby boomers age, with 60 million people suffering from it by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Centers for Disease Control has called it the next
epidemic,'' Schweitz says.
</P>
<P>
   For Leona Malone, the life-altering illness hit at 23. She was a
graduate student at the University of Miami when she experienced
what she thought was an attack of bursitis in her shoulder. Later,
her feet started to swell and hurt. Eventually, her feet would
swell from a size 7 to a size 10 because of the chronic
inflammation that is characteristic of the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have these flare-ups that were so horrible. Your whole
system was hurting and burning. It was hurtful to even have a sheet
touch your body.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembers how, when she was first diagnosed and
hospitalized, friends brought her ``old people's'' gifts, driving
home the perception that arthritis is only a disease of the
elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd bring dusting powder or note paper; they'd bring bed
jackets and forget I liked jewelry.''
</P>
<P>
   That got her down, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I never thought of giving up. I thought, the doctors will
fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   They never could, of course. She's undergone 23 surgeries on her
hips, shoulders, elbows and feet, and a drug regimen that at one
time included so much aspirin _ 16-20 tablets a day _ that her ears
would ring.
</P>
<P>
   She's even tried alternative concoctions, like large doses of
cod liver oil, gin-soaked raisins and copper bracelets. She never
stopped taking her prescription drugs, she said, and has added
glucosamine _ an herbal remedy that Arthritis Today, the magazine
of the Arthritis Foundation (www.arthritis.org), says shows
evidence of easing pain and preserving joint cartilage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her willingness to take on any available treatment,
she's been left with hands that are deformed from the disease. This
is largely, she believes, because drugs that are available today
that have the capability to modify the course of the illness
weren't available when she was first diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Those drugs, which include a class introduced in 1998 known as
biologic response modifiers, have had a tremendous impact on the
disease for some. They work by blocking chemicals in the body that
cause inflammation and tissue damage.
</P>
<P>
   And they have proved the savior of at least one local child with
rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   Toi Leon is a cherubic little girl with a smile that has won her
beauty pageants. At 7, she has lived with juvenile rheumatoid
arthritis five years.
</P>
<P>
   Toi might have suffered similarly to Leona Malone. She was
deteriorating quickly, and her parents, Linda and Larry, had
already ordered a specially equipped wheelchair for her. But she
began taking one of the new biologic drugs, Enbrel, more than a
year ago, and her improvement has been dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   She hops around her home, looking little like a child who had
been dependent on braces, walkers and wheelchairs only a short time
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely put her disease into almost a total
remission,'' says Linda Leon, who _ until her daughter was
diagnosed _ was one of the people who ``had no idea children could
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   The drug, however, is very expensive. Toi's medication costs
$1,200 a month, her mother said, and Linda had to battle to prove
nothing else worked before her insurance would cover it.
</P>
<P>
   But Toi had been through the mill before then.
</P>
<P>
   She woke up one morning and couldn't walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was screaming, and dragging her leg across the floor,''
Linda remembers.
</P>
<P>
   It was a terrifying time. Surgeries, medications, physical
therapy and doctor visits. The diagnosis puzzled the Leons, but
Linda was later diagnosed, herself, with lupus, another form of
arthritis, and thinks she may have passed on a genetic tendency to
Toi.
</P>
<P>
   The disease took its toll on the youngster. She had trouble with
potty training, and wasn't toilet-trained until she was almost 4.
She had little mobility but hated the walker she was supposed to
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``When she couldn't walk, she would find ways to get around,''
Linda said. ``She would hop, she would crawl, she would roll. She
was very determined. Emotionally, she's more aware (than other
children.) She's been there; she's lived it.''
</P>
<P>
   She had a battle with anorexia, too, a brutal side-effect of
another medication that made her lose her sense of taste and endure
bouts of vomiting.
</P>
<P>
   Toi fell behind in schoolwork and ended up in a Head Start
program that gives youngsters an extra edge in school. But when she
started second grade this year, to her mother's delight, she was
put in a gifted program.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she startles visitors by reading aloud from a book about
the body's blood supply, and by announcing, ``I came from the
uterus. Everyone came from the uterus!''
</P>
<P>
   She wants to be a doctor, not a strange choice, perhaps, for a
child who has spent almost her whole life at doctor's offices.
She's already had five operations.
</P>
<P>
   A natural beauty, Toi loves to participate in beauty pageants
and to model. Linda encourages whatever she enjoys, including tap
and jazz lessons.
</P>
<P>
   Toi's modeled for the Arthritis Foundation and for department
store advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd just do it. She's very confident on stage. She had to
smile and project herself. There's a stance you're supposed to
have, she can't do that. So she'll smile and wave to compensate for
what she can't do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Linda, angry at first that her child was struck down, finds
her own compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wonder why it has to be your child and why God did it to
your child. Now, I look at the whole picture, and I figure God did
it for a reason. Because it's a disease a lot of people don't know
about, I have to speak out so people are aware.''
</P>
<P>
   And today, Leona Malone has a life her early doctors might never
have imagined.
</P>
<P>
   Her daughter, Carrah, is 24 and studying to be a lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   And she is a bereavement counselor at Hospice of Palm Beach
County and an honored volunteer for the Arthritis Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``No disease happens in a vacuum,'' she says. ``Life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: carolynsusman(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
