<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5514 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0830-COX     08-29 1959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HAMMERING ON CHILDREN'S HEALTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, turning his focus to children's health, says it is
``put up or shut up time'' for George W. Bush to begin dealing with
the specifics of campaign issues. ``The time for generalities
without specifics I think is just about over,'' Gore told
reporters. He said he was largely at a loss to evaluate Bush's
proposals since they lack details. ``I don't really know how they
make it all add up,'' he said. The Bush campaign said that kind of
talk is ``not very presidential.'' Gore plugged away again Tuesday,
in Albuquerque, N.M., for his proposed $100 billion expansion of
child health insurance. Political strategists say that issue can be
used to target Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   TAKING EDUCATION ATTACK TO SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   Just as he did after his 18-point defeat by John McCain in New
Hampshire in February, George W. Bush responded to his recent sag
in the polls with a sharp attack on Al Gore, unleashing sharp
criticism on education. Bush accused Gore of offering a plan ``with
an illusion of accountability,'' presiding over a ``national
tragedy'' in reading, and of being ``locked in old ways.'' Bush was
holding an education discussion Tuesday at a middle school in
Portland, Maine. Today he is scheduled to hold another education
discussion at a high school in Hampton, N.H. In between, he was to
attend a $5,000-a-couple fund-raiser for the state Republican Party
in Rye, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER AND RELIGIOUS VALUES
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney is promoting popular conservative themes _
character-building and a strong defense _ on a three-day tour
through Missouri, Mississippi, Georgia, North Carolina and Florida.
He told a gathering of Christian athletes in Kansas City, Mo.,
today that teaching children about character is as important as
showing them how to read and write. Cheney shared the podium with
members of the Fellowship of Christian Athletes, a national group
that encourages students and coaches to practice Christian values
and influence others to get involved with churches. One student
participant, Erica Garris, quoted scripture and told the gathering,
``I stand here today professing God as my savior.''
</P>
<P>
   A SCOLDING ON RELIGIOUS OVEREMPHASIS
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about his recent statements on the campaign trail, the
Anti-Defamation League called on Joe Lieberman to refrain from
overt expressions of religious values and beliefs, stating that
``appealing to voters along religious lines is contrary to the
American ideal.'' Said a statement from Howard Berkowitz and
Abraham Foxman of the ADL: ``Candidates should feel comfortable
explaining their religious convictions to voters. At the same time,
however, we believe there is a point at which an emphasis on
religion in a political campaign becomes inappropriate and even
unsettling in a religiously diverse society such as ours.''
</P>
<P>
   APPLYING PRESSURE FOR DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's campaign chairman tried today to increase pressure on
George W. Bush to accept three nationally televised, prime-time
debates in October, saying they would ``give the greatest number of
voters the chance to hear the candidates directly.'' Bush has
agreed to three presidential debates without specifying which ones.
Bush responded, ``I would welcome all three being in prime time,''
but his campaign said that didn't necessarily mean he would accept
any of the debate commission's proposed dates or formats. Bush has
said he prefers relatively informal debates, such as a session
during the primaries when the participants were seated around a
table with CNN's Larry King.
</P>
<P>
   TWO NEW POLLS SHOW A TIE
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush and Al Gore are locked in a dead heat in two new
presidential polls, evidence that Gore is holding his
post-convention poll bounce. The CNN-USA Today-Gallup poll of
likely voters showed Bush at 46 percent, Gore at 45 percent, Green
Party candidate Ralph Nader at 3 percent and Reform Party candidate
