<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5515 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MATRITECH-COLON-BOS &LR;      08-29 0426
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATRITECH-COLON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATRITECH SAYS IT HAS IDENTIFIED COLON CANCER PROTEINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matritech Inc. says its scientists have identified proteins
specific to colon cancer in the blood of patients with the disease,
paving the way to develop a test that detects the cancer even at
its earliest stages.
</P>
<P>
   Although the research is at an early stage, Stephen D. Chubb,
founder and chief operating officer of the Newton biotechnology
company, said Tuesday he believes the findings could translate into
a useable diagnostic tool as early as next year.
</P>
<P>
   If proven accurate, a blood test could represent a significant
savings over the colonoscopy, today's preferred screening test for
colon cancer. Chubb said a test would sell for between $11 and $150
depending on whether it is marketed as a stand-alone kit or a lab
service. A colonoscopy costs between $800 and $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's an opportunity to make a significant
contribution to the welfare of people who are at risk for this
disease,'' Chubb said. ``That's what this is all about. Early
detection to save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   About 130,000 people will be diagnosed this year with colon
cancer, the third most common cancer in the United States,
according to the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   Matritech scientists studied the blood of 20 colon-cancer
patients and 20 healthy people. In all 20 people with cancer, they
found elevated levels of specific proteins. But in the healthy
people, they found no evidence of those proteins.
</P>
<P>
   Matritech's stock price rose 11 percent on the news, closing at
$8.59 on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Thilly, director of the Center for Environmental Health
Sciences at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, however,
cautioned that data is preliminary and that any screening test must
be extremely accurate to be useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of people with colon cancer is small, but the
number to be screened is large,'' Thilly said. ``If the test had a
1 percent false positive rate and you screened three million
50-year-olds, you would have 30,000 false positives when you were
looking for only about 1,200 cases of colon cancer. You'd still be
looking for a needle in a haystack.''
</P>
<P>
   Chubb said he plans to have hundreds more people tested by next
year. He said he is optimistic because of the company's past
successes. Matritech has an FDA-approved urine test to detect
bladder cancer and is developing a blood test to screen for breast
cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
