<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Aug. 30 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   LEE-TRIAL (Albuquerque, N.M.) _ A federal judge on Tuesday
refused to block the release of the former nuclear scientist Wen Ho
Lee on bail and was expected to order prosecutors to give him
thousands of pages of classified internal documents so he can look
for evidence that Lee was singled out because of he is
Chinese-American. Judge James A. Parker's ruling means that Lee,
who was indicted last December on charges that he illegally
downloaded a virtual library of nuclear weapons secrets, could be
released to a form of home detention as early as Friday afternoon.
By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   MISSILE-DEFENSE (Washington) _ Looking at the possible legal
conflicts between action on a limited national missile defense and
the requirements of the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty. By
Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COLOMBIA (Cartagena, Colombia) _ President Andres
Pastrana said Tuesday that Colombia cannot put a dent in
international drug trafficking until the United States and other
countries do much more to control their citizens' appetite for
drugs. ``What we are talking about is the most lucrative business
in the world,'' he said in an interview, ``unless the recent spike
in oil prices has made it the second-most-lucrative business in the
world.'' Pastrana's wary words seemed to strike a dissonant note,
coming on the eve of President Clinton's arrival here Wednesday,
when the leaders are to open a $7.5 billion plan to address the
spreading trafficking problem in Colombia. By Clifford Krauss.
(1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   VOTER-VOICES (Pittsburgh, Pa.) _ Talking to dozens of voters in
a variety of neighborhoods here about their attitudes toward the
presidential candidates, and how and why they may have recently
changed. By Jennifer Steinhauer. (1400 words)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-EDUCATION (Washington) _ A look at education issues in
the presidential campaign: Five years after the Republican Congress
shut down the government in part because of the money President
Clinton wanted to spend on education, four years after Bob Dole
embraced a Republican platform that advocated abolishing the
Department of Education, George W. Bush has made an expanded
federal role in education a central issue of his campaign. Vice
President Al Gore has responded in kind on an issue that has been
an especially strong one for Democrats ever since President Lyndon
B. Johnson got the first federal aid to public schools enacted 35
years ago over the opposition of most Republicans. By David E.
Rosenbaum. (1400 words) The first in a series on the issues of the
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-POLICE-SUIT (Los Angeles) _ A federal judge has ruled that
the Los Angeles Police Department can be sued as a racketeering
enterprise by people who claim their civil rights were violated
LAPD officers. The ruling creates the possibility that the
department could be the first in the nation to face trial under the
Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations law. It also could
dramatically increase the city's liability. By Don Terry.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-QUIZ-SHOW (Bombay) _ In a country where hundreds of
millions live in grinding poverty, the Indian version of ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' has suddenly become the most popular TV
show. Some poor people are using up what little money they have on
phone calls to try to get on the show. We watch it with viewers in
a Bombay slum. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
</TEXT>
