<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Aug. 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Showers and clouds will continue to be directed inland along the
Middle Atlantic Coast as a weak area of low pressure spins just
offshore. Farther north, much of New England will have a partly
sunny day with light breezes from the east. Temperatures will
remain a bit below seasonal levels along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   A strengthening area of low pressure in the northern Plains will
produce periods of showers and thunder from the Missouri Valley to
the southern Canadian Prairie Wednesday. Brisk breezes from the
northeast will combine with the showers to produce afternoon
readings only in the 50s in northern Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Abundant moisture and a jet stream disturbance in the Southwest
will promote cloudy skies and scattered showers from New Mexico to
Idaho.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: REMEMBERING NAMES
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, residents of Hawaii noted a familiar name when a
tropical storm 1,000 miles to the southeast was christened John. In
August 1994, Hurricane John, the most powerful ever recorded in the
central Pacific, spared Hawaii when it passed a few hundred miles
south. When a hurricane does great harm to life or property, its
name can be retired. A retired name cannot be used again for at
least 10 years to avoid confusion in legal actions and insurance
claims. Hurricane Mitch, which devastated parts of central America
in 1998, was the most recent storm to have its name retired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
