<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5523 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-JFK-GIJOE-BOS &LR;      08-29 0699
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JFK-GIJOE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JFK JOINS GI JOE LINEUP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The public could get its first glimpse Wednesday of
``John F. Kennedy: PT 109 Boat Commander,'' a collector's item that
toymaker Hasbro Inc. has created for its GI Joe line of action
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Hasbro displayed a prototype of the action
figure at the American International Toy Fair but would not allow
it to be photographed, saying essentially that ``PT 109 Commander''
was still a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   The finished product is set to be unveiled at the John F.
Kennedy Library and Museum. At a brief ceremony, Hasbro plans to
present the library's foundation with a mint edition of an action
figure that should hit store shelves shortly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to get something like this 100 percent right,'' said
Hasbro chairman and chief executive Alan G. Hassenfeld. ``Not 99
percent right, but 100 percent right.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, Hasbro often consulted with the library to
ensure that the action figure was historically correct.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pleased with the way they approached this and with the
amount of research they did in our photo archives,'' museum curator
Frank Rigg said of Hasbro.
</P>
<P>
   There are no plans for the library to include the action figure
in any of its public displays, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In return for permission to use Kennedy's image, Hasbro made a
donation of unspecified size to the library's foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Aimed largely at adult collectors, the JFK action figure is
being issued in a ``limited edition'' and should sell for between
$30 and $35, Hassenfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   A standard issue GI Joe can sell for about $14.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something you sell millions of,'' said Hassenfeld,
declining to be more specific about sales projections.
</P>
<P>
   If the PT 109 edition sells out, Hasbro will not make more, he
said; that would ``offend collectors.''
</P>
<P>
   It is possible, though, that Hasbro might issue a different JFK
action figure, perhaps one outfitted in dress whites.
</P>
<P>
   Given its limited-edition status, the PT 109 action figure is
unlikely to be a holiday hit or a big moneymaker for Hasbro, a
Pawtucket, R.I. company with $4.23 billion in 1999 sales.
</P>
<P>
   That's too bad for Hasbro. It could use a lift to match last
year's successes with Pokemon, Furby, and ``Star Wars.'' With sales
for those toy lines cooling off, Hasbro recently warned investors
that it could be facing a tough holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   As for the JFK action figure, it seeks to reenact Kennedy's
experience during World War II. In 1943, the young naval officert
commanded a PT boat that was attempting to prevent the resupply of
a Japanese military base in the Solomon Islands.
</P>
<P>
   During a night patrol, Kennedy's boat was rammed and sunk by an
enemy destroyer. Surviving crew members swam to a nearby island.
Ultimately, an SOS carved on a coconut was entrusted to friendly
natives who went for help.
</P>
<P>
   To commemorate the rescue, the JFK action figure is accessorized
with a replica of the now famous coconut.
</P>
<P>
   GI Joe has some history of his own. When he made his debut in
the mid 1960s, GI Joe was an action-figure pioneer.
</P>
<P>
   Some girls and women have long collected dolls. But it wasn't
until the 1970s that action figures became avidly prized by
collectors, said Gareb S. Shamus, chief executive of
Wizardworld.com, a Web site for such hobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   This phenomenon was partly inspired by the first ``Star Wars''
movie and such hit TV shows as ``Star Trek,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to pro wrestlers and last summer's new ``Star Wars''
movie, 1999 was a banner year for action figures, generating about
$1 billion in US wholesale revenues, Shamus said.
</P>
<P>
   As collectors became more numerous, Hasbro launched a special GI
Joe heroes line. The line has saluted such famous generals as
Dwight D. Eisenhower and Colin Powell.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Library was initially cool to the idea for a JFK
action figure. But the library reconsidered, won over by Hasbro's
careful treatment of Powell and Eisenhower.
</P>
<P>
   Said Kennedy Museum curator Rigg, ``That lent credibility to the
project.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
