<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5525 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-0830-     08-29 0468
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ABORTION-0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICAN GOVERNOR VETOES LAW AGAINST ABORTIONS FOR RAPE VICTIMS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Citing majority disapproval in an opinion survey,
the governor of Mexico's Guanajuato state Tuesday vetoed a new
state reform mandating jail time for women who seek abortions after
being raped.
</P>
<P>
   Most abortion is illegal in Mexico, but Guanajuato would have
been the first state to punish with six to three years in jail rape
victims who abort pregnancies. Members of the conservative National
Action Party, or the PAN, pushed through the controversial reform
in that state's legislature on Aug. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Ramon Martin, also of the PAN, based his decision on the
results of a recent survey conducted by the Center for Public
Opinion of the University of Guadalajara. In a statement Tuesday,
the governor's office also said he was influenced by opinions he
received via the Internet, letters and other channels.
</P>
<P>
   Martin said he is ``pro-life'' and that by vetoing the law he is
not closing off more discussion about resuscitating it later.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great majority of citizens asked that the reform be
returned to the state Congress for broader public consultation,''
the statement from the governor's office said. A survey the
governor had commissioned found that 68 percent of 1,200 people
interviewed in Guanajuato in their homes agreed with that
sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are satisfied with the attitude of the governor of
Guanajuato,'' said Martha Juarez of the Group for Reproductive
Information and Choice in Mexico City. ``Although we know that
there is a risk that the law will be discussed again, we hope that
it will be discussed with more care and professionalism and in
accordance with the reality of women in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, a member of the PAN and Mexico's president-elect,
immediately distanced himself from the Aug. 3 legislative action,
calling it a ``local issue'' he does not plan to propose
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the Guanajuato reform, Mexico City's woman mayor,
Rosario Robles, proposed decriminalizing abortion in the city in
cases of rape and life-threatening deformities. The proposal was
approved by the city's legislature on Aug. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Guanajuato will have a newly elected state legislature on Sept.
25, and a new governor on Sept. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Forty percent of those polled on the anti-abortion reform said
they thought that legislators should take into account the opinion
of women who became pregnant after being raped. Eighty-eight
percent said they would be willing to participate in a statewide
referendum vote on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' e-mail is: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
