<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5529 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-LEE-TRIAL-NYT &LR;      08-29 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-TRIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE ORDERS GOVERNMENT TO TURN OVER DOCUMENTS IN LOS ALAMOS CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ A federal judge Tuesday ordered the
government to turn over thousands of pages of classified internal
documents to help him determine whether there is evidence that the
former nuclear scientist Wen Ho Lee was unfairly singled out for
prosecution because he is Chinese American.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, James A. Parker, also rejected government efforts to
delay Lee's release on bail, which could come as early as Friday
afternoon. Lee was arrested and indicted last December on charges
that he illegally downloaded a virtual library of nuclear weapons
secrets, and he has spent the more than eight months since in close
to solitary confinement.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's decision on the documents indicates that he at least
believes there are some grounds for the defense's assertions that
Lee was a suspect because of his ethnicity, not because of the
facts, and that others who may have violated or were suspected of
violating security laws were not prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lee was not charged with espionage, he was investigated
for years on suspicions that he had given highly sensitive nuclear
weapons secrets to China. Lee was born on Taiwan and is a
naturalized American citizen. Although government officials have
said they have no evidence that Lee spied for anyone, they have
claimed in court that Chinese spies routinely seek out
Chinese-Americans in their clandestine recruitment activities.
</P>
<P>
   Selective prosecution motions, like the one heard Tuesday,
rarely lead to a case being dismissed and the judge's decision
represents only a small victory for the defense. Once the documents
are handed over, by Sept. 15, the judge will inspect them privately
and decide whether they should be given to the defense. The defense
could then use them to argue that the case should be dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In its motions, the defense provided statements from two former
senior counterintelligence officials, Robert Vrooman of Los Alamos
National Laboratory and Charles Washington of the Department of
Energy, asserting that Lee had been pursued at least partly because
of his Chinese ancestry. Such concerns have led a number of civil
rights groups, from the American Civil Liberties Union to the Asian
Law Caucus, to take up Lee's cause and file briefs on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered that the government provide several categories
of documents that the defense has been seeking. He ordered the
release of some secret testimony provided to Congress about the
investigation, classified material that the Department of Energy
collected last year for a report on whether the agency engaged in
racial profiling, State Department records on security breaches by
employees that were not prosecuted and a counterintelligence
training tape that the defense says encourages racial profiling. He
also sought statements by the former Energy Department
counterintelligence official Notra Trulock that the investigation
should focus on ethnic Chinese and Trulock's full list of suspects.
Lastly, he sought FBI reports on the number of people who had
access to information about the sophisticated warhead that the
government believes may have been leaked to China and all reports
on administrative inquiries by the Energy Department or the Los
Alamos National Laboratory on the improper handling of classified
data from 1987 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of bail, which Parker granted last Thursday after two
earlier denials, was crucial in the minds of many of Lee's
supporters Tuesday, as well as to the government, which continued
to argue that Lee presented a grave threat to national security.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is charged with downloading weapons test and design data
onto 10 portable computer tapes, seven of which are missing. Lee
has indicated through his lawyers that he destroyed the tapes, but
the government maintains that the tapes could alter the balance of
global power if Lee spirits them away to a hostile power after his
release.
</P>
<P>
   The judge appears to have accepted the defense's claims that
those assertions are exaggerated. And while the judge also rejected
the government's request to delay by one week Lee's release on $1
million bail, he did ultimately grant a three-day stay to give
prosecutors time to prepare an appeal and to receive permission to
file it from the U.S. Solicitor General.
</P>
<P>
   The judge reversed a previous order denying Lee bail after
receiving new information at a dramatic hearing two weeks ago,
including an FBI agent's admission that on several critical
occasions he had provided incorrect testimony that had made Lee
appear deceitful when he had not been.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must note that had Judge Parker been provided the complete
record in December, Dr. Lee would not have spent eight months in
solitary confinement in shackles,'' said Mark Holscher, one of
Lee's attorneys, after Monday morning's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Parker agreed to slight modifications in the
conditions of Lee's release. These include changes such as an
explicit order that Lee can garden in his back yard, that he can
use an ambulance if he requires emergency medical treatment, and
that staff members of the Albuquerque law firm representing him can
pick Lee up and transport him to and from the courthouse here to
meet with lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   The judge tersely rejected arguments by the lead prosecutor,
George Stamboulidis, that tight restraints needed to be imposed on
Lee's communications with his wife, Sylvia, and on his wife's
communications with third parties outside their home near Los
Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll reject that out of hand,'' Parker said when Stamboulidis
began discussing limits on Lee's conversations with his wife.
</P>
<P>
   When Stamboulidis argued that Lee might use his wife to
unwittingly pass along a coded message that would result in the
transfer of weapons secrets, an act of espionage, Parker expressed
pointed skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scenario you described suggests Dr. Lee would consciously
subject his wife to an offense that cold subject her to the death
penalty,'' he said in rejecting any restraints on Mrs. Lee's
communications outside the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just glad he's getting out,'' said Alberta Lee, Lee's
daughter. ``Any conditions are fine.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5530 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-KURSK-LESSONS-HNS &LR;      08-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KURSK-LESSONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE KURSK TRAGEDY SHOULD LEAD TO JOINT U.S.-RUSSIAN RESCUE
EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     Commentary  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MILLARD HARMON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Kursk disaster provides insight into Russian
society at as time when the nation is still in transition.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian delay in seeking outside help was a throwback to a
time when such a disaster would not have been known beyond Soviet
military/government circles. Ending this tradition of secrecy
within 48 hours after the accident shows progress toward a more
open society, a requirement for democracy to function there. This
is a plus for Russia and should be celebrated in the West for what
it is: A historic reversal of the centuries-old policy of hushing
up official embarrassments.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Vladimir Putin, inexperienced in the ways of
leading a democracy, may be the greatest benefactor of the Kursk
disaster because it taught him a valuable lesson: A top government
leader cannot continue a well-deserved vacation where there is a
free press functioning at a time of national crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian media kept the pressure on Putin to break off his
vacation and demonstrate concern about the fate of the Kursk. He
was criticized for his slow response, though it is possible that he
was relying on official _ and misleading _ advice from his military
advisers that the boat would be rescued. At any rate, if he had it
to do all over again, I bet Putin would have hustled to Murmansk to
oversee the rescue operations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the matter of the belated request by Russian
military leaders for outside help.
</P>
<P>
   When they finally got around to asking for foreign assistance,
they turned to Norway and Great Britain, despite the fact that
top-of-the-line rescue equipment was available in the United States
and was easily transportable worldwide within 24 hours by a U.S.
Air Force C-5 cargo aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian reluctance to call on the United States reflects a
kind of Cold War distrust that if Russia sought help from the
United States, U.S. rescue personnel might find out a submarine
secret about the Kursk. Both the Russian and the U.S. navies are
always eager to learn more about the other nation's submarine
technology. But one would think that such concerns would evaporate
at a time of crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is now urging that the United Nations undertake
responsibility for ocean rescues of stricken military vessels. This
proposal serves him well at home by showing his concern about the
loss of life and portrays himself as a man of action. It also
avoids any partnership with the former Soviet Union's foe, the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of a fast-acting United Nations rescue team seems to me
to be a contradiction in terms. Nothing fast ever happens at the
U.N.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs of potential East-West rapprochement.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Russia and the United States are working on a
jointly operated center in Moscow that would protect each nation
against a missile launch based on erroneous information.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-Russian cooperation on the space station is another example
that points to a brighter day ahead for U.S.-Russian relations.
</P>
<P>
   We can hope that the naval leadership of both nations may
someday form a rescue partnership to act in future emergencies.
Submarine escape hatches could be standardized, techniques for
handling torpedo malfunctions could be addressed, and the 24-hour
delivery of U.S. rescue equipment could be extended to serve the
Russian fleet.
</P>
<P>
   Where human lives are at stake, I'm certain that citizens in
both countries would support such a submarine rescue partnership.
If the Kursk episode opens the door to such an arrangement, the
deaths of Kursk crewmen will not have been in vain.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Millard Harmon, a frequent visitor to Russia, is a former
administrator with the State University of New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1845EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5531 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-BOS &LR;      08-29 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-DEBATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROXIMITY OF JFK LIBRARY FUELS DEBATE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The sponsors of the first proposed presidential debate
adamantly rejected suggestions Tuesday that the University of
Massachusetts in Boston doesn't constitute ``neutral territory''
for the event because it adjoins the John F. Kennedy Library.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the two institutions reacted cautiously to the
shots reportedly aimed their way by aides to Gov. George W. Bush.
The officials said they did not want to be drawn into a political
contretempts or be viewed as taking sides.
</P>
<P>
   UMass-Boston was chosen by the nonpartisan Commission on
Presidential Debates as the venue for the first of three debates
between Bush and Vice President Al Gore. Gore has accepted the
offer, while Bush says he it is one of many he is considering.
</P>
<P>
   The Kennedy Library is co-sponsoring the Oct. 3 event and
putting together educational programs leading up to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally ... absolutely neutral territory,'' said Tom
McNaught, the Kennedy Library spokesman. He pointed out that Bush's
father had recently been honored at the library as a Distinguished
American, receiving an inscribed bronze bust of the slain president
from Kennedy's daughter, Carolyn.
</P>
<P>
   The UMass spokeswoman, Annmarie Lewis-Kerwin, also underscored
her institution's nonpartisanship. She added that preparations
hadn't been slowed by the brouhaha over debates because the
commission had assured university officials that the event will
take place on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has repeatedly said he would participate in all three
nationally televised, prime-time events _ and in just about any
other head-to-head confrontation anyone wants to hold. The
Democrat's campaign chairman, William M. Daley, sent a letter to
the commission Tuesday formally accepting its debate schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and his advisers, on the other hand, have expressed
reservations from the start about both the planned format and
venues. The commission, which has been setting up presidential
debates since 1988, is headed by Paul Kirk Jr. and Frank
Fahrenkopf, the former chairmen, respectively, of the Democratic
and Republican National Committees.
</P>
<P>
   Media accounts about Bush's apparent problems with the
commission's debate proposals have appeared since mid-August, even
as growing numbers of Americans have been turning their attention
to the presidential campaign since the two parties' nominating
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was revisited Tuesday in an article in the New York
Times that said Bush was balking at the commission's plans because
the three debates would be aired in prime time by the major
networks.
</P>
<P>
   The article said Bush officials had complained about holding a
debate on the UMass campus because it is so near the library of a
Democratic president. ``At face value,'' the Times quoted one
official as saying, ``it seems difficult to argue that it's neutral
territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush Tuesday derided as ``ridiculous'' the notion that he wanted
to avoid prime-time debates. ``I want as many people to watch our
debates as possible,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP candidate did not directly address the issue of UMass's
location. But a spokesman, Ray Sullivan, later dismissed as
``patently false'' any suggestion that the Bush camp might consider
the university to be an unfair site.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said in a telephone interview that Bush is ``seriously
considering'' offers to debate at more than 40 locations, with a
variety of formats. Asked specifically about the UMass issue,
Sullivan replied: ``We do not have a problem with any of the
venues'' proposed by the commission on debates.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Boston site, the commission has scheduled
presidential debates for Oct. 11 at Wake Forest University in
Winston-Salem, N.C., and for Oct. 17 at Washington University in
St. Louis. It has also planned a vice presidential debate for Oct.
5 at Centre College in Danville, Ky. Among the private contributors
to the Boston event are Fidelity Investments, Fleet Financial, the
Boston Globe, and the Boston Herald.
</P>
<P>
   Janet Brown, the commission's executive director, expressed
confidence Tuesday that all of those events would take place as
scheduled. She recalled that candidates in both parties in the past
have raised questions about format, timing, or other aspects of the
debates, but have always ultimately participated.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign seized on the Times account about Bush Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their problem is that when people learn about both candidates
and their plans for the future, they invariably agree more with
Gore than with Bush,'' said a Gore spokesman, Doug Hattaway. ``So
they're gasping for excuses to avoid prime-time debates.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff reporters Glen Johnson and Anne E. Kornblut contributed
to this report from Portland, Maine, and Albuquerque, respectively.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
