<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5532 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-ANGRY-DRIVERS-1000(2T     08-29 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGRY-DRIVERS-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FED UP WITH THE WHEEL WORLD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By LIZ STEVENS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I hate you.
</P>
<P>
   I know that sounds petty and small-minded, but I just can't help
it.
</P>
<P>
   There I am, proceeding cautiously through my green light, and
there you go, barreling in front of me through your red one. There
I am, patiently inching toward my freeway exit, and there you go
zipping by on the right shoulder, taking cuts.
</P>
<P>
   There I am, coasting down the interstate doing 68, hanging out
in the center lane, checking my rearview mirror frequently, like
the ``conscientious driver I am.'' And here you come, out of
nowhere, blasting toward my rear bumper like a nuclear warhead,
doubling in size every half-second that I glance back, and then _
just about the time your grill is threatening to eat my bumper for
lunch _ swerving into the next lane and high-tailing it out of
sight.
</P>
<P>
   Grrr. I despise you.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I have unrealistic standards. Maybe I'm just grouchy. But
it seems to me that there are an inordinate number of morons behind
the wheel these days and that they simply couldn't care less about
the rest of us good, kind folks.
</P>
<P>
   They tailgate. They weave precariously. They speed. They run
stop signs. They yell and make scary faces and offer up their
middle finger.
</P>
<P>
   It can make a girl, well, ``upset.''
</P>
<P>
   This bad behavior is not road rage, which, strictly speaking,
involves physical violence inflicted on one driver by another.
(Road rage incidents, for all their hype, aren't commonplace.) The
egregious conduct I'm talking about is stuff we encounter on the
road every day.
</P>
<P>
   The rude stuff. The dumb stuff. The stuff you're sure to witness
this Labor Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The experts call it aggressive driving, and it's a bit of a
conundrum for those who study it. Here's why: The roads are
actually safer than they've ever been. In 1999, the traffic
accident death rate was 73 percent ``lower'' than it was in 1966 _
thanks to seat belts, safer vehicles and safer roads.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that thousands of people still aren't dying
unnecessarily _ 41,345 last year, to be exact. But it also doesn't
jibe with the studies indicating that Americans are increasingly
concerned that their fellow commuters are driving like kamikazes.
</P>
<P>
   According to annual surveys by AAA Mid-Atlantic, the number of
Washington, D.C.-area drivers who name aggressive driving as the
top threat on the road has risen each of the past five years. In
February, it peaked at 53 percent, up 7 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a reasonable argument to be made that
(driving behavior) may be deteriorating'' even though the death
rate hasn't climbed, says Lon Anderson, AAA Mid-Atlantic's director
of public affairs. Considering the improvements in road and car
safety, casualties on American roads should be much lower, he
believes. It's bad behavior that's killing us. Speeding alone
contributes to a third of all fatalities; alcohol is still a factor
in more than a third.
</P>
<P>
   ``People act like it's a competitive sport,'' Anderson adds.
``They'll risk life and limb just to arrive at the next traffic
light two cars ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem has not gone unnoticed by police and elected
officials. Numerous state legislatures have passed or considered
laws cracking down on aggressive driving. Two years ago, Dallas
Police responded with the Strategic Targeting Against Road Rage
patrol. On Thursday, San Antonio officially kicks off an elaborate
public-awareness program, complete with billboards and television
spots.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, the book ``Road Rage and Aggressive Driving,'' by
Leon James (aka ``Dr. Driving'') and wife, Diane Nahl, arrives on
store shelves.
</P>
<P>
   The two University of Hawaii professors have studied driving
behavior since 1981 and teach a class in traffic psychology. Their
expansive Web site, www.aloha.net-dyc, includes James' 1997
Congressional testimony on aggressive driving and results from
their Web-based surveys.
</P>
<P>
   There are a variety of reasons people might be more impatient
and impulsive on the byways. For one, congestion is epidemic in the
cities and suburbs, and commutes are longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are frustrated at how much they have to
drive,'' says Stephanie Faul, communications director for the AAA
Foundation for Traffic Safety. ``They're spending two hours a day
in their car, and they feel like they're wasting that time.
Commuting is boring, especially when you contrast it with the fast
pace of a lot of popular entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also dehumanizing,'' Faul adds. ``You don't see the other
people in cars as being human, you see them as other cars.''
</P>
<P>
   The menacing Dodge Ram. The snooty Mercedes. The bratty Ford
Focus. (Or, in my case, the minding-her-own-business Honda Civic,
which has just a slight problem gaining speed when entering the
freeway, so excuuuuse me!)
</P>
<P>
   MORE &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1856EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
