</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAKES PEACE PITCH TO EGYPT, AS DIPLOMACY SWEEP CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO, Egypt _ President Clinton tried to build Arab support for
a Middle East peace in an hour-long meeting Tuesday with President
Hosni Mubarak of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Clinton plans to continue the effort in separate
meetings with the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and Prime
Minister Enud Barak of Israel; Arafat and Barak will be in New York
for a U.N. meeting.
</P>
<P>
   In an early-morning refueling stop Tuesday on his return from a
three-day trip to Africa, Clinton met with Mubarak and a retinue of
aides at the Cairo International Airport. Clinton is eager to
resolve the decades-long standoff in the five months left of his
presidency, but officials say that in reality the end of September,
just before Israeli elections, is the last opportunity to reconvene
a gathering of Middle East leaders. Another deadline looming is the
Sept. 13 date that the Palestinians have spoken of for declaring a
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Time is short for resolving this,'' Clinton said as he stood
at Mubarak's side at the airport. ``And I think all the parties
understand that without the involvement and leadership and support
of Egypt, they won't be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Camp David talks collapsed last month without a deal,
administration officials complained that Palestinians had been
unwilling to compromise on key issues and that Arab leaders,
including Mubarak, had not been active enough in building support
for a pact.
</P>
<P>
   During those talks, Arafat insisted that East Jerusalem be the
capital of a Palestinian state and rejected proposals for shared
sovereignty over the sacred site known by Muslims as Haram al
Sharif and by Jews as the Temple Mount.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, a State Department spokesman who was asked about
the prospects for a three-way meeting in New York next week said he
had no specific information. But the spokesman, Philip Reeker,
insisted that the Camp David meeting ``produced significant
progress on all of the core issues'' and reiterated that the United
States was ready to support the peace process ``in any way
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the parties are ready to make the tough decisions, we're
ready to bring them together,'' Reeker said.
</P>
<P>
   News agencies on Tuesday quoted a senior Palestinian negotiator,
Nabil Shaath, as saying that Arafat and Barak would meet next week
in New York, their first meeting since Camp David. But Barak's
office later denied that a meeting had been set, and Shaath also
later distanced himself from such a session.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who leaves for South America on Wednesday morning after
a brief return to Washington, is engaged in a barrage of diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   During a day trip to Colombia, he will meet in Cartagena with
President Andres Pastrana to show U.S. support for the government's
counter-narcotics effort.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he was in Tanzania to witness the signing of an
agreement by some of the parties involved in the vicious armed
conflict between Hutus and Tutsis in Burundi.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you let this moment slip away,'' Clinton told the parties
in the Burundi dispute, reflecting on his involvement in numerous
international disputes, ``it will dig the well of bitterness deeper
and pile the mountain of grievances higher, so that someday, when
somebody else has to come here and sit at a table like this, they
will have an even harder job than you do.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he spoke from experience, having involved himself
in the entrenched disagreements in Northern Ireland, the Balkans
and the Middle East. Dennis Ross, the U.S. senior Middle East
negotiator, told reporters in Cairo that the latest round of
diplomacy was aimed at preventing progress made during the Camp
David talks from slipping away.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a window here,'' Ross said. ``There is a possibility,
and everything needs to be done to capitalize on that possibility.
We're determined to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross said Mubarak had made clear that the Egyptians were
prepared to do all they could to further the process. At the same
time, he said it would be the parties themselves who would have to
decide on peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, the Palestinians will make their own
decisions,'' Ross said. ``No one is going to make decisions for
them, any more than someone is going to make the decisions for the
Israelis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
