A5579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-WOMEN-BUSINESS-SCHOOL     08-29 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-BUSINESS-SCHOOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERING THE ART OF BUSINESS IN THE COMPANY OF WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  By   JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They were pioneers, those first women to set foot in a
business school. They struggled to be taken seriously in classes
and rarely read a positive word about businesswomen in their
studies. Then two Harvard Business School professors, fed up with a
male culture they thought antagonized female students, as well as
women academics like themselves, had a radical idea: a business
school just for women.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974, with $37,000 in grants and two typing rooms borrowed
from a women's college, they created a school with a feminist bent,
where women were guaranteed to dominate every class discussion.
</P>
<P>
   A quarter-century later, the Graduate School of Management at
Simmons College is still the only all-woman MBA program in the
world _ but how the world has changed. Other business schools have
thrown open their doors to women, even actively recruited them.
Women now make up 30 percent of business school classes, according
to the Education Department, up from 6 percent then, and hold about
half the middle-management positions, up from 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mission accomplished, in a way that would seem to make Simmons
obsolete. Yet this small, unaccredited school in Boston's Back Bay
has increased its class size 25 percent since 1995 while more
prominent business schools are struggling for applicants. Why do
they come? For the same things they seek in a workplace: supportive
colleagues, flexible scheduling and, they say, a chance to be
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Take the babies. ``I wanted mine to coincide with graduation,''
said April Steele, 32, one of seven pregnant women in her strategy
and leadership class this year. Their fellow students gave them no
second looks as they eased themselves into the auditorium chairs,
unless they were looks of sympathy. At one class, a discussion on
financial structuring even sidetracked to obstetricians and massage
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Would a classroom of men tolerate such talk? Not likely, Steele
believes. ``A guy would say, `Let's just move on,'' she said. When
her son was born earlier than expected, she brought him with her to
her final class.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Simmons prides itself on coddling students. Classes
follow the rigorous case-study method pioneered by the Harvard
Business School. But more of the cases feature women
decision-makers, and most are taught by women professors.
</P>
<P>
   More than gender separates her students from the majority of MBA
candidates. Their average age is 32, three years older than the
typical business school graduate. They have an average of eight
years work experience. The majority attend part time, and many are
jumping from jobs as teachers or nurses into business. Classes are
so flexible that a student can flip between day and night classes
and take up to five years to complete a degree.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them would not have gone to business school at all were
it not for Simmons, they say. ``Nontraditional'' students, like
women who did not finish college because of family obligations, are
welcome. (That, in part, is why the school remains unaccredited.)
Half of the applicants over 34 applied only to Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Steele was all but dragged into Simmons by one of her bosses, a
Simmons graduate. ``She gave me the kick I needed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the fiercely loyal network of alumnae is arguably one of
the most active among business schools. Graduates encourage others,
from 20-somethings to established career women, to give it a try,
providing the school with a steady stream of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   While about 20 percent of the students are from abroad, the
majority are locals who wind up in Boston-area companies. Last
year, BankBoston, which has since merged with Fleet, had more than
50 Simmons graduates as executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The joke around town is, `Oh, here comes another Simmons
grad,''' said Gail Deegan, class of 1978, and currently the chief
financial officer at Houghton Mifflin.
</P>
<P>
   When Anne Jardim and Margaret Hennig founded the school, their
focus was simple enough: to teach women how to get along in a man's
business world and how to cope with the so-called glass ceiling
that held them back.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, the sense was teaching women the rules of
the game,'' said Joyce K. Fletcher, a Simmons professor. ``Women
hadn't been socialized to really understand how businesses were
run.''
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Jardim and Hennig ran the school with the
devotion and verve of entrepreneurs. The two scholars, who wrote
the influential 1976 book, ``The Managerial Woman,'' saw Simmons as
a way to promote their thesis that men and women have distinct
management styles, with women more attuned to collaborative work.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most remarkable accomplishment of Simmons is its
ability to survive as its original purpose loses relevance. Laura
D' Andrea Tyson, dean of the Walter A. Haas School of Business of
the University of California at Berkeley and the first woman to
lead a major business school, said classroom equality has not even
been an issue in the two years of her tenure. ``It's certainly true
that the social conditions of the 1970s are not the social
conditions of today,'' Tyson said. ``The opportunities for women
have gotten better, and that's great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
