<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5581 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      08-29 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPLORING THE CULTURE OF WINE IN ANCIENT TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At Beaucaire, near Nimes in the south of France, the Durand
family operates two wineries. One is a typical modern winery
producing red, white and rose wines under the Chateau des Tourelles
label. The other is a re-creation of a Roman winery that thrived on
the site 2,000 years ago and whose remains were unearthed only 20
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can get to Beaucaire to visit Herve Durand's Roman
winery and taste his recreated Roman wines, known as mulsum and
turriculae. But the next best thing might be a visit to the
fascinating exhibition at the Jewish Museum in New York called
``Drink and Be Merry: Wine and Beer in Ancient Times,'' which runs
through Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Through workaday farm tools, gloriously illustrated ceremonial
vessels, paintings, sculpture and mosaics, the show traces the
development of wine and beer _ mostly wine _ since the dawn of
history to the rise of Islam in the seventh century.
</P>
<P>
   While the exhibition emphasizes the consumption of wine and beer
and their place in ancient culture, there are exceptional
depictions of how grapes were grown and how wine and beer were
made. Most of the material is from Israel, where the exhibition was
created and shown last year, supplemented by items from around the
Middle East and from Greece and Rome.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of intense research, no one has been able to determine
what grapes were grown in the ancient world or what kind of wines
were made. From ancient texts it is known that there were many
varieties of wine. As the handsome catalog accompanying the show
notes, ``the Talmud refers to 60 types of wine, discussing them in
terms of their quality, value and use.''
</P>
<P>
   What is known is that some, if not most, ancient wines were made
from fermented raisins. This would mean wines with higher alcohol
levels and increased sugar, which may be one reason the ancient
records speak so often of mixing wine with water. (Such mixing is
still commonplace where hot climates produce high-alcohol wines.)
</P>
<P>
   Pliny the Elder listed 80 wine types and grape varieties,
two-thirds produced in Italy, while the historian and geographer
Strabo, who lived in the first century B.C., concluded that there
were perhaps 130 kinds of wine.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that grapes were cultivated as fruit _ not
necessarily for wine _ in the Neolithic period. Agricultural
archaeologists know, too, that the vines that produced the best
ancient wines were Vitis vinifera, the most important species for
modern wine production. There are now _ and presumably were then _
thousands of varieties of Vitis vinifera.
</P>
<P>
   There were apparently many grades of wine. Excavations at
Masada, the site of King Herod's fortress, turned up the Roman wine
jugs called amphoras bearing the inscription ``For Herod of
Judea.'' Evidently, Herod was partial to Italian wine. Some
amphoras were inscribed, ``From the vineyards of Lucius Laenis,''
who may well have been the Robert Mondavi of his time.
</P>
<P>
   There must have been considerable spoiled wine, because the
fermentation jugs on display show no efficient way of keeping air
out during fermentation. That may explain why so much wine was
flavored. Spices like myrrh were used; so were honey, balsam,
pepper and wormwood.
</P>
<P>
   In Rome, new wine was actually a base from which various drinks
could be made. As Durand put it: ``They added plaster to temper the
wine's bitterness, clay to combat its softness, lime to deacidify
it, saffron to color it and mushroom ashes to bleach red wine
white. Among other things, they added roasted date pits, egg white
and pork blood to wine _ even saltwater, to satisfy the Roman
craving for salt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooden barrels or casks were unknown until the third or second
century B.C. In the ancient world, wine was fermented, stored and
shipped in the amphora, an earthenware jug with a narrow neck, two
vertical handles, wide shoulders and a pointed bottom that was
inserted into a wooden base.
</P>
<P>
   Ranging from little more than a liter to well over 1,000 liters,
amphoras were ubiquitous in the ancient world. Thousands have been
found, mostly in shards but many intact. It is thought that
thousands lie on the sea bottom, particularly the Mediterranean, in
the holds of wine- and oil-carrying ships lost thousands of years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Probably because of the large number of exquisite objects it
displays, the exhibition may seem to emphasize the ceremonial side
of wine culture over the commercial. But it does devote
considerable space to the ancient wine trade.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first vessels for shipping wine was the earthenware
Canaanite jar. The exhibition includes one from the 14th or 13th
century BC, when the jars were common in the eastern Mediterranean,
often carrying wine from Canaan to Egypt. When what is now Israel
was under Ptolemaic rule, Canaan was Egypt's primary source of
wine.
</P>
<P>
   The amounts of wine consumed in the ancient world can only be
interpolated from other records, but they were not inconsequential.
A Roman winery whose ruins were discovered in northern Spain is
estimated to have produced some 75,000 liters of wine a year.
Attached to the reconstructed Roman winery at Beaucaire was a
pottery that is estimated to have produced 3,000 to 4,000 amphoras
a day. They would have had a capacity of almost Gallolike
proportions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
