<SLUG> BC-MA-CENSUS-BABIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWBORN WHITES IN MINORITY IN BOSTON FOR FIRST TIME: CENSUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Balloons and teddy bears filled the nursery at Boston
Medical Center last weekend. Twelve infants lay in their cribs,
eyes shut, looking snuggly in their prams.
</P>
<P>
   Though they don't know it, they represent the changing face of
Boston. Six black babies. Two Latinos. One Asian. Three whites,
according to a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Whites once made up the majority of births in Boston. Now,
they're the minority. In fact, for the first time black children in
nearly every age category outnumber white children in Suffolk
County, according to US Census statistics released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999 the Census estimates that 13,790 white children under
age 4 were living in Suffolk County, which incorporates Boston and
the adjacent communities of Chelsea, Revere and Winthrop, compared
to 20,630 black children. Ten years ago, the Census counted 19,165
white children and 16,447 black children under age 4.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues, the new generations of babies will not
only dramatically alter the racial balance of the city but touch
off major shifts in social policy, school curriculums, media
programming and _ as evidenced in heavily minority cities like Los
Angeles _ ethnic strife, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``As minority children increasingly become the majority, class
and ethnic and racial issues will crystallize around deficits in US
policy relating to education and health care,'' said Charles
Derber, professor of sociology at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Though the birthrate of whites continues to drop on a percentage
basis, whites still far outnumber black statewide _ 5.5 million to
405,000. But in urban areas the growing change in racial balance is
more apparent.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Boston Health Commission's study of 1998
births, Latinos had the highest birthrate, followed by
African-Americans, then Asians, then whites.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the nation, fewer white children are being born than
in years past. The birth rate of white women is 1.9 children,
compared to 2.9 children for Latinas _ the highest rate of any
ethnic group, according to the Census.
</P>
<P>
   Black births are expected to increase steadily by 60 percent
between now and 2050, Asian births are expected to triple, and
Native American births will increase by half.
</P>
<P>
   There are a myriad of reasons for the declining birth rate among
white women: They tend to have more demanding careers, and for that
reason put off having children. Also, in Latino, Asian and
African-American cultures women are expected to put children first,
careers second.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just happening in the United States. You have to
look at white women in an international context,'' said Sheila B.
Kamerman, professor at the Columbia University School of Social
Work and director of the university's Institute for Child and
Family Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The birth rate of white women in industrial countries throughout
Europe has been declining steadily to its current rate of about 1.6
children per woman, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, whites watching the rising births of
minority children may use their political strength to focus on
issues relating to non-minority issues, and steer money away from
issues like public education, specialists say. But eventually as
minorities vote in larger numbers, the balance of political power
will shift.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will have to recognize that other people's children will be
the ones who will be contributing to society,'' Kamerman said.
``They are the ones who are going to be paying the social security
benefits of the elderly in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   She cites California as an example of what happens as minority
populations grow and begin to flex their political muscle. In the
mid-'90s, amid growing anti-immigrant sentiment, California voters
passed anti-affirmative action initiatives that affected minorities
in education, government jobs and schools. Those initiatives have
been struck down in the courts, and politicians these days steer
clear from the issue. Along the way, a large percentage of people
of color _ most notably Latinos and Asian-Americans _ registered to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perspective has switched. People recognize the fact that
minorities will be the majority in California not so far from
now,'' Kamerman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the change in complexion won't come easily in some areas,
says BC's Derber, who fears that as the minority populations swell,
whites will wall themselves off _ exacerbating the class economic
differences between the races.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles has become infamous in the '90s for essentially
producing an architecture and social culture in which a form of
apartheid is raised,'' Derber said. ``You almost have a two-caste
city in which you need pass keys to get into parks, where whites
live in gated communities.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
