<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0289 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5586 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SALT-DESSERTS-2TAKES-     08-29 1241
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALT-DESSERTS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN SWEETS ARE SWEETER WITH SALT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Also see SALT-VARIETIES) 
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It takes a certain kind of person to season sweet
roasted pineapple with salt, place it atop a salty nut brittle and
serve it as a kind of tart. Or to shower a molten chocolate cake
with coarse salt when it comes out of the oven. Or to saute
cantaloupe, sprinkle it with fleur de sel and serve it with a
spoonful of sorbet.
</P>
<P>
   There is such a person. In fact, there are several. That tart
was thought up by Claudia Fleming, the pastry chef at Gramercy
Tavern; the chocolate cake by Philippe Conticini, the chef at
Petrossian Boutique and Cafe; and the cantaloupe dessert by Alex
Asteinza, the pastry chef at Patria.
</P>
<P>
   They are part of a small group in New York who are taking a new
look at how salt is used in desserts, treating it as a tool to
heighten some flavors and contrast others; to assert its own
flavor; and sometimes, as with the chocolate cake, to give a dish
that surprising, delicate crunch. By doing so, they are entirely
changing the way dessert is conceived, approaching it more like a
main course, with a complex structure that balances sweet, salty,
sour and bitter components.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Fleming's pineapple dessert. It is a sublime
collaboration of distinct parts, not a marriage of flavors. A
circle of tiny triangles of roasted pineapple are pointed upward
like jagged peaks. Above them is a cap of black-pepper ice cream,
melting in the crevices. Below is a pebbly foundation of macadamia
nut brittle _ minute bits that shatter like ice in your mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Each has a flavor that feels somehow magnified: the pineapple is
exceedingly rich and succulent, the brittle buttery, the ice cream
minerally and smoky. But there is something else, too, and it is
not apparent on the first taste. Each component is heavily salted.
Taste it again and it will be unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   Salt in the brittle keeps the nuts from seeming flabby. Sea salt
on the pineapple tempers its sweetness, and a healthy dose of
kosher salt in the ice cream underscores the black pepper, making
it it a firm counterpoint to the sweet fruit. But mostly, the salt
adds dimension.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salt does the same thing in pastry that it does in cooking,''
Fleming said. ``It enhances flavor. It rounds out flavor, and it
makes everything seem to come together.'' It also makes you thirst
for more.
</P>
<P>
   Salt's traditional role in desserts was to elevate flavor. But
it was never used to this extent. A typical traditional recipe
calls for no more than a teaspoon. Cooks always assume that the
salt is table salt and that a hint is sufficient. It makes sense to
use more flavorful, mellower salts like sea salt, kosher salt and
delicate fleur de sel _ just as you would in cooking _ and to add
enough until you can taste the difference, until you've actually
seasoned the dessert.
</P>
<P>
   Fleming was enlightened by Conticini, a man for whom both salt
and carrots belong in desserts. For years, he has been stretching
dessert's definitions, using salt where it was never seen, spices
where they were never imagined, and including vegetables and foods
generally accepted as savory under the umbrella of sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   When he gives cooking demonstrations, one of his tricks is to
sprinkle fleur de sel on chocolate and give it to everyone within
reach. Fleming got it once, and it changed her. ``I was like
`Wow,''' she said, ``It made me salivate. It intensified the flavor
of the chocolate and it wasn't really salty. Using salt as a
garnish seemed suddenly natural.''
</P>
<P>
   At Petrossian, Conticini allows salt to get into all sorts of
unusual scenarios. Fleur de sel is sprinkled on hazelnut and
chocolate cakes. The crystals sparkle, like diamonds embedded in
soil. The salt does not emerge in every bite; just now and then a
faint crunch will appear. At these moments the flavor changes _ it
comes alive more, then retreats, and the cake becomes sweet again.
</P>
<P>
   A yablock at Petrossian (listed under the heading ``Teasers,''
which are defined as ``something truly new, unusual combinations of
flavor and texture that are guaranteed to delight the senses'')
contains green apple preserves, marinated carrot sticks,
caramelized popcorn and fleur de sel.
</P>
<P>
   The counters are lined with small stainless steel bins filled
with jellies, nuts, spices, compotes and fleur de sel for topping
ice cream; they are like the vials of powders in a laboratory. The
fleur de sel is sprinkled on the blinchick teaser, a cup filled
with caramel foam, molasses jelly, pears, coconut juice and vanilla
ice cream. It is Conticini's idea of a sundae and it is very good.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the innovators use salt with such abandon. In the
chocolate tart at Le Bernardin, the salt would only be perceptible
if taken away. The chocolate filling is dark, bitter and acidic,
and is mixed with enough butter to be as deadly as it tastes. It is
dammed up by a thin pastry crust, a component that could easily
seem inconsequential except that the salt in it contrasts with the
chocolate, providing some relief and at the same time making you
salivate for more.
</P>
<P>
   The difference the salt makes is very subtle, but to Florian
Bellanger, the pastry chef, it's just the kind of nuance that
distinguishes his work from others'.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is not to taste salt,'' Bellanger said, ``It's to
push the flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Herme, who, like Conticini, is known in France for his
willingness to experiment, began stretching the traditional role of
salt in desserts a decade ago when he discovered fleur de sel.
``It's one of the major ingredients,'' Herme said. ``If you want to
see what it can do, you get a slice of baguette, you put ordinary
chocolate on top, and you put it in the oven. After five minutes,
when it comes out, you sprinkle some olive oil and put maybe four
or five grains of fleur de sel on it, and you will see how fleur de
sel can push the flavor of the chocolate. It's amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt also has a chemical role. In doughs and pastry it enhances
texture as well. A brioche made without salt will be tough and
dense with a hard crust. Puff pastry will taste flat, greasy and
will not color.
</P>
<P>
   Salt has an unusual effect on fat, as well. ``When you eat sweet
butter on bread,'' Bellanger said, ``in your mouth you feel some
kind of fat, some kind of oiliness on the palate. If you do that
with salted butter you don't get that same sensation.''
</P>
<P>
   His Brittany butter cookies, made with salted butter, have a
clean finish. Though the cookies are loaded with butter, you are
left with a salty creamy flavor. This idea recently prompted
Fleming to experiment with her beignets, which she serves in lieu
of petit fours.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, she rolls them in sugar and cinnamon. But this time,
she rolled a few in a mixture of sugar, salt and cinnamon. Those
done her usual way tasted of oil; I was sated after one. Those with
salt maintained a sweet, clean taste, and they kept disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   Salt is most effective with rich, strong flavors. Most caramels,
for instance, are salted to counter the sweetness. In nut brittles,
cookies and ice creams, extra salt gives definition to the flavor
of the nuts and cuts down on their fattiness, if only deceivingly.
If you've ever tasted Ciao Bella's Heath Bar Crunch against any of
its other ice creams, the salt practically screams at you.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   At Eleven Madison Park, Nicole Kaplan, the pastry chef, decided
to use a pistachio paste made with salted roasted pistachios to
fill a pithivier. Even when folded into pastry cream, it had a
cloudlike lightness, and the flavor of the nuts came through
purely, without the interference of sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Acidic fruits like pineapple and passion fruit need salt to
soften their sharpness and to highlight flavors other than
sweetness. For her pineapple creme brulee, Kaplan first salts the
pineapple for about an hour, to draw off some of the liquid and
concentrate its juices, before roasting it.
</P>
<P>
   Some restaurant desserts are actually turning savory. Asteinza's
sauteed cantaloupe is a play on melon and prosciutto. The cooked
melon is sprinkled with both salt and pepper, served with thin
ribbons of fresh cantaloupe and a quenelle of gazpacho sorbet. (It
is as delicious as it is odd.)
</P>
<P>
   The point, however, is not that salt should be used so radically
or pervasively. Sprinkling a little fleur de sel over a warm rich
cake is an easy flourish. So is roasting nuts in sugar and salt
before adding them to cookies or ice cream. You can add more salt
to a cake batter when using a rich frosting or to cookie batter if
you're also adding chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when Fleming first made that black-pepper ice
cream at Gramercy Tavern, she asked Tom Colicchio, the chef, to
taste it. ``He said it needed salt,'' she said, ``and I thought,
`Salt?' Then almost granule by granule he added it, and we could
see the flavor come up. That was the beginning of salt and ice
cream for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Salt is not used superfluously in her desserts _ in fact, it
isn't perceptible in many of them. In the fall, she makes a concord
grape focaccia seasoned with raw sugar, sea salt and pepper. It's
clever, perhaps brilliant, and yet restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Her chocolate caramel tart with caramel ice cream is
unforgettable. Salt crystals on the surface of the tart look like
specks of dust on polished wood. Each bite of the tart is
relentless in its richness and changes as the salt crystals melt;
they are like flickers of light on your palate. From this intensity
you cross the plate, where a scoop of caramel ice cream sits. It is
bitter, almost malty, and also noticeably salty. You end up
bouncing back and forth between indulgence and relief, just as you
would with foie gras terrine and a Sauternes gelee. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED CANTALOUPE WITH FLEUR DE SEL  &QL; 
Adapted from Patria &QL; 
Time: 25 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 medium cantaloupes
</P>
<P>
   8 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon fleur de sel, or coarse sea salt finely ground
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Using a serrated knife, remove peel of both cantaloupes. Cut
them in half lengthwise. With a spoon, gently remove seeds, being
careful not to bruise the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   2. Set aside one cantaloupe half. Place remaining three halves
cut side down on a cutting board. Slice each half lengthwise into
six spears, for a total of 18 spears. Using a vegetable peeler,
shave remaining cantaloupe half into paper-thin slices, and
refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   3. In a large saute pan over low heat, melt 4 tablespoons sugar
until it liquefies and turns a light caramel color, about 1{
minutes. Add half the cantaloupe spears, and saute for about 30
seconds on each side. Add \ cup water, and simmer until water is
almost gone, about 5 minutes. Transfer cantaloupe to a plate, and
repeat with remaining cantaloupe spears, the remaining 4
tablespoons sugar, and an additional \ cup water.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, sprinkle spears evenly with fleur de sel. Place
three spears on each of six serving plates, and garnish with the
chilled paper-thin cantaloupe slices and two turns of freshly
ground pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
