<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0292 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5590 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SALT-VARIETIES-NYT &LR;      08-29 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SALT-VARIETIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN THE SALT OF THE EARTH ISN'T GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Also see SALT-DESSERTS)  
 By By MELISSA CLARK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All of a sudden, the city's chefs have gone salt
crazy.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a matter of too much or too little _ but what kind?
Preferably something so exotic the diner has never eaten it or
heard of it, and probably couldn't buy it anywhere within a
thousand miles. They're using a wild variety of salts for flavoring
and color, actually as garnishes like chopped herbs. The city is
becoming one big salt lick.
</P>
<P>
   At Esca, you might get pearly slivers of raw black bass
sprinkled with black lava salt from Hawaii. The sea scallop ceviche
at Aquavit glitters with sandy grains of delicate African salt. At
Red Cat, the foie gras wears a sparkle of $32-a-pound Hawaiian red
clay salt, a salt that had been used primarily in island rituals
before chefs there picked up on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clay adds a real earthiness to the foie gras that the
other salts don't contribute,'' said Jimmy Bradley, the chef.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year or so, chefs have begun using salts with the
discernment and, some might say, the fanaticism, that was long
reserved for the rarest olive oils. Today it's not uncommon to find
seven or more precious salts in a top kitchen. A chef who collects
them with a fervor that borders on obsession.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Samuelsson, at Aquavit, is constantly on the lookout: his
most recent find was the African clay salt he picked up on a trip
there. But he is also creating his own ``salts'' by drying and
grinding salty ingredients like serrano ham and duck confit. Michel
Nischan, the chef at Heartbeat, discovered his pink Peruvian sea
salt while watching a documentary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's from the Andes,'' he said. ``And they have a land-locked
ocean there, the salt lake that had dried out, and once a year they
harvest the salt. They go out with a saw and cut the salt into
large bricks and they mound them on their llamas. They travel with
them about 200 miles to the nearest city, and they trade them for a
year's worth of provisions. I saw it on the Discovery Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   The salt, he said, has a minerally quality: ``It's unbelievable
on sliced ripe tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   These salts are expensive _ they begin at $32 a pound, and cost
as much as $84 a pound for a smoked Danish salt that Nischan finds
essential for a salmon dish. It's a significant investment _
especially if you consider that plain table salt is about 25 cents
a pound. Some chefs have given that up completely.
</P>
<P>
   At Union Pacific, Rocco DiSpirito uses only sea salt; he even
salts the water for blanching vegetables and boiling pasta with
French sea salt. ``Sea salt tastes a lot better than mined salt,''
he said. ``It's got a real saline, ocean character that comes
across in the food.''
</P>
<P>
   Regular table salt and kosher salt are mined from the earth;
they are cheap and characterless because they must be highly
refined. Sea salt is produced from evaporating seawater. It can be
quickly evaporated and superrefined, and it sells for just a few
dollars, or it can be left with a lot of the minerals in it, like
the good, grayish or off-white sea salts, and the rarer kinds chefs
now covet.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular sea salts among chefs are sel gris, a moist
gray, large-grained salt usually from Brittany or Normandy, and
fleur de sel, an expensive, gently flavored, off-white salt with
small lacy flakes.
</P>
<P>
   Pierre Herme, the French pastry chef, is so completely enamored
of fleur de sel that he never leaves home without it: for the last
10 years he has carried a small, specially made wooden box filled
with it in his briefcase at all times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I often have to use it in restaurants,'' he said. ``It can
even turn a bad meal into something not so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite of Bradley at Red Cat and other chefs is farmed
in Essex, England. Maldon sea salt has characteristic
pyramid-shaped crystals that shimmer in the light like diamond
chips. This salt, like the red clay and most of the more exotic
salts on the scene, is best raw. Bradley compares the salts to the
best quality extra virgin olive oils.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you cook with them,'' he said, ``their flavors diminish.''
</P>
<P>
   Hence the raw fish dishes at Esca called crudos. What makes more
sense than using raw sea salt with raw seafood? David Pasternack,
the chef there, uses a different sea salt with each kind of
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each of the salts possesses a different flavor,'' he said,
``and you have to learn how to use them to their best advantage.
The black salt tastes like you're taking a bite of the earth, so I
use that with a stronger fish. The red salt is milder, so it goes
with a blander fish.''
</P>
<P>
   For cooking, Pasternack sticks with relatively neutral salts,
like a fine-grained Sicilian. He then adds a more potent salt as a
garnish. In an appetizer of seared Maine shrimp, he seasons the
shrimp with the Sicilian salt, then cooks them in extra virgin
olive oil. To finish the dish, instead of a sauce the shrimp get a
drizzle of estate bottled extra virgin olive oil and a shower of
the black lava salt _ two kinds of olive oil and two kinds of salt
for five shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true that all of these unusual sea salts have their
own distinctive flavors, there is undeniably something to be said
for the aesthetics of their large crystalline grains and vivid
colors.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Colicchio, the chef of Gramercy Tavern, occasionally uses
Hawaiian red clay salt to finish a dish of white-fleshed turbot.
</P>
<P>
   When asked why he likes that particular salt with that
particular fish he replied, ``It shows up.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
