<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GOODY-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-TV-GOODY-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    DUEL TREAT: BATTLING 'BOTS, THEIR CREATORS(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By BILL GOODYKOONTZ(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) - Maybe I'm not a discerning enough viewer, but any
show in which someone on-camera can describe what happens as
``They're going to beat the crap out of each other for the
entertainment pleasure of all of us'' is OK by me.
</P>
<P>
   Hmm. Makes it sound like I'm talking about professional
wrestling. No way - that's (beginitalic)so (enditalic)20th century.
I'm talking about (beginitalic)BattleBots(enditalic), a new Comedy
Central series in which people don't fight. Remote-controlled
robots do.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a blood sport,'' Mack Anderson, an executive
producer of the show, told critics last month. ``It's an oil
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also, let's face it, a geek sport, if you want to call it a
sport at all.
</P>
<P>
   The show centers on fights - to the ``death'' - between robots,
which take place inside a big cage, the floor of which is equipped
with ``kill saws'' and the like to help increase the mayhem. And
there is mayhem aplenty.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a little rule of thumb,'' says ``battlecaster'' Bill
Dwyer. ``When sparks fly, robots die.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more entertaining than the battles are the nut cases who
build the robots in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We actually got a chance to do really in-depth coverage of
these people,'' Jason Sklar, one of the
(beginitalic)BattleBots(enditalic) reporters, said. ``We talked to
the men and women behind the men behind the robots.''
</P>
<P>
   And treated them with all the gravity that implies. This is
Comedy Central, after all.
</P>
<P>
   The builders of ``Mauler,'' for instance, are as wacked-out as
they get.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mauler's goal is total robotic domination worldwide,'' its
builder says. One of his sons makes the plan for that clear: ``You
have to make the other robot your {hellip}''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. The show's on cable; the newspaper is not.
</P>
<P>
   (beginitalic)BattleBots (enditalic)has guilty pleasure written
all over it. But it's more than that. The mini-features on the
competitors offer a nice little window on a different world. We all
remember the geek in high school - probably sat by himself at lunch
- who was so completely devoted to some sort of obscure, bizarre
activity that he might as well have lived on another planet. No one
truly understood him but those of his kind.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what became of him? He grew up and built remote-control
robots and fights with them on TV. And TV is better for it.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(a)arizonarepublic
</P>
<P>
   .com or (602) 444-8974.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
