<HEADER>
A5604 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-SATS-BOS &LR;      08-29 1059
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SATS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS BOOST MATH SCORES ON COLLEGE ACHIEVEMENT TESTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Culminating a decade of steady improvement, U.S. high
school students who took the SAT this year posted the highest math
scores since 1969, according to scores released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts students, meanwhile, posted rosy results of their
own, also improving on math while holding steady on the verbal
portion of the test.
</P>
<P>
   Bay State students scored an average of 513 on the math section
of the Scholastic Aptitude Test, up from 511 last year. Their
average verbal score remained at 511. The nationwide averages this
year were 514 and 505, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The Commonwealth also peformed well on Advanced Placement exams,
which cover subjects other than English and math and can be used
for college credit: Seventy-four percent of Massachusetts students
scored at least a 3 on a 5-point scale _ more than in any other
state.
</P>
<P>
   Buffeted by high failure rates on the MCAS, the statewide exam
that will count as a graduation requirement beginning this school
year, Massachusetts officials heralded the SAT and AP results
released Tuesday as proof that student peformance in the state is
improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a pleasure to have some good education news to talk
about,'' said James A. Peyser, who chairs the State Board of
Education. ``Our schools are getting better. Student achievement is
improving. These SAT and AP results are early indicators that
progress is a reality.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the College Board rolled out the state-by-state scores
Tuesday, some critics discounted the SAT gains as virtually
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Chester Finn of the Thomas B. Fordham Foundation, which
advocates standards-based education reforms like the ones under way
in Massachusetts, pointed to recent results on the National
Assessement of Educational Progress. Scores on that test, which is
considered a more accurate barometer of student performance than
the SAT, have remained fairly constant.
</P>
<P>
   ``These should not be taken as some kind of sign of a
renaissance in American education, or a sign that recent reforms
have had a big impact,'' said Finn, who believes it's too early for
such reforms to have taken hold. ``NAEP shows that we're holding
steady on an unacceptably low level.''
</P>
<P>
   Some colleges and universities are moving away from use of the
SAT in admitting students. Mount Holyoke College has stopped
considering it and the University of Massachusetts at Amherst
announced last year that it would give far less weight to the test.
</P>
<P>
   Even Peyser and Education Commissioner David P. Driscoll both
cautioned against reading too much into the SAT gains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, our students are doing better than average, but is that
good enough in our increasingly demanding economy?'' Peyser said.
``Yes, college-bound students in Massachusetts seem to have
brighter prospects, but what about those who do not plan to attend
college?''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reconcile the Bay State's relatively high SAT scores
with the high failure rates on the Massachusetts Comprehensive
Assessment System _ in 1999, 53 percent of 10th-graders failed the
math MCAS and 32 percent failed English _ Driscoll pointed to
several significant differences between the two tests.
</P>
<P>
   The SAT measures students relative to their peers, whereas the
MCAS is designed to measure them against specific academic
standards, Driscoll said. He noted that nearly every student takes
the MCAS, not just college-bound ones. And those who take the SAT
tend to be highly motivated _ and many are armed with strategies
they've learned in SAT preparatory classes.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan Learning Services, the nation's largest test-prep
company, has seen a 50 percent gain in enrollment in the past
decade, according to a company spokesowman.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, where 78 percent of high school students took
the SAT, the scores were close to the national averages. But the
state was above average when compared to other states with high
participation rates. Of the 23 other states with a participation
rate of 40 percent or higher, only four _ Alaska, New Hampshire,
Oregon and Washington _ had higher overall scores. And
Massachusetts officials noted that those four states have far less
diverse populations than the Commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the SAT scores released Tuesday continue a roughly
10-year trend. Scores declined throughout the 1970s and early
1980s, but they stabilized in the mid-1980s and have risen steadily
since then. Many attribute the initial drop to the fact that a far
larger and more diverse group began to take the test.
</P>
<P>
   SAT averages rose for most ethnic groups between 1990 and 2000,
but white students posted larger gains, so the gaps between them
have grown.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board, the century-old association of colleges and
universities that sponsors the SAT, links the rising scores to the
increasing rigor of classes. The College Board adjusted the SAT
scoring system in the mid-1990s, but reconfigured the scores so
they would match before releasing Tuesday's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The significant increase in this year's math score, and the
overall upward trend of the last 10 years, must be due, at least in
part, to changes in the courses students take in high school,''
said College Board President Gaston Caperton.
</P>
<P>
   Even some critics of high-stakes tests such as MCAS and the SAT
believe the numbers reflect well on American schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the longer term trend data does have meaning,
within the limited context that the SAT measures,'' said Bob
Schaeffer of FairTest, a Cambridge-based group opposed to the use
of the SAT in college admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that math scores have been regularly increasing, and
that verbal scores have remained constant despite the
ever-broadening population taking the test, suggests that those who
claim that schools are in crisis in the United States are not
telling the truth,'' Schaeffer said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not surprisingly, the CEO of The Princeton Review, an
test-prep company, had yet another view.
</P>
<P>
   ``SAT scores are up nationwide and The Princeton Review believes
it's a reflection of increased coaching for these tests,'' John
Katzman said. ``As a nation, we're becoming increasingly good at
test-taking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
