u f BC-COSMETICS-KING-NYT &LR;      08-29 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COSMETICS-KING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER OF CONTRARY THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Poppy King is Chief executive of Poppy Industries, an Australian
cosmetics and lingerie company; this was written with Becky
Gaylord)  
 By POPPY KING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   My biggest passion is flea markets, trash and treasure, vintage
stores and bric-a-brac.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not a collector of antiques, as such. That's the next level
up. One of my most treasured items is a handbag I got in the
markets in Marrakesh, Morocco. It's made out of silver. It's more
like a sculpture, really. I was terrified that when I went to, say,
India, I would see four million of these things and think, ``Oh my
God, here I am thinking it was so special.'' But I've never seen
anything like it again.
</P>
<P>
   I collect three wise monkeys. You know: see no evil, hear no
evil, speak no evil. I just love the concept. I've got lots of old
mirrors, lipstick cases and powder compacts. I got the bug for it
through my mum, a mad collector of things, who dragged me around to
the flea markets of Paris when I was little.
</P>
<P>
   As a little girl, I was obsessed with the idea of what it was
like to be a glamorous lady, playing dress-ups and clunking around
the place in Mum's high heels. I was also a terrible little wimp.
I'd never get up on the monkey bars or play with frogs. Today, I
won't do anything where I might break a bone. You don't find me on
the ski slopes zooming down mountains.
</P>
<P>
   I just bought two little puppy dogs, little girls, Sugar and
Spice. They are little fox terriers crossed with Chihuahuas.
They're absolutely gorgeous. Spice is so brave. She'll just leap
into things. It's amazing because you really can see how everyone,
dogs included, have this innate nature.
</P>
<P>
   When I was 18, I concentrated on very important things, like
lipsticks. I'd watch old movies, and the movie stars used to have
lipstick that wasn't glossy, that was deep-colored and matte. I was
asking around department store counters about matte lipsticks. One
sales girl said to me, ``Look, if I had a dollar for every time
someone asked me for a matte lipstick, I'd be rich.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how it crystallized. I just sat down with the yellow
pages and started ringing manufacturers. I had in my mind's eye the
idea of what I wanted. A lipstick that was almost like a crayon. I
spent a year working with the manufacturer. I went through 30
different formulas. There was a lot of puckering up. I remember
thinking, ``Well, if the whole thing doesn't work, at least I'll
have a lifetime supply of lipstick I like.''
</P>
<P>
   I had no hope of going to a bank. I was 18. I had no security to
offer. Starting a lipstick business? I wouldn't have even got
through the door.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't happen very often someone comes to you and says,
``Hey, I've got some money.'' A lot of people get afraid to show
they don't know something. I was willing to talk about it, to
search, to look, to think differently. It helped me get my start.
To muscle into the cosmetics market with $24,000 in your war chest
_ not exactly big bucks.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I didn't even have a drivers license. So, my mum
would drive me to the manufacturer and sit in the car and do her
knitting while I was inside trying on lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   My mother brought my up brother and me pretty much
single-handed. My father died when I was really young. I was always
encouraged to think differently. Ultimately, that's been a
blessing, but also a liability.
</P>
<P>
   I got expelled from school when I was 12. It was a regimented
private girls school. I'd been there since kindergarten. My mother
was supportive because she knew I hadn't been awful, stealing or
taking drugs. I had been a bit precocious. But they told me I was
too different, that I didn't think like everyone else.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
