<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5606 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ALLEN-PERELMAN-NYT     08-29 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-PERELMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO COMIC MINDS THAT APPEAR TO HAVE WORKED ALIKE 
</HEADLINE>
  By   MEL GUSSOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the recently published ``Most of the Most of S.J. Perelman,''
a portmanteau of Perelmania in the Modern Library Humor and Wit
Series, Woody Allen is quoted as saying: ``What happens to you when
you read Perelman and you're a young writer is fatal because his
style seeps into you. He's got such a pronounced, overwhelming
comic style that it's very hard not to be influenced by him.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the following a matter of influence? Or a homage? Or is it
simply a coincidence?
</P>
<P>
   Inept crooks take over a failing store with the idea of digging
a tunnel from the basement to the vault of a nearby bank. Almost
immediately everything goes awry. The thieves know less about
tunneling than they do about safecracking, and customers keep
coming into the store, which is an unwelcome intrusion. But before
the caper is complete, a legitimate business deal brings in a
windfall.
</P>
<P>
   This is the basic plot of Allen's movie, ``Small Time Crooks,''
and also of ``The Night Before Christmas,'' a play by Perelman and
his wife, Laura (the sister of Nathanael West and Perelman's
frequent screenwriting partner). The Perelman family comedy had a
brief Broadway run in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   The similarity of the shenanigans in the two comedies over a
period of almost 60 years was pointed out by the artist Al
Hirschfeld, who saw both the play and the movie. He was a close
friend and collaborator of Perelman and is also a friend of Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Each work has its own twists and turns. In the movie, Tracey
Ullman, playing the wife of the gang leader ( Allen), opens a
cookie shop that becomes phenomenally successful. After about a
half-hour Allen, as director and screenwriter, abandons the caper
and switches to a travesty of social climbing and of the idle rich.
</P>
<P>
   The play, which takes place in a lackluster luggage shop on
Sixth Avenue in Manhattan, is less concerned with the bank robbery
than with the eccentric characters in the neighborhood, busybodies
and fussbudgets who keep wandering into the store and interrupting
the action. Accidentally the thieves dynamite their way into a
delicatessen, which leads to jokes about cole slaw and hot
pastrami. Eventually the store is sold for a high price to the
bank, and everyone _ or almost everyone _ ends happily.
</P>
<P>
   When Allen speaks about his great regard for Perelman, he is
referring to him as an essayist and not as a screenwriter for the
Marx Brothers, or in his lesser role as a playwright. Only two of
his shows could be marked as successes, the Kurt Weill musical
``One Touch of Venus'' and ``The Beauty Part.''
</P>
<P>
   The essays omitted from ``Most of the Most of S.J. Perelman''
(for copyright reasons) are those from the book ``Westward Ha!''
That collection began with the story of ``Sweet Bye and Bye,'' a
musical that Perelman wrote with Ogden Nash and Hirschfeld. In
Perelman's words, the show ``closed in Philadelphia like a 10-cent
mousetrap,'' sending him and Hirschfeld on a round-the-world
journey. He continued to be discouraged about his theatrical
career. As he wrote in a self-portrait: ``Retired today to peaceful
Erwinna, Pa., Perelman raises turkeys, which he occasionally
displays on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen was 5 when ``The Night Before Christmas'' opened, and
closed after 22 performances. So far as is known the play has had
no major revival. It is long out of print, although Samuel French,
the theatrical publisher, found an archival copy from which a
duplicate was made.
</P>
<P>
   There is an antic and occasionally a frantic quality to the
humor. The thieves could have been sketches for characters to be
played by the Marx Brothers. The pretentious leader of the gang,
Otis J. Faunce, could have been made to measure for Groucho. The
gangster dialogue, which Perelman drew from a con man of his
acquaintance, is quaintly colorful. ``Yeah, I was sneezed in Saint
Joe,'' says one ex-con. ``I was the wire for a cannon mob and I run
into a wrong shamus.'' There is also, unfortunately, a sentimental
love story between a drugstore clerk and a gun moll. Still there
are slyly amusing moments in this screwball farce, and because of
the authorship it is worth a second look.
</P>
<P>
   According to Perelman's biographer, Dorothy Herrmann, before the
play opened on Broadway, it had been turned down by George S.
Kaufman, and after its failure, Perelman's agent hawked it in
Hollywood, where it was rejected by Abbott and Costello, W.C.
Fields and the Marx Brothers themselves. Then Edward G. Robinson,
looking to diversify his tough-guy career, decided to make the
comedy and play for laughs.
</P>
<P>
   Retitled ``Larceny Inc.,'' with Robinson's character now named
Pressure Maxwell, the movie opened in 1942. The cast included
Broderick Crawford, Jackie Gleason, Jack Carson, Anthony Quinn and
Jane Wyman (as the moll).
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, there is no patent on the idea of bumbling bank
robbers. Think of ``Big Deal on Madonna Street'' or Allen's ``Take
the Money and Run,'' in which, as Virgil Starkwell, he passes a
holdup note to a bank teller saying that he has a gun, and the
teller corrects his penmanship, insisting that the word as written
is gub and is therefore invalid. Gub or not, the subject is open
for recycling.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever heard of Perelman's play, ``The Night
Before Christmas,'' Allen said, ``Now I have heard of it.'' He
added that in reference to Perelman's Broadway career, he had only
been aware of ``One Touch of Venus'' and ``The Beauty Part.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that in preparation for ``Small Time Crooks,'' he
thought about Ernst Lubitsch's classic, ``Trouble in Paradise,''
``and all those other heist movies I had seen, `Rififi,'
`Topkapi''' _ and of course ``Take the Money and Run.''
</P>
<P>
   Most likely two wits, mutual admirers, simply thought along
related lines. There is, however, another possibility. The Modern
Library series is edited by Steve Martin, who as a humorist owes
his own debt to Perelman and perhaps to Allen. In the introduction
to the series he says that before he started writing he had ``heard
of S.J. Perelman, James Thurber and their like, but I was also
aware that they were heavily influenced by me, even lifting some of
my ideas, backdating them, and carefully inserting them in
magazines from the 30s with the clever use of a razor blade and
glue.''
</P>
<P>
   Following this line of reasoning, it could be said that it was
S.J. Perelman who borrowed from Woody Allen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
