<HEADER>
A5609 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-HOME-DEPOT-WEB0930-CO     08-29 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-DEPOT-WEB0930-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Home Depot opens first Web store, in Las Vegas
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Home Depot has opened the doors of its first Internet
store to customers in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta shoppers will have to wait until at least next
year to click into the retailer's online warehouse. Atlanta-based
Home Depot has been testing e-commerce on a group of professional
remodelers in Las Vegas and plans to roll out Internet sales to
other customers slowly, market by market.
</P>
<P>
   Next online will be San Antonio and Austin, Texas, said Jeff
Cohen, group president of direct marketing businesses. He would not
say when Home Depot's online store would go live in all of the
retailer's markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point in the process, that's difficult to pin down...
the exact schedule will have to do with the results that we see (in
Las Vegas),'' Cohen told analysts and reporters during a conference
call. ``We're committed to be out in several markets this year,
then we're going to take a pause, reflect on that experience and
move forward...as soon as prudently possible.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, consumers everywhere can access hundreds of
pages of how-to information for household projects at
homedepot.com, he noted.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also said it is too early to forecast Internet sales. Home
Depot's direct retail rival, Lowe's Cos., has projected that its
upcoming Internet venture will boost annual sales by at least $1
billion a year initially.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot's long-simmering strategy has taken several turns in
the past year or so. Both Home Depot and Lowe's pushed back their
starting dates as they dealt with the challenges of hanging their
shingles in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot originally set a target date of last fall for its
Internet sales launch, but the project was delayed by a series of
changes late last summer. In August 1999, the retailer said it
would put off the launch by several months because of a major shift
in strategy. Instead of testing sales of a few product categories,
Home Depot decided to load its inventory on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Then in May, Home Depot said it would offer online sales to
contractors, electricians, plumbers and other business customers
first, and then roll out sales to the homeowner market.
</P>
<P>
   Las Vegas was picked for the launch because Home Depot wanted to
take advantage of a test it's conducting with professional
customers there. Home Depots in Las Vegas and several other test
markets have been offering special services to the professionals.
Employees take orders for large quantities of building materials
and other supplies, then pick and pack the orders and have them
ready for pick-up at ``will call'' centers.
</P>
<P>
   The staff that's assigned to the professional test will handle
the Internet-based orders, which can either be picked up or
delivered to customers.
</P>
<P>
   Like Home Depot, Lowe's plans to launch commercial sales market
by market, on lowes.com. North Wilkesboro, N.C.-based Lowe's
started selling certain tools, ceiling fans and steel doors through
affiliated manufacturer sites in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Lowe's site for do-it-yourself customers will go live in all
Lowe's markets but with a limited number of product categories.
Appliances and tools will be the first categories loaded on the
site. Internet sales of those products should be ready by the end
of October, according to the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   While some Internet pundits have criticized Home Depot for
moving slowly on Internet sales, many analysts have defended the
retailer's cautious approach. Home Depot is known for thoroughly
testing new products and services in limited markets before putting
them in all stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are only so many growth initiatives that a store can
undertake at one time,'' said analyst Wayne Hood of Prudential
Securities. ``The market-by-market strategy makes the most sense
because you can resolve problems on a small scale.''
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said one of the most time-consuming aspects of the
Internet launch was loading the retailer's massive inventory of
products online. Each Home Depot store carries 40,000 to 50,000
products, but the product mix varies widely in different parts of
the country. In all, the retailer has a master list of about
400,000 products, said Ron Griffin, chief information officer.
</P>
<P>
   Griffin noted that the company invested heavily upfront to build
a Web site that can easily be updated for new or outdated products,
or different languages as the retailer expands internationally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time an item is added or deleted in our store, it's
instantaneously changed on the Web site,'' Griffin said. ``It's
like putting our store systems on steroids.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
