<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5613 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SHAKESPEARE-FIENNES-T     08-29 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAKESPEARE-FIENNES-THEATER-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO POWER PLAYS BY SHAKESPEARE, ONE RALPH FIENNES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 3)  
 (Editors: Also See CORIOLANUS-THEATER)  
 By ALAN RIDING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ It is almost a rite of passage for promising
Shakespearean actors to play ``Hamlet.'' More than most, though,
Ralph Fiennes seemed made for the part. Onstage with the Royal
Shakespeare Company in a variety of other roles and on screen as
the Nazi camp commander in ``Schindler's List,'' he had displayed
an intense introspection, a sort of irritable melancholy, that well
suited the role of the gloomy Dane. When the time came, his
``Hamlet'' was duly acclaimed in London and in New York, where he
won a Tony Award for best actor in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to Jonathan Kent, who directed Fiennes in both ``Hamlet''
and a 1997 production of Chekhov's ``Ivanov,'' the slim,
ascetic-looking Englishman was no less born to play the ill-fated
monarch in Shakespeare's ``Richard II.'' It was also a role that
Fiennes had admired but never performed, since he first saw the
play as a teen-ager in 1980. When looking for a new chance to work
together, actor and director had no trouble agreeing.
</P>
<P>
   To this fairly obvious choice, however, Kent, an artistic
director at London's Almeida Theater Company, added a more
innovative idea. Why not twin ``Richard II'' with ``Coriolanus,''
another Shakespearean political tragedy, albeit one that is
infrequently performed, indeed one that Fiennes barely knew? The
result is the program that begins on September 6 at the Harvey
Theater at the Brooklyn Academy of Music: 14 performances of
``Richard II'' and 12 of ``Coriolanus'' through Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier 14-week run this spring and summer, Fiennes and an
impressive ensemble of British actors presented both plays to
packed houses in the unlikely setting of a long-abandoned movie
studio in East London. After their New York stop, the performers
will travel to Tokyo for a limited run at the Akasaka Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of presenting two or more plays in repertory is hardly
a novelty. Last year, Kent's productions of Racine's ``Phedre'' and
``Britannicus,'' with Diana Rigg and Toby Stephens in both plays,
also went to the Academy after successful runs in London. More
daring perhaps is the idea of scheduling two plays on some days, as
Kent did with the Racines and is again doing now, as a way of
highlighting their differences and similarities. (The double bills
in Brooklyn are scheduled for Sept. 16, 23 and 30.)
</P>
<P>
   To Kent, the plays not only show constrasting aspects of
Shakespeare's genius; they also offer interesting end-of-millennium
reflections on the nature of power. ``The plays themselves could
not be more different in form,'' the director said in an interview
before the run ended at the former Gainsborough Film Studio in the
London borough of Shoreditch. `` `Richard II,' with its highly
wrought verse, is an exquisite artifact, while `Coriolanus,'
Shakespeare's last tragedy, is almost like free-form jazz. But both
are about men and their shadows, about men clad in their roles _
one of a king, the other of a warrior _ who have not developed
within that cladding. And as it is stripped away, they must
confront themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the burden is on Fiennes to make the pairing work,
although he evidently enjoyed testing his stamina. ``Actually, it's
not as exhausting as doing `Coriolanus' twice in a day, which we
did in the previews,'' he said softly, sipping a mug of tea at the
studio-turned-theater here. ``But, yes, it is exhausting. It's nice
to have the challenge and, at the end of the day, to think, `Wow, I
did `Richard' and `Coriolanus.'''
</P>
<P>
   One quiet and self-pitying, the other loud and insensitive, both
characters nonetheless bring on their own tragedies: Richard II,
the narcissistic English monarch who almost frivolously banishes
his cousin, Henry Bolingbroke, and seizes his land, only to find he
has provoked a rebellion that leads to his overthrow and death; and
Coriolanus, who, banished from Rome for scorning its citizens,
joins forces with his sworn enemy, Tulius Aufidius, only to be
dissuaded from sacking Rome by his all-powerful mother and, in the
process, to invite his own murder by Aufidius.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first thought about it,'' Fiennes recalled, ``it seemed
a very unusual pairing of plays. But Richard and Coriolanus are
both men in power who cannot handle their power. They're both
alone, as it were, isolated by the nature of who they are. They're
not good at opening up or arguing or debating. Richard has been
conditioned to be king and is unable to see anyone apart from
himself in his relationship to God as the divinely appointed ruler.
Coriolanus is completely trapped in how he should behave. It's a
situation created partly by his mother and partly by him with his
impossible arrogance and pride.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   In their political messages, both plays are also quietly
subversive. ``Richard II'' tells of the successful challenge to the
divine right of kings that paved the way for constitutional
monarchy in 1399. But two centuries later, Shakespeare still risked
royal displeasure in writing this play. After the Duke of Essex's
abortive rebellion against Elizabeth I, the angry queen had
proclaimed, ``I am Richard the Second, know ye not that?''
Shakespeare softened the blow by having the Bishop of Carlisle warn
of the ``disorder, horror, fear and mutiny'' that would follow
Richard's ouster, but today the play speaks more loudly of the
perils of absolute power.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coriolanus,'' on the other hand, has been exploited in modern
times by both the right and the left because, in Kent's words, ``it
poses questions and offers no answers.''
</P>
<P>
   Should the Roman citizens have bowed to Coriolanus' authority,
or were they right to impose the people's will? In Nazi Germany,
the play was presented as a paean to Hitler's strong leadership,
which prompted American occupation forces to ban it for eight years
after 1945. In East Germany, though, Brecht was soon portraying the
Roman masses as Marxist-inspired revolutionaries. A half-century
later, Kent's commoners are clearly defending democracy.
</P>
<P>
   To the political logic of twinning these plays was added the
practical consideration that they are easy to cross-cast. Thus, the
rising English actor Linus Roache plays both Bolingbroke and
Aufidius; Barbara Jefford is immensely convincing as the Duchess of
York in ``Richard II'' and as Coriolanus' viciously ambitious
mother, Volumnia; the veteran actor Oliver Ford Davies is the voice
of reason as both the Duke of York in ``Richard II'' and Menenius
Agrippa, the conciliatory Roman senator, in ``Coriolanus,'' and
Emilia Fox plays two long-suffering wives, Richard's Queen Isabel
and Coriolanus' Virgilia.
</P>
<P>
   Both Kent and Fiennes say they make a point of never reading
theater reviews. Had they done so, they would have learned that
London critics much preferred ``Richard II'' to ``Coriolanus.''
``Fiennes comes to the role of Richard as if by genetic destiny,''
wrote Paul Taylor in The Independent. ``The air of petulant
self-preoccupation, the arrogantly sensitive beauty, the mannered,
disdainful lyricism. In these qualities, character and performer
would seem to be soul mates.''
</P>
<P>
   In ``Coriolanus,'' however, instead of presenting a more
orthodox figure of ``authoritarian remoteness,'' as Fiennes put it,
the character is blatantly psychotic, turned into a killing-machine
by his mother, reveling in being drenched in blood as he emerges
victorious in battle. Most London critics were not won over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This role is a raging warrior, this actor is a melancholy
courtier,'' Alastair Macauley wrote in The Financial Times. ``You
can see his intelligence and his good intentions, but none of them
ever turn hard work into communicative acting.''
</P>
<P>
   Unanimous plaudits, though, went to the site used for
``Shakespeare in Shoreditch,'' as the program was known here.
Successively a power plant, the movie studios where Alfred
Hitchcock began his career, and a warehouse, the building was
marked for demolition when Kent won it a one-year respite. The
industrial rawness of the setting underlined the emotional and
physical violence of ``Richard II'' and ``Coriolanus.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Fiennes' decision to return to the stage after a
run of movies, most recently ``Sunshine'' and ``The End of the
Affair,'' fell into the ``you can't please everyone'' category.
There were those who sniped at the Almeida for playing the star
game, using Fiennes _ as it had Juliette Binoche and Kevin Spacey _
to pull in crowds. But others thought that high-profile stage
performances are good for theater for the same reason: They
encourage young people to view theater as special. Certainly,
Fiennes' fans would hear that view from him backstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When my film career started to take off,'' the actor said, ``I
was happy to leave theater behind for a while because I had done
lots of seasons at the National Theater and the Royal Shakespeare
Company. I was very happy to work in a different way. But after a
while I missed theater, not just doing Shakespeare but also the
routine. Going onstage, playing the play right through, no one says
cut, no one says stop, no one says there's a plane overhead, no one
says you've got a sound problem. There's something very pure and
freeing about that, the act of just being on the stage. In the end,
if I had to toss between the two, I would go for theater.''
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, he will be back. No doubt it will be Shakespeare again.
At 37, he believes he is too old for ``Henry V'' and too young for
``King Lear'' or ``The Tempest,'' though he has his eye on
``Macbeth,'' ``Henry IV'' and Iago in ``Othello,'' while Kent has
mentioned ``Pericles.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But going back to Shakespeare never seems like going
backward,'' Fiennes said. ``It's quite simply the most challenging
material for any actor to get to grips with. My mother used to put
on recordings of Olivier doing Shakespeare. I have always loved
language in a dramatic context, particularly Shakespeare. It
excites me the way some people get excited by jazz or opera or rock
music. It's just thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
