<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 BUSH-DEBATE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush wants three prime-time debates but won't commit to schedule
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By CLAY ROBISON 
and JULIE MASON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine _ George W. Bush said Tuesday that he wants
three prime-time debates this fall with his Democratic presidential
opponent Al Gore, but he refused to commit to a debate schedule
proposed by an independent commission.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, who is trying to make education reform the
focus of the campaign this week, spent much of Tuesday responding
to reporters' questions about his intentions for debating Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush denied the suggestion in a New York Times story that he
wanted to avoid prime-time debates against the vice president. The
story also reported opposition in the Bush camp to holding one of
the debates on property owned by the John F. Kennedy Library in
Boston, because that area was viewed as unfriendly, Democratic
territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is inaccurate. I welcome prime-time debates,'' Bush
said aboard his campaign plane on the way to Portland from Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would welcome all three being in prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has committed to a debate schedule outlined by the
Commission on Presidential Debates, which calls for three
prime-time meetings between Bush and Gore in October and one debate
between the Republican and Democratic vice-presidential nominees.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is a nonpartisan, nonprofit corporation that has
sponsored the general election presidential debates since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hasn't agreed to the commission's proposal, but says he
wants three debates with Gore and two between his running mate,
Dick Cheney, and Gore's, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp also prefers two vice-presidential debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that it was ``ridiculous'' for anyone to suggest that
he doesn't want to debate Gore in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want as many people to watch our debates as possible,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican nominee said that he wants a debate forum that
would allow a ``serious discussion'' of issues, rather than one
where the candidates ``can walk around the stage and act
dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure we'll be able to come to an accord about the three
debates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that of the Republican primary debates, he preferred
the ones that were ``more free-flowing _ that you could exchange
ideas without real rigid structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore claims to have accepted 40 debate invitations. Bush
spokeswoman Karen Hughes said the governor has received 53
invitations.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Bush campaign is considering several factors before
accepting any, including whether a debate could be broadcast on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is a candidate who thinks outside the box,
whether it comes to education policy or whether it comes to
debates. Vice President Gore is a candidate who is wedded to the
status quo. We're just exploring all the options,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Chris Lehane scoffed at the conditions and limits
he said are under discussion within the Bush campaign, such as
staging informal round tables on the Sunday morning talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's idea for the perfect debate would be on an Austin
public access channel during the Women's Olympic gymnastic
finals,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign on Tuesday released a letter to Frank
Fahrenkoph and Paul Kirk, Jr., co-chairs of the Commission on
Presidential Debates, supporting three, 90-minute presidential
debates in prime time available for all major networks and
including all the candidates certified for inclusion.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's rules allow only candidates with at least 15
percent support in five national polls. This would exclude
third-party candidates such as Ralph Nader of the Green Party and
Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is proposing presidential debates on Oct. 3, Oct.
11 and Oct. 17 and a vice-presidential debate Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are also eager to work with the commission and the Bush
campaign on the other issues of format and logistics that would be
needed to implement this proposal,'' said the letter, signed by
Gore campaign chief Bill Daley.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
