 PERSONALS: Miss California Puts on Her Game Face 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle news
file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
Miss California  &UR; Rita Ng &LR; , who was at Mr. Lee's salon in San
Francisco on Monday, said that although the Miss America Pageant is
a beauty contest, ``it's not beauty in the traditional sense of
being beautiful.'' She was there to consult with evening-wear
designer  &UR; Colleen Quen &LR;  and get advice from  &UR; Lee Bledsoe &LR;  on her
hair and appearance.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is a ``very strong feminist,'' a Phi Beta Kappa
graduate of Stanford University and model for such companies as
Cover Girl and Oil of Olay. Pageant organizers have provided her
with a personal trainer for the past six months, which is about
health rather than looks, said the 22-year-old. ``I never felt
pressure from Day 1 to lose weight or anything like that. People
ask me, `Don't you feel pressure?' I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Ng, who as Miss Los Altos beat out such contenders as Miss
Garden Grove, Miss Greater Stanislaus and Miss San Luis Obispo
County (formerly Miss Pismo Beach), has been accepted at the
University of California at San Francisco. She will begin medical
school next fall, deferring enrollment even if she doesn't become
Miss America so as to fulfill the obligations of being Miss
California.
</P>
<P>
   Win or lose, for example, she's going to the Riviera this fall
for Wente Wineries, one of the pageant sponsors, although she's not
sure what duties that trip will entail. She's also looking forward
to meeting  &UR; Mikhail Gorbachev &LR;  at an International Academy of
Achievement Summit.
</P>
<P>
   If there's one thing she would change about herself before the
pageant, she said, it would be psychological. ``My weakest spot is
that I'm not used to the tension. I've traveled all around the
world, and there's a lot of tension in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Her platform issue is ``promoting the health and welfare of
America's children,'' and she played Beethoven's ``Appassionata''
on the piano in the talent competition.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- Submarines may be sinkable, but Russian sailors sure know
know how to polish their brass buttons: A Vogue magazine ad for St.
John clothing features a blond model aboard the Russian battleship
Aurora, with nine snappily suited sailors saluting her.  &UR; Tiffany
Anastasakis &LR;  of St. John said the shoot had been set up with a
production company in Russia, but refused to say whether the
sailors or the navy had accepted a contribution in exchange for
their posing. ``They were very happy to do it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   -- &UR; Maya Angelou &LR; , who will take part in a benefit for the
National Poetry Association next weekend -- the group is chaired by
her son,  &UR; Guy Johnson &LR;  -- will travel cross-country from North
Carolina in a bus she has leased for the past year. The vehicle has
two drivers, which allows for nonstop travel, and Angelou finds it
so much more efficient than delay-ridden air travel that she's
thinking of buying it.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; AFFLECK GIVEAWAY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Brash is back and gauche is good,'' says the party column in
the new Harper's Bazaar. And charity begins in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   After  &UR; Ben Affleck &LR;  won $140,000 playing blackjack at the Hard
Rock Hotel and Casino there last weekend, he gave it all away, a
spy told the New York Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tipped out all of his chips to waitresses, dealers,
concierges, bell guys _ it was amazing. Some people were getting
$5,000, some people were getting more.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; QUEENS IN AUSTRALIA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Allen White &LR;  forwards a report in the Advocate on closing
ceremonies for the Olympics in Sydney, which an Australian
newspaper reported last week will include a tribute to Australian
cinema featuring drag queens from the movie ``The Adventures of
Priscilla, Queen of the Desert.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev.  &UR; Fred Niles &LR; , an Australian lawmaker, went on the
record to protest, saying that ``homosexual and lesbian behavior is
not a true representation of Australian culture and lifestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   Director  &UR; Ric Birch &LR;  said the drag queens were supposed to be a
surprise and acknowledged that it was supposed to make reference to
the sizable gay and lesbian community in Sydney, as well as the
movies. ``For the right-wing reactionaries or whatever part of a
community that is outraged about it,'' he told the Advocate,
``well, they're always going to be outraged.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; WHO SAID WHAT
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ```I'm not a puritan about cosmetic surgery,' Bruce says, &LR; 
 &UR; admitting she had a tummy tuck herself before her shamanic &LR; 
 &UR; awakening.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -- From a Health magazine story about  &UR; Eve Bruce &LR; , a
board-certified plastic surgeon and presumably unboard-certified
shaman.
</P>
