<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5620 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-PUBLISHING0830-COX     08-29 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLISHING0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Author of self-published book finds Internet delivers the buzz
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - This is the story of a David making his own way in a
world of Goliaths.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Bowerman is an Atlanta writer who released a
self-published book, ``The Well-Fed Writer: Financial
Self-Sufficiency as a Freelance Writer in Six Months or Less,''
this month. That alone isn't a particularly impressive Information
Age story. There's nothing new or high tech about self-publishing.
</P>
<P>
   However, through his ``guerrilla'' promotion, marketing and
publicity techniques, Bowerman is knocking down doors that normally
open only to the publishing Goliaths.
</P>
<P>
   His weapon of choice? The Information Age version of a slingshot
_ you guessed it _ the Internet. Bowerman says the Net gave him
``laser-like precision ... (that) gave me an ability to very
quickly get to my market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way that I could accomplish the amount that I
accomplished in the period of time I accomplished it,'' Bowerman
raves. ``Absolutely, categorically no way I could accomplish it
without the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before the book was printed, to drum up buzz for his
efforts, Bowerman launched his Web site, www.WellFedWriter.com. The
site grew to include sample chapters, a downloadable version of the
cover art, a sample radio interview, and, of course, the toll-free
number to order the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``By having a Web site, it has made things move so much faster
and made my book and information about my book so much more
accessible,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Internet took center stage upon the book's completion.
With galleys in hand _ freshly printed by a Tennessee firm whose
Web site he found through the Net _ Bowerman logged on in search
for critical feedback on his tome.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the first things you do is get someone who will review
your book,'' he says. ``Once I had my galleys, I got online and did
searches for writing groups, state-based writing organizations, and
you find these sites with all these (links to) organizations. I
also targeted at-home mothers, and there's a whole bunch of Web
sites for at-home mothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Using links that linked to more links that linked to more links,
Bowerman found hundreds of contacts from which to solicit, via
e-mail, writeups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Literally in about a week or less, I had 25 people lined up to
give me reviews for my book and a blurb'' to publish in the book,
he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, someone would write letters _ you may not have
phone numbers for these folks _ so you write letters and you wait
and you wait,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   One editor e-mailed Bowerman minutes after he hit the ``send''
button for review request. ``Fifteen minutes later, I got a
response: Absolutely. I'm excited. I would love to give a review of
your book.''
</P>
<P>
   The reviews were valuable beyond their kind comments. When it
came to submitting an application to have the industry heavyweight
Ingram serve as wholesaler for his book, Bowerman applied for the
program specifically designed for ``the little guys,'' he says.
Attached to his application was a one-page, single-spaced sampling
of contacts he made via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   He received a surprising e-mail in return. Because printing the
book is only half the battle, Bowerman had won important kudos for
drumming up interest in and awareness of his book.
</P>
<P>
   ``In light of all the marketing you have done, we want to offer
you a full publisher contract,'' says Bowerman, proudly reading the
Ingram response. ``They are treating me like I'm a big publisher
even though I am working out of my own house. Because of the
Internet, I look a lot bigger than I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Three major book clubs have similarly been impressed with
Bowerman's efforts. ``The Well-Fed Writer'' was a July selection of
the Writer's Digest book club, and both the Book-of-the-Month Club
and its sister organization, the Quality Paperback Book Club, will
promote Bowerman's book to their members.
</P>
<P>
   Writer's Digest has sold most of its 1,000 copies. Bowerman is
expecting another order soon from the group, which has more than
45,000 members, because ``Well-Fed Writer'' is ``our
second-highest-selling featured alternate selection in more than
two years,'' his contact there wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The epilogue to this story? If Bowerman were to pen one, it
would probably go something like this: ``If you're willing to put
in the sweat equity, the Internet is a wonderful tool to leverage a
small amount into a big impact.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
