<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUNICH-OLYMPICS-$ADV03-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN INNOCENCE DIED AT THE OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 3) 
By RICHARD SANDOMIR    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the 1972 Summer Olympics in Munich had ended on its 10th day,
it would have been remembered for Olga Korbut's pixieish dance
along the balance beam or Mark Spitz's record run of seven gold
medals in swimming. These were to be the Games of peace and
camaraderie _ a democratic West Germany's rebuke to Nazism and to
Adolf Hitler's fraudulent quest to use the 1936 Berlin Summer Games
as a showcase for Aryan physical superiority.
</P>
<P>
   But before dawn on the 11th day, Sept. 5, eight Palestinian
guerrillas scaled an unguarded fence in the Olympic village and
invaded the apartment building housing the Israeli team. They took
11 athletes and officials hostage and, over the course of a
slow-motion 20-hour siege that riveted the world, killed them all.
</P>
<P>
   If any innocence remained at the Olympics, it ended that day,
with the fedayeen, whose hooded faces came to symbolize terrorism,
and the preternaturally calm leader, Issa, with his blue suit and
white hat, his face blackened by shoe polish, negotiating with a
grenade in his hand while untold millions watched on television.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Germans had chosen pacifism over security,
policing the Olympic village with 2,000 unarmed guards. ``Their
whole mind-set was on being non-militaristic,'' said Jim McKay, who
anchored the ABC Sports coverage, which earned him a news Emmy
Award. ``They were supposed to be the serene Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the eight Black September terrorists, only one, Jamal
al-Gashey, a teen-ager at the time, survives. Five were killed
during the bungled firefight with untrained German snipers at a
military airport that ended the siege. Three others, including
al-Gashey, were jailed, but they were released in late October 1972
in exchange for the freedom of a Lufthansa jet that had been
hijacked by the Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine,
another guerrilla group. The Mossad, Israel's secret service,
eventually killed two of the three.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the Summer Games from Sydney approach, we see al-Gashey,
who has eluded his Israeli hunters, in middle age, his face
obscured in shadows and distorted by grainy video, wearing a ball
cap, denim shirt, eyeglasses and a mustache and smoking a
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight years older, he is onscreen in ``One Day in
September,'' a documentary in which he describes his life as a
Palestinian refugee and his pride in what the Black September
terrorists did to the Israelis inside the Olympic village at 31
Connollystrasse.
</P>
<P>
   The first image of this long-wanted man is of his clasped hands.
Then comes his voice, calm and measured, which offers no regrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a member of a Palestinian family which fled our village
in Galilee from Zionist gangs in 1948,'' he says through a
translator. In the liberation movement he was given a gun, he says,
and ``for the first time in my life, I felt inspired, I felt truly
Palestinian, that I wasn't a wretched refugee.'' Later in the film
he adds: ``Before Munich, the world had no idea about our struggle,
but on that day, the name of `Palestine' was repeated all over the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   For the makers of ``One Day in September,'' which won the
Academy Award for best documentary last March and will be seen on
Sept. 11 at 8 p.m. on HBO, finding al-Gashey was crucial: The film
would have been made without him, but no one else could describe
the terrorists' training in Libya, their arriving in Munich with no
idea of the plan, their watching volleyball at the Olympic Park on
the day before they broke into the Israelis' dormitory. ``I felt
very proud,'' al-Gashey says, ``that for the first time I was
finally able to confront the Israelis.''
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Cohn, the co-producer of the $2.5 million film and a
winner of five previous Oscars, said: ``He was our guarantor of
even-handedness in the film. I don't think I would have made the
film with as big a budget if I didn't have Jamal.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohn and the director, Kevin Macdonald, would not disclose where
al-Gashey lives other than to say that he was interviewed in Africa
and moves frequently to protect himself, his wife and two children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a series of coincidences and fortuitous circumstances
that led us to find someone who knew him and would act as a
go-between,'' Macdonald said. ``It was a kind of six degrees of
separation situation, where somebody knew somebody who knew
somebody. I had heard that one of the Palestinians was still alive
and that a Palestinian reporter had tried to interview him a couple
of years before, but it didn't work out. That started me to
thinking. So after eight months, we got him.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Gashey hovers over the documentary, a haunting yet oddly
congenial presence. The film is structured like a suspense story:
Jump-cut editing gives the illusion of accelerated action, and
recreations show how the terrorists entered the Israeli residence
and how one Israeli, Gad Zabari, escaped. The background music is
by Deep Purple, Led Zeppelin and Philip Glass _ not the classical
selections that might be expected for such a dour story.
</P>
<P>
   The film was completed last October, in time to meet the
deadline to be seen by the documentary panel of the Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, but before Cohn had made a
distribution deal. Once it became a finalist, the documentary was
screened by the academy, the American Film Institute and the Simon
Wiesenthal Center. The four other finalists, including ``The Buena
Vista Social Club,'' had all been released theatrically.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have had 100 conversations with Arthur,'' said Sheila
Nevins, the executive vice president of original programming for
HBO, who acquired the documentary for $1 million before it won the
Academy Award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept asking, `What about `Buena Vista,' what do you hear?'
I'd say, `Nothing.' I think Arthur was a little insecure until
after he won. I saw him at intermission of the Oscars, racing
around thrilled. He pushed hard to win, he politicked, he
screamed.''
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the events in Munich, Nevins added: ``I was awake and
alive at the time, but I didn't really recognize the magnitude of
the event. Somehow I glossed over it as a precursor to what
terrorism would become. I was so astounded by my ignorance.''
</P>
<P>
   The film does not detail a half-century of Palestinian-Israeli
conflicts, as the Palestinian-born writer Edward Said insisted it
should have in The Guardian of London; it focuses its narrative on
a day when the West Germans, confounding anyone who expected
efficiency and military precision from them, proved incompetent in
their negotiations with the terrorists and their attempts to rescue
the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were, I think, a little bit naive, you know,'' Brig. Gen.
Ulrich Wegener, then an aide to Hans-Dietrich Genscher, West
Germany's interior minister, says in the film. Genscher offered
himself in exchange for the Israelis. Manfred Schreiber, Munich's
police chief, offered money.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Gashey is the only Palestinian voice, albeit a powerful one,
in the film. Macdonald uses him as counterpoint to the Israeli
side, especially to the love story of Andre Spitzer, the affable
Israeli fencing coach who was killed by the terrorists, and his
Dutch wife, Ankie. Their brief life together is the film's
emotional anchor. There is 8-millimeter footage of their modest
wedding; there are moments in which Ankie expresses fear for
Andre's safety and frustration with conflicting news reports about
his fate, and there is a visit by their grown daughter, Anouk, to
her father's grave in Israel, which ends the film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was only a year and three months that I was married to
Andre Spitzer,'' says Ankie Spitzer. ``But I remember that year as
the most beautiful and wonderful year of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   After the film's theatrical release in Israel, several of the
slain Israelis' families objected publicly to the use of the most
graphic police photographs of the bloodied and tortured bodies of
Joseph Romano, a weight lifter, and Moshe Weinberg, a wrestling
coach.
</P>
<P>
   Cohn and Macdonald blurred the images. ``But I did it
reluctantly,'' Cohn said. ``You can't do a film about terrorism
without showing terror.''
</P>
<P>
   As cooperative as al-Gashey and some of the Israelis were, Cohn
encountered considerable resistance from German officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had so much trouble getting Genscher and Schreiber to
talk,'' Cohn said. ``I went to Genscher, who is very decent, noble
and intelligent, and said, `Dr. Genscher, you must appear, so it
doesn't look like you're hiding.''' Eventually, Genscher, Schreiber
and the remaining Germans consented, but their memories serve only
to underscore their failures, from not having a trained
anti-terrorist squad to not equipping the untrained group of five
police snipers at the airport with walkie-talkies. Had the snipers
been carrying them, they would have learned that they would be
facing eight terrorists, not five, as the German authorities
initially believed.
</P>
<P>
   With unconcealed contempt, Zvi Zamir, who then headed the
Mossad, disdains the Germans' handling of the crisis and their not
letting him bring a trained rescue team from Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't capable,'' he says. At least one of the airport
snipers was too far away to spot the terrorists in his gun sight.
``Unbelievable,'' Zamir says with simmering anger.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald said that one reason to make the film was to create a
``public outcry'' that would force German and Bavarian state
authorities to release all the files about the handling of the
massacre, a goal that has eluded the Israeli families in years of
court challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've shoved rotten fish under the carpet for 28 years, and
as the years go by, it stinks even more,'' he said. ``They've
exacerbated it so it looks like some kind of conspiracy.''
</P>
<P>
   One conspiracy theory the film advances, but fails to prove, is
that German officials helped plan the Lufthansa hijacking to rid
themselves of the three Olympic terrorists and keep further attacks
off German turf. ``The entire affair,'' the narrator Michael
Douglas says, without offering any evidence, ``was a set-up,
organized by the German government in collusion with the
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Why else, the film suggests, did the plane have only 12
passengers, and no women and children? Why else, it asks, would the
Germans make the deal with such ``indecent haste'' and without
consultation with Israel? That the government of Chancellor Willy
Brandt capitulated to the hijackers' demands is undeniable. Wegener
says as much in the film, as does the former mayor of Munich. But
no one offers proof that Brandt's government helped plan the
hijacking.
</P>
<P>
   Macdonald said that in an off-camera interview, Abu Daoud, the
longtime Palestinian leader who admits in his memoir to helping
plan the Olympic massacre, described a German-Palestinian
conspiracy. So did another Palestinian source.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Daoud is not altogether reliable,'' said Macdonald, who
added that he nonetheless felt bound to suggest that something
wrong had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm saying is, this is as much as I know,' he said. ``I
think there's a fair likelihood that it happened.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
