<SLUG> BC-keyword-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore outlines steps for expanding health coverage
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JULIE MASON 
and CLAY ROBISON &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. _ Asking voters to give him a mandate to seek
universal health care, Vice President Al Gore on Tuesday outlined
steps he would take for expanding coverage to children and parents
in low and moderate income families.
</P>
<P>
   His Republican presidential opponent, Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
meanwhile, rebuked Gore for a comment Monday that Bush should ``put
up or shut up'' on a health care plan of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said that Gore's comments to reporters aboard Air Force Two
``underlined the point I make that if we want to get something done
in Washington, we have to do something to change the tone of the
discourse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't sound very presidential to me,'' said Bush, who
campaigned Tuesday in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has promised to unveil details next week of a health care
plan that would include prescription drug benefits for older
Americans. He has said he favors giving Medicare beneficiaries the
option of selecting from a range of private health plans that would
include drug coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has proposed providing a prescription drug benefit for the
elderly under Medicare at a cost estimated at $250 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's put up or shut up time,'' Gore said Monday night about
Bush and health care. ``The time for generalities without specifics
is kind of over.``
</P>
<P>
   Bush said on Tuesday that he has been talking about health care
since the primaries last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Gore) may not like what he hears, but I'm talking about
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, campaigning Tuesday in a park with dozens of supporters
seated on lawn chairs and blankets on the grass, said he is
offering specifics in hopes of generating a national mandate on
health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``You deserve to give a mandate during this election for what
you would like to see in the future,'' Gore said at the midday
rally. ``And my motive in presenting you all of these specifics is
partly to ask for your judgment on the program that I am offering
and partly to ask for your support for my candidacy.``
</P>
<P>
   Under the plan Gore is proposing, the Children's Health
Insurance Program (CHIP) would be expanded to cover children living
at 2.5 times the poverty level, or about $41,000 a year for a
family of four. Current CHIP guidelines cover children whose
families earn up to 200 percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   The federal program is administered on a state-by-state basis,
allowing federal funds to match state dollars for covered families.
Gore officials estimate his proposed expansion would capture nearly
one million additional children nationwide whose family incomes
fall between 200 and 250 percent of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his proposals for widening children's coverage,
Gore wants to expand CHIP to 7 million uninsured parents of
Medicaid or CHIP-eligible children.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's CHIP package would be funded through the projected
federal budget surplus at an estimated cost of $95 billion over 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to other stops where Gore's campaign has offered a
harsh assessment of Bush's handling of children's health care
coverage in Texas, Gore told New Mexicans only that his own plan
was a good one and that Bush should move quickly to release one
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Bush signed the bill authorizing CHIP in Texas last year,
although he supported capping eligibility at 150 percent of poverty
level. He has called for allowing states greater flexibility to
expand CHIP coverage, in addition to tax credits for families
lacking employer health benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's campaign day Tuesday included a stop at Moore Middle
School in Portland, Maine, where Houston Independent School
District Superintendent Rod Paige and former HISD reading manager
Phyllis Hunter praised the governor as an education reformer.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was to attend a fund-raiser Tuesday night in Portsmouth,
N.H., and campaign Wednesday morning in Hampton, N.H., before
heading for the battleground state of Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire voters handed a victory to Bush's primary
opponent, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., but the state is considered a
likely win for Bush over Gore, and Bush said he harbors ``no hard
feelings'' about the primary defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In other campaign developments Tuesday, Gore picked up the
endorsement of Native American leaders in New Mexico, a group that
comprises an estimated 12 percent of the state's electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Gore traveled to Eugene, Ore., where he was to
meet up with his vice presidential running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, D-Conn. The two scheduled a joint campaign appearance
Wednesday in Seattle. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
