<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SAYS CEO WON'T TESTIFY BEFORE CONGRESS ON TIRE FLAWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, La., Fla.)   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Ford Motor Co. said Tuesday that its chief executive
and president, Jacques Nasser, had declined invitations to testify
next week before congressional committees investigating tire
failures, mainly on Ford Explorers. This prompted criticism from
one lawmaker who is leading inquiries into the recall of 6.5
million Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bridgestone/Firestone, the U.S. unit of Japan's
Bridgestone, agreed to send its chief executive, Masatoshi Ono, to
testify even though he speaks limited English, congressional
officials said. Bridgestone has been criticized until now for not
being as open about the recall as Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Vines, a Ford spokesman, said Nasser was most needed at
the company's headquarters to oversee the recall and work with tire
makers and other Ford suppliers. A senior Ford safety official and
a senior engineer, both of whom have been involved with every
detail of the problem, will be sent to testify instead, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., who heads a House Commerce
subcommittee that will be holding a hearing next Wednesday, said
through a spokesman that it was ``curious'' that Nasser could find
the time to make television advertisements about the recall but not
to explain to Congress what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin ``is very miffed,'' said Ken Johnson, the congressman's
communications director. ``We want Ford's unscripted version of
what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said Ono had agreed to come to Washington because ``he's
anxious to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   The tussle between lawmakers and Ford came as the automaker
blamed Bridgestone for tire problems in Venezuela and Thailand,
while Bridgestone said it did not believe there was a problem with
the tires.
</P>
<P>
   Vines said that Ford asked Bridgestone three times to check its
tires in Venezuela, but that Bridgestone's scientists in Venezuela
and Akron, Ohio, had insisted that they could never find any
problem with them. Ford ended up recalling the Explorers equipped
with Firestone tires in Venezuela in May and replacing them with
Goodyear tires at Ford's own expense following a series of crashes,
Vines said. Ford engineers have cut up some of the recalled tires
and found that the rate of tread separation on them is 500 times as
high as on the worst recalled tires in the United States, he said
in a telephone conference call Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone maintained Tuesday that the tires met Ford's
specifications and did not have quality problems. Bridgestone said
it did not need to recall any tires in Venezuela, although the tire
maker has asked its dealers to return unsold tires that may have
been mislabeled. Toyota, which equipped some Land Cruisers with the
same tires in Venezuela, said it had not heard reports of problems
and did not see a need for a recall.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Dominguez, chief investigator for Venezuela's consumer
protection agency, the Institute for Consumer Protection and
Education, Tuesday repeated the accusation he made on Monday _ that
Ford shared responsibility for the crashes because the Ford
Explorer was too prone to roll over. ``There are problems with the
tire and there are problems with the vehicle _ let's be clear about
this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Vines said that statistics in the United States showed that the
Explorer was less likely to roll over than other sport utilities.
Venezuela does not keep comparably detailed figures on traffic
deaths. Ford on Tuesday urged the Venezuelan consumer agency to set
up an independent commission to review the tire issue, instead of
proceeding with its plans to bring formal complaints against Ford
and Bridgestone on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Jon Harmon, a Ford spokesman, said this evening that Ford's
Venezuelan subsidiary had asked Bridgestone's Venezuelan subsidiary
in October 1998 to study why Ford was receiving reports of tire
failures on Explorers. That is the earliest that Ford has
acknowledged that any of its operations were aware of problems with
the Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone assured Ford in November 1998 that the tires in
Venezuela did not pose a problem, and provided further reassurances
in January, March and August of 1999 in response to further Ford
inquiries, Harmon said. Bridgestone officials said they would check
their records.
</P>
<P>
   In Thailand, where Ford replaced Firestone tires on 160
Explorers in March and April, Ford officials said Tuesday that they
had thought the problem was because of unique climate conditions
there and did not indicate a possible problem in the United States
too.
</P>
<P>
   The first people to point out problems with the Firestone tires
on those Explorers were not the buyers, but the drivers of the
company's own fleet of 40 Explorers, said Mike Pease, executive
director of Ford Sales &AMP; Service Thailand, in Bangkok. Early this
year, Ford's Thai drivers discovered two or three Firestone tires
with cracks near the treads, Pease said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford sent the tires to Bridgestone's Thai subsidiary, which told
Ford its tests were inconclusive. ``They couldn't tell from the
tires whether it was from any one factor,'' Pease said. All of the
160 Explorers sold in Thailand happened to have tires from
Bridgestone's factory in Decatur, Ill., and the recall in the
United States has focused on tires from that factory.
</P>
<P>
   Ichiro Fukumori, managing director of Bridgestone's Thai
operations, said he had no knowledge of Ford sending it defective
tires. Pease declined to identify exactly whom at Bridgestone Ford
had communicated with.
</P>
<P>
   Pease said that because other equipment problems had also
occurred in Thailand, Ford had assumed that the tire problems there
were caused by a unique combination of heat, pollution and
potholes. When Ford imported a car from Europe to Thailand, for
example, the car's air conditioner could not handle the local
humidity without producing water leaks, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the attorney general of Florida filed a
civil racketeering suit against Ford and Bridgestone, and requested
extensive documents from both companies.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone's stock fell 6 percent Tuesday in Tokyo. For the
month of August, it is' down from 2515 yen to Tuesday's close of
1526 yen, a loss of 39 percent. Ford's stock fell 94 cents, to
$25.56.
</P>
<P>
   David M. Garrity, an analyst at Dresdner Kleinwort Benson, an
investment bank, on Tuesday lowered his rating on Ford stock to
``add'' from ``buy,'' saying that Ford's image had been hurt and
that the odds of an expected stock buyback soon had fallen sharply
because that would look callous during a recall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
