<HEADER>
A5630 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-GAPOWER-RACISM-0830-C     08-29 0922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAPOWER-RACISM-0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five nooses displayed, company says
 &HT;    By Matthew C. Quinn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Georgia Power Co. said Tuesday that five hangman's
nooses have been displayed at company facilities, but that an
intent of racial discrimination or harassment had been determined
in only one case six years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to allegations in a racial discrimination lawsuit,
David Ratcliffe, the utility's chief executive, said a white
manager ``apparently displayed a noose in the presence of an
African-American employee'' in 1994 at Plant McDonough near Smyrna.
But that manager apologized to the employee and has retired from
the company, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe said four other nooses were discovered at company
facilities since a group of African-American employees filed the
lawsuit against Georgia Power and parent Southern Co. on July 27.
One of them was at Plant McDonough, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While no intent of racial harassment had been determined in
those four cases, Ratcliffe said, the ropes ``were found in areas
where they could have been seen and therefore may have been
offensive to our employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe spoke at a news conference to detail the company's
actions in response to employees' allegations that the utility and
Southern Co. foster a ``pattern of discriminating against
African-Americans'' who work there and show ``reckless
indifference'' to a racially hostile workplace. Also Tuesday,
attorneys for the seven employees who are suing filed a motion
alleging that Ratcliffe improperly contacted employees who are
prospective plaintiffs as members of a class. The lawsuit seeks
class-action status to represent all 2,100 African-American
employees of Southern and its subsidiaries.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys asked that the company be ordered to not make
``further improper communication'' with prospective plaintiffs. At
the same time, the lawyers sought authorization to contact such
employees themselves. Court rules generally prohibit such
communication by either side without court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe said he has contacted employees since the lawsuit was
filed, including calling two at home. But he denied he tried to
encourage them to settle their prospective case or discourage them
from seeking legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit says the hangman's noose ``has long been one of the
most chilling representations of racial harassment.'' But two
Georgia Power vice presidents and several managers were aware of a
noose displayed at the company's operating headquarters in
Cornelia, in North Georgia, and took no action to remove it, the
lawsuit alleges.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe said the company's internal investigation had been
unable to determine that executives knew about noose displays and
failed to take action.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he had spoken to an employee responsible for
displaying a noose at the Cornelia facility ``and do not believe he
intended to intimidate or harass his fellow employees.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he is satisfied the employee intended no malice. ``In
fact, he is a Scout leader,'' he said. ``However, he did show an
unacceptable level of insensitivity and poor judgment,'' Ratcliffe
said and has been asked to make an apology to ``anyone who might
have been offended by his actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe told a news conference it is ``not unusual for line
crews to use ropes'' in their daily activities or tie knots during
downtime on a rainy day. ``This individual simply tied a noose and
left it lying around for an extended period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd Terrell, a company spokesman, added later that linemen
sometimes use knots that resemble hangman's nooses in storm
restoration and building and rebuilding power lines.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Davis, recently named the company's vice president for
diversity action, said in an interview last week that his heartbeat
quickened when he saw a photograph of the noose found in Cornelia
that was included as an exhibit with the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an intimidating thing for a black man,'' said Davis,
who is African-American. He added that such a display is
reminiscent of cross burning. ``A noose is something that any black
person considers offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   In an affidavit filed with Tuesday's procedural motion a Plant
McDonough electrician said a white foreman had displayed a ``poorly
tied hangman's knot'' in his presence in the plant's control room
six years ago. The foreman ``said to me in essence that 'the reason
I was kicked out of the Ku Klux Klan was because I would not tie a
noose,''' the employee said.
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe said the foreman's actions ``were offensive to me and
to the company'' and that he _ Ratcliffe _ had offered a personal
apology to the African-American employee involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take no comfort in the fact that the employee who was
responsible is no longer with the company and it occurred six years
ago,'' he said. ``This type of unacceptable behavior will not be
tolerated.'' But he said the manager's actions ``should not be seen
as a reflection on the rest of our company.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe also answered an allegation in the employee lawsuit
that African-American employees were forced at a 1999 Southern Co.
marketing meeting to ``watch their Caucasian supervisors sing and
dance to Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratcliffe said a band hired for the event did play Dixie but
were not asked to do so by management. ``The band was told to leave
the stage. It did so and did not return,'' Ratcliffe said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
