u i BC-CHINA-JAPAN-450&AMP;ADD-N     08-29 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-JAPAN-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN COMPLAINS TO CHINA ABOUT ITS ACTIONS AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ During a visit by Japan's foreign minister, Japan and
China have affirmed their friendship, resolved to remain peaceful
partners and scheduled a visit to Japan in October by Prime
Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there have been unavoidable reminders of the tensions that
always lurk in relations between these two Asian powers that are
struggling to contain a strategic rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, President Jiang Zemin's trip to Japan was
shadowed by China's continued bitterness over Japanese atrocities
in World War II and Japanese resentment over demands for historical
apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Now, two days into the four-day visit by Foreign Minister Yohei
Kono, the Chinese have not pressed the historical point and,
according to Japanese officials, have not even made their usual
complaint about Japanese-U.S. plans for regional missile defenses,
which could be used against China in a battle for Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   But the Japanese arrived with unusually blunt and public
complaints, about what they see as ominous Chinese maritime
incursions. They also warned that Japan's large-scale foreign aid
to China _ $2.2 billion in 1998 _ could no longer be taken for
granted, given China's growing wealth and what Japan considers its
aggressive behavior at sea.
</P>
<P>
   In late May and in July of this year, Chinese naval vessels
cruised just outside Japan's 12-mile territorial limit apparently
gathering intelligence, said the Japanese foreign ministry
spokesman, Yasuhisa Kawamura. The ship movements, while not a
violation of maritime law, were inconsistent with friendly
relations, Kawamura said, noting that in the first incident the
vessels completely circled Japan's main islands.
</P>
<P>
   Of equal concern, 30 times last year and 17 times through Aug. 7
of this year, Chinese research vessels conducted operations,
without the required permission, inside Japan's 200-mile exclusive
economic zone. Some Japanese experts speculate that the ships are
mapping the offshore sea bottom, data of great value to the
military.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Kono raised these concerns in a lengthy meeting with
his Chinese counterpart, Tang Jiaxuan, telling him that Japanese
``feelings of distrust'' toward China are rising, the Japanese
spokesman later reported.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding the naval vessels, Tang said the situation ``no longer
exists,'' Kawamura told reporters. The Japanese interpret that as a
promise that such cruises would be called off for now.
</P>
<P>
   As for the incursions by research vessels, both sides agreed to
develop procedures to notify each other in advance of expeditions
and to begin negotiations on disputes about maritime borders, which
the Japanese called ``a step forward.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Japanese have freely shared their concerns with foreign
reporters here. In his meeting Tuesday, Kono told Jiang that
``relations are in a good state but they are not problem-free,''
according to the Japanese spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese appear determined to prevent any open rift with
Japan, stressing the advantages of cooperation. Kono has been
greeted by a raft of top officials here including, diplomats noted,
Zeng Qinghong, chief of the Communist Party's organization
department, who has no formal position in foreign policy but is
considered a powerful adviser to Jiang and a rising political star.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, China's government-controlled media quoted Jiang
as saying, ``I'm optimistic on the future of Chinese-Japanese
relations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
