A5632 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-CHENEY-VISIT-KAN &LR;      08-29 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHENEY-VISIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHENEY VISITS KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The venue for Dick Cheney on Tuesday was the
Fellowship of Christian Athletes national headquarters in Kansas
City. The topic was character.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching character, Cheney told an audience of about 70, is as
important as learning how to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want them to know right from wrong,'' Cheney said in a
quiet voice, referring to George W. Bush's goal of teaching
children to be ``good and kind and decent'' in public schools.
``Nothing is more important than teaching character.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Wyoming congressman and defense secretary under
President George Bush described character as ``the very essence of
our country.'' America's creed, Cheney said, is ``leadership based
on character.''
</P>
<P>
   So it came as no surprise that Texas Gov. George W. Bush's
running mate had a very definite opinion on whether President
Clinton should have been removed from office last year as a result
of the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have voted to impeach him,'' Cheney said in an
interview with The Kansas City Star. ``Because I thought he was
guilty. I thought he lied under oath. And I thought the House made
a strong case to that effect.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, Cheney told an interviewer later, a ``man of few words''
who prefers low-key campaign events that are in sharp contrast to
the more lively events that Democrats Al Gore and Joe Lieberman
regularly stage.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's event certainly fit Cheney's preferences. The FCA
crowd was in business attire and remained quiet for most of
Cheney's brief remarks. In fact, attendees waited to politely
applaud until well after Cheney and his wife entered the hall.
</P>
<P>
   His toughest remarks directed at the Democratic team also were
brief and were presented with no change in Cheney's somber tone.
The running mate criticized Gore for opposing any type of school
voucher plan that would provide federal grants to parents with
children in failing schools. The parents could then use the money
to pay for private schooling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore does not support the idea of giving low-income parents
a wide range of choices,'' Cheney said.
</P>
<P>
   As he often is on the campaign trail, Cheney was joined by his
wife, Lynne. Others featured at the gathering were Royals' first
baseman and FCA member Mike Sweeney and Erika Garris, a junior at
Knob Noster High School and FCA member who has signed a pledge to
remain drug-free.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Cheney stopped at the Carriage Club near State Line
Road and Shawnee Mission Parkway for a private fund-raiser that
brought in an estimated $50,000 for the Missouri Republican Party.
He then left Kansas City for Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made character education a part of his school platform.
He's proposed increasing to $25 million from $8 million the amount
spent on ``character education grants'' so that teachers can learn
how to incorporate character-building lessons in their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has proposed increases in the amount spent on
abstinence education from $62 million a year to at least $135
million a year, which, he notes, is the amount the federal
government spends on teen contraception programs.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1954, the FCA is a faith-based organization aimed at
student and professional athletes. The group's motto is that
building better persons translates into molding better athletes.
</P>
<P>
   On other topics, Cheney deflected pressure from Gore's campaign
to accept three nationally televised, prime-time debates as
proposed by the Commission on Presidential Debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he ``would welcome'' three prime-time debates. But
his campaign said that did not mean that Bush would accept the
commission's proposed dates or formats.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with The Star, Cheney pointed out his campaign
has received 41 debate invitations from different groups. The
invitation from the commission is ``one proposal out of several,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of different ways to go,'' Cheney said. ``And
I don't think there's necessarily any one particular approach. My
guess is we'll end up with a mix, and that's probably as it should
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the B-2 stealth bomber fleet based at Whiteman Air
Force Base in Knob Noster, Mo., Cheney said he opposed moving the
fleet closer to the world's hot spots in Europe and the Mideast.
The bomber was not used in the Persian Gulf War, when Cheney was
defense secretary.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of great features of the B-2 is the fact that you can base
it here in Missouri and can, with air-to-air refueling, literally
hit virtually any target any place in the world without having to
land on foreign soil,'' he said. ``That's a great asset.''
</P>
<P>
   On another topic, Cheney said Bush is just as prepared as his
father to assume the presidency, although he said the Texas
governor's background is based more on domestic policy while his
father had more foreign policy experience when he became president.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one president ever arrives in the Oval Office with total
experience,'' Cheney said. ``It's not a one-man operation. You have
to build a team. The governor has demonstrated that he's very much
committed to that course of action, and he's started to assemble a
good team.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave Clinton some credit for overseeing the nation's robust
economy. But Cheney said that the causes of America's economic boom
predated the Clinton administration by more than a decade. One of
those causes was the major tax cut Ronald Reagan passed early in
his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not want to attribute to him sole responsibility for
our current prosperity,'' Cheney said of Clinton. ``I don't think
that's accurate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
