<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENSUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASHES CONTINUE BETWEEN CENSUS BUREAU AND ITS GOP OVERSEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Fla., Calif., N.Y., N.J., Pa., Ga., Ill.)   By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even as it seeks to complete the official
population count for the year 2000, the Census Bureau finds itself
engaged in a low-level war with House Republicans over how the
bureau is conducting its head count.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the summer, members of the House Subcommittee on the
Census and their staffs have demanded explanations from the Census
Bureau about its counting methods. House Republicans have also been
quick to call for investigations when they believe the bureau is
withholding information or failing to make an attempt to count
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say their activities are routine efforts at
congressional oversight, while Democrats suspect the Republicans
are laying the groundwork for later legal attacks on the accuracy
of the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bureau has $6.5 billion that it is spending on this
census,'' Chip Walker, the subcommittee's assistant staff director
said in explaining the panel's intense scrutiny of the Census
Bureau's operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken a different approach than the Democrats on the
subcommittee. The Democrats have taken a hands-off approach. They
are willing to let the bureau spend the $6.5 billion as it sees
fit. We don't believe that we approach fulfills our oversight
responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say the Republicans seek to portray the Census Bureau
as incapable of carrying out routine tasks, let alone a complex
operation like statistical sampling, which would supplement the
actual count and which the Republicans oppose.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the subcommittee staff does not turn up systemic
wrongdoing on the Census Bureau's part, its constant questioning
may raise doubts about the bureau's methods.
</P>
<P>
   Such doubts may be useful in what is expected to be a protracted
legal battle over whether population data compiled using sampling
can be used in redistricting, the drawing of of lines for
congressional and state legislative districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lays the groundwork for the legal action that will probably
take up the first half of the next decade,'' said one Republican
strategist who spoke only on a promise of anonymity. ``Both parties
view the stakes of redistricting very high. So on the Republican
side the strategy has shifted from fighting the theory of sampling
to fighting the mechanics of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Under its current plans, the Census Bureau is gathering
demographic data from a sample of 314,000 households and will use
that to adjust population counts in areas as small as city blocks.
The bureau is using this method, which is nearly completed, to
adjust for the millions of people it expects to miss using
traditional counting methods.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have opposed the sampling method and Democrats have
supported it in large part because many of those who are missed
tend to be minorities living in traditionally Democratic areas.
Political strategists believe such an adjustment would give
Democrats an advantage when legislative boundaries are drawn.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, the House census subcommittee staff charged that
the Census Bureau completed its work too quickly in 15 local census
offices in cities including Los Angeles, Atlanta, Chicago, Newark,
Philadelphia and New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans based their suspicions about wider problems to
the discovery in June by federal auditors of wrongdoing by census
takers in Hialeah, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The auditors found that the census takers had had stopped
visiting households that had failed to send back their
questionnaires after only one unsuccessful attempt, rather than
after the mandatory six tries, and that in some cases they had
simply made up the answers.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the problem, the Census Bureau sent census takers
to reinterview the residents of all households that had not mailed
back their forms. After an internal investigation, Kenneth Prewitt,
the Census Bureau director, announced last month that he had not
found any problems in the 15 local census offices named by the
subcommittee staff.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Republicans demanded that the bureau save more than
30 million forms that had been completed by census takers across
the country who conducted interviews in households that did not
mail back questionnaires. Normally these forms are destroyed after
the data they contain are scanned into Census Bureau computers. But
the Republicans say they want them saved to make sure the
information being inserted into the computers is accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau officials said Tuesday that merely holding on to
the forms will cost $3.5 million to $5 million in storage costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States Congress wants to pay $5 million to store
these things in a warehouse for 10 years, we'll cooperate,''
Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Rep. Dan Miller, R-Fla., who chairs the
subcommittee, called for a Justice Department investigation into
the bureau's participation in a political and cultural symposium
held in Los Angeles by Tavis Smiley, a popular black radio and
television personality two days before the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that because the symposium was listed by the
Democratic National Committee as an event that was taking place in
Los Angeles around the time of the convention, it was a partisan
Democratic event and the bureau should not have taken part. In a
press release, Miller said the event cast a ``dark cloud'' over the
census.
</P>
<P>
   Smiley who has worked closely with the Census Bureau for more
than a year trying to boost the number of blacks who mail back
their census forms has hotly denied any link between his symposium
and the Democratic convention. He said that three Census Bureau
workers merely set up a table at the event and handed out
information on the census.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was in no way connected to the DNC,'' Smiley said. ``The
DNC gave me no money, there was no speaker from the DNC. The Census
Bureau gve me no money.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2030EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0325 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5634 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-VOTER-VOICES-2TAKES-N     08-29 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOTER-VOICES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LITTLE THINGS, AS WELL AS THE BIG, AFFECT VOTERS' THINKING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Here is how it happened for Joyce Doty: She started
the summer already sold on George W. Bush. Then, the conventions
rolled around. Suddenly, Vice President Al Gore was looking
handsome, sounding smart and intriguing her with the idea that
``maybe he wasn't too corrupted by Clinton after all.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's convention performance, and subsequent stump speeches,
have given her pause. ``I started deciding that he doesn't have the
charisma,'' said Doty, who is in her 50s. ``He didn't do a good job
of bringing the issues to the front. I would say he is in danger of
losing my vote, if not overwhelmingly so.''
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of people interviewed in six neighborhoods here _ ranging
from the exclusive suburb of Fox Chapel to the quiet working-class
corner of Carnegie to the largely Jewish Squirrel Hill _ said they
too had been experiencing epiphanic moments about their
presidential candidates in recent days, often in ways that had
caused them to rethink the way they intend to vote.
</P>
<P>
   For some people, the shifts have sprung from large single events
_ a convention speech, a tax proposal, or the candidates' choices
of running mates. But for many others, their change in thinking has
emerged from the smallest but most resonant of details, like a
well-place bottle of wine in a televised home video of Gore with
his family that made Josh Kamody suddenly decide that Gore was
``fun, someone I felt I would like as my dad.''
</P>
<P>
   For Gregg Rosen, it was the discovery that Bush's running mate
did not favor the Head Start program that sent his vote packing.
Rebecca Hepka, 23, was more or less indifferent to the race until
she heard one of Gore's people use the term ``living wage,'' which
sent her into paroxysms of rage and made her decide to vote for
Bush. ``I don't like that term, no way,'' said Hepka, who sells
medical insurance. ``I don't want to give away all my taxes to have
other people set up for life.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the campaign appears to have heated up here
considerably since the political conventions, and knowledge of the
issues as well as opinions about the candidates are suddenly in
abundance. Many people interviewed agreed that the candidates had
revealed far more about themselves in recent days. In most cases,
these shifts have favored Gore, whose legendary stiffness has been
softened in many voters' eyes by a sheen of sincerity. Recent
national polls place the candidates in a dead heat, the result in
part of a postconvention bounce that pulled Gore closer, and in
some cases beyond, his rival.
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, Gore was gaining some favor with people who said
they had not planned to vote at all, like Linda Kelso, a store
clerk who said that a recent visit to downtown Pittsburgh by Gore's
daughter softened her. ``It seemed sincere, like they were really
for the people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, both men have benefited from exposure. ``I was
negative on both earlier this summer,'' said Ann Hazlett, 71, a
retired social worker who lives in Fox Chapel. ``I was negative on
Bush the person and Gore the party. But I liked Bush better later
in the summer when he began to be more substantial and not such a
smarty. And while I didn't think Gore's speech was outstanding, I
felt there was sincerity there and I thought he did a good job of
distancing himself from Clinton, who I no longer think will be
telling him what to do. Really, I've warmed on them both.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, 50 people do not represent America; they do not even
represent Pittsburgh. But what was striking was that the vast
majority insisted that they rarely vote strictly along party lines,
and that they claimed to have been swayed so strongly in recent
days. Many of them said they were early supporters of Sen. John
McCain or Bill Bradley, and have started to weigh the relative
merits of what they were left with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am party-indifferent,'' said Rosen, 47, a lawyer. ``My
feelings started to evolve when Bush called the Greek people
Grecians, and my opinion of Gore had been neutral. I would say now
it is neutral to positive, largely because Bush doesn't have any
policy positions. He speaks in conceptual terms.''
</P>
<P>
   Although fewer in number, some people interviewed said that
recent days had brought them to Bush. ``I was for Bush and now I am
more so,'' said Heather Hurley, who works with Hepka selling
insurance downtown. ``I thought Gore looked better than ever but I
don't care, because Bush's tax plan is more fair. And I like what
he said last week about a strong military.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh has voted largely Democratic in recent decades,
though its suburbs are sprinkled with Republican strongholds. The
city and its suburbs are split between the 14th and 18th
Congressional Districts, where Clinton took well over 50 percent of
the vote in both 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Since the decline of the steel industry, the city has struggled,
with some notable success, to establish a more varied economic
base. The city's downtown _ heavy on old-fashioned stores like
Candy Rama, where clerks wear pink smocks and much of the
merchandise is under a dollar _ has gone through a number of
revitalization plans, the latest of which calls for gutting most of
the historic storefronts.
</P>
<P>
   The city has doggedly pursued economic improvement and has tried
hard to retain its population, especially young people, who have
tended to flee in recent decades. A recent building spree includes
ballparks and a new convention center.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Kelley, 41, and her husband, Carl Brotsker, 50,
represent emerging prosperity. The two leaned toward Bradley during
the primaries, and have spent the summer looking for cues on how to
proceed from speeches, the stock market and those who watch it, and
the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Their paths have diverged at points. ``I was going to announce
to Melissa that by pain of death I would be voting for Bush,'' said
Brotsker, who lives on the city's North Side. His reason was fairly
simple. ``As my economic situation has improved, I've been more
intrigued by the Republican economic platform.''
</P>
<P>
   But then he started hearing whispers among those who handle his
investments and market prognosticators that swayed him. With some
embarrassment, he confessed that a comment of support for Gore
voiced by a money manager in an online chat swayed him greatly.
``The markets have seemed to indicate that the Bush tax cut might
be inflationary,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley has had her own series of epiphanies. ``What I knew of
Gore did not impress me initially,'' said Kelley, a lawyer. ``But
he has been better at articulating his policies. It has been a long
time since I have heard a candidate say women will retain choice
regarding abortion, and that was impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Joseph I. Lieberman. ``Making a choice can be
a defining thing, an active thing,'' Kelley said. ``Gore's choice
of Lieberman gave me an indication of other types of actions he
might take. So I remain cynical, but I am happier than I had
been.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, several people indicated that the candidates' choice of
a running mate was hugely influential. ``I didn't like either of
them until Gore chose Lieberman,'' said Carmen Hatcher, a systems
technician. ``I don't believe Gore is a strong leader, but
Lieberman will guide him.'' Hazlett said: ``I don't like Dick
Cheney, which I hate to think would influence me so much. And I
can't say that Lieberman would make me vote for Gore, but I have to
tell you I am surprised by how many of my friends talk about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Some voters have stuck hard to one issue. ``I believe that Gore
has a better understanding about education and has shown that in
recent speeches,'' said John Bornyas, an education administrator.
``And I have gotten negative on Bush in the week since he could not
get his numbers straight. But I need to see them both in the
debates. And the truth is, there is always the Green Party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
