<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5638 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-HOPKINS-REVIEW-NYT     08-29 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOPKINS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC`S NOTEBOOK: SCALPEL! REAL-LIFE DRAMA! STAT!
</HEADLINE>
 By JULIE SALAMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   At 14, Tiffany should be worrying about pimples and braces. But
she is also facing a stark choice between possible infertility and
possible death. When her father presses her to explain the pain
caused by her uterine cancer, she responds in a tone conveying
daughterly indulgence and annoyance. ``It's like someone stabbing
me from inside,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Her reaction and her father's restrained grief were recorded on
small digital video cameras held by television producers. So was
the moment when the surgeon called Tiffany's parents to deliver his
not very optimistic diagnosis, and so was the surgery that removed
Tiffany's uterus.
</P>
<P>
   It might once have seemed shocking to be privy to such
intimacies, but we are growing accustomed to the idea that no life
should go unexamined _ in front of a national audience. On
Wednesday night at 10 ABC News presents Tiffany's story and others
in the first episode of ``Hopkins 24/7,'' a six-part documentary
series that has captured three months of life and death at Johns
Hopkins Medical Center in Baltimore. The hospital gave the
producers unprecedented access to its inner workings, though not,
of course, unrestricted access. There are no segments on really
unpleasant topics like medical malpractice, for example.
</P>
<P>
   The program continues Thursday night at 10 and Wednesday nights
through Sept. 27 at 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopkins 24/7'' makes for fascinating television while
rewriting our notion of the patient-doctor privilege. Before
filming, but after obtaining permission from the Hopkins
administration, the program's producers printed up notepad-size
release forms that they could hand out like parking tickets to
patients who seemed like promising subjects. One of the producers,
Terence Wrong, told me that he was surprised at how many people
(about 85 percent, he estimates) signed away their privacy. If the
immediate celebrity conferred on ``Survivor'' contestants has a
ripple effect, we may soon see agents clamoring to represent
patients as they head for the operating room.
</P>
<P>
   Our major medical centers have increasingly doubled as stage
sets for documentary television crews. It started on cable with the
Learning Channel's ``Trauma: Life in the ER,'' the channel's
top-rated program (which New York Times Television produces for
TLC), now beginning its fifth season. A few ``Trauma'' alumni
worked on ABC's new program.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 25 TLC is adding ``Code Blue,'' filmed in Charity
Hospital in New Orleans, to its schedule, which also includes a
program called ``Paramedics,'' about emergency medical teams. On
Sept. 28 the Discovery Channel begins its ``Hospital,'' filmed at
the Duke University Medical Center, opening with the story of a man
who crashed his motorcycle while riding without his helmet and then
suffers paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s the filmmaker Frederick Wiseman pioneered the use
of cameras to examine our major institutions (including
Metropolitan Hospital in Manhattan, in the original ``Hospital'').
``Hopkins 24/7'' pays homage to Wiseman's subtle, observational
approach, but it is part of a more recent trend that combines
cinema verite with the conventions of dramatic narrative. These
real stories are carefully edited to give them a structure
especially recognizable to devotees of prime-time dramas like
``NYPD Blue'' or of course ``ER,'' with major and minor characters
and intercutting story lines. To achieve this, the ``Hopkins''
producers spent three months filming _ amassing 900 hours of
videotape _ and six months editing.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the narration for ``24/7'' comes from doctors, patients
and family members. Occasionally Sylvia Chase, a correspondent for
ABC News, tersely relays scene-setting information, but off camera.
This is a welcome deviation from network newsmagazine convention,
which requires information to be filtered through on-air
correspondents whose celebrity becomes a distraction.
</P>
<P>
   The program covers an extraordinary range of medical problems
(including cancer, anorexia, brain disorders, organ transplants)
and personalities whose diversity at times seems too good to be
true (but is). In one segment we meet Dr. Michael Ain, a surgeon
and a dwarf, who candidly discusses the discrimination against him
because of his size. He specializes in operating on children and
other little people who can look at him eye to eye. In another we
meet Dr. Rick Montz, a leading oncologist (the kind your mother
might call a ``top man''). He's also a middle-aged ponytail wearer
who revels a bit too smugly in his own iconoclasm (describing
ovarian cancer as ``bad juju'').
</P>
<P>
   The first episode introduces Eddie Cornwell, a handsome surgeon
with a messianic streak. He is determined to stop the flow of
bleeding young men who stream into the Hopkins emergency room from
the streets of East Baltimore, which delivered 362 shooting victims
in one year. So he takes boys on hospital tours, giving them (and
us) a close look at what a buff fellow looks like after he has been
shot and had a colostomy. One youth, looking horrified at the man's
pulpy stomach region, mumbles, ``I'm going to stick to
basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   The cameras capture the adrenalin charge of the emergency room,
but also the quiet tension of patients making decisions using
information they can't possibly comprehend. In one episode, just as
a woman's 3-year-old daughter is about to undergo surgery, the
mother learns that more than half her child's brain has to be
removed, more than previously expected. The mother insists on
talking to the surgeon, and asks asks, ``What does the basal
ganglia do?'' Later the child's father gives his reason for
deciding to trust the doctor: ``I know he prays before every
surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   To their credit, the producers of ``24/7'' have tried to err on
the side of humanism, not exploitation. While the prime-time
newsmagazines endlessly chase the latest outrage _ no matter how
slight _ this crew has followed another journalistic tradition of
reportage that doesn't expose, but reveals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
