<HEADLINE>
INDIAN PREMIER'S HEALTH PROBLEMS RAISE POLITICAL CONCERNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CELIA W. DUGGER  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, the
grandfatherly face of Hindu nationalism, is having health problems,
and they are creating unease here in India's capital.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, 75, known abroad as the man who raised fears by
ordering tests of nuclear devices two years ago, is revered at home
as a consensus builder. On Sunday, he cut short his appearance at
the national convention of his political party, the Bharatiya
Janata, and returned to New Delhi from central India. After resting
at home on Monday, he returned to work Tuesday and presided over a
cabinet meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The government said in a statement on Monday that the prime
minister's doctors had advised him to stay off his feet because of
a flare-up of osteoarthritis that was causing severe pain in his
knees.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee's spokesman, H.K. Dua, said that the prime minister
would still depart on Sept. 5 for a week and a half in the United
States that will include a New York visit and an address to
Congress, as well as separate meetings with President Clinton and
Vice President Al Gore and a trip to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea is to keep up the momentum of improved Indo-U.S.
relations,'' Dua said.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee has seemed more frail and slow-moving recently. After
he finished his Independence Day speech earlier this month, his
security men had to lift him up and carry him down from the Red
Fort ramparts. Three months ago, he canceled engagements because of
what his doctors described as a sore throat.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee may be suffering from nothing more serious than the
discomforts of old age, but rumors that he has a life-threatening
illness persist.
</P>
<P>
   His health is central to the stability of the coalition
government his party leads. He has attracted an eclectic group of
secular political allies by setting aside his party's hard-line
Hindu nationalist positions on issues like the construction of a
Hindu temple on the site of a demolished Muslim mosque. But even
more than his stance on any given issue, his accommodating style is
widely seen as the glue that holds together the oddly fitting
pieces of the coalition.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In recent months, journalists have openly asked about the prime
minister's health. Reporters who met him on Sunday when he landed
at the airport bluntly asked if he had any serious health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee laughed and said no. During an interview last November
he gave the same answer when asked whether he was sick. First, he
burst out laughing, then said he had no grave disease. ``Age is a
serious problem,'' he added wryly.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his shakiness on his feet, Vajpayee demonstrated his
firm grip on the Bharatiya Janata Party at the convention in Nagpur
in central India. His choice for party president, Bangaru Laxman,
took office this weekend. Laxman, the first party president from a
formerly untouchable caste, had not been the front-runner until the
prime minister anointed him.
</P>
<P>
   Some party leaders and members of hard-line Hindu nationalist
groups associated with the party criticized the government for
failing to protect Hindu pilgrims in Kashmir from a recent
terrorist attack. Some also said the government had been too
willing to enter negotiations with anti-India militants who want
Pakistan included in talks about the future of Kashmir. A territory
that Pakistan wants, Kashmir is India's only Muslim-majority state.
</P>
<P>
   But in brief remarks before he hurriedly left the convention,
Vajpayee warned his critics within the party not to go too far and
violate party discipline.
</P>
<P>
   In his absence Tuesday, the party unanimously adopted a
resolution supporting his decision to attempt negotiations with the
Hizbul Mujahideen in Kashmir _ talks that were aborted after Hizbul
called off its cease-fire on Aug. 8. In more belligerent tones, the
party also warned Pakistan to halt its support to militants in
Kashmir, although Pakistan denies giving such support.
</P>
<P>
   ``A clear message needs to be sent to terrorists and their
masters across the border that every Indian life is precious and
will be defended, and that indulging in cross-border terrorism
cannot continue to remain a cost-free option,'' the resolution
stated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
