<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5640 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AIG-HYUNDAI-NYT &LR;      08-29 0475
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIG-HYUNDAI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYUNDAI SECURITIES GETS ANOTHER $200 MILLION FROM TWO U.S.
INVESTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAMUEL LEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ A group of Western investors, including
Wilbur Ross, a specialist in corporate rescues, and the American
International Group, plan to increase their investment in three
financial affiliates of the Hyundai Group to $1 billion to gain a
firmer hold on Hyundai Securities, South Korea's largest brokerage
firm.
</P>
<P>
   The increased investment of $200 million, in addition to $800
million announced in June, would give the group _ which also
includes GE Capital, an American subsidiary of Aegon of the
Netherlands and Wisconsin and California pension funds _ a 23.7
percent stake in the brokerage firm. Hyundai Securities is the plum
in the deal: its profit nearly tripled in the last year to 305.2
billion won _ now almost $275 million.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign investors will face a daunting task in trying to
revive the troubled money management arm of the group. The unit,
Hyundai Investment Trust and Securities Co., has liabilities
exceeding its assets by 1.2 trillion won, or $1.08 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Like other such investment businesses in South Korea, Hyundai
Investment Trust saw its financial problems worsen after the Daewoo
Group collapsed under $80 billion of debt. Investment trusts are
the largest purchasers of corporate bonds in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Some Korean shareholder activists said Tuesday that they were
also concerned by signs that Hyundai Securities would retain its
current head, Lee Ik Chi, who in the past has been accused of
misappropriating investors' funds to prop up ailing units of the
Hyundai Group.
</P>
<P>
   If any steps were taken to ensure Lee's position, ``it would be
deeply troubling,'' said Jang Ha Sung, a prominent advocate for
minority shareholder rights and professor of business
administration at Korea University. ``No one knows what was behind
the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hyundai Group, South Korea's largest business conglomerate,
is trying to reduce its $48 billion in debt by selling stakes in
its affiliates to foreign investors. Through a tangled web of
equity holdings and debt guarantees in other subsidiaries, South
Korea's giant family-run conglomerates have propped up ailing units
through cash infusions from healthier affiliates. For the Hyundai
Group, its brokerage firm served as the main source of such funds.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai's government-led creditors in recent weeks have stepped
up demands for restructuring in an attempt to stamp out such
practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cash-flow problems at Hyundai Investment Trust Securities
expanded liquidity problems to the entire group,'' said Kim Kyoung
Won, a spokesman for Hyundai Securities, which owns a 24.2 percent
stake in the Hyundai Investment Trust. ``But through the AIG
investment, this problem has been solved.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2037EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0332 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-SOOKE-HARBOUR-800(2TA     08-29 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOOKE-HARBOUR-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ESCAPE TO EDEN ON VANCOUVER ISLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   By R.W. APPLE Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SOOKE, British Columbia _ Sinclair and Frederique Philip make an
unlikely pair. She comes from Cannes, on the lush Cote d'Azur; he
grew up on the spare Canadian plains. He likes fish; she likes
meat. He is reserved, ironic and intellectual, an international
economist by trade; she has an earth-motherly warmth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, together they took a white clapboard house, built in 1928
on a lonely promontory on timber-clad Vancouver Island, facing the
Strait of Juan de Fuca and the Olympic Mountains of Washington
State beyond it, and in 21 years turned the place into an enticing
and idiosyncratic retreat for epicures.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Sooke Harbour House is one of Canada's half-dozen best
restaurants, and it has a kitchen garden unlike any other in North
America _ more than two acres of herbs, vegetables and edible
flowers, many of them rarities, gradually devouring the lawns
around the house, tumbling down to the sea, scaling hillsides in
every direction, a living tapestry of leaf, shrub and color.
</P>
<P>
   Tuberous begonias with blossoms the size of dinner plates fill
baskets and window boxes, and a few petals are plucked each day to
flavor the mignonette sauce served with freshly opened local
oysters. A climbing fig twines around a dining alcove and provides
fruit in the fall. Aromatic lemon verbena and jaunty nasturtiums
grow in profusion close to the house, adding a sweet scent and
flashes of bright color to the many pleasures of Sooke. Herbal teas
are made from verbena, and nasturtium blossoms enliven salads.
</P>
<P>
   Bergamot and borage flowers, two Philip favorites, will not soon
supplant salt and pepper, but they and other products of the garden
contribute not only subtle flavors but also an element of surprise
to the menu, helping to accomplish the mission of serving only
seasonal, organic food produced or harvested in British Columbia.
People come here, Philip told me, ``for the Canadian experience,''
whether they come from Canada, the American Northwest or farther
afield.
</P>
<P>
   So you will find no caviar and no mangoes at Sooke Harbour
House, because none are produced in the province. But I'll wager
you won't miss them _ not with line-caught sockeye salmon,
trap-caught black cod and Dungeness crab fished out of the waters
of Sooke Inlet; not with roast leg of suckling kid raised by a
local farmer and lobster mushrooms and chanterelles foraged in the
rain forest; not with West Coast mussels, plus marine exotica like
gooseneck barnacles and limpets, all of them gathered by hand from
rock-strewn beaches nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter where I go,'' said Edward Tuson, the 36-year-old
head chef, ``Nepal and India, Malaysia, Vancouver, I end up coming
back here. I have total freedom, as long as I play by Sinclair's
rules and keep it local. I invent something, fuss with it, change
the menu every day. There's this fabulous garden, there's a network
of farmers, and I have a fisherman who wakes me at 8, 8:30, every
morning, calling to tell me what's best in the day's catch.''
</P>
<P>
   Close to 100 people eat here each night, in two big,
alabaster-white dining rooms, one with a huge fireplace, both with
big windows framing the vista of sea and sky. The rooms are
decorated with the work of local artists, commissioned by Philip
(and with whimsical gifts from grateful diners: People send
miniature hats _ straw for summer, wool for winter _ for the duck
decoys on the mantlepiece).
</P>
<P>
   Candles burn in the chandeliers. The window in one door is
shaped like a crab. Like the whole place, the dining rooms are
casual, unpretentious, very much in harmony with the rugged
surroundings, but totally professional.
</P>
<P>
   Self-taught the key players may be, but this is no amateur hour.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Philip met in 1967 at a party in Nice given by a
friend of hers. He had just arrived from Canada, to work on his
French before heading to Africa. He never got there. They lived in
Aix-en-Provence for a while, then at Grenoble, where he studied
economics, and then in Toronto. On a business trip, he came upon
Sooke Harbour House and decided to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years, the Philips lived in the basement with their
children and worked upstairs. Making the place go took a kind of
manic concentration and energy, and three years ago, just when they
had almost paid off the mortgage, but not quite, they took out a
new, bigger one to expand the inn to 28 bedrooms. He is now 53, she
52, and the staff, all recruited locally, has grown from three to
80.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sinclair,'' Philip said, ``does his research on anything the
same way as he did the research for his Ph.D. at Grenoble, so when
he decided to start the garden, he read everything in print on
herbs and edible flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the choicest things Philip grows were brought here, in
the form of seed or seedlings from commercial nurseries. That is
the case with the tiny, seductively perfumed woodland strawberries
the French call fraises des bois, as well as the Mabel Grey
geraniums from South Africa, whose leaves have a lemon-lime scent _
a little like Sprite.
</P>
<P>
   But he has learned a lot from the Northwest Indian tribes that
have lived on Vancouver Island since time immemorial and from
people who study them, like Nancy Turner, an ethnobotanist at the
University of British Columbia. They taught him about cooking with
the tender young needles of the fir tree and about many of the sea
creatures that live on the beaches and in the tidal pools. One of
the inn's most talented foragers is Carol Planes, an Indian, who
regularly clambers down slippery rocks to gather shellfish.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have been eating this stuff forever,'' Philip
said. ``You listen to them, and you learn.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Early clients blanched at things they were offered to eat.
Philip remembers people asking, ``How can you eat those bitter
greens?'' Philip was often asked to taste a dish first, in a
customer's presence, to demonstrate that it was actually edible.
</P>
<P>
   You still see perplexed looks on people's faces when they sit
down to their first meal and read a menu entry like this one:
``Gooseneck barnacle terrine with grand fir and calendula petal
emulsion, bull kelp pickle and sea cucumber.'' But they soon learn
that weird as it may sound, it tastes like the very essence of the
sea. It tastes like Japan. It tastes very good.
</P>
<P>
   With it and the other inventive dishes on the menu come wines
from a 91-page list _ wines from France and Australia and Italy,
Germany and California and Oregon, including runs of older vintages
of Stag's Leap Cask 23 and Silver Oak cabernet sauvignons; Grange
shiraz from South Australia and choice, scarce Leonettis from
Washington. On top of that, there are intriguing wines from
Vancouver Island itself, as well as the Okanagan Valley, British
Columbia's premier viticultural area.
</P>
<P>
   But the magic of Sooke Harbour House lies in more than its table
and its cellar. The setting is remarkable, with fog and mist
swirling in from the sea, sometimes lying like a duvet on the
harbor. Clearing and clouding over several times a day, the sky
first reveals and then obscures the mountains, like some cosmic
theatrical curtain rising and falling. And all the while, sea lions
and orca whales frolic offshore while ospreys and loons circle
overhead.
</P>
<P>
   The rooms, each different, each decorated with Indian and other
local art, are the spacious balcony seats for this spectacle. Most
have fireplaces and refrigerators; each gets its ration of two big
sugar cookies every day.
</P>
<P>
   It is the kind of place that defies a person to get or stay
uptight. I went planning to catch up on some reading and writing,
but I failed.
</P>
<P>
   One of the Philip daughters, Nishka, 19, gave me a running
commentary one morning when I tagged along behind her as she
gathered flower petals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' she said, pointing to some chivelike stems topped with
purple flowers, ``is called `society' garlic, because it's not
supposed to get on your breath or anything. But I have my doubts,
eh? These orange flowers you see everywhere are pot marigolds, or
calendulas. They bloom all year, throughout the calendar, which is
where they get their name. The breakfast people put them in cheese
biscuits, to make the biscuits taste twice as cheesy. Long ago,
they were used to color Cheddar.''
</P>
<P>
   Who would guess where flavors lurk in the garden? Day lily
flowers go into sorbet, carnation petals are added to salads, and
sweet woodruff, an herb with a perky white flower, long used by
Central Europeans in wine punches, is used at Sooke in ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   No culinary use has been found yet for the passionflower vine
that grows along the eaves on one side of the house. It is a pet of
Nishka's, not only because of its pretty, complex purple-blue
flowers, but also because it spreads so exuberantly. ``You can hear
it growing,'' she assured me with a grin.
</P>
<P>
   A little farther along, Nishka stopped at two groups of plants,
side by side, which looked identical to me. To her, too, as it
turned out. A book I found later in the house identified one as
Korean mint (Agastache rugosa), which smells like root beer, and
the other, a cousin, as anise hyssop (Agastache foeniculum), which
has a slight licorice flavor. That night, my wife, Betsey, and I
had a sauce subtly flavored with anise hyssop, among other things,
on a piece of black cod. Another night, a small packet of black cod
arrived in a crab and corn broth, flavored with shingeku, or
chrysanthemum leaves.
</P>
<P>
   In both dishes, it was the fresh, sweet taste and the firm,
slightly springy texture of the fish that hit you at first bite.
Only slowly did the herbal flavors assert themselves, adding an
unanticipated contrast.
</P>
<P>
   A gray, gawky cardoon plant grew into a tree near a cluster of
borage plants _ ``borage for the bees,'' Nishka said, ``they love
it.'' So do Englishmen, I told her; they put whole stalks of the
stuff into the Pimms' Cup they like to drink at Wimbledon or after
a cricket match. Across the way, she pointed to a hedge of hops,
grown not for beer but for the delicate young spring shoots, which
the Belgians (and also the Philips) cook like asparagus.
</P>
<P>
   In a shady spot at the foot of the hedge some fernlike sweet
cicely was doing nicely. Some of it was destined for a mild
sabayon, also flavored with ginger and white peaches, which Tuson
served us on superbly briny sea urchin roe he had taken from the
shell a mere five minutes before we ate it.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Cook, head gardener for 13 years, grows all sorts of salad
crops, including shiso, the hauntingly flavored Japanese leaf, and
arugula and red romaine and Red Sails lettuce. Most of them are
planted in raised beds, so the soil can more easily be renewed with
compost, as successive crops are harvested.
</P>
<P>
   Cook's is more or less a year-round operation. It seldom snows
at Sooke, which lies in hardiness Zone 8, the same as Charleston,
S.C., a beneficiary of benign Pacific breezes and currents. A few
of the tenderer plants, like verbena, are lifted from the soil and
kept inside for the brief winter, and cuttings are taken of others
to start fresh plants when spring arrives.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the lettuces, the pansies, the English daisies and
the hardier herbs (like an 11-foot rosemary bush outside one of the
guest rooms) keep right on chugging, year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Not everything flourishes at Sooke. It took Cook a half-dozen
tries to establish Mexican marigolds, which have a flavor similar
to tarragon, and even in this cosseted corner of the Pacific, dill
gets scraggly and sun-hungry basil doesn't grow very tall.
Reassuring, I guess, for us brown-thumbs.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET LAVENDER, MAPLE SYRUP AND CARROT ICE MILK
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Sooke Harbour House
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 40 minutes, plus freezing time
</P>
<P>
   For the carrot puree:
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds organic carrots, trimmed and peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh organic rosemary or 2 tablespoons dried
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unfiltered organic apple juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   For the ice milk:
</P>
<P>
   2 cups 2 percent milk
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons fresh or dried organic lavender flowers or a 2-inch
cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   8 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   { cup maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   \ cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   \ cup brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce brandy, Cognac, rye or rum.
</P>
<P>
   1. To prepare carrot puree, combine carrots, rosemary, apple
juice and brown sugar in a medium nonreactive saucepan. Place over
high heat until simmering, then cover, and reduce heat to
medium-low. Cook until carrots are soft, 35 to 40 minutes. Remove
from heat, and set aside to cool.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a food processor, puree the carrots with any remaining
juice. Process until the puree is very smooth, about 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. To prepare ice milk, combine carrot puree, milk and lavender
in a medium saucepan. Place mixture over medium heat until it just
reaches a simmer. Remove from heat, and keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   4. In a medium nonreactive bowl, combine egg yolks, maple syrup,
granulated sugar and brown sugar. Heat mixture over a double
boiler, whisking until it is thick and light in color, about 15
minutes. Remove from heat, and place a strainer over mixture. Pour
in carrot puree, stirring and pressing with a rubber spatula until
puree passes through into egg mixture.
</P>
<P>
   5. Return double boiler to heat. Whisk until mixture is steaming
and thick enough to coat the back of a spoon, about 15 minutes.
Remove from heat, and whisk occasionally as it cools. (If mixture
begins to curdle, pour into a blender and process until smooth.)
</P>
<P>
   6. When mixture has cooled, stir in brandy. Freeze in an
ice-cream maker, according to manufacturer's instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1{ quarts (about 6 servings).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
