<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5646 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART(TRIMS)     08-29 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-ART(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HER SPOT ON OLYMPIC TEAM NOW SECURE, SERENA WILLIAMS DEFENDS OPEN
TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT11 and 12 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ White lines marked off the court inside Arthur Ashe
Stadium, but Serena Williams arrived to defend her U.S. Open title
as if she was stepping out onto a dance floor, wearing a party
dress from a Woodstock reunion.
</P>
<P>
   In a black mesh outfit cut low and high, with a fuchsia-colored
tie-dyed print curving along provocative lines, Williams scrambled
to put away points in hot-pink Pumas. But as impossible as she was
to miss during her 6-3, 6-2 bludgeoning of Tina Pisnik on Tuesday,
Williams managed to camouflage herself less than an hour later. In
a hallway outside of an interview room, Williams slipped inside of
a vestibule, where she went unnoticed as Lisa Raymond exited an
adjacent door and walked past her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to run into her,'' Williams admitted a few
minutes later. ``Obviously, she's probably still not feeling great.
It was a tough one to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams wasn't talking about a match. Just a week earlier,
Raymond's lawyer argued in front of an arbitrator in Manhattan that
she _ and not Williams _ had earned the right as the No. 1 doubles
player to represent the United States on the four-woman Olympic
team.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the U.S. Tennis Association had selected the top
doubles player to be the fourth person on the team. But this time,
the coach Billie Jean King went against precedent and chose on
singles rankings alone. And although arbitrator Richard Jeydel
called the USTA's selection process unclear and misleading, he
ruled that Williams would remain on the team with Lindsay
Davenport, sister Venus Williams and Monica Seles.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome was devastating to Raymond. And perhaps most
upsetting to her the fact that King, famous for fighting injustices
against women, didn't come to her defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely an irony to that,'' Raymond said after
dismissing Magdalena Grzybowska 6-1, 6-0, on the Grandstand Court
on Tuesday. ``Billie got her Dream Team.''
</P>
<P>
   America has a group capable of sweeping the medals, right down
to the powerful doubles combo of Venus and Serena Williams. This is
the intimidating team King wanted to assemble, the popular players
the USTA needs to promote the sport and the group NBC must be
thrilled to have in order to boost the Olympic television ratings.
</P>
<P>
   It's win-win for everyone but the unassuming Raymond, a career
wallflower on the Tour. Although Raymond is a top-25 singles player
and dominant in doubles, she is more solid than sizzle on the
tennis scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great we have the Williams sisters,'' Raymond
said. ``I think it's great we have the Anna Kournikova's, the
rivalries with the Williamses and Lindsay and Martina Hingis. You
would just hope when you're making a decision like this, that would
be put aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the attention-getters on the women's tour, Serena
Williams may be the hottest product. She is the one who rang the
opening bell on the New York Stock Exchange on Monday morning, the
one with a doll created in her stylish image and the defending
champion who turned everyone's head in her first-round match
Tuesday. With overhead smashes that sent the crowd flinching at her
might, with blistering forehands that clipped the lines, her
powerful game was on display. And so was her taste in a tennis
dress she helped design.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows how well _ how good I look, how well in shape I am,''
said Williams with a sly smile. ``It's just really flattering, I
think.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the men will wear dresses next. As a sign of how anonymous
the men's tour has become, there was barely a buzz in Arthur Ashe
Stadium when second-seeded Gustavo Kuerten was upset in four sets
by Wayne Arthurs.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the tour's best hope to fill the void that will soon be
created when Pete Sampras and Andre Agassi leave the stage. Here
was the charismatic Brazilian with the colorful style and telegenic
game. Here was the one player the tour had heavily featured when
officials kicked off a marketing campaign with the slogan ``New
Balls, Please'' in an effort to promote the young stars.
</P>
<P>
   But the instant Arthurs slashed an ace by Kuerten on match
point, the moment the curly-haired French Open winner dropped his
head in defeat, the marketing campaign aimed at their American
audience during the Open suffered a humiliating hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I said to them, I don't want to be promoted,'' said
Kuerten, who is an icon in Brazil. ``I'm already too much promoted.
I want to be unknown. I don't want to go and people recognize me
everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some players are more comfortable with attention that others.
Serena Williams seems to revel in it. At times during her match
against Pisnik, she turned ordinary points into theater. Instead of
a simple overhead, she cracked her racket like a whip as she
crushed the ball for winners. Instead of giving up on a well-placed
passing shot by the Slovene, she raced against the odds to reach
it, if only to extend the point one stroke longer.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Williams put on a show for those assembled in
Arthur Ashe Stadium, the site of her first _ and, so far, only _
Grand Slam title one year ago. If Williams feels any pressure from
the hype around her, she isn't letting on. When told that John
McEnroe was quoted as saying a good male college player or senior
player could beat her, she just grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want a piece of me?'' Williams said, playfully challenging
McEnroe. ``Obviously, men are stronger than women. He can throw
down if he wants. I don't know. Who knows? It's interesting. It
would be interesting to see where we stand on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Any match with Williams is usually quite a sight. Tuesday,
everyone was riveted to one of the tour's top entertainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems wherever I go, there's a lot of attention on me,
anyway,'' Williams said. ``It's like I'm used to it. It really
doesn't change with the new outfit, the dolls, Stock Exchange bell.
I'm kind of used to a lot of attention.''
</P>
<P>
   She can disappear when she wants, too. Raymond never saw
Williams as she walked down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a really nice girl,'' said Williams, who was an
unwitting participant thrown into the selection fray. ``She made it
clear that she wasn't bringing the case against me; she just
thought she should be able to go. It's completely understandable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
