<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOBBYISTS-RESTAURANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 LOBBYISTS AND TECHIES FIND A COMMON THEME: LET THEM EAT STEAK 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the old days, before Microsoft met the Justice
Department, high-tech companies could not tell a lobbyist from a
congressman. Hint: one wears tasseled loafers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the lobbyists and the high-tech executives are so tight they
have gone into business together. This week, the Caucus Room, a
steakhouse, opens in downtown Washington under 65 partners whose
rosters of political connections, high-tech interests, and in some
cases both, are longer than a Manhattan wine list.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas H. Boggs Jr., a prominent lobbyist, and Haley Barbour,
former chairman of the Republican National Committee and now in the
lobbying business, hold the largest shares, $150,000 each. Ted
Leonsis, a top executive at American Online, and Jon Ledecky of
E2Enet are on the list.
</P>
<P>
   It is a bipartisan bunch: Terry McAuliffe, President Clinton's
top fund-raiser; C. Boyden Gray, a former counsel to President Bush
and now with the law firm Wilmer, Cutler &AMP; Pickering; Thomas
Downey, a former Democratic congressman and now a lobbyist; Richard
Burt, the former ambassador to Germany; and Frank Luntz, a
Republican pollster. Even the Senate sergeant-at-arms, James
Ziglar, has a share in the $3.3 million federal-style restaurant
with mahogany paneling and marble floors, not so subtle reminders
of the hallowed halls of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   At first blush, opening a restaurant seems an unlikely
get-rich-quick scheme. The failure rate is high. But the Caucus
Room quickly became the hottest investment in town and was
oversubscribed in four days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like an IPO,'' said Boggs, but one about
contacts, not money. ``It's a downtown watering hole and a place to
make deals,'' he said. ``And it's time for the techies and
politicians to realize they are in the same world. Pre-Microsoft,
techies thought Washington wasn't something they had to worry
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Raoul Fernandez, founder, chairman and chief executive officer
of Proxicom Inc., an Internet company that does business with the
Fortune 500 companies, agrees. ``All tech companies have a level of
sensitivity to educating the Hill,'' said Fernandez, who once
worked for Jack Kemp, a former Republican congressman from New York
and Bob Dole's running mate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an issue right now that I have to have Tommy or
Haley help me out, but I want to stay in touch with those people,''
Fernandez said, adding he could not think of a better way to stay
in touch than investing in their political hangout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted and Jon and I are in this from a business standpoint,''
Fernandez said. ``It's going to provide meeting rooms that are not
available today. I hope being an equity owner will move me up the
list when I need one of those rooms.'' Fernandez has invested
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   And for a lobbyist, owning a restaurant where lobbyists take
their clients sounds like a perfect set up. As John F. Jonas, a
partner in Boggs' firm, Patton Boggs, and a partner in the
restaurant, explained it: ``You are billing them for your time, and
they pay for the meal. In that way it's sort of a sweetheart
deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the partners say they are also in it for the status.
``People probably invest in restaurants for the same reason they
invest in thoroughbreds or race cars,'' Jonas said. ``It has
panache to be able to say I have an interest in a restaurant.
Hopefully, the people in the restaurant will be a little nicer to
you. You won't have to beg for a table or sit in the back corner
and have the kitchen door slam into you.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonsis, who burst on to the Washington scene when he bought the
city's hockey team, the Capitals, and a minority interest in its
basketball team, the Wizards, said in an e-mail message that he
became a partner because he ``needed a place to be assured of
having some privacy when I dine with partners such as Michael
Jordan.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``Becoming a partner in a restaurant was on my list of
101 things to do before I die.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbour hoots at what he calls this ``psychic benefit stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My psychoanalysis is a little dull from drinking bourbon for
40 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One might ask whether Washington actually needs another
steakhouse. But for lobbyists, apparently, you cannot have too many
steak houses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The food will be good but it won't be the finest French
restaurant,'' Jonas said. But, he added: ``I don't think a great
French restaurant would be a hangout for politicians and lobbyists
because many of them are not of the fine French ilk. Steak is safe
food. You don't have to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But you do have to think about how much. Surf and turf at the
Caucus Room will cost $59.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
