u i BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-NYT &LR;      08-29 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-RACISM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS RACISM CONFERENCE IN SOUTH AFRICA OPENS, DIVISIONS STILL
PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The poor of South Africa made their
way from remote farms and rural villages last month to testify
before government hearings around the country. And in their
painstaking accounts of modern-day wrongs, there rang disturbing
echoes of this country's ugly history.
</P>
<P>
   In Coligny, black patients spoke of doctors who still keep
segregated waiting rooms. In Orkney, police officers complained
about supervisors who bar blacks from sharing toilets or spoons
with white colleagues. And in Bloemfontein, black students
described how white classmates hurled condoms filled with water at
them.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, this country's simmering anxieties over racism
have flared as President Thabo Mbeki and Tony Leon, the leader of
the predominantly white opposition, have exchanged bitter words,
and the president has publicly accused Leon of being a racist.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa is preparing to hold a national conference on
racism this week, and the testimony from the hearings offers an
intimate look into how racism still touches lives beyond the
headlines and political squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of black people testified, with most complaining about
racial slurs and discrimination in hiring and promotions.
</P>
<P>
   But in rural provinces, a troubling number also described
vicious crimes and places where the rules of apartheid seemingly
remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings were in preparation for the conference, which is to
be opened by Mbeki on Wednesday, in the hope that a public airing
of the problems will unite the country in a battle against hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have spoken about reconciliation and we have spoken about
nation-building, but we have never as a nation spoken about
confronting our racist past, and how we move forward and deal with
racism,'' said Pansy Tlakula, a member of the Human Rights
Commission, which is coordinating the conference.
</P>
<P>
   But talk of the conference has highlighted the divisions in this
racially polarized society. The conference has been welcomed by
some and disparaged by others, with supporters and naysayers
falling on predictable sides of the color line.
</P>
<P>
   Of the hundreds who attended the public hearings, only a handful
were white. The rights commission is often dismissed by whites as
being biased against them.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Mine Workers Union, which represents 65,000
Afrikaners in mining, telecommunications and electrical
engineering, plan to picket the conference, saying it fails to
address the racism that white employees now experience in the
workplace.
</P>
<P>
   While Vusi Mona, a columnist for The City Press who is black,
praised the conference as an ``opportunity to deal with racism
candidly,'' Solomon Jacobovsky described it in a letter to the
editor published Tuesday in The Citizen as a waste of precious
taxpayer dollars. ``What, if anything, have these undertakings
achieved?'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   There is certainly no indication that the conference will ease
tensions between the leading politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Leon denounced Mbeki's insistence on searching for
African solutions to the AIDS epidemic, saying his efforts
represented little more than ``snake-oil cures and quackery.''
</P>
<P>
   The president responded by attacking Leon as ``willing to
enunciate an entrenched white racism that is a millennium old.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to him, a politician who practices his craft on the
African continent, these solutions, because they are African, could
not but consist of the pagan, savage, superstitious and
unscientific responses,'' said Mbeki, who is financing local
scientists in their search for an AIDS vaccine but who has been
criticized for embracing theories about AIDS disparaged by most
scientists.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and academics have urged the two men to stop their
quarrel and to find common ground. And while there has been no hint
that tensions between them are easing, the public hearings did
offer tentative signs of hope.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Nel, one of the few whites to testify at rights commission
hearings, said he was pleased that his children were growing up in
an integrated world. And Tlotlo Mokoke, a 9-year-old schoolboy,
testified that in his class white children and black children share
food and toys.
</P>
<P>
   Graeme Simpson, the executive director of the Center for the
Study of Violence and Reconciliation, said the conference was a
good idea, although he was doubtful that it would have much
influence on the lives of ordinary people.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real risk that it stays quite a lot of hot air for
most people,'' he added. ``But at the same time, it's an absolutely
central issue. It's very obvious that racism is alive and well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
