<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5650 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-TRANSMETA-MARKETPLACE     08-29 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSMETA-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: TRANSMETA'S IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   By DANNY HAKIM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In January, a semiconductor company called Transmeta promised to
make laptop computer batteries that would last a full workday.
Though it is still months away from its planned delivery date,
Transmeta has since signed deals with prominent computer makers,
including IBM and Sony, and has filed for an initial offering of
its stock.
</P>
<P>
   That public stock offering is widely expected to get a blazing
reception, despite a market far cooler to new technology offerings
than last year's. After all, the company is backed by two prominent
billionaire investors, the financier George Soros and Paul Allen,
co-founder of Microsoft. Its star employee is Linus Torvalds, the
30-year-old native of Finland who created the free Linux operating
system and who is revered by many young programmers. And its Crusoe
processors promise to be contenders in a rapidly growing market for
laptops and mobile computing devices.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some professional investors are not too optimistic about
how the dust will settle after the offering. They point out that
the devices with Transmeta processors have not yet reached the
public, and the company has recorded $119.4 million in losses in
just over five years. And then there is Intel. Though technology
analysts believe Transmeta's technology will have advantages in the
mobile computing market, Intel has proved a fierce competitor time
and again.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Torvalds' presence, Transmeta is not a company whose
business is based around the Linux operating system; it is a
semiconductor company that plans to use Linux in conjunction with
some of its chip designs. Nonetheless, some analysts and money
managers raise the specter of slumping Linux-related stocks when
talking about Transmeta. After huge public offerings last year,
shares of Red Hat and VA Linux Systems have lost in excess of 70
percent each this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a hot IPO with a big valuation,'' said
Christopher J. Bonavico, who manages two technology-driven mutual
funds with about $620 million in assets for the insurer
Transamerica. Bonavico does not plan on participating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investing in nifty technology is very dangerous,'' he added.
``Look where Red Hat is now. You could say I would've bought it and
then sold it, but someone always gets left holding the bag.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashok Kumar, a semiconductor analyst at U.S. Bancorp Piper
Jaffray, was even more skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   ``Initially, there was a lot of hype, which has since died
down,'' he said. ``I don't think you can classify their approach as
revolutionary. I don't think the niches Intel is leaving unfilled
are big enough to establish a business model. When your competitor
is Intel, it's a risky proposition. Previous attempts to find
chinks in their armor have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, William P. Savoy, president of Vulcan Ventures,
Allen's venture capital firm, called Transmeta ``one of the most
exciting hardware investments we've ever made.'' He added, ``It's
so appropriate to bring this technology out when the world is
moving to lower and lower power-consumption devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Venu Reddy, a semiconductor analyst at the fund manager Waddell
&AMP; Reed, which did not invest in Transmeta in the private market,
said his firm would likely participate in the offering, even though
he did not believe the Crusoe processor was as groundbreaking as
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because you use the Transmeta processor doesn't mean your
battery power will be improved by leaps and bounds,'' he said.
Still, ``even if Transmeta gets 5 percent of the market, we can
make a lot of money,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry that analysts estimate at $40 billion a year, a
new company might not need a leading role to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   But Transmeta has high expectations for a company that has yet
to see products with its semiconductors hit the market. The date of
its offering, which has Morgan Stanley Dean Witter as the lead
underwriter, has not been set, nor has a price range. But Transmeta
seeks to raise $200 million for 10 percent of its company,
according to people close to the company, giving it an implied
valuation of $2 billion. At that price, it would need about $128
million in annual sales to achieve a price-to-sales ratio
comparable to that of Intel.
</P>
<P>
   Transmeta has a built-in audience, the technophiles that are
fans of Torvalds and are curious about Transmeta's chip design,
which uses software for functions that conventional chips do with
transistors. That, in conjunction with other design features, will
allow laptop batteries to run for up to eight hours, instead of two
to four, the company has said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the company unveiled its technology at a heavily attended
press conference in January, Transmeta labored under a veil of
silence and nondisclosure agreements. It was not even entirely
clear it could be called a semiconductor company. The approach only
inflamed curiosity about the company, which was incorporated in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a huge amount of interest, and not just
because Linus is a part of it,'' said Jeff Bates, the executive
editor of Slashdot.org, a popular online journal for technology
enthusiasts that is a unit of VA Linux. ``A lot of people are
curious about how Crusoe works.''
</P>
<P>
   Bates and the site's other editors have posted dozens of stories
chronicling each twist and turn in Transmeta's development,
analyzing the company's patents for clues and posting articles with
titles like ``Another Peep from Transmeta.'' Readers have responded
with thousands of messages.
</P>
<P>
   Before January, rumors on Slashdot had Transmeta collaborating
with the National Security Agency (not true), devising new uses for
Linux (true), and plotting the destruction of the world (not true).
</P>
<P>
   ``The question was, what has Linus Torvalds been working on in
the lab for all these years?'' said Charles Rutstein, an analyst at
the technology consulting firm Forrester Research. ``Now that's
been answered and people are waiting for proof. Show me the
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutstein, who sees the merits of the company's technology,
expects that the next step will be a ``major manufacturer signing
with them and saying `we're going to produce millions of devices
with Transmeta chips.'''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Alexander Cheung, manager of the hedge fund
Long Bow Capital Partners, believes a recent deal by Sony to use
Transmeta chips in some laptops will be news enough to drive a
lofty offering.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what IPOs are all about,'' he added. ``People looking
for a ray of hope.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2051EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5651 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-TASTINGS &LR; - &UR; NYT &LR;      08-29 0512
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTINGS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELIGHTS OF A FAMILIAR GRAPE 
</HEADLINE>
 - NYT  (Editors: the a in Macon requires a circumflex.) 
 By   ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wine drinkers in this country learn early on about
the Maconnais region in southern Burgundy. Its dry, clean white
wines are generally reliable and inexpensive, and for a beginner,
offer a fallback when choices are otherwise overwhelming. It's as
easy to point to a bottle of Macon-Villages at the wine shop as it
is to ask for a glass of chardonnay at a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Macon producers are likewise learning about American wine
drinkers. They now frequently add the word ``chardonnay'' to the
Macon label, since that is, after all, the white grape of the
Maconnais and Burgundy. Few words are so alluring to American wine
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of Macons are made by large cooperatives intent on
maximizing production, and thus fill the beginners' market. But
some Macon wines are made by small quality-minded producers, and
exhibit a delightful concentrated fruitiness that is fresh and
deep, crisp and satisfying. Wines like the Thevenet listed below
and the Petit Chapeau (which comes from property owned by the
celebrated Domaine des Comtes Lafon of Meursault) offer much more
than reliability: they offer pleasure, which beginners can enjoy as
much as anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Macons shipped to the United States are generally labeled
Macon-Villages or Macon followed by the name of a particular
village, like Macon-Pierreclos. Also from the Maconnais are wines
labeled St.-Veran and Pouilly-Fuisse, which are more expensive but
not always better.
</P>
<P>
   The artisanal Macons are not always better, either. Some taste
so powerfully of oak that I can only imagine that the winemakers
fancied that they were making expensive white Burgundies. In
Burgundy, such wines theoretically balance the oak with equally
powerful fruit flavors, but in the warmer, flatter Macon the depth
of flavor rarely exists. The wines I like best are made either
without oak or with just a little bit of it to round out the flavor
of the grapes.
</P>
<P>
   The first three of these six wines are significantly better than
the others, though all are more interesting than the
run-of-the-mill Macon.
</P>
<P>
   JEAN-CLAUDE THEVENET, MACON-PIERRECLOS 1998 $12 &QL; 
Perfumed fruit and anise aromas; both fruity and earthy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PETIT CHAPEAU, MACON-VILLAGES 1998 $15 &QL; 
Brilliant citrus aromas; clear fruit flavors, with richness and
depth. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOMAINE ANDRE BONHOMME, MACON-VIRE , CUVEE SPECIALE 1998 $16 &QL; 
Round, ripe fruit aromas; razor sharp flavors; dry and refreshing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JOSETTE ET JEAN-NOEL CHALAND, DOMAINE DES CHAZELLES, &QL; 
MACON-VIRE 1998 $14  &QL; 
Aromas of yeast and apples; deep, rich flavors; long finish. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MERLIN, MACON LA ROCHE VINEUSE 1998 $13 &QL; 
Zippy citrus and apple aromas; creamy texture. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VERGET, MACON-VILLAGES, TETE DE CUVEE 1998 $14  &QL; 
Round and oaky with a creamy texture but lacking fruit. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Listed in order of preference. Prices are those paid in various
Manhattan wine shops.  &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
