<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Foley, McCollum attack hate crimes
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Saying those who commit crimes based on
hatred should be punished, U.S. Reps. Bill McCollum and Mark Foley
announced plans Tuesday to push new federal hate crime legislation.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum, a Republican candidate for the U.S. Senate, made
appearances in Tampa, Orlando, Miami and West Palm Beach to promote
House passage of a Senate hate crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Both Foley, who is running for re-election, and McCollum
admitted that chances of the legislation passing this year are
slim. But both argued that if they can stir enough interest in the
bill, legislation could still make it this year.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting with Jewish leaders at Temple Beth El, McCollum said
hate crimes have become an increasingly serious problem. He said
judges should be given the power to lengthen sentences for crimes
based on racial, sexual, religious or gender hatred.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the strongest opposition to the bill has come from those
who oppose including ``sexual orientation.'' McCollum said those
who want to leave sexual orientation out of the legislation are
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue is not gay rights,'' he said. ``The issue is civil
rights and hate crimes that are fundamentally wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In a written statement, McCollum's Democratic rival, Insurance
Commissioner Bill Nelson, accused McCollum of being a recent
convert to hate crimes legislation who is using the issue only for
campaign purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, R-West Palm Beach, defended McCollum, saying the
Altamonte Springs Republican had been involved in hate crimes
legislation long before he became a candidate for office.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
