<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5656 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-IONIDES-ARTIFACTS-$AD     08-29 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IONIDES-ARTIFACTS-$ADV03-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN GOOD EYE AND GOODLY FORTUNE COME TOGETHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 3) 
 By MITCHELL OWENS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in the 1920s, the designer Basil Ionides was one of
Britain's brightest aesthetic lights. His books _ ``Color and
Interior Decoration'' and ``The Modern English Interior'' _ were
best sellers, the former chockablock with watercolor illustrations
of his homes, prime examples of a scientific approach to the play
of light on bold but carefully graded color schemes. Ionides'
professional piece de resistance was the 1929 mirror-and-glass
decoration of the Savoy Theater in London, whose icy glitter still
staggers the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Ionides (pronounced eye-AH-nuh-deez) was also an outstanding
collector. By the time of his death in 1950, at 66, the half-Greek,
half-English designer and color theorist and his wife, Nellie, had
amassed an impressive haul of early Chinese porcelain. A dish from
this cache, which was sold at Sotheby's in 1963 and 1964, will be a
centerpiece of an exhibition at the Chinese Porcelain Co. at 475
Park Ave. (58th Street) from Oct. 12 to Oct. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Measuring 13 1/2 inches in diameter and about 3 inches deep, the
dish is a rare example of Kangxi famille noire, a style of
decoration whose floral motifs and naturalistic scenes are set on a
near-black background. What makes the 18th-century antique special
is the dark background's gentle luster, a fleeting, slightly
metallic sheen that an enraptured early observer poetically called
``the reflections of a raven's wing.'' Curious, too, is the
technique behind the effect, which must have appealed to Ionides,
whose hallmark was layering of different tones of paint to create a
vivacious surface. Since pure black was difficult to achieve by
Chinese potters of the day, they created a near-black effect by
applying shades of green over blackish-brown enamels.
</P>
<P>
   The show, whose 30-odd exhibits include blanc de chine and
famille verte, features an additional famille noire treasure: A
baluster vase once owned by John D. Rockefeller Jr. and his son
Nelson. Records indicate that the vase may have been purchased from
the estate of J. Pierpont Morgan. Both it and the Ionides dish now
belong to a private collector in South America.
</P>
<P>
   Basil Ionides came by his aestheticism naturally, growing up in
a clan of prominent Byzantine Greeks who emigrated to England
around 1820, eventually gaining fame as patrons of London's art
world in the late 19th century. An aunt was a muse to William
Morris, the high priest of the Arts and Crafts movement. Several
family members were painted by Watts, Rossetti and Burne-Jones, the
Pre-Raphaelite artists; Oscar Wilde and James McNeill Whistler were
family friends.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a fitfully successful stockbroker, Ionides was a
delicate, spoiled child whose artistic bent triumphed over a spotty
formal education. ``I doubt if it be a true advantage for a boy to
be first at a prep school, however good, that is run by a cousin of
his mother,'' recalled Dorothea Butterworth, his elder sister.
``And then at a public school house run by family friends who
encourage him to work or pass time in their own private garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Women played a crucial role in Ionides' life, none more so than
his wife, Nellie Samuel Levy. A friend of Queen Mary, she had
already amassed considerable objets d'art by the time she married
the designer, her second husband, in 1930: Canton enamel snuff
boxes, English chinoiserie silver, 18th-century etchings of the
Thames (she also had a charming weakness for tapestries and
paintings depicting poodles).
</P>
<P>
   When they met, Ionides already had a couple of houses stuffed
with antique ceramics. Not surprisingly, it was art that brought
the couple together. The 40-something widowed philanthropist and
Ionides, a slightly younger bachelor who lived with his mother,
were introduced by Margaret Jourdain, an expert on Georgian
furniture, who recommended Ionides to decorate Nellie Levy's London
house at 49 Berkeley Square West.
</P>
<P>
   Though impressed by his new client's taste, Ionides was not
unmindful of her financial attributes. She marched to the altar
fully loaded with a fortune derived from Shell Oil, which was
founded by her father, Marcus Samuel, one of the first British Jews
to receive a peerage. The money was an asset of which her husband
was immodestly proud. James Lees-Milne, an adviser to the National
Trust, visited Buxted Park, the couple's storied country house in
Sussex, in the 1940s and was astonished to hear the designer _
``pleasant, jolly, bon viveur, large and well-fed,'' he recorded in
his diary that evening _ confide that Nellie Ionides' estate would
be worth more than two million pounds after her death.
Unfortunately for her husband, the Hon. Ionides outlived him by
more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Ionides transformed the Berkeley Square house into a private
museum. Nellie's hundreds of Battersea enamels _ plaques,
candlesticks, boxes _ were stored in a round vaulted room lined
with glass-fronted cabinets of stripped-down neo-Classical design.
In the next room went a horde of porcelains, arranged on open
floor-to-ceiling shelves. A 1938 photograph of the connecting
spaces shows in the background, propped on a shelf, the dish that
will be on display. Whether it was originally his purchase or hers
is unknown.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkeley Square interiors were an exceptional tribute to
Basil Ionides' discerning eye and Nellie Ionides' fortune, as was
Buxted Park (now a hotel). Both houses have long since changed
hands, but the handsome Kangxi dish that graced them remains: Mute
witness to the glory that can spark when two people with
complementary minds are joined as one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
