<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5657 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-JUDGE-EVANS-ART-     08-29 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-JUDGE-EVANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA'S GRAND OLD MAN OF WINE RETIRES FROM JUDGING 
</HEADLINE>
 (Editors: Photos are available by calling Tim Fish of WineToday,
707 523-7922) 
 By HELEN PITT   
 WineToday.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTER VALLEY, Australia _ From his hilltop home, Len Evans, one
of Australia's best-known wine personalities, uses binoculars to
survey the activity as far as he can see, much like a feudal lord
keeping a check on the family estate.
</P>
<P>
   From his house, Evans keeps an eye on the construction progress
at his latest venture, the lodge at nearby Tower Estate. He also
takes a peek at The Rothbury Estate, the winery he established in
1968 but lost to Australian wine company Mildara Blass in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Evans turns 70 on Thursday, and for many years he has been
regarded as Australia's grand old man of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was known as Australian wine,'' Evans recalls. ``In the
great boom of Australian table wine in the 1960s and 1970s, I could
call any wine company and I didn't have to say my name; they knew
my voice.''
</P>
<P>
   That voice and accent are still distinctively Welsh, but his
tastes are decidedly Australian. Although within the Australian
wine world he's renowned for his brusque, opinionated and often
prickly manner, no one ever questions how Evans almost
single-handedly put Australia on the world winemaking stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the patriarch _ the godfather of Australian wine,'' says
winemaker Geoff Merrill of Geoff Merrill Wines, who recently
attended a dinner to mark Evans' retirement after 23 years as
chairman of judges at the Sydney Royal Wine Show.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to taste, he has that indefinable `something,'''
says friend and fellow wine writer James Halliday, who has known
Evans since 1967. ``When you couple that with his Welsh showman
style, you have fertile ground for a big personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, he says, is a ``boisterous, generous, at times imperious,
at times impulsive, larger-than-life figure intent on having the
best possible time, all of the time.''
</P>
<P>
   After 47 years in the Australian liquor industry, Evans remains
indefatigable, much like his California counterpart, Robert
Mondavi. His opinions are still sought and are widely respected
within the wine world.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Australia will be one of the three big wine
producers over the next 50 to 60 years,'' Evans declares. ``In 1985
we exported 1 million cases. Today we're well on the way to 30
million a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans, who began in the liquor trade as a glass washer, has come
a long way, much like the Australian wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was a teen-ager in a British boarding school, Evans has
loved wine. He kept a bottle of Madeira with him in his school
dormitory, which he would sip on Sunday evenings, well aware that
if he were caught it would mean instant expulsion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't drinking it because it was alcohol and I wanted to
get drunk, I was doing it because it was a nice thing to do and I
have always loved the romance of eating and drinking nice things,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   After serving in the occupation forces in Germany, and leaving a
promising career as a professional golfer, Evans emigrated first to
New Zealand, and then to Australia, in 1955. He took many manual
labor jobs, even building dingo fences in outback Queensland, then
came to Sydney in 1958, where he began the glass washing job at a
Sydney hotel.
</P>
<P>
   It was at a time when Australia was a nation of beer and
fortified wine drinkers. Evans progressed to food and beverage
manager at another hotel, the Chevron Hilton, just as the
Australian table wine industry was emerging.
</P>
<P>
   In 1962 he became Australia's first wine writer. In 1965 he
established the Australian Wine Bureau, which began the task of
gaining global recognition for Australian wines.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people accept the export success of Australian wine
as if it was their own work,'' Evans says. ``But it was 20 years of
an enormously hard slog. We were considered a hick country with
hick wines, just like the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember I met Robert Mondavi in Harrods department store in
London, where he was offering spotty English youths a glass of
wine; people who wouldn't know who the hell Robert Mondavi was. I
said, `Robert, what the Christ are you doing here??' And he said to
me, `Somebody has got to sell the stuff.' And that's what I was
doing too _ sell the stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans wasn't just selling wine, but buying it, too. In addition
to purchasing The Rothbury Estate, he also bought property across
the globe, including two chateaux in France.
</P>
<P>
   While he may have retired from wine judging, Evans is hardly
retiring in any other aspect of his life. He is overseeing the
interior decoration of Tower Lodge, the 12-room guesthouse that is
part of the Tower Estate. Evans is undertaking this project with 12
other Australian business identities, including winemaker Brian
McGuigan.
</P>
<P>
   Evans has also teamed up with Halliday on an Internet wine
venture, Winepros, which keeps him actively involved with the
industry. In his spare time _ not that there is much _ he turns his
hand to making ceramics and mosaics, a hobby he shares with his
wife, Trish. She, along with Evans' three children, have also been
involved in varying degrees in the food, wine and hospitality
world.
</P>
<P>
   Evans claims to have loved every minute of his working life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once in a while I see a wine of extraordinary quality,'' he
says, ``and it really does excite me. After all these years, a
great wine is still a thrill to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   (WineToday.com, a daily Internet wine publication, is published
by The New York Times Co.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2100EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
