<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-COLD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO NEED TO LOOK FOR RAIN _ IT'S IN YANKEELAND
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By PAUL BOURGEOIS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anyone in Texas wondering where all the rain has gone can stop
looking.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have it.
</P>
<P>
   Not the ones who routinely whip up on the Texas Rangers. It's
the folks in Albany, the one in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While Texas crops and lawns are dead or dying, and some areas
are rationing water, New York's capital city is awash.
</P>
<P>
   While we wonder if the rain will ever start, the Albanians, as
they call themselves, are wondering if it will ever end.
</P>
<P>
   They're calling it a ``monsoon'' and ``the summer that almost
wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   As hot, as dry and as sunny as cities in Texas have been, Albany
has been cool, wet and cloudy. A couple of times this summer the
overnight low there dipped into the 40s.
</P>
<P>
   In the Albany Times-Union on Tuesday, people were complaining
about how the rain has ruined vacations, weddings and holiday
plans. Tourism is down.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big difference between Albany and Fort Worth on a
normal basis, but this year has been extreme,'' said George
Maglaras, a National Weather Service meteorologist in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sort of in the reverse of what's causing your dry
weather. Basically, you have high pressure in the atmosphere over
Texas. You seem to be right in the middle of it, and we're lucky
enough to have a low-pressure system.''
</P>
<P>
   Maglaras said that a high-pressure area usually has a
corresponding low-pressure area. We've got one. They've got the
other.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, that means that we're hot and dry, and Albany is cool
and wet.
</P>
<P>
   How wet?
</P>
<P>
   For the year, Albany has had 35.13 inches of rain, 11.23 inches
above normal. Since June, they've had 15.88 inches, almost 6 inches
above normal.
</P>
<P>
   Maglaras said Albany had 15 days of rain in July and 12 so far
this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's quite a bit above normal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since June 30, most of Texas has had zip. For the year, 21.19
inches has been measured in North Texas, about an inch and a
quarter below normal.
</P>
<P>
   Another sprinkle and Albany will be setting records.
</P>
<P>
   So are we. Each day with no rain is a record.
</P>
<P>
   While they have our rain, we have their sun.
</P>
<P>
   Maglaras said a major indicator for Albany is the percentage of
sunshine. The sun shone on Albany only 42 percent of the time in
June. It should be about 60 percent. In July it was 52 percent,
about 12 percentage points below normal.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Texas Tuesday, the sun was shining 89 percent of the
time. It would have been higher except for the dry, tiny clouds
that drifted by for a second or two.
</P>
<P>
   Albany's highest temperature in July was 84. Our high in July
was on the 16th: 106 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Maglaras said July tied for the coldest ever in Albany with an
average daily temperature of 67.6 degrees, 4.2 degrees below
normal.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast in Albany Wednesday called for a low of 63 and a
high of 78, a degree or two cooler than our low.
</P>
<P>
   In North Texas Wednesday, the day should start at about 79 or
80, then rise to a toasty 101 or 102.
</P>
<P>
   There's no rain in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Albany expects showers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
