<HEADER>
A5668 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BO     08-29 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLLINS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHURS SERVES UP A BLOW TO BRAZILIAN PRIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If you're talking off-off-off Broadway in tennis, the
metropolis of Wrexham, Wales, might come to mind. The mind it came
to would probably be as far out and forsaken as the Wrexham Tennis
Club, where a few weeks ago a multitude of 20 gathered to watch the
defeat of a stranger from Slovakia named Ladislav Svarc by another
stranger from Australia named Wayne Arthurs.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a Wales of a match except that Arthurs
knocked the spark out of Svarc with a sinister serve _ a snaky,
venomous sidewinder that was still rattling and ravaging Tuesday on
quite a distant and different stage. Arthurs had promoted himself
to Broadway _ the US Open _ by sneaking through the back door of
qualifying, and he was shooting out the bright lights of a leading
man, Gustavo ``Guga'' Kuerten, the world's No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Arthurs, standing No. 96 for the current season, was the extra,
the spear-carrier who speared the star, 4-6, 6-3, 7-6 (7-4), 7-6
(7-1), in a vast amphitheater that became Wayne's world.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly, the Brazilian stock market crashed, coffee bushes
wilted, the county's samba dancers pulled up lame, and the Amazon
showed signs of drying up. Green and gold flags slid to half-mast,
and the president declared a state of mourning. Their beloved Guga
couldn't get out of the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Indianapolis, where Guga broke his hard-court jinx by
capturing that title nine days before, is also off-Broadway. But
that triumph of the French Open champion, Brazil's most adored
athlete, had raised his compatriots' hopes that he could succeed on
the mean green slabs of Flushing Meadows, where he barely lost in
the quarterfinals to Cedric Pioline a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But how could the leading man get his lines straight as Arthurs
kept cranking his left arm so ominously and unleashing serves that
sped or spun so unnervingly, amounting to 58 of his points (26
aces, 32 unreturnables)?
</P>
<P>
   Guga was in retreat, backing up as far as 4 yards behind the
baseline to give himself a longer, better look at balls that seemed
to be yellow BB's or apparitions wobbling crazily with slice and
topspin. After a while, the Brazilian felt he needed cataract
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``You guess to return, and sometimes you guess right,'' Guga
said. ``I didn't do the right thing at the right time. The right
time was all the break points I had'' _ he cashed one of nine _
``that can change it around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a great feeling coming here, great expectations. But
Arthurs is a tough guy for the first round. He can beat anybody in
the first round with that serve. I had chances.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Arthurs kept the ball tight to Kuerten's body on those
crucial break points _ rib-ticklers that weren't funny in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Arthurs, a willowy, 6-foot-3-inch blond out of Adelaide, is a
throwback, an old-fashioned Aussie serve-and-volleyer,
chip-and-charger. But nobody in Australia knew that. He was living
in England, dinking along in small tournaments such as the
unremarkable Wrexham Challenger, making a living.
</P>
<P>
   Abruptly at Wimbledon '99, where he also qualified, his life
changed through his own deeds _ and the misdeed of countryman Mark
Philippoussis. Arthurs began serving as though he had a thunderbolt
up his sleeve, going unbroken in six starts, and he nearly beat the
best returner in the business, Andre Agassi, in the fourth round.
Suddenly he was warmed in the sunshine of Aussie Davis Cup captain
John Newcombe's broad smile.
</P>
<P>
   Newc was impressed, then destitute shortly afterward, when
Philippoussis tumbled while beating Pete Sampras in the
quarterfinals and wrecked a knee. Arthurs, whose dreams of playing
Davis Cup for the homeland had never been realistic, was now in
Newcombe's plans, though not for the quarterfinal victory over the
US in Boston, clinched by Patrick Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   But Rafter broke down at the US Open, and Arthurs was in the
lineup for the semis against Russia, a rookie at 28. Only one other
Aussie had debuted at a more advanced age: Horace Rice at 39 in
1913. Arthurs came through big-time, beating Yevgeny Kafelnikov and
Marat Safin to put his guys in the final.
</P>
<P>
   By then, Philippoussis was back to ice another Davis Cup for
Australia, but Arthurs was proudly on the sidelines. ``Yes, I
thanked Mark for getting hurt and giving me my chance,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Wrexham, Wales, in July, for heaven's sake?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad Wimbledon,'' he said of another Wayne's world
situation, in which he fell to Wayne Ferreira immediately. ``I
needed matches, and I got five in winning the Wrexham Challenger.
Also $3,500, and the applause of about 20 spectators.'' Plus a
handshake from the inimitable Ladislav Svarc.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a few more here today,'' he said, recalling the
14,000 witnesses to his southpawing of Kuerten in the gross canyon
called Ashe Stadium. More than had ever watched him toil, and shine
as no qualifier had done in the opening round.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Arthurs had made a long journey from off-off-off Broadway
to Broadway itself while plunging Brazil into despair. He has come
up in the world, making some decent money, moving to Pinner in
Middlesex, the hometown of a singing tennis degenerate named Elton
John. He is not immodest in saying he serves better than John.
``But he sings better than me,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   But the fond folks in Australia wouldn't mind if their newfound
Wayne crooned a couple of Elton's hits to highlight his afternoon
feat. He made Guga look like a ``Candle in the Wind,'' sobbing,
``Goodbye, Yellow Brick Road.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
