<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0356 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-DLJ-CREDIT-SUISSE-ART     08-29 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DLJ-CREDIT-SUISSE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREDIT SUISSE BUYING DONALDSON, LUFKIN &AMP; JENRETTE FOR $12.8
BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT22 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Credit Suisse Group is expected to announce Wednesday
that it plans to buy Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, a Wall Street
investment bank, for about $12.8 billion, according to people
involved in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   An acquisition of Donaldson by the big Swiss bank would be the
second buyout of a Wall Street firm by a Swiss bank this summer,
and it would expand Credit Suisse's presence in financial markets
in the United States and Europe. The bank already owns Credit
Suisse First Boston, an investment banking unit that has become a
powerhouse in underwriting Internet companies and other technology
stocks in the last few years. Adding on Donaldson would make First
Boston the leading underwriter of high-yield, or junk, bonds, and a
top-ranked underwriter of stocks and provider of merger advice to
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Credit Suisse is offering to pay $45 cash and $45 in stock to
AXA SA, the French financial-services conglomerate that owns 72
percent of Donaldson, and $90 in cash for the rest of Donaldson's
shares, said people involved in the negotiations. Credit Suisse is
setting aside another $1.2 billion in a bonus pool to be used to
retain employees, those people said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Donaldson, Lufkin shot up early Tuesday as rumors of
an imminent buyout swept around financial markets. Shares of
Donaldson rose nearly 20 percent, or $16.44, to $82.25. Shares of
DLJDirect, which track the firm's online trading business, rose
$2.25, to $10.19.
</P>
<P>
   According to people involved in the negotiations, the deal came
together quickly during the last few weeks. In documents drawn up
by investment bankers, Donaldson was referred to by the code name
``diamond.'' One of those documents estimated that, together, the
two firms would have ranked fifth among U.S. securities firms last
year with combined net income of $1.8 billion. In the first half of
2000, they would have had net income of $1.2 billion, the document
showed.
</P>
<P>
   AXA would wind up owning about 8 percent of Credit Suisse.
Analysts and investors said that AXA had been looking for a buyer
for Donaldson to reduce the volatility of its earnings, and
possibly to raise cash to expand its insurance and money-management
businesses. AXA is the majority owner of AXA Financial, formerly
known as the Equitable Life Insurance company. AXA Financial in
turn is the majority owner of Alliance Capital, a fast-growing
mutual fund company.
</P>
<P>
   The buyout would spell the end for Donaldson 40 years after it
was founded by three partners who used stock research as the
foundation for building an independent investment bank. The name is
likely to disappear as the firm's operations are merged with First
Boston's. The online stock-trading unit, DLJDirect, will be renamed
CSFB Direct, the people said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Roby, the chief executive of Donaldson, would become
chairman of First Boston's executive committee. First Boston's
chief executive, Allen Wheat, would run the combined investment
banking operations.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said they were concerned about the amount of overlap
between the two firms' investment banks. People involved in the
negotiations said the merger was expected to yield about $1 billion
in annual costs savings by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Smith, an analyst at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods, said she
had ``mixed feelings'' about the proposed deal. ``It certainly
would help their market shares,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But, ``Culturally, there could be some clashing,'' she said.
``DLJ is more conservative and has a partnership-type feel.''
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson traditionally has been one of the most generous firms
on Wall Street. It pays out a higher percentage of its revenues _
about 54 percent last year _ to its employees than most other
firms.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is starkly different from the proposed $12 billion
acquisition of PaineWebber Group by another Swiss bank, UBS AG.
That deal, announced seven weeks ago, would give UBS a nationwide
network of brokers to sell the stocks and mutual funds created by
its investment bankers. UBS executives said they planned to operate
PaineWebber, the fourth-largest brokerage firm in the United
States, as a separate unit of the company and expected minimal
overlap between the two firms.
</P>
<P>
   First Boston and Donaldson are essentially competitors in the
creation, sale and trading of investment products. Both firms rank
high in the underwriting and trading of stocks, especially those of
young companies in fast-growing industries, such as technology,
telecommunications and health care.
</P>
<P>
   For several years, Donaldson has dominated the junk bond
business, an area of expertise it started building a decade ago by
hiring salesmen and traders from Drexel Burnham Lambert, the
defunct firm that was home to junk-bond maven Michael Milken in the
1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, that specialty has not served Donaldson so well. The
market for junk bonds has been in a protracted slump. At the same
time, a bigger investment bank, Goldman Sachs has made a big push
into the business. So far this year, Goldman has raised more money
for clients by selling junk bonds than any other firm has.
</P>
<P>
   By paying a premium to buy Donaldson, Credit Suisse is betting
that the market for junk bonds will rebound strongly. Combined, the
two firms would stand atop the junk-bond underwriting rankings,
known on Wall Street as league tables.
</P>
<P>
   David Williams said he thinks Credit Suisse is making a smart
wager _ but then, he is biased. Williams manages the Excelsior
Value and Restructuring Fund, which owns about 275,000 shares of
Donaldson stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think junk bonds are a screaming buy in here,'' Williams
said. ``But I bought it because it was cheap. The moral of the
story is it pays to buy cheap stocks.'' Williams said he thought
$90 a share was a fair price for Donaldson because it amounted to
about three times the firm's book value, or the value of its assets
minus its liabilities. Three times book value is considered the
going rate for securities firms. UBS is paying slightly more than
that for PaineWebber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
