<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-BURMA-DISSIDENT-ART-N     08-29 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BURMA-DISSIDENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY AUTHORITIES DETAIN MYANMAR'S DEMOCRACY LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand _ Her car has been shunted to the side of the
road. The air has been let out of its tires. The military
authorities say they are offering her food and medical care, but
they are also making sure she is going nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-democracy leader of Myanmar, Daw Aung San Suu Kyi, has
been camped in her car for six days now near a small country town
in a symbolic attempt to travel to meet with her supporters.
</P>
<P>
   She has done this four times before, in 1998, sitting stubbornly
in her small white Toyota for as long as 13 days at a time,
unharmed but firmly prevented from carrying out her political
activities.
</P>
<P>
   An official of her party, the National League for Democracy,
described the standoff as a ``war of endurance.'' It is a phrase
that applies equally well to her 12-year battle of wills with the
military rulers of her country, the former Burma.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story hasn't changed very much over the years,'' a Western
diplomat said. ``It's a standoff between the government and Aung
San Suu Kyi and her movement. It's perhaps worse to the extent that
the government now seems engaged in an attempt to destroy her party
definitively, once and for all.''
</P>
<P>
   As the years have passed and her party members have been jailed
or forced to halt their political activities, Aung San Suu Kyi's
options have narrowed. She has been struggling just to keep her
movement alive and to hold the attention of foreign governments
that is perhaps her political lifeline.
</P>
<P>
   The Burmese military junta is equally stubborn.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when the people rose up against three decades of
military repression, the army crushed huge demonstrations by force,
taking hundreds of lives.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, with Aung San Suu Kyi under house arrest, her party won
an overwhelming victory in a surprisingly free parliamentary
election. The military reacted by annulling the results and
tightening its grip on power.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995 she was freed from formal house arrest but found herself
surrounded by security officers and restricted in her movements and
political activities.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband, a British scholar, was dying of cancer two
years ago, the government denied him permission to visit her,
suggesting that it would be more appropriate for her to visit him
abroad. She refused, convinced that the government would prevent
her from returning, and he died without seeing her.
</P>
<P>
   Her current foray out of the capital, Yangon _ the former
Rangoon _ demonstrates the weakness of her position as well as its
strength. It shows how few options she has to challenge Myanmar's
leaders but also how little she needs to do to draw international
attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``She needs to keep people, not only in Burma but the rest of
the world, aware of the continuing repression and deprivation of
rights in Burma,'' said Sunai Phasuk, a political scientist at
Chulalongkorn University in Bangkok. Her gesture drew immediate
support from the United States and Britain, as well as the
London-based rights organization Amnesty International.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States condemns this abridgment of Aung San Suu
Kyi's right to freedom of movement and her right to visit whomever
she chooses,'' said Philip Reeker, a State Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond statements of support, there is little that foreign
governments can do to affect the political situation in Myanmar.
The United States has banned new investment there and barred visits
from its leaders. The European Union has shunned Myanmar at
international meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But Myanmar's leaders have only hunkered down, apparently
comfortable with an international isolation that they first imposed
on themselves in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   In its public statements about the current confrontation, in the
town of Dalla just across the river to the south of Yangon, the
government has taken a lighthearted tone verging on ridicule.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that ``security conditions'' do not permit her to
travel farther, it portrays her _ and 14 supporters traveling with
her in two vehicles _ as enjoying a pleasant rural interlude.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daw Suu Kyi and her travel companions are still continuing
taking a rest at Sarpachaun Ward of Dalla Town, a small but
charming and scenic town which is a 10-minute boat ride from
Yangon,'' read a statement issued on Monday. ``While Daw Suu Kyi
visits some homes in Sarpachaun Ward, her travel companions and
attendants enjoy visiting downtown Dalla as well as taking daily
dips in Sarpachaun stream.''
</P>
<P>
   It said that a doctor and six medical assistants were standing
by. And it suggested that she ``return home and continue her
political activities in a more secure environment.''
</P>
<P>
   The government-controlled press joined the fray Tuesday, though
it did not mention Aung San Suu Kyi's attempted car trip, deriding
her as a ``democracy princess'' and asserting, ``She'll go down the
drain eventually.''
</P>
<P>
   The government also took the opportunity to argue against
economic sanctions, which she and her party support, saying the
sanctions had cost jobs in manufacturing and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the party claims to be promoting human rights,'' an
official statement said, ``in reality the very rights of the people
of Myanmar to enjoy a better and fuller life have been undeniably
violated and abused by the very same people calling for democracy
and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Photographs released by the government show two vehicles parked
amid shrubbery, joined by a makeshift tent and surrounded by
pink-shirted supporters, most of them members of the youth wing of
her party.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said the cars were parked on a dirt trail about 180
yards off the main road, blocked from going farther by two trucks.
They told Agence France-Presse that the air had been let out of her
tires and that party members were taking turns standing by her car
with a large umbrella to shield Aung San Suu Kyi from the hot sun.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the travelers ``a determined group,'' party members
reached by telephone in Yangon said they were sending extra food,
medicine and mosquito repellent in preparation for a long stay.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
