<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5684 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-1050(     08-29 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSILE-DEFENSE-1050(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT IN WASHINGTON DEEPENS OVER MISSILE PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska)   By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Pentagon and the State Department are sharply
divided over how far work on a limited national missile defense
system could proceed before the United States would be required to
give Russia formal notice that it was violating a crucial arms
control treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the Pentagon and State Department said that
disagreement within the administration was a primary reason for
Defense Secretary William Cohen's delay in making a recommendation
to President Clinton this month on proceeding with the project.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has focused on the point at which construction of the
missile system, which involves elaborate radar installations, would
violate the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty of 1972, which lies at
the heart of the arms controls built up over the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians have steadfastly refused any changes in the treaty
to permit elaborate new radar installations, fearing that they
would lead to a larger system that would undermine Russia's nuclear
force.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from the agencies said Cohen was wrong when he told
the Senate Armed Services Committee last month that administration
lawyers had reached a consensus. Cohen said then that there was
agreement that building a crucial radar station in Alaska could
continue until 2002 before the United States would violate the
treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That represents just one of three interpretations drafted by
administration lawyers, the officials said. But senior
policy-makers at the State Department and the National Security
Council are strongly opposed, the officials added. The opponents
contend that this interpretation would be overly aggressive and
unilateral, and would surely anger the Russians and European
allies.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Pentagon, Rear Adm. Craig R. Quigley, said
Cohen and his aides declined to discuss his Senate testimony. Cohen
is the administration's leading advocate of building missile
defenses.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to President Clinton declined to discuss the internal
debate but confirmed that officials were considering several
options and that Cohen's statement last month did not reflect a
consensus view. ``It is true that there are a number of options
available to the president,'' said P.J. Crowley, a National
Security Council spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The question of when the United States would violate the treaty
is a pivotal one that Clinton has to answer before approving even
limited steps to begin building a radar station on Shemya Island at
the western edge of the Aleutians. The Russians would surely object
to the United States and its allies. American officials'
interpretations vary based on when in the construction process the
treaty violation would occur.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is now widely expected to make a recommendation to Clinton
in a few weeks on how to proceed. But the officials said the legal
questions could delay a decision to move ahead further.
</P>
<P>
   The division is so sharp that Clinton may be forced to choose
among conflicting advice, if he decides to move ahead at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really squishy business,'' a senior military officer
said. ``Smart lawyers can disagree.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the Pentagon timetable, the first contracts for the Alaska
radar work, as well as a site for the missile interceptors, would
have to be awarded this year so that work could begin next spring
and a working system could be in place within the administration's
goal of 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials have warned that the United States could
face a threat from some countries, including North Korea, by then.
There is universal agreement that building the radar would amount
to a violation of the treaty. The administration had hoped to
negotiate amendments with the Russians that would permit the
limited system now being developed, but Moscow has refused.
</P>
<P>
   Officials previously said that Clinton would decide this summer
whether to deploy a system. But with the Russians objecting and
even the allies expressing concern, the officials have since
signaled that Clinton simply plans to decide whether to move ahead
with an initial development. He would leave a final decision to
deploy _ and break the treaty _ to the next administration.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the legal interpretations have become so important,
because each interpretation sets a different moment when Clinton
must, as the treaty requires, give the Russians six months' notice
of American intent to withdraw from its anti-missile restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House's request, lawyers from the State Department
and the Pentagon have drafted the three legal interpretations of
the treaty that, in their view, would allow some work to begin
without breaking the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   In his appearance before the Senate's Armed Services Committee
on July 25 and again at a news conference the next day, Cohen said
that administration lawyers had reached a consensus that the United
States would not violate the treaty until workers laid down rails
that would support the radar itself at the station at Shemya. That
is not scheduled to happen until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen emphasized that Clinton had not yet made a decision, but
at the news conference he added, ``There is a consensus that until
such time as the construction is under way that would lay the rail,
so to speak, for the actual radar being deployed there, that would
not constitute a breach.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense and administration officials said that Cohen, the only
Republican in Clinton's Cabinet was expressing his support for the
most liberal interpretation of the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   That view, the officials said, is being challenged by senior
aides to Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, including the
undersecretary of state for arms control, John D. Holum, who is the
chief arms control negotiator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have an aggressive interpretation of the treaty to
argue that the rails are the point at which you would be in
violation,'' a senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   All the interpretations drafted by the lawyers would overturn a
legal understanding dating from the Reagan administration that even
the most minimal steps to construct parts of a missile defense _
including pouring concrete _ would breach the treaty. For years
during the 1980s, Reagan aides insisted that a half-built radar
station near Krasnoyarsk in Siberia violated the treaty and
eventually forced the Russians to halt the work.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The second interpretation holds that the United States would be
in violation at the point workers begin pouring concrete, which is
scheduled to begin next May. Given the fact the treaty requires
either the United States or the Russians to give six months' notice
of an intent to break out, Clinton would have to then notify the
Russians by December, just as his second term ends.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have said that Clinton is loath to be the president
who brings an end to the ABM treaty, which has been strongly
supported by arms control advocates since it was negotiated in the
Nixon administration.
</P>
<P>
   The third interpretation argues that a violation would not occur
until the concrete foundation for the radar site is complete. That
is expected later next year or even the year after, depending on
weather conditions and other potential delays. That would leave the
decision on breaking the treaty to the next president.
</P>
<P>
   The senior administration official said that the question was
proving especially difficult since the treaty does not specify what
exactly would amount to a violation. ``There is some room for legal
interpretation,'' the official said, ``but I think it's fair to say
that not all of the options are equally defensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the administration's proposal said moving ahead
with a missile defense _ while arguing that the first steps toward
it would not constitute a violation _ would amount to a diplomatic
disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Daryl G. Kimball, executive director of the Coalition to Reduce
Nuclear Dangers, an advocacy group here, said that unlike the
Russian radar at Krasnoyarsk, there would be no question that the
site at Shemya was intended to be part of a system that would
ultimately violate the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The administration has made it abundantly clear what the
purpose of this would be,'' Kimball said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's own schedule has increasingly been called into
question because of test failures and delays in building a new
booster rocket for the missile interceptors. ``If the technology
isn't there, you don't have much of a choice,'' one official said.
``If you can foresee that the system won't be ready until 2006 or
2007, why would you push it now?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
