<HEADER>
A5691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-29 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA: BRINGING UP SUB'S VICTIMS
</P>
<P>
   Russian and Norwegian divers will begin next month to remove the
bodies of the 118 sailors who died in the sinking of the nuclear
submarine Kursk. Deputy Prime Minister Ilya Klebanov said that the
divers would cut six holes in the sub and that Russian divers would
enter to retrieve the bodies. The sub will be raised next year, he
said. Klebanov repeated that Russia believes that a collision with
a foreign vessel caused the sinking, rejecting American reports
that a torpedo exploded inside the sub.
</P>
<P>
   SPAIN: BASQUE COUNCILOR SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen believed to belong to the armed Basque separatist
organization ETA shot dead a young town councilor of the ruling
Popular Party as he arrived to open his candy store. Manuel
Indiano, 29, was shot at least 10 times in the stomach and chest in
the attack in the Basque town of Zamarraga. His was the 12th
killing linked to ETA since it ended a unilateral truce last
December, and the seventh since mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: CATHOLICS' NAZI-ERA FUND
</P>
<P>
   The Roman Catholic Church says it will set up its own $2.3
million fund to compensate Nazi-era forced laborers. Bishop Karl
Lehmann said people forced to work for Catholic institutions had
been excluded from a $4.7 billion fund set up by the German state
and industry. The decision was criticized by Otto Lambsdorff, the
government's fund negotiator, and Michael Witti, a lawyer for
Jewish victims. The Protestant church paid $4.7 million into the
main fund.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY: POPE CONDEMNS CLONING
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II condemned as morally unacceptable attempts at
human cloning to obtain organs for transplant involving the
manipulation and destruction of human embryos, and called on
scientists to look for alternative methods that respect the dignity
of human beings. The pope left his summer retreat at Castel
Gandolfo outside Rome to tell 5,000 transplant specialists that
``science itself points to other forms of therapeutic
intervention.''
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA: EX-PRESIDENT MISSING
</P>
<P>
   The family of Ivan Stambolic, a former Serbian president and
opponent of President Slobodan Milosevic, was reported missing five
days ago, and his family said it was still awaiting word of his
whereabouts. His lawyer, Nikola Barovic, said, ``The fact that
state-controlled media have not reported a word about the
disappearance of a former Serbian president proves to me that a
political decision had been made for him to be arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: GIRL, 11, SHOT
</P>
<P>
   An 11-year-old girl was in stable condition after being shot
during an attack on her house in County Londonderry in the latest
incident linked to the violent feud between Protestant guerrilla
groups. Meanwhile, a Protestant leader called for calm. ``The main
groups should call a cease-fire or a cessation in hostilities even
for a short time to allow talks at various levels to take place,''
said John White, chairman of the Ulster Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   PERU: INVESTIGATING GUN CHARGES
</P>
<P>
   President Alberto Fujimori, under fire for the military's
suspected role in smuggling 10,000 Kalashnikov rifles from Jordan
to Marxist guerrillas in Colombia, says even top army officers will
be investigated. ``Nobody is safe here, not even brigade generals
nor division generals,'' he told Colombian television. Jordan said
the guns were legally sold to Peru's army in 1998, but Peruvian
officials insisted they never bought them from Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: KIDNAPPING COMPLICATION
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court complicated efforts to win the release of the
kidnapped matinee idol Rajkumar by blocking a plan to free dozens
of men said to be members of the gang run by his abductor, the
South Indian outlaw Veerappan. The outlaw had demanded the release
of his compatriots and the state of Karnataka had obliged by
dropping criminal charges against them.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: THOUSANDS FLEE FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people have been evacuated from flooded
villages in Andhra Pradesh, a southern state, and the death toll
has risen past 140 as heavy rains continue to raise river levels
dangerously high, producing the worst flooding in decades.
Forecasters say another storm system has formed over the Bay of
Bengal.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   IRAN: STUDENTS CONDEMN TROOPS
</P>
<P>
   Iran's leading pro-reform student group accused troops under the
control of the supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei of attacking
them during riots in the town of Khoramabad that left one person
dead and dozens injured. A spokesman for the student Office to
Consolidate Unity called on Khamenei to clarify his position on the
forces fighting ``under his banner'' during the disturbances. He
said 60 students were hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: BLAST NEAR U.S. OFFICE
</P>
<P>
   A car bomb injured six people near the U.S. Consulate in Cape
Town. For more than two years, Cape Town has been plagued by
small-scale bomb attacks, some of which the police have linked to a
radical vigilante group operating in and around the city.
Investigators are not sure if the consulate was the target of the
bomb, which exploded about 200 yards away from the building, a
police spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA: FBI JOINS PRIEST INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   The United States has taken the unusual step of sending three
FBI agents to help with the investigation into the death of the
Rev. John Kaiser, 67, an outspoken American priest, a U.S. official
said. The three arrived after a request from the Kenyan attorney
general, an embassy spokesman said. Kaiser, who had worked in Kenya
for 36 years, was found shot dead outside Nairobi.
</P>
</TEXT>
