<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DISBAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS DISBARMENT IS TOO HARSH A PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Even if President Clinton lied under oath to a
federal judge about his relationship with a White House intern,
disbarment would be too strong a penalty, the president's lawyers
said in court papers Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their statement, filed with the Pulaski County Superior Court in
Arkansas, was in response to a recommendation by a state
disciplinary committee that he be stripped of his law license
because of ``serious misconduct.'' The committee has said he gave
false testimony in 1998 about his relationship with the intern,
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   In their statement, Clinton's lawyers noted that the president
still disputed that his testimony was technically false. But even
if the allegation were correct, the lawyers said, ``a sanction of
disbarment would be excessively harsh, impermissibly punitive and
unprecedented in the circumstances of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers, David Kendall and Nicole Seligman of
Washington, said in their filing that Clinton's alleged offense was
not connected to the practice of law nor was he convicted of _ or
even charged with _ a felony. In Arkansas, they said, disbarment
has never been imposed in a case that did not involve a felony
conviction or a matter involving the practice of law.
</P>
<P>
   A trial on the disbarment issue could occur sometime this fall.
In any event, Judge Leon Johnson, who is presiding over the case,
has indicated that he expects to conclude the proceedings before
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The disciplinary case involves Clinton's statements under oath
on Jan. 17, 1998, when he gave a deposition in the sexual
misconduct lawsuit brought against him by Paula Jones.
</P>
<P>
   In the presence of Judge Susan Webber Wright, a federal trial
judge who was presiding over the civil lawsuit, Clinton said he had
never engaged in a sexual relationship with Lewinsky and he denied
that he had ever been alone with her but for a fleeting moment.
</P>
<P>
   After Clinton acknowledged in August 1998 that he had had an
improper physical relationship with Lewinsky, Wright ruled that his
behavior in the deposition constituted contempt of court.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president,'' she said, ``deliberately violated this
court's discovery orders, thereby undermining the integrity of the
judicial system.'' She said that ``sanctions must be imposed to
redress the president's misconduct and to deter others who might
consider emulating the president's misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright fined Clinton $1,202 to cover her costs in traveling to
Washington to attend the deposition and ordered him to pay some
$90,000 in fees to Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has argued that his deposition testimony, in which he
denied having sexual relations with Lewinsky, was accurate because
the oral sex in which they engaged in did not fit the definition of
sexual relations that had been approved by Wright.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2125EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
