<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5695 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     08-29 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS SAVOR   NEW VIEW   FROM TOP 
</HEADLINE>
   By   GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What a lovely summer this has been in New York. The
only thing more fun than having one winning baseball team is having
two, and New York is currently blessed with that.
</P>
<P>
   There has been 12 o'clock lightning in two boroughs, and there
has been midnight suspense from Western time zones when it was
impossible to turn off the television set and get some sleep, and
there was even Benny Agbayani's grand slam from Japan just as day
people were getting ready to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   Rock around the clock. What a season. How hard it is to take
even a day away from baseball to ponder the U.S. Open or to ponder
rumors of another year of professional football.
</P>
<P>
   How excruciating it is to anticipate the weeks of attention to
the bizarre charm of synchronized swimming and dressage at the
Summer Games in Sydney, while Derek Jeter and Mike Piazza are (as
Red Barber used to say) tearing up the pea patch.
</P>
<P>
   The summer became even more glorious Tuesday when the Mets woke
up in their collective beds in New York in a tie for the best
record in baseball, while the Yankees stirred in their respective
hotel rooms in Seattle still ensconced in first place in their
division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play this game for the fans,'' Mets Manager Bobby Valentine
said. ``It should never be lost in the shuffle. If you're a fan of
the Mets, you've waited weeks, months, years for this.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets tried to stay on top last night against the Houston
Astros in a fresh and autumnal Shea Stadium, with the Braves' home
game against the Reds flickering on the scoreboard behind right
field.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets are clearly the novelty act in this city of good
feeling, not having been in first place this late in a season since
1990. Bear in mind that last October's heroics came only after a
season of bickering and brinkmanship, skittering slumps and
flailing egos. Now the Mets have the best record in baseball since
the All-Star Game break, and there is serenity everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I injured or being rested?'' Robin (.234) Ventura asked
Valentine when he was informed he was not in the starting lineup
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The two laughed, a far cry from recent years when Valentine had
to deal with assorted mutineers and grumps, and was occasionally
tetchy himself.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine is so calm that he almost, that is, almost seemed to
enjoy being in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're playing, the daily thing is important,'' Valentine
said. ``You just play 'em. I understand totally that the only
standings that count are at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine, however, did note, ``We were five or six games behind
only two weeks ago.''
</P>
<P>
   How true. Although separated by hundreds of miles Tuesday night,
the Mets had caught up with the Braves. It was a minor version of
the way the 1951 New York Giants caught up to the Brooklyn Dodgers,
after a 13{-game deficit, and leaned on the batting cage in
September and leered at the Dodgers as if to say, ``We didn't
die.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had the feeling that the Braves knew that for at least
one night the two teams had, finally, been equal in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were always the team that was behind the Braves,'' Agbayani
said. ``They'll be aware of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani thought that last year's nervous-making wild-card
heroics had led to a calmer Mets team this time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed last year, it was so exciting,'' said Agbayani, a
rookie back then. ``We kept wondering: `Are we going? Aren't we
going?' We had to wait out the wild card. After last season, you
feel you can do it all, not just the wild card. As a team, we've
been through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Agbayani knows the drill now. Last days of August, home game,
the Open across the way, tickets to be had. He, Darryl Hamilton,
Ventura, Todd Zeile and Edgardo Alfonzo all went over to catch a
few matches at midday Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely amazing how they return first serve,'' said
Agbayani, talking about the men who regularly return serves of 125
miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't touch those serves. Maybe the second serve, even
with the spin they put on it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets wandered back across the boardwalk to prepare for the
Astros. They had 31 games left in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   It is too soon to prattle of a Subway Series, but this much is
true: Only the most sour Met and Yankee fans can work up a hatred
for the other side in a season that has been so sweet, so far.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
