<DOCNO> NYT20000829.0370 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5700 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a BC-BEATING-DEATH-SPI &LR;      08-29 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATING-DEATH-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUTHS ARRESTED FOR ``KILLING FOR THE THRILL'' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JACK HOPKINS and RUTH TEICHROEB  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TACOMA, Wash. _ Eight youths _ including boys only 11, 12 and 13
years old _ have been arrested for a beating death and series of
vicious attacks that police say were committed for the ``thrill''
of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, that's what they were doing _ killing for the
thrill,'' said police spokesman Jim Mattheis.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest suspect would be entering sixth grade next week and
is believed to be the youngest person ever facing a murder charge
in Pierce County. Several suspects burst into tears when police
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Experts point to a kind of ``pack'' behavior among youths inured
to an escalating level of violence by exposure to extremely violent
video games, movies and other media.
</P>
<P>
   Running with a gang can be ``infectious,'' said Karil Klingbeil,
an associate professor of social work at the University of
Washington and social work director at Harborview Medical Center in
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much like a virus,'' she said. ``A kid alone walking
down a street wouldn't even think of attacking someone. But the
group bravado gives him a tag-along mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, all males who range in age up to 19 years old, are
expected to be charged with first-degree murder, possibly as early
as Wednesday. All were booked into juvenile detention or jail.
</P>
<P>
   All the suspects are believed to have participated in the Aug.
19 assault of Erik Toews, who died Friday from multiple injuries
suffered when he was beaten, kicked and clubbed with sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Toews' brother said the young age of the accused makes
his death tougher to comprehend and resolve.
</P>
<P>
   Families of murder victims naturally want revenge and it makes
it easier when the person charged is ``the most evil person out
there,'' Brian Toews said. ``Then you can just feel good about
locking them up and throwing away the key.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when you are talking about kids, you wonder about the
circumstances of their guilt,'' he said. ``And that is stealing
away part of our grief. It makes it even more unresolvable for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Erik Toews, who was working two jobs to help support his mother
and one of his brothers, was attacked in the 1300 block of North
Fourth Street, near the family's home in the city's historic
Stadium District.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old man was walking home from work at a neighborhood
coffee shop when he was assaulted shortly after 10 p.m. in what
police say was an unprovoked attack.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the youths arrested Monday night and Tuesday have
been linked to nine assaults that have occurred near Wright Park
since July 26. And they suspect the youths committed a number of
other assaults in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there are other cases out there that haven't been
reported ... possibly because the people were assaulted by little
kids,'' Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   The youths suspected of taking part in the assaults all live in
the same neighborhood, near Bryant Elementary School and only
blocks away from the scene of some of the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The youths knew one of the men they attacked and that victim was
able to assist the police investigation, Mattheis disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Police also gained valuable information while working undercover
in the Wright Park area last Wednesday night, he said. Police
encountered and talked to some of the eight suspects at that time.
</P>
<P>
   None of the suspects was surprised to see the police show up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew we were coming,'' Mathheis said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects are not part of any organized gang. They are just
neighborhood friends, Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids just got together and decided they were going to go
out and beat somebody up,'' he said. ``That was their whole
intent.''
</P>
<P>
   In such circumstances, younger children follow the orders of
older teens to win acceptance, said Sgt. Dianne Newsom of Seattle
Police Department's gang unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to belong,'' she said. ``And they don't want to go
against the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   Klingbeil, the Harborview social work director, predicted that
as more details come out, the youths will share some common
elements in their backgrounds, from low self-esteem and alienation
to truancy and family violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect these kids are heavily involved in instances of
family violence _ child abuse, spousal abuse and that sort of
thing,'' Klingbeil said.
</P>
<P>
   But she also said there will likely be a few suspects who until
now had decent grades and had never been in trouble until lured
into criminal activity by their peers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the desire for a sense of belonging that takes you into a
gang,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The crimes obviously raise the question of parental supervision,
said Newsom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it sad? It makes you wonder what 11-year-olds were doing
out at midnight,'' Newsom said. ``Society needs to do something
about the parents who allow that.''
</P>
<P>
   While Klingbeil said some of the parents had probably given up
on their children, others may be shocked by how far astray their
offspring have gone.
</P>
<P>
   A worrisome trend is that more younger children are committing
violent crimes, she said. And they have a limited ability to
understand consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are very impulse-ridden kids,'' Klingbeil said. ``They
don't start out the day thinking they are going to murder that
night _ let alone get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   Many children are exposed from infancy on to extreme violence in
movies, videos and on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a normalizing effect,'' Klingbeil said. ``And there are
usually more pleasant endings on television than in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Toews said the family is devastated by the loss.
</P>
<P>
   `If he had died from an accident or an illness, we could have
eventually made some sense out of it. But the fact that he was
senselessly beaten to death makes it harder,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tacoma police Chief James Hairston agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the senseless nature of this that makes it so
disturbing,'' Hairston said.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that most of the youths reported committing the
assaults were black and Hispanic and all but one of the victims was
white had led to public speculation that the attacks were racially
motivated.
</P>
<P>
   But police said that wasn't the case and noted two of the youths
arrested are white and one of the victims was black.
</P>
<P>
   Police have come under fire for not warning residents of the
attacks until after Toews died. Critics said his life might have
been spared if police had warned of the danger. Seven of the
attacks occurred before Toews was assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   But Hairston and Mattheis continued to insist that the
department acted as quickly as it could. They said detectives
weren't able to detect a pattern in the assaults until days after
Toews was attacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we didn't want to raise the level of fear in the
community,'' Hairston said.
</P>
<P>
   Police will hold community meetings in the next few days to
discuss their handling of the case and assure the public that the
attacks were not racially motivated, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   Police withheld the names of those arrested and released little
information about them. They said some had prior juvenile records.
But others, including the 11-year-old boy, have not been in trouble
before, Mattheis said.
</P>
<P>
   Toews' friends and co-workers, meanwhile, were hoping some good
would result from his death.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a greater awareness and sense of community now,''
said Cole Peregrine, Toews' supervisor at The Usual Coffee and News
in Tacoma. ``We are not just an island and need to support each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the neighborhoods where the attacks occurred were
relieved to learn of the arrests.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be nice to be able to walk on the streets again and
not have to worry about whether someone is sneaking up behind
you,'' said Ronald Taylor, who lives near Wright Park. ``I'm glad
they made some arrests.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everybody was completely happy. Some worried about the
next outbreak of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on what happens next,'' said Deb Tippen, who
lives just a few blocks from where Toews was killed. ``We're safer,
but for how long?'' she asked. ``The arrests are not a permanent
fix.''
</P>
</TEXT>
