<SLUG> BC-F16-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS SAY AIR FORCE PILOT WAS `BUZZING' IN-LAWS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CHRIS VAUGHN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ An Air Force Reserve pilot killed Monday
evening was ``buzzing'' his in-law's farmhouse when he apparently
lost control of his F-16 and crashed into their field, authorities
and witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Stephen W. Simons' actions in the minutes leading up to the
fatal accident _ witnessed by his in-laws and a number of family
friends outside the farming community of Tulia in the Texas
Panhandle _ is likely to be the focus of the Air Force's
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, as stunned colleagues from the Fort Worth-based
301st Fighter Wing mourned privately, Air Force safety
investigators arrived to interview witnesses and examine the
wreckage of the single-seat, single-engine $20 million jet fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Simons, 41, of Fort Worth, an experienced fighter pilot of
almost 20 years, was headed east to Naval Air Station Fort Worth
from Utah on Monday evening when he flew low over his in-laws'
house, said Trooper Wayne Beighle of the Department of Public
Safety in Amarillo.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was saying `hi' and something went wrong,'' Beighle said.
``We had no indications the plane was trailing smoke or there were
any problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One witness said he had done aerobatic maneuvers before the
crash. This wasn't the first pass he had made.''
</P>
<P>
   Billie Byrd, a neighbor and long-time friend of Simons' in-laws,
witnessed the accident with her husband, who had come out of their
farm implement business to see Simons pass by about 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came by twice,'' she said. ``We don't know what happened.
He lost altitude and clipped a little hog shed. It's just terrible.
It's something you don't want to see.''
</P>
<P>
   The Byrds counted Simons as a friend. He visited this summer
when his family was in town, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said Monday's flyover of his in-laws wasn't the first one.
``He had done it before,'' she said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Roberta Smith, a spokeswoman for the 10th Air Force, said
there would be no comment on the reports of Simons' actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those rumors and hearsay and eyewitness reports are all things
the accident investigation board looks at,'' Smith said. ``They'll
be completely thorough in finding out what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The Simons family said they did not want to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Simons' death shook the close-knit brotherhood of the 457th
Fighter Squadron, which he belonged to since the early 1990s. The
last time a squadron member was killed was 1987, when an F-4
crashed into Lake Worth near the naval air base, killing the pilot
and weapons officer.
</P>
<P>
   The squadron ceased flying operations Tuesday and isn't likely
to resume them for another day or two to give pilots a break,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still in shock,'' said Maj. Jeff Smiley, the squadron's
operations officer. ``We're just numb and we're trying to collect
ourselves. We need to find out what happened and we need to take
care of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   Smiley described Simons, the father of two girls, as a
``Renaissance man,'' who spoke German and Spanish and was a
``first-rate'' pilot who had more than 2,000 hours in the F-16,
F-15 and F-4 fighters.
</P>
<P>
   He had combat sorties over Bosnia-Herzegovina and Iraq,
including a stint this summer enforcing the so-called no-fly zone
over Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Simons, a graduate of the U.S. Air Force Academy, had also been
a first officer for Delta Air Lines since 1988, most of that time
based out of Dallas/Fort Worth Airport. This summer, he began
flying out of John F. Kennedy Airport in New York on the Boeing
767, an airline spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was an awesome dad and husband,'' Smiley said. ``I had a
lot of envy for him because of the way he handled his personal
life. His family came first.''
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force will conduct two separate, concurrent
investigations _ one that is released only to Air Force personnel
and one that is public. The Secretary of the Air Force will also
receive a briefing on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   The safety investigation, which is not public, is usually
completed within a month and is used internally to try to prevent
future accidents, said Col. Dave Williamson, chief of the safety
issues division at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff researcher Shannon Canard contributed to this report.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
