<SLUG> BC-CNN-CHANGES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. NEWS CHIEF AT CNN EXPECTED TO QUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JIM RUTENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rick Kaplan, who has been the president of CNN's U.S.
news-gathering operation since 1997, is expected to announce
Wednesday that he is leaving the network, executives close to the
situation said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   CNN executives are also planning to announce other major changes
in the network's executive structure.
</P>
<P>
   The resignation comes at a particularly difficult time for CNN,
a unit of Time Warner Inc., leaving its leadership unclear in the
heart of a presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   CNN's ratings have been sliding precipitously recently and its
parent company is about to complete its merger with America Online.
In some respects, the timing could not be worse, losing the chief
of its domestic news unit while it is in the midst of covering the
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   News of Kaplan's departure began circulating through CNN late
Tuesday afternoon and took many on his staff by surprise. There
were conflicting reports as to whether he was leaving on his own
accord or if he was asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, his tenure at the network has been rocky.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan joined CNN after a 17-year career as a producer at ABC
News, where he won 34 Emmy Awards serving as executive producer of
both of that network's leading news programs ``Nightline'' and
``World News Tonight.'' He also became the first executive producer
of the ABC news magazine program ``Prime Time Live.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his hiring, CNN executives said they expected him
to lead the network to improved ratings. But his time at CNN has
been marked by a series of confrontations over news and personnel
decisions. The main show that Kaplan created, ``CNN Newsstand,''
was embroiled in an embarrassing fiasco in 1998 when its very first
program, called ``Tailwind,'' a report charging that U.S. forces
used nerve gas in Vietnam, was found to be so full of errors that
it had to be retracted, complete with an on-the-air apology. Two
producers were fired and one executive resigned.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's job was considered in jeopardy at the time but he was
absolved of the final responsibility for the broadcast by the CNN
President Tom Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, the highly popular Lou Dobbs, the anchor of the
network's most profitable program, `'Moneyline'' quit after
fighting with Kaplan over news coverage that interrupted Dobbs'
programs. ``Moneyline'' has since dropped sharply in both ratings
and profits, and Dobbs has been publicly wooed by NBC.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last year, CNN's founder, Ted Turner, expressed
interest in bringing Dobbs back to CNN, a move that Kaplan strongly
opposed. Dobbs did not return.
</P>
<P>
   Many at CNN had expected that Kaplan would leave the network
after this year's election campaign was over.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation Tuesday night that his departure might
have had something to do with the network's ratings during the
Republican National Convention, which were lower than they were
four years ago. However, its ratings did recover for the Democratic
convention.
</P>
<P>
   There was no word Tuesday night on who will replace Kaplan. But
several people close to the situation said there would be various
other changes in store for the CNN executive structure.
</P>
<P>
   Eason Jordan, who is in charge of International news for the
network, was expected to be promoted to an editorial position in
which he would oversee all the CNN news operations. Jim Walton, in
charge of CNN's sports division, was also expected to take a larger
role with the network.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2141EDT &QL; 
