<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTERS-BERINGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER'S DEAL TO BUY BERINGER PUTS OTHER WINERIES IN PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Foster's Brewing Group's $1.14 billion
acquisition of Beringer Wine Estates Holdings is likely to prompt a
new wave of consolidation among California's premium wineries,
analysts and industry executives said on Tuesday. The deal, they
said, effectively puts the ownership of significant independent
winemakers in play.
</P>
<P>
   News of the offer for Beringer by Foster, the Australian beer
and wine company, came a day after another California wine
producer, R &UR; . &LR; H. Phillips, said it would be purchased by Vincor
International of Canada for $92 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other independent winemakers that could become takeover targets
include Kendall-Jackson, Robert Mondavi and Sutter Home.
Kendall-Jackson, considered a likely candidate for an initial
public offering, had been in talks with Beringer about a possible
merger, but the talks broke off last week, an executive close to
the winery said, because of conditions raised by Jess Jackson,
Kendall-Jackson's founder.
</P>
<P>
   In acquiring Beringer, Foster is buying the oldest operating
winery in the Napa Valley of California, with 10,200 acres of
vineyards. Beringer _ which over the years has grown well beyond
its onetime boutique-winery status _ had sales of $700 million in
the fiscal year that ended in June. In addition to Beringer labels,
its brands include Chateau St. Jean, Souverain and Napa Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   Foster already owns several leading Australian winemakers, and
in February, it bought Windsor Vineyards in the Sonoma Valley of
California, the No. 2 direct seller of wine in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the acquisition of Beringer, Jean-Michelle Valette, a
wine industry consultant and former president of Franciscan
Vineyards, said, ``While there were half a dozen premium wine
companies that had all attained the same scale over time, all of a
sudden you now have a clearly dominant player, with global reach
and distribution in a number of significant markets. I think it's
going to cause a big scramble among the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Beringer rose $10.25 on Tuesday, to $55.31 on the
Nasdaq Stock Exchange; Robert Mondavi added $1.13, to $40 on the
Nasdaq. Class A shares of Canandaigua Brands, of Fairport, N.Y.,
were up $2.19, to $53.81 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
