<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DLJ-MERGER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUYOUT OF DLJ CATAPULTS CREDIT SUISSE INTO GOLDMAN SACHS' LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also DLJ-CREDIT-SUISSE) 
 By ANDREW ROSS SORKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When investment bankers talk about the competition,
they tend to base much of their comparisons on one slice of the
business: the high-flying, much publicized world of mergers and
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Credit Suisse's acquisition of Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP;
Jenrette illustrates the importance placed on the multibillion
industry of advising companies on whom they should take over or
sell to next.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Credit Suisse and Donaldson is expected to
catapult the combined company into a league with Goldman, Sachs &AMP;
Co. and Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, the top two firms and possibly
edging out Merrill Lynch for No. 3 in completed deals so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, the acquisition bolsters Credit Suisse's mergers
and acquisitions practice in key areas like the ultracompetitive
and fast-growing telecommunications industry. Donaldson has advised
on some of the largest telecommunications deals recently, working
on Deutsche Telekom's acquisition of VoiceStream Wireless for about
$50 billion and France Telecom's purchase of Orange for $37.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   According to Thomson Financial Securities Data, Credit Suisse
First Boston, the investment banking unit of Credit Suisse, ranked
No. 4 in completed merger and acquisition deals worldwide for the
first half of the year, completing 173 deals, which represents 21.2
percent of the advisory market.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson ranked No. 14, with 157 deals, representing 6.5
percent of the advisory market.
</P>
<P>
   Combining Donaldson's telecommunications advisory team with
Credit Suisse First Boston's telecommunications and well-respected
technology group should help the new firm raise even more business
as both industries continue to converge, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Credit Suisse First Boston lured Frank Quattrone
away from Deutsche Bank to build its technology team, making it one
of the best in country. Credit Suisse First Boston's technology
team has advised on deals like Terra Network's acquisition of Lycos
for $12.5 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
