<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5709 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBN-DILLON0830-COX     08-29 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DILLON0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bengals' Dillon returns to practice following arrest
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Bengals Pro Bowl tailback Corey Dillon returned to
practice on Tuesday, but gave few details about an alleged
altercation with his wife that led to his arrest in a Seattle
suburb on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking from a hallway outside the Bengals locker room at Paul
Brown Stadium, Dillon refused to discuss what happened but wouldn't
deny that he struck his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tragedy that this happened,'' he said. ``I never
intended to be in this situation and bring this kind of cloud over
the team. I never intended for this to happen. It's bad. It's real
bad. Hopefully, in due time, it'll be cleared up and I can move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the NFL's Personal Conduct Policy, arrested players
are ``required to undergo an immediate, mandatory clinical
evaluation and, if directed, appropriate counseling'' that is
supervised by the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Players convicted of a crime are subject to disciplinary action
by NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue that could include a fine or
suspension without pay. NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said the league
doesn't comment on cases unless a fine or suspension is announced.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, who has a hearing scheduled Sept. 27, met with Bengals
president Mike Brown, head coach Bruce Coslet and running backs
coach Jim Anderson on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted to talk to (us),'' Brown said. ``We had a meeting
and he explained what happened. I don't think it's understood
accurately publicly, but he has to bear up under the criticism and
earn his way back into the good graces of the pubic.
</P>
<P>
   ``In time, this will be resolved and when everyone has a better
knowledge of it, I think it will fade away.''
</P>
<P>
   A member of the Bengals front office said Dillon's ordeal could
affect his performance on the field. Dillon held out 20 days of
training camp before signing a one-year $3 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be tough,'' said Eric Ball, a former Bengals
running back who works with players as the team's director of
player relations. ``He's had a long battle with his contract. He's
worked hard. He's done well. He's done what has been expected of
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this (arrest), it's going to be a setback. But I think
Corey is the type of person who can bounce back from it and move
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon, 24, was arrested in Federal Way, Wash., on Saturday by
police officers who responded to a domestic violence complaint.
</P>
<P>
   When officers arrived, they found Dillon's wife bleeding from
the mouth in front of a house. Dillon, who was in the driveway, was
booked into the King County jail for investigation of fourth-degree
assault and was released a few hours later.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the couple were in a car when the alleged fight took
place. Dillon's wife got out of the car and walked one block to the
address where police were summoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to explain my side of the story,'' Dillon said. ``But
right now, it really doesn't matter what I say. This is prejudged.
Right now, me talking about it is not going to help the situation.
As far as I'm concerned, this should have never happened. This was
accidental and in due time I hope people will see what really
happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been tough on both of us. It's pretty tough on me. I
really haven't had that much contact with her, and I've been
advised not to.''
</P>
<P>
   Dillon's arrest is the latest setbacks for the team.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the NFL's anti-crime policy, Bengals starting left
guard Matt O'Dwyer was suspended the first two games of the 2000
season for his involvement in a July 1999 bar brawl in Long Beach,
N.Y. His suspension was later reduced to one game. He'll miss the
Sept. 10 opener against the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Kick returner Tremain Mack and offensive tackle Jamain Stephens
were each suspended four games in 1999 for violating the NFL's
Substance Abuse Policy.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon had been arrested in March 1998. He was charged with
driving under the influence, negligent driving and driving with a
suspended license. Three months later, he pleaded guilty to lesser
charges of negligent driving and driving with a suspended license,
got fined $500 and received two years probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my teammate,'' quarterback Akili Smith said of Dillon.
``I'm going to trust whatever he says and then it's time to move
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Email: chickludwig(at)coxohio.com
</P>
