<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOSTERS-WINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIAN BREWER BUYS BERINGER WINE FOR $1.14 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   By HELEN PITT   
 WineToday.com   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MELBOURNE, Australia _ Australia's Foster's Brewing Group Ltd.
announced that it has acquired leading California premium wine
producer Beringer Wine Estates, a California premium wine producer,
for an estimated $1.14 billion or $2 billion in Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition, announced Tuesday in Melbourne, is part of a
merger agreement between the two companies. Following the merger,
Beringer would be wholly owned by Foster's, which also owns the
Australian wine company Mildara Blass. Foster's said in addition to
its tender offer, it will also assume $319 million in Beringer debt
($560 million in Australian dollars).
</P>
<P>
   Mildara Blass owns a number of Australian wineries, including
The Rothbury Estate, Wolf Blass, Jamiesons Run, Yarra Ridge and
Yellowglen.
</P>
<P>
   Beringer owns several top-selling U.S. premium wineries, among
them Chateau St Jean, Chateau Souverain, Meridian Vineyards, Stags'
Leap Winery and St Clement.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will be launched by way of a tender offer for
Beringer shares at $55.75 cash per share. Beringer stock closed
Monday on Wall Street for $45 1/16, up $1.50 from Friday's close of
trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Beringer senior management team, including chairman and
chief executive Walt Klenz, and Wine Master Ed Sbragia will
continue with the company following the merger.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's president and chief executive officer Ted Kunkel said
acquiring Beringer will create the world's first truly global
premium wine company.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining event for Foster's,'' Kunkel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This combination gives us a business partner with a similar
philosophy,'' said Klenz in a prepared statement. ``It will provide
us with access to new markets and new business opportunities which
assures Beringer Wine Estates' place as a key player in the world's
premium wine industry going forward.''
</P>
<P>
   In a webcast conference from Melbourne, Kunkel said the
acquisition would double the size of Foster's wine division and
create a ``new industry leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Potential exists for significant global cross-selling
opportunities between Beringer and Mildara Blass, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Exports currently account for 50 percent of Mildara Blass'
revenue, while Beringer's exports currently account for less than 4
percent of Beringer's, Kunkel said.
</P>
<P>
   Foster's bought Mildara Blass, one of Australia's top five wine
companies, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The deal shocked some wine industry observers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This floors me,'' said Jon Fredrikson of the San Francisco
wine research and consulting firm of Gomberg, Fredrikson and
Associates. ``At the price they are agreeing to pay, they are
showing how much faith and respect they have in the wine industry
in the U.S. The price they are paying is something you expect from
the high technology field and not from the wine industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Fredrikson said that Foster's has already proved its interest in
getting into the U.S. market when in February it bought Windsor
Vineyards, with annual sales of $34 million, as part of its online
wine retailing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``This gives them (Foster's Mildara Blass) some good positioning
for the premium brands; they should get more shelf space lineage in
U.S. stores even in the same price point,'' said Eileen Fredrikson
of Gomberg Fredrikson. She added that even though Beringer has a
strong export arm, Foster s will add some international strength
for its exports.
</P>
<P>
   One question on the minds of some analysts is what happened to
the rumors swirling about Beringer buying Kendall-Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still can't comment on those kinds of rumors,'' said Mora
Cronin, vice president of public relations for Beringer. ``We can
comment on this (the Foster's acquisition) and we're excited about
it and the new chapter in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall-Jackson had no comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Cronin said that no changes are expected as a result of the
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Essentially, it is business as usual. No layoffs are planned.
The organization will remain unchanged.''
</P>
<P>
   Beringer is the oldest continuously operating winery in the Napa
Valley. Texas Pacific Group, an investment firm, and its affiliates
own 52 percent of Beringer. Beringer owns or controls more than
10,000 acres of vineyards in California.
</P>
<P>
   Combined revenues for Beringer Wine Estates and Mildara Blass
Ltd. for the first half of 2000 were $886 million.
</P>
<P>
   (WineToday.com, a daily Internet wine publication, is published
by The New York Times Co.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
