<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TECHNOLOGY NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-COMMERCE AMAZON.COM TO OPEN FRENCH WEB SITE
</P>
<P>
   The online retailer Amazon.com will open a French-language Web
site, selling books, music and videos. The new site, Amazon.fr, is
the company's third venture outside the United States, after online
stores for Britain and Germany. A spokeswoman said the company
hoped to serve French speakers outside of France as well.
Amazon.com, based in Seattle, will operate the French site from
offices in Guyancourt and a distribution center in Orleans.
Separately, Amazon.com announced that it had expanded its marketing
alliance with America Online. No terms were disclosed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC SITE MAKING A SHIFT
</P>
<P>
   GetMusic, the online site owned by two big music labels,
Bertelsmann and Seagram's Universal Music group, is getting out of
selling music. GetMusic plans to announce Wednesday that it is
entering five European countries, but the music sales will be
handled by Bertelsmann's BOL unit. GetMusic is also looking for a
company to take over the music store it now runs on its original
site in the United States, perhaps CDNow, the ailing company that
Bertelsmann agreed to buy last month, said Andrew Nibley,
GetMusic's chief executive. Nibley asserted that GetMusic, with 1.2
million users, had strong prospects as a media company, earning
money from advertising. For now, it is the No. 1 site for Internet
users under the age of 12, thanks largely to its close ties to
Britney Spears and N Sync.
</P>
<P>
   BRONFMAN MAY TESTIFY AGAINST MP3.COM
</P>
<P>
   The chief executive of Seagram Co., Edgar J. Bronfman, Jr., is
expected to testify Wednesday in a federal trial being held to
determine the scope of the damages that MP3.com will pay Seagram's
Universal Music Group for violating its copyrights with its
Internet music service. MP3.com's chief executive, Michael
Robertson, concluded testifying before a skeptical Judge Jed Rakoff
on Tuesday, saying he had not set out to willfully violate
Universal's copyrights when he created an online database of
thousands of albums.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET BET IS BUYING 360HIPHOP
</P>
<P>
   BET.com, a Web site created in February as adjunct to the Black
Entertainment Television cable network, has reached a tentative
agreement to buy a key competitor, 360HIPHOP.com. That Web site,
started in June by Russell Simmons, the founder of Def Jam Records,
is geared to music trends and information. Under the agreement, the
two companies will combine business operations, but maintain
separate Web sites. BET.com is ranked among the most popular
African-American-oriented sites on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   NEW VERTICALONE BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   VerticalOne, a unit of the S1 Corp., is expected to announce
Wednesday that it will provide account-aggregation services to
Yahoo and to Wells Fargo bank, allowing them to provide a single
place on the Internet where their customers can keep all of their
financial data, like the balances in their bank and brokerage
accounts, frequent-flier programs and credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   HARDWARE GATEWAY TRIES TAX PROMOTION
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to take the no-tax edge away from pure direct-sales
rivals like Dell, Gateway will temporarily absorb the sales tax for
consumers who buy desktop and notebook PCs at most of its 290
Country Store locations. The promotion, which began Tuesday and
ends Thursday, was started after Gateway executives saw sales spike
when states like Pennsylvania and South Carolina offered sales-tax
blackout periods to their residents. ``The response to that program
was huge, so we decided to extend it to additional states,'' said
Brad Williams, a company spokesman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
