<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5720 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TEXAS-MEDICAID-NYT &LR;      08-29 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-MEDICAID-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE FINDS DEEP FLAWS IN TEXAS' MEDICAID PROGRAMS FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also GORE) 
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ A federal judge has ruled that Texas' system for
administering preventive medicine and certain other health care for
children in Medicaid programs is badly flawed, and he has ordered
the state to make improvements.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Judge William Wayne Justice of U.S. District Court found
that the state had not lived up to the terms of a 1996 consent
decree or provided appropriate health care under federal law to
more than 1.5 million children eligible for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the ruling was focused on the Early Periodic Screening,
Diagnosis and Treatment program, which exists, the judge said, ``to
ensure that poor children receive comprehensive health care at an
early age, so that they will develop fewer health problems as they
grow older.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice, in a ruling filed Aug. 14, found, among other
things, that the state had failed to educate indigent families
about available treatments and had not provided transportation to
see doctors.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also found that the managed care plans that serve
about one in three Texans on Medicaid had not provided appropriate
care. He cited inadequate and incomplete medical checkups and said
that in some cases health maintenance organizations had improperly
blocked children's access to specialists.
</P>
<P>
   In one example, the judge cited testimony about a 17-month-old
boy who had been treated for ear infections 17 times. After
treating the boy three more times, the boy's new primary care
doctor sought permission from the family's Medicaid HMO to send the
boy to an ear, nose and throat specialist. But the request was
turned down because the primary care provider had not treated the
boy six times in the past six months, as was required by the HMO.
</P>
<P>
   The class-action lawsuit was filed in 1993 on behalf of Texas
children eligible for Medicaid. About 1.4 million children in the
state do not have health insurance, according to public-interest
groups, and about 600,000 of those are eligible for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling comes as Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican
presidential candidate, has faced accusations of striking
inadequacies in the state's health care for poor and uninsured
children.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for Bush's office, said the state
was spending more money on Medicaid outreach programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe it is important for children to receive
preventative health care,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit originally resulted in the 1996 consent decree meant
to improve health care for indigent children. But earlier this
year, lawyers for the plaintiffs returned to federal court in
Austin to argue that the state was not living up to the decree.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Zinn, the lead plaintiff lawyer, noted that last year
Texas lawmakers enacted a moratorium on expanding managed care into
any new areas of the state. ``The judge's finding on managed care
confirms that the state does not yet have its house in order,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolynn Singleton, a registered nurse who owns four clinics in
North Texas that serve mostly poor patients, described the state
system as chaotic and very difficult for indigent patients to
navigate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most are worried about keeping their lights and water on, not
whether their child has immunizations or health care,'' said
Singleton, who testified in the suit. The system, she said,
``imposes too many barriers that isolates them from that care.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered the state to propose remedies within 60 days.
Defendants include officials at the state's Health and Human
Services Commission and Department of Health. Both agencies, which
are run by appointees of Bush, referred questions about the lawsuit
to the state attorney general's office.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Horton, a spokeswoman for that office, said the attorney
general had not decided whether to appeal, and that it was too soon
to say what remedies might be proposed. She declined to comment
about the judge's characterizations of the state's system, but she
pointed to court filings by the state that contend that the state's
efforts are adequate.
</P>
<P>
   According to those filings, the state made almost 5 million
``outreach'' contacts to clients last year; the budget for medical
transportation has increased by 300 percent; and a $7.6 million
contract for Medicaid outreach services is the largest in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Zinn noted that lawmakers, including Bush, have pushed tax cuts,
representing money that could go toward health care and other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The tax cuts pushed by Bush have become a political issue as the
state has run into a larger-than-expected budget shortfall, owing
in part to higher Medicaid expenses from rising prescription costs.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say Bush's state tax cuts have hurt services, and
suggest that his national tax-cut proposals are risky. Republicans
say shortfalls happen every budget cycle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
