<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, AUG. 30 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Wednesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MEDIA-TALK-NYT (Moved on Sunday, Aug. 27)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Aug. 27
about an MSNBC billboard promoting ``The News With Brian Williams''
misstated a comparison between the average audience for the
program's 9 p.m. showing and what MSNBC says was its cumulative
audience during April. The average nightly audience of 203,000 is
one-206th of the cumulative audience of 42 million, which includes
the number of different viewers tuned in to at least one minute of
any of its showings, including four repeats a night. It is not
one-20,500th.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OED-IN-AMERICA-NYT (Moved on Friday, Aug. 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, Aug. 18
about Jesse Sheidlower, who heads the North American office of the
Oxford English Dictionary, misstated one of his publishing credits.
He was the editor of the book ``The F-Word,'' not its author. The
article also omitted part of the title of the reference work from
which that book was largely derived. It is The Random House
Historical Dictionary of American Slang.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
