<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5724 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f BC-MAKEUP-ARTIST-LADN     08-29 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAKEUP-ARTIST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    UNION CARD FULFILLS A DREAM FOR BUDDING MAKEUP ARTIST
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tinseltown is an ideal place to reinvent yourself
career-wise, as Kathleen Freeman-Smith said she found after leaving
her native London and her life as a variety show dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Only, at first she had no idea what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, the Toluca Lake resident will mark this Labor
Day as a makeup artist for feature films and TV shows as a new
member of Make-Up Artists &AMP; Hair Stylists, Local706.
</P>
<P>
   Joining the union ended three years of nonunion shoots that
dragged on for up to 18 hours for little, if any, pay -- conditions
that took the glamour out of prepping stars like Timothy Hutton and
Rebecca DeMornay.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard, definitely hard,'' said Freeman-Smith, 32.
``There's a lot of people out there that want to do the same thing.
You start out and work for free or assist people and take whatever
you can to build up a portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a union trainee, she can become a journeyman in two years
and head a production's makeup department.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming one of the 1,429 active union members makes
Freeman-Smith eligible for health benefits, a pension and industry
recognition, said union representative John Inzerella.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you really want to have a career in this, you have to be
part of the union -- we have all the big shows,'' Inzerella said.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in north London, Freeman-Smith said, she never
envisioned living in Los Angeles, working in the film business.
</P>
<P>
   She met her future husband on a cruise ship in the Mediterranean
and followed him first to his hometown of Atlanta before they moved
to Los Angeles so he could pursue a career making documentaries and
films.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in no position to help me, but certainly being close to
productions got me serious enough to look a little further into
what I might want to do,'' Freeman-Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-week course in makeup in Hollywood introduced her to the
craft. It was up to her to find a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of glamour in it -- you work long hours,
you're up at 5 in the morning, working nights,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Smith said he knew his wife's persistence would pay off:
``She came to America not knowing what she wanted to do and after
seeing my line of work in film and television, she might be
interested in makeup.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeman-Smith said she enjoys the technical challenges of
applying regular and special effects makeup and has little interest
in meeting celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   During the years of struggle, she kept focused on her goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you first leave makeup school, everyone's desperate to
join the union,'' she said. ``Everyone has the impression that once
you're in the union, you start to work on big movies. Now that I'm
in the union, it's great, but you have to start on the bottom again
and work your way up.''
</P>
<P>
   That means building a rapport with producers and directors of
union shoots because her old contacts on nonunion productions are
of no use now.
</P>
<P>
   Union membership has conferred several advantages, such as
working feature films, getting significantly better pay plus
overtime, something her nonunion colleagues only dream of.
</P>
<P>
   But the uncertainties of her early career persist in prospects
of a strike next year by actors, writers and directors that could
be financially devastating for all production workers.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
