<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: BIG CORPORATE TRAVEL-MANAGEMENT COMPANIES
OPTIMISTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (duplication warning: also sent with `f' code)  
 By JOE SHARKEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry, I don't see you in the computer at all,'' said the
ticket agent at the Continental Airlines counter. She had been very
helpful, tapping away diligently, looking for my name and the
electronic ticket that I insisted would be attached to it.
</P>
<P>
   Beside me, my wife looked plenty worried. She always travels
with a paper ticket, which she books through a travel agent. But I
sometimes use e-tickets, booking bargain fares through one of the
online travel sites.
</P>
<P>
   On this day in mid-August, we were traveling together on
separate business, happily to the same place: Phoenix. We'd also
tacked on a week of vacation, planning to finish our chores within
a few days and then drive down to Tucson to ride horses for a week
at a ranch in the Sonoran Desert.
</P>
<P>
   The ticket clerk stopped tapping and gave me a look of dark
sympathy. The word ``whoa'' formed in my mind. This is embarrassing
to admit, considering that I write a newspaper column about, ahem,
business travel, but it seems that I had showed up at the airport
with a piece of paper that said ``Arizona Trip'' across the top.
The paper, which I thought was a printout of a confirmed e-ticket
reservation, was in fact nothing more than a printout of a planned
itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Through my own dumb fault, when I thought I was booking my
multiple-destination ticket online about six weeks earlier, I had
neglected to click through to actually complete the purchase. I had
printed out the incomplete itinerary and tucked it in my travel
folder, blissfully unaware that I didn't have a ticket. Now the
plane was about to board, and all I had was a sheet of typing
paper.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, the flight was full except for a single first-class seat,
priced at a terrifying $2,200, one-way. Worse yet, there was no
flexibility in my schedule. I absolutely had to be in Phoenix that
night for a series of interviews starting the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   In a fix like this, who you gonna call? Well, friends, you
better believe I called a travel agent.
</P>
<P>
   My wife flew off on schedule. Desperate, I phoned American
Express and explained the problem. The agent tapped for about 30
seconds and, voila, I was booked a few hours later on a nonstop
Continental flight from Newark to Phoenix, with a return flight
from Tucson. What's more, the agent informed me that I was
automatically upgraded to first class, since I was paying full
fare. I got to Phoenix only about six hours behind schedule, and we
were galloping across the desert a week after that.
</P>
<P>
   I wish I could report that the cost to keep me on schedule was
somewhere close to the original $660 fare I believed I had booked
online. In fact, it was about $2,100, round trip. This illustrates
the difference between the prices for air fares paid by most
leisure travelers, who have the flexibility to book well in
advance, and business travelers, who often do not have any
flexibility and have to make last-minute arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   But my experience also illustrates a reason major
travel-management companies, after a few years in which the travel
agent world has been rocked and compressed by the virtual
disappearance of commissions from airlines, are feeling pretty
optimistic these days.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get jammed up on a trip, and it sure is nice to pick up
the phone and have someone fix the problem right away,'' said Hal
Rosenbluth, the chief executive of Rosenbluth International, one of
the top five U.S.-based corporate travel-management companies.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, hundreds of small travel agencies have gone out
of business as airlines sharply reduced commissions. But at the
annual convention of the National Business Travel Association in
Los Angeles last month, representatives from the big
travel-management companies were sounding quite happy.
</P>
<P>
   Smart travel-management companies, which now charge fees for
services rendered rather than depending on commissions from the
airlines, are in fact prospering in a new competitive environment
that cedes a small portion of the market to the pure online bargain
bookings and at the same time opens up more room for specialized
services, especially for corporate travel.
</P>
<P>
   The big agencies are ``no longer seen as intermediaries for the
airlines,'' said Jud Linville, president for corporate services at
American Express, where air travel bookings grew 13 percent last
year, to $10.9 billion. Travel management has become ``a very
rational business _ we get paid for the value we create,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the big travel agencies are actually scrambling to hire
people. ``The industry now has a lot of technology with not a lot
of forethought,'' said Rosenbluth, whose company booked $2.4
billion in air sales last year, according to Business Travel News,
a trade publication. ``One of our real concerns now is the need to
attract good people'' to handle growing customer service demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to come down to who can attract, train and retain
the best people,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
