<SLUG> BC-AT&AMP;T-EXCITE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T SHARES UP ON SPEEDY EXCITE(AT)HOME DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By SIMON ROMERO with ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's stock rose Tuesday on the news that the company had
incorporated Excite(at)Home into its operations more quickly than
expected, suggesting a speedier move into high-speed Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not all good news for AT&AMP;T investors. Standard &AMP;
Poor's said Tuesday that it had put the company's debt on review
for a possible downgrade, citing management miscues and costly
acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   After the stock markets closed on Monday, AT&AMP;T said that it had
increased its voting stake in Excite(at)Home to 74 percent from 56
percent, giving it a controlling interest. AT&AMP;T will now include in
its own results the figures for Excite(at)Home, a broadband
provider based in Redwood City, Calif. The companies had been
expected to consolidate their financial results in the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``AT&AMP;T has thrown a life preserver to Excite,'' said Emily
Meehan, an analyst at the Yankee Group, a communications consulting
company. ``Now it remains to be seen whether Excite will bleed
profits from AT&AMP;T or get turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors bid AT&AMP;T's stock up $1.13, to $32 Tuesday, but the
shares remain deeply depressed, off nearly 50 percent from the
52-week high in November. The company is said to be considering a
number of ways to bolster the stock.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P, the credit-rating agency, cited concerns about AT&AMP;T's
costly acquisitions of TCI and MediaOne, which made it the nation's
largest cable television operator, as major reasons for putting the
stock on its watch list for possible downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't a fait accompli, but it shows we're very concerned
about the general direction of AT&AMP;T,'' said Rick Siderman, senior
telecommunications credit analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's. Still, it
is not clear if any downgrade will increase AT&AMP;T's borrowing costs,
because Moody's Investors Service already rates AT&AMP;T lower than
S&AMP;P.
</P>
<P>
   S&AMP;P said that AT&AMP;T's long-term debt could be cut more than one
notch below its double-A-minus rating and its short-term rating of
A-1-plus.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, S&AMP;P expressed concerns about ``operational and
management miscues'' in AT&AMP;T's core businesses of long-distance
service, which has been squeezed by fierce competition, and its
wireless services _ concerns echoed by others.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management has gone from little room for error to almost
none,'' said Pascal Aguirre, principal in the business strategy
group at Renaissance Strategy Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Closing the Excite(at)Home transaction early will have little
impact on the company's earnings projections for the entire year,
stock analysts said. But for the third quarter, AT&AMP;T's earnings
will be reduced by an estimated 5 cents. Operating earnings will be
35 to 38 cents a share, the company said, down from its previous
target of 40 cents to 43 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Excite(at)Home lost an estimated $2.5 billion last year on
revenue of about $500 million and continues to lose money this
year, according to Renaissance Strategy.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T picked up another company Tuesday that did little to
improve its bottom line immediately but gave it a solid footing in
Latin America. AT&AMP;T Latin America, which was formed by AT&AMP;T last
year, merged with the South American telecommunications company
FirstCom to form Latin America's newest specialized broadband
communications provider.
</P>
<P>
   FirstCom, whose stock had been traded on the Nasdaq, has served
businesses and other high-volume customers in major cities in
Chile, Colombia and Peru. During the first six months of this year,
it posted a net loss of $32.4 million, or $1.06 a share. Patricio
Northland, FirstCom's chief executive, attributed the losses to the
heavy build-out of the company's fiber optics network in the three
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The new AT&AMP;T Latin America stock began trading on Nasdaq on
Tuesday and closed virtually unchanged at $17.38. Since the
regional company was formed last year, AT&AMP;T Latin America has
aggressively moved into the region, by acquiring Netstream in
Brazil and Keytech LD in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Northland, who is now chief executive of AT&AMP;T Latin America,
said the company had identified 22 business centers in Latin
America where it would focus its marketing efforts. It already has
a substantial presence in 10 of them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
