<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-IGNITIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CALIFORNIA JUDGE SAYS FORD FACES IGNITION RECALL
</HEADLINE>
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a ruling that could deal a blow to the Ford Motor Co., a
California judge late Tuesday largely agreed with complaints that
Ford knowingly installed defective ignition mechanisms in nearly 2
million vehicles produced from 1983 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In his tentative decision, Alameda County Superior Court Judge
Michael E. Ballachey said he intended to issue orders ``compelling
recall and repair'' of the vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The part in question is an ignition module that regulates
current to the sparkplugs. In 300 models, the module was mounted on
the distributor near the engine block, where it was exposed to high
temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Car buyers' lawyers said Ford had been warned by an engineer
that high temperatures would cause the device to fail and stall the
engine. Consumer advocates estimated the costs to Ford of
compliance would be $70 million to $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the decision, which will be discussed at a hearing at the
Alameda County Court on Sept. 28, could be more damaging to Ford's
reputation than to its finances, consumer advocates said. In the
wake of the Firestone tire recall, the company is working hard to
retain public trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is bad news at a bad time,'' said Clarence M. Ditlow of
the Center for Auto Safety in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the tire recall, he continued, the company is
mounting television ads that say, ``Trust us, we put safety first.
This decision says, We put profits first.''
</P>
<P>
   The California plaintiffs brought their case against Ford in
September 1997. Their lawyers produced documents intended to
establish that Ford withheld information from federal regulators
about the engineering defect.
</P>
<P>
   In his 10-page ruling, Ballachey was sharply critical of the way
Ford dealt with the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration.
``Ford's strategy, clearly established by the credible evidence,
was `If you don't ask the right question, we don't have to answer
with what common sense tells us you want to know,''' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Krusel, a Ford spokeswoman, said, ``The real-world data
and engineering analysis is in direct conflict with the court's
ruling.'' She added: ``There is simply nothing to fix. We expect
this ruling will be reversed on appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   In November, a mistrial was declared in the first phase of the
case, in which jurors were asked to determine if Ford was liable
for damages. In that trial, Ford denied any defects.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2156EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
