<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EUROPE-BOURSES-NYT &LR;      08-29 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EUROPE-BOURSES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SWEDISH COMPANY BEGINS HOSTILE TAKEOVER BID FOR LONDON STOCK
EXCHANGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL with SUZANNE KAPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ OM Gruppen AB, the owner of the Stockholm stock
exchange, began a $1.2 billion hostile bid Tuesday for the much
bigger London Stock Exchange, touching off the first takeover fight
for an exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the Swedish exchange announced its cash-and-stock
offer, the London exchange _ which is seven times the size of the
Swedish one _ postponed indefinitely its Sept. 14 shareholder vote
on its planned merger with the Deutsche Boerse in Frankfurt,
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   And, adding to the tumult, Rolf Breuer, the chairman of the
Deutsche Boerse, said in an interview with The International
Herald-Tribune that the exchange was prepared to consider changing
its agreement with the London exchange into ``a friendly takeover''
instead of a merger of equals. Deutsche Boerse, however, would take
its cue from London on whether to proceed with a sweetened offer,
people close to those discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Frankfurt exchange said that it had no plans
to enter a bidding war. But officials there said it was unclear
whether other contenders _ like the Euronext alliance of the Paris,
Belgian and Dutch exchanges _ would also consider an offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the debate would reopen, we would be very interested to
enter the debate,'' said Vincent Van Dessel, general manager of the
Brussels exchange. ``But I am not sure an offer is something we can
envisage.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome, the fate of the 200-year-old London
exchange, and its control of the world's oldest and Europe's
biggest securities market, will most likely be tied more closely to
one or more European exchanges, which are trying to devise new ways
to trade across borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll end up in bed with the Germans or we'll succumb to the
Swedes,'' said Richard Grossman, a director of Redmayne Bentley
Stockbrokers, which is a shareholder in the London exchange.
``London is bound to lose its independence.''
</P>
<P>
   London is dominated by the trading floors of big American banks,
which in the past have supported the idea of a London-Frankfurt
merger because of the trading volumes and increased liquidity it
would yield.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to have the volume and that's what
London-Frankfurt has got,'' one executive said.
</P>
<P>
   A combined London-Frankfurt exchange would be known as iX and
would trade securities with a combined market value of $4.3
trillion, compared with Stockholm's $330 billion. London alone
trades $2.8 trillion in stocks, compared with more than $11
trillion on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's developments come after two years of muddled efforts
by European exchanges to meet investors' demands for a single
market after the introduction of the single European currency, the
euro, and to confront a challenge from cheaper and more nimble
Internet-based stock-trading networks.
</P>
<P>
   Those trends have increased pressure on exchanges like London's
to issue their own shares to speed consolidation. But Tuesday's
hostile bid highlighted the risk of going public in a market as
fragmented as Europe's and as vulnerable to predators. The
London-Frankfurt merger is supposed to be a precursor to an
alliance with the Nasdaq stock market, offering 24-hour global
trading in high-growth stocks. That deal would collapse if the
London-Frankfurt merger falls apart.
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq said Tuesday that it was ``committed to the iX venture,
with its economies of scale and its vision for a global market
partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   However, its chairman, Frank Zarb, said recently that ``Nasdaq
will be in Europe one way or another,'' implying that the exchange
could consider other options.
</P>
<P>
   OM began its hostile bid after officials at the London exchange
rejected an initial overture Friday, saying they were dissatisfied
with the amount of detail OM had provided, according to executives
close to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, OM offered stockholders in the London exchange (PS)7
in cash and 0.65 of a new OM share, valuing each share of the
London exchange at (PS)27.19, or $40, 16 percent more than Friday's
closing price. The London exchange called the offer ``derisory''
and urged its shareholders to take no action. OM has 28 days to
publish its offer.
</P>
<P>
   OM said its offer was conditional on 90 percent approval by
London exchange shareholders _ a threshold that might prove
difficult to reach, according to traders in London and Frankfurt.
The London-Frankfurt deal would have required 75 percent approval
at the Sept. 14 meeting, now postponed.
</P>
<P>
   OM's move came after shareholders in the London exchange, most
of them relatively small traders, had already signaled their
unhappiness with the London-Frankfurt deal, arguing that there was
insufficient detail on issues like cost, regulation, clearing and
settling to evaluate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was imperative that there was a delay in voting,'' said
Brian Mairs, a spokesman for an industry group representing private
client and other noninstitutional traders, which account for
one-third of the shares in the London exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has to offer the same benefits to us as to the big
players,'' he said, referring to the big banks operating in London,
which have generally remained silent on the OM bid despite the
sense among some of them that, in the words of one executive, ``the
reality is that iX has a lot more support out of the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, some analysts said, the uncertainties surrounding
the Sept. 14 vote probably encouraged OM to make its bid, possibly
to thwart the creation of a European giant or to hobble the
London-Frankfurt merger while OM rolls out the Jiway pan-European
electronic trading platform that it is developing with Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter.
</P>
<P>
   But the OM bid drew criticism from shareholders like Guinness
Peat, a finance group that owns about 1 percent of the London
exchange, which called the Swedish offer ``pretty unappealing''
because it undervalued the London exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Other investors have complained that OM's bid is based on
overvalued OM stock.
</P>
<P>
   OM, which is using its status as a leading supplier of market
technology to support its bid, went on the offensive Tuesday to
promote its bid, calling it ``a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   ``LSE would keep its strong position, with OM, a leading
technological supplier, at its side; it's a very serious
alternative to iX,'' said Olof Stenhammar, OM's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the proposed iX merger squanders the potential
of LSE and that with our proven management skills and leading
technology, we can secure LSE's position as the pre-eminent
European stock exchange,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
