<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD HOLDOUTS; LABOR ONLINE; BUCHANAN OUT OF ACTION; LIEBERMAN
ON GORE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Va.)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD HOLDOUTS
</P>
<P>
   Joe Eszterhas, the Hollywood screenwriter whose credits include
``Basic Instinct'' and ``Showgirls,'' is urging industry
colleagues, many of them Democrats, not to contribute to the
Democratic Party until Vice President Al Gore and Sen. Joseph
Lieberman explain their positions on ``freedom of creative
expression.'' In a full-page ad in Tuesday's Daily Variety, the
widely read trade paper, Eszterhas took issue with comments by
Lieberman about excessive sex and violence in movies and television
shows. He accused Lieberman of making ``not so veiled threats''
about withholding license renewals, instituting federal
prosecutions and legislating censorship if writers and studios did
not censor themselves. Lieberman's spokeswoman, Kiki McLean,
replied, ``When there are products that are not necessarily good
for our kids and our families, he's not going to be shy to
challenge the industry. He's somebody who believes strongly in the
First Amendment and has always had an open dialogue about what we
can do voluntarily to help our families do better.''
</P>
<P>
   LABOR ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has created a Web site where Vice President Al Gore
will hold a live Web cast on Labor Day for union members. The Web
site will allow union members to send e-mail messages to political
candidates, including the Vice President, Gov. George W. Bush and
members of Congress. The Web site _ www.workingfamilies.com _ will
also feature a speech by John Sweeney, the union president, and
video messages from what labor leaders call ``The Texas Truth
Squad,'' a group of workers from Texas who are traveling the
country to accuse Bush of doing little on issues that unions care
about. On the site, users will also be able to register to vote and
can examine the voting record of candidates for federal office. The
site will be up from Aug. 30 to Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHANAN OUT OF ACTION
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party presidential hopeful Patrick Buchanan has canceled
all public appearances until after Labor Day, after undergoing a
second gall bladder operation because doctors found another stone.
``He feels a lot better and is coming along fine,'' said Brian
Doherty, his campaign spokesman. ``But after two operations and
losing 15 pounds or so from not being able to eat much, he needs to
rest another week.'' Buchanan first underwent a gall stone
operation on Aug. 17. After being released from the hospital on
Aug. 19, he was recovering at his Northern Virginia home when he
had a sharp abdominal pain. Doctors removed a second stone on Aug.
23 and he was released three days later. He plans to remain at home
until Sept. 5.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN ON GORE
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joseph Lieberman has a new, pointed pitch about his running
mate. He says Vice President Al Gore is the best leader for the
information age. Speaking to several thousand communications
workers in Anaheim, Calif., Tuesday, Lieberman warned that the
United States could not afford to have a president in the 21st
century who did not understand the new economy and technology.
Then, in a not-so-veiled dig at whether Gov. George W. Bush had the
depth and preparedness to lead in a high-tech age, he invoked a
couple of not-so-swift television cartoon characters, saying, ``We
as a nation can't afford to make Barney Rubble investments in a
George Jetson world.'' Lieberman said that Gore not only understood
the new economy and technology but wanted to speed its advances by
investing in training people and by making college tuition
tax-deductible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
