<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNSOLICITED OFFER IS MADE FOR LONDON STOCK EXCHANGE
</P>
<P>
   OM Gruppen, the owner of the Stockholm stock exchange, began a
$1.2 billion hostile bid for the much larger London Stock Exchange,
touching off the first ever takeover fight for an exchange. The
London exchange then postponed its Sept. 14 shareholder vote on its
planned merger with the Frankfurt exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Frankfurt exchange indicated it was willing to consider
changing the terms of its agreement with the London exchange to ``a
friendly takeover'' instead of a merger. And the London exchange
could also draw interest from the Euronext alliance of the Paris,
Belgian and Dutch exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   COMPANIES TO SET UP A LINUX LAB
</P>
<P>
   In a validation of the growing popularity of Linux, Intel, IBM,
Hewlett-Packard and several other companies plan to announce on
Wednesday that they will jointly create and finance a laboratory
for developing and testing advances in the operating system.
</P>
<P>
   CONSOLIDATION SEEN IN WINE INDUSTRY
</P>
<P>
   The Foster's Brewing Group's $1.14 billion acquisition of
Beringer Wine is likely to prompt a wave of consolidation among
California's premium wineries. Analysts and industry executives
said the deal effectively puts in play every significant
independent wine maker, including Kendall-Jackson and Robert
Mondavi. Shares of Beringer rose $10.25, to $55.31.
</P>
<P>
   SPEEDY DEAL LIFTS AT&AMP;T SHARES
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AT&AMP;T rose on the news that the company had
incorporated Excite(at)Home into its operations more quickly than
expected, suggesting a speedier move into high-speed Internet
services. Investors bid AT&AMP;T's stock up $1.13, to $32. But Standard
&AMP; Poor's said that it had put the company's debt on review for a
possible downgrade.
</P>
<P>
   DOW AND S&AMP;P SLIP; NASDAQ RISES
</P>
<P>
   Stocks ended mixed, with banks and airlines mainly lower while
some technology issues made modest gains. The Dow Jones industrial
average fell 37.74 points, or 0.3 percent, to 11,215.10. The
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index slipped 4.25 points, or 0.3
percent, to 1,509.84. The Nasdaq composite index finished up 11.58
points, or 0.3 percent, to 4,082.17.
</P>
<P>
   HOME SALES SURGED 14.7 PERCENT IN JULY
</P>
<P>
   Sales of new single-family homes surged 14.7 percent in July,
well above expectations, and the consumer confidence index dipped
slightly but remained close to the record.
</P>
<P>
   THE POWER OF CONTRARY THINKING
</P>
<P>
   Poppy King says her mother brought her up to think differently _
a quality that has proved to be both a blessing and a liability in
her life. But it was certainly a blessing when it led her to start
up Poppy Industries, an Australian cosmetics and lingerie company.
Her biggest passion is flea markets, vintage stores and
bric-a-brac.
</P>
<P>
   INVESTORS TO RAISE STAKE IN HYUNDAI
</P>
<P>
   A group of Western investors, including Wilbur L. Ross, a
specialist in corporate rescues, and the American International
Group plan to increase their investment in three financial
affiliates of the Hyundai Group to gain a firmer hold on Hyundai
Securities, South Korea's largest brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL AGENTS FIND WAY TO ADAPT
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of small travel agencies have gone out of
business as airlines sharply reduced commissions, smart
travel-management companies, which charge fees for services
rendered rather than depending on commissions, are prospering by
offering specialized services, especially for corporate travel.
</P>
</TEXT>
