<HEADLINE>
DUST OF 25   HOUSES COLLAPSING CLOUDS PHILADELPHIA'S REVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBSBy    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Things had been looking up in this long-suffering
city. Downtown was thriving again, the new mayor was still savoring
his honeymoon and this month's Republican National Convention left
Philadelphians with a feel-good, ego-boosting bounce.
</P>
<P>
   The euphoria has come crashing down with a spate of building
collapses that have helped to remind people here that there is a
crumbling wasteland of neglected neighborhoods just beyond the
glittering city center.
</P>
<P>
   A soggy summer, decades of deferred maintenance and
Philadelphia's swampy past have conspired against the city's 30,000
vacant and decaying row houses, most of them north of the office
buildings and hotels that have sprouted downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Since last Thursday, 25 buildings have come down, either
partially or fully, and city officials estimate that another 3,100
are in imminent danger of falling. So far no one has been seriously
hurt, though two men were slightly injured by the collapse of a
wood awning. Until last week, the city averaged about 20 collapses
a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When is it going to stop?'' Robert Solvibile, the commissioner
in charge of building inspections, asked with exasperation. ``This
is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Calling the rash of collapses a crisis, housing officials
commandeered a police helicopter Tuesday morning and began an
aerial survey of the city's most dilapidated neighborhoods.
Solvibile said airborne inspectors had spotted more than a dozen
buildings on the verge of tumbling down.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to triple its cadre of 20 inspectors by the end of
the week, the city is teaching housing authority employees how to
spot a dangerously decaying row house. Officials say they plan to
double the number of emergency demolitions to about 60 a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see a problem, and we're determined to make sure it's
solved before it becomes a tragedy,'' said Barbara Grant, a
spokeswoman for Mayor John F. Street, who has been in office since
January.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent blush of prosperity, much of Philadelphia
remains untouched by the good times. The city is still saddled with
tracts of abandoned houses, the legacy of a hemorrhaging of 500,000
residents that began in the 1950s. During years of mismanagement
and municipal bankruptcy, the rows of elegantly detailed brick
houses, many now vacant, began to fall into disrepair.
</P>
<P>
   Even occupied houses began to crumble as their owners grew older
and poorer. Mark Alan Hughes, a professor of public policy at the
University of Pennsylvania, said recent studies indicated that more
than half of all home owners in the city were over 60 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have elderly widows who haven't been up to the third floor
in years,'' Hughes said. ``Then a little leak in the roof and a
rainy summer can lead to a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's swampy terrain has also contributed to the
sagging foundations and listing facades. Although William Penn
built his colonial outpost on solid ground, the 19th-century
builders who threw up thousands of brick-faced row houses for the
growing middle class were not as thoughtful. Many of the most
troubled neighborhoods were built on the soot and debris that
developers used to fill in the marshes that once stretched
alongside the Schuylkill and Delaware River.
</P>
<P>
   Even wealthy home owners are bedeviled by the unstable ground,
said Hughes, who had to shore up the walls of his 1866 home with
reinforcing rods.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have the resources, you can deal with it,'' he said.
``If you don't, it can be catastrophic.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, other aging cities have tackled the problem of
abandoned housing with more success. Chicago, Baltimore and New
York have aggressive programs to quickly identity and demolish
buildings at risk of falling down. Elyse Fink, a spokeswoman for
the Department of Buildings in New York, said there were only a
handful of collapsed buildings incidents last year, most of them
involving new construction. ``We just don't have as many empty
buildings as we used to,'' Fink said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his mayoral campaign last year, Street made urban
renewal a central theme and he has promised a $250-million
neighborhood rehabilitation program that will be paid for with
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those who live in the city's more bedraggled
neighborhoods say they have already seen some improvements. Soon
after his election, the mayor began a program that removed more
than 30,000 abandoned cars from local streets. Even before the
recent spell of collapses, a fast-track demolition process allowed
contractors to dismantle houses as soon as they were condemned by
inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the improvements, it was hard to find anyone in North
Philadelphia with rosy predictions of renewal. After years of
living with drugs, poverty and violent crime, many residents said
they now had a new fear: dying beneath a pile bricks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Standing in front of a vacant lot on 29th Street, James Bark,
14, recalled how the house there had quietly fallen in on itself a
few days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cloud of dust was so thick, I couldn't see anything,'' he
said, shaking his head. He looked down the block and gestured to
dozens of other forlorn houses, their facades peeling off, others
with roofs supporting small groves of trees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hang out in front of these abandoned buildings,'' he said.
``Any one of those could go. Our house could fall. The house next
door could fall. We just don't know anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
