<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Texas drought `very bleak'
 &HT;    Agriculture secretary adds 24 counties to disaster list
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By EVAN MOORE 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Dan Glickman visited
drought-stricken farmers near here Tuesday and termed conditions
``very bleak'' as North Texas edged past a 66-year record with 60
consecutive days without rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   That mark surpassed the record set in 1934 and matched in 1950
when the northern portion of the state went 59 days without rain.
</P>
<P>
   Glickman visited a farm in Wise County, then spoke with farmers
near the town of Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to remember that this is a regional drought. It
extends up through the midwest.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you have to take into account that this is the fourth year
out of five for some of these farmers. Many of them have been
receiving assistance for some time now.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've seen is very bleak,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My primary reason for coming here was to talk to folks and
then go back and look at what we can do administratively to help.''
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Glickman had named 153 Texas counties as either
primary or contiguous agricultural disaster areas. He added 24 to
that list Tuesday, bringing the total to 177. Farmers in those
areas will be eligible for low-interest loans through the USDA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drought causes more damage than hurricanes, floods and
earthquakes, but it's insidious,'' Glickman said. ``The long-term
effects will be difficult to assess.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman said he intends to make recommendations to Congress for
additional monies for farmers, but, realistically, with only about
30 days left in the legislative session, little may come of that
action.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, Congress created the National Drought Policies
Commission to look into what can be done,'' Glickman said.
``Hopefully, they'll have a report soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Just to the east of the area Glickman visited, Tarrant County
has been among the hardest hit, although no water rationing has
been instituted in Fort Worth or its suburbs, and the overall
supply is not critically low, said Mike Williams, spokesman for the
Tarrant Regional Water District.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our `west fork' lakes are really low, but our major supply
comes from Cedar Creek and Richland Chambers (southeast of Tarrant
County) and they're at about 93 or 94 percent capacity,'' Williams
said.
</P>
<P>
   The west fork, or Tarrant County Lakes, includes Bridgeport,
currently 17 feet below normal; Eagle Mountain, 8 feet below
normal; Lake Worth, 2 feet below normal, and Benbrook, 7 feet below
normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the soil moisture content is so low, people just keep
pouring water on their lawns,'' Williams said. ``If this continues,
we may be asking for voluntary rationing, then enforced rationing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We suggest that people limit their watering to about 1 inch
every five days.''
</P>
<P>
   There appears to be little or no relief in sight, said Bill
Proenza, director for the southern region of the National Weather
Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a regional drought,'' said Proenza. ``It's affecting
not just North Texas, but New Mexico, Louisiana, Mississippi,
Alabama, Georgia and Florida _ just about the entire southern
region.''
</P>
<P>
   The area is as dry as the northwestern United States, where
record wildfires have plagued firefighters in recent weeks, Proenza
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not having the number of fires, or the severity of
fires, simply because we haven't had the high winds, and we have
more roads and it's quicker and easier to put them out here,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, looking forward to September, we're still looking at
`climatology' (excessively dry) conditions. I'm afraid there's no
great change in sight.''
</P>
<P>
   That could spell financial setbacks for North Texas ranchers,
who have traditionally looked forward to rain in early September.
Steve Munday, director of the Texas and Southwestern Cattle Raisers
Association, said some area ranchers have begun liquidating herds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others are culling their herds pretty deeply, and I expect the
statewide cattle inventory will be off a few percentage points this
year,'' Munday said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can feed them when the grass is low, but there's not much
you can do when you run out of water.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, cattle prices haven't dipped too low yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought's effects were felt early in the small, North Texas
town of Throckmorton, where the reservoir began running dry in July
and town residents began digging a pipeline to a water tower 21
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   The line was finished in less than two weeks with the help of
675 volunteers, said Throckmorton Public Works Director Steve
Bowlin. He said two pump stations have since been installed and the
line was being pressure-tested Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found two leaks, but we're getting them fixed and we should
have it pumping by some day next week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's none too soon, Bowlin added. The receding waters of
Throckmorton Lake were about 6 inches above the pump level Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The effects also are reaching south to Austin and San Antonio,
the latter of which is the nation's largest city to rely solely on
ground water for its municipal supply.
</P>
<P>
   There, the state's largest springs are drying. The U.S. Fish and
Wildlife Service has reported that Comal Springs in New Braunfels
and its source, the Edwards Aquifer, are dropping and the
endangered fountain darter fish could be in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The best hope lies in the tropical storms that usually form in
September, Proenza said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to get in the position of wishing for
disasters,'' he said, ``but, sometimes they can be monsoonal and
bring nothing but rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most we can hope for at present.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, however, Proenza's satellite pictures showed no
storm formations and only one weak area of precipitation, east of
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
