<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOPEFULS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAMS ARE INSPIRING UNDERDOGS IN WAITING 
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When was the last time you heard these words: Teams are dreaming
of becoming the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   It was not too long ago that the Rams were the punch line of
jokes, Lawrence Phillips, the team's No. 1 draft pick, made the
police blotter once a month and the stadium was filled not with
bodies, but boos.
</P>
<P>
   A Super Bowl changed that. A remarkable long-shot story changed
that. Everyone is now a Rams wannabe.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend the National Football League begins its first
season of the new century and clearly the sport has embarked on
Football A.D.: After Dynasties.
</P>
<P>
   With the fall of empires like the San Francisco 49ers and the
Dallas Cowboys comes a wide-open game and the notion that any team
with an accurate quarterback, speed and confidence can snag the big
prize.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis proved that using that formula can change a
franchise's fortune in an instant as the Rams jumped from four
victories in 1998 to a 13-3 regular-season mark last season,
followed weeks later by a Super Bowl championship.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is a cadre of teams, some in the middle of the pack,
others at the bottom of the pile, that believe they can make the
leap that the Rams made. What is unclear is the accuracy of those
feelings. Are these hopes realistic, because the NFL is now a
parity-filled league, or do these teams need to wake up and smell
the Gatorade?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is trying to find the next Rams, but you know what, I
don't think there is one,'' said General Manager Ernie Accorsi of
the Giants, a team that might be a contender in the ``Who Wants to
Be the Next St. Louis?'' sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Rams did was remarkable,'' Accorsi said. ``It was
unprecedented. You have all these prognosticators on television and
teams saying who will be the next Rams. But no one seems to be
considering that what the Rams did may never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to the dreamers, many of whom are players
emerging from the optimism-fest known as training camp, and your
cynicism will be met with a smirk. The rallying cry of some teams,
as one player said, seems to be, ``Hey, if the sorry Rams can do
it, so can we.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's only natural to look at what the Rams did and
think you can do it, too,'' Philadelphia Eagles quarterback Donovan
McNabb said.
</P>
<P>
   Jessie Armstead, a Pro Bowl linebacker with the Giants, said:
``There are going to be surprise teams. There are always surprises.
Why not us?''
</P>
<P>
   That is what a lot of teams are asking: Why not us?
</P>
<P>
   The question is certainly being heard in Philadelphia. The
Eagles, winners of five games last season, have a franchise
quarterback in McNabb, a solid runner in Duce Staley and a strong
defense. The Eagles also play a last-place schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland is another possible St. Louis. The Raiders have a good
runner in Tyrone Wheatley, who, despite splitting time with
Napoleon Kaufman last season, still rushed for 936 yards and eight
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, coming off a 7-9 season, think they have the
quarterback to make a serious push. But the difference between New
York and St. Louis _ and it is a huge one _ is that St. Louis had
one of the best pass defenses in football last season. The Giants
have far from that.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets won their last four games in 1999 to finish 8-8 in what
amounted to one of Bill Parcells' best-ever coaching jobs.
Quarterback Vinny Testaverde is back from his Achilles' injury and
running back Curtis Martin remains one of the most dangerous
weapons in football.
</P>
<P>
   But Parcells is no longer coaching the Jets and neither is the
former defensive coordinator Bill Belichick, who is at New England.
That is too much brainpower to lose. The Rams had a unified,
top-notch coaching staff in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Jets, the Baltimore Ravens also had eight victories a
year ago, and they might be the most intriguing of the teams trying
to duplicate what the Rams did. The Ravens won't have as far to
climb, so they don't fit into the true Rams model, but Baltimore
had a history of heartbreak when the franchise was still in
Cleveland, and in that the Rams and the Ravens have a common
ground. The John Elway-led Denver Broncos beat Cleveland three
times in the American Football Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Ravens, like the Rams a season ago, have one of the top
defenses in the league, a potential franchise runner in the rookie
Jamal Lewis and a quarterback, Tony Banks, who was excellent in the
last half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Baltimore is a popular pick. To truly fit the miracle Rams
mode, a team has to come from nowhere. Cincinnati, Chicago or New
Orleans _ now those are real Rams wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Accorsi and others are right. Maybe looking for the next
Rams is like Geraldo Rivera searching for Al Capone's hidden vault.
It's a sexy idea but not truly attainable.
</P>
<P>
   Then again the Rams were not supposed to have a chance. So maybe
fans in Cleveland should start packing their bags for a little
Super Bowl trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
