<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD TO STAY AT DH, FOR NOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GORDON VERRELL  
 c.2000 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Darin Erstad is still bothered by soreness in
his left side and will remain in the designated-hitter role
tonight, and possibly longer, rather than take up his customary
spot in left field.
</P>
<P>
   After Erstad tested his side Monday by throwing it was thought
he was close to returning to the outfield. But manager Mike
Scioscia confirmed Tuesday that his All-Star left fielder is still
feeling pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not playable in left field,'' Scioscia said. ``After he
threw the other day, he was still feeling discomfort. It's the only
thing that bothers him: throwing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't anticipate it being anything long term, but he won't
be in the outfield (tonight).''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are idle Thursday, then begin a seven-game trip
Friday night in Chicago. Tuesday night, Erstad batted leadoff and
was the DH for the fifth game in a row.
</P>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER SONG: Major-league clubs may expand their rosters
beginning Friday. Scioscia anticipates the Angels will promote only
five or six players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to bring up guys who can help us,'' he said. ``Guys
aren't coming up if they can't contribute.''
</P>
<P>
   One example is backup catcher Shawn Wooten. He would have been
called up anyway, Scioscia said, but was brought in earlier when
Matt Walbeck, ordinarily the backup, injured his knee last week and
was placed on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels also have several players eligible to return from the
DL, including pitchers Tim Belcher, Mike Fyhrie, Seth Etherton and
Jarrod Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   SMILE, IF YOU CAN: The Angels assembled in center field at
Edison Field several hours before Tuesday night's game for the
annual team photo shoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not really the team picture,'' cracked one press boxer,
well aware of the Angels' overloaded disabled list, ``that's really
(team physician) Dr. (Lewis) Yocum and all his patients.''
</P>
<P>
   And, also from the press box ...
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia and a reporter were discussing the proper pronunciation
of reliever Al Levine's name _ le-VINE or le-VEEN? _ and Scioscia
said, finally, ``I don't care what it is as long as he keeps
throwing that blowing ball up the plate.''
</P>
<P>
   The guy with the bat-bustin' heavy pitch settled the argument.
It's le-VINE.
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: The Angels' protest of their 11-inning, 7-6 loss
Aug. 21 in Boston was formally denied Tuesday by the AL office.
``We felt we were on solid ground,'' Scioscia said, ``but the
league didn't see it as solidly as we did.'' ... The Angels worked
out a two-year extension of their affiliation with Cedar Rapids
(Iowa) of the Single-A Midwest League, taking the partnership
through the 2002 season. The Angels have had a Single-A farm in
Cedar Rapids since 1993. Current Angels catcher Bengie Molina
played on Cedar Rapids' 1994 championship club. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
