<SLUG> BC-CBS-BUILDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS' `BLACK ROCK' BUILDING IS SAID TO BE FOR SALE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Viacom, which acquired CBS this year, plans to sell
Black Rock, the elegant granite-clad skyscraper built to symbolize
the broadcasting company's view of itself as ``the Tiffany
network,'' according to officials involved in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   The building could be placed on the market as early as next
month, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-story tower, at 51 W. 52nd St. in Midtown Manhattan,
could fetch up to $370 million, according to real estate industry
estimates. Viacom executives said they were in the early stages of
discussions with a real estate brokerage firm and that any
potential sale would not involve moving many _ if any _ CBS
employees out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   They added, however, that those plans could change. If the
building was sold with CBS continuing to occupy about half of it,
real estate analysts said, the sale price would very likely be
significantly decreased.
</P>
<P>
   The officials from Viacom and CBS, who spoke on the condition of
anonymity, said that given the hot real estate market in that area
of Midtown, near Rockefeller Center and the Chrysler building,
selling Black Rock would be more profitable than continuing to
lease it to other tenants.
</P>
<P>
   The 36-year-old building was placed on the market last year, but
was taken off because the bids, which were about $300 million, were
too low. But real estate industry officials said the company could
get significantly more for the building now, especially if it moved
many CBS employees into other Viacom buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market with no vacancies, and they are one of the
only significant blocks of space in Midtown Manhattan,'' said Darcy
Stacom, the executive director for financial services at Cushman &AMP;
Wakefield, a commercial real estate brokerage firm in Manhattan.
``Clearly, the first time CBS went to market they were offering a
fully leased building. If they are now going to offer an entire
block of space, it will be an attractive investment opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   If the building is sold without CBS as a tenant, Stacom
estimates, it could garner as much as $425 per square foot, or
about $369 million.
</P>
<P>
   Though Black Rock is a relatively young building, it was made a
New York City landmark in 1997. Noted for its minimalist design and
its somber, dark granite skin, Black Rock stands in stark contrast
to the steel-and-glass towers nearby on the Avenue of the Americas.
It has the distinction of being the only skyscraper designed by the
famous modernist Eero Saarinen.
</P>
<P>
   The potential sale was first reported Tuesday by Bloomberg News.
Insignia/ESG, a commercial real estate company that has done
business with Viacom, is the leading contender for the project,
officials familiar with the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   The move comes after decisions by the other two major networks,
NBC and ABC, to move parts of their operations out of that section
of Midtown. Each of the networks has been acquired in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The building was built by William S. Paley, the founder of CBS,
in the 1960s, when the network was moving beyond its status as a
premier broadcast network and expanding into films, magazines and
theater production. It began serving as the CBS headquarters in
1968, as Walter Cronkite and other distinguished journalists kept
the network's pre-eminence in news broadcasting unchallenged.
</P>
<P>
   To Paley, Black Rock was not just a building; it was a monument
to the company's success.
</P>
<P>
   But management problems, competition from cable and other
factors all contributed to troubles at Black Rock. In 1987, CBS
began retrenching and focusing the company more solidly on
broadcasting. In 1981, CBS had 9,900 employees working in New York;
by 1992 there were only 4,700.
</P>
<P>
   That year, CBS, which has studios on West 57th Street, began
moving workers out of Black Rock and began leasing the building to
law firms and other tenants. The company now occupies only 350,000
square feet in the 870,000-square-foot building.
</P>
<P>
   Black Rock, named for the Canadian granite used for its exterior
and lobby walls, is the only skyscraper built by Saarinen, the
architect of the Vivian Beaumont Theater and the butterfly-shaped
T.W.A. terminal at Kennedy International Airport. It was one of the
last projects designed by Saarinen, who died in 1961, three years
before CBS moved in.
</P>
<P>
   A building must be 30 years old to become a New York landmark;
that designation was given to Black Rock at age 33, in 1997. ``We
did it with a group of buildings to get the best of the modernist
buildings,'' said Katy McNabb, a spokeswoman for the New York City
Landmarks Preservation Commission. ``We wanted to show people what
they had to offer.''
</P>
<P>
   In its designation report, the commission called the building
``one of New York's premier post-World-War-II-era skyscrapers and
one of the country's great works of modern architecture.'' The
report said it was New York's first postwar reinforced-concrete
skyscraper. Saarinen said his goal was to build a structure that
was both elegant and ``the simplest skyscraper in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite CBS' diminished presence at Black Rock in recent years,
it has gone to great lengths to protect both the symbolism and
architecture of the building, a notion that has comforted historic
preservationists.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Willis, an adjunct professor of urban studies at the
Graduate School of Architecture, Planning and Preservation at
Columbia University, said that the dark color and the absence of
interpretations in its facades made the building unique.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was designed to be the simplest modernist building in New
York City,'' Willis said.
</P>
<P>
   Its entrances are on West 52nd and West 53rd streets, creating
the effect of an absolutely pure granite slab on the Avenue of the
Americas. ``Certainly, it is one of the most elegant of the
modernist buildings,'' Willis added. ``It is self-consciously
unlike the other modernist buildings, with its somber quality and
its minimalist style. It is not like the glass box.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
