<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN DEFENDS HIS CALL FOR GREATER ROLE FOR RELIGION
</HEADLINE>
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Explaining his call for a greater role for
religion in public life, Sen. Joseph Lieberman said he meant it as
a matter of public discourse, not public policy, adding that he
does not consider those who are not religious to be amoral or unfit
for public office.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really less a matter of programs or legislation than
it is of giving respect to the constructive role that faith can
play in the lives of individuals, and in the lives of the
community,'' Lieberman, the Democratic vice-presidential nominee,
said in an interview aboard his campaign plane late Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman spoke a few hours after the Anti-Defamation League
issued a statement criticizing his emphasis on his faith and saying
religion should have no place in the political arena. With that
criticism, one of the nation's most prominent Jewish groups was
publicly chastising the first Jew to be nominated by a major party
for national office.
</P>
<P>
   Although Lieberman knew of the Anti-Defamation League's
statement when he gave the interview on Monday night, his aides
said on Tuesday that he did not then know its details. The senator
declined to discuss the statement Tuesday, ignoring reporters'
shouted questions as he hurried from a convention of the
Communications Workers of America that he had addressed here.
</P>
<P>
   But his campaign spokeswoman, Kiki McLean, said, ``He is someone
who always expresses his support of tolerance and separation of
church and state, and believes the ADL does a lot of good work, and
in this instance respectfully disagrees.''
</P>
<P>
   Giving a homily at a church in Detroit on Sunday, Lieberman said
that ``there must be a place for faith in America's public life,''
and quoted John Adams and George Washington, linking both the
founding of the nation and morality to religion. He offered much
the same sentiment on Monday at a breakfast with religious leaders
in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   But in the interview on Monday night, he said he had not meant
to suggest that irreligious people cannot be moral. ``Religion in
my opinion can be, and in my opinion usually is, a source of good
behavior,'' he said. ``But two things: I know religious people who
I consider not to be moral, and I also know people who are not
religious who I consider to be extremely moral. So, you know, I'm
talking here about probabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would object to an atheist's being president, he
said, ``Personally, no, if I thought it was a good person'' _ a
more liberal stance, polls show, than a great majority of Americans
take.
</P>
<P>
   He said he respected former Sen. Bill Bradley's refusal to talk
about his religious views during the presidential primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Talk of religion is nothing new for Lieberman, who made it part
of his previous campaigns and wrote about it in a book published
this year, ``In Praise of Public Life.'' At virtually every stop in
this campaign, he mentions his own devout faith and the faith of
Vice President Al Gore, frequently telling his listeners that
people of all religions are ``children of the same God.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore and Gov. George W. Bush have both talked about
religion in interviews and debates, Lieberman has gone further,
making his faith a central part of his stump speech.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's comments have inspired a debate on the role of
religion in politics, raising concerns in some quarters about
maintaining the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday's New York Times/ABC News Webcast, ``Political
Points,'' the Rev. Barry W. Lynn, executive director of Americans
United for the Separation of Church and State, accused both parties
of using religion to pander for votes.
</P>
<P>
   On the same Webcast, Forest Montgomery of the National
Association of Evangelicals said the media applied a double
standard, treating Lieberman more gently than they would a
conservative Christian saying the same things. But Montgomery
added, ``Evangelicals are very comfortable with everything the
senator's been saying.''
</P>
<P>
   In Albuquerque, N.M., on Tuesday, Gore defended Lieberman in a
series of interviews with local television stations around the
country. ``He also believes as I do in separation of church and
state,'' Gore told KSDK in St. Louis. ``I believe in what he's
saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman and his aides have been quick to draw distinctions
between his own comments and efforts by some Christian
conservatives to mingle religion and politics, noting, for
instance, that he supports abortion rights and opposes organized
prayer in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's a difference here between respecting faith and
feeling free to talk about the way in which it informs and benefits
American life, and talking about it in a way that may make some
people feel excluded,'' Lieberman said in the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand that some people who are particularly sensitive
to religious discrimination may get uncomfortable when people talk
about their faith, but I find it both informative and
encouraging,'' he added. When religious Christians discuss their
faith, as Gore has done repeatedly, ``I don't feel excluded by
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think somehow for various reasons we either started to talk
about religion in ways that were divisive, or we stopped talking
about it altogether,'' he said. ``I think we lost something
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, he put his views in the context of the nation's
founders, who he said valued both faith and religious freedom. They
saw that in a society in which government does not tightly control
people, ``it's helpful to have other sources of good behavior,'' he
said, ``and so religion is one of those. So in that sense, it is an
ally of government in trying to create a good society.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
