<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-425&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAZIO SUGGESTS MRS. CLINTON LIED ABOUT HIS RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rep. Rick Lazio charged Tuesday that Hillary Rodham
Clinton had deliberately distorted his voting record in Congress,
and he prepared to unveil a new advertisement Wednesday that aides
said would feature Sen. John McCain harshly challenging Clinton's
fund-raising practices in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be a doormat,'' Lazio, a Suffolk County Republican,
declared outside Junior's Restaurant on Flatbush Avenue in
Brooklyn, where he had just consumed a breakfast of scrambled eggs,
home fries and cheesecake. ``It is fair to criticize my record. It
is not fair to make things up about my record.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio made his remarks as both candidates for the Senate
struggled to seize the high ground in the debate over who went
negative first, even as both exhibited a level of bellicosity that
is unusual coming the week before Labor Day, which traditionally
marks the start of the full-fledged campaign season.
</P>
<P>
   The state Democratic Party announced that its new ad on behalf
of Clinton began broadcasting Tuesday. It ties Lazio to Newt
Gingrich, the former House speaker, and asserts that Lazio
supported Gingrich in Congress while expressing opposition to some
of his initiatives while campaigning in New York. The ad says,
``Tell Lazio to stop playing both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Lazio complained about Clinton's campaign tactics, he
prepared to escalate his own offensive with a second attack ad in
three days. This one, an adviser said, features McCain, the Arizona
Republican who has championed campaign finance reform, asserting
that Clinton's embrace of the issue was untrustworthy given her
extensive reliance on such funds.
</P>
<P>
   McCain is a prime sponsor of legislation in the Senate that
would bar the use of so-called soft money, the largely unregulated
donations raised by party committees and outside groups. Clinton
has endorsed the bill. He has also praised Clinton this year,
saying she would be a Senate ``star'' if elected.
</P>
<P>
   The McCain ad, as well as another asserting that ``you can't
trust'' Clinton, will be the two main Lazio TV commercials on the
air leading up to Labor Day. Although the ostensible issue raised
by the McCain ad is campaign finance, aides to both candidates say
there is little evidence that New York voters are particularly
interested in that subject. The real purpose of the ad, a Lazio
adviser said, is to use a politician popular with New Yorkers to
raise questions about Clinton's credibility in an area where
Republicans and Democrats both believe that Clinton is vulnerable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both ads have long been planned, although Lazio asserted that he
was introducing them only in response to Clinton's attacks over the
last month. She has cited votes he has cast against Democratic
initiatives to provide federal financing for hiring teachers, and
to expand Medicare benefits to pay for prescription drug benefits
for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more down in the mud that they get, the more they distort
and spout untruths, the more it's going to be necessary for us to
correct our record,'' Lazio said, adding: ``You know what the story
is. She's stuck in the 40's in the polls. They can't win by being
positive. They can only win by trying to tear me down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was on a campaign fund-raising trip in Seattle on
Tuesday. Cathie Levine, her spokeswoman, challenged Lazio's
assertions. ``The day Lazio entered the race he promised to run a
positive campaign, and has launched negative attacks against
Hillary since his announcement speech,'' she said. ``Maybe it's the
drop in the polls. Maybe it's because he can't run on his record on
the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's aides have claimed that Clinton was distorting his
record; the candidate went further Tuesday, suggesting that she was
lying. Asked for examples, he noted that she had said he had voted
to cut Medicare spending, when in fact he had voted to cut
increases in Medicare spending. Republicans and Democrats have long
argued over whether it is fair to refer to that vote as a vote to
cut spending.
</P>
<P>
   With Clinton out of town, it fell to state Comptroller H. Carl
McCall and New York City Comptroller Alan G. Hevesi to continue the
first lady's attacks on Lazio's tax plan. They asserted that he had
deliberately underestimated the cost of his tax plan to distance
himself from Gov. George W. Bush's tax plan.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio attacked Clinton after stopping by Junior's, where he had
breakfast with Ruth Morris, a Democrat from Brooklyn, among others.
Morris said she did not approve of all the negative campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   But Morris also said she might vote for Lazio because she was
unhappy with Clinton's failure to enact a national health care
plan. And her enthusiasm for Lazio grew after he told her that he
would pay for her eggs and home fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in here to have breakfast _ and next thing we knew we
had an entire contingency from the press,'' Morris said. ``We asked
him to pay. And he did. First thing the Republicans have done for
me in a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
