<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 23:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-N     08-29 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-TESTAVERDE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TESTAVERDE IS READY FOR HIS CLOSE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vinny Testaverde leans back in a chair, easily crossing the legs
that are more closely scrutinized than the Rockettes'.
</P>
<P>
   It is a week before the New York Jets' regular season begins at
Green Bay on Sunday, and Testaverde responds to questions about his
Achilles' tendon and big toe with confidence brimming so fully that
he pounces on speculation about his health with all the momentum of
Venus Williams closing fast on a floating drop shot.
</P>
<P>
   Worried about the toe?
</P>
<P>
   ``Never did,'' he said. ``To be successful in this league you
have to play hurt. All the little injuries, the less serious ones,
if you can't play with those type of injuries you can't play in the
National Football League.''
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has taken a grueling road back to this level of
conviction from the season-ending Achilles' injury he sustained in
the opening game last season. It is a quality the Jets will
immediately have to rely on after an off-season of tumult.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde took fewer than 50 snaps during the preseason, and he
has not played since Aug. 12, so he has not completely shorn the
rust that still mottles him.
</P>
<P>
   His goal was not merely to play again, but to return to his
level of play in 1998, when he threw for 29 touchdowns and seven
interceptions in leading the Jets to the brink of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Testaverde moved smoothly and threw strongly in his
limited action this preseason, his numbers were unimpressive: 11 of
21 passing for 244 yards, with two interceptions _ both for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   He admits that he does not know how he will perform during the
first games. A slow start in September would not be unexpected,
especially since Testaverde is learning to live without Keyshawn
Johnson and with new receivers like Vincent Brisby and Laveranues
Coles.
</P>
<P>
   But coach Al Groh is so sure of Testaverde's readiness that he
said he had not given Testaverde's health much thought after
watching him run last week in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde said he never had a doubt about attempting a comeback
from the Achilles' injury, even when he could have wondered what he
would return to. Bill Parcells was going to the front office and
Johnson was going to Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde spent six to eight hours a day rehabilitating the
Achilles' with a dizzying prescription of whirlpool therapies,
massages, stretches and balance exercises.
</P>
<P>
   His mind was addled by the tedium and his body _ bereft of any
aerobic work _ was soft. He felt lousy, even though he was never in
pain. And when he could finally start lifting weights and running
again, his body was sore every day and he was slow. ``I went
through this period when I thought, `This is impossible,''' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the eight-month mark in his rehabilitation, Testaverde felt
his explosiveness returning, but that accomplishment was
overwhelmed that day by the concern that once the first hits from
another team came, he might be able to go no further.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know,'' Testaverde said. ``Can somebody land on the
back of my foot and everything be OK? You don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dan Marino ruptured his Achilles' tendon in 1993,
Testaverde was on the sideline with Cleveland. That was as much as
Testaverde knew about such an injury until he found himself in the
training room last year, hearing the whispers that Marino, who was
hurt at age 32, was never the same afterward. Testaverde's
ignorance was his shield.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ruptured Achilles'; it doesn't sound like much,'' Testaverde
said. ``Once it's you in that situation, you realize the severity
of it. During training camp I went out to dinner and a man came
over. He said, `The same day you did yours, I did mine.' He was in
the Marines. He can no longer perform his duties, so he's working
in a restaurant. I think about him; I think about me. He can't
perform his duties for his country because of that. Can I come
back?''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever doubts Testaverde harbored were exacerbated by the
constant irritation at the mention of his age. He will turn 37
during the season, a point that has buzzed about him like a
persistent fly.
</P>
<P>
   The backup quarterback, Ray Lucas, and running back Curtis
Martin think Testaverde is stronger now than before, because his
arm and legs are well-rested from the layoff. With each day of
practice, Lucas said, Testaverde's throws grew crisper, his
decisions grew faster. The game, as Testaverde put it, slowed down
in his mind's eye.
</P>
<P>
   He has stopped thinking about the heel and he has shelved
thoughts of retirement. Those were born of his own fears, which he
has allayed. With opening day upon him, Testaverde said he is
exhilarated.
</P>
<P>
   The critical test of his confidence came in a preseason game
against the Baltimore Ravens, when the 330-pound defensive lineman
Sam Adams grasped Testaverde from behind by his ankles and pulled
him to the ground. Adams landed on the back of Testaverde's left
heel, driving his big toe into the ground. The Jets were anxious
when Testaverde got up limping, but Testaverde had a
glass-half-full view of the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think about the heel when I got hurt,'' he said.
``All I could think about was the shooting pain in my toe. Which
was good. I'm confident in everything now, mentally and physically.
Throwing the football, taking off running, having that feeling of
dropping back in the pocket and taking a hit if I have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
