<HEADER>
A5887 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-BUYING-TRACKS-NYT     08-29 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-BUYING-TRACKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUYING SPREE AND A PLAN TO BOOST RACING 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ While horse racing's marketers have
extolled their own performances but called for more consolidation
to save the industry, two of the sport's most aggressive executives
have driven forward on parallel paths with their own solution:
buying and networking racetracks across America.
</P>
<P>
   The two are Frank Stronach, president of Magna Entertainment,
and Tom Meeker, president of Churchill Downs. Between them, they
now own 13 racetracks and control 40 percent of the market share of
racing's $13.7 billion gambling business.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Stronach and his worldwide auto-parts
company have spent more than $300 million to buy Santa Anita,
Golden Gate Fields and Bay Meadows in California, Gulfstream Park
in Florida, Remington Park in Oklahoma and Thistledown and Great
Lakes Downs in Ohio. And they make no secret of the fact that they
would like to add Monmouth Park in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs, meanwhile, has spent more than $325 million in
cash or stock to acquire Hollywood Park in California, Calder Race
Course in Florida, Ellis Park in Kentucky and Arlington
International in Illinois. Those tracks joined a company that
already included Hoosier Park in Indiana and Churchill Downs, home
of the Kentucky Derby, the premier race in the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Meeker, a 56-year-old lawyer who has been calling the shots at
Churchill Downs since 1984, arrived early in Saratoga Springs this
month for the annual Round Table Conference of racing owners and
officials on Aug. 13. The main message this year was delivered by
the National Thoroughbred Racing Association, which is still
debt-ridden in its third year as racing's ``league office.'' But
Meeker put his own goal bluntly:
</P>
<P>
   ``Our objective is to reach a critical mass, to deliver our
product to the people of the United States and, ultimately, the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   By product, he meant horse racing and the gambling that goes
with it. But Meeker said he was not threatening to crush small
tracks under the advancing armor of large tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will help the industry,'' he said, ``if we recognize that
there will be consolidation. There will be dominant players. The
smaller tracks fear that `these big boys are going to try to put us
out of business.'
</P>
<P>
   ``But Frank Stronach and the New York Racing Association group
and the other big players, we don't want to put anybody out of
business. We want them to stay in business to take our product.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach, a 67-year-old Canadian who runs his global empire from
Toronto, speaks of his racetracks as entertainment centers with
family appeal. He is also a successful horseman. His Stronach
Stables produced Red Bullet, winner of this year's Preakness. And
he has openly contested the spending and tax methods of the
National Thoroughbred Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each track will have its separate needs,'' Stronach said,
reviewing his goals. ``When I first went to Santa Anita, I noticed
that the soup in the dining room wasn't hot enough. At Gulfstream
Park, there has been some problem with the condition of the turf
course. And they have racing for only 60 days or so each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to make sure of the product you are selling. And you
can enhance it with entertainment that is appropriate and
meaningful to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach, a focused man from Austria with a great mane of white
hair, takes pride in the benefits that Magna has installed for its
employees, such as bonus payments and a voice in the company. He is
forcefully direct in manner. He wasted no time in starting major
construction projects at Santa Anita (and making sure the soup was
hot) after he bought the track last year.
</P>
<P>
   The family of racetracks operating under the banners of Meeker
and Stronach already control two essential ingredients of racing:
the horses and the betting money. Lonny Powell, the director of
racing for Magna and Stronach's chief deputy, said from his office
at Santa Anita that this was part of the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem in our industry,'' he said, ``is to
guarantee the supply of horses. It might be a stretch in some
places, but if you control racing circuits, you guarantee fuller
fields.''
</P>
<P>
   So, in the struggle to gather racetracks into circuits with
common goals, where does Magna stand?
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably, we're getting to the early part of the middle,''
Powell said. ``The first part was very accelerated. But we'll
continue as long as the moves are part of our plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our plan has three aspects. First, to achieve as much
efficiency as possible from standing tracks. Second, in markets
where it's doable, to enhance the year-round facilities of tracks
in a racing environment, tracks like Santa Anita and Gulfstream,
with their great locations. And third, to build a simulcasting
network with the tracks associated with Magna, with home betting
obviously the aim.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Stronach and Meeker have not squeezed the lemon dry.
Despite the expenditure of $325 million in cash or capital to
expand Churchill's network, Meeker said no drain on resources had
been felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of this has put a strain on our resources,'' he said.
``With the acquisition of Arlington Park this year in exchange for
stock, our debt ratio actually dropped.''
</P>
<P>
   What role will the New York Racing Association play, and what
damage may it suffer, if Stronach and Meeker keep rolling forward?
It is conceivable that the NYRA may even end up competing with
Stronach and Meeker in the bidding for New York's Off-Track Betting
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're always concerned that you can keep offering
high-quality racing,'' said Terry Meyocks, president of the NYRA,
which has a state franchise to operate the Belmont Park, Aqueduct
and Saratoga tracks. ``All we can do is try to keep offering the
best product we can. We hope we're important enough to hold our own
in any racing business, no matter who dominates it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Meyocks pointed out that the NYRA, with a 20 percent share
of the national gambling market in racing, held a special legal
position that would preclude it from joining the gold rush.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would have to change the law in New York state before we
could acquire tracks outside,'' he said. ``We're licensed to run
the three franchise tracks in New York, but none others.''
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, Stronach and Meeker keep casting their eyes and their
money coast to coast, pursuing consolidation, which they are
betting will revive horse racing before it is too late.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
