<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 23:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5889 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBO-SNIDER-LADN     08-29 1192
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SNIDER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIS RECORD MAY FALL, BUT SNIDER WILL ALWAYS BE `LORD' OF THE
DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before they are linked by numbers, which should be any day now,
they were linked by attitude.
</P>
<P>
   They are Dodgers outfielders, separated by more than four
decades. Two power hitters, whose home ballparks were nearly 3,000
miles apart, united by approach.
</P>
<P>
   Duke Snider was a Dodgers institution, one of the ``Boys of
Summer'' who brought fame, and finally, a World Series title to
Brooklyn. He spent 16 years as a Dodger.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield is a comparative Dodger newborn, in his third
season with the Dodgers, with his fourth club overall.
</P>
<P>
   It is Snider _ ``The Lord of Flatbush'' _ who has for 44 years
held the Dodgers' single-season home run record. In 1956 he led the
National League with 43 home runs, the last Dodger to do so.
</P>
<P>
   It's a record Sheffield is likely to surpass soon. He's at 40
now, with more than a month to play.
</P>
<P>
   And neither cares.
</P>
<P>
   Snider said it never meant all that much to him. Sheffield said
it really doesn't matter to him whether he sets any record.
</P>
<P>
   Their approach is the same _ it's just a stat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have mixed emotions because 43 was a number as far as
I was concerned,'' Snider said. ``Numbers weren't all that
important _ it was winning the game and winning the pennant.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield admits he knows almost nothing about Snider _ redubbed
``The Silver Fox'' when the team moved to Los Angeles _ but echoes
his sentiment about individual statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just numbers, just records,'' Sheffield said. ``It's
about wins and losses to me. Some guys like to play the game for
people to recognize their numbers. But I play to be recognized by
how many rings I can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I'm playing this game for money or awards. I
have money. I have awards. It's about wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Snider, now retired as a broadcaster, spends his summers
overlooking the Pacific from his place in Fort Bragg, a small
community four hours north of San Francisco. He spends the other
three seasons overlooking the sixth fairway on a Fallbrook golf
course.
</P>
<P>
   Life seems good for Snider, who turns 74 next month. He is in
relatively strong health following 1987 bypass surgery. He has cut
down his memorabilia signings to about five a year. He is still
married to Bev, his high school sweetheart in Compton, after 54
years. He works in a pair of Dodgers Fantasy Camps every year.
</P>
<P>
   And if Snider is something less than fanatical, he still remains
interested in the team he helped lead to two World Series titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I check and see how they do every day when I pick up the paper
and look at the box score,'' Snider said. ``I'm not what you call a
rooter. I sleep through the night if they don't, but I like to see
them win. They were my bread and butter.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Snider came West with the team when they moved to Los
Angeles, playing in the Coliseum and later collecting the first hit
at Dodger Stadium, it was in Brooklyn his legend grew.
</P>
<P>
   In the '50s, New York was home to three of the greatest center
fielders of all time _ Snider (Dodgers), Willie Mays (Giants) and
Mickey Mantle (Yankees).
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke was a five-point player,'' said Dodgers senior vice
president Tommy Lasorda, a former teammate. ``Duke was a power
hitter who could hit for average, could run, field and he could
throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Duke was an outstanding ballplayer. When they talk about
center fielders, they talk about Mantle and Mays. But, damn, you
have to put that guy in there with them. He was great.''
</P>
<P>
   Snider was often overshadowed by Mays and Mantle, though he
actually led the three in homers and RBI during the four seasons
(1954-1957) they all played full-time in New York. He hit more home
runs in the '50s (326) than any other major leaguer.
</P>
<P>
   For a man who shows little regard for personal records, he set
plenty. He is the only player to twice hit four home runs in a
single World Series ('52, '55). He became just the third player to
hit 40 or more home runs in five consecutive seasons, and Babe Ruth
and Ralph Kiner were the others.
</P>
<P>
   Snider still has the National League World Series records for
home runs (11) and RBI (26). The 389 home runs, 1,271 RBI and 814
extra-base hits he collected as a Dodger remain team records.
</P>
<P>
   Snider spent the final two years of his career with the Mets and
Giants, but while with the Dodgers took in a young, hard-throwing
right-hander who also hailed from Southern California _ Don
Drysdale.
</P>
<P>
   The two remained close friends long after their careers ended
and their duties as broadcasters (Snider with the Padres, Expos and
Dodgers) kept the miles between them.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Meyers-Drysdale said there was a mutual respect between the
two, although it could sometimes manifest in unusual ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the old-timers game, either Duke or Pee Wee (Reese) would
get up against Donny, and Donny would always knock them down,''
said Meyers-Drysdale. ``They just had this love relationship, this
respectful relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when Duke went through the card-show thing, there was
still a respect about Duke and the way he handled it.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``card-show thing'' found Snider in court. Snider and
Willie McCovey pleaded guilty to income tax evasion in 1995. Snider
admitted not reporting $100,000 in cash from card show and
memorabilia appearances from 1984-93.
</P>
<P>
   Snider was fined $5,000 and paid about $30,000 in back taxes. He
was sentenced in Brooklyn, where he took full responsibility and
apologized to his fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took some advice from the wrong person,'' Snider said.
``They said take this and don't declare it. Then they're the ones
that told the IRS they had given me X-amount of dollars. I made a
mistake. But I'm not making it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching-friendly Dodger Stadium has helped to keep his team
home run record in check _ 43 home runs being a fairly modest total
by today's standards. Only five other major-league teams have a
single-season record that's lower.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more surprised it hasn't been broken than anything else,''
Sheffield said.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield already has the Marlins' home run record. He hit 42
for Florida in 1996. Snider said he met Sheffield once while he was
Marlin, but Sheffield doesn't remember it.
</P>
<P>
   Snider said they spoke by phone last Sunday. He told Sheffield
he won't be back in Southern California for another week, so hurry
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said instead of coming to your games and be sitting there
waiting for you to do it, go ahead and get it done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said if Sheffield hasn't broken the record by the time he
returns to Fallbrook, he might come up for a game, but isn't
interested in camping out at the stadium until it falls.
</P>
<P>
   Snider said he was in Florida last week for a memorabilia show
with ex-Dodger pitcher Johnny Podres, who kidded him his record was
about to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `That's fine,''' Snider recalled. ``And then Johnny
said, `Yeah, but you've still got one record nobody is ever going
to break _ the Brooklyn Dodgers home run record.''' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
