<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNTAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AND SO IT FLOWS: TALE OF THE CITY
</HEADLINE>
  By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The City Council speaker called a news conference at
Columbus Park in Lower Manhattan on Tuesday to illustrate vividly
the findings of a council study on drinking fountains in city
parks. It did not go exactly as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The council's Office of Oversight and Investigation had checked
the fountains in more than 300 parks across the city and found
rusted spigots, basins littered with chicken bones and standing
water that threatened to attract mosquitoes infected by the West
Nile virus.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker, Peter F. Vallone, said 23 percent of the fountains
did not produce any water _ including the one in Columbus Park _
and 36 percent failed to dispense water properly.
</P>
<P>
   He called on the Parks Department to overhaul 1,500 of the
city's nearly 2,500 outdoor drinking fountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as hard to get a free sip of water in our parks as to
get a taxi at rush hour,'' Vallone said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not always.
</P>
<P>
   Between Monday afternoon, when word of the news conference
circulated, and Tuesday afternoon, when Vallone was intending to
try _ for the benefit of reporters and television cameras _ to get
a drink from the broken fountain in Columbus Park, something
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the news conference began, it was discovered that
the drinking fountain in Columbus Park worked just fine.
</P>
<P>
   It seems the Parks Department, wise to Vallone's plans,
dispatched plumbers to the park to make hurried overnight repairs,
denying Vallone the drama of a broken spigot.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show, if they can fix this overnight, what
they could do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Tuesday, Henry J. Stern, the parks commissioner,
said he welcomed the council survey and did not dispute its
findings. He attributed the poor condition of park fountains to
their age, which he said generally exceeded 50 years, and complex
underground plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their figures are essentially reasonable, and they have called
attention to an annoying problem,'' Stern said. ``Now it is in
their hands to provide a remedy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
