<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAIN-SURPRISE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    LOS ANGELES WAKES UP TO WET MORNING
</HEADLINE>
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRENT HOPKINS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A surprise shower dampened Los Angeles on Tuesday
in the first measurable August rainfall in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy skies that had been blanketing the area suddenly dropped
nearly one-third of an inch of rain in Van Nuys, the wettest spot
in the Los Angeles region, the National Weather Service reported.
Burbank recorded 0.13 of an inch and downtown Los Angeles had 0.07.
</P>
<P>
   The last time any measurable amount of rain fell in August was
1990, when a half-inch was recorded in Burbank, Weather Service
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   It last rained in Los Angeles on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Weather Service predicted that the storm would clear out
late Tuesday with partial clouds and fog this morning, and clear
skies in the afternoon through the rest of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Weather Service officials said the cause of Tuesday's shower was
a low-pressure system.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an upper-level low-pressure area sitting off the edge
of the coast pulling up a lot of the moisture from the south,''
said Ray Tanabe, weather information specialist.
</P>
<P>
   Klaus Weickmann of the National Weather Service's Climate
Diagnostic Center in Washington, D.C., said it could have just as
easily not rained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly random fluctuation that doesn't have to have a
particular cause. Weather patterns are a chaotic phenomena. We
can't always say that there's a particular reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The rain offered little relief from the fire danger brought on
by a dry summer, said Bob Collis, spokesman for the Los Angeles
Fire Department, dismissing the rain as minor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A little bit of rain doesn't make too much difference, you
need copious amounts like El Nino. As soon as it dries out, we'll
be back where we started.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after three years of typically eccentric El Nino and
La Nina conditions, there are signs the weather phenomena are
calming, according to the latest satellite data from the
U.S.-French TOPEX/Poseidon mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that the global climate system is finally
recovering from the past three years of dramatic swings from the
extra-large El Nino of 1997-1998, which was followed by two
unusually cool and persistent La Nina years,'' said oceanographer
William Patzert of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's rain was a major inconvenience for those on the
freeways in the morning. Between 5 and 9 a.m., the California
Highway Patrol recorded 45 collisions, said Officer Frank Sansone.
Though no fatalities were attributed to the rain, the number of
crashes was up 71 percent from the same period last week.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
