<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESL-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY'S COLLEGES TURN AWAY IMMIGRANTS WHO DON'T MASTER ENGLISH 
</HEADLINE>
  By KAREN W. ARENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Business was brisk on Monday at City College's
English-as-a- second-language department _ the headquarters for
teaching English to foreign students.
</P>
<P>
   There was Rachid Haddoury, a husky 27-year-old who had two years
of college in Morocco before coming to New York. He wanted to
enroll as an engineering student at City College of New York. Yet
when placement tests showed that his English reading skills were
still weak and his writing only somewhat better, it was not clear
whether the college would offer him classes in English as a second
language. The college has begun to discourage students from
enrolling until their English is better.
</P>
<P>
   Next came Vladimir Cuevas, a 19-year-old student from the
Dominican Republic who studied English at an Educational
Opportunity Center run by the State University of New York on 125th
Street in Manhattan for a year. He did not do well on the reading
or writing tests either. When he came to register this week, he was
told he needed better mastery of English before he could enroll.
</P>
<P>
   They were part of the steady stream of students on Monday in the
office of Elizabeth Rorschach, the department chairwoman, sitting
in the black armchair next to her desk, pleading to join intensive
classes in English as a second language, or ESL as they are known.
</P>
<P>
   Teaching immigrants has long been a primary mission for City
College, where fewer than 44 percent of the incoming freshmen in
1998 spoke English as their first language.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of ESL students has been slipping at City College
and other parts of City University in recent years. Last fall, City
College filled 17 class sections with foreign students learning
English. Now it is budgeting for five.
</P>
<P>
   College officials say they are seeing fewer applicants needing
English as a second language. But the college is also barring
students like Cuevas, the Dominican student with relatively low
scores, saying the students need to improve their English first.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, such students might have been allowed to enter the
college and spend several years improving their English while they
took college courses. Now, City University has told its senior
colleges to reduce the number of less-prepared students, and that
includes some of those who know the least English.
</P>
<P>
   Under university policies being phased in this year and next,
the senior colleges are not supposed to enroll students who have
not passed all of the university's placement exams. Foreign
students who have attended high school outside the United States
are exempt from this policy; they may enroll without having passed
the reading or writing placement tests. But once enrolled, they are
given only a year to pass them.
</P>
<P>
   That is a stiff challenge for foreign-born students weak in
English. So the colleges are trying to enroll those who are closest
to passing and are advising the rest to attend adult education
classes or the university's language immersion institutes, so they
can improve their English without using up financial aid or
struggling so hard in classes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the new university guidelines are not binding on City
College until next year, college officials have been trying to
improve the caliber of their student body anyway. When officials
judged which students had a real chance of academic success, those
not ready for the highest level of ESL were not included.
</P>
<P>
   But success can be difficult to predict, especially for students
who speak limited English. And there are disagreements at the
college and around the university about how selective to be.
</P>
<P>
   Rorschach and some other faculty members are concerned that the
university standard is unnecessarily harsh; because teenagers and
adults can take many years to perfect a new language, it may be
unfair to judge students by whether they are likely to pass
university placement tests in a single year, they say.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Weinbaum, a City College mechanical engineering
professor, said a recent review of the approximately 1,500 students
who had graduated from the engineering school between 1993 and 1997
found that nearly a third had required instruction in English as a
second language.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the students who came to Rorschach's office were
eager to be put in intensive English classes, a few, like Kyah
Thuya, a student from Myanmar, were dismayed to find that they were
considered barely qualified to enter City College and would have to
take 10 hours a week of noncredit courses, probably for a year or
more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to waste time,'' said Thuya, frowning, after
talking with Rorschach. He said he had spent two years at the
Newcomers School in Queens after arriving in New York in 1998 and
passed the Regents English exam with a score of 66.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Espaillat, a transfer student from the Dominican Republic
who entered City College last year, t has failed the writing test
three times and says he must pass it before the spring semester if
he is to stay enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I will make it if I work hard,'' he said on Monday,
adding that he was thinking about paying for private lessons to
help.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my life,'' he said. ``I don't want to work as cashier
or in grocery store. I want to keep going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
