<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ASTROS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEITER LEAVES WITH AN INJURY, AND THE METS FALL TO THE ASTROS,
11-1 
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Al Leiter pitched and Moises Alou swung and a foul
ball came next. It happened nine times in one at-bat in the third
inning Tuesday night, and if it was painful for a Mets fan to
watch, imagine how Leiter felt.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' left-hander was already in pain, with a strained
muscle in his backside. Then Alou delivered a single that skipped
up the middle and scored a run, continuing a torturous four-run
inning that kicked off the Houston Astros' 11-1 victory. Leiter is
not expected to miss his next start, but he left after that third
inning, his shortest start of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Derek Bell also left the game with an injury,
departing in the eighth after he banged his left knee against the
padded wall down the right field line in pursuit of a foul fly.
Bell suffered a contusion and X-rays were negative; he is
day-to-day.
</P>
<P>
   The only remaining drama after the Astros built their 4-0 lead
was whether Atlanta would lose and thus preserve the Mets' tie for
first place in the National League East. The Braves were beaten,
4-2, by the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter lost to Houston for the second time this month, his
record dropping to 14-6. Wade Miller, the Astros' rookie
right-hander, pitched a complete-game five-hitter, improving to
3-5.
</P>
<P>
   The game was marred by sloppy play; the Mets made three errors,
including one by Lenny Harris, whose shaky fielding at third base
earned mock cheers from fans who had little else to make noise
about.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter felt discomfort warming up, and it worsened during the
game. But it was hard to tell anything was wrong until the third
inning, which would have been painful enough for him without an
injury.
</P>
<P>
   After Roger Cedeno walked with one out, Julio Lugo smacked a
liner toward Harris, who has been an important contributor for the
Mets but had not started in five games. Robin Ventura is healthy
but has struggled, with one hit in his last 16 at-bats, and Manager
Bobby Valentine gave him the night off even though Houston started
a right-hander.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have an answer,'' Valentine said, when asked why
Ventura has struggled, ``and it's not because I haven't given it an
awful lot of thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura has been fine defensively, though there's no telling if
he would have caught Lugo's line drive. In any case, it deflected
off Harris's glove and rolled into foul territory, good for a
double. Jeff Bagwell came up next and bounced a single up the
middle, putting the Astros ahead, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo walked, putting runners at first and second, and
Alou's killer at-bat came next. The Astros' right fielder saw 11
pitches and did not swing and miss at any. He fouled off the first
four pitches, then took a pitch as Bagwell stole third.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter tried everything, but Alou kept fouling off pitches _
seven in all after the second strike _ before he bounced a ball off
the mound and through the middle for a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching coach Dave Wallace came to the mound, and Leiter
stayed in to strike out Tony Eusebio. But Chris Truby singled in a
run, and Tim Bogar tapped a ball toward third. It was the classic
Ventura play _ the third baseman charges, barehands it and flings
it to first, falling over as he throws. But Harris, not Ventura,
was at third, and his throw was too late to catch Bogar.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth run scored, and after Leiter got Miller to ground to
Harris, the left-hander's night was over. Pat Mahomes batted for
Leiter after two singles opened the Mets' third. But Mahomes popped
up his bunt attempt, Darryl Hamilton struck out and Bell grounded
out to strand two runners.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes's night was just as rocky when he took the mound. The
Astros scored before Mahomes got an out, on a single, a stolen base
and a Lugo double, and another run came in on a sacrifice fly. That
put the Astros ahead, 6-0, and they could have had another run in
the fifth, but the Mets successfully appealed a play at third,
claiming Truby broke for home too soon on a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   No matter _ Houston had another big inning left, scoring three
times in the sixth in a rally touched off by Bagwell's 40th homer.
Mahomes was lifted after allowing five runs in three innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jerrod Riggan, a 26-year-old right-handed closer, was called up
from at Class AA Binghamton, arriving at Shea Stadium in the middle
of the game. Riggan worked a 1-2-3 seventh inning, getting three
groundouts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
