<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-KAPLAN0830-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN president Kaplan will leave network
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - CNN will announce the departure today of Richard A.
Kaplan, president of CNN-U.S.
</P>
<P>
   The move is part of a reorganization of upper management at CNN
News Group, which includes CNN International, CNNfn and CNN-SI.
</P>
<P>
   The exact scenario of Kaplan's leaving was not available Tuesday
night and CNN executives would not talk on the record. Kaplan could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, head of CNN's domestic channel, is scheduled to announce
his departure at an executive meeting today. Sid Bedingfield, CNN
executive vice president and Kaplan's key lieutenant, is expected
to be named interim president.
</P>
<P>
   Other CNN management changes are expected, including the naming
of Phil Kent, a financial executive from Turner International, as
chief operating officer of CNN, and a promotion for Eason Jordan,
president of international networks and one of CNN's key movers.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN reorganization, which has been in the works for some
time, is designed to better position the news network in the
changing world of media and the Internet. CNN is a key part of the
pending America Online-Time Warner merger and the network's
expansion will be tied closely to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan, 53, was brought in three years ago to revitalize
CNN-U.S. and raise the network's ratings. Although he instituted
major changes that were praised by analysts _ such as hiring Jeff
Greenfield as a political commentator, building a more modern
newsroom and eliminating a lot of repeated news _ CNN's ratings
have been down about 35 percent all year, compared to 1999. In
addition, cable competitor Fox News Channel has been gaining ground
on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   During CNN's 20th anniversary celebration in May, CNN Newsgroup
chairman Tom Johnson blamed the ratings slump on an unusually
lengthy period of slow news. ``When there is no news, our audience
is very weak,'' Johnson said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson hired Kaplan in 1997 from ABC News, where he had earned
a reputation as a tough, respected and sometimes intimidating
executive producer of Ted Koppel's ``Nightline.'' He was charged
with making the network sharper, better and higher-rated.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, the CNN staff divided into pro- and
anti-Kaplan factors. He moved some anchors aside and shook up the
production staff. Anchors called the 6-foot-7-inch Kaplan ``T Rex''
behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   One of his first major moves was the launch of the newsmagazine
``NewsStand'' in July 1998. Originally conceived as a joint effort
with Time Warner magazines Time, Fortune and Entertainment Weekly,
Kaplan intended the program to be ``appointment television'' that
viewers would turn to even when there was no major news story.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan thought so highly of it that for the first time, actor
James Earl Jones changed his announcement from ``This is CNN'' to
``This is CNN NewsStand.''
</P>
<P>
   But the program exploded on launch with a story about Operation
Tailwind, a U.S. military mission in Laos in 1970. CNN alleged U.S.
soldiers used nerve gas and targeted U.S. defectors. Peter Arnett,
one of CNN's heroes of the Persian Gulf War coverage, was the
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   The outcry from the military was loud and sustained. CNN ordered
an investigation and soon retracted the story and apologized. One
key producer was allowed to resign, two others were fired and
Arnett was barely used again, until finally his contract was not
renewed.
</P>
<P>
   Many veterans at CNN blamed Kaplan, who had worked hard on
``NewsStand,'' for the fiasco. ``NewsStand'' eventually evolved
into little more than the 10 p.m. CNN news block.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan also oversaw the building of CNN's new newsroom in 1998.
The $7.5 million project improved CNN's on-air look and gave relief
to staffers, who previously had been crammed into close quarters.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Kaplan launched ``The World Today,'' the 8 p.m.
newscast anchored by Wolf Blitzer, Joie Chen and Jim Moret, again
with great fanfare and talk of it being CNN's ``flagship''
newscast. When a hurricane threatened the East Coast or there was a
big news story, the ratings soared. But as has always been the case
for CNN, when the story went away, the audience went away.
</P>
<P>
   Through all of these launches, remakes and attempts to boost
ratings without sacrificing CNN's credibility, Kaplan was the
source of constant rumors inside CNN that he was on the way out.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1999, though, he survived a run-in with Lou Dobbs, the
powerful ``Moneyline'' anchor and friend of Ted Turner, and emerged
triumphant with Dobbs leaving CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Kaplan's crowning moment at CNN was the 20th anniversary in May.
He helped assemble a huge roster of VIP speakers and guests, and
took particular joy in planning the blow-out party in Philips Arena
with Diana Ross and the Supremes providing entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not clear how much of a role CNN's ratings
decline this year played in Kaplan's departure, it's likely that he
would have been seen as victorious if the network's ratings had
risen.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallways at CNN behind the scenes, there are large framed
graphs that chart the ratings through the years, showing peaks (the
Gulf War, the O.J. Simpson trial) and valleys (the rest of the
time).
</P>
<P>
   During his three years at CNN, Kaplan refused to hang one in his
office. He said last year: ``I actually detest those graphs.''
</P>
