<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 23:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5902 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-WHITMAN-NYT     08-29 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-WHITMAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN PRESENTS HER GOALS BEFORE THE ELECTION WHIRLWIND 
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   TRENTON, N.J. _ Cautioning that
election-year politics should not be allowed to overshadow New
Jersey's pressing public policy issues, Gov. Christe Whitman
challenged legislators on Tuesday to enact modest increases in
financing for several health care programs and to tighten campaign
finance restrictions when they begin their fall session next week.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters at a briefing in the State House, the
governor unveiled her legislative wish list for the fall: an
additional $25 million to expand the state's prescription drug plan
for the elderly; $17 million to allow more low-income families to
qualify for the Family Care health insurance program; and at least
$10 million to increase the amount the state reimburses doctors who
treat Medicaid patients.
</P>
<P>
   In a proposal that may encounter opposition from legislators,
Whitman also offered campaign finance restrictions that would force
all advocacy groups that advertise for or against candidates to
identify their members and donors.
</P>
<P>
   During her seven years as governor, Whitman has made it a ritual
to publicly release her legislative priorities in January, when she
delivers her State of the State message and makes budget proposals.
But the governor, who must step down in January 2002 because of
term limits, said she broke with tradition this year because she
did not want the presidential race, or the political jousting
between the legislators who hope to succeed her, to unduly dominate
the state's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though it's a big election-cycle year, there's time to
get some of these issues out of the way,'' Whitman said.
</P>
<P>
   With just 16 months remaining in her term, Whitman said she was
determined to strengthen some of the policies she has championed
since taking office in 1994. She asked that the Family Care
program, which was enacted last year to help low-income residents
afford health care, receive additional financing to allow all
families with an income of up to $10,000 to qualify. The governor
said it was crucial to raise the cutoff limit from its current
level of $8,000 because many of the people who have left the
state's welfare rolls in recent years do not qualify for coverage
now and have less incentive to remain in the work force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're so focused on welfare-to-work and making it work,'' she
said. ``We need to remove barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   But the two leaders of the Legislature _ Donald T. DiFrancesco,
the Senate president, and Jack Collins, the Assembly speaker _ are
both vying for the Republican nomination for governor in 2001, and
Whitman acknowledged that they are likely to exert more power over
the legislative agenda during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco, for instance, recently announced a proposal for
property tax relief and is scheduled to release a health care
package on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was pleased with much of DiFrancesco's plan,
especially a provision that would allow patients to sue health
maintenance organizations if they receive substandard care.
</P>
<P>
   She said she would also ask legislators to form a panel to help
patients through the complex process of challenging decisions by
HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she hoped that the election year would help marshal
public support for her campaign finance proposals, which would
require more public disclosure by donors and advocacy groups and
eliminate the state's matching funds for contributions from
out-of-state sources. But the governor did not push for some of the
more sweeping proposals to overhaul the state's campaign finance
laws, like limiting expenditures in local races or reducing the
$30,000 donation limits to political action committees controlled
by New Jersey legislative leaders.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
