<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORINE NAMED TO U.S. TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Galaxy midfielder Sasha Victorine had just
finished training Tuesday when he got the word from team
administrator Eddie Hidalgo _ he's going to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Victorine, named an alternate on the U.S. U-23 Olympic team two
weeks ago while fellow Galaxy teammates Danny Califf and Peter
Vagenas were named to the team, is going to Sydney after all.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Soccer officials will make it official this afternoon.
Victorine will replace Chicago's Chris Armas, who strained his knee
Aug. 16 while playing a World Cup qualifier against Barbados.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Armas' injury, it has been a waiting game for
Victorine, who will play his final regular-season game with the
Galaxy tonight against San Jose at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   After that, he'll join Califf and Vagenas for Olympic training
in Chula Vista before leaving for Sydney on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   All three Galaxy Olympians will miss the final two
regular-season games and at least the first round of the MLS
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an exciting feeling to get the word,'' said Victorine.
``And it's relief at the same time. It's a big weight off my
shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep it off my mind as much as I could, but it was
impossible with everyone talking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's great news for Victorine, it's another tough blow for
the Galaxy (13-8-8, 47 points), which is trying to catch Western
Division-leading Kansas City (14-7-8, 50 points). The Wizards lead
by three points (one full game) with three games to play.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, the Galaxy is without starters Cobi Jones
(U.S.), Luis Hernandez (Mexico) and Mauricio Cienfuegos (El
Salvador) tonight. All three are in training for World Cup
qualifiers on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   At least the Earthquakes (6-15-8, 26 points) helped even things
out. San Jose is without seven players _ Ronald Cerritos, Wade
Barrett, Richard Mulrooney, Giovanni Savarese, Jimmy Conrad,
Mauricio Solis and Scott Bower _ because of national team
commitments, injuries or suspensions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a nice change to play someone else that misses some
players,'' Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``But for us, since the
deal with Luis went down, we've only had 10 days where we have had
the whole team together. That's not an excuse, but it's been hard
to establish rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why it's a surprise the Galaxy is still within striking
distance of K.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a surprise considering how often we have turned down
opportunities to catch them,'' said Schmid. ``We have had numerous
chances, but every time we get presented with an opportunity we
say, `No thank you.'''
</P>
<P>
   With strikers Victorine and Jones gone, Schmid will audition
Sebastian Vorbe and Seth George up front. One of these two will
earn a starting nod during the playoffs with Victorine lost to the
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our depth has not shown itself up front,'' said Schmid. ``But
I've got to start somebody up there.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
