u k BC-EDIT-RAY-NYT     08-29 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-RAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RAY'S ILL-TIMED REPORT 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Aug. 30:
</P>
<P>
   From the moment he succeeded Kenneth Starr as independent
counsel, Robert W. Ray has been aware of the need to conclude the
investigations of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton in a
fair and timely way, without needlessly disrupting the campaign
season. Ray has dribbled out reports on two elements of a broad
inquiry that has lasted more than five years and cost $50 million.
Now, according to a story by Neil A. Lewis in Tuesday's Times, Ray
plans to deliver the third and potentially most controversial
report in mid-September or shortly thereafter _ in other words,
just when the New York senatorial contest between Mrs. Clinton and
Rep. Rick Lazio is kicking into high gear.
</P>
<P>
   This page has long supported a full investigation of Whitewater
and all the other unresolved allegations involving Bill and Hillary
Clinton that disappeared from public view during the Lewinsky
scandal. In March, Ray reported on allegations that the White House
had improperly collected confidential FBI files, which he
attributed to a bureaucratic foul-up. In June, he reported on Mrs.
Clinton's role in the firing of seven White House travel office
employees. Though he found no grounds for prosecution, Ray was
correctly critical, in our view, of Mrs. Clinton's sworn statements
that she had nothing to do with the dismissals.
</P>
<P>
   The third report will deal with the allegations that originally
got everyone's attention, mainly that the Clintons had used their
influence during the president's years as governor to prop up a
failing Arkansas savings and loan, and that Mrs. Clinton in
particular had not been fully candid about her role. Those issues
had been raised initially by investigative reports in the Times.
</P>
<P>
   But if the independent counsel had the evidence to bring a
criminal indictment against Mrs. Clinton on Whitewater, he should
have and would have done so by now. At this point, given Ray's
inability to bring indictments, the need for an orderly election
overrides the need for a detailed report summing up the
prosecutor's findings. In such a report, Ray is almost certain to
pass judgment on Mrs. Clinton's behavior and subsequent testimony,
much as he did in the Travelgate report. It is because of this that
fundamental questions of timing and fair play arise.
</P>
<P>
   Ray argues that a mid-September release will leave plenty of
time for comment and rebuttal. This ignores political reality. Ray
has had months to bring a prosecution or to get information of
persuasive political importance before the voters. In the absence
of stunning new information worthy of prosecution, he should stand
aside and let the voters decide based on the existing voluminous
public record. If Ray cares at all about his credibility, and about
whether the public sees his report as an objective document or a
time bomb lobbed at Mrs. Clinton's campaign, he will delay until
after the campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
