<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-29 23:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5907 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-29 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S MARTIN HOPES FOR BETTER THINGS THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The book about Kenyon Coleman's 1999 season would
be called ``When Bad Teams Happen to Good Players.'' If anybody had
bothered to write a book about such a forgettable season.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman is too pleasant a fellow to say that about his
teammates. But I'm not.
</P>
<P>
   Until last year, Coleman, the large-but-likeable defensive
lineman and UCLA co-captain, had never played on a team with a
losing record. In fact, he'd never played on a team that failed to
win a championship of some sort, not in three seasons at Alta Loma
High in San Bernardino County and not in two Rose Bowl seasons in
college.
</P>
<P>
   The only ribbing he'd ever had to endure was the most flattering
sort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember teasing him during his sophomore year, when it
looked like we were on our way to the (national) championship, that
he was going to win titles in both high school and college, and
that would make him kind of unique,'' said Michael Coleman,
Kenyon's older brother, who is a UCLA football team manager.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Bruins' 20-win streak ended disastrously with losses to
Miami and Wisconsin at the end of the 1998 season, and they went
4-7 in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it hurt him pretty bad when we lost last year,''
Michael said. ``We would go home, and people would be telling him,
`You guys are sorry.' It was real hard on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman could take satisfaction in personal achievement. He
finished the year with a strong game (nine tackles) against USC,
and was named second-team All-Pac-10 by the conference coaches. But
the USC game was a defeat, and the team finished ninth in the
Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Not much satisfaction in that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really separate (team and individual) things,''
Michael said. ``People tell him, `You did this and that,' and he
says, `Whatever.' He's a team player.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, 6-foot-6 and 280 pounds, did a lot of this and that in
his junior season, but none of it was enough to make winners of the
Bruins. Their defense ranked ninth in the Pac-10 and their offense
wasn't any better in the first year after Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt I was playing up to my ability, but when you're in that
situation, you always feel you could do more to help the team,''
Kenyon said.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman's team orientation probably began early in life. He's a
member of a large family, with a brother and three sisters, all
collegians. His father, Johnny, is a retired IRS auditor, and his
mother, Patsy, took care of the kids.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny was a strict father (was the IRS thing a tip-off?) who
made church attendance mandatory. Kenyon still gets on his knees
and prays in the locker room before games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenyon would score 50 points in a basketball game,'' Michael
said, ``and our dad would humble him and tell him, `You need to
work with your teammates more.'''
</P>
<P>
   If only it worked that way in football, where even the best
player is at the mercy of his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, 21, is the best player on the UCLA team that is
unranked as it opens its season against No.3 Alabama on Saturday at
the Rose Bowl. The Sporting News rates him All-Pac-10 and
second-team All-America. Draftniks size him up as a first-round
pick for the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts see his talent even though his statistics (50 tackles, 3
sacks last year) are unspectacular.
</P>
<P>
   This year his numbers should grow. After switching from end to
tackle each time UCLA went to the nickel defense in 1999, making
him more susceptible to double-teams by opposing blockers, he'll be
at end on every play in 2000, free to show off his pass-rushing
ability.
</P>
<P>
   The defense as a whole is supposed to be improved. Coleman sees
the whole team improving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last season started out with the handicapped (parking) thing,
and then we had a lot of injuries,'' he said in the campus athletic
offices. ``You felt kind of helpless. You'd think, `If we fixed
this one thing, it would get better.' But you couldn't do that
because so many things went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman thinks the Bruins, healthy and more experienced, have
top-15 potential. If he's right, he'll have a much happier season.
</P>
<P>
   Top 15 means never having to hear you're sorry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Kevin Modesti's column appears in the Daily News three days a week.
He can be reached at (818) 713-3616. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
