<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-TRADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NELSON, MAVERICKS GET THEIR BIG MAN IN LAETTNER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Two weeks after helping foil a four-team, 11-player
trade involving Patrick Ewing and Vin Baker, Dallas Mavericks
coach/general manager Don Nelson finally got his man.
</P>
<P>
   After Nelson convinced the Detroit Pistons they were getting a
raw deal in a proposed four-team trade, the Mavericks reaped the
benefits Tuesday by acquiring Christian Laettner and Terry Mills
from the Pistons in exchange for forwards Cedric Ceballos and John
Wallace, point guard Eric Murdock and $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Laettner and Mills fill the Mavericks' need for more big bodies,
and they have the Pistons to thank for this deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``That earlier four-team deal would have been the worst trade
we've ever seen for Detroit,'' Nelson said Tuesday from his
off-season home in Hawaii. ``They were an hour from putting that
thing to bed, but we gave them a reason to take a second look.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of phone calls and a lot of hard work. But the
bottom line is we got a couple of good players and Detroit made a
much better deal than they would have.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner, 31, is a natural power forward who played the past two
seasons for the Pistons. The eight-year veteran _ he was the third
overall pick in the 1992 draft by Minnesota _ averaged 12.2 points
and 6.7 rebounds while starting all 82 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he likes the idea of starting Laettner at center
because Shawn Bradley is prone to foul difficulties whenever he
starts. But he also said Bradley will start some at center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to be in control of that matchup as a coach,'' Nelson
said. ``But I think Shawn and Christian will do what's best for the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Mills, he also doubles as a power forward and center and
has a deft shooting touch from three-point range. Last year Mills
started 78 of the 82 games he played for the Pistons and averaged
6.7 points and 4.8 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Ceballos was the principal figure the Mavericks lost in the
trade. Last year Ceballos was third on the team in scoring (16.6),
led the Mavericks in rebounds (6.7) and finished tied for third for
the NBA's Sixth Man Award.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace and Murdock were acquired earlier this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Mavericks owner Mark Cuban said he didn't bring Laettner in to
be a savior, adding that he'll also back up Gary Trent at power
forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll get a lot of minutes and he'll get a lot of shots, just
like Ced did,'' Cuban said. ``So we're ready for him to contribute,
but not to be the focal point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Christian is the absolute student of the game. I think he'll
really enjoy the sets that we run; they're not really complicated
and they give everybody on the court a chance to excel.''
</P>
<P>
   For salary-cap purposes, it helped, too, that Laettner is in the
final year of a contract that pays him $6.725 million this season.
Meanwhile, Mills, 32, signed a three-year contract with the Pistons
before Tuesday's trade.
</P>
<P>
   However, only the first year of the contract ($1.4 million) is
guaranteed, meaning the Mavericks can dump him after this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban said Tuesday's trade was held up for almost two days
because some other teams were trying to break it up. Cuban added
that Laettner telephoned to tell him how excited he was to sign
with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Both Laettner and Mills come from a winning pedigree, albeit on
the collegiate level. Mills played a key role on the Michigan squad
that captured the 1989 NCAA title, and Laettner helped guide Duke
to NCAA championships in 1991 and '92.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago the Pistons were set to receive spare parts David
Wingate, Vernon Maxwell, Greg Foster, Tyronn Lue, Vladimir Stepania
and John Celestand and draft picks in a four-team trade with
Seattle, New York and the Los Angeles Lakers. The Sonics would have
received Ewing with Baker going to the Knicks and Laettner to the
Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   But Nelson, who coveted Laettner, got in the middle of it, and
the rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a coup because of two things,'' Nelson said of Tuesday's
events. ``First of all, we got Laettner. And second, we messed up
the big trade and kept Seattle from getting better and the Lakers
from getting better.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
