<SLUG> BC-EDIT-ENDORSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CONGRESSIONAL ENDORSEMENTS 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
  The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 30:
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congress has become a crucial battleground this election year
with Republicans trying to strengthen their slim majority in the
House and Democrats battling to overturn it. New Yorkers are
beginning to see some evidence of this struggle in several key
primaries to be held September 12.
</P>
<P>
   Southern Suffolk County, 2nd District.: The seat relinquished by
Republican Rep. Rick Lazio to run for the Senate has become one of
the key swing districts nationally for both parties. On the
Republican side, Joan Johnson, town clerk of Islip, offers
Republicans a high-profile choice over Robert Walsh, a retired
banker. Johnson, an African-American, was featured prominently at
Republican convention. With her strong community credentials and
moderate views on social issues, Johnson would be the better choice
for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic primary pits two solid candidates against one
another _ David Bishop, minority leader of the Suffolk County
Legislature, and Steven Israel, majority leader of the Huntington
Town Board. Bishop has a number of key party endorsements, but we
recommend Israel for his broader knowledge of national and
international affairs and his ability to forge bipartisan
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn-Queens, 9th District.: After a promising first term,
Rep. Anthony Weiner is being challenged in the Democratic primary
by City Councilman Noach Dear. Weiner has fought energetically for
gun control, noise abatement of airlines and relief for abused
women. Both candidates support campaign finance reform. Weiner
voted for the Shays-Meehan bill last year, and Dear promises to
support it if elected.
</P>
<P>
   Dear, an ardent conservative on many issues including abortion
and gay rights, is also listed on the Republican line in this
district. On the Democratic line, we recommend Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn, 10th District.: Rep. Edolphus Towns is being
challenged by Barry Ford, a Harvard-trained lawyer who did well
against the congressman in a three-way race two years ago. Towns
has a powerful organization in this district, but after 18 years,
his record in Congress has been minimal and his support for tobacco
and other special interests is troubling. For that reason, we
endorse Ford, an energetic community activist who wants more
educational improvements, school construction and an empowerment
zone for the area.
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn, 11th District.: Una Clarke, who cannot run for
re-election to the City Council, has turned to the district seat
now being held by her former mentor, Rep. Major Owens, who has
represented the area since 1982. Owens has not kept up with his
constituent services, making him vulnerable to someone who has been
a formidable voice in the city on women's and immigrant issues.
Both sides have turned this into an excessively bitter contest.
However, Clarke campaigns under the shadow of a $48,000 fine from
the city's campaign finance board that remains unresolved. For this
reason, we recommend Owens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
