<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EMULEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CAVEAT INVESTORS 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, Aug. 30:
</P>
<P>
   It may be tempting to put all the blame for the latest Wall
Street hoax on on the frenetic pace of today's financial and news
cycles. But this was also a case of greed taking advantage of lax
vigilance.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, investors in Emulex, a maker of fiber optic
communications equipment, shaved more than $2 billion off the
company's market value. A terse press release announced that the
company's chairman was departing, and that it would be restating
its earnings for the past two years. Trouble is, Emulex never
issued the press release. Internet Wire, an online news-release
service, had accepted the document from a third party claiming to
be Emulex's public relations firm, without checking its
authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   Some reporters who tried to reach California-based Emulex failed
because of the time difference. Presumably the bogus publicist had
wagered in the markets that the stock would plummet, as it did from
$103 to $45 Friday morning once a number of financial news outlets
carried the item. The Nasdaq market finally halted trading on the
stock at 10:33 a.m. It snapped back once trading resumed early that
afternoon, after the hoax had been revealed. But for some
investors, the damage was done.
</P>
<P>
   Internet Wire has called the perpetrator a ``very sophisticated
criminal.'' But in truth, the low-cost service and several
reputable media organizations dropped the ball; this criminal could
have been thwarted with a single phone call. Emulex and the Nasdaq
can also be faulted for not reacting more quickly to events. Surely
in this day and age investors should not lose billions to fraud
simply because California is in a different time zone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-29-00 2332EDT &QL; 
