<HEADLINE>
TWO CASINOS FINED FOR NOT PREVENTING UNDERAGE GAMBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two Kansas City casinos were fined a combined
$500,000 on Tuesday for failing to prevent a 16-year-old girl from
boarding the riverboats during a weekend gambling spree in June.
</P>
<P>
   Station Casino Kansas City and Harrah's North Kansas City Casino
&AMP; Hotel were each hit with $250,000 fines by the Missouri Gaming
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second such offense for Station Casinos Inc., which
paid a $250,000 fine in 1997 after a woman and her 12-year-old
daughter were caught playing slot machines at the company's St.
Charles, Mo., casino.
</P>
<P>
   The action Tuesday also included new allegations that Station,
on separate occasions in May and June, had let 20-year-old males
gain entrance to the Kansas City casino with false identification
and gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Station and Harrah's have 30 days to accept the fines or file
appeals that would be resolved at a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Troy A. Stremming, Station's Midwest counsel, acknowledged the
casino's responsibility but told commissioners the company may
appeal the amount of the fine, which he termed ``excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Stremming noted that company employees apprehended the underage
gamblers in all three cases and reported them to the Gaming
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Station Casinos takes this matter very seriously,'' he said.
``Unfortunately there's not a perfect system in place. Sometimes
(underage gamblers) find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   The teen-age girl, who was said to appear much older, presented
another person's driver's license to Station employees during the
evening of June 9 and was admitted to the casino. Until Sunday
morning, that ID fooled pit bosses, bartenders, card dealers and
others.
</P>
<P>
   She was with her mother at least part of that time, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on June 9 the girl also was admitted to Harrah's Mardi
Gras casino boat and gambled there, too.
</P>
<P>
   The mother, 41-year-old Carla Jean Wilson of Ash Grove, Mo.,
near Springfield, is a well-known player at area casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Clay County authorities in July charged Wilson with a class B
underage gambling misdemeanor that carries a penalty of up to six
months in the county jail and a fine of up to $500. She is
scheduled to appear in court Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Several Station employees who had contact with the girl were
fired or disciplined, but casino executives refuse to divulge how
many employees were involved.
</P>
<P>
   One of those fired was Becky Meyer. The 49-year-old Raytown
woman was the first of several employees who inspected and approved
the girl's false identification.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer said Tuesday that she was still out of work.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she sympathized with the casinos.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad that the boats have to pay,'' Meyer said. ``I think
she (Wilson) should have to pay. She knew what was right and what
was wrong. A 16-year-old should know right from wrong, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's officials had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, the commission approved the relicensing of
Harrah's North Star, the smaller of its two casino boats.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's Assistant General Manager Bill Noble disclosed to the
commission that once Harrah's completes its announced $45 million
expansion of the Mardi Gras casino about a year from now, the North
Star will close and probably replace a smaller Harrah's vessel in
Metropolis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The company had said earlier it would continue to operate both
vessels in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Noble said Kansas City customers had expressed a clear
preference for the larger Mardi Gras boat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of expanding operations by more than 1,000 slot machines
and nearly 20 table games, the change will result in only a
marginal increase in Harrah's gambling capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Noble pledged that no employees will lose their jobs in the
consolidation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
