<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKS-OFFER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMERCIAL FEDERAL TURNS DOWN BANKER'S OFFER TO BUY COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN MARGOLIES  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City banker Tom Burcham and a fellow
investor said Tuesday that thrift giant Commercial Federal Corp. of
Omaha, Neb., had rejected their offer to buy the company for what
they said was $1.3 billion in cash and stock.
</P>
<P>
   The $13 billion-asset institution owns banks and thrifts in
Nebraska, Missouri, Kansas and five other states and operates 22
branches in the Kansas City area. The company is the fourth-largest
savings and loan in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Burcham, 58, is chairman of Missouri Bank &AMP; Trust Co., a small
bank in downtown Kansas City owned by Burcham and members of his
family. He owns less than 3 percent of Commercial Federal's stock,
which he acquired when the company purchased Burcham's stake in
First United National Bank and Trust Co. of Great Bend, Kan., three
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Burcham and fellow investor John Eggemeyer III, president of the
bank investment firm Castle Creek Capital in Rancho Santa Fe,
Calif., said they had proposed to pay Commercial Federal
shareholders $18.50 in cash and 25 percent of the common stock in a
new holding company they planned to form. The two estimated their
offer to be worth $24 for each share of Commercial Federal, or
about $1.3 billion. That would represent 40 percent more than
Commercial Federal's book value.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial Federal's stock has been in the doldrums for more
than two years, closing Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange at
$16.88, down from its 52-week high of $23.81 and its April 1998
peak of $39. The stock's book value as of March 31 was $17.29.
</P>
<P>
   The two said they learned this week that their unsolicited offer
had been rejected. Burcham said Commercial Federal's chairman and
chief executive officer, William Fitzgerald, informed the two that,
based on a restructuring Commercial Federal announced earlier this
month, the company's board did not support the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald on Tuesday said Commercial Federal's board, ``along
with our financial advisers, saw (Burcham and Eggemeyer's
proposal), as submitted, as not being of substantial value for the
shareholders, given the restructuring that has been under way for
the past six months.''
</P>
<P>
   Fitzgerald declined to comment further and referred inquiries to
Merrill Lynch, Commercial Federal's investment banker. Merrill
Lynch officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial Federal, parent company of Commercial Federal Bank,
announced Aug. 15 that it expected to take a pretax restructuring
charge of $118 million to $138 million to get rid of more than $2
billion in lower-yielding assets and to pay off higher-cost
borrowings. The company also said it would expand its stock buyback
plan by up to 5.5 million shares, or 10 percent of its outstanding
stock.
</P>
<P>
   Like other financial institutions, Commercial Federal has seen
its cost of raising funds from deposits and other sources rise in
tandem with interest rates, shrinking its interest margins. The
Federal Reserve has raised interest rates six times since June
1999, from 4.75 percent to 6.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad that they've rejected this offer,'' Eggemeyer
said Tuesday. ``The company has missed its earnings estimates now
for basically two years. They've written off $250 million, or
almost 20 percent of their capital, in that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They let their chief financial officer go about nine months
ago, they let their president go about four months ago and most
recently had major defections in their community banking group. So
you've got management in turmoil, a company that has underperformed
for an extended period of time and a lot of angry shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Burcham and Eggemeyer said their offer was backed by Credit
Suisse First Boston, a major investment bank. The two said they
sent a formal proposal letter to Fitzgerald on Aug. 17 and received
Fitzgerald's negative reply, dated Aug. 24, on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both said they were concerned that Commercial Federal's board
did not give their offer a proper hearing and that shareholders
were not informed of the offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating that this offer never saw the light of day,''
Eggemeyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Burcham said he and Eggemeyer ``have no intention of trying to
do a hostile takeover'' and considered their negotiations with
Commercial Federal concluded.
</P>
<P>
   About a year ago, Franklin Mutual Advisors, a mutual fund that
holds about 8.3 percent of Commercial Federal's stock, urged
Commercial Federal to seek a buyer. Although nothing came of the
effort, Franklin secured two seats on Commercial Federal's board
after a bitter proxy fight.
</P>
<P>
   An Aug. 16 research report by Friedman Billings Ramsey &AMP; Co.
Inc., an Arlington, Va., investment banking firm, stated that
Commercial Federal might receive ``continuing pressure from
shareholders to sell the company as management continues to
struggle as an independent institution.'' The report pegged the
thrift's worth at between $20 and $24 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning about three years ago, Commercial Federal embarked on
an aggressive acquisition campaign, completing seven purchases in
six states totaling nearly $4 billion in deposits. The acquisitions
included Midland Bank in Lee's Summit, which Commercial Federal
bought for $83 million in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Eggemeyer, 54, has served as a top executive at a variety of
financial organizations, including First Chicago Corp., Norwest
Corp., Chemical Banking Corp., U.S. Bancorp and Drexel Burnham
Lambert. He co-founded Castle Creek, which invests in financial
institutions, in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Last year he orchestrated the sale of Western Bancorp in Newport
Beach, Calif., to U.S. Bancorp for $958 million, or 4.4 times its
book value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
