<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH DOES THINGS HIS OWN WAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Ivy League-educated, professorial Homer Smith
always brought a unique perspective to coaching football. After
all, what other quarterback coach would spend half of practice flat
on his back under center just to make sure the snap was executed
properly?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only place to see it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith also brings a unique perspective to UCLA's season opener
Saturday against No.3-ranked Alabama. He's one of few links between
the schools, having done several tours of duty as the quarterback
coach and/or offensive coordinator at both places.
</P>
<P>
   The 68-year-old Smith, who retired after the 1997 season at
Arizona, lives in Tuscaloosa, where he tutors young quarterbacks,
has his own Web site (www.homersmithfootball.com), and publishes
manuals on anything from clock management to a quarterback's
footwork.
</P>
<P>
   Other coaches may have taught the same plays, but they rarely
did it like Smith.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA receivers coach Ron Caragher was a backup quarterback under
Smith for two seasons. He remembers Smith emphasizing how important
it was on option plays for the backfield to maintain its formation
as the play unfolded, like fighter pilots do.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, a flight squadron buzzed over Spaulding Field.
Smith, who had coached at Army, had called in a favor from some
friends in the military, Caragher said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is revered in Alabama for bringing the Crimson Tide's
offense out of the dark ages in 1989, when unheralded quarterback
Gary Hollingsworth set school records for attempts and completions
and Alabama won its first 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   At UCLA, he's more renowned for his work with Tommy Maddox, Rick
Neuheisel and Tom Ramsey, among others.
</P>
<P>
   In his first stint at the school in 1972-73, he was the
architect of the Bruins' wishbone offense under head coach Pepper
Rodgers. In 1973, the Bruins averaged a school-record 400.3 yards
per game rushing and scored 56 rushing touchdowns _ marks which
still stand.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between the schools, Smith says, is like grits
and glitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is different significantly (in Alabama),'' he said.
``There's more fervor, and it goes year round. There are just more
talk shows about it, the newspapers print more. It occupies a
bigger part in the athletic picture than it does in L.A., and the
fans get a little more heated. But UCLA has a classy program.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who might have broken the mold by taking a year off from
coaching in 1982 to pursue a masters in theology at Harvard, is
going with convention in this game: he likes Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think UCLA will get points on Alabama's great defense
because they play great offense year-in and year-out,'' he said.
``But Alabama's player strength and speed will make a difference
every time the ball's kicked and every time the ball's put in play.
And Alabama's very strong at quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   KOCHER HEALING: Defensive tackle Ken Kocher, who suffered a high
ankle sprain last Tuesday, may play against Alabama. He was walking
around Spaulding Field on Tuesday without the aid of crutches or a
walking boot for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears if he keeps progressing he might be able to play,''
head coach Bob Toledo said, adding that Kocher wouldn't start and
would likely be on the field for 15-20 plays.
</P>
<P>
   KICKS FOR FIKSE: Sophomore Nate Fikse will punt Saturday,
holding off true freshman Chris Kluwe, though Toledo said he may
use Kluwe some. A decision on whether Ryan Nece, who has been
bothered by torn cartilage in his left shoulder, or Marcus Reese
will start at weakside linebacker will likely be made today, Toledo
said.
</P>
<P>
   CORRECTION: Seniors Oscar Cabrera and Kenyon Coleman were voted
captains for the season, not for the Alabama game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
