r f BC-SPRINT-FUTURE-2TAKES-     08-29 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-FUTURE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT'S PRESIDENT LOOKS AT THE COMPANY'S FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Since Sprint Corp. and WorldCom Inc. gave up
on their $129 billion merger, Wall Street has kicked the breath out
of Sprint's main stock.
</P>
<P>
   The shares, known by their FON trading symbol, closed Tuesday at
$32.56, less than half the $76 in stock that WorldCom was going to
pay. Sprint's separate PCS stock, which tracks the operation of its
wireless business, traded Tuesday at $48.06, 20 percent off its
price July 13 when the deal was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the stock price slide has sickened Ronald T. LeMay,
Sprint's president and chief operating officer. But during a recent
interview, LeMay outlined Sprint's plan to address Wall Street's
uncertainties about how the telecommunications company will move
forward independently.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint, which employs roughly 20,000 people in the Kansas City
area, will shift from being known primarily as a national
long-distance provider to a mover of voice and data by both land
lines and wireless technology, LeMay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not happy at all where the stock price is. I am a big
shareholder too. I can empathize because I am feeling it,'' said
LeMay, whose value of Sprint and Sprint PCS securities has fallen
by about $223.7 million, to about $127.6 million, since the merger
was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The company will focus on markets worldwide where it is
currently building out networks of its Internet backbone _ which
connects Internet service providers to the Internet _ and its
wireless broadband technology.
</P>
<P>
   Its wireless broadband, the ability to provide Internet service
with wireless technology, has the potential to reach roughly a
third of the U.S. market to serve both consumers and businesses.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, LeMay said Sprint would work its way out of the
stand-alone consumer long-distance market, packaging its
long-distance with such services as PCS wireless and Internet
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not going to be the same uniform national market people
have gotten accustomed to when people look at long-distance
carriers,'' LeMay predicted. ``It is going to be much more a
locally oriented market with long-distance and other things as
components.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question there are fundamental changes occurring in
the market. The question, analysts said, is whether nine months of
merger negotiations sapped Sprint of some of the talent, drive and
agility to master the rearranged steeplechase.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are saying the right things, that the market is changing
and they are changing to meet that challenge,'' said Jeff Kagan, a
telecommunications industry analyst based in Atlanta. ``Recognizing
the problem and admitting you have a problem is half the battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``They still have to deal with the reality, that they are
without the same bench strengths they had a year ago. The company
has to either go it alone and fill in all of their weak spots or be
acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of what has happened to Sprint's share price is tied to
the annulment of the merger, analysts say. Investors are
disenchanted with the telecommunications category generally, and
the shares of AT&AMP;T, WorldCom and many others are trading well off
prices of a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for long-distance service continue to drop, putting
pressure on company earnings at the same time many companies are
investing tens of millions of dollars in the data and wireless
networks essential to be competitive. That revaluing of the
telecommunications industry was already under way at the time that
Sprint's merger with WorldCom was canceled, giving a double hit to
Sprint's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still MORE
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ...double hit to Sprint's stock.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts still like Sprint. They say it is innovative and
has a motivated work force and some strong assets, particularly its
wireless and local phone services. But they say that several
factors tied to the failed merger raise questions about Sprint's
ability to move forward.
</P>
<P>
   One is the loss of more than half a dozen top executives. A
provision of the Sprint stock option program allowed options that
otherwise would take years to earn to become available when
shareholders approved the merger, even if the deal was not
finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts even question whether William T. Esrey, the chief
executive who built Sprint into a force to be reckoned with, is the
person to lead it now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Esrey and his top people said Sprint could succeed alone and
then they went into the WorldCom deal,'' said Steve Koppman, senior
analyst with Dataquest, a division of the Gartner Group of
information technology consultants. ``Now, when he says they can go
on their own, it doesn't sound credible to the market.''
</P>
<P>
   LeMay called that assessment ``hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill said very clearly...at the time that we decided to merge
with WorldCom, that going alone was still a viable strategy. To
suggest that we had concluded that we couldn't make it on our own,
there wasn't a strategy we couldn't employ going forward, it
absolute hogwash,'' LeMay said. ``People are engaged in revisionist
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street wants Sprint to clearly articulate a strategy and
present people who can carry out that strategy, and Sprint is
working to do that, LeMay said. ``That's the issue, not Bill
Esrey.''
</P>
<P>
   The company will present its plans and introduce the new
management to investors and analysts in presentations before the
end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans include Sprint's place in the explosive growth
expected in data transmission. Though Sprint does not have the
world's largest Internet backbone, it is often acknowledged as one
the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Internet backbone business is about a billion dollars now
and is growing at about 75 percent a year,'' LeMay said. ``We think
we can accelerate that growth next year.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Sprint has its Integrated On-Demand Network,
or ION technology, which allows customers to use multiple fax,
phones or Internet hookups through a single line into the home or
business. Though Sprint has some difficulties with that technology,
LeMay said it was the technology customers wanted, a single line to
provide all their voice and data needs.
</P>
<P>
   By the beginning of 2002, LeMay predicted, Sprint also will be
able to offer ION services through its wireless network, greatly
expanding its market potential. That means the company will be able
to offer the service without having to work through a local
telephone provider. And it will be able to serve customers who live
too far away from special equipment to get high-speed Internet
connections by land lines.
</P>
<P>
   The tremendous growth of data movement over wire lines will
happen with wireless service as well, LeMay said: ``People are
going to find uses for that technology that we simply cannot
comprehend now. It is a major part of our growth opportunity. It is
just a matter of timing.''
</P>
<P>
   But in any transforming market, timing can be everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole industry is going through a major shift. All
companies, including Sprint, face uncertainty,'' Kagan said. ``But
Sprint also is facing these challenges after they lost a lot of
senior talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Esrey's time to become a bold visionary leader or step
aside. It can't be business as usual. Sprint is at a very important
transition point. We will just have to wait and see.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
